<SLUG> BC-NY-GRANDPA-GOVERNOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL LEWIS, `MUNSTERS' GRADPA, MAKES A QUIXOTIC BID FOR GOVERNOR
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Afew days before Election Day, one of the candidates
for governor of New York will defy basic political strategy by
going to New Jersey. There, he will don a vampire's cape, apply
enough makeup for a suitably ghoulish cast, and help the Fairfield
Garden Center promote its sale of Halloween costumes and lawn
ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the scheduling challenges for Al Lewis, the Green Party
gubernatorial candidate for now, Grandpa Munster forever. October
was his busy season well before he aspired to elected office, and
he has places to go: a New Jersey garden center, a Minnesota mall,
even some gig at a haunted house in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done these, God knows, how many times,'' said the
candidate, in that streetwise voice so eerily familiar. ``If they
don't pay, I don't go.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis never disrespects the bumbling vampire he portrayed
more than 30 years ago on ``The Munsters'' television series. It
has paid his bills, brought him international fame and lately given
him the opportunity to promote _ sometimes eloquently, other times
nastily _ a contrarian world view shaped by 88 years of knocking
around. He was 24 years old when his Democratic opponent, Peter
Vallone, was born, and 35 when Gov. George Pataki, the Republican
incumbent, came into this world.
</P>
<P>
   He spends part of each day signing autographs, waving to people
who call out ``Grandpa,'' answering expressions of love from
strangers with exhalations of ``Yeah, yeah'' and ``God bless.'' But
he is just as likely to rage against General Electric's pollution
of the Hudson River, recite statistics suggesting that the poor pay
too much in taxes, or dismiss those who disagree with him as fools
or worse.
</P>
<P>
   And while he may dodge the occasional question _ about his
educational background, for example _ Lewis readily volunteers
information that other candidates might keep to themselves. ``Are
you then going to tell me that I am also a friend of what some
people label America's greatest pornographer, Al Goldstein?'' he
snapped. ``Yes, I am! I've never denied that. Am I also a friend of
John Gotti? Yes! He's a man who, whenever I was in his company,
treated me with respect _ never belittled me, nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   With piercing eyes in perpetual squint and with sideburns that
burst from his jowls like exploding pillows, Lewis looks very much
like a man who once concocted tonics in a bathtub by night, then
touted the restorative powers of the beverage by day. Back then, he
called himself ``The Professor.'' At various points in his life of
wandering, he has also worked as a circus roustabout, a merchant
seaman, a restaurateur, and, of course, a character actor for radio
and television.
</P>
<P>
   But it was by landing the role of Grandpa Munster, from 1964 to
1966, that Lewis earned his curious niche in the public
consciousness; he calls it ``jerkumstances.'' Now, through the
wonders of satellite dishes and reruns, he is seen, again and
again, mouthing the same sitcom lines, turning into the same rubber
bat on a string. ``If we went to Tokyo, Milan, Paris, Marseilles,
Glasgow or Prague,'' he said, ``all they'd yell is, `Grandpa!'''
</P>
<P>
   That one role spawned decades of appearances at Halloween
parties, autograph and memorabilia shows, children's programs and,
well, pretty much anything campy. A couple of years ago, he
appeared at a ``Mr. and Mrs. Nude'' contest at a nudist camp in
Indiana (``Nice people own it,'' he said). And he recently served
as master of ceremonies for the 30th anniversary party of Screw
magazine, the publication of his friend, Goldstein, the
pornographer.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is fine and good. But how did Al Lewis became a
gubernatorial candidate?
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Lewis ran his own weekly radio program on WBAI, a
format that allowed him to drop his Grandpa routine and share
political views shaped largely by his mother, a garment worker who
made sure he attended the annual May Day rallies in Union Square
Park. ``You want to lay blame for what I have to say?'' he asked.
``Blame it on my mother. Go to the cemetery in New Jersey and throw
rocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of his populist ruminations reached several members of the
Green Party, which, like other minor political parties in New York,
are ever vigilant for candidates who might bring them the 50,000
votes needed to secure automatic placement on the ballot for the
next four years. And this year, the pressure on so-called third
parties is intense. A new party, the Working Families Party, has
emerged, and is backing Vallone, while the Liberal Party continues
to endorse Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross _ even though she lost the
Democratic primary and even though her wealthy husband, Wilbur
Ross, took back most of the roughly $4 million he had pledged to
her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Party leader Raymond Harding acknowledged that these
circumstances require him to ``roll up my sleeves and work.'' But
he still had time to pass judgment on the Green Party's choice of
Lewis as its candidate for governor: ``What that represents is a
gimmick.''
</P>
<P>
   But Craig Seeman, the Green Party official instrumental in
luring Lewis, said the actor's appeal went beyond his fame. Some
research found that he was also a longtime advocate of various
causes and had appeared at political rallies over the years. ``He's
very much green in his politics,'' Seeman said.
</P>
<P>
   After being approached by the Green Party in the spring, Lewis
consulted with his wife, Karen _ the director of Eviction
Intervention Services, a tenants' rights group in Manhattan _ and
his three sons. They told him to go for it.
</P>
<P>
   Having humbly accepted the nomination, Lewis now travels around
the state, often at his own expense, talking green: for affordable
housing, community gardens and a clean environment; against
union-busting and the privatization of public hospitals. His
assessment of his rivals is succinct. Vallone, the New York City
Council Speaker, is ``a nice guy but a hack politician''; Pataki
is, simply, ``a potato head.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' quixotic campaign has had its share of setbacks and
discrepancies. He received some criticism, for example, for saying
he was 75 _ not 88 _ on a voter registration form. It was an error
of necessity, he explains, required to counter the rampant age
discrimination in the entertainment business.
</P>
<P>
   The most devastating hit came last week, when a state Supreme
Court justice refused to allow Lewis' name to appear on the ballot
as ``Grandpa Al Lewis.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Daghlian, spokesman for the state Board of Elections, said
the board had opposed the request because ``it's our opinion that
people don't go around calling him `Grandpa Al Lewis' all the
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
