<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A WOMAN WHO BOWED OUT ON HER OWN TERMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JANE GROSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEHAMPTON, N.Y. _ Until the last days of her life, Elaine
Benson told only a chosen few that she was dying. Even when the
effects of chemotherapy forced her to wear a wig, and friends
noticed, she brushed them off with a joke or a fib.
</P>
<P>
   To reveal the secret would have cast a shadow over the summer
season on the East End of Long Island, in a community that
considered Ms. Benson its soul and her art gallery its cultural
center. It would sadden those who knew her, affect her many civic
projects and burden people who depended on her.
</P>
<P>
   That was not Ms. Benson's way. ``She didn't want anyone to look
at her with sad eyes,'' said her daughter Kimberly Goff, who will
succeed Ms. Benson as head of the Benson Gallery here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone makes a big deal about dying, it disrupts
everything,'' said Dan Rattiner, publisher of a weekly newspaper
for which Ms. Benson wrote a column that appeared without fail
until the last week of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ms. Benson is dead at 74 of non-Hodgkins lymphoma, and more
than 500 friends assembled Sunday at the public-access television
station in Wainscott to mourn her.
</P>
<P>
   The guests were a Who's Who of artists and writers, among them
Claes Oldenberg, Robert Dash, Shana Alexander and Jerry Della
Femina. Valet parking, a well-stocked bar and a mountain of
crudites were provided. White orchids decorated the tables.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers, carpenters and hospital orderlies were part of the
gathering, which was marked by quiet grief as Ms. Benson's
accomplishments were celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will miss her most as the heart and soul of this
community,'' said Betty Friedan, the author and feminist, who
delivered one of 15 brief eulogies that were punctuated with Cole
Porter and George Gershwin tunes. ``And believe me, there is a soul
to this place, beyond all the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Bird Francke, a journalist and author, also saw Ms. Benson
as the embodiment of the hidden side of the Hamptons. ``We are
always being misinterpreted,'' she said. ``We are a people who love
each other, support each other and support the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Benson's resume was lengthy and bold, crossing many areas of
civic life in the town she had called home since 1964. She was a
founder (along with the second of her three husbands) of the Benson
Gallery on Montauk Highway, where she was known for nurturing young
artists, and a weekly columnist for Dan's Papers, where she took
young journalists under her wing and was known on the masthead as
Faculty Adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Ms. Benson raised more than a half-million
dollars for causes as diverse as the John Steinbeck Writers Room at
Southampton College, the Animal Rescue League, and the East End gay
rights organization. She was also the director of community
relations at Southampton Hospital and a board member of the local
television station.
</P>
<P>
   Her friends were as diverse as her endeavors. Ms. Francke
described Ms. Benson as a ``very good friend,'' adding that
``everyone will say that same thing _ that was her gift.''
</P>
<P>
   That, and discovering young artists, like Nico Yektai, a
29-year-old sculptor. He had his first showing at the Benson
Gallery three years ago, when Ms. Benson made room for his work in
an already full exhibition of emerging talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``She looked at my portfolio, nodded, and said, `I can work with
this,''' Yektai said. ``She was so generous of spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   This week's issue of Dan's Papers had pages of elegiac letters,
as well as a memorial article about Ms. Benson. It also reprinted
her last column, from the Oct. 2 issue, which went to press after
her death.
</P>
<P>
   In that column, Ms. Benson told readers of the diagnosis she had
been given more than two years earlier, while she was nursing her
husband, who was ill with throat cancer, through his final days.
She wrote, in spare, uninflected prose, of her decision not to
resume chemotherapy when her cancer recurred, and her wish that
there be no visits or flowers.
</P>
<P>
   She had left nothing to chance. The music for her memorial
service had been chosen and the caterer hired. The service was to
be held in the same space where friends had mourned her husband,
Joseph Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   The master of ceremonies would again be Frazier Dougherty, owner
of the television station. He was to wear the same vintage Bill
Blass suit _ red-and-black plaid _ and the same patent-leather
dancing slippers with grosgrain bows.
</P>
<P>
   He was also instructed not to tell a soul what he knew until
after her death. ``That was Elaine's way,'' Dougherty said, as a
dapper pianist played Cole Porter's ``You'd Be So Easy to Love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
