<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL COLUMN: NO TIME FOR PARCELLS TO PLAY FAVORITES NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The New York Jets' season took an unexpected turn
for the worse here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   This game against the reeling Rams was cast as a winnable
challenge. No, Curtis Martin was not playing, and St. Louis was not
a division rival. But the Jets were on a roll, so this was a good
chance to let Glenn Foley shake off the rust. The Jets would see
what Foley had after a two-week layoff and how they would function
without Martin, their star running back. How did they do? Terribly.
Absolutely terribly.
</P>
<P>
   Otis Smith, the veteran defensive back, blamed the loss on lack
of preparation and overconfidence. Overconfidence? How a team that
finished 1-15 two seasons ago and failed to make the playoffs last
season can be overconfident against anybody is a mystery. But that
is what Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets might expect to be a step slower without Martin, but
Foley's performance is disconcerting, rust or no rust. Before he
was finally replaced by Vinny Testaverde in the third quarter,
Foley turned the ball over three times, twice on interceptions,
once on a fumble on a first-quarter blitz.
</P>
<P>
   Foley's performance is bound to turn what had merely been a
dilemma into a full-blown controversy. And there should be
controversy. Foley is now 1-7 as a Jets starter; Testaverde is 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, early as it is, are at a crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   And for the second consecutive season, the quarterback position
is a harpoon in Bill Parcells' side.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has told Foley _ and the news media _ that the starting
quarterback job is his as long as he is healthy. Parcells' loyalty
to Foley is admirable, but he has stubbornly stuck by his guns, and
now must deal with more questions.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the coach defended his handling of the quarterback
situation last season. Parcells is given quite a bit of license,
with good reason. We all know the biography _ two Super Bowls won
with the Giants, a Super Bowl appearance with New England. He
revived the Jets after a 1-15 season, and nearly got them into the
playoffs. That is why some members of the news media accept his
gruff style and barking.
</P>
<P>
   But Parcells had better let this one go. Testaverde should be
the Jets' quarterback. Testaverde is not a crowd favorite; he is
not a Parcells favorite. He's not my favorite, for that matter.
That's not the point. He's better, he's healthier and actually had
a full head of steam going into Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   When Foley is sharp, he's accurate and tough and all the things
we've said. But on Sunday he was rusty. In the first half, his
fumble with one minute 26 seconds left in the first quarter led to
the Rams' first score and lit a spark. From that point on, the Rams
applied the pressure. They wanted to see, as Parcells wanted to
see, whether Foley could function coming off an injury.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two months, Testaverde has been the perfect Jets
company man, saying that he just wanted to fit in, wanted to help
the Jets in any way possible. But after two strong starts, the
35-year-old veteran is becoming more aggressive in talking about
assuming the starting role. ``There's no question I would have
liked to play earlier,'' he said. ``But it's coach's decision as
always. I'm not going to argue with him about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was noncommittal when he was asked about the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know; let me see what goes on,'' he said. ``Like I
said, it wouldn't have made any difference who was playing today.''
</P>
<P>
   That's doubtful. Testaverde has been sharp. While Foley said he
wasn't affected by his two-week layoff, rustiness showed.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde didn't have to win the job; Foley gave it back. Now
we wait and see the wisdom of Solomon and Bill Parcells' attempt to
get the harpoon out of his side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
