</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons roll to a Giant win, 34-20
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ A national television audience learned
Sunday night what Falcons fans have known all season: Atlanta's
better half is the second.
</P>
<P>
   After a sluggish first half, the Falcons dominated the New York
Giants in the final two quarters, scoring on four of their first
five possessions after halftime for a 34-20 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Falcons' first victory on prime-time TV in four
years, and it left the Falcons (4-1) tied with the San Francisco
49ers atop the NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, leading 14-13 at half, broke open the game behind
running back Jamal Anderson, who ran for 83 second-half yards to
finish with 110 yards on 30 carries. He is just the third Falcons
player to run for more than 100 yards in three straight games.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Chris Chandler threw touchdown passes of 36 and 55
yards, and ran 1 yard for a score early in the fourth quarter to
finish off the Giants (2-4).
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has outscored its five opponents in the second half this
season by a total of 96-30.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons won with the help of a 2-yard fumble return by
reserve defensive end Antonio Edwards early in the second quarter,
the first consistently heavy pass rush all season (six sacks), and
a couple big plays.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, each team gained just 125 yards. Chandler
completed 7-of-16 passes for 113 yards, and Anderson and fullback
Bob Christian each lost fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta took a 7-3 lead in the first quarter on a 36-yard
touchdown pass from Chandler (14-of-27, 266 yards) to Tony Martin
on a post route.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta stretched the lead early in the second quarter, when
Edwards stripped the ball from New York quarterback Danny Kanell,
plucked the ball out of the air and took a big step into the end
zone for a 2-yard score. That made it 14-6 with 13:05 left in the
first half. In the third quarter, the Falcons cranked it up. They
went 65 yards on 11 plays to start the second half, scoring on
Morten Andersen's 26-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   On their next possession, Terance Mathis got open down the right
sideline for a 55-yard touchdown reception for a 24-13 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 0009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
