<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1204 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ALCS-HNS &LR;      10-12 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
CLEVELAND _ Rule No. 1: Never provide the competition with any
extra incentive to go out and beat you, especially if he's
nicknamed ``Boomer.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rule No. 2: Don't fall behind Boomer early.
</P>
<P>
   While warming up in the right-field bullpen prior to Sunday's
critical Game 5 of the American League Championship Series, New
York Yankees starting pitcher David Wells received a rude greeting
as a few Cleveland fans shouted insults directed at Wells' family.
</P>
<P>
   Wells got mad, then got even, and now the Yankees are one
victory away from advancing to the World Series for the second time
in three years after a 5-3 victory over the Indians before a crowd
of 44,966 at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   New York, which holds a 3-2 advantage in the best-of-seven
series, can secure the AL pennant Tuesday at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little disturbed because of some reactions I got out
there when I was warming up,'' said Wells, who gave up two runs in
the first after the Yankees provided him with a three-run lead in
the top half of the inning. ``When you have a bunch of clowns out
there that start talking about your mother, and not knowing that my
mom passed away a year and a half ago, it really bothered me.
</P>
<P>
   ``What got me was that some little kids started to do the same
thing. They were lowlifes trying to be cute. I don't care what they
say about me. When they talk about any members of my family, it
really bothers me. So to all those idiots out there, this one is
for you.''
</P>
<P>
   After allowing a home run on his fourth pitch of the game to
Kenny Lofton, part of a two-run response to an early New York
outburst, Wells took his frustration out on the Indians over the
next six-plus innings. He struck out 11 batters, a career high for
the postseason, to remain perfect in three playoff starts this
year.
</P>
<P>
   After swinging the momentum in its favor with two straight
victories over the Yankees earlier in the week, Cleveland has
dropped two in a row and must win the next two games _ both in New
York _ to return to the Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough,'' Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove said
after his starting pitcher failed to get past the second inning for
the second time in the ALCS. ``We've got to put it on the line two
more times.''
</P>
<P>
   Indians starter Chad Ogea, who won two games against Florida in
the World Series last year, ran into trouble from the get-go,
falling behind 3-0 after seven batters while lasting just 1
innings. Jaret Wright, bypassed for Sunday's start after lasting
two-thirds of an inning in the series opener, walked seven but gave
up just one run _ a solo home run by Chili Davis _ in six innings
of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Here's all you need to know about what kind of day it was for
the Indians: Ogea hit two batters, walked two and allowed a pair of
singles that staked the Yankees to a 3-0 lead before Wells even
stepped to the mound. Chuck Knoblauch was hit to lead off the game,
and following a strikeout by Derek Jeter, Paul O'Neill singled and
Bernie Williams walked to load the bases. Davis, who was 2-for-5
with three RBIs, hit a two-run single past a diving Richie Sexson
at first base. Tim Raines drove in another run two batters later
with a grounder to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've dug ourselves a hole fairly often this postseason,''
said Hargrove, whose Indians have been outscored 15-3 in the first
inning of nine playoff games. ``We've been able to come back from
that, but it's not the ideal way you want to come into the
ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland rallied to within 3-2 in the bottom half of the inning
on Lofton's leadoff home run and a sacrifice fly by Manny Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   New York added a second-inning RBI single by O'Neill and a
fourth-inning homer from Davis to go ahead 5-2. The Yankees did not
have a hit after the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove defended going with Ogea instead of Wright, who lowered
his ERA for the series from 67.50 to 8.10.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Jaret's) last two starts in the postseason weren't what we've
come to expect out of him, and so, consequently, we went with a
more experienced pitcher in Ogea,'' Hargrove said.
</P>
<P>
   Few, however, can match the postseason success of Wells. In
going 3-0 with a 1.90 ERA in this year's playoffs, he has allowed
only five earned runs in 23 innings while limiting opponents to a
.202 batting average. He is 7-1 lifetime in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Even after watching Wells give up two early runs and fall behind
in the count on several occasions, Yankees manager Joe Torre didn't
panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an animal. He goes after you,'' Torre said. ``He fights
it and battles it. I'm probably prouder of his effort tonight than
maybe the shutouts and even the perfect game because (of what this
game) meant to us and he didn't panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who pitched a perfect game May 17 against Minnesota,
worked out of potential disaster in the fifth when he got Travis
Fryman to pop out to end the inning with two runners on base. Wells
struck out five of the final eight batters he faced before being
lifted with one out in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera came on in relief for the Yankees and induced
Mark Whiten to hit into a 4-6-3 inning-ending double play. Rivera
threw the ninth to earn the save.
</P>
<P>
   As Wells walked off the field in the eighth, he showed a little
extra emotion toward the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans are entitled to be crazy and wild; that's part of the
game,'' Wells said. ``But I think they should just focus on trying
to rattle you up and not get personal with other people than that
individual.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was Wells who had the last word.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
