<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1210 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-12 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez 
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
IRVING _ It was a story about redundancy. Redundancy, I said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The running back, the receiver, the cornerback, the defensive
tackle and the offensive line. Old reliables. Emmitt Smith, Michael
Irvin, Deion Sanders, Leon Lett and Nate Newton and Co.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly for some people, even those who have celebrated
Sunday-afternoon regular-season victories again and again over the
years, there remains a spark and a thrill in simply putting on the
pads, playing the game and earning a dollar or two. Or 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   For some, it never gets old. It never causes the nerves to fray.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys 27, Panthers 20 on Sunday showed us that no matter how
much money is in the bank, how pitiful your division is looking and
how abundantly average your team might be compared to what it once
was, some people still bust their tails when the whistle blows.
</P>
<P>
   For some, even those with stars on their helmets and
championship rings on their fingers, an October regular-season game
against a bad team is not monotony _ something you would rather
skip in favor of a hunting trip. It still means something.
</P>
<P>
   You step in, bad knee and all, like Lett did Sunday afternoon,
and you have maybe your best game of the season with six tackles, a
forced fumble and dominance up front.
</P>
<P>
   You grab the ball deep in the backfield like Smith did time and
again against the Carolina Panthers, knowing you probably have lost
a step and the defense will be keying only on you since Troy Aikman
is on the sidelines with an injury. But you twist for every extra
yard on every play. You finish with 112 yards, score a touchdown
and look terrific all day.
</P>
<P>
   You get smashed to the ground on a run-of-the-mill sideline
pattern, like Irvin did late in the first quarter, bloodying your
nose. But you step back in and just moments later set up a
touchdown with a clutch catch on virtually the same route. You have
your best game of the year, finishing with six catches and 146
yards.
</P>
<P>
   You dominate an entire side of the field during the
game-deciding stretch, like Newton and Larry Allen did Sunday, and
ultimately earn all the praise from the head coach after the
offense rocks the Panthers for 428 yards.
</P>
<P>
   You ice the game by prowling quietly for three-plus quarters,
almost anonymously, if that's possible for a guy nicknamed Neon,
then step in front of a last-ditch toss, like Sanders did in the
final seconds, and intercept the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was explosive. Redundant. Irvin was clutch. Redundant.
Deion made a big play. Redundant. Lett clogged the middle, and the
offensive line made big, gaping holes.
</P>
<P>
   We have heard all these things before.
</P>
<P>
   But it never gets old for this team from the NFC Least searching
for mention among the NFL heavies of 1998. And it all seemed
particularly significant in Dallas on this day, when the opponent
was a winless team whose starting quarterback gave up and whose
starting tailback forgot how to find the airport.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same old story for the Dallas Cowboys at Texas
Stadium. That's the promising news. Great players still did great
things.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly for some people, being young, popular and a
multimillionaire remains a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   But for Kerry Collins, the Panthers starter who shocked his team
last week when he announced he had lost his mental edge and
willingness to play the game, it was all too much. The $6 million
signing bonus Collins received three years ago and the $1.1 million
bonus before this season apparently were enough to send him into a
funk and ultimately a duck-hunting trip over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After his self-demotion, Collins was deactivated for Sunday's
game. Some of his teammates would tell you calling Collins
deactivated is itself a redundancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took a seat on us,'' Panthers guard Corbin Lacina said.
``The last couple of weeks, Kerry didn't have anything for us. He
didn't have the confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, running back Fred Lane missed the team's charter
on the way to Dallas and was benched by coach Dom Capers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our rules,'' Capers said. ``We abide by them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers spent the postgame wondering how things could have
gone so wrong so fast. Just two seasons ago, this was a team that
beat the Cowboys in an impressive playoff show. Just last December,
they beat them again.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, while Carolina might have played hard under the
hand of former Cowboys backup Steve Beuerlein, it made critical
mistakes and failed to make critical plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a passion out there,'' fullback William Floyd said.
``Steve was the new sheriff in town, and he acted like it. He
wanted to be out there. He took control. But we didn't have enough.
I don't know what it was that killed us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was redundancy.
</P>
<P>
   Deion still wanted to play and did. Collins didn't. Irvin still
wanted to play and did. Lane missed the plane. Smith, Newton,
Allen, Lett. They all wanted to be here.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys still felt the hunger, even on a run-of-the-mill NFL
Sunday afternoon. Apparently, it never gets monotonous for these
guys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
