<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE HYPE, WIN VS. DENVER WASN'T A `MUST' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ To borrow from the football vernacular, the ``hot
read'' angle for today's column would be a spirited bash of the
Seahawks for squandering their 3-0 seasonal start.
</P>
<P>
   The recent three-game stretch against some of the NFL's best,
which ended Sunday, was forecast to be the season-maker for Paul
Allen's little investment in sinew instead of cyber.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Seahawks lost at Pittsburgh and Kansas City and Sunday
at the Kingdome 21-16 to Denver, the conventional wisdom is that
the season is toast, the Seahawks are still boys among men, and
let's see what the Sonics are ... well, forget that last part.
</P>
<P>
   Still, was not the game against the defending Super Bowl
champions called a must-win game in some precincts? When a team
loses a must-win, is there anything left but the eternal abyss, or
worse _ the Mariner bullpen?
</P>
<P>
   To make our offense a little less predictable, we'll skip the
hot read, and choose another route.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a must-win game _ not even in the NFL, where the
overused phrase ``big game'' has the same value as an air kiss in
Hollywood. It didn't make or break the Seahawk season. It proved
little except that biggest difference between the Broncos and
Seahawks is running back Terrell Davis.
</P>
<P>
   A considerable difference, true, but the Seahawks aren't in the
Super Bowl hunt. The Seahawks will be thrilled to take a little
postseason food off the table and come back for big meat another
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like with two minutes to go, we're going to win this
game,'' said Seahawk guard Pete Kendall. ``I think it was third and
nine, and we knew we were in four-down territory (at the Denver 28)
and there was no doubt we'd make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, quarterback John Friesz threw a bad pass that was
picked off. End of game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was hardly worse that the pass Denver quarterback John
Elway threw in the second quarter that Seahawk linebacker Darrin
Smith intercepted and returned for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there were few Seahawk mistakes that weren't matched by
the Broncos. So too for the splendid plays. The Seahawks had only
the one turnover, had the same number of QB sacks as Denver and had
about the same penalty yardage. Elway was little better than the
Warren Moon/Friesz combo. The only difference in total offense came
on Davis's 70-yard run in the final minute when the game was being
tucked away.
</P>
<P>
   Friesz put it as well as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody all the time,'' he said, ``is doing a little bit
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about it. Despite losing the alleged three big games, the
Seahawks have not been physically dominated nor soundly beaten.
They have lost them by a combined 19 points, 11 at KC in the first
tsunami recorded in Midwest weather history.
</P>
<P>
   They are bleeding from a hundred small wounds, most
self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the difference was the Seahawks healed up from some,
moved on and were on the edge of upsetting the champs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two games, when we'd get backed up by a penalty,
forget it,'' said Kendall. ``I thought today we did a good job of
overcoming adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dug ourselves a hole, but in the second half, we got to a
point were we could see out.''
</P>
<P>
   What can be seen is the shrunken distance between themselves and
the Broncos. The most recent two games against Denver have been
lost by a total of eight points. Last November, the Seahawks fell
30-27 at Mile High when they were stopped on downs at their own 46
with 1:02 left.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the defense curbed the NFL's No. 2 offense with some
superlative work by the secondary. The offense, once Moon was
benched _ which should have happened sooner, given his reduced
effectiveness from a cracked rib _ moved against a good defense
better than it has all season.
</P>
<P>
   What is happening to the Seahawks is nothing like what used to
happen to them, even as recently as early last season.
</P>
<P>
   They are no longer ill-prepared, overmatched and under-talented.
They have the NFL's fourth-highest payroll, quality veterans on
either side and a little depth on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   They have offensive problems, but it doesn't include turnovers.
It's not as if coach Dennis Erickson and his staff don't know
offense.
</P>
<P>
   That was the indictment of these coaches before _ offense was
(begin italic) all (end italic) they knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Effort is not a problem, either,'' said Friesz. ``It's a great
group of guys who were meant to win football games.''
</P>
<P>
   Friesz recalled during his time as a backup in San Diego that
the Chargers started the 1992 season 0-4 and won 11 of the next 12
``with not nearly the talent of people we have here.''
</P>
<P>
   Players always dismiss talk of tight games, moral victories,
cutting the gap and other such sporting homilies as irrelevant to
the matter of W's and L's. But that political correctness ignores
the simple fact that the stage of almost has to be reached before
it can be surpassed.
</P>
<P>
   There are no must-wins for teams in the almost category.
</P>
<P>
   The only must is to get better, for which the 10-game season
starts in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
