</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-BRONCOS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS COME UP SHORT, LOSE TO DENVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As the tears began welling in Warren Moon's eyes, it
was difficult to tell which hurt more: The cracked rib just behind
his left armpit, or the sting of losing a third straight close
game.
</P>
<P>
   Moon paused, heaved a heavy and prolonged sigh, then finally
offered, ``It's a combination. I am in a lot of pain right now, but
I'm very disappointed about the outcome of this game too. We had a
chance to win and we didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third week in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, all the ingredients seemed to be there for an upset of
the unbeaten Denver Broncos. The defense again played well enough
to win, and even scored on a 23-yard interception return by
linebacker Darrin Smith. The first true sellout at the Kingdome
since 1993 was loud enough to disrupt the Broncos' offense and at
times seemed capable of willing the Seahawks to victory.
</P>
<P>
   But again, as was the case in losses at Pittsburgh and Kansas
City the previous two weeks, the offense didn't hold up its end and
the Broncos escaped with a 21-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the rib Moon cracked in Kansas City that forced the
Seahawks quarterback to leave the game in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the interception John Freisz threw right at Broncos
linebacker Glenn Cadrez after replacing Moon. It happened at the
Denver 27-yard line, with 1 minute, 49 seconds left in the game and
with wide receiver Joey Galloway wide open over the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on another slew of penalties against the Seahawks'
struggling offense and suddenly suspect special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the Seahawks are now 3-3 and searching for
answers to too many questions heading into their bye week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' defensive end Michael Sinclair said. ``I
don't think they came in here and just blew us away. That's the
frustrating part, not winning these games when we've had chances to
win them. But we're not getting it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do something. We've got to change something.''
</P>
<P>
   The now 6-0 Broncos had something to do with the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Davis ran for 208 yards, the second-highest total ever
against the Seahawks, just behind Bo Jackson's infamous 221-yard
effort in a Monday night game at the Kingdome in 1987. Davis scored
on a 2-yard run in the fourth quarter and then eliminated any
Seahawk comeback hopes that remained after Cadrez's interception by
bolting 70 yards to the Seattle 5-yard line with less than 90
seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback John Elway, making his first start after missing the
previous two games with a sore hamstring and back, threw TD passes
of 50 yards to Rod Smith and 19 yards to Shannon Sharpe. Smith
finished with eight catches for 136 yards, both career highs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming here, we knew it wasn't going to be a typical
regular-season game. It somewhat had playoff implications to it and
it felt like a playoff game,'' said Davis, who now has rushed for
865 yards and nine TDs in just six games _ a pace that would
produce a 2,306-yard, 24-TD season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was huge, no doubt about it. Coming into their place
and beating them here is definitely a check for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Broncos could not checkmate the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Elway's TD passes on two of the Broncos' first four
possessions, the Seahawks stayed close because of Smith's
interception return and a 23-yard field goal from Todd Peterson to
cap the opening series of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's big play, the fourth interception return for a TD by the
defense this season, came from the zone-blitz package that has been
so successful for the Seahawks. The linebacker dropped into
coverage on the weak side and all of a sudden there was Elway's
pass that was intended for Rod Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opened up and my eyes got big because I saw that he was
going to throw it ... He probably didn't see me at all,'' Darrin
Smith said. He was right. He did fool Elway, who is in his 16th and
perhaps final season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was something I haven't seen in 16 years, when the
soft-side linebacker picks off a weak-side hook,'' Elway said.
``I'm giving the credit to Darrin. He made a great, great play. If
I had to do it again, I'd throw the same play, the same pass I
threw. He just made a great play.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense seemed to make plays all afternoon to keep the
Seahawks in this game. Linebacker Chad Brown made 14 tackles,
including a sack. Cornerback Willie Williams broke up four passes.
Cornerback Shawn Springs intercepted his third pass of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense was brilliant most of the game,'' guard Brian
Habib said. ``They kept us in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   After Davis scored to make it 21-10, and Moon was forced to
leave the game, it seemed the Seahawks were done. But Friesz hooked
up with Mike Pritchard on a 50-yard TD pass to cut the lead to five
points with 10{ minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great play by Pritchard and it was also a great
read by Friesz,'' coach Dennis Erickson said, noting that they saw
the Broncos were blitzing and made them pay.
</P>
<P>
   And Friesz wasn't done. On the Seahawks' next possession, he
drove them from their own 23 to the Denver 28. Suddenly, it was
Mile High Stadium in November of 1995, when Friesz came off the
bench to erase a 20-point deficit against the Broncos for the
biggest comeback win in Seahawk history.
</P>
<P>
   But it took Cadrez only a blink to slap everyone back to
reality.
</P>
<P>
   Cadrez was supposed to be blitzing on the play. But when his gap
closed, he said, ``I figured don't just waste myself. So I backed
up and kind of read the quarterback. He looked one way and I went
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Friesz never saw the Broncos' linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a guy you don't look at,'' Friesz said. ``You've got
your eyes moving a thousand different directions and at that time
the clock is going off in your head and you have to get rid of the
ball. He was the guy I lost and didn't see.''
</P>
<P>
   Then result, for the Seahawks, was pain on top of pain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
