<SLUG> BC-FBC-UW-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURPRISING CAL COMING TO SEATTLE 4-1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After going without a victory for 26 years at USC, Cal
has now won two in a row in Los Angeles against the Trojans. The
Bears might start thinking anything is possible, even a victory
over Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Cal (4-1) comes to Husky Stadium Saturday as the third of four
straight October home games for Washington (3-2). Through good
times and bad, through Joe Kelly and Jason Shelley, nothing has
been quite as certain for Washington as a victory over Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1976, Don James' second year as coach, has Cal beaten
Washington. The Bears have whiffed in the 15 games since then,
sometimes in the worst-imaginable circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Cal had the Huskies down 27-3 in Seattle and lost 28-27
in what is regarded as Washington's biggest comeback ever. In 1993,
in what might have been Damon Huard's worst and best game at
Washington _ he had a fumble and four interceptions _ the Huskies
fell behind 23-3 in the third quarter, and rallied in the final
moments for a 24-23 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing is contagious,'' coach Tom Holmoe said Sunday from his
office at Cal, and he hopes winning is, too.
</P>
<P>
   Cal has beaten Houston, Oklahoma and USC by a total of six
points. The latest was a 32-31 win over the Trojans, achieved on a
22-point comeback in the final 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you win a couple of close games, you just believe you're
going to do it,'' Holmoe said. ``If it happens again, the team will
know it's been in close games.''
</P>
<P>
   At Montlake, meanwhile, Washington savored a 53-12 victory over
Utah State, behind 13 sacks. UW coach Jim Lambright assessed
injuries, and it appears wide receiver Ja'Warren Hooker's is worst
of the new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Hooker sustained a subluxation of the right shoulder, which
means there was movement in the joint, probably sidelining him
against Cal. Receiver Gerald Harris might play for the first time
since the Nebraska game, however.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Willie Hurst was limping with a bruised hip incurred
Saturday. The Huskies hope to have him available to practice by
Tuesday but his status is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Brock Huard is able to throw lightly despite his
injured shoulder, but is highly unlikely to play. He would give way
again to Marques Tuiasosopo.
</P>
<P>
   Against USC, the Bears fell behind with an uncharacteristic
performance on defense, and won it with an unusual outburst by the
offense. Cal allowed USC 296 yards in the first half and trailed
31-10 in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Cal then clicked on offense, its season-long bugaboo, went ahead
and was at the USC 22 when the game ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 42 runs and 42 passes, which is very good,'' Holmoe
said. ``Early in the season, I guess we were pretty predictable.
Maybe last night, we mixed it up better.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmoe's offensive coordinator, former Dallas Cowboys tight end
Doug Cosbie, called plays from the press box for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Lambright liked the Cal victory over USC, but not primarily
because it helps get his team's attention for the Bears. He's
thinking standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives USC (4-2, 2-1) a loss,'' he said, smiling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
