<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINIELLA SAYS M'S NOT SEEKING SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If changes are made to the Mariners' coaching staff
for 1999, manager Lou Piniella said, they will not be made with an
eye on his successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't thought anything like that,'' Piniella said Sunday
from his home in Tampa, Fla. ``We're just trying to put together
the best staff we can.
</P>
<P>
   `` . . . We have explored some possibilities, but it's not with
the idea of putting a coach in place to succeed me or not.
Invariably, that's going to happen, but that's not why we're
looking as an organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella, who has managed the M's since 1993, is under contract
through the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are contacting coaching candidates from inside and
outside the organization, and former Colorado Rockies manager Don
Baylor is a possible addition.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, a teammate of Piniella's with the 1983 and '84 New York
Yankees, managed Colorado for six years until being replaced by Jim
Leyland last week. Baylor has been offered a front-office job with
the Rockies and will earn $600,000 from them next year.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella did not say if the Mariners had talked to Baylor, but
he indicated the team will not make large-scale coaching changes.
Four of the M's seven coaches have been re-signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a bad year last year,'' said Piniella, whose team
finished 76-85, ``and when you do, you look at all you can and see
where you can improve. That's the first order of business (the
coaching staff), and it will be done in short order.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Woody Woodward and Piniella both said a decision
should be made on the coaches by the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward has also been reviewing reports on potential free
agents and players who might be available through trade, and
keeping track of the team's prospects in the instructional league.
</P>
<P>
   M'S NOTES: Several Mariners have undergone minor surgeries since
the end of the season. Left-hander Jeff Fassero is throwing lightly
at the M's spring-training complex in Peoria, Ariz., after having
three loose bone chips removed from his elbow and should be
recovered by the end of December. Designated hitter Edgar Martinez
(left) and first baseman David Segui (right) both had arthro-scopic
knee surgery and also should be fine before spring training. . . .
Right-hander Freddy Garcia, who would have gotten a September
call-up if not for a triceps injury, is in the instructional league
learning to throw a circle change-up, which should relieve the
stress on the muscle. ``He's coming along fine,'' Piniella said. .
. . The prospect who has Piniella's immediate attention, however,
doesn't even play baseball. Piniella's son Derek plays football for
Virginia Tech, and Piniella will take in the Hokies' homecoming
game against Temple this weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
