<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS VICTORY WAS VERY UNCARDINAL-LIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Electrical power finally was restored to Sun
Devil Stadium on Sunday. Cardinals fans got the shock of their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   They saw a game so unusual, a victory so un-Cardinal-like, that
even the players expressed amazement.
</P>
<P>
   Usually when the boys in red pants commit five turnovers and get
a punt blocked they find themselves playing catch-up at the end of
the game as they did last week, trying desperately to stop the
clock. But here they were, with three minutes left, beating the
Chicago Bears, 20-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals haven't led by 20 points in the fourth quarter
since _ hmm, how long has it been?
</P>
<P>
   Larry Centers couldn't remember ever enjoying such a comfortable
lead. He has been a Cardinal nine long years.
</P>
<P>
   This was beyond unusual. This was unheard of. But then who ever
heard of a middle linebacker picking off an enemy pass and then
stealing a second one and then a ``third'' and also causing a
fumble and snatching a blocked punt out of the air and doing a
Walter Payton imitation, running 31 yards for a first down, all in
``one'' game?
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not believe it,'' Centers said, speaking for us all.
</P>
<P>
   But Ronald McKinnon did it.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals defense did it. This group which is establishing
an identity and a reputation picked off four Erik Kramer passes and
forced four fumbles. Eight Chicago turnovers. That's a lot, even
for the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill saw one team suffer
eight turnovers in a game was in 1950. Cardinals quarterback Jim
Hardy delivered eight passes into the hands of the Philadelphia
Eagles. Like milk of magnesia, the NFL record has stood the test of
time.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago (1-5) is a bad team, one of several. The Bears primarily
exist this year for the purpose of taking a pie in the face. But
``eight'' turnovers. Dave Wannstedt may not survive this.
</P>
<P>
   For all anyone knows, the Bears may have fired their head coach
during the third quarter but Wannstedt never got the message.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon intercepted it.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals let their first shutout in six years slip away.
But how can anyone mark down the defense? This group continues to
get better and better. Playing without their starting cornerbacks,
the Cardinals snuffed the Bears running game and turned Kramer's
afternoon into a nightmare. There was Eric Swann, in his face.
There was Simeon Rice, scooping up a Curtis Enis fumble. There was
McKinnon, here, there, everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon is small for an NFL middle linebacker. Some questioned
whether he could replace Eric Hill. But you know how many
interceptions Hill made in nine years as a Cardinal? Three fewer
than McKinnon did in one day.
</P>
<P>
   He was in the right place at the right time, always around the
football. Kramer, his victim, must have felt like a good-natured
volunteer from the audience who spends a few moments on stage with
a nightclub magician. Before sending the fellow back to his seat,
the entertainer, an accomplished pickpocket, says, ``Oh, you forgot
your watch . . .'' Then, matter-of-factly, ``Did you drop this?''
handing the subject his wallet. Money clip, pocket comb and
suspenders follow.
</P>
<P>
   For a defensive coach, this was a dream game. Dave McGinnis
called it a ``monster'' effort. This was a game that helps
reinforce the players' belief that they have something special
here, or will some day. Positive results build confidence and trust
in the coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like inviting friends over for dinner,'' McGinnis, the
defensive coordinator said, ``and they can't get enough to eat.''
He looked around him, at the happy faces. Simeon Rice's grin lit
the locker room. ``They like what we're feeding them.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense is growing. It carried the offense again. That the
Cardinals could produce only 20 points off eight turnovers against
a weak team is worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a big win, an important win. The Cardinals are 3-3,
for the first time since 1991. They're playing in a weak division.
Can they win eight games, or nine?
</P>
<P>
   A linebacker intercepted three passes Sunday. At halftime, a
63-year-old man kicked a 25-yard field goal and won $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Anything seems possible. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or
david.casstevens(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 0100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
