<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1234 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-BEARS-AZR &LR;      10-12 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BEARS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIFT BEARERS  
 CARDINALS' DEFENSE FORCES 8 TURNOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD   
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Perhaps it happened when they were located on
Racine Street, or when they were the Morgan Athletic Club or the
Normals.
</P>
<P>
   Some time in the Racine/Chicago/St. Louis/Phoenix/Arizona
Cardinals' 100-year history, they must have forced their opponent
to commit eight turnovers as they did in Sunday's 20-7 victory over
the Chicago Bears at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But the NFL and the Cardinals aren't aware of it. So the eight
takeaways, including three interceptions by middle linebacker
Ronald McKinnon, stand as a team record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ain't never had a defense this good,'' said Cardinals
offensive tackle Lomas Brown of his 14-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Bears quarterback Erik Kramer entered the game having thrown
only two interceptions and having been sacked only four times. He
was picked off four times and sacked twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, 3-3 for the first time since 1991, also forced
four fumbles and deflected about a half dozen passes. Three of the
tips resulted in interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our front four is causing so much havoc,'' said cornerback
Aeneas Williams, who played sparingly after suffering a sprained
ankle on a first-quarter interception return. ``They are getting to
the guys before they even get to the line of scrimmage. They are
getting to the hole and stripping the ball. They are hitting guys
before they are prepared to get hit, and the balls are coming out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe in the adage: Defense wins games. Offense
brings the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 50,495 fans wasn't thrilled with the offense's
three lost fumbles and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   That explains the Cardinals' 20-point output instead of perhaps
double that amount. Five times they began drives in Bears'
territory but managed only two touchdowns and two field goals by
Joe Nedney.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our defense wasn't playing like they were, it could have
been 70 (points),'' said Bears Coach Dave Wannstedt, whose team
dropped to 1-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' most important turnovers were the two forced in a
two-minute span late in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They were leading, 3-0, when former Bears defensive lineman Carl
Simpson stripped rookie running back Curtis Enis at the Cardinals'
48. Defensive end Simeon Rice picked up the loose ball and ran 27
yards to the Bears' 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``This defense is like a desert swarm,'' said defensive tackle
Eric Swann.
</P>
<P>
   Five plays later, reserve running back Mario Bates scored on a
2-yard run, his first touchdown as a Cardinal, to give them a 10-0
lead with 1:53 left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   On the ensuing kickoff, Bates forced Glyn Milburn to fumble, and
the Cardinals' Kwamie Lassiter recovered at the Bears' 14.
</P>
<P>
   Bates' second 2-yard score gave the Cardinals a 17-0 halftime
lead, their biggest margin of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals turned the ball over on their first two
possessions of the second half, but their defense held each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're killing ourselves,'' Brown said. ``The defense is
carrying us now. When we hold up our end of the bargain, we're
going to be something to contend with.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense also was responsible for the Cardinals' final score.
</P>
<P>
   On the second play of the fourth quarter, McKinnon stripped
fullback Ty Hallock at the Bears' 43. Rookie defensive end Andre
Wadsworth recovered at the 45, setting up Nedney's 40-yard field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon wasn't finished putting on a show.
</P>
<P>
   After the Bears' Ricky Bell blocked Scott Player's punt midway
through the fourth quarter, McKinnon picked it up near the right
sideline and cut across the field for a 31-yard gain and a first
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was out of gas,'' Wadsworth said. ``He blew a gasket after
he came to the sideline. He lost oil. He got a flat tire.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon's three interceptions were a single-game record for a
Cardinals linebacker. His 31-yard return of the blocked punt was
the team's longest run of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can do it all,'' said McKinnon, jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   The only downer for the defense was allowing the Bears to score
on a 79-yard touchdown pass with 2:30 left. Otherwise, they would
have had their first shutout over the Bears in 71 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
