<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-USOC-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA TO HAVE MAJOR OLYMPICS PRESENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In 1996, Kerri Strug landed on a sprained ankle and
Gary Hall Jr. dueled with an angry Russian in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Zeke Jones and Crissy Ahmann narrowly lost gold medals
to unknown challengers in Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Michael Carbajal lost a controversial decision as Jay
Barrs rocked-and-rolled in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, there will be more Arizona athletes with major roles to
play in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The state's rich Olympic history, diverse population, weather,
geography and variety guarantees that Arizona athletes will star,
stun, inspire, disappoint, anger, frustrate and entertain at the
next summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   Who and how?
</P>
<P>
   The how will remain unknown until after the opening ceremonies
Down Under. But who? Possibilities have begun to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, this land-locked desert state promises to have it
biggest Olympic impact in the water. Arizona has some of America's
best-and-brightest swimming prospects. One is a veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Hall was Arizona's most decorated Olympian in 1996. He won two
individual silver medals and two relay gold. It's the silver that
people remember. And it's the silver that sets the stage for him to
attract a lot of attention before Sydney. Hall lost twice to
Russian Alexander Popov. He has yet to beat him. A Hall-Popov
rematch looms.
</P>
<P>
   But there's an if. Arizona's most-decorated Olympian is also its
most controversial. Last summer, the Phoenix Swim Club sprinter
served a two-month suspension, later lifted, for a positive
marijuana test. He's often at odds with USA Swimming, one of the
United States Olympic Committee's many Olympic governing bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, USA Swimming appreciates his singular talent. It continues
to pay him a stipend to train. Despite the controversy, he's a
member of its All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   Hall also has come to symbolize a potentially rich area in which
to train and develop Olympic swimmers. A leading Olympic candidate
is Misty Hyman, a Stanford sophomore and a former Shadow Mountain
High School star and a link in the long line of great butterfly
swimmers that includes Ahmann, a 1992 silver medalist from Benson.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman missed making the 1996 team by three-hundreths of a
second. Ironically, her greatest challenge in 2000 could come from
young women within the state. There's Kayln Keller at Phoenix Swim
Club, Hyman's teammate Jana Krohn at the Valley's Desert Fox Club,
Ashley Tappin of Tucson and 1996 Olympian Trina Jackson, also of
Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Tappin and Jackson are members of the national champion
Hillenbrand club, which is coached by Frank Busch of the University
of Arizona. Busch is swimming's 1998 Coach of the Year. He's a
leading candidate for the next Olympic job.
</P>
<P>
   Tucson also is a major corner of the gymnastics map. It's known
for Strug and her vault with a sprained ankle en route to a team
gold medal in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, Tucson's impact on gymnastics could come from the men.
Yewki Tomita, 18, is a contender for the U.S. team. His dad, Yochi
Tomita of Tucson's Gymnastics World, is in line for a coaching
post. He was an Olympic assistant in 1984. Another leading
possibilities is Jason Gatson, a Mesa native and national team
member.
</P>
<P>
   Other potential Arizona Olympians: &QL; 
Track &QL; 
Dan O'Brien, the 1996 decathlon gold medalist, has a home in the
Valley. Sprinter Tim Harden, a member of 1996's silver-medal
winning 400 relay, is living and training in Tempe. Arizona senior
Amy Skieresz of Tucson is a possibility in distance events. Trina
Painter of Flagstaff is a contender in the marathon. Two-time
Olympic hurdler Lynda Tolbert-Goode has talked about Sydney, and
former ASU sprinter Maicel Malone, a 1996 relay gold medalist, is
expected to make another run. Gea Johnson, free from a drug
controversy, has talked about a comeback in the heptathlon. &QL; 
Wrestling &QL; 
Jones, a former ASU coach now at West Virginia, might attempt a
comeback. Two Valley wrestlers, 1996 silver medalist Melvin Douglas
and fellow Olympian Townsend Saunders, also are possibilities. In
all, the Valley-based Sunkist Kids has 12 wrestlers ranked by U.S.
Wrestling. In Greco-Roman, heavyweight Matt Gahfari, a 1996 silver
medalist, is a good bet to make a return. &QL; 
Boxing &QL; 
Gyms in the Valley's Mexican-American neighborhoods are filled with
kids who could be the next Carbajal, a 1988 silver medalist.
Featherweight Ray Martinez, 18, is a leading contender. At 140
pounds, Ramon Olivas is quickly emerging after a national
Blue-and-Gold title a few weeks ago. At heavyweight, there are
former Scottsdale resident Davarryl Williamson and Keith Govan of
the Police Athletic League. &QL; 
Archery &QL; 
Barrs, formerly of Mesa and now of Salt Lake City, figures to try
for his third Olympics. He'll bring his Walkman. His wife, Janet
Barrs, is another contender. Also don't forget Atlanta gold
medalist Justin Huish, formerly of ASU, and 1996 teammate Judi
Adams of Scottsdale. &QL; 
Elsewhere &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Shooting: Adam Saathoof of Herford, Denise Morrison of
Flagstaff and Dan Nygood of Prescott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Softball: UA star Allison McCutcheon and former UA star Leah
O'Brien, a 1996 gold medalist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Basketball: Jason Kidd of the Suns and Australians Michele
Timms, Kristi Harrower and Michelle Griffiths of the Phoenix
Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weightlifting: National team member Christina Wilson, a
130-pounder from Flagstaff. Gea Johnson may try to qualify in this
sport, too. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
