<HEADLINE>
`ATHLETES' DEFI NITION UPSETS DISABLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - After 104 years without a definition, the U.S. Olympic
Committee has decided who qualifies as an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Not that ice dancers are in and ballroom dancers out _ or vice
versa. But the definition of ``athlete'' which establishes the
criteria necessary to be a member of the Athletes Advisory Council
and athlete member of the board as approved Sunday on the final day
of the USOC board of directors meeting in downtown Phoenix .
</P>
<P>
   ``No document in the history of the USOC has ever gone through
so many revisions,'' said Steve Sobel, chair of the USOC membership
and credentials committee.
</P>
<P>
   The voice vote was not unanimous, as representatives of disabled
sports questioned why their athletes remain ineligible for the AAC,
board of directors and groups operating under the board. To qualify
for those positions, an athlete must have represented the United
States in the Olympic or Pan American Games, world championships or
an Operation Gold event within the 10 years preceding election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only do this one step at a time,'' USOC President
William Hybl told Doug Pringle of the Disabled Sports Associations.
Hybl then established a task force, to be chaired by Terry
O'Donnell, to integrate disabled athletes into the highest reaches
of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, two disabled athletes are being invited to AAC
meetings as observers.
</P>
<P>
   The 110-member board also heard from John Krimsky, USOC deputy
secretary general, about a 50-city Magic of the Olympics tour that
will run from February through August 2000 as a buildup to the
Sydney Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   One of the stops will be the Phoenix Symphony Hall, where
opening ceremonies are being held today for the eighth U.S. Olympic
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour Magic of the Olympics will feature the U.S. Olympic
Symphony with music of John Williams and conductor Keith Lockhart,
video from Olympic historian Bud Greenspan, pop entertainers and
Olympic athletes such as decathlete Dan O'Brien of Phoenix,
heptathlete Jackie Joyner Kersee, gymnast Mary Lou Retton and diver
Greg Louganis.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know of the Olympics, but not about the Olympics,''
said USOC Executive Director Dick Schultz. ``It's all part of
building the brand, which supports a variety of programs we have
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   All presumably with a positive impact on the USOC-Salt Lake
Organizing Committee joint marketing of the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Joklik, president of the Salt Lake committee, told the
board that replacing IBM as an Olympic worldwide sponsor is one of
the most critical short-term issues. IBM is ending its 30-year
Olympic association after the 2000 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Today's congress highlights will include appearances by 60
Olympians at 17 Valley schools through the Champions of Life
outreach program, and a keynote address by Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., at the opening ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Olympians scheduled to be at schools and working with
students in interactive sessions at the Phoenix Civic Plaza deck
are wrestler Matt Ghaffari, archer Justin Huish, gymnasts Shannon
Miller and Blaine Wilson, swimmer John Naber and speed
skater-cyclist Chris Witty. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
