<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-RUNNINGBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATES' TD CARRIES `WORTH THE WAIT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Sure, Adrian Murrell is a proven back who
deserves his starting assignment in the Cardinals backfield.
Getting him plus a seventh-round draft pick from the New York Jets
in exchange for a third-round pick was one of the the Cardinals'
great off-season heists.
</P>
<P>
   But there is talent on the Cardinals bench, too. Mario Bates was
signed as a free agent, and Michael Pittman was drafted in the
fourth round. And neither has been getting much action.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bates hadn't touched the ball at all until he carried
it three times Sunday in the first half of the Cardinals 20-7 win
over the Chicago Bears. But two of those three totes went for
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long time coming,'' Bates said. ``But it was worth
the wait. The coaches kept telling me, `Be patient, be patient.'
Coming into the season, I thought the rotation might be different.
The main thing is I was able to do something for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittman proved to be a bulldog, and not just because he is from
Fresno State. He carried 17 times for 56 mostly hard-fought yards.
In the fourth quarter, when the Cardinals (3-3) enjoyed a 20-0 edge
and were interested in running out the clock, Pittman got the call
13 times, responding with 54 yards. He fumbled one away, though,
setting up the Bears only score.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a rookie mistake that I learned a lot from,'' Pittman
said. ``I have a bad habit of stretching the ball out to get extra
yards. In that situation, I should just go down because we had a
big lead and we wanted to use the clock. Next time, I'll do what I
have to do to hold onto the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just good to get a few opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Murrell still was the team's leading rusher with 67 yards on 21
carries.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it was the first time the Cardinals got into the
three-back rotation, and it produced 145 rushing yards on a
season-high 46 carries, allowing the Cardinals to control the clock
for a season-high 36 minutes _ a whopping 12-minute advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they decided to do it undercover,'' Bates said with a
smile. ``Every running back wants the ball. It was nice to finally
touch the ball. It's hard to get enough carries for everybody. We
have a lot of talent back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin has been looking for this kind of production
from the ground game. Realizing he had two capable backs who were
just spectators for five weeks, he had the coaches design specific
packages for each.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like Mario and we like Michael and we want to get them in,
but sometimes it's hard to do,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Murrell, Bates and Pittman each has a significantly different
style that makes them a formidable rotation, according to center
Aaron Graham, who calls the blocking schemes up front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pittman likes to cram it up in there. He's a really hard
runner,'' Graham said. ``Adrian is a slashing type runner. Mario
did a great job on the goal line. You've got speed and power with
those three guys, and you can give the defense different looks.
That's good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way this defense of ours is playing, giving us great field
position, if we can put points on the board we're going to win
games. We still have work to do on our offense, but being able to
run the ball is big.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting close to where we want to be with our offense,''
Graham said.``We should have been able to score some more, but
we're excited. We've made progress. It wasn't great, but it was
good.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
