<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-MCKINNON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME BALL IS 1 OF MANY MCKINNON HAD HANDS ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - As the Cardinals celebrated their 20-7 defeat of
the Chicago Bears Sunday, the team announced that tackle Eric Swann
had been named the ``Truly Nolan Defensive Exterminator of the
Game.''
</P>
<P>
   Which raises a Truly Interesting question. What more is Ronald
McKinnon supposed to do?
</P>
<P>
   Let's see:
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon intercepted three Erik Kramer passes, a single-game
Cardinals record for a linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   He caused a fumble, punching the ball away from Kramer for
teammate Andre Wadsworth to recover. It led to a 40-yard Joe Nedney
field goal and 20-0 Arizona lead.
</P>
<P>
   And he turned disaster into a positive play when the Bears'
Ricky Bell blocked Scott Player's punt deep in Arizona territory.
McKinnon hauled the ball in and headed upfield like a tailback for
31 yards and a first down.
</P>
<P>
   His performance was Truly Unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of big plays Ronnie made, I haven't been around
anyone who's done anything close to that in a game,'' said
Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin, who awarded McKinnon a game ball.
</P>
<P>
   Swann had a nice game himself, playing despite swelling in a
knee that had made him questionable for the game. Swann didn't
start but came off the bench to deflect a couple of passes,
including one that McKinnon intercepted, and recorded his third
sack of the season.
</P>
<P>
   So, a Truly Perplexed McKinnon had to wonder what else it takes
to get that award.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work hard?'' McKinnon asked.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Cardinals undersized middle linebacker is used to
being overlooked. He went undrafted in 1996, despite leading North
Alabama to three consecutive NCAA Division II national
championships and winning the Harlon Hill Trophy _ a Division II
version of the Heisman _ as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Even after McKinnon started 11 games at outside linebacker and
five at the inside position last season, there still were questions
whether the 6-foot, 240-pounder could adequately replace Eric Hill
in the middle after Hill signed as a free agent with St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   There should be little doubt now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have the size and speed that maybe you're always
looking for, but he gives you everything he's got on every play.
He's a tremendous asset to this football team,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   If McKinnon needed any more motivation, he might have gotten it
Saturday when defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis brought along
another undersized linebacker he used to coach _ Hall of Famer Mike
Singletary.
</P>
<P>
   The former Chicago Bear great was on hand to watch McKinnon's
performance Sunday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
