<SLUG> BC-BBN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES COULD PULL IT OFF 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The following is not a prediction. Simply call it a
warning.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves are uniquely qualified to become the first
team in the history of major league baseball to win a best-of-seven
after being down, three games to none.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one to B-S anybody,'' said Braves manager Bobby Cox
immediately after his team's 8-3 victory over the Padres Sunday
night. ``I have a lot of faith in our pitching staff. And it's
about time our bats came alive. If we had any kind of clutch hits
in the first two games, we could have won, and that includes the
game (Kevin) Brown pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   The least anyone now can say about the Braves is that they are
alive and breathing comfortably. Cox sends all-time postseason win
leader John Smoltz to the mound Monday night. He has to feel pretty
good about that, no?
</P>
<P>
   We know he's feeling a lot better about his team's offense after
watching the Braves knock out 12 hits, the most resounding of which
was the 459-foot grand slam struggling cleanup man Andres Galarraga
deposited deep into the left-center field seats off San Diego
reliever Dan Miceli to cap a six-run seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga had stroked 44 home runs this regular season, but only
one of them had come after Sept. 7. As for the postseason, suffice
it to say that merely putting the ball in play has been an
achievement for the affable and dignified Venezuelan slugger.
</P>
<P>
   When he came to the plate in the seventh, his evening's work had
consisted of two bases on balls and a 6-4-3 double play. He was 1
for 11 with no runs batted in and five strikeouts. The Big Cat had
been a Big Tabby.
</P>
<P>
   But Miceli fell behind and then made the fatal mistake of
placing a fastball in the old wheelhouse. Galarraga swung the bat
and the ball took off for parts unknown. There was never any doubt
that we were looking at a grand slam. The only question was whether
or not we were looking at an unsanctioned, non-NASA satellite.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good hitter,'' said San Diego manager Bruce Bochy of a
man who has driven in 411 runs in the last three years. ``I was
hoping he wasn't going to find his stroke right there. Miceli fell
behind, and Galarraga got a pitch he could handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox had told people before the game that he felt his biggest gun
was ready to fire. ``I just thought the odds were with us tonight
with his bat,'' Cox said with a shrug. ``It had to happen sometime.
That was a very big hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire Braves party was having a difficult time believing
the team's batters were as impotent as they had looked in the first
three games. They were too wise and perhaps even too gentlemanly to
say much about the San Diego starting staff, which, aside from the
frightening Brown, does not have anyone of All-Star caliber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept thinking, `If we could just catch a break,''' Cox said.
``I'm not saying we were playing well enough to have three wins, or
anything, but it was time for the worm to turn a little bit with
our lumber. We haven't been hitting the daylights out of the ball,
but it helps to have one fall in that's not hit hard.''
</P>
<P>
   So guess what? Mixed in with the grand slam by Galarraga and the
leadoff homer by Javy Lopez that tied the game at 3-3 in the
seventh and the triple by Keith Lockhart and the line double by
Chipper Jones were puny infield hits by both Lockhart and Andruw
Jones. Suddenly the Atlanta box score had some meat for a change.
</P>
<P>
   As for the pitching, Denny Neagle was good enough, and the
relievers were very solid indeed. Neagle, making his initial 1998
postseason appearance, worked 5 2/3 innings and was chased
following an opposite field homer by _ who else? _ Jim Leyritz and
a double by Ruben Rivera. Dennis ``El Presidente'' Martinez retired
the one batter he faced to wind up being the pitcher of record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Neagle pitched a great game,'' maintained Cox.
``They really only hit four balls hard. The ball Leyritz hit was, I
thought, a gapper. But I noticed in batting practice that the ball
was jumping.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres seemed to have the ol' Mo squarely on their side when
the amazing Leyritz, who had knocked in the second San Diego run
with a solid single to right back in the third, hit a 1-2 pitch
from Neagle over the right-center-field fence with one away in the
home sixth to make it 3-2. The noisy gathering of 65,042, already
convinced that their squad is some sort of Destiny's Darlings, was
in a celebratory mood.
</P>
<P>
   But Lopez, no stranger to postseason heroics, jolted them back
to reality when he hit the first pitch from starter Joey Hamilton.
And from then on things got ugly, as Randy Myers, the world's most
expensive set-up man ($4 million-plus per), did everything from
throw a wild pitch, give up a go-ahead single to Ozzie Guillen, and
walk Chipper Jones to load the bases for Galarraga to clear with
one mighty swing.
</P>
<P>
   It was, frankly, a rare bullpen failure for the Padres, who are
far more than the feared Trevor Hoffman in the late innings. ``It
just didn't happen for us tonight,'' said Bochy. ``The bullpen's
done a tremendous job all year. Hey, it's gonna happen sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   Bochy remains sanguine, and you would, too. He's still got the
3-1 lead, the weight of baseball history and a fully rested Brown
ready in Game 6, if necessary. But Cox has a few things going for
him, too. No manager in a comparable position has ever had three
prime-of-life Cy Young Award winners lined up like this.
</P>
<P>
   And now the bats are stirring. You can be sure that Cox slept
better than any 1-3 manager in baseball history Sunday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
