<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS NOW MUST TAKE A GIANT STEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - The roller coaster goes up. The roller coaster
goes down.
</P>
<P>
   Twists and turns. Staggering climbs and precipitous drops.
Thrills around every corner. And when it's over, you're right back
where you started.
</P>
<P>
   The mad dance around mediocrity continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being 3-3 means nothing if we end up 3-4,'' tight end Chris
Gedney said. ``We've ``got'' to learn to take the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   Until they do, the Cardinals will never shed their conspicuous
past.
</P>
<P>
   When the clock put an end to one mess of a football game on
Sunday, after the hosts accepted every turnover from Team Creme
Puff and walked off with a 20-7 victory, there was a certain amount
of satisfaction in the air.
</P>
<P>
   With a win over Chicago and a win in St. Louis _ cities that
once housed the family business _ the owner probably thinks his
head coach is Lombardi, not Tobin. With a defense accumulating its
share of respect and bad nicknames, the draft-day chatter is
starting to seem prophetic. And with a win total that is one shy of
last season, it is easy to think the compass is pointed in the
right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. Parlaying eight turnovers into a 13-point victory over Da
Bares is nothing to brag about. Not when Jake Plummer is still
throwing ill-advised passes. Not when the revamped offense is still
sputtering. Not when the average scoring drive on Sunday was a
whopping 27 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave (the football) to us, we gave it to them, and they
gave it right back again,'' Gedney said. ``One of those days where
no matter what they did, Chicago wasn't going to win that game.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those days when a good team would've won by 45 points.
Instead, the Cardinals were lining up to field an onside kick in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after hearing the chatter in the Bears' locker room,
you'd have thought they lost to a Pop Warner outfit.
</P>
<P>
   Bears Coach Dave Wannstedt, not even sure of the Cardinals'
proper name: ``Phoenix is a good team. But we didn't give ourselves
a chance to play as good as we can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bears lineman Big Cat Williams on the Cactus Curtain: ``Yeah,
they have big names on the defensive line. But I don't feel they
were a big factor today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bears center Chris Villarrial on the apparent domination of Eric
Swann: ``We were stuffing him on the line, but he was getting his
paws up in the air and batting the ball down.''
</P>
<P>
   Bears defenseman Mike Wells: ``The whole damn day was a slap in
the face to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Bears are as ignorant as they are bad. But
they're right about one thing. This was nothing to brag about.
</P>
<P>
   Unless it's a steppingstone to something bigger. Unless they
take out the New York Giants on Sunday in the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   Now that would be progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being 4-3 would be huge,'' Plummer said. ``Winning in New York
would send a message to other teams going into our bye week.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, things could be so much brighter. If Andre
Wadsworth had been in camp all summer, the Cardinals may have been
ready to win in Dallas. If they hadn't squandered a game against
the Raiders, they'd be sitting at 4-2. Nevertheless, six weeks into
the season, they're probably just where you expected them to be.
</P>
<P>
   But at some point, the Cardinals have to settle in to their
destiny. They must decide who they are, what they're about, where
they're going to finish.
</P>
<P>
   They are heading to New York, ready to battle the road, the turf
and former offensive coordinator Jim Fassel. They are embarking on
one of those weeks that reveal a lot about the character of your
football team. Another chance to prove much has changed in the
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer to be 6-0,'' Plummer said. ``We should've won last
week, but we've moved on. And being 3-3, compared to last year, I'm
very happy. But we want to get above .500.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. If they're really a team on the rise, they must get off
the roller coaster. And for once, get out ahead of the curve. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
