<HEADLINE>
PLUMMER DUE HEFTY RAISE, IF CBS REPORT IS ACCURATE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - If  &UR; Mike Lombardi of CBS television is correct,
 &UR; Jake Plummer is on the verge of becoming a wealthy young man.
</P>
<P>
   But while it is a foregone conclusion that Plummer, the
Cardinals' second-year quarterback, is due for a huge pay bump
before long, Cardinals officials say it's not necessarily coming
this week, as Lombardi reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to know,'' Plummer said.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer, who started his 15th game Sunday, a 20-7 win over the
Chicago Bears, is making $302,100 in base salary this season, the
second year of a three-year deal that included a $700,000 signing
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   For most starting quarterbacks, another zero could be added to
the end of the base salary. Plummer is due to get $362,500 in base
salary next season, but the Cardinals are expected to tear up the
deal before training camp next summer.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of circumstantial evidence to point to a quick
deal. The Cardinals are roughly $3 million under the NFL salary
cap, and Plummer's agent,  &UR; Leigh Steinberg, is due in Phoenix today
for a book signing.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing is imminent, according to  &UR; Bill Bidwill Jr.,
Cardinals vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``CBS reported that? It's news to me,'' Bidwill said. &QL; 
Guaranteed success &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals defensive lineman &UR; Eric Swann laughed at the report in
a Chicago newspaper that he had guaranteed a win. The Bears'
offensive linemen took it personally and responded with highly
indignant statements.
</P>
<P>
   Swann, playing on arthritic knees that caused him to miss
practice on Thursday and Friday, heightened their indignity by
making a sack, forcing a fumble and constantly pressuring
quarterback  &UR; Erik Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never said it,'' Swann said. ``That's not my style. I think
it was just something their coaches made up to motivate their
players. I've never made any statement to the media about
guaranteeing a win or being boastful in any way.'' &QL; 
Hey, get back here! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rookie running back  &UR; Michael Pittman had only five carries in
the first five games before Plummer handed the ball to him 17 times
_ for 56 yards _ Sunday. Thirteen of those carries came in the
fourth quarter, a load that so exhausted Pittman that he tried to
take himself out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I yelled at him as he was leaving the field to get back in the
huddle, that you don't take a break,'' Plummer said. ``But he's in
on all those special teams, and he was tired. He made big plays
today . . . and he had a great game.'' &QL; 
Lonesome ends &QL; 
 &UR; Joe Nedney's 49-yard field goal in the first quarter was the
longest of his career by two yards.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mario Bates' two rushing touchdowns marked the first such
performance by a Cardinals back since  &UR; LeShon Johnson did it 34
games ago at New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' eight takeaways are the most by a defense since
San Francisco took eight from New Orleans on Sept. 14, 1997. It
marked the most turnovers by a Cardinals foe since Seattle coughed
it up eight times on Oct. 29, 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
