<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL'S WELLS FOR YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CLEVELAND _ He's still a big man in this, his hometown, but
there's only one place where they call him the Boss.
</P>
<P>
   And now that his New York Yankees have seized the advantage in
the American League Championship Series with a 5-3 win in Game 5
Sunday, don't think for a moment that George Steinbrenner ever
fretted that the Cleveland Indians, the team in the town he left
behind, would rain on the historic parade of the team he has called
his own for the last quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked out of here with friends Friday night, I said,
`We're going to win this thing,''' Steinbrenner said in his usual
don't-even-dream-of-thinking-anything-else way. ``That's how
worried I was.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 48 hours since Steinbrenner supposedly uttered his
fearless forecast, the outlook for his Yankees has taken a dramatic
bounce. Down 2 games to 1 after the Indians turned the Bombers into
the bombees with four home runs in Game 3, the Yankees responded to
their first advanced calculus test of the year by acing it. They
won Game 4 behind Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez, the clever
righthander who defected from Cuba, and Game 5 behind David Wells,
the free-spirited lefthander who inhabits his own universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how many Christmas dinners he's going to be
over,'' said Steinbrenner, who reluctantly bent his martial dress
code to allow Wells to pitch with his uniform jersey flapping and
T-shirt exposed, ``but we're going to sit together for some hockey
games, like we did last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm even getting to like that Metallic band.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who at that moment was passing Steinbrenner in the
hallway outside the visitors' clubhouse, overheard the Yankees
owner talking about his favorite band.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Metallica,'' Wells said, emphasizing the last syllable.
``Metallica.''
</P>
<P>
   Staked to a 3-0 lead in the first inning against Chad Ogea, the
Indians' starter of last resort and even less fortune whose
deflection turned a double play ball by Paul O'Neill into a
rally-stoking single, Wells gave the Indians two right back in the
bottom of the inning. The first came on a leadoff home run by Kenny
Lofton, who later in the game would be lulled into acting like the
slugger he's not, dropping his bat at the plate on a big fly he
supposed was another home run but was just another out.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Vizquel and Travis Fryman followed Lofton's home run with
hard-hit singles, and when Vizquel stole third, he put himself in
position to score on Manny Ramirez's sacrifice fly. The Indians,
even without injured starters Sandy Alomar and David Justice, had
Wells in an unaccustomed fix.
</P>
<P>
   But Wells struck out Mark Whiten and Richie Sexson to put an end
to that uprising, and then held the Indians to just one more run,
Jim Thome's 439-foot crank into the second deck in the sixth, while
striking out a total of 11, a career high in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Thome connected, the Yankees had expanded their
lead, adding another run off the luckless Ogea in the second on
another single by O'Neill, and one more off Jaret Wright in the
fourth. That one came on a home run by Chili Davis, the DH who for
much of the Yankees' record-setting season was recuperating from a
torn tendon and ligaments in his right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They carried me all year, it's about time I did something,''
said Davis, the 38-year-old DH who said he was thinking of the man
who might have been playing in his place, Darryl Strawberry, before
doctors discovered he had cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who struck out five of the last eight batters he faced,
was lifted by manager Joe Torre after whiffing Vizquel, the first
batter in the eighth. His departure did not come without protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still have time to send everybody back,'' Wells said he
told Torre, who already had summoned reliever Jeff Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson gave Torre reason to regret his decision when he hit
Fryman with a pitch and gave up a single to Ramirez, putting the
tying runs on base.
</P>
<P>
   The moment was ripe for a massive second-guess, especially by a
certain suit. ``Was I managing?'' Steinbrenner said, deadpan.
``Yeah, I sent word down.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner has been known to dial the dugout, but never, he
said, with Torre. Asked if he were managing along with his manager,
Steinbrenner shook his head. ``I don't do that anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When did he stop, the day before?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``When I got Torre.''
</P>
<P>
   His faith in his manager was rewarded when Torre went to his
closer, Mariano Rivera, and Mark Whiten, the Mexican League refugee
who had homered in Game 3, bounced into a rally-killing double
play. It was started by second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, who had
just moments earlier taken a step in the right direction, courtesy
of Yankees coach Willie Randolph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie just moved me over a little bit when Mark got ahead in
the count,'' Knoblauch said. ``From the sound of the bat, I knew
Mariano had jammed him, so I knew I had to come charging fast to
give Derek Jeter any chance to turn the double play.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter did his part, and Rivera did his with a flourish, striking
out Enrique Wilson for the final out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   So now the Series shifts back to New York, the Yankees one game
away from matching the Boss's blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody expected us to roll right through everyone,'' said
O'Neill, ``but we didn't. We knew it wouldn't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wish we could fly to our ballpark and play right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
