<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CHIEFS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS EXCEL IN CRUNCH TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Many of the Chiefs were stunned and
speechless after sustaining a 40-10 loss to the Patriots Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City coach Marty Schottenheimer, wasn't one of them,
although small talk wasn't his top priority after the game.
</P>
<P>
   He did muster this tribute to the team that had just embarrassed
his: ``In my opinion, they're the best team we've played all
season, and that includes the Minnesota Vikings, who we played in
preseason. They've got offense, they've got defense, and they've
got a kicking game that involves excellent athletes, and clearly
they had the better of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs were considered one of the AFC elite entering the
game, with a 4-1 record despite playing without quarterback Elvis
Grbac for four of those games and playing two of them in miserable
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who are now 4-1 and who stand atop the AFC East
with the New York Jets coming to town for a showdown next Monday
night, did the unthinkable to the Chiefs. They held them to 14
yards rushing while New England gained 206 yards on the ground, 104
of them on 23 carries by rookie Robert Edwards, including his fifth
rushing touchdown in his first five games, something that hadn't
been done since the 1970 NFL-AFL merger. Drew Bledsoe completed 17
of 26 pass attempts for 226 yards and three touchdowns, helping
lead the offense to 31 first downs.
</P>
<P>
   The defense, besides making the play of the game by stopping a
fourth and 1 in the first quarter, also corrected a problem from
its first four games _ allowing third-down conversions. The
Patriots entered the game allowing such conversions 45.3 percent of
the time, but Sunday the Chiefs converted only 1 of 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs' weapons were rendered ineffective. Derrick Thomas
was held to five tackles and had no sacks. The Chiefs' defense
didn't sack Bledsoe and couldn't stop the run.
</P>
<P>
   It was so one-sided that backup running back Sedrick Shaw gained
68 yards. Scott Zolak and Tom Tupa each saw time at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say we're one of the elite teams because we
haven't beaten Denver,'' said Ty Law, who held Andre Rison to one
catch for 5 yards. ``When we beat Denver, we can start talking like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The turning point?
</P>
<P>
   Many thought it was the defense stopping the Chiefs on fourth
and 1 on their 48-yard line in the first quarter. Schottenheimer
wasn't one of them. ``It was not a game-turner,'' he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   On third and 1, Donnell Bennett was stuffed for no gain by
Willie McGinest and Lawyer Milloy. There was little hesitation by
Schottenheimer to go for it. His team trailed, 7-0, and desperately
needed momentum. Coaches often say if you can't make less than a
yard, you're not good enough anyway. And so the handoff from Grbac
went to fullback Tony Richardson. Henry Thomas engaged the Chiefs'
line while Ted Johnson and Todd Collins came over the top and
finished the play, stopping Richardson for no gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't gonna be like this next week (vs. the Jets),'' said
Chris Slade, who caused a fumble after Bennett had carried for 12
yards, which was recovered by Henry Thomas, which set up the first
Patriot score, a 1-yard run by Edwards with 4:53 left in the first
quarter. ``They ain't gonna quit. That fourth-down play was a big
stop for our team. I think they quit after we stopped them.''
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to be the consensus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea they would give up like that,'' said Law. ``We
really sent a message that it's difficult to come into our house
and win a game. I think they know that now.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest said he never would say the Chiefs quit. He had been
fired up on that very drive. The Chiefs had started at their 24 and
were at the 39 in the blink of an eye as McGinest was called for
being offsides. He felt the offensive lineman had flinched and that
the call should have gone the other way, and as he argued he took
off his helmet, an automatic 15-yard unsportsmanlike penalty. At
the time it looked like it could have given the Chiefs some
momentum. Grbac connected on an 8-yard pass to Kimble Anders. But
the Chiefs were stuffed there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like that get me hyper,'' said McGinest. ``People might
say I lost my cool right there, but I was right. I made the mistake
of taking my helmet off, but after that happened I got so fired up
I wasn't going to let them get anything.''
</P>
<P>
   That stop only helped produce 3 more points for the Patriots, as
they made it 10-0 on Adam Vinatieri's 32-yard field goal, but it
gave them hope and deflated the Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   The defense held the Chiefs to just 1 yard on their next
offensive series, and this time the offense cashed in. After Troy
Brown's nifty 12-yard punt return to the 50, Bledsoe drove the team
home in seven plays, with Edwards ending the drive with a 15-yard
TD catch. He made a nice grab while stretched out to catch a high
ball. Bledsoe made the play by eluding Leslie O'Neal and Derrick
Thomas and stepping up into the pocket _ just like Dan Marino used
to do _ to get off his throw.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead, 17-0, early in the second quarter, the Patriots sensed
they could go for the kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell it was getting to them,'' said defensive
lineman Chad Eaton. ``In the first quarter their guys were standing
up and cheering for their team. By the second quarter there was
less of it, and by the third quarter everybody was on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Where was Derrick Thomas in all of this, you ask?
</P>
<P>
   He, too, disappeared. Armstrong and Moss both drew him at
various times and took him out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just straight blocking,'' said coach Pete Carroll.
``Bruce had a fabulous game taking care of him and Zefross did a
great job when he had him. We did a couple of other things to take
care of him, but it was mostly man-against-man.''
</P>
<P>
   Another key play came when Patriots punter Tupa was roughed by
Ron George. The Chiefs had stopped the Patriots for the first time
midway through the second. Tupa punted 35 yards into the wind to
the Chiefs' 24, but long snapper Mike Bartrum was called for
holding. The Chiefs made the worst possible decision. They took the
penalty, forcing another punt. Instead of making a play, George hit
Tupa's left leg and he went down.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had first and 10 at the Chiefs' 46, and they
pounded the ball on the ground with Edwards again. A reverse run by
Terry Glenn resulting in an 8-yard loss was made up for moments
later when Bledsoe spotted Shawn Jefferson alone on the right side
for 31 yards to the Chiefs' 16.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Edwards ran for 6 and 8 yards before Bledsoe found
Coates all alone for a 2-yard toss and 6 more points with 2:48 left
in the second. The Patriots led, 24-0, and the rout was on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
