<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS FINALLY SHOW METTLE AGAINST IRON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Kansas City Chiefs played playoff
football Sunday. Unfortunately for them.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs, who have been knocked out of the playoffs five times
in the first round in the past eight years, entered Foxboro Stadium
armed with the top-ranked defense in the league. Three hours later,
they left with people thinking that defense was simply rank,
because on a day when the Patriots knew they had to prove something
against a future playoff rival, they did.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of losing games like this against football's
heavy iron, New England wasted no time dismembering the Chiefs'
defense, running up 27 first-half points on a team that had allowed
just 24 first-half points in its first five games. From that point
on this was no longer a football game. It was a mugging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a rhythm going with the running game and the passing
game that was really nice,'' Patriots coach Pete Carroll said after
his team had finished off the Chiefs, 40-10, to improve its record
to 4-1 and its self-esteem to Norman Vincent Peale-like levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any area of the game we didn't feel good
about today. I wasn't thinking it would be a game like this. I
thought it would be a much tighter game but there was nothing
stopping us today. It was a fine day's work.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a dominating day's work, the kind veteran safety
Willie Clay talked quietly about his club badly needing several
days earlier. As Clay spoke last Wednesday of what the Patriots
were about to face, he thought back to the kind of beatings the
Broncos and Packers had administered not only to New England but to
other teams who thought they could compete with them the past few
years.
</P>
<P>
   In such games, the top teams make statements about themselves,
Clay said, and when possible they make loud ones. If that's the
case, the Patriots were a shoulder-padded version of Metallica
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   By the start of the second half, New England led, 27-0, had
piled up nearly 150 yards more than the Chiefs' offense, and had
not allowed Kansas City to convert a third-down situation. But that
was only the beginning, although what came next was the end for
Kansas City on this day.
</P>
<P>
   New England took the second-half kickoff and marched 81 yards in
eight plays. Through a long day, the Chiefs would six times allow
New England to gain first downs by penalties, but on this drive,
they were relatively uncooperative in that manner.
</P>
<P>
   But by then, the Patriots had them by the throat and did what
the best of teams do in such a circumstance. They made the Chiefs
pay again, driving them into the ground with Robert Edwards rushing
for 38 of his 104 yards on this drive and tight end Ben Coates
finishing it off by breaking open in the end zone for an 11-yard
touchdown catch that pushed the margin to 34-0 just 4:12 into the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   It mattered not a whit after that what the Chiefs were up to
because the issue was decided and Kansas City had learned a hard
lesson. It learned what happens to a team that comes to New England
these days not ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   After that score the game became a simple matter of collecting
numbers, and the Patriots collected some big ones and one little
one. Edwards rushed for 100 yards for the first time in his career
while also becoming the first rookie since the NFL-AFL merger to
score a touchdown in each of his first five games. Terry Glenn
finished with seven receptions for 78 yards and once again could
have had more had a couple of throws been on target. Drew Bledsoe
threw for three touchdowns, including two to Coates in a reminder
of the old days. But as important as all those numbers were, the
smallest ones, like the 14 yards the defense allowed the Chiefs'
running game, said the most.
</P>
<P>
   Those 14 yards rushing were the second lowest allowed in Patriot
history and led to a remarkable total yardage disparity of 304
yards (438 vs. 134) and an equally mind-boggling difference in time
of possession. The Patriots controlled the ball for nearly three
quarters of the game (41:48 to 18:12), dominating with Edwards's
power runs and Bledsoe's deft passing until the Chiefs finally did
what no one thought they'd do.
</P>
<P>
   They spit the bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``By halftime they just quit,'' Patriots linebacker Chris Slade
said. ``When we stopped them on fourth down (after Henry Thomas
stuffed up the middle and linebackers Todd Collins and Ted Johnson
slammed down Tony Richardson for no gain on a fourth and 1) it
seemed to stun them.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently so, because New England not only scored on that drive
to make it 10-0 but went on to score the next five times it had the
ball. By the time they finally slowed down, the Patriots had made a
statement, all right.
</P>
<P>
   What that statement means in the long run is difficult to assess
24 hours after the fact, but if nothing else it surely accomplished
one thing. It will give old friend Bill Parcells heartburn all week
as he tries to prepare his New York Jets for a Monday night
confrontation here in another game where Willie Clay and his
teammates will try to make a statement.
</P>
<P>
   A statement just like Sunday's.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion they're the best team we've played and that
includes the Minnesota Vikings,'' Chiefs' coach Marty
Schottenheimer said. ``They've got offense, they've got defense.
Clearly they had the better of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on a gray, rainy day that was loud and clear to everyone at
Foxboro Stadium. Especially the Chiefs.
</P>
</TEXT>
