u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     10-12 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN DIEGO _ The first question to Bobby Cox before Game 4 of the
National League Championship Series concerned a cat named Andres.
The Braves' manager was asked why Atlanta's cleanup hitter, Andres
Galarraga, seemed to be clean out of hits and RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Cat, 1-for-11 with five strikeouts and performing more
like a fat cat, hadn't issued a loud hiss in this series, which the
Padres were trying to end shockingly in the minimum four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just missing some pitches,'' Cox said. ``Hitting some
high pop-ups, things like that. We feel he's getting close. As you
know, a guy like him can carry you in a series like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox shrugged. ``Maybe today,'' he said, ``Andres can unleash
some of his power.''
</P>
<P>
   But after three plate appearances Sunday, Galarraga had
unleashed nothing, walking twice and grounding weakly into a double
play to stifle a potential breakout inning that had begun with
Keith Lockhart's leadoff triple and Chipper Jones' ensuing RBI
single.
</P>
<P>
   When Galarraga arrived in the batter's box with the bases loaded
in the seventh inning, he was the only Braves starter other than
the pitcher, Denny Neagle, who didn't have a hit. Although
Atlanta's brink-of-disaster lumber slumber was showing signs of
being over _ Javy Lopez's home run and Ozzie Guillen's RBI single
had just put the Braves up 4-3 _ Galarraga was still snoozing.
</P>
<P>
   A catnap? He must have lulled Dan Miceli to sleep, too. If prior
results matter, and baseball people surely act as though they do,
the Padres had to love the matchup. Galarraga was 1-for-7 with five
strikeouts against Miceli, explaining why Miceli had been hustled
out to the mound at such a crucial juncture.
</P>
<P>
   Playing the percentages, they call it. But the past should never
be used as a fail-safe guide for predicting the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought the odds were with us tonight with
(Galarraga's) bat,'' Cox said, reflecting on his now-prophetic
pre-game comments. ``It had to happen sometime and, boy, it was a
big one tonight. Just a big, big hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Miceli's second pitch to Galarraga, a 92-mph fastball over the
middle of the plate, was ripped so hard and so far, neither San
Diego outfielder in the vicinity of where it rocketed out of the
park, on a line above the fence in left-center, bothered to move
more than a couple of steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit a ball he could handle,'' said Padres manager Bruce
Bochy. ``Miceli didn't have anyplace to put him after he'd fallen
behind. We were in a jam there. That's going to happen sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Some dingers ring louder than others. This one was deafening,
and it hushed rowdy Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, `Thank you, God,' for this one,''' Galarraga
admitted. ``That is probably the best pitch I've seen in the whole
series.''
</P>
<P>
   The locals, 65,042 strong, had come to celebrate San Diego's
second-ever National League pennant, this one to be secured not at
the expense of the hapless, lovable Cubs, as was the case in 1984,
but over the team everyone else in the league loves to hate. The
Braves inspire jealousy because they spend and win at will,
explaining why they have become permanent participants in the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   Seven in a row. But Atlanta, batting .200 against the Padres
through three losses, was in danger of going down swinging _ and,
mostly, missing. Would you believe 34 K's after 30 innings? And the
Braves' offense had produced just three runs behind John Smoltz,
Tom Glavine, Greg Maddux and, after three innings, Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   So Galarraga, who has accumulated more than 500 RBIs over the
past four regular seasons, exceeded said total with one mighty
swing. It was the sixth grand slam in NLCS history, and only time
will tell whether it's too little too late for Atlanta, which had
brought him down from Colorado for moments such as these.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has recovered from a 3-0 deficit in a baseball playoff
series. The Padres remain cocky enough occupying the catbird seat
that Bochy won't do what he did against the Astros _ that is, send
Kevin Brown out on three days' rest tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Bochy is finished gambling. He'll stick with his rotation this
time, pitching Andy Ashby against Smoltz in a repeat of the Game 1
pairing the Padres took, after a two-hour rain delay, in 10 innings
3-2. Brown, San Diego's brightest postseason star, will be saved
for a possible Game 6 matchup Wednesday in Atlanta against Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Andy's turn,'' Bochy said. ``He's a big reason why we're
in this situation. And he's pitching on his normal days' rest.
That's why he'll be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   What did Smoltz think of the 8-3 win?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still playing,'' he said. ``That's what we have to focus
on, nothing else. Of all the teams that have been down 3-0, I like
our chances the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 3-1 isn't a fun place to be, but compared to what could
have been their alternative, it's well, it's the Cat's meow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
