<HEADER>
A1248 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NLCS-HNS &LR;      10-12 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
SAN DIEGO _ ``Sweep, sweep, sweep.'' The chant was almost
deafening, and that was before the first pitch had been thrown.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some two hours later Sunday, you could have made a case that the
Q in Qualcomm Stadium stood for quiet. That was around the time the
Atlanta Braves silenced the crowd by scoring six runs in the
seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   It served as the catalyst for the Braves' 8-3 victory over the
San Diego Padres and helped them avoid being swept in the National
League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Open mouth, insert broom; there would be no sweep party on this
night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Braves brushed up on the subject of winning,
something it appeared they had forgotten how to do until the
must-win wake-up call of Game 4. The Braves turned a one-run
deficit into a five-run lead with the explosive seventh-inning
rally keyed by Andres Galarraga's grand slam off Padres reliever
Dan Miceli. It was only the sixth bases-loaded homer in the history
of the NLCS and the first since Gary Gaetti hit one for St. Louis
against the Braves in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I hit it, I said, `Thank you, God,''' Galarraga
said. ``It was a fastball right down the middle of the plate.
That's probably the best pitch I'll see in this series. That's the
biggest home run I've ever hit. I kept us alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres will get a second chance to finish off the Braves
tonight when they send Andy Ashby to the mound against John Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still going to be do-or-die for us,'' Braves left fielder
Ryan Klesko said. ``But with the type of pitching we have, you
can't count us out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's starting pitchers _ Atlanta's Denny Neagle and San
Diego's Joey Hamilton _ basically battled to a stalemate, but the
game turned on the ineffectiveness of the Padres' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Relievers Randy Myers and Miceli allowed three hits and four
runs in the decisive seventh inning. The Braves had scored one run
off the Padres' relievers in their first seven innings of NLCS
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bullpen had been doing a great job, but it just didn't
happen for us tonight,'' Padres manager Bruce Bochy said. ``They
couldn't quite get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Padres did their job, knocking out Neagle in
the sixth inning. Hamilton was soon to follow. From that point, it
became a battle of the bullpens _ a showdown the Braves won easily.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Martinez, John Rocker, Odalis Perez, Rudy Seanez and
Kerry Ligtenberg shut out the Padres over the final 3 innings. The
Padres managed three baserunners after Neagle left the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves welcomed the return of their offense, which managed
to score more than two runs for the first time in the series. Not
surprisingly, the middle of the Braves' batting order _ dormant for
most of the series _ played a large role in the offensive
awakening. Chipper Jones, Galarraga and Klesko combined for four
hits, three runs and six RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone came through,'' Klesko said. ``We hope this gets us
going again. It's key for us to drive in some runs, because more
times than not, our pitching is going to give us a very good chance
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres' chances of winning the game and wrapping up the
series looked pretty good in the third inning when second baseman
Quilvio Veras walked and scored on Tony Gwynn's double into the
right-field gap. Jim Leyritz singled home Gwynn to give the Padres
a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton promptly gave back one of the runs in the fourth
inning, when Braves second baseman Keith Lockhart crushed the first
pitch of the inning over Steve Finley's head in center field for a
triple. Jones brought Lockhart home with a single to left.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves tied the score in the sixth inning with some clutch
two-out hitting by Jones and Klesko. Jones ripped a double down the
right-field line and scored on Klesko's base hit to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``The odds were definitely in favor of those guys getting some
hits to fall sooner or later,'' Hamilton said of the Braves' Big
Three, who are hitting just .184 in the NLCS. ``They're all good
hitters, and good hitters are going to get their fair share of
hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz energized the crowd of 65,042 in the sixth when he hit a
line-drive home run over the wall in right field to put the Padres
up by a run. It was Leyritz's fourth home run this postseason and
the seventh playoff homer of his career. The crowd didn't settle
down until Leyritz took a curtain call.
</P>
<P>
   ``That felt nice,'' he said. ``At that point, I thought we had
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He thought wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton mishandled prosperity again, this time serving up a
game-tying, first-pitch homer to Javy Lopez to open the seventh
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just a bad pitch,'' Hamilton said. ``It was so bad, I
don't even see how Javy hit it. That pitch almost hit him in the
neck.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves then went for the jugular. Ozzie Guillen put them on
top later in the seventh with an RBI single off Myers, and
Galarraga's grand slam put the game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time the bats came around,'' Cox said. ``It was
time for the worm to turn a little bit with our lumber.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
