</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELLS PROVED A REAL CHARACTER WIN 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ He looks like a sack of inner tubes under a Yankee
baseball cap. He gets away with facial hair when none of his
teammates are allowed a whisker. He's the only Yankee who told the
Boss to put up his dukes when the two exchanged insults in the
clubhouse last year. When ubiquitous locker room suckup Kevin
Costner offered congratulations, David Wells said, ``Hey, Dude. You
want a jockstrap or something?''
</P>
<P>
   And on this World Series-bound team of past, present, and future
stars _ a team that has now won a major league record 120 regular
and postseason games _ David Wells is The Man. Sunday, he beat the
Indians, 5-3, in the fifth game of the ALCS, and dedicated the
victory to the fans who hazed him about his late mother while he
was warming up in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those idiots out there _ this one's for you,'' Wells said
after the game. ``When you get a bunch of clowns out there who
start talking about your mother, not knowing that my mom passed
away a year and a half ago ... There were some low lifes out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of got me out of focus and it took me a while. I was
fighting myself. I played against the Yankees for a long time, and
I never heard anybody get personal with my family members at Yankee
Stadium. And this is not the first time it's happened in Cleveland
with me. I don't understand it and I don't appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells got off to a shaky start. After getting staked to a 3-0
first-inning lead (it took Cleveland starter Chad Ogea almost a
half hour to get three outs), he almost gave it all back in the
bottom of the frame.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Lofton led with a homer just inside the foul pole, then
Omar Vizquel and Travis Fryman singled and Wells had to face the
heart of the Cleveland order. He compounded the pressure by
uncorking a wild pitch, but got out of the inning, still leading,
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little uncomfortable when he got behind on the
hitters,'' said Yankee manager Joe Torre. ``Normally when we get
him runs he shuts them down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to wake up,'' admitted Wells. ``Obviously. I had to move
the ball around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' star southpaw struck out at least one batter in
every one of his innings except the fourth. He was The Show _ even
on a ball he never touched. Early in the game, Wells charged toward
the Yankee dugout after a pop fly and almost tumbled down the steps
as the ball bounded out of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was goofy all night,'' Torre said. ``He's just one of many
colorful players who play the game. He's a loose horse, no question
about it. He enjoys the game and it's catching.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some laughter on the mound when Torre came out to lift
him in favor of Jeff Nelson in the eighth. Wells had just fanned
Vizquel, giving him five punchouts of the previous eight batters.
Like a band refusing to leave the stage, Wells initially would not
give Torre the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a second wind,'' said Wells. ``I felt like I did in the
second or third inning. I just wouldn't give him the ball. He tried
to pry it out of my hand. That's how good I felt. I wanted to stay
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine refusing to yield the baseball. Wells never wants to
come out. He never wants to rest. He said he'll pitch Game 7 of
this series on two days rest if they need him. He wanted to pitch
Game 4 when the Yankees trailed, 2 games to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said, ``He had some left. He wanted me to send Nellie
back. I told him to just go and get the round of applause.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland fans showered him with mock cheers as Wells walked to
the dugout. He waved his cap at them in mock appreciation. It was
good theater.
</P>
<P>
   Torre's move almost backfired when Nelson put two runners on
base, but Mariano Rivera made an early entrance and got a double
play grounder from perennial bowser, Mark Whiten.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real testimony to his ability that Wells was able to
pitch that deep into the game,'' said Cleveland manager Mike
Hargrove. ``It didn't look like he had command of his pitches like
he did in the past, but he pitched well enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells went 18-4 with a 3.49 ERA this year. He pitched a perfect
game, appeared on Letterman, and started the All-Star Game. On a
team with David Cone and Andy Pettitte, there was never any doubt
who the No. 1 starter was. Wells is now 3-0 with a 2.90 ERA in the
1998 postseason and he'll be ready to start the first game of the
World Series in New York Saturday night. Or Wednesday in Game 7.
His lifetime postseason record is 7-1 with a 2.41 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably prouder of this effort tonight than the shutouts
and the perfect game because of what it meant to us,'' said Torre.
``He had so much fun with it tonight. He's an animal. He goes after
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland fans should have learned a lesson from Fenway nuts. In
1990, Boston fans taunted Oakland's proud righty, Dave Stewart,
calling him ``Lucille'' while he warmed up in the bullpen. Stewart
took the mound and beat the Red Sox, 9-1, en route to another
Oakland sweep of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Some guys cave in when they're mocked. Guys like Stewart and
Wells just come back and beat you in your own house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 0117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
