<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIMPRESSIVE OPENING ACT FOR BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Mass. _ He had had a night to sleep on it and rehash
it over and over.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the final analysis, Bruins coach Pat Burns, though
pleased his team escaped with a point in the 3-3 tie with St. Louis
in the season opener, wasn't all that excited about the
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Saturday) night we didn't play well,'' said Burns, after
leading the Bruins through a spirited, and often times physical,
90-minute practice Sunday at Ristuccia Arena. ``Everybody in the
dressing room knew it. We went out there, we hadn't played in over
a week, it was opening game, the big celebration. Those things all
came into play.
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't excuses, these are the facts. The players knew
after the game that they didn't play that well. We gave them the
puck a lot. We did things that the Boston Bruins last year never
did. That's why we have training camp. This is all starting over
again.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Burns did like was the goaltending of Byron Dafoe, who
turned back 29 of 32 shots, and who couldn't be blamed for two of
St. Louis's three goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Byron Dafoe kept us in the game the whole time,'' said Burns,
who watched the Bruins twice overcome two-goal deficits. ``We were
making some awful mistakes out there. I think the puck weighed
about 20 pounds there for awhile. We were getting a lot of passes
intercepted.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he'll come right back with Dafoe in Monday's holiday
matinee against the Islanders at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Burns, facing a seven-game road trip after Monday's game, was
asked how important it was to crack the win column before heading
out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game's important, every one of them,'' he said. ``If we
lose the game, we don't say `Oh, no, we lost the game and now we
have to go on the road and it's going to be disastrous.' Everybody
asks `Is this the most important one, is that the most important
one?' Every game's important, including (Monday's).
</P>
<P>
   ``But like I say, there's going to be highs, there's going to be
lows and we know that. But you can't tell the players, `If we lose
this game, boys, we're done on the road trip.' You might as well go
to Hawaii and send the points in to the other team if you're
thinking that way. We're going out to try and win every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob DiMaio thinks a win against the Islanders would be the
perfect going-away gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would mean a lot to us confidence-wise before going on such
a long road trip,'' said the Bruins winger. ``It would be nice to
know we play well at home. These points that we get here are
invaluable because you never know what will happen on a long road
trip. Oh, yeah, they're very important to team confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to be a good home team and if you can have momentum
going on a road trip like this, it can do nothing but benefit you.
We're looking to have a good solid game and take that with us on
the road.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dmitri Khristich, slowed the past two weeks with a shoulder
sprain, skated full tilt Sunday and Burns said he'll play Monday.
Burns also said Chris Taylor, who sat out the opener, will suit up.
Peter Nordstrom, Peter Ferraro, and Antti Laaksonen are among the
candidates to be scratched. Burns said rookie defenseman and top
pick Jonathan Girard also will sit this one out ... Defenseman
Dennis Vaske was the only player to miss the practice. He is out
indefinitely with back muscle spasms ... The Bruins have redesigned
their web page (www.bostonbruins.com) in conjunction with their
75th anniversary season. There's a team history page as well as
player bios and updated statistics ... The Islanders fell to the
Penguins, 4-3, in their opener. New York fell behind, 4-0, in the
first period before scrambling back.
</P>
</TEXT>
