<HEADER>
A1253 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHER-RAISES-2TAKES     10-12 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-RAISES-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SCHOOL DISTRICT MAY USE BOOK AID FOR RAISES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY AND TERRI HARDY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Los Angeles school board members are likely this
week to reopen negotiations with teachers -- and top administrators
and other staff -- for new pay raises using a $60 million state
funding windfall intended for textbooks and improved educational
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Three board members said in interviews they are willing to
consider a 2 percent districtwide hike and sources said there is no
serious opposition from the other board members.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on top of a contract for a 10 percent pay raise over
three years signed just last year, the new raises are certain to
spark controversy for a district already facing a potential breakup
movement and Mayor Richard Riordan's well-funded effort to seize
control of the board in next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles teachers -- who in a recent year beat the county,
state and national average for teachers with pay of $44,474 for
about nine months of work -- are spearheading the effort to reopen
negotiations. But board sources said any raise also would be
granted to administrators and other employees.
</P>
<P>
   The board is expected to discuss the issue Tuesday behind closed
doors.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers union and some board members said the Los Angeles
Unified School District should boost salaries to remain competitive
with other districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a teacher shortage,'' said school board member Valerie
Fields, whose district includes the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be competitive,'' said Fields, who was a primary
grade teacher for 12 years. ``We want to get teachers with
credentials. We don't want to rely on people with emergency
credentials. We need to do what we can to attract and retain
qualified teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996-97, the most recent year for which national comparative
figures are available, the LAUSD teacher's average of $44,474
compared with averages of $42,992 statewide and $38,436 nationwide.
Los Angeles ranked ahead of San Diego and San Francisco in starting
salaries but lagged behind in pay for teachers with advanced
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal on the table would extend pay raises not only to
teachers but to all other employees and even could be the basis of
raising salaries for the superintendent and other top managers.
</P>
<P>
   Board members Julie Korenstein and David Tokofsky said they
would vote to reopen contract discussions if accountability
measures are part of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the economy was foundering, the teachers saved the school
district by taking pay cuts,'' Tokofsky said. ``Now, when the
economy is booming, it seems only fair that they should benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   School board member Jeff Horton declined comment on the issue
because it involved labor negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Barbara Boudreaux said she would consider granting
pay increases to all school employee groups and restoring
eliminated jobs, such as those of gardeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to reopen negotiations if accountability is part
of the pay raises,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not morally correct or politically correct to ask for pay
raises if you are not performing for that raise,'' Boudreaux said,
adding that she is not satisfied with the steps the United Teachers
Los Angeles union has taken thus far to hold members accountable
for student performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``UTLA has been dragging its feet, and that troubles me,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
