<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEFS TAKE OFF WEEK A LITTLE EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The National Football League had the Kansas
City Chiefs scheduled for an off day next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Patriots, they decided to take it a week
early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the worst game we've played since I've been
here,'' said general manager Carl Peterson. Coach Marty
Schottenheimer wasn't quite sure if he agreed. ``It could have
been,'' he said, ``but there might have been ones just as bad that
fell through the cracks and you don't remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played bad, and that is disturbing. I had no idea this
would happen. I didn't think we could make the kind of mental
mistakes we made today. We made enough mistakes in this game to
last us a whole season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have the bye week to deal with these problems. The
solutions are right there in the locker room, and we are going to
deal with those next week. We have the players to play a lot better
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs failed in every phase of the game: offense, defense,
special teams, and, most of all, mentally. They did some things
that were just plain stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, one talk show analyst said this was a game that
would show if the Patriots could reach the next level.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, the question was: Could the Chiefs get back to
the level they have played at in recent years?
</P>
<P>
   These are not the Chiefs of even a year ago. They are not as
formidable along the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the game, the Chiefs were the No. 1 defensive team in
the league, giving up 240 yards per game. Sunday they gave up 438,
nearly double what they had allowed in each of their first five
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they got us down, 17-0, they could do just about anything
they wanted to do,'' said the Chiefs' Derrick Thomas, who was
handled by Bruce Armstrong of the Patriots. ``We never got them in
(long-yardage) positions where we wanted them to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs had been giving up just 127 passing yards per game.
Bledsoe had 174 at the half behind great protection from his
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   The calling card of the Chiefs' defense is its speed, and it has
a great reputation for pressuring the passer.
</P>
<P>
   But Foxboro Stadium is not Arrowhead Stadium in Kansas City,
where the Chiefs are nearly invincible with their noisy home crowd
impacting the offense of the visiting team.
</P>
<P>
   In this one, the opposite happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``This crowd really got into the game when they jumped on us
like that,'' said Chiefs center Tim Grunhard. ``When a team jumps
in front like that, the defensive coordinators get very creative.
They give you things you've never seen before. And that is tough to
deal with. We just couldn't run the ball, and that made it tough.
But we will be better. We have to believe we are better than this.
New England is very good. Edwards seemed to give them real energy,
the way he was running with the ball and made extra yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the numbers, these tell the story of the game: The
Patriots rushed for 206 yards, the Chiefs 14. And the Patriots
controlled the ball for 41:48, leaving the Chiefs 18:12.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the game, the Patriots were 29th, or second worst, in
the league in time of possession, averaging 26 minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was easy for them,'' said Schottenheimer. ``They
played excellent. You cannot give a quarterback of that caliber the
time he had to throw the ball today. He never had to feel hurried.
He could feel very comfortable and say to himself, `today is going
to be one of those days.' He made some outstanding plays, and some
throws that only a few quarterbacks in this league can make.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our side, the frustration is the dumb things we did.
Roughing the kicker when we had great field position. Getting a
penalty on a field goal that gives them a first down and sets them
up for a touchdown. We don't usually play like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The little things killed us on offense,'' said Chiefs
quarterback Elvis Grbac. ``Offsides, going in motion. There is no
reason for that. These are things that we have to correct.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was their day,'' said Schottenheimer. ``Take nothing away
from them. They were excellent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
