u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-     10-12 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT SCHEME GIVES BLEDSOE MORE CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The only question left after the Patriots
offense shredded what is universally regarded as one of the NFL's
better defenses may be this: What does Larry Kennan think now of
the emerging juggernaut in New England?
</P>
<P>
   Week by week the New England offense is emerging from the
darkness and murk of last season and improving game by game, so
much so that, as receiver Terry Glenn put it, ``Guys are really
starting to jell. We've got a lot of confidence in each other
now.'' Glenn said he wasn't surprised the Patriots scored 40 points
Sunday, saying the Chiefs ``kind of gave up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   At the center of what is becoming a fine mix of running and
passing is the quarterback, Drew Bledsoe. And, as Glenn pointed
out, Bledsoe and the offense should be getting better as the season
wears on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only my third year here and we're into our third
different offense,'' said Glenn, who had seven catches for 78
yards. ``And it was a little difficult to learn at first. And right
now we're starting to learn it and Drew is starting to feel
comfortable with it. And I think that's the big key _ Drew feeling
comfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Comfortable?
</P>
<P>
   So much so that Patriot fans Sunday saw Bledsoe do something
that no one ever imagined he could or would do _ run a naked
bootleg that left jaws gaping all across New England and resulted
in a 23-yard pass to a wide-open Glenn. Not to mention Bledsoe's
ducking under Kansas City's Derrick Thomas, scooting away from the
Chiefs' rush, and hitting Robert Edwards with a nifty 15-yard TD
pass in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just kind of an impromptu kind of play,'' said
Bledsoe, who has been adding improvisational quarterbacking to his
usual repertoire of crisp passes from the pocket to Glenn, Ben
Coates, Shawn Jefferson, and friends. The TD pass to Edwards ``was
designed to go to Terry to the right _ I had three receivers to the
right _ but the Chiefs did a nice job of covering it. I felt some
pressure from the backside, but I think Bruce Armstrong did a nice
job of running their guy by me and then I saw Robert ... and I
chucked it out there ... and he made a great catch for the
touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   And the play from the ozone, the naked bootleg? The play that
even his teammates knew nothing about?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the option is going in next week,'' first joked
Bledsoe. ``But naaah ... it's something we've talked about at
different times during the season. My intention was to try and run
for the first down, but when the guy came off (Glenn), I threw it
to Terry. Nobody else knew about it, so I figured it was probably
going to be called back because there was going to be a penalty for
linemen downfield. But it so happened that nobody was downfield,
and it ended up being a great play.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is all coming together for the offense, coordinator Ernie
Zampese's system doing so much more than Kennan's offense did last
year, Bledsoe quarterbacking better than ever, Edwards running the
ball very well, and the receivers intense and involved, all of
which gives opposing defenses much to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take our receivers against anyone,'' said Bledsoe. ``I
told Terry Glenn before the game, `Listen, you're going to have
(cornerback) Dale Carter on you, but I'm coming at you anyway
because I think you can get open on him.' And Terry did a nice job
on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Which may be the final factor in the offense renaissance,
Glenn's returning to past form. Man-to-man against Carter, one of
the better corners in the league, was a challenge that Glenn said
he welcomed. Time after time, Glenn escaped Carter's jamming at the
line of scrimmage and beat the corner, before Carter hurt his knee
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carter may be the best corner in the league,'' said Glenn.
``He plays the position almost as if he's the wide receiver. At
first, he was playing the position the way he always plays it, but
then we started beating him with some short outside stuff, and then
he changed his bump-and-run stuff and came up even more. And then
Drew was able to go at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly with short slants, ``and we were able to attack him
the way Carter was doing his defense,'' said Glenn. ``I started
releasing to the inside and Drew hit me on a couple of slants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We played as good as we can play against a good team,'' said
Bledsoe. But the Patriots, Bledsoe went on, ``weren't trying to
fool them except for a few plans to contain Derrick Thomas. We
didn't really do anything special.''
</P>
<P>
   Which may be the most pleasant prospect of all for New England
fans, that Sunday's 40 points against a good defense may be more
routine than extraordinary. As was supposed to happen _ but didn't
_ last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
