</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EDWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS SCRAMBLES TO MAKE TD CATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ On the play that coach Pete Carroll called
``the big play of the day,'' Robert Edwards was doing his duty,
protecting Drew Bledsoe from Derrick Thomas and onrushing pals,
when the scheme broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play wasn't designed to go to me,'' said Edwards, the
Patriots' rookie running back. ``I was supposed to be blocking the
back side and I looked back and saw that Drew was scrambling.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, football instinct must come to the fore to save a busted
play. Some players have that instinct, many don't, just as some
teams have it collectively and some don't. But on that first-down
play from the Chiefs' 15-yard line early in the second quarter,
Edwards showed he is more than a promising running back. Much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were always taught in camp and at the beginning of the
season,'' said Edwards, explaining why he departed from his
blocking duty, ``that whenever Drew scrambles, we should try and
get open, so Drew won't get hit. So I scrambled and Drew just laid
the ball out.''
</P>
<P>
   It might have been enough in assessing the full Edwards package
that the back found an opening in the Chiefs' secondary, giving
Bledsoe an inviting target, but when Bledsoe threw the pass, it was
a bit too long, forcing Edwards to leap through the air headlong.
But the rookie not only caught up to the pass, he had the soft
hands to caress the ball before landing in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went for it,'' said Edwards of his catch, which would have
been remarkable even for a wide receiver, and then modestly added,
``It was a good throw.'' Said Carroll of the TD grab: ``That was an
incredible catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards Sunday gained 104 yards on 23 attempts in little more
than a half of football, his first 100-yard game in the NFL.
Edwards Sunday scored two TDs, the fifth consecutive game he has
scored, the first time since the 1970 NFL-AFL merger a rookie had
scored a TD in his first five pro games. Edwards showed he is more
than a football player with numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The part that you have to like about him,'' said Carroll, ``is
his ability to break a tackle. This really is the first time that
(opposing) guys couldn't get him down. He came around the corner a
couple of times and there was one guy, two guys, three guys he just
kept shaking off.''
</P>
<P>
   Most New England football fans know that Edwards, in effect, was
traded for Curtis Martin. The Patriots used the draft choice the
Jets gave up for signing Martin to select Edwards as their first
pick. So far, so very good.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my first couple of games, I was thinking a lot,'' said
Edwards. ``I was trying not to make mistakes, but now I'm getting
more comfortable and I'm starting to relax and just go out there
and play just like I did at Georgia. I'm not second-guessing myself
now on a lot of things I do; I'm just making a decision and going
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert is not the fastest guy and he's not the toughest guy in
terms of running people over,'' said teammate Terry Glenn, ``but
he's got all of it mixed in together. Now when we look for guys to
step up and make big plays, that's what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, for one, said Edwards's impressive entry into the NFL
was not surprising to him. ``We drafted him in the first round
because of his talents,'' said the QB, ``and he's really starting
to show those talents now. He's doing a nice job running with some
freedom and making some nice cuts. He's also doing a nice job of
making some yards after that first hit.''
</P>
<P>
   And this isn't surprising to be happening so soon?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' replied Bledsoe. ``I mean, he's a first-round draft pick
... that's what he's supposed to do. You know, I was a first-round
draft pick as a quarterback and I was supposed to come in and play.
That's what he's supposed to do, but he's doing a nice job of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, from words of many Patriots, it is becoming clearer that
Edwards not only may be as good as hoped when he was drafted first
by the team, he may be even better. The comparisons to that last
good running back to come out of Georgia _ the Broncos' Terrell
Davis _ now do not seem as far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's strong and he runs aggressively,'' said Carroll of his
rookie. ``And he slashes at you and he just keeps on coming.''
</P>
<P>
   But Edwards also has that football instinct and he has those
soft hands, and now his presence alone does so much for New
England's passing game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious that (Edwards's running) has a big effect on our
passing success,'' said Carroll. And as Kansas City coach Marty
Schottenheimer put it, ``If you let them run the ball, they've got
a double-edged sword, and you've got a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the words from Kansas City center Jeff Smith captured
this phenomenon of a rookie back, still virtually anonymous outside
New England but who is making the plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think their running back, that young kid they have,'' said
Smith, ``is going to be great.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said the politically correct words, that ``I'm not here
to replace Curtis, I'm just here to do my job, and I'm just trying
to do my job well. But now I'm getting better and I'm starting to
feel a lot of things. I'm just reacting now and not thinking about
what I'm doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1263 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-     10-12 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS DEFENSE PULLS OUT ALL THE STOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Willie McGinest, bothered by an encroachment
call against him with 4:42 left in the first quarter Sunday, yanked
off his helmet and gave the officials an earful. The officials
yanked out their yellow flags and gave the Patriots defensive
lineman a 15-yard unsportsmanlike conduct penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The outburst moved the ball from the Chiefs' 24-yard line to the
39, and it marked the first blunder by a unit that stalled the
Chiefs on Kansas City's first drive of the game and forced a
turnover on the second. When Chiefs quarterback Elvis Grbac
completed an 8-yard sideline pass to Kimble Anders on first down,
it appeared as if momentum was shifting.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Chiefs thought so, too, for on second and 2 they ran
the ball up the middle, electing to attack the core of the defense.
Donnell Bennett gained 1 yard, so Kansas City tried again, up the
middle on third and 1. No gain by Bennett, stopped by McGinest and
Lawyer Milloy. The Patriots had made their case, but the Chiefs
wanted one more try at their core.
</P>
<P>
   And the guy who began the series with an embarrassing loss of
temper couldn't have been happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted them to go for it,'' McGinest said. ``I wasn't ready
to get off the field yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs ran up the middle a third time, and saw Henry Thomas
seal the middle and linebackers Ted Johnson and Todd Collins jump
over the top to stop fullback Tony Richardson. Momentum never came
close to shifting after that, and the Patriots went on to a 40-10
rout of the Chiefs. It marked New England's first win over Kansas
City since Oct. 4, 1981.
</P>
<P>
   A Chiefs offense that entered Sunday's game averaging 127.6
rushing yards and 184.2 passing yards a game managed just 14 yards
rushing (2 yards in the second half) and 120 yards passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To hold a team that prides itself on running the ball, that
says something,'' said free safety Willie Clay. ``We had a lot of
guys running to the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots also had one interception against an offense that
hadn't thrown one all season. Kansas City converted just one of 10
third-down plays in the game and was 0 for 2 on fourth down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We practiced the (fourth down and 1) play all week and we knew
in that situation they give the ball to the fullback,'' said
Johnson. ``It was great penetration by the defensive line. That's
the key to that deal. You have days like that. A lot of things went
our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson led the team with six tackles, followed by Milloy with
five. Slade had three tackles, one forced fumble, and one sack.
McGinest, who left the game briefly because of a left knee injury,
had two tackles and one pass defensed.
</P>
<P>
   In helping lead the charge, the defensive end made up for his
outburst. ``Things like that just get me hyped,'' said McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people see the game and they think, `Oh, he's going
to lose his head. He's overreacting,''' he said, ``but the tackle
clearly jumped. And I went off his move and they called me. Then I
took off my helmet. I wasn't thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that I just got so fired up and my adrenaline was
pumping and the defense just fed off of me. They thought they had
the momentum, and hey, our defense has said we're not going to let
anyone get a yard on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, which entered the game having scored at least 16
points in each of its five games, never got closer than the Patriot
36-yard line in the first quarter. When the Chiefs scored their
only touchdown, with 52 seconds left in the third quarter, the game
had all but been decided.
</P>
<P>
   That meant a lot to a unit that said all week it had read
clippings lauding Kansas City's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``All week long we heard stuff about us being underdogs and
Kansas City being a better team, No. 1 in defense and No. 1 in many
offensive categories,'' said McGinest. ``We just stayed humble, we
just wanted to come out and execute. When we play together as a
team it's hard to beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots might need a similar effort next Monday night, when
they host the New York Jets and their former coach, Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Santa Claus is coming to town,'' said Ty Law. ``(Parcells)
plays Santa Claus to the team and motivates his team to win. We
still didn't play a perfect game (Sunday). There were things we
need to improve on and coach Parcells will pick that up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
