<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALARRAGA GETS HIS GROOVE BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ At the time it sounded less like a hunch than a
hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel he's getting close,'' Atlanta manager Bobby Cox said
of his sluggish slugger Andres Galarraga two hours before the
Braves' do-or-die game against the Padres Sunday in the National
League Championship Series. ``He's just missing some pitches. Maybe
today he can unleash that power.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Cox's instincts were sharper than Ryan Leaf's
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga's October was developing as dismally as that of the
San Diego Chargers' petulant rookie quarterback. The Braves' first
baseman brought a batting average of .091 into the fourth game of
the best-of-seven series. The player who collected 121 RBI during
the regular season had one hit (and three errors) to his name,
which was starting to sound suspiciously like goat.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he trudged to the plate with the bases loaded in the
top of the seventh inning, he had left seven runners moored to
bases in 13 at-bats. He was well on his way to infamy when San
Diego reliever Dan Miceli delivered a reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   On a 1-0 count, Miceli threw a 92-mile-per-hour fastball that
Galarraga bashed over the left-center field fence with plenty of
room to spare. The ball soared some 440 feet and lifted the Braves
to an 8-3 win.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga's shot struck the collective gut of the Qualcomm
Stadium crowd of 65,042, which forgot a fundamental rule of
baseball in the sixth after Jim Leyritz's solo homer broke a 2-2
deadlock. Never mind that you never, ever, ever look one at-bat
ahead, much less nine outs, the carried-away crowd started chanting
``Sweep.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, already out of sorts after losing three games they
just as easily could have won, were in no mood to be baited.
Galarraga wasn't the only one who finally fought back against a
tide that was threatening to sweep the Braves out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez, last seen striking out Saturday to end the eighth
inning with the bases loaded and the Braves behind by one, struck
out on three straight pitches in his first plate appearance Sunday.
But he dug in and laced starter Joey Hamilton's first pitch of the
seventh over the right-field fence to knot the game at 3 and tie
the crowd's collective stomach in knots.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones then singled and advanced to second when Randy
Myers, who came on in relief of Hamilton, threw a wild pitch with
Greg Colbrunn at the plate. Ozzie Guillen, who was making his first
start of the series _ chalk it up to another Cox hunch _ singled
with two outs, scoring Jones, who easily beat Ruben Rivera's throw
from left after Rivera bobbled the ball. Keith Lockhart then
singled and Chipper Jones walked to set the stage for Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga had been there, botched that. He had flied out to deep
center in the 10th inning with the tying and winning runs on base
last Wednesday to end the first game.
</P>
<P>
   But he showed the same resiliency that had served him so well
during his 13-year wait to play in a NLCS. He also dredged up the
sweet swing that had produced 44 home runs during the regular
season. Galarraga, 37, froze as soon as the ball left his bat and
followed the majestic flight of the sixth grand slam in NLCS
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit it, I said, `Thank you God for this one,''' said
Galarraga, who started his major-league odyssey in Montreal and
moved on to St. Louis and Colorado before signing a three-year, $24
million deal with the Braves this past November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really needed (the homer) and the team really needed it to
stay alive,'' Galarraga said. ``They haven't been throwing me too
many good pitches. That's probably the best pitch I've seen all
series.''
</P>
<P>
   Well before Galarraga got his groove back, there were subtle
signs for those San Diego fans willing to take off their
rose-colored glasses that the Padres' charmed run was sputtering.
In the first inning outfielder Tony Gwynn struck out, a rarity
along the lines of a total eclipse of the sun. In 461
regular-season at-bats, he struck out only 18 times.
</P>
<P>
   He rebounded with a two-out double in the third that drove home
Quilvio Veras, whom starter Denny Neagle had walked, for the
Padres' first run. Leyritz singled Gwynn home and just like that
San Diego had one more run than the Braves had mustered in the
previous two games.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle, the starter whom everybody but Cox seemed to think
should be shunted for John Smoltz, yielded all the Padres' runs.
But Dennis Martinez, John Rocker, Odalis Perez, Rudy Seanez and
Kerry Ligtenberg stymied the Padres, allowing them only one hit the
rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is the Padres will get another look at Smoltz, who has
lost only one game since June 26. If nothing else, Cox's crew has
made good on its word to make this series interesting.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
