<SLUG> BC-FIESTA-STADIUM- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER FAILURE STUNS FIESTA  
</HEADLINE>
 BC_F AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - If Saturday's power failure at Sun Devil Stadium
didn't spark Fiesta Bowl Executive Director John Junker to push for
a new home for his game, it did provide a jolt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be evident why there are concerns,'' Junker said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Junker was watching the Notre Dame-Arizona State game from a
press-level suite when a transformer blew during halftime, causing
most of the stadium's electricity to fail and knocking the ABC
regional telecast temporarily off the air.
</P>
<P>
   When he became aware of the extent of the problem, Junker said
his thoughts went something like, ``Thank goodness this isn't a
night game, and thank goodness this isn't January 4.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the date of what college football is billing as its
national championship, in the Fiesta Bowl at Sun Devil Stadium _ at
night. A similar occurrence ``would not be in the best interests of
the Valley of the Sun, Arizona and our community,'' Junker said in
an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had it been a night game, it would have been a real mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Last April, Junker voiced concerns about the condition of Sun
Devil Stadium as it relates to other, newer stadiums that might
want to join the Bowl Championship Series that currently includes
the Fiesta, Orange, Rose and Sugar bowls.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Junker said he was ``keeping an open mind'' about
the Cardinals' proposed $650 million stadium at Rio Salado and that
he was wondering about the future of Sun Devil Stadium, which is 40
years old.
</P>
<P>
   After the incident on Saturday, Junker said his view was
reinforced, but he would not talk about the new stadium proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so busy preparing for the game, we haven't taken a
specific position, per se,'' he said. ``But one position we have
taken is that we have to have the best place possible to continue
our growth. That shouldn't be surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU stadium manager Tom Sadler, who said it might be several
days before the cause of the problem is known, rented a generator
and had it installed Saturday night. There was full power for
Sunday's Chicago Bears-Cardinals game.
</P>
<P>
   Junker praised Sadler and his staff, ``but it's obvious there
are reasons to have concerns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of those apparently is television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly was a wake-up call,'' said ABC producer Jay
Rothman, who will produce the Fiesta Bowl. ``We will do everything,
based on (Saturday), to be bullet-proof in terms of having the
appropriate power, generators, what have you.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC did not have a backup generator on hand and was able to
resume its telecast only when limited power was restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very unusual situation to have this in a major
stadium, considering that it's also an NFL stadium,'' said director
Chip Dean, an ASU graduate who played free safety for Frank Kush in
the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will we be prepared to guard against this? Certainly. Do I
think this is a black mark against the Fiesta Bowl because maybe
the stadium is old? Definitely not. I look at it simply as a
strange situation that we'll address and they'll address.''
</P>
<P>
   Topics already being addressed include relocating the broadcast
booth, from which Keith Jackson will call his last college football
game, and improving camera placements. The press box at ASU is
among the highest of any stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   All the Fiesta Bowl tickets have been sold, so ABC likely would
have to buy some seats, remove them, and then build its new press
box.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
