<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COATES'S ACTIONS SPEAK LOUDER THAN WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Ben Coates was a man of many moves but few
words Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But his statistics did the talking after the Patriots' 40-10
thrashing of the Chiefs, a game in which Coates caught two passes _
both for touchdowns _ to move into a distant second place on the
Patriots' all-time list with 44 career scoring receptions, behind
Stanley Morgan (67).
</P>
<P>
   The difference, of course, is that Morgan was a wide receiver
and Coates is a tight end who does a lot more than just catch
passes in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take my receivers against anybody's,'' said quarterback
Drew Bledsoe, who hit Coates with a 2-yard strike in the second
quarter and an 11-yard toss into the right corner of the end zone
that had the veteran Coates stretched to the limit late in the
third quarter, making it 34-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was OK, two catches, two scores,'' said Coates before
quickly departing the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Coates passed Gino Cappelletti (42 TD catches) and with his 13
receiving yards, he is only 42 behind Cappelletti for fourth place
on the team's all-time list. Cappelletti stands at 4,589 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen for the Pro Bowl the last four seasons, Coates had been
hobbled by ankle injuries this season and sat out the second game
against Indianapolis. He had seven receptions a week ago against
New Orleans (his highest total in 32 games) and his scores Sunday
were his first of the season, indicating that he is starting to
round into form.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've hooked up for a lot of touchdowns over the years,'' said
Bledsoe. ``On the second one today, when I released the ball it
felt good but the wind took it. I didn't know if he was going to
get it, so he made a nice play on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put it in the end zone, you know he's going to get
the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Coates put on an extra burst, taking the ball in full
stride before his momentum nearly took him down the runway leading
to the Patriots' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a rhythm going with the running and the passing game,''
said coach Pete Carroll, who saw Coates, as in so many games in the
past, contribute to the beat.
</P>
<P>
   Willie McGinest, who has bumped shoulder pads with Coates in
practice for five seasons, put it another way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben's the ultimate competitor,'' said McGinest. ``With Ben,
it's like being at the bank. You know your money's safe. And if the
bank gets robbed, you're insured.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a silent threat. He doesn't say much, he just gets it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   In practice, said McGinest, ``we really go at it. It all starts
there. He's always working hard and he's been around long enough
(since 1991) to know a lot of the tricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's experienced, a big, strong guy who can run, who's smart
and can find the gap, and any time you've got that combination in a
tight end, well, what more can you say?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want any other tight end on my team.''
</P>
<P>
   For four seasons, Patriots running back Tony Carter was an
opponent and the former Chicago Bear said he's glad to be on the
same side as Coates these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a great player, a Pro Bowl type. He's one of those
guys who's popular in the locker room, who keeps things together,''
said Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I played against him, his name always came up. He was one
of the guys you had to stop if you hoped to stop the New England
Patriots. You can't say all he can do is catch the ball, because
he's such an excellent blocker.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he believes Coates was feeling more comfortable on
the field Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had some nicks and some things that set him back this
year, but he's getting the job done. He's moving in the right
direction,'' said Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Coates wasn't saying much, however.
</P>
<P>
   But his numbers continue to speak volumes about the best tight
end in franchise history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
