<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-FOLLOW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 PLAYS, 3 TDS, 1 LOSS  
 2-MINUTE EXPLOSION ENDS UA'S DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Arizona football Coach Dick Tomey has seen many
things in his 36 years of coaching, but a team scoring three
touchdowns on three consecutive offensive plays, all in the span of
a little over two minutes?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been involved in a situation like that,'' Tomey
said. ``That's a moment in the history of Arizona football that we
all need to hope is not repeated.''
</P>
<P>
   And he watched it all over again Sunday morning as he reviewed
tape of the Wildcats' 52-28 loss to UCLA Saturday night at Arizona
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA (4-0) and Arizona (5-1) were playing a nice little game of
serve-and-volley until the Bruins broke loose. First, flanker Danny
Farmer beat cornerback Chris McAlister for a 64-yard touchdown
pass. On the next possession, tailback Keith Brown from Mountain
Pointe High scored on a 54-yard run. Then following an
interception, Brown scored from 20 yards out to complete the 21-0
blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 50 minutes, it's a great game, as good a game as you've
ever seen,'' Tomey said. ``And then you erase the tape.''
</P>
<P>
   At least you do if you were cheering for Arizona, which saw its
chances for a Fiesta Bowl bid and a shot at a national title
ruined. The Wildcats dropped from 10th to 16th in the AP poll,
while UCLA moved from third to second, thanks in part to Texas
A&AMP;M's upset of previously unbeaten Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Tomey seemed to still be battling the emotional
hangover. He lamented the mistakes that cost the Wildcats the game,
while also starting to look ahead to this Saturday's game at Oregon
State.
</P>
<P>
   The loss broke Arizona's nine-game winning streak, dating back
to early November of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have somebody come do that to you on your home field just
really hurts,'' he said. ``I think the guys are really
disappointed. I hope so. I hope it hurts like hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had this feeling in almost a year. We just have to
hate it enough that we don't want it to occur much.``
</P>
<P>
   While pleased with some aspects of his team's play on Saturday,
Tomey was particularly disappointed with two areas: the Wildcats'
tackling and a lack of a running game.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona limited UCLA quarterback Cade McNown to a substandard
performance (10-24, 171 yards), but the Bruins' tailbacks were
relentless. The regular starter, Jermaine Lewis, was suspended for
the game for his involvement in a fight, but the Bruins didn't
suffer. Freshman DeShaun Foster rushed 20 times for 118 yards and
two touchdowns. Brown finished with 91 yards on nine carries and
two touchdowns. Overall, the Bruins rushed for 297 yards on 44
carries, a 6.8-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Foster) is an outstanding player,'' Tomey said. ``He's big
and fast, and he's hard to tackle. But at the same time, our
tackling at times was atrocious. But given all that, with 11
minutes to go in the game they have 230 something yards in total
offense. They've had that in the first quarter in some games, so we
were doing some things right, but not nearly enough.''
</P>
<P>
   While McNown was helped by his running game, Arizona
quarterbacks Ortege Jenkins and Keith Smith had little support. The
Wildcats rushed for just 90 yards on 40 carries. Starting tailback
Trung Canidate had just 16 on 13 rushes.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey, however, doesn't think the loss will create any
psychological problems for the Wildcats this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if people are going to work as hard as we've worked
and accomplish as much as this team has accomplished, and let one
disappointing game . . . talk them out of being successful, then
I'd be disappointed,'' he said. ``I think we're stronger mentally
than that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
