<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-FOLLOW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEALY'S ONLY WAY OUT IS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - It was an unlikely scenario for a hometown lad
and one of the country's top freshman quarterbacks of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Three interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Crowd boos.
</P>
<P>
   Being replaced by an inexperienced backup.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what it has come to for Arizona State's Ryan Kealy,
who may have hit rock bottom in the Sun Devils' 28-9 loss to Notre
Dame Saturday. Although the quarterback's struggles are only one
element of ASU's 2-4 start, it's a mystifying occurrence for a
player who showed such promise in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   One day after the loss, Coach Bruce Snyder tried to make sense
of Kealy's difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very competitive, very emotional guy,'' Snyder said.
``He doesn't come across that way in normal conversation. But I
think he really runs deep. And it's not shared a lot. You combine
those two things with high expectations and with the team not
playing the way it should, and he feels like he's not doing what he
could to help them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things tearing and pulling at him. I'm a
two-bit psychologist, I guess, uncertified, but I really feel for
him. He wants to be good. He wants to help this team so badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is a lot more fun when you have guys like that, as
opposed to guys who don't care as much. I like working with him. I
want to help him. The team wants to help him. This record is
certainly not all his fault. But to him, it just feels as if it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy's numbers this season are almost identical to his first
six games last year, when he had yet to find his groove: A 54.5
percent completion rate in 1998 vs. 54.9 in 1997. Eight touchdowns
vs. seven touchdowns. Seven interceptions in 1998. Seven
interceptions in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But Kealy picked up the pace during the second half of 1997,
throwing eight more touchdown passes and only one interception.
This is where ASU thought the sophomore would pick up this year.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Sun Devil Stadium crowd was vocal about its
impatience and booed Kealy after bad plays.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans have been terrific,'' he said. ``My only hope is that
people would understand that the guy is really trying and really
cares. If they're booing me, I don't have a problem with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But here's a guy that's won a lot of games around here that
really cares what he's doing. So that's hurtful. Unexpected?
Probably not, because a minority of today's fans aren't sensitive
to that kind of thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he bounces back and has a four-touchdown game, things
will change, and we know that.''
</P>
<P>
   When will that be? Snyder hasn't said who will start against
Stanford on Oct. 22, only that he is is scrutinizing ``every
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the defeat, Snyder said he was pleased how the team
reacted to the loss in the locker room. Several players, including
safety Mitchell Freedman, center Grey Ruegamer and tailback J.R.
Redmond, stood up and spoke to the team about not giving up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were adamant after the game about turning this thing
around,'' Snyder said. ``They were angry. I don't think there is
any quit at all involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to charge into what we're going to call our second
season. We have five solid games, league games. If we solve our
problems and play well, we can get most of them and end up at least
with a decent taste in our mouth.'' &QL; 
Note &QL; 
Snyder is awaiting a definitive word on defensive end Quincy Yancy,
who sprained an ankle and knee in the game. It appears he won't
need surgery. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
