</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-CHICAGO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSORO CATCHES ON QUICKLY 
</HEADLINE>
 MARATHON-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Everyone expected Sunday's Chicago Marathon to be
fast. It's just that no one expected a rookie to be fastest. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Morocco's Khalid Khannouchi won here in a stunning 2
hours 7 minutes 10 seconds, the fastest first marathon in history.
He returned as the favorite Sunday, intent on bettering that
remarkable time. But as Khannouchi faded in the final miles,
victimized by the combined burdens of a bad left ankle and the
heavy crown of defending champion, newcomer Ondoro Osoro of Kenya
stormed past in the final mile for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Move over, Khalid, in more ways than one: Osoro's 2:06:54 is now
the fastest debut ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first marathon and I think I am very happy,'' said
the 30-year-old, whose effort in almost ideal conditions catapulted
him to third on the all-time performance list and earned him
$55,000 for the win and more than $50,000 in performance bonuses
and incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi was second in 2:07:19, Gert Thys of South Africa
third in 2:07:45, and Joseph Kahugu of Kenya followed in 2:07:59.
It was the first time in history the top four times were under
2:08. Moses Tanui, the Boston Marathon winner in 1996 and 1998, was
a distant fifth in 2:09:43.
</P>
<P>
   Osoro was joined in the winner's circle by countrywoman Joyce
Chepchumba, who bided her time behind Colleen de Reuck for 22 miles
before passing the cramping South African. Chepchumba, who trains
in Germany with world-record holder Tegla Loroupe, then put more
than three minutes on de Reuck on her way to victory in 2:23:57.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time a Kenyan man and woman were victors in the
same major marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Osoro, in the lead pack throughout much of the race, ran wisely,
especially after a surge by Khannouchi and Thys at 20 miles gapped
him by a minute. By 23 miles he was a second in front of Thys and
just seven seconds behind Khannouchi, and by 26 miles he led
Khannouchi by 15 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``After passing him, I wanted to run fast so that when he comes
to sprint I'm already gone, because he's a very good sprinter,''
said Osoro, who finished three seconds behind Khannouchi in the
Utica Boilermaker 15K in July.
</P>
<P>
   But there would be no sprinting Sunday for the 26-year-old
defending champion, who was harboring a secret: His left ankle was
hurting for the past two weeks, and being in shape to run even
faster than last year soon would mean nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running with the pain,'' said Khannouchi, who had to be
carried into the postrace news conference. ``I was thinking about
dropping out, but I just decided to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is Osoro any stranger to pain. After several years of
running track and cross-country, he was severely injured in a car
accident when a 12-ton truck smashed into him on the notoriously
hazardous Kenyan roads. Knocked unconscious, his right arm broken,
his hip injured, Osoro could not compete for two years. Now
training in Boulder, Colo. where he lives with his wife and four
children, Osoro turned to road racing after his recovery, and holds
the world record (45:37) for a 10-mile loop course.
</P>
<P>
   De Reuck appeared to be in control through 19 miles, when she
held a 38-second lead on Chepchumba. But de Reuck's quadriceps
began seizing, and less than 2 miles later the 27-year-old took the
lead for good, running a personal best by almost three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joyce just came flying by me,'' said de Reuck, who finished
fifth last April in Boston and third in 1997. Trailing her by 16
seconds was Elana Meyer, the South African who holds the
half-marathon world record but has yet to win at 26.2 miles after
two seconds and a third at Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, no one came close to claiming the $1 million put up
by New Balance for an American breaking Bob Kempainen's 2:08:47 US
record: Jerry Lawson, the likeliest candidate, dropped out at 6
miles when a strained right hamstring caused his calf to tighten,
and the first American, Rod DeHaven of Madison, Wis., came in at
2:13:01, 15th overall. Attleboro, Mass., native Mark Coogan was
20th in 2:15:32. Kristy Johnston was the first American woman,
eighth overall in 2:32:37.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best story belonged to Tatyana Pozdnyakova, a
43-year-old who paid her own way from Ukraine _ and then the $60
entry fee on top of that _ to enter at the last minute. Not only
did Pozdnyakova's $16,500 in prize and bonus money for winning the
master's division give her an impressive return on her investment,
but her 2:29:25 is the second-fastest marathon run by a woman over
40.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
