<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES SHOW SIGNS OF LIFE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO - Thump-thump. Thump-thump. Thump-thump.
</P>
<P>
   That was the faint sound of a heartbeat emanating from the
Atlanta Braves' clubhouse after the team fought off elimination in
the best-of-seven National League Championship Series with an 8-3
victory over San Diego in Game 4 on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   A mere nine outs away from having their 1998 season flat-line in
a most humiliating fashion (which is what a four-game sweep will do
to a club), the Braves' offense uncorked a six-spot on San Diego's
pitching staff in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   A one-run Atlanta deficit turned into a Braves rout. The six
runs in the seventh inning doubled what the Braves' offense, which
basically spent the previous 34 innings sleep walking, had managed
to score in the first three games combined.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the stranglehold the Padres had on this series doesn't
seem quite as tight as it did 24 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego still has the upper hand. Atlanta must play nearly
perfect baseball the rest of the way to pull off what would be a
first in the history of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But believe it or not, all the talk in the winning clubhouse
centered around the impossible becoming possible, overcoming a 3-0
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   You know what? This is the only team today, possibly in the past
30 years, capable of staring history in the face and rewriting it.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will send John Smoltz, the winningest pitcher ever in
the postseason to the mound today against Andy Ashby. Smoltz, who
gave up two runs and walked a season-high five batters in Game 1,
was practically oozing with confidence after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it like I'm not going to be the guy to let the
season end,'' Smoltz said. ``It won't be me.''
</P>
<P>
   Should Smoltz extend the series _ three times he's pitched with
the Braves facing elimination in the NLCS, and the Braves have won
all three _ Atlanta's next pitcher would be Tom Glavine, who would
oppose the great Braves slayer, Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   If a Game 7 occurs, it would be four-time Cy Young Award winner
Greg Maddux against Sterling Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   Can history unfold right in front of our eyes over the next four
days? The odds say no. The Braves say yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all realize history says this cannot happen,'' Atlanta
pitching coach Leo Mazzone said. ``But when you're talking about
one of the greatest rotations in the history of the game, anything
can still happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a staff that has consistently responded under the gun.
Hell, if they pull this off, I may very well just go retire. I know
it can't possibly get any better.''
</P>
<P>
   In 118 previous seven-game series, not once has a club overcome
a 3-0 deficit to win.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not one of those clubs has had the benefit of sending
Smoltz, Glavine and Maddux in order to try to pull it out of the
Grand Canyon-sized hole the Braves placed themselves in by losing
the first three games.
</P>
<P>
   While Atlanta's rotation is unmatched, the Braves found
themselves trailing for one very good reason _ they weren't scoring
runs. Atlanta was in search of a hero Sunday who did not pitch and
up stepped Andres Galarraga, the Big Cat.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga, who had four hits (all singles) in his first 23
postseason at-bats in 1998, slammed a massive 459-foot grand slam
to put a big, fat exclamation point on Atlanta's six-run uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, the raging overflow crowd of 65,042 went nearly
silent. All you could hear were the 35 or so people who leaped out
of the Braves' dugout and Ted Turner and Jane Fonda, who cheered
madly while hugging from their front-row seats along the third-base
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having done something positive in this game gives me the
chance to do something positive again in the next one,'' Galarraga
said. ``I think we have the team to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Braves victory tonight would make that heartbeat sound
more like, THUMP-THUMP! THUMP-THUMP! THUMP-THUMP. And that's a
sound the Padres simply do not want to hear. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 0144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
