<HEADER>
A1281 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-PADRES-BOS     10-12 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PADRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES WIN IN GRAND STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The Big Cat is back. Sooner or later you knew Andres
Galarraga would come to life for the Braves. And the best thing
about it for Atlanta is he just could be the spark for the biggest
comeback in major league baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   After a woeful September and a 1-for-12 slump in the National
League playoffs, Galarraga Sunday night did what earlier in the
season was expected of him almost every night. With the Braves on
the brink of elimination, he came through with a grand slam to
highlight a six-run seventh-inning explosion that carried Atlanta
to an 8-3 victory over the San Diego Padres in Game 4 of the NLCS.
The Padres still lead, three games to one. But at last the Braves
have some momentum, and with their pitching it may help them out of
the mighty hole they're in.
</P>
<P>
   This was classic Atlanta baseball. With the Braves clinging to a
4-3 lead, Galarraga stepped up and hit his slam off Padres
righthander Dan Miceli, which stunned a crowd of 65,042 at Qualcomm
Stadium that only an inning or two before had been calling for a
series sweep. This is what the Braves wanted to see after trading
away Fred McGriff last winter and signing Galarraga. The Big Cat
had only two home runs and nine runs batted in during September.
Sunday night's blast was dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 5 Monday night, Andy Ashby of San Diego and John Smoltz
of Atlanta will hook up in a rematch of Game 1. If the Braves win,
it's back to Atlanta for Game 6 and possibly 7. Be aware, however,
that no baseball team has ever overcome a 3-0 deficit in a playoff
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was huge,'' said Denny Neagle, a 20-game winner a year
ago who gave up three runs in 5 2/3 innings but gave Atlanta a
chance to win. ``More importantly, some of our big guys came
through. I think Galarraga needed that. A little jolt in the arm
like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we won this game, 4-3, we'd still have felt good,
but it would have been scratch and claw. We put up eight runs
Monday night. Galarraga gets a grand slam. Some guys got some
clutch hits for us. That's what we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves fell behind in the third, 2-0. Atlanta got one in the
fourth and tied it in the top of the sixth. The Padres went ahead
in their half on a solo home run by former Red Sox Jim Leyritz. But
then it was San Diego that fell apart. Atlanta re-tied it at 3 on a
homer by Javy Lopez leading off the seventh. When Andruw Jones
followed with a single, that was it for Padres starter Joey
Hamilton, and on came a San Diego bullpen that had been living on
borrowed time.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Myers, who started the year with the Blue Jays, sandwiched
two outs around a wild pitch. But then he gave up a run-scoring
single to Ozzie Guillen to put Atlanta ahead, 4-3. An infield
single by Keith Lockhart and a walk to Chipper Jones finished
Myers. Miceli took over and Galarraga slammed a 1-0 pitch into the
seats in left-center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just looking for something in the strike zone,'' said
Galarraga. ``All I wanted to do was get a base hit and drive
somebody in. As soon as I hit it, I knew it was a home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt good going to home plate. I know I haven't been
hitting well, but the way they have been pitching me was really
difficult. When you go 0 for 2, 0 for 3, you swing at bad pitches.
I wanted to do something to help the team win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot of frustration to deal with,'' added
Galarraga. ``I was more patient at the plate. I had two walks and
hit into a double play. But I also hit a home run. I feel much
better. My home run kept the team alive. It will give them more
emotion for tomorrow. I know my family is happy to see me do
something to help us win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres knew Galarraga was due.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good hitter,'' said Padres manager Bruce Bochy. ``I was
hoping he wouldn't find his stroke. We had two outs. But that home
run was a hit that broke our backs. Miceli was in a situation where
he fell behind and had no place to put him. He (put) a ball where
Galarraga could handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the series continues. The Braves had 12 hits, as their
bats finally woke up. But if they lose Monday night, they go home
with nothing to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The series is not over,'' said Andruw Jones. ``We have to go
out and play the same baseball that we played today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
