<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-LINES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES' SCHOENFELD SHAKING UP LINES ALREADY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The linesmen assigned by the NHL for the Coyotes'
season-opening 4-1 loss to the Ottawa Senators on Sunday were Baron
Parker and Shane Heyer.
</P>
<P>
   The ``mad linesman'' in the bench area was Coyotes Coach Jim
Schoenfeld, who mixed and matched lines like a crazed chemist
throughout the game.
</P>
<P>
   But only because he needed to light a fire.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld started the game with Cliff Ronning centering captain
Keith Tkachuk and Rick Tocchet on the No. 1 line, with Jeremy
Roenick centering Greg Adams and Shane Doan on the second line, and
Juha Ylonen centering Bob Corkum and Dallas Drake on the third
line.
</P>
<P>
   By the 14-minute mark of the second period, the Coyotes were
trailing, 3-0, and Roenick was up with Tkachuk and Tocchet. Drake
also took some shifts with Tkachuk and Roenick, while Tocchet was
matched with Adams and Ronning on the No. 2 line. Drake, in fact,
took shifts with all three lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were having a difficult time with some of our
players handling Ottawa's speed,'' Schoenfeld said. ``So we changed
the lines accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to generate some more offensive opportunities,
and, unfortunately, it didn't pay off. We were really fumbling the
puck. I don't know if it was nerves or the fact it was the first
game . . . we were running with the ball before we caught it.
Obviously, you do that and they're going to get a turnover and cash
it on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, no doubt, stemmed from Tkachuk's prolonged
preseason holdout and his appearance in only one preseason game,
which didn't allow Schoenfeld opportunity to get a good feeling for
the makeup of his lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, who are now 0-4-1 in their last five against the
Senators, did appear tentative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started with cob webs on us. That's a good hockey club,
too, and they spanked us pretty good,'' Tocchet said. ``I think we
were all a little bit jittery every time we touched the puck. When
it was 1-0, I think we panicked a little bit. Even when it's 2-0,
you have to stick to the game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Drake-Roenick-Tkachuk combination finally paid dividends
when Roenick scored the first goal of the season on an assist from
Drake at 9:14 of the final period.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld also mixed up his defensive combinations, starting
the game with Teppo Numminen and Jyrki Lumme paired together, Keith
Carney with Oleg Tverdovsky, and Bryan Helmer with Gerald Diduck.
By the midway point of the second period, Numminen was with
Tverdovsky and Lumme with Carney.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tells what kind of game it was and how things were
going,'' Numminen said. ``You have to make changes to get something
going.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 0152EDT &QL; 
