<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-SENATORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES BOOED _ AND EARN IT  
 LOOK BAD IN LOSING 1ST GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Keith Tkachuk wasn't the only Coyote to get booed
Sunday night at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The entire team got an earful from the crowd during it's
bellyflop of a season opener against the Ottawa Senators. And it
probably should have been worse. The final score, a 4-1 rout,
certainly could have been.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, it was the first game. So what if it showed?
</P>
<P>
   It was only the second game this fall for Tkachuk, the Coyotes'
captain, who missed most of training camp because of a
controversial holdout. Like his only preseason appearance, he was
booed lustily when he was introduced and almost every time he
touched the puck.
</P>
<P>
   When they weren't getting the puck swiped or watching it slide
between their skates, the majority of his teammates got the same
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Senators pooped on the party, streaking to a
4-0 lead and making everyone among the 15,812 quickly forget about
all the opening night pomp. The sparklers, the fireworks, the
spotlight, the pre-game introductions didn't matter for very long.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we play like this on Thursday against Colorado, the score's
going to be 10-1,'' Coyotes right wing Dallas Drake said.
</P>
<P>
   Senators goalie Damian Rhodes looked in mid-season form,
stopping 22 shots. His supporting cast played mostly error-free
hockey as Ottawa opened the season 2-0 for the first time in
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators also are now 4-0-1 in their past five games against
the Coyotes, who dropped to 8-9-3 in season openers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were all a little bit jittery,'' Phoenix forward
Rick Tocchet said. ``We all had a tough time handling the puck. We
all kind of panicked a little bit. Even when it's 2-0, you've got
to stick to the game plan, but it just seemed like everything went
to hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Jeremy Roenick prevented Rhodes from pinning a shutout on
the Coyotes, as he scored the club's only goal midway through the
final period, thanks to a diving effort by Drake that got him the
puck. But that was about the only highlight for the men in white.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game was even halfway through, the Coyotes were
halfway in the tank. Ottawa breezed to a 3-0 lead seven minutes
into the second period, and no remedy seemed to be in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Andreas Dackell, filling in for the injured Daniel Alfredsson on
Ottawa's No. 1 line, started the deluge at 9:06 of the first period
by snaring his second goal of the young season with a finishing
tap-in of Sean McEachern's backhanded pass through the slot.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes thought they tied it in the second, but Tocchet's
would-be goal in close on Rhodes was waived off after a review.
Less than a minute later, Radek Bonk rifled a rising slap shot from
the right circle to make it 2-0 for the Senators.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Gardiner then came up with what might have been the play
of the night. The third-year pro threw a crushing backcheck on
defenseman Jyrki Lumme, knocking away the puck behind the Phoenix
net. Roenick slithered in to corral it, but Gardiner swiped it away
with a flick of his blade, and shoved it past an unsuspecting
Nikolai Khabibulin, who never saw it coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough game,'' said Tkachuk, who fanned on an open net
early in the game. ``I'm discouraged and I'm disappointed, but it's
not the end of the world. We've got 81 games left to play. We just
went away from the game plan and they took it to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
