A1366 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-ELECTIONS-SFCHR     10-12 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-ELECTIONS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENDER LESS OF A FACTOR IN '98 RACES 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLA MARINUCCI  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The political tidal wave dubbed the ``Year of the Woman'' that
swept California in the 1992 elections is hardly creating a ripple
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While Barbara Boxer maintains her support from Democratic women,
moderate Republican women as well as Democratic men appear to be
rejecting the senator's re-election bid. Abortion, a hot button
that even two years ago was still uppermost in many minds, does not
seem to be helping pro-choice Boxer _ even though her opponent,
Matt Fong, has said Roe vs. Wade was ``wrongly decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic gubernatorial candidate Gray Davis has been hoping to
boost his campaign for governor by attracting Republican women with
his clearly pro-choice credentials. But polls indicate he is not
having much luck, either. A Field Poll released last week showed
that just 15 percent of Republican women support Davis over his
Republican challenger, Dan Lungren _ not the landslide once
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In California, so many women have achieved higher levels of
office. ... Gender doesn't play such a role in the decision. The
debate focuses more on issues,'' said Stephanie Cohen, spokeswoman
for EMILY's List, one of the nation's powerhouse money-raisers for
Democratic pro-choice female candidates like Boxer. ``With two
women senators, 13 women in the congressional delegation and five
women running for statewide office ... if there was a novelty to
it, it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week's Field Polls revealed some startling numbers about
the issues _ and how potent a force female voters will be _ in the
drama of this year's California races.
</P>
<P>
   While California voters consider Boxer to be the stronger
candidate on the majority of issues they care most about _
education, jobs and economy, guns, abortion, environment, health
care and strong leadership _ they still give Fong a 4-point lead,
the Field Poll showed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Males have this 5-to-3 negative view of Barbara Boxer,'' said
Field Poll director Mark DiCamillo, a difference he calls
``striking.'' Because men have a historically higher propensity to
vote, DiCamillo notes that, at least in the U.S. Senate race, the
gender gap ``is working in the other direction _ against Boxer. ...
This time around, men are asserting their will and affecting the
outcome to a greater extent.''
</P>
<P>
   In the governor's race, the polls also suggest evidence of a new
perspective among voters _ men and women alike.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion did not rank among the top five issues of concern to
voters in recent Field Polls, ``and in the Los Angeles Times poll,
it didn't rank in the top 20,'' noted Dan Schnur, the Republican
consultant working to elect both Lungren and Fong. ``There's a
certain number of voters on both sides of the issue who vote only
because of that issue. But it's a relatively small number.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans like Schnur argue that Democrats, particularly
Boxer, have simply overplayed certain issues to female voters _ and
the female card as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1992, Barbara Boxer was the chromosome candidate,'' said
Schnur. ``Now the voters have spent six years watching her in
office, and they've come to realize that _ while demographics are
important _ they're not all that important.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some Democrats agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Boxer's agenda. I supported her last time. But being a
woman is just not enough anymore,'' said Elahe Enssani, a Bay Area
civil engineer who runs her own Bay Area high-tech firm and teaches
at San Francisco State University. The activist Democrat said she
will probably vote for Fong this time around _ even though she does
not agree with him on key issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all bought into the `Year of the Woman,' but she hasn't
been a strong enough figure in the Senate ... and she seems too
much of a partisan,'' said Enssani.
</P>
<P>
   That view disturbs many who are actively working to have more
women _ and women's issues _ in the forefront of politics. Some
suggest that the President Clinton-Monica Lewinsky scandal may be
having its effects on voters _ particularly on women.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this state, I don't believe there's a gender backlash. It's
a backlash and a dissatisfaction about politics in general,'' said
Marie C. Wilson, president of the White House Project, a
nonpartisan public awareness campaign dedicated to drafting more
female candidates for top elected positions. ``Women are fed up
with the political process ... and when women get upset, women
(candidates) are more likely to be the victims than men.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said that, because elected female officials like Boxer
are still relatively few in number, they are ``held to a higher
standard'' by voters _ and, unlike male candidates who are seen as
vigorous advocates, women are often seen as ``shrill and pushy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It worries me at every level,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   But some political insiders say that female voters, who have
often put strong emphasis on gender in both issues and candidates,
are now considering a wider palette.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say that we use (abortion) as a litmus test is an insult,
quite frankly,'' said Bobbie Lungren _ wife of the Republican
candidate _ who is traveling statewide to speak to women's groups.
``We do women a disservice when they say we're a one-issue group.''
</P>
<P>
   While noting that her husband is against abortion, Lungren said
that female voters will choose their candidate based on critical
issues like public safety, education and job creation.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason, said Sharon Davis, wife of Gray Davis and an
activist in groups like the National Women's Political Caucus, that
Democrats are emphasizing women in this year's get-out-the-vote
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their vote will be very important to us,'' she said, noting
that polls show that her husband is considered the stronger
candidate not only for voters favoring a pro-choice stance but also
on the issues most important to female voters _ education, health
care and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the findings of other surveys, Democratic pollster
Paul Maslin, who works for Davis, said his research indicates that,
while this year may not be a replay of the ``Year of the Woman,''
``the gender gap is huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, he insisted, female voters are ``having a big impact.
They have been our prime target, and it's paid off,'' said Maslin.
``The vast majority of the progress we've made is with women voters
... and I don't see (Republicans) making inroads there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
