<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-EPONYMOUS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAMING PLACES AFTER OTHER PLACES IS A BAD IDEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK, Vt. _ I was born in Woodstock, but not this one. This
is the Woodstock after which my Woodstock in Illinois was named. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Notice: No ``Who cares?'' comments will be tolerated.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure why anyone thought it was a good idea to change the
name of my hometown from Centerville _ a perfectly serviceable and
geographically descriptive name _ to Woodstock. But I now regret
that it was done. And I think there may be a good lesson here about
the dangers of naming one thing after another. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that the two places or persons sharing the same
name almost never bear anything but the faintest resemblance to
each other. And yet people are always comparing them. It's
ridiculous. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when I grew up in Woodstock, Ill., barely a week
ever went by without someone describing how settlers from
Woodstock, Vt., came to Centerville and got its name changed to
Woodstock because, like its Vermont counterpart, Woodstock, Ill.,
has a central business district built around a park. We called the
whole thing The Square, there being four equally long streets on
each side of a park, complete with bandstand and war monument. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The clear understanding was that if locals ever ventured east to
Woodstock, Vt., they would discover a square green park downtown
surrounded by businesses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's simply not true. The green here is no square part at
all but, rather, an oblong stretch that seems for all the world to
be at one end of downtown, not smack in the middle. And the
business district isn't a square here anyway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Woodstock, Ill., square is, in fact, so vastly superior to
the Woodstock, Vt., green that the wonder is the Vermont Woodstock
didn't simply empty out 150 or so years ago as pioneers got abroad
their moose-drawn Conestoga wagons and headed west to Illinois. (I
suppose it explains the scarcity of moose in northern Illinois even
to this day.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For reasons I'll never grasp, there must have been folks here
who were so used to the stretchy-shaped green that they believed
they actually preferred it to the much more sensible Square of my
home town. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty more about Woodstock, Vt., that doesn't resemble
Woodstock, Ill., including a nearby and pretty nice hill called
Mount Tom, which in Vermont, where things are generally more dainty
and quaint than elsewhere, qualifies as a mountain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock, Ill., has nothing close to a mountain. I lived most
of my boyhood near the top of South Street hill, which was high
enough to serve as the starting point for the annual Soap Box Derby
races. But South Street hill is to a mountain what Bill Clinton is
to a celibate monk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So in 150-plus years, Woodstock, Ill., and Woodstock, Vt., have
gone their separate ways. Which is exactly what people should _ but
too often don't _ expect to happen when one place or person gets
named after another. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever known a man who has a Jr., II, III or IV stuck at
the end of his name to be the spit and image of the previous person
with that name? No. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is New York anything like York or New Jersey like Jersey? Not at
all. Was ``Rocky XIV'' as good as ``Rocky''? Ha! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So let's swear off naming things after other things. Here's a
good way to remember the rule: Sequels Aren't Equals, Especially if
Preceded by Prequels. Think about that while I wander around here
in the wrong Woodstock in search of my roots _ or at least someone
who might remember a 1951 trip made here by my late father, uh,
Bill Tammeus. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
