<HEADLINE>
BESTSELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating for all needing.)  (For release on Sunday, Oct. 18.) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated bestseller list for paperback
books. Please see BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list and where
the book stood the previous week.) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending Oct. 3, 1998,
at almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of non-fiction can change from week to week,
reflecting changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. DIVINE SECRETS OF THE YA-YA SISTERHOOD, by Rebecca Wells.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Perennial, $13.50.) Three generations of
</P>
<P>
   Southern women.
</P>
<P>
   2. WHAT LOOKS LIKE CRAZY ON AN ORDINARY DAY ..., by Pearl
</P>
<P>
   Cleage. (Avon, $12.) Returning to her rustic hometown, a
</P>
<P>
   woman finds many changes since she left _ and romance.
</P>
<P>
   3. COLD MOUNTAIN, by Charles Frazier. (Vintage, $13.) A wounded
</P>
<P>
   Confederate soldier journeys home toward the end of the Civil
</P>
<P>
   War to meet and old love and a new world.
</P>
<P>
   4. SPECIAL DELIVERY, by Danielle Steel. (Dell, $6.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Romance comes to a pair who once disliked each other.
</P>
<P>
   5. FLOOD TIDE, by Clive Cussler. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Dirk Pitt in pursuit of a notorious Chinese smuggler
</P>
<P>
   at work in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   6. ONE TRUE THING, by Anna Quindlen. (Dell, $6.99.) A
</P>
<P>
   woman who cared for her fatally ill mother is charged
</P>
<P>
   with killing her.
</P>
<P>
   7. AND THEN YOU DIE, by Iris Johansen. (Bantam, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   On assignment in Mexico, a photojournalist copes with
</P>
<P>
   terror and romance.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE COBRA EVENT, by Richard Preston. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A terrorist uses a genetically engineered virus
</P>
<P>
   to attack New York.
</P>
<P>
   9. LITTLE ALTARS EVERYWHERE, by Rebecca Wells. (Harper
</P>
<P>
   Perennial, $13.) An account of earlier experiences of
</P>
<P>
   members of the Ya-Ya sisterhood, first published in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   10.(x) BLOOD WORK, by Michael Connelly. (Warner, $7.50.) A
</P>
<P>
   retired FBI agent attempts to solve the murder of an
</P>
<P>
   alluring woman's sister.
</P>
<P>
   11.(x) THE NOTEBOOK, by Nicholas Sparks. (Warner Vision, $5.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A World War II veteran meets an old flame who is
</P>
<P>
   about to be married.
</P>
<P>
   12. 10 LB. PENALTY, by Dick Francis. (Jove, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A politician's career is imperiled by actions taken by his
</P>
<P>
   enemies against his son, a onetime jockey.
</P>
<P>
   13. COME THE SPRING, by Julie Garwood. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The pleasures of a family reunion are spoiled by the
</P>
<P>
   arrival of a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) WIZARD AND GLASS, by Stephen King. (Signet, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Volume 4 of ``The Dark Tower.''
</P>
<P>
   15. THE DECEPTION, by Catherine Coulter. (Topaz, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   A young woman, posing as a widow, is hired to be a nanny
</P>
<P>
   in Regency England.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) AMBER BEACH, by Elizabeth Lowell. (Avon, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A businesswoman on the trail of her favorite brother,
</P>
<P>
   who has vanished along with a fortune in stolen jewelry.
</P>
