<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Anemic Congress taking it's political ticks and
tricks to lethargic voters
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton may yet pull an education-policy rabbit out of
the empty-hat 105th Congress, but either way, the 105th will soon
and mercifully relieve us of itself, to go home and seek license
from the voters to act out again next year. It is a dismal
prospect, which voters, if the current soundings prove right, will
ratify in perhaps historically small numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Though of course it would be in the voters' interests to come
alive instead, it will be hard to berate the electorate if it takes
a dive. This has not been a Congress to entice citizens into
supposing there is any connection between politics and their actual
lives.
</P>
<P>
   With the majority exuberantly skinny-dipping in the shallow
waters of sex scandal, the 105th has shunned great themes and good
works in favor of pursuing petty grudges and doctrinal trivia.
</P>
<P>
   There was a classic moment of sorts as the gavel was descending.
The nomination of Dr. Jane E. Henney to lead the Food and Drug
Administration had been overwhelmingly approved by the Senate Labor
and Human Resources Committee. Henney is a former top official of
the agency and currently heads the University of New Mexico Medical
Center. She has broad support from medical associations and from
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Henney's nomination seemed a done deal until Sen. Don Nickles,
with his usual pious clowning, invoked personal privilege to block
her nomination. Nickles fears Henney might one day regulate tobacco
and let Americans have access to the RU-486 abortion pill Europeans
have used for years. That is, she may not practice politically
correct right-wing medicine.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the GOP leadership happily indulges even
unilateral showboating for the tobacco and anti-abortion lobbies.
This has been a Congress atwitch with such political ticks.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., has denied the nation able ambassadors
by killing nominations over ancient political tiffs. One appointee
has been barred just because he is homosexual, although Luxembourg,
his intended posting, has said it couldn't care less. Judicial
nominees have been backlogged by senators who suspect legal
radicalism lurking in self-evident and proven moderates. A
potential surgeon general was denied for his support of sex
education and contraception. (What year is it?)
</P>
<P>
   And so on. And in the course, Congress _ bee-busy picking
personal and ideological nits _ shunned proffers to contain tobacco
use, clean up toxic campaign funding, stop HMO abuses and square
Social Security away for the future. It is the hope of Republican
leadership, these days arch conservative, to build at the polls
this fall, with partisan activists on alert and middle ground
voters opting out, a new Congress that won't even think about such
things.
</P>
<P>
   Politics can matter for the better, as when, in a rare spot of
functioning bipartisanship, Congress and White House in 1996
overhauled welfare, set up a balanced budget, updated
telecommunications law, increased the minimum wage. But politics
can matter by omission, too, to which the last two years stand in
dour witness.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, politics counts. Your choice.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
