<SLUG> BC-SHARON-STONE-IN-THE-MIGHTY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THIRD COMING OF SHARON STONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Sharon Stone in a scene from ``The
Mighty.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Time ticks away for everyone, even Sharon Stone.
 &HT;    America's reigning blonde bombshell, who raised America's
temperature by uncrossing her legs in ``Basic Instinct'' (1992),
turned 40 in March. And she loves it.
 &HT;    ``Forty makes me need a nap,'' Stone jokes. ``No, I think it's
wonderful. I really like it. It's the best time so far. It's nice
to be done being a girl.
 &HT;    ``I feel like I've had several incarnations,'' she says. ``When
I see photos of myself, I see three separate women: one up to
`Basic Instinct,' one from `Basic Instinct' up to a year ago and
the one I am now.
 &HT;    ``I think I look so different. I look smaller, more vulnerable
and more fragile, but also more pure.''
 &HT;    Could it be that marriage _ earlier this year, to San Francisco
Chronicle publisher Phil Bronstein _ suits her well?
 &HT;    ``It's a chicken-and-egg thing,'' she says during a freewheeling
conversation at the Four Seasons Hotel in Beverly Hills. ``I took a
year off, and I spent that year with my family and friends. I spent
time with myself to see how I really felt about my life.
 &HT;    ``I probably wouldn't have met Phil if I hadn't taken the time
off,'' she adds, ``and now Phil is a big part of the changes in
me.''
 &HT;    That change is visible onscreen as well. In her latest film,
``The Mighty,'' Stone drastically dims her starpower to play a
supporting role as Gwen Dillon, the concerned, working-class mother
of a brilliant but physically challenged teen son named Kevin
(Kieran Culkin).
 &HT;    Kevin and fellow outcast Maxwell (Elden Henson), a huge kid
who's mentally slow and emotionally troubled by a dark past, become
pals and form a symbiotic relationship: Kevin's got the brains and
the sharp tongue, while Maxwell provides the brawn.
 &HT;    Even as they deal with reality _ pressures at school, assorted
bullies and disturbing family issues _ the boys enjoy flights of
fancy during which they pretend that they're noble knights saving
damsels in distress and vanquishing evildoers.
 &HT;    ``There was no way this movie was going to get made unless
somebody attached themselves to it,'' says Stone, whose company,
Chaos Productions, executive-produced the film.
 &HT;    Part of Stone's interest in the film, which opens in limited
release on Oct. 16, then around the country a week later, stemmed
from her own formative years growing up in Meadville, Pa.
 &HT;    ``When I was in elementary school I skipped a grade,'' she
recalls. ``They did a Mensa program at my school, where they took
some of us and we had class in the cafeteria for half the day,
separate from everybody else.
 &HT;    ``That made us all geeks, of course,'' she says. ``When I was in
high school, I went half a day to college and half a day to high
school. So once again I was separated out.''
 &HT;    And, like Kevin and Maxwell, Stone endured the taunts of her
peers.
 &HT;    ``Kids are vicious about everything,'' Stone says with an edge
to her voice. ``Kids are vicious about `You're tall,' `You're fat,'
`You're short.' They can be really awful.
 &HT;    ``That's what I think is so special about `The Mighty,''' she
adds. ``It respects kids and it respects their intelligence, their
wisdom and depth.
 &HT;    ``I'm not at all against the goofball teen movies. I just don't
think that's enough nurturing for the spirit of a teen-ager.''
 &HT;    Dressed down in a baggy gray sweater, with hardly any makeup on,
Stone is nonetheless a stunner, every inch the movie star next
door. The presence of a burly bodyguard and a hovering personal
publicist only heightens the effect.
 &HT;    Stone does not, however, look 40. It's laughable that Warner
Bros. deemed her too old to star opposite Mel Gibson in
``Conspiracy Theory'' (1997).
 &HT;    The studio instead opted for Julia Roberts, then 30 years old,
and ``Conspiracy Theory'' went on to a modest-at-best theatrical
run.
 &HT;    ``My thought is that Mel got what he deserved,'' Stone says in a
venomous tone, a sly smile hardly concealing her disgust.
 &HT;    It's a characteristic reaction from an actress who has used her
stardom as a license to speak her mind, even when it may ruffle
feathers in the power offices of Hollywood. In fact, especially
when it may ruffle those feathers.
 &HT;    ``Oh, I don't give a sh-t,'' she says offhandedly, her blue eyes
open wide. ``There are a lot of people in the business that I like
and respect, but I never believe at the end of the day that they'll
be there if I have a problem.
 &HT;    ``There are a couple of people I've met through the business who
are my real friends now,'' she adds. ``But the people who are
producing a movie I'm on ... no. After they call `Wrap,' they don't
give a sh-t.
 &HT;    ``It's OK with me now,'' the actress hastens to add. ``I can
have a congenial, wonderful, fun, exciting time with these people
at work. I made a decision that I'm going to go to work and I'm
going to love the people I work with.
 &HT;    ``Maybe I won't like them all, but I'll love them. That makes it
easier.''
 &HT;    As soon as Stone completes her promotional duties for ``The
Mighty,'' she'll hightail it back to the San Francisco apartment
she shares with her husband. She'll also continue her fund-raising
efforts on behalf of charitable causes, most notably AMFAR, the
American Foundation for AIDS Research.
 &HT;    And turning 40 hasn't slowed her career down any. This is a busy
year for Stone, whose film ``Sphere'' opened _ and quickly closed _
in January. She also is currently on screen, or at least on the
soundtrack, in the animated release ``Antz.'' The actress, who
provides the voice of Princess Bala, calls the film ``really
charming and funny and cute.''
 &HT;    Stone will next turn up in director Sidney Lumet's
long-completed remake of John Cassavetes' 1980 drama, ``Gloria.''
The film, in which Stone plays the gun-moll role originally essayed
by ``Mighty'' co-star Gena Rowlands, should be released in early
1999.
 &HT;    In the meantime, Stone is reading scripts, relaxing with her
husband and pondering her future. She wants her next role to be
exactly right, one that meshes with her third-time's-the-charm
post-40 identity.
 &HT;    In other words, no ``Basic Instinct 2.''
 &HT;    ``I turned it down,'' she says of a recent offer to reprise her
role as ``Instinct's'' mantrap bisexual murderess. ``I don't
believe it's timely, but the people who want to make it obviously
think it is.
 &HT;    ``The conquest of that character just doesn't thrill me now.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
