<HEADER>
A1577 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINGER-BRYAN-ADAMS-ST     10-12 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-BRYAN-ADAMS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYAN ADAMS, SINGING FOR AN AUDIENCE OF ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of singer Bryan Adams. 
 By BONNIE SIEGLER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    If you think Bryan Adams is going to pander, if you expect his
work to be user-friendly, if you want him to take your expectations
into account ... forget it.
 &HT;    This, after all, is a guy who wanted to call his second album,
``Bryan Adams Hasn't Heard of You Either.''
 &HT;    And surely Adams has earned some slack. He got his first record
contract at age 18, and that second album _ retitled, at the record
company's insistence, ``You Want It _ You Got It'' _ set him on the
road to fame. ``Cuts Like a Knife'' (1983) was his breakthrough
album, spawning the top-10 single ``Straight From The Heart.''
 &HT;    Since then he was won awards in Japan, Australia, Austria and
Ireland _ ``I think I have a little following everywhere,'' he says
_ to go along with a shelf of American Grammys and Canadian Junos.
His name is listed in ``The Guinness World Book of Records'' for
the longest-standing No. 1 single in British music, 16 weeks for
``Everything I Do, I Do It For You.''
 &HT;    Not that he's counting.
 &HT;    ``I could care less how any of my music is received,'' Adams
says. ``I don't care what people think of my music. I mean, this is
my 10th album. If I was going to worry about what people thought of
me, it's kind of late in the game for that.
 &HT;    ``I'm not much bothered by appealing to a certain age group or
record-buying public,'' he adds. ``I don't think anybody can really
gear their music toward any age bracket. That's ridiculous. I
really make music for myself.''
 &HT;    So, to judge by the title tune from his latest album, ``On A Day
Like Today,'' Adams is feeling upbeat, with a cheerier, less-gritty
tone to his voice than usual.
 &HT;    ``I think it's the kind of mood I'm in right now,'' the
38-year-old singer says, munching on some potato chips ``for
nutrition.'' ``I had no premeditated plans with this song _ it's
just what came out.
 &HT;    ``The whole theme of the album is about breaking out a little
bit,'' he continues. ``In fact, there's a single called `Get Away'
_ getting away from ho-hum, everyday life. A lot of coming to terms
with daily banter in this album. I think this one has some of my
best work on it.''
 &HT;    That far, at least, the album reflects its creator.
 &HT;    ``I just like the idea of not being constricted,'' Adams says.
``I like the idea of being a bit of a free bird and free spirit.
Most of my family are very free-spirited people, so I think the
theme works for me.''
 &HT;    That joy in freedom is a natural result of the singer's roving
youth. His father was a member of the Canadian foreign service, and
the family moved regularly.
 &HT;    ``I lived in Israel for a year,'' he recalls. ``At an early age,
I was introduced to the drug scene, to war, to influences you never
forget. Those early years kind of formed my spirit.''
 &HT;    One thing was constant, though: He got kicked out of school
everywhere in the world, he says, for offenses ranging from lobbing
a soccer ball through the headmaster's window to skipping class.
 &HT;    ``I was completely incorrigible,'' he admits with a laugh. ``If
I liked the teacher, I'd go to class. I'm the same way today. If I
get the feeling that someone doesn't give a sh-t, then I'm just not
interested.''
 &HT;    Adams dropped out of school in the 12th grade and got his first
full-time job, as a dishwasher.
 &HT;    ``That was a big milestone in my life,'' he says. ``It just
showed me how much I hated working in a kitchen, so I wanted to get
out of that.''
 &HT;    He stuck with it for a year, however, until he'd saved $1,000 to
buy his first guitar, a Fender Stratocaster.
 &HT;    ``I still have that guitar today,'' he says, ``and won't ever
give it away.''
 &HT;    Despite the fact that his father, a former opera singer,
considered rock-'n'-roll the worst noise in the world, Adams
decided to take a shot at a musical career. But, though he's sold
more than 55 million albums worldwide, he insists that he never
lusted after wealth or fame.
 &HT;    ``I think what really drives me is the idea of writing songs,''
he says. ``It takes me a long time to get things together.
Normally, my track record for putting out albums is pretty slow.''
 &HT;    Adams hasn't always been a critical darling. His last couple of
albums _ ``I Do It For You'' and ``Have You Ever Really Loved A
Woman'' _ have caused some reviewers to say he's lost his edge.
 &HT;    ``Let them,'' he says. ``I don't really strive for global
success. I just get on with making the records, and if one catches
the ear of somebody and goes the distance, then it's great.''
 &HT;    He's contributed to the soundtracks of two films _ ``Robin Hood:
Prince of Thieves'' (1991) and ``Don Juan DeMarco'' (1995) _ and
says he'd like to do more.
 &HT;    ``I really like writing for film,'' he says, ``so I'll probably
do more of that in the future.''
 &HT;    Indeed, he's already written a song titled ``Cloud 9'' for
``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' a romantic comedy starring Hugh Grant that's
due out on Valentine's Day.
 &HT;    Adams denies any interest in politics, but has long donated
time, effort and money to various causes. Recently, he joined Eric
Clapton, Mark Knopfler and other singers for a compilation album,
``Man To Woman,'' which promotes breast-cancer awareness.
 &HT;    ``Men of note sing for a good cause,'' he says. ``I've done
things for good causes before.''
 &HT;    That doesn't always mean singing, either. Adams shares the
screen in his video for ``On A Day Like Today'' with a big, gray
elephant, a nod to his involvement with the Tennessee-based
Elephant Sanctuary.
 &HT;    ``I thought putting him in the video would give them some
publicity,'' he says. ``I think they can use every donation they
can get. So I guess I am an animal-rights activist in some way.
 &HT;    ``I've been a vegetarian for 10 years,'' he adds. ``Morally, I
like the idea, plus I feel so much better. After reading the book
`Fit For Life,' it changed my philosophy toward life and food.''
 &HT;    His involvement in charity work _ he's also done work for
Amnesty International, Save the Whales and, during the days of
apartheid, a concert in support of the then-jailed South African
leader Nelson Mandela _ is all part of Adams' quest to find
balance.
 &HT;    ``Practicality doesn't drive my life,'' the singer says. ``It's
more discipline that keeps me going. I think I'm a very disciplined
person, and a goal-oriented one, too. I like to challenge myself
and get things done. If I say I'm going to put an album out this
year, then I'll move a mountain to get it done.''
 &HT;    In this case, he's skipping the traditional tour to promote the
album. Time in the studio is more important to him right now than
commercial pragmatism.
 &HT;    ``I'm just going to sit this one out until I see what the record
does,'' he says. ``I'm actually starting to record another album,
and I don't want to stoke up the fire just to have it rained on.''
 c.1998 Bonnie Siegler  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Bonnie Siegler is a Playa del Rey, Calif.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
