A1578 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUEEN-LATIFAH-IN-LIVI     10-12 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEEN-LATIFAH-IN-LIVING-OUT-LOUD-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEENS HIGH: THE FAR-RANGING WORLD OF QUEEN LATIFAH 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Queen Latifah in a scene from ``Living
Out Loud.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Some queens are born, some are made and some ... well, some
thrust queenliness upon themselves.
 &HT;    Take Dana Owens, a young girl who grew up in a family of police
officers in middle-class Irvington, N.J., in the 1960s. She didn't
necessarily envision herself as a future rap diva, she just wanted
a new name.
 &HT;    ``It was a custom for kids in my Jersey neighborhood to take on
a new name,'' she says. ``For some reason, we were never satisfied
with what our parents gave us.''
 &HT;    Leafing through a Muslim book of names, the 8-year-old Dana
stumbled onto the name ``Latifah.''
 &HT;    ``The description said `delicate and sensitive on the inside,'''
says the notoriously tough-as-nails Queen Latifah. ``That's me.''
 &HT;    As for ``Queen,'' she says, that was easier.
 &HT;    ``You might have noticed that I'm African-American,'' she says.
``I also wanted to be a rapper. I chose the Queen part because I
didn't want to be MC Latifah.''
 &HT;    As it turns out, Latifah has a realm wider than many queens have
boasted.
 &HT;    For example, there's her new film, ``Living Out Loud,'' opening
Oct. 23. She plays a sultry jazz singer who counsels a recently
divorced Holly Hunter. Latifah also appears in ``The Bone
Collector,'' a Denzel Washington thriller due next year.
 &HT;    On the music front, she recently released a rap CD called
``Order in the Court,'' and an album of jazz standards from
``Living Out Loud'' will follow.
 &HT;    As if that weren't enough, she's working on an autobiography
that will be released in 1999.
 &HT;    All this, in what Latifah calls a transition period.
 &HT;    ``I'm kind of figuring out what I'm going to do over the next
five years,'' she explains. ``The only thing I know for sure is
that I want to make a lot more movies. I mean good movies. I could
make movies until the day I die.
 &HT;    ``But let me add that I'm not removing myself from music,'' she
says. ``That's never going to happen.''
 &HT;    ``Living Out Loud'' casts the rap queen as a jazz singer, which
Latifah says wasn't so hard a gap to bridge.
 &HT;    ``People say, `Oh, it's such a stretch,''' she says, ``but not
necessarily. I've always been a person who knew about all kinds of
music growing up, so jazz wasn't really that new to me. I remember
my father played jazz records when I was a little girl.''
 &HT;    Latifah had no trouble identifying with the film's theme of
loneliness. Her brother, who was a police officer, died in a 1992
motorcycle accident.
 &HT;    ``It was the worst time in my life,'' she recalls, ``because I
was lonely and lost. To be lonely is one thing. Then to feel lost
is like, `Oh, God, where the hell do I go from here?'''
 &HT;    She smiles sadly.
 &HT;    ``The road back is the most fun part,'' she says, ``because
there is a path that you find to save yourself. It's the road to
healing. When you find it, it's like a light that just shines on
you.
 &HT;    ``I found it on the day when I said, `I'm tired of being unhappy
and being alone and being afraid.'''
 &HT;    Time, patience and prayer turned her life around, Latifah says.
 &HT;    ``I had to remember who I am and how it used to be,'' she says.
``I had to remember how strong and outgoing and fearless I was. I
started saying, `Damn, this sad person is not who I really am! Who
is this new person who is so lost? How can we get rid of this
person?'
 &HT;    ``And I had to just recognize certain things and traits that
could put me back in the same situation,'' she concludes. ``Once
you get through some of that, you start to find your way back.''
 &HT;    There were roadblocks, however. Two years ago, her BMW was
stolen at gunpoint in Harlem, in front of a Kentucky Fried Chicken.
Latifah's friend Shawn Moon was shot in the stomach, and nearly
died in her arms.
 &HT;    ``When Shawn got shot, he was trying so hard to stay alive,''
she recalls. ``I knew I had to take control. I didn't wait for an
ambulance. I hailed a car to get him to the hospital quickly. In
that car, breathing was the big issue for him. I had to talk him
out of giving up.''
 &HT;    The source of her strength, Latifah says, has always been her
police-officer father.
 &HT;    ``He told my brother and I that basically we could do
anything,'' she says. ``My father was a Vietnam vet and police
officer. He was very handsome, and my mother was very beautiful. I
think I got my strength from them, because on a daily basis I would
say, `Look at my parents.''
 &HT;    Very young, her talent as a performer became evident.
 &HT;    ``I grew up in a house full of hams,'' she recalls. ``I would
just watch TV and imitate accents. I was this weird kid who would
speak Jamaican one day and Spanish the next.
 &HT;    ``I would imitate commercials and walk around going, `Hi, I'm
Ruta Lenska.' Remember that old commercial? My aunts would always
wake me up when I was sleeping and go, `We're so sorry, but Dana,
come here, girl, and do the Ruta Lenska commercial.'''
 &HT;    At 17, Latifah decided to take her shot at music.
 &HT;    ``I said, `If I can make it happen within a year, I'll stick
with it,''' she says.
 &HT;    It happened. Her debut album, ``All Hail the Queen'' (1989),
sold more than a million copies and was nominated for a Grammy
Award. ``Black Reign'' (1994), which won a Grammy, made her the
first female solo rap artist to achieve gold-record status.
 &HT;    The next year, Latifah branched out, founding Flavor Unit
Records, which now represents rap artists such as LL Cool J,
Outkast and N.E.X.T.
 &HT;    Still itching for new worlds to conquer, the rapper won critical
acclaim as a lesbian bank robber in ``Set It Off'' (1996). Since
then, she has also appeared in ``Hoodlum'' (1997), ``Sphere''
(1998) and the television series ``Living Single.''
 &HT;    She doesn't discourage comparisons with Will Smith.
 &HT;    ``Will was actually one of the reasons I did the TV show,'' she
recalls, laughing. ``My partner was in the hallway watching `The
Fresh Prince' on TV, and she was like, `Damn, if Will Smith can do
this TV show, maybe we can get a show.'''
 &HT;    These days, though, television takes a back seat to movies.
 &HT;    ``The problem is that there are a few black actresses in my age
group,'' Latifah says, ``and we're always competing for the same
roles. Most of all I want people to be able to see my name on a
marquee of a film or on a poster and know that movie is good just
because my name is on it.''
 &HT;    To Latifah, this is the secret of her legendary toughness.
 &HT;    ``I would like them to say that Queen Latifah tried to fight the
good fight the whole way,'' she says. ``And that I stayed in touch
with who I was. I didn't sell out, I didn't lose myself. I didn't
become someone else just for money or just for a career or any of
that stuff. I stayed me. I learned. I grew.''
 &HT;    So just how tough is she?
 &HT;    ``I am tender _ I think people know it,'' Latifah says. ``My
fans don't think I'm too tough. That is the downside.
 &HT;    ``A few guys have tried to feel my butt in clubs and have
realized that I'm a little tougher than what they thought,'' she
says, laughing. ``I just grab their hands, give them a look and
say, `Honey, we don't go there.'''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
