<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1579 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PETER-GALLAGHER-IN-SE     10-12 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETER-GALLAGHER-IN-SECRET-LIVES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NOT-SO-SECRET LIFE OF PETER GALLAGHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Peter Gallagher with Mitch Rouse and Brad
Whitford in a scene from ``The Secret Lives of Men.'' 
 By STEPHEN COLE  
 c.1998 Canadian TV Guide  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter Gallagher has a 16 handicap in golf and a sex handicap in
acting.
</P>
<P>
   So far in his career, which first broke the surface in ``Sex,
Lies and Videotape'' (1989), the dimpled, blue-eyed actor has
specialized in playing handsome, fallible heroes _ the leaky
dreamboats who always drag the girl down with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I've played a lot of callow, insensitive types,'' the
40ish actor concedes, relaxing on a stool in a bar in Pasadena,
Calif., minutes after doing a press conference for his new ABC
sitcom, ``The Secret Lives of Men.'' Hanging around the edges are
his co-stars in the series, Mitch Rouse and Brad Whitford.
</P>
<P>
   ```Sex and Lies' gave me visibility,'' Gallagher says, swigging
from a glass of ginger ale, ``and perhaps an industry pigeonhole.
But, you know, the parts I've taken, I'd like to think they're
about good writing and not about image.''
</P>
<P>
   Those parts have included roles in ``While You Were Sleeping''
(1995) and Robert Altman's ``The Player'' (1992) and ``Short Cuts''
(1993), but he admits that he agreed to play a divorced,
golf-with-the-boys-on-Saturday regular guy in a television sitcom
in a conscious attempt to lighten his movie image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can get trapped playing certain kinds of roles,
and the idea of playing comedy _ good comedy _ has always appealed
to me,'' says the native of Armonk, N.Y., who was trained in the
classics and performed on Broadway in such shows as ``A Doll's
Life'' and ``Grease.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of doing a TV sitcom didn't bother me at all,'' he
says. ``If you're committed as an actor to look for good writing,
and the best writing you've encountered in a long time is a sitcom,
you do it without thinking twice.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude led the married, bicoastal father of two to sign
on for a comedy that ABC liked so much that it added the show to
its Wednesday lineup _ one of its biggest nights of the week _
alongside proven hits ``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' and ``The Drew Carey
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher is happy to have a desirable time slot, but hastens to
add that he doesn't know much about the business end of television,
and doesn't want to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned in movies not to believe anything you hear and only
half of what you see,'' he says. ``So much is out of the actor's,
or sometimes even the director's and producer's control. One big
executive loses his job, and a project that everyone was so high on
is suddenly headed for the trash heap.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Gallagher says he's content playing Michael, an
honorable businessman and dad who suddenly finds himself in the
unpleasant business of divorce, with only the golf-buddy
friendships of fellow divorcees Phil (Whitford) and Andy (Rouse) to
keep him sane.
</P>
<P>
   The three live in apartments in Manhattan. Their wives got the
kids, the houses and most of the money. Instead of enjoying
home-cooked meals, they meet almost nightly at Bocelli's, a cozy
Italian eatery where the owner, Kate (Christine Dunford), provides
their sustenance.
</P>
<P>
   The setup may sound depressing, but Gallagher insists that it's
a barrel of laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most fun I've had in a long time,'' the actor
says. ``What a joy it is to come to work and literally have fun all
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitford, a big-screen veteran of ``The Client'' (1994) and
``Red Corner'' (1998), agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weird thing is, you're having fun with the torment of
people's lives,'' he says. ``There's a real depth to this show.''
</P>
<P>
   Rouse, best known for ``The Truth About Cats &AMP; Dogs'' (1996),
says that the show could work only as comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be too heavy,'' he says. ``It just wouldn't work if
it was a drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Gallagher whirls on his fellow actor, seething with
mock outrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing?'' he demands. ``This is a drama, you
dummy!''
</P>
<P>
   Rouse does a Kramerlike shiver and slaps his hand over his
mouth, which prompts his co-stars into a fit of giggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``See?'' Gallagher says, smiling. ``Fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Another rewarding aspect of ``Secret Lives,'' Gallagher adds, is
the use of a golf course as a regular setting for the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing golf for 10 years,'' he explains, ``and I
never appreciated until this series what a great dramatic
possibility the sport really is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf absolutely, fundamentally keeps you honest,'' he says.
``It humbles you. You might think you know a person, then you play
golf with him and see how he reacts to adversity and to his own
limitations, or see how some people cheat when they're scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he adds, golf provides a framework for the male bonding
that drives the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the cliche is women talk about their problems and men
don't,'' he says. ``But whatever demons haunt you in real life come
out, barking and full-out, on the golf course. When you hit a poor
shot, you're naked.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching Gallagher interact with Whitford and Rouse suggests
that the three, who didn't know each other before filming, have
already developed the joshing, lightning-quick rapport of old
college roomies.
</P>
<P>
   That quality, Gallagher says, is more important than being able
to master the quick verbal ping pong of a television sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm aware of the so-called `sitcom rhythm' on TV, it's
inevitably on badly written comedies where the actors do nothing
but exchange wisecracks,'' he says. ``Funny on TV should be like
being funny on stage, or in real life for that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Except there's a laugh track,'' Whitford adds.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher gives him a look.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't a laugh track,'' he says. ``Those were other
golfers behind the bushes, laughing at everything we said.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Stephen Cole is a staff writer at Canadian TV Guide, based in
North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
