 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2489 - October 12, 1998   NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2489 -- Oct. 12, 1998 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. INTERNET KILLED THE VIDEO STAR Clinton's impeachment, if and
when it comes, will not herald a crisis of Constitution but a
crisis of media. Brilliant exploitation of television may have won
this president his office, but he must blame his downfall on an
inability to resist the impact of another, new medium : the
Internet. By Douglas Rushkoff. 1,000 words. (N/A Great Britain and
Australia.) 2. CONCRETE : THE KEY TO CONSTRUCTION Concrete, both
bane and boon to the urban landscape, was perfected to an art form
by the builders of ancient Rome. But the recipe - cement, additives
and water - was lost for centuries with the fall of the empire and
only rediscovered several hundred years ago. Legions of scientists
have been fine-tuning the product ever since and today there are
scores of variations. One can carry the weight of a car on a
surface the size of a fingernail. By Dr. Erwin Lausch. From GEO
magazine. 2,300 words. (English translation available.)
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
FREUD UP AGAINST THE WALL Some people wanted an exhibit that said
Freud was wrong, that he was a bad person, that people should have
the moral courage to condemn him - but that's not how the new Freud
show at the Library of Congress is. Actually, it used to be that a
curator had an exhibit criticized after it opened. Now the
complaints come early and relentlessly, and shape what gets shown
and how. The Freud show is a sad case in point. By Margaret Talbot.
From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (4,000 words) +
edited article available.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
BARBARA KINGSOLVER AT THE BARRICADES Barbara Kingsolver's big new
book, ``The Poisonwood Bible,'' is a tragic family saga set in the
Congo just as that republic is winning independence from Belgium.
But it also has a more subversive intent : to expose America's role
in the Congo of the '60s. As she puts it, ``If I were to write a
non-fiction book about the brief blossoming and destruction of the
independence of the Congo, and what the CIA had to do with it, then
probably all 85 people who are interested in the subject could read
it.'' Instead she wrote a novel with family, culture and an exotic
locale. By Sarah Kerr. From The New York Times Magazine.
Full-length (3,100 words) + edited article available.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
From THE NEW YORK TIMES BOOK REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   A. OF HUMAN BONDAGE : In the 17th and 18th centuries, the idea
of slavery was not yet firmly defined. George M. Fredrickson
reviews the book ``Many Thousands Gone'' by Ira Berlin. 1,500
words. B. HEARTS OF DARKNESS : Wole Soyinka (the Nigerian
playwright who won the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1986) reviews
the book ``We Wish To Inform You That Tomorrow We Will Be Killed
With Our Families'' by Philip Gourevitch, which traces the authors
of Rwanda's genocide.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
THE STRICKEN SOULS OF SARAJEVO Foreigners visiting Sarajevo for the
first time are usually disappointed. They expect to see more
evidence of the ravages of war on buildings and on the faces of
people they pass in the street. Yet there remain deep scars in the
suburbs, some of which are still in ruins. It has been calculated
that each inhabitant was hit at least once by shrapnel. Evidence
gathered by psychiatrists suggests that the city's younger
generation is emotionally disturbed and drained of energy.
Christian Lecomte talked to young people in Sarajevo. From Le
Monde. 1,500 words. (English translation available.)
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
PORTRAIT - LEONARD COHEN For 30 years, Leonard Cohen has played at
subverting his own success as a singer and poet. Now he is a monk
at a Zen centre in California. Has the sinner-songwriter finally
found peace? By Pico Iyer. From Prospect magazine. (N/A U.K.) 3,000
words. 8. FROM MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE : A. PREVENTING EAR
INFECTIONS : New research raises the possibility that giving
children a special kind of gum or a spoonful of sweet syrup might
help ward off childhood ear infections. 500 words. B. LASER EYE
SURGERY - IS IT FOR YOU? Dr. Elliot Finkelstein writes about
surgery for near-sightedness. 500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
WHAT'S DOING IN TRINIDAD Events, sightseeing, hotels and
restaurants on the Caribbean island of Trinidad. By Larry Rohter.
From The New York Times. 1,000 words + photos + map.
