<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1623 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIGHTING-ALS13-COX     10-12 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIGHTING-ALS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is there nothing we can do to help Mom with als?
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The serene smile Fanny Pedata wore to
her party may well have been an old smile, indeed, a smile left
over from 7 or 8 years ago when she last had control of her facial
muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it was just the joy of knowing 95 friends and family
members had gathered at a benefit to buy her more time in her own
home. Pedata, 62, for 13 years a secretary at Pratt &AMP; Whitney, has
Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis _ commonly called Lou Gehrig's
disease.
</P>
<P>
   She cannot move. She cannot breathe unassisted.
</P>
<P>
   But she can think as clearly as she did before ALS took over.
She can communicate. And she does worry about the $4,000 a month it
takes to care for her on her $1,800-a-month income.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she raises her eyebrow,'' explains her son, Dominick
Pedata, of North Palm Beach, ``that means she wants to spell, so we
grab the spelling chart.''
</P>
<P>
   And then she blinks as a family member prompts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We divided the alphabet into four lines,'' adds a daughter,
Connie McCormick. ``We point to the line and then the letter. We
can talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's take at the $25-a-head dinner, dance and silent
auction at the Palm Lakes Estates Recreation Hall in Riviera Beach
was just more than $3,000. The money will buy her another month or
so at home until, inevitably . . .
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably what?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing. The family cannot find a nursing home in the area that
will accept an ALS patient who uses a respirator to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was the kind of person who would do anything for
anyone,'' says McCormick, 44. ``She was very active, always
working, always there for others, whether it was family, someone on
her bowling team or giving to the United Way.''
</P>
<P>
   Before her $1 million health insurance policy ran out in 1993,
Pedata received 24-hour nursing care in her home. When that was
gone, there was no safety net. Fanny Pedata, the bureaucrats seem
to be saying, is somebody else's responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the insurance actuaries explain, nobody is supposed to
live for 10 years with ALS.
</P>
<P>
   Pedata's $1,800 disability income disqualifies her for Medicaid,
and misses by half the minimum it takes to watch over her. If her
family ever stops struggling to keep her at home with caretaker
help, she will go to a hospital at, the family points out, an
ungodly cost to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Living in a hospital, too, would bring unspeakable heartbreak to
Pedata, whose only solace is familiar surroundings and people who
know how to comfort her and communicate with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her mind is sharp as ever, and she is quite aware of the
hardships of the family and the strain they're under,'' said Karen
Roberts, a Pratt &AMP; Whitney secretary who befriended the family
years ago. ``Unfortunately, there are no agencies to provide
financial assistance to long-term survivors of ALS, and in all
honesty most people do not live long enough to have this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedata's daughter, Annette Appleby, 39, said the strain of
looking after her mother has contributed to several divorces in the
family, her own included.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the insurance runs out, where is this safety net we keep
hearing about?'' said Appleby, a cable company telephone operator.
``Where are the social agencies and charities when we need them
most? There is no financial assistance for home care. When the
United Way comes to my workplace, I'm so angry I say, `Don't even
come near me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   McCormick, a child-care worker, has kept her mother in her home
for a year at a time, and for lesser periods when caretakers quit.
The strain on a marriage, finances and children cannot be imagined
by outsiders, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have wonderful caretakers now, but in the past, we have had
a big turnover,'' said McCormick. ``Every time there is an
emergency, somebody has to cover or our mother dies.''
</P>
<P>
   And don't get the family started on how the insurance company
went through the $1 million insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, the care was there, but $40 an hour for registered
nurses,'' said Appleby, ``when the money would have lasted twice as
long with licensed practical nurses or aides. We're stretching our
money with untrained caretakers that we train.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedata's children, and even her 79-year-old mother, Nina
Kilbane, and her 81-year-old stepfather, Charles, have learned to
feed Fanny through the hole in her stomach, to clean her, change
her bedding and maintain the respirator that keeps her alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``As hard as this ordeal is on us,'' said Dominick, ``it's
harder on our mother. It's very distressing to keep going to the
community and asking for money, but we don't know what else to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, we could go to the well of public sympathy one more time
by mentioning that anyone who would like to help care for Fanny
Pedata at home could send a check to The Philomena Pedata Benefit
Account at Washington Mutual Bank, 4470 Northlake Blvd., Palm Beach
Gardens, FL 33410.
</P>
<P>
   As for other possible sources of help, I called both the
Muscular Dystrophy Association and the United Way of Palm Beach
County Inc., and explained the family's dilemma. Both agencies said
that many thousands of families in the nation struggle heroically
with invalid care crises.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Brown, director of public affairs for MDA, said that its
services to Pedata have included clinic visits, follow-up care, and
help with equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our local program services coordinator is exploring ways for
MDA to assist (with equipment costs for) Mrs. Pedata,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't give money to individuals,'' said Scott Baddesch,
United Way executive director. ``(But) we can talk to social
workers who may be able to qualify this family for help either
through the government programs or perhaps a foundation grant.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, we've got to find a way to keep Fanny Pedata
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
