<SLUG> BC-HANDY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moderation, exercise help keep hands healthy
 &HT;    By Norma Martin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Your hands get an intensive workout. They type
at computers, chop vegetables, play guitars, hammer nails and dig
landscapes. And then they go home and work some more.
</P>
<P>
   When they're exhausted, their owners are painfully aware of
their condition _ through ailments such as repetitive motion
injuries, chronic tendinitis and carpal tunnel syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Hands, like any other body part, need preventive care if they're
going to operate at peak performance. Healthy hands are part of a
healthy lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Early intervention often can prevent small problems from
becoming big ones, experts say. The key is paying attention to how
the hands are being used. After a long day of typing, are you
playing two hours of tennis or gardening for three hours?
</P>
<P>
   If so, stop. Your hands need a rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big misconception is that computers are going to get you,''
said Sharon Guebert, a certified hand therapist with HealthSouth
Hand Rehabilitation Center.
</P>
<P>
   Leisure activities can be a culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask what are they doing at home,'' she said. ``How are they
handling the pots, how long are they playing tennis or spending on
knitting, crocheting or gardening?''
</P>
<P>
   Over-indulging in a favorite hobby can be detrimental to hand
health. So can performing the task incorrectly.
</P>
<P>
   Hand therapists say they've seen their share of young baseball
players and gymnasts with repetitive motion injuries. Often, their
problems are related to improper form while participating in a
sport.
</P>
<P>
   What steps can you take to help maintain healthy hands?
</P>
<P>
   First, be aware of how much stress the hands are enduring.
</P>
<P>
   Then, develop the habit of stretching. All hand therapists are
advocates of hand stretches to release the buildup of tension that
occurs from repetitive tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking a short period of time, and it's very important
for overall tissue health,'' said Guebert. ``Every hour, stop what
you're doing and stretch those hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Another preventive measure is using tools designed with the
hands in mind. Ergonomics, the concept of fitting tools to the
body, is the emphasis here.
</P>
<P>
   But also keep in mind that fabulous tools aren't going to help
if they're used improperly, said Paula Davison, a certified hand
therapist with Seton Northwest Hospital's sports medicine program.
</P>
<P>
   As Davison's patients, such as M.W. Bell, work their way back to
hand health, she often recommends tools they can use.
</P>
<P>
   In Bell's case, the most essential item was a new pen. She said
it was the first thing she purchased after leaving the hospital
following a long illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't hold the old ones,'' said Bell.
</P>
<P>
   With everything from toothbrushes to hammers coming with kinder,
gentler handles these days, Davison has some advice for those
shopping for hand tools _ whether they are for the kitchen or the
workshop. Three things are important: a light weight, padding and
bigger handles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want tools that mash into the palms,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Davison also notes that ergonomic design doesn't go hand in hand
with price. ``I've seen some very expensive gardening tools that
aren't in the least ergonomic,'' she said. ``They're pretty . . .
but there's no way you could use those for any period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Norma Martin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
