<HEADER>
A1625 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INFINITE-DRESS13-COX     10-12 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFINITE-DRESS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The infinite fit
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Click.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now, back to MacGyver.'' Click.
</P>
<P>
   `` _ Doppler radar _ '' Click.
</P>
<P>
   `` _ high fly ball to right field _ '' Click.
</P>
<P>
   `` _ everyone will think you just bought it in Paris!''
</P>
<P>
   Well, well, well, what is this? It's bedtime, but I've been
hooked by an infomercial for something called the Infinite Dress.
</P>
<P>
   One dress, oodles of styles. Thirty-four, to be exact. I watch
as smiling models walk up and down a runway, slipping fabric from
shoulder to shoulder, magically revealing nothing more than a
little cleavage in the process. Cocktail wear to poolside wear to
jumpers, all for $59 plus shipping and handling. Intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   Tying my own shoelaces is tough enough, but this is an
irrational hour. I call the number and place an order.
</P>
<P>
   About a month later, a thin cardboard box arrives with an
instructional video and booklet and the Infinite Dress itself.
</P>
<P>
   The dress, I soon find, is the octopus of outwear, eight feet of
stretchy black DuPont fabric with two long tails that wrap around
you in dozens of ways. There's Style No. 5, which has a Greek
goddess appeal. And No. 27, a one-shouldered cave woman look. Style
33 (``to be worn with your favorite choker necklace,'' the booklet
says) makes a halter-topped dress with a disco flair.
</P>
<P>
   No time to experiment yet. I stuff the dress and instructions
into my backpack and fly to New York, where I promptly forget about
it until the final day of my visit.
</P>
<P>
   By then it's the last thing clean I have, so by the light of the
painfully dim hotel lamp, I wrap myself in Style No. 28, a backless
V-neck look that requires crossing the tails in back and bringing
them forward to tie at the waist.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sexier look than I'm used to, but this is New York City,
I figure. And I'm going to fashion shows. Everyone will be looking
at the models.
</P>
<P>
   I plan to dart into strange restrooms throughout the day, trying
Style No. 2 or Style No. 17 or Style No. 32, depending on what I
can manage in a tiny stall.
</P>
<P>
   In between pit stops, I will plop my Infinitely Dressed self in
the path of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   MOSS, MELLEN AND MENKES
</P>
<P>
   After the Calvin Klein show, I scoot into the elevator just in
time to stand next to supermodel Kate Moss. I tap her on the
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, um,'' I squeak. ``I'm wearing this dress and, uh, what do
you think of it?''
</P>
<P>
   Kate, who was whispering and giggling with a friend, stops
smiling and glances over her shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fine,'' she says, turning back.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, it's this infomercial product,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't respond.
</P>
<P>
   I have more luck with fellow fashion editors. I start at the
top, with Suzy Menkes of the International Herald Tribune. She's
the dean of the group, easily recognizable by her trademark There's
Something About Mary flip of bangs. (No funny stuff, though _ she
uses a barrette.)
</P>
<P>
   She squints. ``It looks like a Yohji Yamamoto,'' she says,
invoking a hip Japanese designer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's from an infomercial,'' I tell her.
</P>
<P>
   She leans forward and says, in that clipped British accent, ``A
what?''
</P>
<P>
   She sends me to Polly Mellen, creative director for Allure
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like one I own, by Helmut Lang!'' says the
ever-enthusiastic Mellen. ``It also looks Japanese! Stand up! Oh, I
never would have said Helmut Lang if you had been standing. Now
that you're standing, I can see what you've done with it. It's
something you're able to get into and turn into an expression of
the moment. I wish it wasn't black _ I'm moving away from black. It
would be great in red or white. I can tell you like to wear strong
clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   I back away.
</P>
<P>
   But their musings don't match the response I get on the street.
A cement truck rumbles by. ``Hey hooooooker!'' the driver yells.
</P>
<P>
   Hooker? Shamed, I approach a nun who is leaving the Guardian
Angel Church on 10th Avenue. ``Sister, does this dress make me look
like a tart?'' I ask. ``Well, it would be better if you had a
jacket on, but at least you're covered up,'' she responds.
</P>
<P>
   I thank her, and cross the street, ignoring a passing shout of
``Put it on!''
</P>
<P>
   I wear dirty clothes on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   THE CULPRITS
</P>
<P>
   I wear the dress to meet the couple behind the infomercial,
producers Wendy and Rory Fielding of Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   Rory sees the dress _ in Style No. Something I Made Up _ and
smiles. ``I've seen the Infinite Dress, but only on models,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   They give me a little history. The dress was born sometime in
the '70s and had a brief shining moment, even making it on the
cover of Spanish Cosmo. Then it kind of disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   But a few years ago, Rory saw the dress on the Home Shopping
Network and the Fieldings bought the rights. They went to the WXEL
studios with about every model in the Boca-Fort Lauderdale area,
and in two days they filmed a 30-minute infomercial. They picked
Jennilee Harrison _ former star of Dallas and Three's Company _ as
the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   They changed the dress' price from $89 to $59, tested the
infomercial in a few small markets in March and it caught on.
</P>
<P>
   Now the show is running about 300 times a week across the U.S.
And so far, they've had $8 million in sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of fashion and David Copperfield and
Siegfried and Roy,'' Rory Fielding says. ``I knew it would be
fabulous for TV. We're planning a retail launch in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem has been, there's no rack appeal,'' Wendy says.
``You can't put this on a hanger.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course you can't. It's an 8-foot-long dress.
</P>
<P>
   And at the moment, mine is wadded up in a file cabinet at work.
Style No. Nothing. The truth is, it makes my butt look big.
</P>
<P>
   But it would make an infinitely comfortable hammock.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1626 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWORLEANS13-COX     10-12 2005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWORLEANS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting gastronomic in The Big Easy
 &HT;    By Dale Rice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Paul Prudhomme. Emeril Lagasse. Susan Spicer.
Frank Brigtsen.
</P>
<P>
   If you recognize three out of four of those names, it's obvious
why you travel to New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't, it's time you learned.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz, football, a rich history, the occult, Audubon Zoo, art
galleries, shopping for antiques and the biggest party scene either
side of the Rockies may lure visitors to New Orleans the first
time, but it's the culinary scene that helps bring them back.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, there are oysters, shrimp, crawfish, gumbo,
etouffee, po' boys, muffulettas, bread pudding and beignets _ the
foods that New Orleans made famous. (Or should that be the other
way around _ the foods that made New Orleans famous?)
</P>
<P>
   But that's only a beginning, a tiny beginning. New Orleans is
one of the top gastronomic cities in the United States, if not the
world. There may be more high-quality restaurants per square mile
in the French Quarter than anywhere on the globe.
</P>
<P>
   If you think that's hyperbole, then listen to what the readers
of Conde-Nast Traveler magazine had to say. Those upscale,
well-traveled, insightful readers consistently have named New
Orleans one of the top 10 destinations in the world. And they knew
what they were voting for.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb Loin with Goat Cheese and Zinfandel Sauce at Spicer's
Bayona. Paneed Milk-fed Veal with Fresh Lump Crabmeat Ravioli and
Roasted Red Pepper
</P>
<P>
   Cream Sauce at Lagasse's NOLA. Broiled Gulf Fish with
Crabmeat-Parmesan Crust and Lemon Mousselline at Brigtsen's
Brigtsen's (his restaurant and last name are one and the same).
Roasted Chicken Roulade Tchoupitoulas at Prudhomme's K-Paul's
Louisiana Kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   That's New Orleans of the '90s, filled with chefs who are
melding ingredients and techniques to produce awesome dishes. But
they are only one reason _ albeit the first and foremost _ to visit
the city. There are others. So grab a napkin and join us on a
culinary journey through the Big Easy. Restaurants
</P>
<P>
   Cajun. Creole. French. Italian. Southern. Traditional. Avant
garde.
</P>
<P>
   This is a city where cooking styles and traditions get blended
at the pace of a Cuisinart on high speed. Consequently, most
restaurant menus are an eclectic mix of dishes, as chefs frequently
reach to one tradition to start an item and borrow from another to
finish it.
</P>
<P>
   In this atmosphere, creativity abounds. And creativity leads to
excellence.
</P>
<P>
   For example: Commander's Palace has consistently been ranked by
critics as one of the top 10 restaurants in the country. Others
such as Bayona, Emeril's and Bistro at Maison de Ville are
recognized nationally. Frank Brigtsen was named James Beard Chef of
the South this year.
</P>
<P>
   And that's only the tip of the iceberg _ and we're not talking
lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say that this is a city where there are more
wonderful restaurants than adjectives to describe them. Candy shops
</P>
<P>
   Truffles the size of tennis balls. Pralines the size of
Frisbees. OK, OK, so that's a little exaggeration. But if you're a
fan of chocolate or pecans, it's difficult to walk by one of
several candy shops in the French Quarter and not be drawn in
almost uncontrollably by the scent and sight of these confectionery
delights.
</P>
<P>
   At Laura's Candies and Creole Gourmet on Conti Street, the
truffles are the size of golf balls. Lined neatly behind the
counter, these candies sport milk and dark chocolate exteriors that
cloak soft, creamy centers in a variety of flavors such as
raspberry, maple and pina colada. Split two of these $15.95-a-pound
treats with a friend (obviously you'll want to sample more than one
flavor) and you'll both be on a chocolate high until dinner.
</P>
<P>
   In the French Market, Evans Creole Candy Factory and Aunt
Sally's Praline Shop must be turning out pralines by the hundreds
every day. At Evans, there are four kinds to choose from _ maple,
chocolate, rum and traditional. (Although it's awfully easy to be
distracted by the incredible turtles, formed of macadamia nuts,
almonds or pecans, at $18.95 a pound.) At Aunt Sally's the pralines
are available in individual boxes _ making the transport home that
much easier. Culinary antiques
</P>
<P>
   Looking for 17th-century glassware? How about 18th-century
silver? Or 19th-century porcelain?
</P>
<P>
   Stroll along Chartres and Royal Streets in the French Quarter or
travel Magazine Street west of the central business district, and
you'll find dozens of fine antique shops with thousands of kitchen
and dining items tucked among the treasures.
</P>
<P>
   But step into Lucullus Culinary Antiques, and it's all there
under one roof _ an entire shop dedicated to the fine art of
dining, antique style. There's everything from a hand-painted Spode
fish platter to an assortment of sterling silver toast racks to a
set of seven, hand-blown Dutch glasses from the 18th century
(priced at $5,500). Cafe du Monde
</P>
<P>
   On the edge of the French Market, just across the street from
Jackson Square, there's a cafe where they've been drinking coffee
since the 1860s: Cafe du Monde.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's 3 p.m. or 3 a.m., you can find patrons sipping the
famous chicory-flavored coffee and eating plates of beignets, the
little yeast-type doughnut covered with confectioner's sugar that
may be one of New Orleans' best known foods.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, Cafe du Monde is filled with people taking a
break and listening to the jazz musicians playing nearby. In the
middle of the night, it's a stop between bar-hopping and slumber
for many who've obviously imbibed a lot more than coffee as they
made their way along Bourbon Street. Grocery stores
</P>
<P>
   In an age of giant supermarkets with thousands of specialty
foods, people still flock to two small groceries that have been
operating for most of this century on Decatur Street.
</P>
<P>
   Central Grocery &AMP; Deli, founded in 1906, bills itself as the
home of the original muffuletta, that glorious sandwich of cold
cuts, cheese and olive salad on a large roll.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the narrow aisles that are difficult to maneuver,
shoppers line up to order muffulettas (and eat them at the counters
in the rear of the store) and load bags with imported cheese, olive
oil, spices, herbs, pasta and other imported delights you can't
find on the shelves of most mega-markets.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby at Progress Grocery, a less crowded atmosphere invites
shoppers to grab a muffuletta or browse a wide variety of Cajun and
Creole spice mixtures, as well as imported products from Europe and
the Middle East. And if you need a gift for someone special, why
not pick up an Alligator Bob's smoked alligator stick. It's only
$1.69, and the look on the recipient's face will be worth every
penny. Farmers Market
</P>
<P>
   Opening daily at sunrise, the Farmers Market by mid-morning is
teeming with people, many on their way to the flea market that's
just behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh fruits and vegetables are piled high, while refrigerated
cases hold fresh seafood that you long to take home. (Extra large
Gulf shrimp were priced at $10.95 a pound one day this summer,
while barbecued crawfish tails were just $2.50 a pound. It's hard
to pass a bargain like that.)
</P>
<P>
   While the open-air market is covered, offering some protection
from rain showers or the hot sun, it rapidly becomes sweltering in
summer. But even oppressive heat doesn't deter tourists from coming
there for the spices, sauces, mixes and coffees that also fill the
stands. Cooking schools
</P>
<P>
   Trendy or traditional? Take your pick when it comes to
instruction.
</P>
<P>
   If gumbo, dirty rice and bread pudding are your idea of a great
meal in New Orleans, then there are two cooking schools right up
your alley: Cookin' Cajun Cooking School and New Orleans School of
Cooking.
</P>
<P>
   At Cookin' Cajun, in a downtown mall overlooking the Mississippi
River, 35 to 40 participants packed a small room to watch Susan
Murphy, who laces her instruction with tips and humor, prepare a
Rockefeller sauce for an oyster appetizer, shrimp and okra gumbo
and pecan pie tarts.
</P>
<P>
   Later that same weekend, a few blocks away on the edge of the
warehouse district, Michelle Nugent led nine adults in preparing a
more sophisticated meal in an intimate setting at Spice Inc., the
latest venture of Bayona chef/owner Susan Spicer. Spice Inc. is a
small, upscale market featuring meats, cheese, prepared foods,
baked goods, cooking supplies, including its own line of dried
herbs and spices, and lessons.
</P>
<P>
   At the hands-on Saturday night dinner, which Spice Inc. limits
to 16 participants, students alternately prepared the courses _
Mussels Peasant Style, Salad Greens with Portobello Mushroom, Ancho
Shrimp and Seared Ribeye with Chimichurri Sauce and Creme Renversee
au Caramel _ under Nugent's guidance and then gathered around the
table to savor their work. And it was an effort worth savoring.
Cookbooks
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere you turn in the French Quarter there are souvenir
shops with dozens of cookbooks featuring Creole and Cajun cooking,
along with the well-known (and not-so-well-known) chefs and
restaurants of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   But for serious cookbook lovers, the type who appreciate the
musty smell of old paper almost as much as the aroma of garlic, the
French Quarter provides fertile hunting grounds for used culinary
tomes.
</P>
<P>
   At Crescent City, which probably has the largest collection at
300-plus, the books are arranged neatly by subject, just inside the
front door. At two other stores, Dauphine Street Books and the
Librairie Book Shop, the arrangement is less orderly, with
overflowing shelves and stacks of books on the floor. But don't let
the piles deter you; you never know what little gem you might find.
Lagniappe
</P>
<P>
   In the tradition of New Orleans, a lagniappe is a little
something extra. In this case it's a special treat _ not for the
visitor _ but for the four-legged family member left at home.
</P>
<P>
   These treats can be found at Three Dog Bakery, an unusual shop
on Royal Street, where you'd swear the refrigerated cases hold
French pastries and other baked goods that you could gobble in a
minute.
</P>
<P>
   But while they look like they're made for the dessert tray,
they're better suited for the dog dish. Carob and other ingredients
merely look like chocolate and other sweets; in reality everything
is canine friendly.
</P>
<P>
   What better way to assuage any guilty feelings about leaving the
pooch behind than to return home with a small sack for the dog and
a big bag of culinary treats for you.
</P>
<P>
   Bon appetit! Eating and shopping in The Big Easy
</P>
<P>
   Here are the New Orleans addresses and phone numbers for the
shops and restaurants mentioned in the story:
</P>
<P>
   Aunt Sally's Praline Shop, 810 Decatur St., (800) 642-7257
</P>
<P>
   Bayona, 430 Dauphine St., (504) 525-4455
</P>
<P>
   Bistro at Maison de Ville, 733 Toulouse St., (504) 528-9206
</P>
<P>
   Brigtsen's, 723 Dante St., (504) 861-7610
</P>
<P>
   Cafe du Monde, 800 Decatur St., (504) 581-2914
</P>
<P>
   Central Grocery &AMP; Deli, 923 Decatur St., (504) 523-1620
</P>
<P>
   Commander's Palace, 1403 Washington Ave., (504) 899-8221
</P>
<P>
   Cookin' Cajun Cooking School, Riverwalk mall, (504) 586-8832
</P>
<P>
   Crescent City Books, 2204 Chartres St., (504) 524-4997
</P>
<P>
   Dauphine Street Books, 410 Dauphine St., (504) 529-2333
</P>
<P>
   Emeril's, 800 Tchoupitoulas St., (504) 528-9393
</P>
<P>
   Evans Creole Candy Factory, 848 Decatur St., (504) 522-7111
</P>
<P>
   Farmers Market, 1200 N. Peters St., (504) 522-2621
</P>
<P>
   K-Paul's Louisiana Kitchen, 416 Chartres St., (504) 596-2530
</P>
