<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1627 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPERA-BOCELLI-COX     10-12 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-BOCELLI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is this pop-opera phenomenon the next Pavarotti?
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A voice is a color, it's a sensation, it's impossible to
describe.''
</P>
<P>
   So says Andrea Bocelli in his video A Night in Tuscany, the PBS
pledge-drive favorite that has catapulted the 40-year-old Italian
singer to worldwide renown. It's as profound a summation of the
human voice as any poet might utter. But Bocelli should know.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to him, and you swear you've got a direct line to the
angels. The voice is like a richly aged red wine: complex,
mysterious, full of notes of sweetness and sadness. It is not your
typical operatic tenor, an instrument of bravado. It is, in a word,
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``A voice is a color . . . '' How ironic, of course: Andrea
Bocelli is blind.
</P>
<P>
   He's also the hottest thing in opera since Messrs. Carreras,
Domingo and Pavarotti topped the charts with their Three Tenors
routine. When Bocelli sings at the newly opened National Car Rental
Center on Tuesday, it will come at a moment when the handsome but
scraggly singer, who looks like a cross between Omar Sharif and Don
Johnson, has all but conquered the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Since the release of his first CD in his native country five
years ago, Bocelli has posted sales figures associated more with
Madonna and Puff Daddy than Verdi and Puccini, to name two of the
most prominent composers in his repertoire. Romanza, his signature
album of contemporary Italian songs, has sold 2 million copies in
America since it bowed a year ago. ``Which is a pretty outstanding
achievement for an artist who doesn't sing in the English
language,'' says Kevin Gore, a senior vice president at PolyGram,
Bocelli's label.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more. Since it first aired in December 1997, A Night
in Tuscany has become a PBS blockbuster, a program like those Three
Tenors, John Tesh and Yanni specials that become a cultural
phenomenon. It is duly trotted out each pledge drive _ and the
switchboard automatically lights up. ``In the PBS business, we say
it's a program that has legs,'' explains Jay Lynch, director of
creative services at local PBS affiliate WXEL-Channel 42. ``Every
time we've aired it, it has broken our (pledge) goal.''
</P>
<P>
   No question about it: There's something about Andrea. But what
exactly? By the tenor's admission, his voice is still a work in
progress. ``I think I can do better in every aspect,'' he told The
Washington Post in April as he prepared for his American debut at
the Kennedy Center. ``I am very far from where I want to go. I need
much to study.''
</P>
<P>
   And although he has studied _ with opera great Franco Corelli,
no less _ it's hard to dismiss his point. Bocelli's singing is far
from note perfect: There's a decisive thinness in his upper
register, a tendency to ignore rhythms, a lack of bite when the
words demand it. ``The voice isn't a complete instrument in the
same way of a Pavarotti or a Domingo, and he chooses to sing a lot
of the same repertoire,'' says Malcolm Arnold, a South
Florida-based opera singer and vocal coach. ``I have a problem with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Arnold admits there's another quality to Bocelli, a
quality reinforced by his technical imperfections _ and perhaps by
his blindness, the result of a soccer accident when Bocelli was 12.
``There is a honesty to him that seems to be lacking in typical
tenor gesturing, both vocally and physically,'' Arnold adds. ``What
he does is free from artifice.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold's point is reiterated by a careful viewing of A Night in
Tuscany, which was filmed in Pisa, a city not far from Bocelli's
pastoral birthplace of Lajatico. When the tenor sings, he rarely
moves. Rather, the music seems to inhabit him in a quiet, measured
way. The closest he comes to gesture is when his face breaks into a
warm smile: He is happy _ and so are you.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the reluctant hero is what he is,'' says Crystal Buie, a
Boynton Beach nurse who heads up an international Bocelli fan club.
``He doesn't screw up his face . . . He just stands there and
sings.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of what Buie calls ''the whole package'' is the repertoire.
Although Bocelli claims to be an opera singer first and foremost,
he freely embraces popular material. ``Because it's very important
to bring the public to the theater,'' he says in A Night in Tuscany
of his crossover philosophy. ``I think pop music and opera music
are two very different things, but it's difficult to say (which is)
inferior or superior.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Carreras, Domingo and Pavarotti, who in their quest
to achieve global stardom sing just about anything from Sinatra
soliloquies to Lloyd Webber would-be arias _ often quite
atrociously _ Bocelli cultivates a very specific kind of pop song:
the Italian power ballad. It's a music rarely heard in this country
_ the closest you'll come are the overblown anthems of Celine Dion
_ but it finely straddles the line between rock and opera. And it
suits Bocelli's voice like velvet.
</P>
<P>
   For proof, listen to Bocelli's recording of Con Te Partiro, the
hit tune he re-recorded as an Italian-English duet with Sarah
Brightman, Time to Say Goodbye. It's a stretch of unrestrained,
bittersweet melody _ broken by the occasional conversational
refrain _ that builds to enormous climax. If a pop star sang it, it
would sound beyond his or her reach. If an opera star sang it, it
would sound overblown. With Bocelli, it's just right.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing has also played a crucial role in Bocelli's rise. The
first airing of A Night in Tuscany, for example, was timed around
the gift-buying holiday season _ and just when the tenor's albums
were being delivered in bundles to American stores. Bocelli has
also made the usual media rounds, appearing everywhere from The
Rosie O'Donnell Show to the pages of People magazine (in its ``The
50 Most Beautiful People in the World'' issue).
</P>
<P>
   And there are times during the documentary portions of A Night
in Tuscany, when the tenor is shown strolling the beach with his
wife, Enrica, and the elder of his two sons, 3-year-old Amos, or
walking through his parents' vineyard, that Bocelli becomes little
more than an advertisement for the Italian tourist authority. A
viewer is led to believe that one man's voice embraces an entire
Mediterranean lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   But all is forgiven because of the power of that voice _ and the
sincerity behind it. Bocelli is indeed a simple man, a product of a
rural background _ his parents sold farm equipment and bottled
their own wine. He studied music as a child _ piano, flute and
saxophone _ but his real interest was in singing. He went to law
school and practiced for a year as a backup career, but he soon
found he preferred working his way through the Italian piano-bar
circuit, where, despite his classical pedigree, he started as a pop
interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Bocelli's big break came in 1992 when the Italian rock star
Zucchero auditioned him for a pop-opera collaboration. The part
eventually went to Pavarotti, but Zucchero took notice and invited
Bocelli on tour. Pavarotti also praised him _ and reportedly told
Zucchero, ``You don't need me.''
</P>
<P>
   Television appearances further established Bocelli's reputation
in Italy. And with the release of the single Con Te Partiro, an
international star was born. It wasn't long before Bocelli was
singing for Pope John Paul II _ in a special concert that paired
him with Bob Dylan, of all people.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bocelli is contemplating any number of offers, from more
recordings to worldwide touring to operatic roles. So far, he's
done only a handful of productions, including the career-defining
role of Rodolfo in a production of Puccini's La Boheme that was
televised in Italy. ``Overall Bocelli acts the part better than
many a sighted tenor,'' observed Richard Dyer in The Boston Globe.
``And although he is still figuring out how to pace himself through
a full performance, he sings it better than anyone since the young
Jose Carreras 25 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his visual impairment, it's a subject that Bocelli rarely
discusses. A young victim of glaucoma, he was already losing his
sight before the soccer accident. But even after going permanently
blind, he never let it stand in his way. To this day, he rides
horses and skis. And, of course, he sings wherever there's an
audience waiting to hear him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what colors look like, and I have an idea of the
world,'' he said in a 1997 interview. ``I believe we all have a
destiny that we can perceive. Mine was singing.''
</P>
<P>
   And in making those colors come to life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
