<HEADER>
A1628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-REGULARS13-COX     10-12 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-REGULARS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Just regular folks
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Even if you didn't know anything about
Frank Amanti, you would be able to tell he was a regular customer
at the Smoke Inn cigar store in Tequesta, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's the black lacquered sign that dangles above his
personal easy chair in the store's tiny lobby. In gold letters it
reads: ``Casa Don Cheech Club.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don Cheech, that's me,'' Amanti says, puffing out a stream of
smoke after a healthy draw of his cigar.
</P>
<P>
   What does a guy have to do to get his own sign in a place like
this?
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta be a steady customer, that's all,'' the retired
Chicago fire chief says, noting he's been just that since the store
opened two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Amanti and about two dozen other regulars _ though only Don
Cheech gets a plaque _ gather every Saturday around noon to sit and
smoke and talk and laugh and argue and smoke some more and devour a
plate of sausage and peppers with a little cup of espresso mixed
with Sambuca. (They bring in their own food.) Owners Jerry Somma
and Abe Debabneh turn on the TV so the guys can watch the
hyperkinetic Emeril Lagasse whip up a dish on the Food Network.
(Fans of the show, they dub themselves The Emeril Club).
</P>
<P>
   But when new customers walk in, Debabneh walks toward them,
shakes their hands and says, ``Come on in! Come on in!'' to break
the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always greet them and invite them in. We treat everyone
like they're a regular.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like Don Cheech. The reason he keeps coming back? ``It's
the friendliest place I know,'' he says. ``You can come here and
just relax. You can't get therapy like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a ``regular'' _ whether it's at the corner bar, a beauty
parlor, whatever _ takes more than just consistent patronage.
</P>
<P>
   Being a regular means being passionate about the business you
frequent, even if it's only for that favorite item on the menu or
the friendly way one of the workers greets you. To be a regular,
you have to love the place. You have to get to know the nooks and
crannies of the personalities of the people who work there.
</P>
<P>
   There's a difference between being a creature of habit and being
a regular. And you have to surrender a little bit of yourself, too.
How else are they going to find out you like your tuna on rye, not
wheat, without pickles and with a slice of slightly melted cheese?
If you don't brag about the grandkids while they polish your nails
or moan about the Marlins over a cold one, how will anyone know
what to talk about the next time you visit?
</P>
<P>
   The model for the homespun business would, of course, be Cheers,
the TV bar where everybody knows your name. On that show, everyone
sat on their same bar stools, drank the same drinks, behaved just
how you expected them to behave. Even watching Cheers became a
habit. For 11 years, you knew what to expect, knew the rhythm of
the punchlines, the quirks of the characters, the tidy half-hour
resolution. Just watching made you a regular.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it goes in the real world, too.
</P>
<P>
   HOMESPUN ATMOSPHERE BRINGS 'EM TO THE OWL
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is another Cheers,'' says John Loennecker as he
waits for his slice of carrot cake at The Green Owl in Delray
Beach, Fla. ``They all know us and we know all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   By ``us'' he means himself and his wife, Janet. The couple eats
at The Owl, as it's known by locals, at least four times a week.
Sometimes they eat there twice a day. They've been coming to the
Owl since they retired and moved to Delray from Nanuet, N.Y., about
10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the turkey burgers and the BLTs,'' he says as he waves
to a couple of other regular customers who are taking their seats
at an adjacent table.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make a good sandwich,'' Janet says. ``Not everyone makes
a good sandwich.''
</P>
<P>
   The homespun atmosphere hooked the Loenneckers, too. Wedged into
a quaint corner slot of East Atlantic Avenue, The Owl is decorated
in mid-'70s kitsch. Planks of paneling on the walls are adorned
with owl knick-knacks. A layer of thin, unpadded green carpeting
surrounds a horseshoe shaped green Formica counter in the middle of
the eatery that puts customers elbow-to-elbow. And, truth be told,
there is dreadfully ugly owl-themed wallpaper. The joint has the
ambiance of a bachelor uncle's basement apartment that desperately
needs an update.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants me to take down the wallpaper, but I like it''
says Dave Gensman, who co-owns The Owl with his brother John and
family friend Bill Cline. ``I think the paneling makes it homey.''
</P>
<P>
   The Owl draws a heavy mix of downtown regulars (city and county
officials are often seen hobnobbing at the counter) and seasonal
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   `THROUGH KIDS, WEDDINGS AND SICKNESSES TOGETHER'
</P>
<P>
   Paula Gibb knows a good hairdresser when she sees one. She's
been seeing the same one since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Every Thursday, like clockwork, Gibb drops by Shirley
Stillwell's shop, the Powder Puff Beauty Salon in Port Salerno,
south of Stuart, Fla., for a shampoo and set. And once every three
months, she gets a new perm, just like today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy Shirley's personality and I like what she does to my
hair,'' Gibb says.
</P>
<P>
   Time has made them friends. Stillwell's son, Tom, helped Gibb
become the first woman inducted into the Port Salerno Kiwanis Club
about 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through the years, you go through kids and weddings and
sicknesses together,'' says Gibb, who lives with her husband, Dave,
not far from the shop in the Miles Grant subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gibb, most of Stillwell's customers are older and repeat
visitors _ as many as 98 percent of them are familiar faces, and
many have been coming to the shop since it opened in 1973.
Stillwell, who has been styling hair for 44 years, likes it that
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think older customers are more loyal than younger
clientele,'' she says. ``Young, working people don't have as much
time for appointments.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the customers, Stillwell has longtime employees that
add to the shop's stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``One girl's been with me 21 years . . . another's been here 16
years,'' she says. ``I think customers like it when they can come
in and not see a new face every time.''
</P>
<P>
   SON IS NOW WALKING IN FATHER'S FOOTSTEPS
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthony, now, now . . . '' Bob Murray says in a gentle tone to
the toddler who has just tipped a chair over in the showroom of
Dixie Shoe Repair, at the corner of Okeechobee Boulevard and South
Dixie Highway in West Palm Beach, Fla. ``C'mon back and pick this
back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray stands with a bemused look on his 69-year-old face, his
hands clenched and perched on the waistband of his polyester
slacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like his father, he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Three decades ago, Murray used to walk Anthony's father, Stephen
Bonanno, around the store when it was over on Clematis Street.
Murray, who worked downtown, was a customer of Stephen's father,
Bennie Bonanno, back then. The shop has been family owned and
operated since 1963. Murray's been there almost from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen's 34 now and runs the repair shop with his wife, Monica.
His mom, Eva, makes custom sandals and other leather goods in the
showroom. Stephen and Monica's kids, the aforementioned Anthony and
8-year-old daughter Bailey, treat the shop like a home away from
home. So do their mutts, Butch and Cuddles.
</P>
<P>
   The family atmosphere and good service have kept Murray and
other steady customers coming back. Suzette Green of West Palm
Beach has been a Dixie Shoe Repair patron since the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is part of West Palm Beach, along with the orchids
and hibiscus and everything tropical,'' she says. ``It's original
and different and unique and I like that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
