<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIOLIN-MAKER13-COX     10-12 1514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLIN-MAKER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gerado's violin
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Some see South Florida as the final stop
on life's long road, the dark end of an alley where people pile up
like dry leaves and old newspapers. But this story could only
happen right here, where all sorts of people come from all sorts of
places, not to die, but to live.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Florida stories, it began in another time, another
place.
</P>
<P>
   Gerado Passavanti left a job undone, a dream unrealized when he
died of pleurisy in 1930, aged 52, in the Bronx. If he had died in
his native Italy, there would most likely be no story to tell. But
he died in America, where fate and immigrants and dreams take a
common highway. Sometimes they all meet on that road and travel
together for a while before going their separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   Passavanti was trained in fine arts and engineering at the
University of Naples and came to New York from Italy early in the
century with all the talents his new nation could ask for and all
the dreams a young man could conjure. He helped design a new
torpedo for the U.S. government during the Great War. He loved
opera and art; he was a fine pianist and wood carver.
</P>
<P>
   But his last name ended in a vowel. This bode ill for his
advancement during the Big Red Scare of the 1920s, when America was
petrified of the illusionary socialist fervency of the swarthy
immigrant classes.
</P>
<P>
   So Passavanti found work as a projectionist in a Bronx silent
movie theater and put his dreams on ice. The man who loved music
spent his days in silence. Maybe his son Lucius would realize the
father's hopes. Lucius showed the same talents _ music, art, the
ability to craft beauty from raw materials. He attended Beaux Arts
in New York, as well as the Industrial School of Art, and learned
to run the movie projector during his father's lunch breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Then his father died. Lucius was 17.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Passavanti had been crafting a violin for a friend
named Guaneri. Guaneri had a son named Johnny, who could play piano
and cello and violin brilliantly. You may have heard of the Johnny
Guaneri Quartet, still playing after 50 years, though Johnny died
some years ago. But neither Johnny nor his father ever got the
violin Gerado Passavanti was making.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody did.
</P>
<P>
   When Passavanti died, the pieces of his partially completed
violin went into a box for 68 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lucius, now 85, spent those decades designing fashion jewelry
for big New York merchants like Tiffany's and Coro Vendome. He
played piano, took classical guitar lessons, became a portrait
painter. He was never far from fine art.
</P>
<P>
   The violin in its box was never far from Lucius. He asked New
York violin makers to complete the job, but they said no, don't
have time. When he retired in 1986, he and his wife Rose moved to
Vero Beach, Fla. The violin went under his bed.
</P>
<P>
   Then a few months ago, Lucius was looking at jewelry in a Vero
pawn shop. As usual, he asked yet again about someone to finish his
father's violin. He was given a name, but as usual, things didn't
work out. The man was moving, couldn't help Lucius. But he told
Lucius of a 79-year-old, 10th-generation cabinet maker and crafter
of fine stringed instruments named Zoltan Toth.
</P>
<P>
   Toth lives in Port St. Lucie. Passavanti called him. Toth said
he'd take a look at the box of wood.
</P>
<P>
   You might guess how this ends, only it's not that simple.
</P>
<P>
   Toth's father also came to America early in the century, from
Hungary, in 1906. He was the ninth generation of Toths to make
furniture. When his son Zoltan showed much musical talent, his
father sent him back to Budapest to study cello at the Royal
Academy of Music.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Nazis came and next the Stalinists, and Zoltan
returned to the U.S. to play cello in large symphony orchestras
throughout the midwest. That career lasted until one day in his
late 20s when, helping his father in his wood shop, he cut off the
tip of the ring finger on his left hand. End of cello career.
</P>
<P>
   Zoltan became an architect. He built 12 houses for his wife,
Irma, in the coming years. They moved from one creation to the
next. He built all the furniture in all the houses _ tall case
clocks with 17th century English works, TV cabinets, beds, tables,
book shelves to house the art books, a music stand _ all crafted
from glowing fruit woods and dark woods, hand rubbed and oiled. He
took up photography. National Geographic magazine bought his
photos. He and Irma collected 19th century European oil paintings.
His life was rich in art.
</P>
<P>
   But he dearly missed his cello.
</P>
<P>
   Then he designed a medical building for a Cleveland plastic
surgeon. A three-piece band played at the ribbon cutting ceremony.
Zoltan told the surgeon that he once played cello in groups like
that. He held up his left hand to explain why he no longer did. The
surgeon put him in a hospital that week and rebuilt his finger.
</P>
<P>
   Zoltan Toth was back in business. It was 1967. He played with
dance bands and orchestras for 20 years _ Kansas City, Cleveland,
Harry James, Vaughn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   He traveled, crafted, played music. Once, he slipped back into
Hungary carrying a beat-up junker of a cello. His passport said he
was a cellist, so the Communist border guards waved him and his
cello through customs. His old teacher in Budapest gave Toth his
heirloom cello, told him to treasure it. Toth was again waved
through customs as he left the country, having switched the junker
and the heirloom.
</P>
<P>
   He built cellos and violins in his garage workshop. When he
moved to Port St. Lucie a decade ago he moved the workshop, too. He
didn't come here to retire. He came to make music.
</P>
<P>
   So he looked at Passavanti's box of violin pieces and said, OK,
let's put it together.
</P>
<P>
   It took a month. He knew the wood was almost 100 years old. He
usually uses 40- or 50-year-old wood in his instruments. The fibers
in old wood have broken down, are ready to express subtle nuances
of tone and resonance. A violin top moves like your diaphragm _ it
expands and contracts. A guitar top is braced differently. It
vibrates more. A violin top has to breathe. A combination of old
wood, the right finish, the right bracing are the secrets to
beautiful violin sound.
</P>
<P>
   The wood looked very good. He polished the spruce top. The grain
looked good, narrow and true. He fit the maple sides and back,
glued, buffed, finished, clamped, glued and braced. It was
difficult because violins are built around frames, or forms. He had
the pieces but he didn't have a form. He had to build a new form to
fit the pieces. He used the fine tools a surgeon would employ to
splice and cut and fit the sides to the back.
</P>
<P>
   The ebony finger board went on, the tuning pegs. Strings.
</P>
<P>
   He has made more than 100 instruments. They are all beautiful to
Zoltan Toth. His cellos sell for more than $10,000. This one looked
as good as the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Then he played it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extraordinary,'' says Toth. ``It usually takes a year
of hard playing to begin to break in a violin. The tone was here,
rich. It was responsive. The high registers are so clear. It's
stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   He has played violins made by Antonio Stradivari. He has played
violins made by the great Guadagnini family. Many old violins are
priced out of sight because of their rarity, not their tonality, he
says. This violin is superb, in looks and tone.
</P>
<P>
   Toth asked a local violinist, John Enyart, to play the
instrument. Enyart owns a Guadagnini, more than 100 years old and
worth well into six figures. He bought it 40 years ago. His father,
a missionary in South America, procured him his first violin by
trading a mule for the instrument. Enyart has a doctorate in music
from the Conservatory of Cincinnati. He teaches music at Indian
River Community College and plays in local orchestras.
</P>
<P>
   ``This instrument is beyond description,'' he says, ``although I
think stunning is a fit description.''
</P>
<P>
   Toth and Enyart and Passavanti are all assembled among the forms
and bracing and lathes of Toth's workshop. The air virtually moves
as Enyart plays his fingers up and down the neck of the violin. The
deep tones are viola rich, the high notes crystalline in their
clarity.
</P>
<P>
   Toth is dressed in a red-checkered shirt. He is almost 79, but
his legs are those of a young tennis player. His eyes flash bright.
</P>
<P>
   Passavanti is 85, looks decades younger.
</P>
<P>
   They are talking about Harry James, 19th century European
masters, how to spot a fake emerald, how to listen to Bartok. They
speak softly of Italy and Hungary and the Bronx and their children
who grew to be architects and microbiologists.
</P>
<P>
   What a small world it is, they say, their meeting after all
these decades so that Gerado Passavanti's unfinished violin could
come to completion.
</P>
<P>
   There is music in the voices of the old men.
</P>
<P>
   Enyart is off to the side, eyes closed, swaying gently as he
bows the instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Gerado Passavanti is listening.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
