<HEADER>
A1633 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZYDECO13-COX     10-12 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZYDECO13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New sounds of zydeco keep dancefloors hopping
 &HT;    By Don McLeese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Long renowned and crowned as the ``king of
zydeco,'' the late Clifton Chenier might have trouble recognizing
much of the musical legacy that has flourished in his wake. Yes,
the sound is still based on the interplay of -- sprightly accordion
and the metallic scrape of a rubboard. Yes, the music still fills
the country roadhouses and radio airwaves throughout the Creole
communities of Southwest Louisiana (spilling over the border into
pockets of East Texas), making a visitor feel like he has entered
another dimension: Planet Zydeco.
</P>
<P>
   But who is this Beau Jocque character, boasting and toasting
like a rapper, exhorting his fans to ``Check it out, lock it in,
crank it up''? And what about Keith Frank, whose ``What's His
Name'' was inspired by Snoop Dogg and whose transformation of the
theme from an old TV show _ ``Movin' on Up'' from ``The
Jeffersons'' _ has become a signature anthem for both the man and
the music? Then there's Little Brian Terry over in Houston, with
all his hip-hop jive about ``H-town.'' And Chris Ardoin may have a
familiar name _ he's a descendent of Amede Ardoin, Chenier's
predecessor as Creole accordion king _ but his style owes more to
the smooth seduction of Boyz II Men.
</P>
<P>
   And, while we're at it, who turned up the bass so loud that the
floors are throbbing, the walls are shaking and the fillings in
everyone's teeth are rattling?
</P>
<P>
   If he were alive, Chenier might look at the bandstand, and not
understand what's going on. But then he'd turn his eyes to the
packed dance floors and the lines out the door at El Sid O's,
Richard's or any of the other mainstay clubs in the area
surrounding Lafayette, La., and a big smile would cross his face.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the question remains: How much outside influence can
zydeco assimilate and still be zydeco?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a longstanding debate in the zydeco community,'' said
Michael Tisserand, author of the newly published book ``The Kingdom
of Zydeco'' (Arcade, $29.95), an exhaustively researched,
intelligently analyzed and lovingly written guide to this most
vital of regional musics. ``Just yesterday, I was talking to a
couple of musicians who said, flat out, 'That's not zydeco they're
playing' (referring to the younger, rap-oriented generation of
accordionists). Or the debate will be over the single-row (button)
accordion versus the piano-row accordion, and someone will say one
or the other isn't zydeco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people put all the weight on the song, saying this is a
real zydeco song and this isn't, but I put a lot of weight on the
context the music is being made in. Even in the most extreme
examples, like Keith Frank singing the theme song to 'The
Jeffersons,' there are elements that are very zydeco-related. First
of all, it's performed at home, playing to a crowd of black Creoles
at a dancehall. The band is based completely around the accordion
and the rubboard. And it's a dance song.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the terms Cajun and Creole are often used and confused
interchangeably, Tisserand provides a valuable lesson in how
distinct but interrelated the two cultures are. ``When people in
Southwest Louisiana describe themselves as 'black Creole,' they
usually mean that they prefer a way of life that expresses itself
in traditional food, the French language and zydeco,'' he writes.
By contrast, Cajun is Caucasian culture, referring to the refugees
from French-speaking Acadia (what is now Nova Scotia), who settled
in Louisiana. Originating as an ethnic slur, ``Cajun'' occasionally
carries backwoodsy, rednecky connotations.
</P>
<P>
   While the division is as stark as black and white, the
interminglings are such that, as Tisserand writes, ``Arguably the
single most important cultural and musical influence on the Creoles
has been from their neighbors the Cajuns.''
</P>
<P>
   Young blacks increasingly have been buying into zydeco the
further it moves from the traditional French two-steps and waltzes
and the more that it incorporates the attitude and rhythms of
contemporary hip-hop. As Tisserand maintains, the watershed year
for zydeco was 1987, when the music filled the soundtrack of ``The
Big Easy'' and was incorporated by Paul Simon into his
``Graceland'' song cycle. It was also the year Clifton Chenier
died, after more than a decade of heroic performances while his
health was failing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scope of Chenier's influence may be the only thing that
nearly every zydeco musician can agree on,'' writes Tisserand,
though, these days, such inspiration lies more in Chenier's memory
than in his music. Most of zydeco's younger generation has been
more profoundly influenced by Boozoo Chavis, a Lake Charles peer of
Chenier who came out of musical retirement in the mid-'80s, and
whose return sparked an interest in a simpler, more rhythmic type
of zydeco, played on a button accordion, designed less for displays
of virtuosic sophistication than keeping the dance floor hopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``His comeback was so powerful that he was attracting people who
remembered him from 20 years ago, and then slowly the younger
people started infiltrating those dances,'' Tisserand said. ``Even
though he was a contemporary of Clifton, he had this raw vitality
to his music that turned peoples' ears around.''
</P>
<P>
   As different as the styles may be, the younger accordionists are
operating much in the same manner as Chenier's generation did,
drawing influence from the popular music of the day (in Clifton's
case, Ray Charles and Louis Jordan) and translating it into the
regional dialect of accordion and rubboard. As Brian Terry told
Tisserand, ``Cliff did country into zydeco and blues into zydeco.
Just because I got an accordion and a scrubboard doesn't mean I
can't play hip-hop and rap. You know, music changes every six
months, and you've got to change with the times. How can you draw a
line and say, 'This is going overboard with it'? How can you go
overboard with music?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think zydeco's pretty absorbent,'' said Tisserand, who wrote
the book in part to provide historical background for fans drawn to
``nouveau zydeco.'' ``I never heard anybody criticize Clifton the
way I do hear some in the Creole community criticizing Beau Jocque
or Keith Frank or some of the other younger musicians for
assimilating influences. I think maybe the dividing line is the
older generation's distrust of rap, feeling that it brings a
different kind of influence into the community, and that it is
tainted with urban life and drugs and guns and things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, it has also revitalized the music in such a manner that
it has lost all the anachronistic mustiness of a museum piece. With
a bitter rivalry for supremacy between Beau Jocque _ Chavis'
protege, then his musical sparring partner and one of the music's
most popular touring acts _ and the younger Keith Frank, who
dominates the Creole roadhouse circuit while remaining virtually
unknown beyond it, the question of succession within this musical
monarchy remains an open question of vital debate.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A kingdom of zydeco, then, is a delicate balance,'' writes
Tisserand. ``A monarchy is ultimately decided by dancers voting
with their feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Don McLeese writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
