u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWATCH13-COX     10-12 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salon back in the news with new business model
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the precarious world of online magazines, necessity is
clearly the mother of invention. Just as the smoke cleared from
Salon magazine's Washington fiasco, which culminated in the
resignation of D.C. bureau chief Jonathan Broder and a whole lot of
publicity, Salon was back in the news with a new business model.
For $25 a year, readers can now become members.
</P>
<P>
   The new revenue scheme resembles a PBS pledge drive. For $25,
you'll get discounts on Salon merchandise, including posters, tote
bags and note cards. You'll have access to the members' lounge chat
area, featuring exclusive discussions with Salon staffers and
special guests. You'll also get a Salon T-shirt, a free ticket to
attend the Salon Magazine Book Awards party in New York City and _
get this, you high-minded literary types _ an Octavo CD-ROM
reproduction of John Milton's famous defense of free speech,
``Areopagitica,'' published in 1644. If they mailed you a ``Three
Tenors'' video, you'd swear it was pledge week on your local PBS
station.
</P>
<P>
   Salon's new business model hasn't been tried before. Slate, the
Michael Kinsley-run, Microsoft-owned Web publication charges users
yearly subscription fees in return for access to the vast majority
of its content.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still harkens back to the sobering reality of online
content at this point,'' says Jupiter Communications Patrick Keane,
``and that is that most users will not pay for content.''
</P>
<P>
   Keane says most users still won't pay because the Internet is
flush with content, whether its national news organizations or
analytical essays of the type Salon publishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analysis and deep content won't ferment into a robust
subscription business, and (Salon) doesn't think so, either,''
Keane says. ``It will be a very small portion of their audience
that will pay to support them. The majority of their revenues will
continue to be advertising. They are admitting to the fact they
can't make it on advertising alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The efforts of Salon and other online publications that focus on
content are scrambling to avoid the fate of Wired, the mother of
online publications. Parent company Wired Digital was sold to the
Lycos Network.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos began as a search engine at http://www.lycos.com as did
Tripod (http://www.tripod.com), an online community targeting young
adults. Wired Digital includes Hot Wired magazine, Wired News,
Webmonkey (a Web site building tool) and the Hot Bot search engine.
</P>
<P>
   Old-timers will remember that not more than five years ago,
Wired.com was on the bleeding edge of Web publishing as one of the
first magazines to hit the Web. IAn influential and much copied
e-zine, Wired was widely regarded as the premier Web innovator.
</P>
<P>
   Wired seems like an ancient relic of the wild days of the
Internet, before ad banners, before Web addresses turned up on
buses and cereal boxes and before the Gap had its own Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Keane says Wired will continue to be a strong Web brand and have
a loyal following among the technology set. However, most Web
watchers see the company as damaged goods _ a Web innovator that
tried to do too much.
</P>
<P>
   Salon, on the other hand, is still a work in progress, still
attracting loyal readers, some of whom might be induced to buy a
poster or mail in membership dues to help Salon pay the bills.
Piles of banner ads and clever copy just aren't enough anymore.
Just ask HotWired.
</P>
<P>
   What's New
</P>
<P>
   Cats magazine: The official Web site for Cats magazine, these
pages offer a comprehensive sampling of features from the monthly
newsstand edition. Cat lovers can take advantage of such
``cattractions'' as Feline Features, Cat Chat, Cat Nips (news
briefs &AMP; book reviews) and Paw Prints (photos from users).
</P>
<P>
   http://www.catsmag.com/home.html
</P>
<P>
   _ Homeowner's Finance Center: Thinking of refinancing your home?
Start here. This helpful site is filled with straight-talking
articles on why and when to refinance, how to choose between a
fixed or adjustable-rate mortgage, etc. Users can request the
attention of a specialist to advise them on their specific
situation. You can even apply online.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.homeowners.com/homeowners/refitop.html
</P>
<P>
   _ The Trip.Com: This online mag offers everything for the
traveler: flight, hotel and car reservations, real-time flight
tracking, restaurant reviews, interactive maps and travel news.
Guides &AMP; Tools include a currency converter, destination guides,
state and city maps and a nationwide flight tracker.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.thetrip.com/
</P>
<P>
   _ The Spa: You need some pampering. Life has become an endless
cavalcade of stresses. You need to get some exercise, some good
eats ... some sleep! Check out the spa nearest you, or click around
the site and explore spa resorts across the U.S. and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.spafinders.com/
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
