<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magazine details hackers' chop shop
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Is there an electronic equivalent of the old auto chop
shop? The October issue of Yahoo! Internet Life magazine says yes.
It describes how some hackers crack the copy protection on popular
software and then distribute it for free. Such software is called
``warez'' in Internet slang and includes such programs as Microsoft
Office 97. It details how a hacker named Christopher Fazendin
managed to disable the 90-day trial feature on a full version of
Office. In essence, he enabled users to get a copy of the program,
which normally retails for $350, for $4.99.
</P>
<P>
   It's poised to be the next generation of CD-ROM, offering up to
17 gigabytes of storage or enough to hold an entire two-hour movie.
The technology is called DVD, which stands for either digital
versatile disc or digital video disc, depending on the source. You
can read all about it in the November issue of MacWorld. The
magazine discusses in detail the strengths and weaknesses of DVD
and how ready it is for commercial rollout. DVD is what geeks call
cross platform, meaning it works with either Macs or PCs. While for
sale, DVD has several problems. For one, there aren't a lot of
titles yet for it. Mac users face another problem in that there
aren't a lot of manufacturers producing DVD drives for this market.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Two more board games have come to the computer desktop. Hasbro
Interactive has released computer versions of ``Clue'' and ``The
Game of Life.'' While based on the original games, the computer
versions have several new twists. For one, the games are 3-D and
animated. There's also a soundtrack. In ``Life,'' players can now
travel through time. Both games retail for $29.95 and are available
only for PCs with Windows 95 or 98.
</P>
<P>
   Computers are great tools for learning languages. And software
companies are increasingly releasing titles that teach everything
from Spanish to Japanese. The latest is Kids Spanish from Knowledge
Adventure. Designed for ages 6-10, Kids Spanish teaches the
language through games and exercises. Kids learn comprehension,
vocabulary and grammar.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   You can follow the baseball playoffs and World Series on the
Web. The leagues have set up an official site, which tracks news of
the games and other information. You'll find the site at
http://www.worldseries.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Now for something completely different _ and it's not a Monty
Python site. The Money Origami site teaches how to turn a bill into
an origami pair of glasses, bow tie or a ring. Yes, it's totally
useless, but some say it's quite fun. You'll find this site at
http://www.msd.si.net:80/(tilde)clay/money/.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
