<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-REPORT13-COX     10-12 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's a wired, wired, wired, wired world
 &HT;    By John Ghirardini
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In just a few years, the Internet has transformed the
wired world into a global village, and communicating with your
neighbors on the Net can be as easy as talking over the back fence
_ no matter how far away that fence is.
</P>
<P>
   With the right software and hardware, your computer turns into
an online videophone that lets you talk to someone long-distance _
just like calling Grandma from the telephone on the kitchen wall _
and see the person at the same time. If all you have is a sound
card and a microphone, you can have an audio chat that boasts
surprisingly good quality. Plunk down $100 for a USB or
parallel-port camera and you're ready for a face-to-face encounter.
</P>
<P>
   The best part is that the call costs nothing, and Net surfers
all over the globe are joining the free-for-all.
</P>
<P>
   At any given time, thousands of participants from more than 25
countries are logged in to the servers handling calls. That doesn't
even count ``lurkers'' _ those who are viewing the server directory
but aren't logged in.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Basque, 39, lives in Listuguj, a village on Canada's Gaspe
coast, near Quebec City. Basque has been computing only since
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fascinated by how you could contact the world so
easily,'' Basque said last week. ``I spoke to someone in France
just this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   The movement toward videoconferencing is a natural progression
from e-mail and from Internet Relay Chat, in which a conversation
is typed at the keyboard and both parties see it.
</P>
<P>
   But both e-mail and IRC rely on a growing lexicon of
``emoticons'' and acronyms to convey the meanings provided in
everyday speech by inflection, facial expressions and body
language. With videoconferencing you see the real thing, even if it
sometimes is as jerky as a Hong Kong-made martial arts movie and
the voice doesn't match the movement. Installing a video capture
card (about $60) makes outgoing video smoother, and has the added
benefit of having a plug for a standard camcorder as well as one
for an ``eyeball'' camera sitting atop a monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's tough to make a video connection, but the audio
is usually solid. Sending video data takes up a lot of bandwidth
and also is dependent on the speed of the connection and the amount
of traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Net congestion becomes a problem (in the future), video
will be the first to go. It's the voice that's important,'' said
Jeff Pulver, owner of Pulver.com, a New York-based Internet
communications consulting firm. Pulver also pointed out that like
it or not, the best video quality available on the Net comes from
commercial sex sites, which have a vested interest in presenting
smooth video.
</P>
<P>
   That profit motive keeps such sites at the cutting edge of video
technology, Pulver said, adding that the companies producing the
free software ``have very little incentive to put resources'' into
the products.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least 10
</P>
<P>
   videoconferencing programs available for free on the Net. Most
have application-sharing, whiteboard and standard typed-chat
functions built in. If you don't want to go the video route and
spring for a camera, you don't have to. Most of the programs log in
to a server, and the directory shows which parties are available or
have video sending capability. You can receive video no matter
what.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the most popular free programs are CU-SeeMe,
Microsoft's NetMeeting and VocalTec's Internet Phone 5.
</P>
<P>
   CU-SeeMe is the granddaddy of videoconferencing programs, having
been invented at Cornell University in the 1980s. The latest
version is available for Windows and Macs and will display up to 12
video windows at a time. CU-SeeMe connects to ``reflector'' sites
that list people available for chat.
</P>
<P>
   A commercial version of the program from White Pine Software has
additional features and sells for $99 retail or $69 over the
Internet. White Pine's Web address is http://www.wpine.com.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's NetMeeting will only show two video windows at a
time _ sending and receiving _ but works seamlessly with Windows
95. It's available for free download from http://
</P>
<P>
   microsoft.com, and often comes bundled with Windows 95 or 98.
You may already have it on your machine; look at Program Files for
a separate entry, or it may be under Internet Explorer. There is a
Mac version available at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Phone 5 also is available on the Web at http://
</P>
<P>
   www.vocaltec.com. With IPhone, you have to register the software
before the video portion will work, but the audio works well. Much
like NetMeeting, IPhone logs in to a directory server from which
individual connections are made. IPhone has both Windows and Mac
versions.
</P>
<P>
   If you have someone you call often _ a family member, for
example _ one of the best ways to connect is direct
computer-to-computer, using as a ``phone number'' the IP address
assigned when a computer logs on to an Internet service provider.
If you know the IP address of the person you're calling, click the
``call'' button on whichever videoconference software you're using
and type it in. The call will go straight to the other machine,
bypassing servers and minimizing potential slowdowns. To find the
IP address in Windows, run a built-in program called Winipcfg. On a
Mac, look at the TCP/IP entry under Control Panels.
</P>
<P>
   Videoconferencing may not be perfect, but it has helped bring
the original promise of the Net into sharper focus: The free
exchange of thoughts and ideas without regard to national
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bassel Mohsen, 23, lives in south Lebanon. Mohsen has only been
computing for six months, but one of his first acts was to fire up
NetMeeting. He's now in regular contact with electronic friends in
the United States, Australia and Jordan, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mohsen's aim in using videoconferencing was ``to talk to and
meet people from around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The village just keeps getting smaller.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO GET HOOKED UP
</P>
<P>
   Videoconferencing software can be downloaded free from the
Internet. Some commercial software titles are sold that include
camera and microphone, and most have both Windows and Macintosh
versions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hardware requirements include a sound card ($30-$100) and a
microphone ($6-$50).
</P>
<P>
   _ Optional hardware:
</P>
<P>
   USB or parallel-port color camera ($99-$169). A parallel camera
shares a port with your computer's printer. An A-B switch ($20) is
needed if both stay connected at all times.
</P>
<P>
   Video capture card ($60 and up).
</P>
<P>
   _ Kits are also available:
</P>
<P>
   Big Picture Video Phone (U.S. Robotics, $160, includes capture
card, color camera and software).
</P>
<P>
   Creative Video Blaster ($100, USB color camera, software).
</P>
<P>
   Intel Create &AMP; Share ($130, USB color camera, software).
</P>
<P>
   QuickCam VC ($169, USB or parallel-port color camera, software).
</P>
<P>
   Diamond Supra Video Kit ($175, includes capture card, color
camera and software).
</P>
<P>
   John Ghirardini writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
