<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computer detective snookered by software
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Further Adventures of Ace Warner, Software
Detective:
</P>
<P>
   6 p.m. Using trusty Opinel knife, slice away shrink-wrap on a
package titled TuneUp, a Quarterdeck program. The box proclaims it
to be``the sure-fire way to keep your PC up-to-date.'' Online
hardware and software updates, virus protection and more!
</P>
<P>
   6:05 p.m. Unstick shrink-wrap from hand, scrape off on
wastebasket. Open box. Turn box upside down. CD-ROM case falls out.
</P>
<P>
   6:08 p.m. Put CD-ROM in drive, accept all defaults, let program
install while digging manual out of disk case and perusing it.
Program amounts to a $30-a-year subscription; purchase is good for
a year, then you've got to resubscribe. The genre hasn't changed.
Program offers TuneUp AV, an anti-virus program with regular
updates.
</P>
<P>
   6:13 p.m. Installation complete. View ReadMe file, which reveals
TuneUp AV won't find boot-sector viruses on FAT32 disks. Oh well.
So much for TuneUp AV.
</P>
<P>
   6:19 p.m. TuneUp connects to its home base. As expected,
announces there is an update for it. For TuneUp, that is. Suggests
I download it. But of course.
</P>
<P>
   6:23: p.m. Download begins. Takes 10 minutes to get to 5
percent. A big one. Go to Start menu. Select Programs. Select
Accessories. Select Games. Select solitaire.
</P>
<P>
   6:28 p.m. Cards are running lousy. Download has reached 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   7:15 p.m. Drag solitaire window aside to check download
progress. There's a little panel there that says ``Could not
complete download. Try again later.'' What do you mean, could not
complete download? Did the little guy pumping the handle get tired?
Did somebody refuse to work overtime? I never saw a message like
that. ``Connection failed,'' OK, but the connection is fine.
``Download interrupted,'' maybe. But it doesn't say it was
interrupted; it just says it couldn't do it anymore, as in ``Oh,
God, I just can't go on.''
</P>
<P>
   7:30 p.m. TuneUp can find nothing in the way of updates for me
but a lot of minutiae from Microsoft, and a few things I can't
identify. Log off. Get Diet Coke, handful of cookies.
</P>
<P>
   7:40 p.m. Using the Opinel, ravage the shrink-wrap on a package
called Update AnyWare, from GreenTree. Another of the ilk. Another
subscription. This one uses your own browser. Install program.
</P>
<P>
   7:50 p.m. Using Netscape, connect to the Update AnyWare home
page. Get password. It says I need to update my Netscape plug-in. I
say OK.
</P>
<P>
   8:01 p.m. I arrive at a Netscape location. It tells me that I
will find below the name of the Netscape plug-in I need. Below is a
line saying ``The plug-in you need for your plug-in type does not
exist.''
</P>
<P>
   8:07 p.m. Back to AnyWare. This time agreeing to download a
plug-in simply brings up a download dialog box that indicates it's
not a plug-in I need, but a whole new program. I agree, and the
download lasts for only about 10 rounds of solitaire.
</P>
<P>
   8:28 p.m. Go off-line, install the update. Back online, back to
AnyWare. Unwittingly, I select ``Check Out,'' which checks me out.
Log back in. It tells me I need to update my Netscape plug-in. It
wants me to download the same file I downloaded half an hour ago.
Bye-bye.
</P>
<P>
   8:45 p.m. Toss two boxes into the trash. Put feet on desk. Talk
to guinea pigs. Wait to see if mysterious blonde knocks on door. Oh
well. Some days the magic works, some days it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution. E-mail:
jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
