<HEADER>
A1728 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREIG-COLUMN13-COX     10-12 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREIG-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ya-Ya sister seeks keepsakes of mingled tears
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My four sisters and I are very close despite our geographical
distance, and are big fans of Rebecca Wells' book ``Divine Secrets
of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood.'' would love to give each a gift featured
in the book, a lachrymatory. It is an old custom in which a small,
glass vial containing tears is worn on a chain. Where might I find
such a thing? _S. Elsea
</P>
<P>
   A: A vial containing mingled tears symbolizes the joy and sorrow
two people have shared. Bill Flenniken of Morrae Laboratory Glass
in Austin makes these vials (cork top, screw top, glass stopper or
completely sealed) to hang on a chain for $12 to $18 each.
Flenniken once sealed samples from 12 oil wells for a client's
family in keepsake vials.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have about a hundred Disney Beanies, most still in plastic
bags. I want to donate these to a group who will give them to
children. _ Jean Schaal
</P>
<P>
   A: Several nonprofit organizations would love this donation: For
example, here in Austin, Arc of the Capital Area, Austin Families,
SafePlace and Bastrop Family Crisis Center (phone: 512-321-7760.
Maybe others with bonus Beanies will follow your lead!
</P>
<P>
   Q: During my dad's recent hospital stay, my mom and I had
various discussions. The subject of the Mary Worth comic strip came
up (how, I do not know!). Mom maintains Mary Worth was originally
known as ``Apple Mary'' and sold apples during the Depression. She
further contends the movie ``Pocketful of Miracles'' (Bette Davis,
Glenn Ford) was based on the ``Apple Mary'' character. Your
mission, Jane, should you choose to accept it, is to verify my
mom's memory and prove to the doubters she knows what she is
talking about! _Diane B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your mother's memory has all the right components. Mary Worth
replaced the Apple Mary strip when its creator, Martha Orr,
retired. But the similarities end with the name. Mary Worth, a King
Features soap-opera comic strip, began in 1934 and centers on the
compassionate widow of Wall Street tycoon Jack Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pocketful of Miracles'' (a remake of the 1933 ``Lady for a
Day'') is the story of Apple Annie, a New York street vendor who is
turned into a Manhattan society matron to fool her daughter's
suitor. The Bette Davis character could have been based on Apple
Mary.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697;
e-mail jgreig(AT)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968. Jane Greig is
a staff writer for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
