<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: A space of his own
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When our oldest son left for college, there was
much debate about which younger sibling would inherit his room.
Little did I suspect it would be my husband who claimed it.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he's moved out of our bedroom lock, stock and blanket.
He hasn't. But he has planted his flag and staked his claim to our
son's former desk.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, this man has sought a personal work space in our
various households. For 20 years, he has never had it. It doesn't
seem that much to ask, and we did try. He had his dresser top, but
it was too small. He had a nightstand, but it already held a phone
and clock radio. He had the kitchen table, but it was too messy.
We're talking one grumpy Papa Bear.
</P>
<P>
   Year after year, he disconsolately shuffled his stack of papers
from one corner to another on his dresser top. His income tax files
were stuffed in the back of kitchen cabinets, crammed between the
blender and the popcorn popper. His favorite family pictures were
tucked into his sock drawer. He had no place for his stamps, his
return address labels or his envelopes. He was a quietly unhappy
man.
</P>
<P>
   By nature, he is extremely well-organized. When we first
married, he had a nook or cranny for everything. His album
collection was alphabetized within each genre and his dresser
drawers were a thing to behold. He said it had something to do with
being able to find a pair of brown socks in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Then the children came along, and his orderly world was turned
upside-down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want my own space,'' he'd say occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have your side of the bed,'' I'd reassure him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have things I need to file,'' he'd say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want one of the bathroom drawers?'' I'd offer
helpfully.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps I did not fully realize the degree of his angst. I've
never had a place of my own. The desk that holds our computer is
open territory to everyone in the household _ including the dogs,
who curl up under it.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, every available flat surface in our house serves
as ``my desk.'' I do have a filing system, though. School papers
are by the range top, church and volunteer work papers are by the
microwave, mail is on top of the television, and my column writing
is on top of the coffee maker (perhaps in hope something will start
perking).
</P>
<P>
   I don't agonize over this. I figure someday, when all the
children are gone, we'll reclaim our house and fit it to our needs.
I can wait. My husband could not.
</P>
<P>
   So, as the two younger siblings bickered about who would move
what where, my husband took me aside and announced his plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want this room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Without me?'' I whimpered.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, dear. I just want the desk.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, he got it. He took all one weekend to move his stuff. In
a happy flurry, he labeled file folders and organized pens,
pencils, stamps, rubber bands and pushpins. He set up a desk lamp,
plugged in his stereo and alphabetized his CD collection. He hung a
montage of photos, cards and messages on the wall in front of the
desk.
</P>
<P>
   For hours, he kept himself busy. I'd peek in and see him quietly
humming to himself as he bent to rearrange the contents of a
drawer. Who knew this would mean so much to him?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he proudly showed me his handiwork, opening drawers
with a flourish, pointing out the intricacies of his filing system,
the pristineness of the desktop itself. I was properly impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, he slips off to the back room and does his stuff,
whatever that is. But he does it happily _ in his own space.
</P>
<P>
   The two younger boys will just have to wait. Maybe when they're
40, they can have their own space, too.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas. She can be reached online at VMKabat(AT)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
