u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURNER-COLUMN13-COX     10-12 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hatred real national crisis facing America
 &HT;    By Bronwyn Turner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ All these special reports on television and talk
of national crisis take me back to my childhood days (never mind
how long ago that was.) When I was 10 years old, growing up in
Austin, we also were in the midst of a national cliffhanger in the
month of October.
</P>
<P>
   The watch words then were not ``high crimes and misdemeanors,''
but ``duck and cover.'' Missile sites under construction had been
discovered in Cuba and nuclear war was a real possibility.
</P>
<P>
   My parents sat down and prepared us and distilled water bottles
would be stored in the hall closet. When we heard the sirens, we
were to go into the bathroom and duck and cover our heads.
</P>
<P>
   At school, drills were held. Our building was located beside an
old rock quarry, with high limestone cliffs forming a giant
backstop to the baseball field. We carried our chairs over our
heads and walked out to those cliffs, the only shelter close enough
to shield us from the effects of a nuclear blast.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, neither the bathroom nor the cliffs would have
been adequate shelter. But perhaps the drills themselves were the
important thing and to keep us watching, waiting and ready.
</P>
<P>
   Today's national crisis seems small in comparison. But maybe we
need to have drills for this crisis also. How we react to all this
brouhaha may be just as important as the final outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The drill I would suggest is this: watch, wait and be ready for
hatred, for murmuring. May I suggest that hatred is woven all
throughout this matter and rationalized in a most righteous manner.
There is just a surprising amount of venom being vented these days
and ``I hope he dies a painful death from prostate cancer,'' a
caller said in a phone call to a congressman. Lest you think those
kind of calls just come from ``northerners'' in Washington, you
should listen to the ``Sound Off'' column entries that must daily
be edited out of the Lufkin Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   There is also veiled hatred and sarcastic digs at the personal
lives of the people involved in this scandal. There are many bad,
bad jokes.
</P>
<P>
   To be honest, this is a complicated issue for Christians, with
matters of forgiveness discussed in the same breath as impeachment
and moral duty. In the face of such complexity, I bow to the wisdom
of someone with experience in such matters and Chuck Colson,
special counsel under President Nixon, became a Christian in the
midst of Watergate. He has special insight on politics and
forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we forgive?'' Colson writes in a column in the Wall Street
Journal. ``And is it right for Christians to urge impeachment?
Isn't that a political question?''
</P>
<P>
   Colson, who asked for forgiveness himself, pleaded guilty to
breaking the law. He served time in prison. He is now chairman of
Prison Fellowship Ministries, and is frequently contacted by the
media these days for
</P>
<P>
   comparisons to Watergate. He also has comments about
forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take the president at his word in his statement of
repentance at his prayer meeting,'' Colson wrote. ``God forgives,
and so should we. All of us fall short of the glory of God; all of
us need to repent; none of us can be
</P>
<P>
   self-righteous.''
</P>
<P>
   But Colson also stresses that ``Christians have no business
avoiding their political responsibility.... One of the unique
contributions of Christian thought to the founding of our
government was the rule of law and that and the idea that no man
can be above it. So it is not un-Christian to insist that justice
be done, that the president be held accountable for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``.... I hope and pray that Mr. Clinton is genuinely repentant,
that he will be restored to his family and that Americans will
forgive him. But that doesn't mean he's entitled to avoid the
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   I would not differ from this stance, but would add this warning:
We are not entitled to hate. And there is a great temptation to do
that in this situation, and to rationalize it.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this picture (borrowed from a National Broadcasting
Radio program): There is this dog and there are two very important
things to note about it. The first we know, the second we don't.
</P>
<P>
   First, this dog bites. Second, we do not know when.
</P>
<P>
   Hatred is a dog unleashed too often these days. Emotions are
running high; people are criticizing, judging, jabbing at others
and in that atmosphere, this dog is going to bite.
</P>
<P>
   It's just my two bits, but in my opinion, in this crisis, the
drill needs to be to pen that dog up and concentrate on issues and
not personal attack.
</P>
<P>
   To rationalize hatred while campaigning for truth and justice
may be a high crime in itself. We need to be above that.
</P>
<P>
   Bronwyn Turner writes for the Lufkin Daily News, Lufkin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
