<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDY-TUNES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE FINDS MOZART FINE-TUNES STUDY HABITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHELE MORGAN BOLTON  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ In the film ``Amadeus,'' composer Wolfgang Amadeus
Mozart's patrons complained that his music had ``too many notes.''
</P>
<P>
   Simplify, they said. Take out a few.
</P>
<P>
   But to some students and faculty at the Hudson Valley Community
College, the musical genius has just the right number of notes.
</P>
<P>
   They believe in the Mozart Effect, a recent phenomenon that says
people learn better while listening to the music of Mozart and
others from the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The school has established a Mozart Effect Study Area in a
peaceful room in the campus library, where the soothing strains of
compositions written from approximately 1700 to 1825 play quietly
in the background.
</P>
<P>
   A test run for a few weeks last spring revealed a profound
effect on many students' work performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experiment was actually during final exams,'' said Susan
Blandy, an architecture professor and faculty librarian. ``And the
response was amazing. We had students come back and say they had
never done so well. Now we figure, why wait for final exams?''
</P>
<P>
   Blandy also is president of Troy's Friends of Chamber Music. She
actually experienced the Mozart Effect while studying philosophy in
college. She just didn't realize it while struggling to digest 150
pages of Plato a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't getting through the first paragraph,'' Blandy said.
``But then a friend suggested I listen to Bach and Mozart.''
</P>
<P>
   The college's Mozart study area has room for about 25 people.
</P>
<P>
   Students may play tapes supplied by the school or bring their
own. It makes no difference what piece is playing, Blandy said. Nor
does it matter if the music is written in the major or minor scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the style that's key,'' she said, and its rhythmic,
logical syncopation.
</P>
<P>
   The Mozart Effect is based on a study by Don Campbell, who
published a book by the same name. Classical musicians including
flutist James Galway, violinist Pinchas Zukerman and clarinetist
Richard Stoltzman swear by the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The human brain has two sides. The music elicits additional
activity that works to calm the ``chatterbox'' side and work with
the ``listener,'' Blandy said.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that cows give milk easier if classical music is
playing; some maintain the music eases labor and delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really no surprise,'' Blandy said. ``Because this is
getting the other side of the brain to work.''
</P>
<P>
   But Blandy warned to steer clear of more rambunctious composers
like Strauss, Stravinsky and most especially John Philip Souza.
Instead, choose Bach, Hayden, Handel, Vivaldi, Pachelbell or even
early Beethoven _ anything before the Fifth Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that helps students study has got to be a positive,''
said John Buono, president of the community college in upstate New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Naylor, a freshman majoring in electrical construction
maintenance, said he seeks out the Mozart Effect Study Area because
it is quiet, relaxing and there isn't a lot of disturbing activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music is there, but it's just in the background,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Librarian Bob Matthews agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the first things I noticed was that everything was
calm, quiet and students were really working,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
