<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-TRAUMA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITH HELPS FLOOD-RAVAGED COMMUNITY REBUILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN GUTIERREZ-MIER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL RIO, Texas _ On the night of Aug. 23, surrounded by
blackness and rising floodwaters, Claudia Coronado clung to a tree,
unable to see her 6-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Separated during the torrential rain spawned by Tropical Storm
Charley, Coronado could hear her son reply when she yelled out his
name. The moment was a test of her faith in God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was the end of the world,'' Coronado said of the
flooding that killed nine people and destroyed 581 homes in the San
Felipe neighborhood in this border city of 35,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The storm dumped 18 inches of rain, turning a placid creek in
the poor neighborhood into a torrent.
</P>
<P>
   Coronado said the rain began seeping into her home shortly after
midnight. She then decided to move her car to higher ground and
left her mother and child behind.
</P>
<P>
   `I didn't get very far and decided to abandon it and get back
home,'' she said. ``The water was so strong, I had to follow fence
lines in order to fight the current.''
</P>
<P>
   As Coronado described it, she almost made it home but had to
scramble up a tree as floodwaters rose and the current grew
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother and son and other relatives were on the roof and we
kept yelling at each other,'' she said. ``I prayed a lot on that
tree and my faith is stronger because of the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Four hours passed before Coronado and her family were rescued
and reunited.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled that tumultuous night with a sense of calmness
while sitting in the office of Our Lady of Guadalupe Catholic
Church, where she was filling out paperwork for federal relief.
</P>
<P>
   Her story isn't unusual, said the Rev. Jose Caracoza, pastor of
the 92-year-old church in the heart of San Felipe neighborhood. The
majority of those left homeless by the raging floodwaters were
members of the parish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right after the floods, there were people who were angry _
even angry at God,'' Caracoza said. ``They asked, `Why me?' There
was a crisis in faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Anger is one of many emotions most victims of disasters
experience, said the Rev. Norm Hein, vice president of chaplaincy
at Lutheran Social Services of the South in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``When disaster strikes, reactions vary. You have people that
are angry at God, and those that praise God for sparing their lives
or loved ones,'' he said. ``It's making sense out of the sorrow
that the church and faithful can provide to make sense out of what
seems senseless.''
</P>
<P>
   Hein has worked 20 years with Lutheran Disaster Response
Services and assisted disaster victims nationwide. He spent 17 days
last month in Del Rio helping flood-ravaged families.
</P>
<P>
   Since the flood, Caracoza has reassured parishioners that God
was with them that night and encourages them in their faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message is for them to pick themselves up and continue
walking with the Lord,'' Caracoza said.
</P>
<P>
   Coronado has heeded her priest's advice, but she said her son,
Francisco, remains emotionally scarred.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has nightmares and asks why God let this happen,'' said
Coronado, whose home was demolished by the flood. ``I hold him and
tell him it was nature and that God helped us survive.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Alderete home, located two blocks from San Felipe Creek,
scattered nails and fresh sheetrock are evidence that many families
are on their way to recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The Alderetes said most of the progress on their home is due to
the kindness of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baptist men came out and worked on our house and that helps me
believe God is out there and things will get better,'' said John
Ray Alderete, 19.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ruben Chairez, pastor of Primera Iglesia Bautista in
San Felipe, helped coordinate a statewide appeal to Hispanic
Baptist Churches calling for volunteers to help rebuild
neighborhood homes.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, 92 volunteers from across Texas arrirved to
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it's important that we show all those affected by
the flood that God cares, regardless of their denomination,''
Chairez said. ``As brothers in Christ we have to give these people
hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
