<SLUG> BC-FLORES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS YEAR'S HALLOWEEN STYLES WON'T MASK THE TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VERONICA FLORES  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ With Halloween approaching, it's no surprise that
likenesses of Monica and Bill are hot tickets at costume shops.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers unfortunately couldn't get ahead of the political
ball. President Clinton's admission of an extramarital affair
didn't break early enough for them to mold rubber masks or
coordinate Halloween costumes.
</P>
<P>
   So customers are winging it, snatching up wigs, berets, cigars
and other props. For ``the dress,'' shops suggest the Gap, since
that's where Monica bought the now-infamous blue garment.
</P>
<P>
   Requests are high, too, for Linda Tripp and Kenneth Starr
ensembles. But costume-hunters also will have to put together their
own Halloween wardrobe. Suggestions include power suits, with a
stringy blond wig for Linda and a briefcase, stern face and Bible
for Starr.
</P>
<P>
   But the foursome aren't the only scary figures to make headlines
this year. Ghouls and gals are aplenty from which trick-or-treaters
can choose. Some to consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ Osama bin Laden, the alleged mastermind behind the bombings of
two American embassies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional Arab garb is a must. And the costumed
trick-or-treater also should utter the words, ``Who, me?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Charlton Heston, president of the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   His likeness is easy to mimic. Think of Moses with a gun. If the
rod and staff can't comfort trick-or-treaters, maybe an Uzi will.
</P>
<P>
   _ Al Sharpton, the omnipresent civil-rights opportunist.
</P>
<P>
   A jury ruled in July that Sharpton and two others had defamed a
New York prosecutor by accusing him of participating in the rape
Tawana Brawley. In the 1987 case, the teen-ager claimed she'd been
kidnapped and raped by white police officers. A grand jury found
Brawley had fabricated her story.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton still won't apologize, now insisting even more loudly
that he's the victim of political persecution. He's shed his
trademark sweat suits and ornate gold jewelry for a business suit
and bullhorns. So his likeness might be difficult to emulate. But
whatever you do, your costume won't be complete without a portable
grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patricia Ireland, president of the National Organization for
Women.
</P>
<P>
   Last month NOW declared Monica and Bill's tryst was ``damaging
to the work place'' but said it wasn't sexual harassment. Hence,
the ``Clinton exception'' Ireland costume. It requires only the
wearing of a placard that reads, ``We won't stand for this behavior
... unless Bill did it.''
</P>
<P>
   To boost NOW's flagging image as they make their claim, perhaps
the other side of the sign should read, ``We are NOT an arm of the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Me? I think I'll go as Miss Goody-Two-Shoes. Then, at least, I
won't have to wear a mask.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Veronica Flores is a columnist for the San Antonio
Express-News, P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
