<SLUG> BC-VIAGRA-MILITARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY GEARS UP TO DISPENSE VIAGRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Active-duty and retired military people soon will
have access to Viagra, the little blue pill that's helped thousands
of men overcome impotence.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at both local military hospitals say guidelines first
must be implemented before Viagra can be offered to patients at
Brooke Army Medical Center and Wilford Hall Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be Monday or Tuesday or Wednesday,'' BAMC
spokesman Craig Martin said. ``It could be a couple of weeks; it
could be a month. We do not know. I don't want people reading your
story and lining up Tuesday morning thinking we have it.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 3.5 million men nationwide have obtained prescriptions
since the release of Viagra in April. But the revolutionary drug
has been slow to make its way into military hospitals because it
only recently received funding in the federal budget, which took
effect Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The pill also can't be dispensed until it first is placed on an
approved pharmacy list, Fort Sam Houston spokesman Phil Reidinger
said. Military doctors have been prescribing Viagra over the past
several months to their patients, who then have purchased the drug
at civilian pharmacies, said Dr. Ed Sabanegh, a lieutenant colonel
and chief of urology at Wilford Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of providing Viagra to active-duty personnel,
reservists and veterans will be an estimated $50 million this
fiscal year, said Virginia Stephanakis, a spokeswoman for the Army
Surgeon General's Office. Stephanakis said she didn't know how many
of the 8 million active-duty personnel, reservists, retirees or
their family members in the Defense Department's medical system
have received prescriptions for Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   There are 573,000 active-duty soldiers, retirees and family
members in BAMC's nine-hospital, 14-state region, which stretches
from Texas to North Dakota and Louisiana to Arizona, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Guidelines for dispensing Viagra were issued Aug. 8 by Dr. Sue
Bailey, assistant secretary of defense for health affairs. Under
those rules, physicians may prescribe Viagra only after deciding
the drug is the best way to treat impotence, Stephanakis said.
Patients will receive just six pills each month.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, which has been sold illegally because of high demand,
won't be replaced if patients report their supply has been lost or
stolen. Military pharmacies and their networks won't stock Viagra
because of its cost _ $10 per pill. Instead, doctors will order it.
</P>
<P>
   For men who suffer from impotence, Viagra blocks an enzyme that
breaks down a naturally occurring substance that causes erections,
Sabanegh said. Side effects of the drug may include headaches,
flushing of the face, indigestion, nasal congestion and mild vision
impairment.
</P>
<P>
   Some patients being treated for high blood pressure can take the
drug. But those taking nitroglycerine or suffering from severe
heart disease should not take Viagra. The drug isn't guaranteed to
work. And although Viagra widely has been hailed for giving
impotent men a second sex life, at least 69 men known to have taken
the drug have died, U.S. Food and Drug Administration spokesman
Brad Stone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
