<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1892 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEWICK-MAN-SPI &LR;      10-12 2701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEWICK-MAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEWICK MAN: LEGAL STRATEGY OVERSHADOWS SCIENTIFIC QUEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kennewick Man is a scientific celebrity, a cause celebre.
</P>
<P>
   The 9,300-year-old skeleton has been dubbed ``the most
significant archaeological find of the decade.'' Prominent
scientists are suing the federal government seeking access to study
him, arguing his bones are ``of major significance for science and
American prehistory.''
</P>
<P>
   Native Americans claim the bones are those of an ancestor,
contending the ``Ancient One'' should be reburied and is not the
property of scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The federal lawsuit, which has pitted scientists against the
tribes, will resolve the question of who gets first dibs on the
bones. If Kennewick Man is determined to be Native American, the
tribes' claim may prevail. But the bones are so ancient that
determining ancestry is no simple matter.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the task is the persistent notion that Kennewick
Man's long and narrow skull, among other things, suggests that he
was not Native American. Some have even proposed he may be of
European extraction _ a Caucasian.
</P>
<P>
   If public controversy were a good measure of scientific
significance, Kennewick Man would be one of the more profound
chapters in the history of American archaeology and anthropology.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not a good measure.
</P>
<P>
   Kennewick Man is in the limelight because of what he represents
in court, not because of what his bones may contribute to science.
Experts not involved in the flap say the discovery is of modest
importance, at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just appears to support what scientists have been saying
for years,'' said Donald Grayson, an archaeologist at the
University of Washington and a highly regarded expert on
prehistoric America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this will change our view of Native American
ancestry,'' said David Meltzer, an archaeologist and professor of
anthropology at Southern Methodist University in Dallas. ``The fact
that Kennewick Man doesn't look to some like a Native American
(skeletal type) doesn't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The distant ancestors of modern Native Americans probably varied
a great deal more than we know, he said, so it would be wrong to
conclude skeletal differences imply a distinctly different lineage
or race.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennewick Man, whose bones were found two years ago after
they washed out of a bank along the Columbia River in southeastern
Washington, may prompt changes in law, if not science. The bones
have sparked a legal battle that has highlighted ambiguities in the
federal law that governs how ancient remains are handled.
</P>
<P>
   The law is the Native American Graves Protection and
Repatriation Act of 1990. It gives tribes a lot of say over Native
American skeletal remains.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy began in July 1996 when two young men watching a
hydroplane race on the Columbia River noticed a skull in the water.
They notified law enforcement, and the coroner was contacted.
</P>
<P>
   The coroner called a local private archaeologist and occasional
forensic anthropologist, James Chatters, to have a look. Chatters
said at first he thought the bones might be those of a 200-year-old
white settler, because of Caucasoid skeletal features.
</P>
<P>
   On the second day, a closer look at the pelvis using a CT scan
showed it contained a stone spear point _ a Native American style
known as a Cascade point that was used 4,500 to 9,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Chatters' critics say, local tribes should have
been notified. Chatters said he assumed such notification would be
handled by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, which had jurisdiction
over the site.
</P>
<P>
   But the corps heard about the discovery only after it was
reported by the media and someone from the Confederated Tribes of
the Umatilla Indian Reservation in Pendleton, Ore., called to
complain that they hadn't been informed, said Dutch Meier,
spokesman for the Army Corps in Walla Walla.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, a custody battle erupted between the Umatillas and
Chatters, eventually drawing in other tribes and scientists, and
culminating in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed in federal court in Portland on behalf of
eight scientists in the field of archaeology and paleoanthropology
against the Army Corps. The corps had taken custody of the bones
from Chatters and planned to honor the Umatillas' request to
repatriate the bones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to block the transfer,'' said Doug Owsley, a physical
anthropologist at the Smithsonian Institution and one of the eight
scientists suing to gain access to the bones. ``It was clear they
were going to take the skeleton and bury it at an unknown
location.''
</P>
<P>
   In their lawsuit, the scientists argue that the corps is
inappropriately denying them access to the bones and
misinterpreting the law. A key part of their claim is the argument
that the skeleton is of exceptional value to science.
</P>
<P>
   That legal strategem, along with Chatters' use of the misleading
word ``Caucasoid,'' helped set the stage for the weird saga of
Kennewick Man.
</P>
<P>
   Many accounts of Kennewick Man have suggested this is a
discovery so significant it could force scientists to rewrite their
theories about how humans first came to the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   For example, an article in The New Yorker magazine June 16,
1997, criticized the government for ``withholding Kennewick Man,
who might turn out to be the most significant archaeological find
of the decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Such accounts are based on the notion that he's significantly
different from Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very, very different,'' Chatters said of the ancient
skeleton. The Richland archaeologist has retreated from earlier
claims he and his colleagues made about the skeleton appearing
Caucasian, but he's not backing down from the claim that Kennewick
Man is unique.
</P>
<P>
   If the radiocarbon tests done on a finger bone are accurate and
represent the rest of the bones, Kennewick Man is indeed the oldest
and most complete prehistoric skeleton ever found in the Pacific
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   But just because the bones are rare doesn't make them
scientifically unique. There are a half-dozen or more such ancient
remains found in North America, and there's no credible evidence
yet to suggest the Kennewick Man discovery will not fit in with
those finds.
</P>
<P>
   What little we know about Kennewick Man, says the UW's Grayson,
indicates he was a descendant of one of those groups of prehistoric
Asians who migrated to this continent via today's Bering Strait at
least 13,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeological, genetic and linguistic studies support that
theory. What's debatable is if some people came earlier, how many
migrations took place and whether they traveled by coast-hugging
boats as well as by foot.
</P>
<P>
   A site that may revolutionize our understanding of how the
Americas were peopled is in Monte Verde, Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Leading archaeologists, including Grayson and Meltzer, have
studied the site and confirmed evidence indicating people lived
there at least 12,500 years ago _ 1,300 years before the heretofore
earliest-known human presence in America, found in Clovis, N.M.
There is also preliminary evidence in Chile hinting at human
habitation as early as 33,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really cool,'' Meltzer said. By itself, he said, this
doesn't alter the conventional Bering Strait theory about how the
Americas were peopled. But it does seem to push the time of entry
back dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Finding 9,300-year-old Kennewick Man, by comparison, doesn't
lead scientists to rethink current theories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting and useful, but perhaps not that
significant,'' Grayson said. What's really at stake in Kennewick
Man, he said, is the legal interpretation of the federal law
governing ancient remains.
</P>
<P>
   What may be at stake as well, he said, is the working
relationship between scientists and the tribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a real cooperative relationship,'' said Adeline
Fredin, director of history and archaeology for the Confederated
Tribes of the Colville Reservation. But the fight over Kennewick
Man has hurt that, Fredin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Archaeologists have been digging up our ancestors' remains for
years, and the bones get put in boxes that get left in the back
rooms of museums,'' said Jeff Van Pelt, cultural resources director
for the Umatillas. ``We're not anti-science. We just want a say in
what happens to our ancestors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act was
passed to address such concerns and has so far forced the
repatriation of tens of thousands of human remains back to tribes.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens to a skeleton so ancient it may not be
definitively linked to any modern Native American tribe? The
scientists say the law is vague on that point and needs to be
clarified.
</P>
<P>
   The Umatillas have claimed Kennewick Man as an ancestor because
the bones were found on territory they ceded to the federal
government in a treaty. The group of scientists challenged the
claim, contending only intensive study could establish what, if
any, link exists to modern Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It's a paradox. The Umatillas don't want their ancestor's bones
desecrated by intensive study. The scientists say they need the
studies to determine if it's really their ancestor.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate John Jelderks, the Portland judge handling the
lawsuit, has ordered non-invasive tests _ at least for the first
phase _ to be done by an independent scientist at the UW's Burke
Museum of Natural History aimed at determining if Kennewick Man was
Native American. The remains are to be transferred to Seattle later
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Based on his own assessment of the skull, Chatters boosted the
Caucasian notion earlier this year when he released a facial bust
of Kennewick Man that many said looked like a white European,
resembling the lead character on the television series ``Star Trek:
The Next Generation,'' Capt. Jean-Luc Picard.
</P>
<P>
   Because nearly all the evidence so far points to Asia as the
ancestral home of the first Americans, it certainly would be
significant if Kennewick Man turned out to be a wayward European.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't rule it out,'' contended the Smithsonian's Owsley,
one of the eight scientists suing to gain access to Kennewick Man.
Until further tests are done, he said, it would be premature to
dismiss that as a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the scientists, members of a California-based
pagan religion called the Asatru Folk Assembly have staked a claim
on Kennewick Man. They contend the remains are evidence that
ancient Vikings arrived in America first, before the Asian
ancestors of modern Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But another of the scientists suing for access to the bones, D.
Gentry Steele of Texas A&AMP;M University, believes Kennewick Man is
more likely to be Asian than Caucasian. What little is known about
the bones corresponds to what Steele and his colleagues in physical
anthropology have been reporting from studies of the other ancient
skeletal remains found throughout North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be another sample confirming the hypothesis we
established in 1992,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Steele's hypothesis, in a nutshell, is that some of the first
Americans emigrated from ancient southern Asia. The dominant theory
has been that the migrations came from prehistoric northern Asian
populations.
</P>
<P>
   That might seem a fine point, but it's a distinction that
probably helped cause the adversarial mess that now surrounds
Kennewick Man.
</P>
<P>
   The term physical anthropologists have used in the past to
describe a southern Asian skeletal type is ``Caucasoid.'' Northern
Asians are ``Mongoloid.''
</P>
<P>
   The southern Asians had a more European look to their skulls,
with a longer braincase and narrower face. The northern Asians had
a rounder face with a shorter braincase, much like the skulls of
many modern Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Kennewick Man's skull was different, more like the southern
Asian type than the modern Native American type, and so it was
initially described as a Caucasoid. But that doesn't mean white
man, Steele said, adding that he tries not to use such terms any
more because they are misleading.
</P>
<P>
   Even Owsley agreed, when pressed, that it is a bit far-fetched
to claim Kennewick Man is an ancient European. It's a notion that
persists not so much because of the evidence as because of the lack
of it, he acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never used the word `Caucasian,''' Chatters contended. He
said the media misinterpreted his use of the word ``Caucasoid,''
which led to the mistaken impression that he was claiming to have
found an ancient white man.
</P>
<P>
   Chatters may have been careful not to say ``Caucasian'' when he
said the skull appeared ``Caucasoid,'' but he also didn't emphasize
the distinction. And two of his colleagues on Kennewick Man didn't
think there was any distinction.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine MacMillan, an anthropologist at Central Washington
University, and Grover Krantz, an anthropologist at Washington
State University well-known for his work on studies of ``Bigfoot,''
or sasquatch, were both consulted by Chatters and asked to provide
their professional opinions on the bones.
</P>
<P>
   Both MacMillan and Krantz judged the remains to be Caucasian.
</P>
<P>
   Krantz went further, arguing that this meant a modern Native
American had no more of a claim ``to this skeleton than it would if
an early Chinese expedition had left one of its members here.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the tribes were concerned, the scientists were pushing
this extraordinary claim simply because it negated the law that
would have applied if the remains had been judged Native American.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked with Jim (Chatters) for years,'' said the
Colvilles' Fredin. ``He has always been very professional and
precise. We had a very cooperative relationship up until this. ...
He saw an opportunity for fame, and he just made a lot of
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of scientists and other tribal members agreed with
Fredin and said the dispute over Kennewick Man could have been
avoided if the tribes had been promptly notified and allowed to
participate in the study.
</P>
<P>
   Chatters doesn't think so. He said the Colvilles at first
enthusiastically endorsed all sorts of studies and tests of
Kennewick Man to identify his family tree. As recently as April,
the Colvilles said they favored DNA testing aimed at determining if
the remains are Native American.
</P>
<P>
   But once the Umatillas took umbrage, Chatters said, all the
tribes fell in line _ against him and any form of scientific
testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so easy to insult these guys,'' he said. ``Working with
them is like walking through a minefield.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it should be, said the Umatillas' Van Pelt.
</P>
<P>
   Few scientists, few non-Native Americans for that matter, appear
to understand what it's like to have had generations of ancestors
and buried artifacts dug up and carried off to museums in the name
of science, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just information and data to us,'' Van Pelt said.
``These are our ancestors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Umatillas believe that knowledge comes not only from
scientific study, but also from adherence to cultural and religious
traditions, he said. Van Pelt and other tribal members have been
working with young people to teach them respect for those
traditions, which includes respect for their ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists need to remember that science is not necessarily an
end unto itself, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We teach our young people to walk in balance with the land and
within our traditional ways,'' Van Pelt said. Perhaps scientists
need to learn more about striking such balances, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to have the remains go to the Burke, because we've
had a good relationship there,'' Van Pelt said. Some testing of
Kennewick Man is inevitable, he said, and can be accepted so long
as the rights of Native Americans are considered along with the
needs of science.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian's Owsley said he hopes there will be room for
collaboration after resolution of the Kennewick Man case.
</P>
<P>
   The law ``is well-intentioned legislation,'' Owsley said. But
the regulations are unclear when it comes to ancient remains, he
said, and such disputes will continue until the law is corrected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
