<HEADLINE>
INFERTILITY RESEARCHERS FOCUS ON AGING EGGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For all the advances in fertility treatments,
one grim fact remains: Women's eggs begin a sharp decline in
viability after age 35, and by age 45 few can conceive their own
biological children.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians like George Lee at the California Pacific Medical
Center in San Francisco see it all the time. And they gently steer
their older patients _ who make up a large portion of those seeking
fertility treatments _ to consider using someone else's eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, most women still insist on trying at least a few times
to use their own eggs before turning to egg donation and bearing a
child that is not genetically related, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The desire to reproduce with our own genetic material is very
strong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While egg donation remains the best option for older women,
emerging techniques could provide better answers to the problem of
aging eggs. They also hold hope for younger women faced with cancer
treatments or premature menopause that may leave them infertile
before they've had a chance to have children.
</P>
<P>
   Freezing eggs, freezing some or all of the ovaries and even
transferring genetic information from old eggs into new egg cells
are the subject of research reported last week at the American
Society for Reproductive Medicine's meeting in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Although no major breakthroughs were revealed, a New York team
created a stir with its announcement that it was attempting to
create a pregnancy with an artificial egg, using an older woman's
genetic material transplanted into a young egg cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theoretically, this has the potential of allowing these women
to have a unique form of egg donation, where she gets to keep her
chromosomes and just gets the young egg,'' said Jamie A. Grifo,
chief of reproductive endocrinology at New York University Medical
Center, where the experiments are being conducted.
</P>
<P>
   With no success so far, that technology remains a distant
possibility. Closer at hand are the freezing techniques, which are
starting to be used with young women facing cancer diagnoses who
want to preserve their ability to have children.
</P>
<P>
   Although sperm has been frozen for years, and frozen embryos are
now used routinely in infertility treatments, freezing delicate
human eggs has bedeviled scientists.
</P>
<P>
   If freezing became workable, healthy women approaching their
35th birthday who want to delay child-bearing could ``bank'' their
eggs for future use. It could eliminate the wrenching custody
battles over frozen embryos, and ease the concerns of some couples
who have religious objections to creating fertilized embryos,
freezing them and discarding the ones that aren't needed.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, teams around the world have been working on the
technology. The first birth from a frozen egg was reported in
Australia in 1986. In the 10 years following only a handful of
other clinics were able to do the same, always after hundreds of
tries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with all these technologies (is that) if you can
try 500 times and you get one success, that's not something that is
clinically viable,'' said Kutluk Oktay, director of reproductive
endocrinology and infertility at New York Methodist Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Still, laboratories around the United States and the world are
reporting scattered victories:
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers from the Florida Institute for Reproductive
Medicine of the Baptist Medical Center in Jacksonville, Fla., said
they had some success with keeping eggs at a higher temperature
before freezing. One woman implanted with embryos from the
procedure has given birth to twins, another is in her third
trimester with twins and a third has a single pregnancy now in the
first trimester, they reported.
</P>
<P>
   _ A group from the Institute for Reproductive Medicine and
Science of Saint Barnabas Medical Center in Livingston, N.J., won a
prize from the society for a technique using a freezing solution
containing much less salt. They had a 90 percent success rate with
mouse eggs, and in a small sample of 10 human eggs achieved a 100
percent success rate. Of the human eggs, 70 percent were fertilized
and developed to at least a four-cell embryonic stage, although
they did not report any pregnancy attempts.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Korean team said they revisited an old process using a
biological anti-freeze to get 65 percent to 85 percent of the eggs
to survive thawing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, scientists at last week's meeting said they wanted to see
more results from multiple laboratories before declaring techniques
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely need confirmation,'' Oktay said.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential technology involves freezing some or all of
women's ovaries, which contain many thousands of eggs in their
immature state. Wrapped in the protective tissue, those eggs better
survive the freezing process. But scientists still haven't
perfected ways of maturing them in the laboratory to the point
where they can be fertilized and create an embryo.
</P>
<P>
   Oktay reported this week that he had implanted previously frozen
human ovarian tissue into mice and was able to get the ovaries to
ripen and give off mature eggs.
</P>
<P>
   If the concept proves workable, the tissue wouldn't have to be
reimplanted in the same place in the body. In fact, scientists said
the idea would be to insert the ovarian tissue under the skin, wait
for the body to ripen the eggs, and then harvest them easily for
in-vitro fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   In Scientists believe much of the problem isn't with the nucleus
of the cell, which houses most of the genetic material, but with
the machinery around it. By transferring the nucleus into a fresher
cell from a younger woman, scientists hope they can avoid many
problems of aging eggs. At least two teams, one at Cornell Medical
Center in New York and another at NYU Medical Center, are working
on the concept.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, NYU's Grifo said he will know this week if a
44-year-old woman who was implanted with two embryos created with
the artificial eggs became pregnant. An earlier attempt with one
embryo and a 47-year-old woman failed. His group has permission
from the university's medical ethics board to try the procedure
with three more patients.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the resulting children would actually have two
mothers. The vast majority of the maternal genetic material would
come from the older woman, but there are a small number of genes,
called the mitochondrial DNA, that are part of the younger egg cell
and would also be passed on to the offspring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
