<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-OPRAH-WINFREY-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPRAH GOES FOR THE OSCAR GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) 
 World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides and black and white photos of Oprah Winfrey in
``Beloved'' are available. 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    She's one of the richest entertainers in history. A force of
nature whose fortune Forbes magazine estimates at $675 million.
There is little doubt Oprah Winfrey will become America's first
black billionaire.
 &HT;    Now she wants the world to take a long hard look at slavery, not
from the outside as Steven Spielberg did in last year's
unsuccessful ``Amistad,'' but from the inside _ the inside of Sethe
the slave in Toni Morrison's story ``Beloved'' (Plume, 1994).
 &HT;    ``It was doing this movie that took me to the reality behind the
words of _ (she starts to sing) _ 'Before I'll be a slave, I'll be
buried in my grave.'''
 &HT;    Moments before, she had bounced into a hotel in Chicago, looking
drop-dead gorgeous. On the current cover of Vogue she looks like a
high fashion model, dressed completely in brown, accented by a
razzle-dazzle gold watch and a pair of spectacular diamond
earrings.
 &HT;    Born to unmarried teenagers in Mississippi, Winfrey never
struggled for anything so much in life as to make ``Beloved'' into
a movie. She spent 10 years trying to bring the story to the
screen, discovering in the process, she says, ``the real meaning of
life.''
 &HT;    Somehow in the story of Sethe who kills her infant daughter to
save her from slavery, Winfrey sees herself. ``I felt when I read
this book, that I was Sethe and that Sethe was me,'' she said,
``and that we were all connected somehow. I was stunned and
overwhelmed and couldn't even articulate what I was feeling.''
 &HT;    She's seen the completed movie many times but every time it has
the same effect on her. ``I need a lobotomy after it,'' she laughs.
``I am just hysterical, crying every time like I'd never been in
the movie, like I hadn't lived it for 10 years. I couldn't believe
my own emotion.''
 &HT;    There were days when she was so upset that director Jonathan
Demme had to give her the day off. ``I was crying and crying and
crying,'' she said. ``Finally Jonathan said, 'We're gonna turn the
camera around on Danny (Danny Glover who plays slave Paul D) and
just let you cry it out. And we'll come back tomorrow and shoot
you.'''
 &HT;    Making the film, she insists, changed her focus on life. She was
tired. She has palatial homes: on the lake in Chicago, on a
160-acre spread in Indiana, on an 85-acre ranch in Telluride Colo.
So who needs the grind of a daily TV show?
 &HT;    ``After 'Beloved' I thought, who wants to be sitting everyday
working on a talk show? I was gonna free myself. But getting to the
realization of what slavery was, I thought, how dare I think tired?
I come from a people who had no shoes, I come from a people who did
not know which way north was, who didn't have milk for their
children. So how dare I with all my square footage and all my Prada
shoes think that I'm tired and need a rest?''
 &HT;    All her life the 44-year-old Winfrey has been a dreamer, always
knowing there was more in store for her than poverty and a
dysfunctional family. ``I remember sitting on the linoleum floor in
Milwaukee when I was 10 watching the Oscars. I never missed that
show and Sydney Poitier won for ``Lilies of the Field.'' And then
something clicked in me that said, 'A colored man did that. I can
too.'''
 &HT;    But even when she started in broadcasting at a small radio
station in Nashville, Tenn., she could not possibly have imagined
reaching icon status.
 &HT;    ``What's it like to be an icon?'' she mocks in a singsong voice.
``I didn't even know what an icon was till a couple of years ago.
Because your perception of yourself is not based on what other
people think of you. Like that Vogue cover. I know I spent two days
working with them on it. But that's not how I see myself.''
 &HT;    The best part of it all, Winfrey says, is when she feels
genuinely loved and appreciated by her audience.
 &HT;    ``Growing up I wanted to be Diana Ross. And you know you're
always looking at other people, thinking, if I could just be that,
or if I could have her hair. And then one day a woman in Midland,
Texas, wrote me a letter saying, 'Watching you be yourself every
day makes me want to be more of myself.'
 &HT;    ``I think I want that on my tombstone.''
 &HT;     c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based
<TEXT>
reporter.) &LR;  &QL;
</TEXT>
