<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1918 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INFIDELITY-HNS &LR;      10-12 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFIDELITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CASUES MARITAL INFIDELITY AND ITS EFFECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE COSTANTNOU  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Infidelity and sex. Always tantalizing subjects,
they have gone beyond the bedroom, tabloids and talk shows to the
national news arena, thanks to the never-ending saga of Bill
Clinton and Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Just what is infidelity? And can those marriages be saved?
</P>
<P>
   Experts say spouses can be unfaithful even when there is no
extramarital sex. Or just a little. In fact, say experts, you don't
even have to touch or be touched.
</P>
<P>
   It is the secrecy, the inherent lying, that defines an affair.
If in doubt, ask yourself: Would my spouse be upset if he or she
knew I was ``seeing'' this other person? If the answer is yes, say
experts, then you are being unfaithful.
</P>
<P>
   To marriage counselors, sex therapists, relationship experts and
psychologists, this admission of secrecy is the big ``Ah-ha!
Gotcha!''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the wronged spouse is more upset by the notion of a
double life and the betrayal of trust than the sex itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex for sex's sake is not a violation of the main
relationship,'' said Ellyn Bader, a counselor at the Couples
Institute in Menlo Park, Calif. ``To me, infidelity exists when
there's lying and sneaking around. That's the unfaithful part.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the number of trysts doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time is an affair,'' said Mary Lamia, a Kentfield, Calif.,
psychologist who does couples therapy. ``An affair is any action
that diverts from the fidelity and loyalty in a marriage. It is a
breach of trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be one time or 100 times.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, then. Who or what is to blame for this affair?
</P>
<P>
   Is an affair a reflection of lowly moral character, of someone
who is weak and cowardly, arrogant and self-centered ... an utterly
loathsome, duplicitous, thrill-seeking hedonistic jerk?
</P>
<P>
   Or is the affair a symptom of a troubled marriage, a pathetic
shell of a relationship where needs go unmet, communication is
nonexistent, and resentment and boredom have replaced love?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, say experts, is a bit of both.
</P>
<P>
   People have affairs for all sorts of reasons. There's the allure
of something forbidden. The thrill of taking risks and getting away
with it. The need to be attractive.
</P>
<P>
   They do it for power and they do it for revenge. They do it out
of boredom and they do it out of loneliness. They do it for fun and
sexual adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, monogamy is tough for anyone, say counselors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monogamy is really hard,'' said Sara Alexander, a San
Francisco couples counselor. ``It's not just a relationship issue
or a character issue. It's an existential issue. Our hearts and
bodies are not monogamous people.''
</P>
<P>
   When marriage was invented, about 2,500 years ago, ``most people
had the courtesy of dying young, before they got bored,'' said
Marty Klein, a Palo Alto, Calif., marriage counselor and sex
therapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surviving spouse was then free to have another sexual
experience in another marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, throughout history, said Klein, polygamy was an accepted
practice in many societies. He said marital tensions about fidelity
arise today because monogamy, though imposed by societal
conventions, is not natural.
</P>
<P>
   No marriage is perfect or trouble-free. But in a marriage with
avowed monogamy, an affair is proof that at least one spouse has
serious dissatisfactions, and that the couple is not talking
honestly enough.
</P>
<P>
   Extramarital sex is the smoke. But where there is smoke, experts
say, there's fire.
</P>
<P>
   Gender differences play a role in the motives and rationales,
experts say. Women are more likely to have an affair if they are
dissatisfied with their marriage. They are usually looking to fill
an emotional need, and are therefore more likely to get emotionally
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Men, on the other hand, tend to compartmentalize their lives.
They're more capable of having sex just for sex's sake, without any
emotional attachment. And they can have sex with another woman even
if they are happy in their marriage and they love their wife.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the longer the affair, the more romantic and
emotionally involved the cheating spouse becomes, the harder it is
to mend the marriage, said David Sitzer, a psychologist at Family
Services Mid Peninsula, a counseling agency in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   The trick to saving the marriage, he and other counselors said,
is to talk, talk, talk.
</P>
<P>
   Couples must also have a heartfelt desire to work it out.
</P>
<P>
   To the pros, professional counseling is a must. Yet only a small
percentage of couples with infidelity problems go to a therapist.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent survey by the American Association for Marriage and
Family Therapy, in Washington D.C., infidelity is second only to
physical violence in the harm it does to the wronged spouse's
mental health. Infidelity even topped drug and alcohol abuse by a
family member, and financial problems, as a cause of marital
distress.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, only 45 percent of those surveyed said they would suggest
professional help if a friend asked for advice about coping with an
unfaithful spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area therapists say their key job is to get each spouse to
open up, to be honest with their spouse _ and with themselves _
about their feelings.
</P>
<P>
   This is harder than it sounds. People don't want to hurt their
spouse's feelings with the truth. They fear their spouse's anger,
abandonment or rejection. Sometimes, they don't even know what
they're feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, said counselors, this inability to be forthright with
their spouse drove them to somebody else. But now, with the
marriage in crisis, it is often easier to open up, said counselors.
</P>
<P>
   An affair that has been exposed ``is a turning point in a
marriage,'' said Jack Morin, a San Francisco psychologist and
author of ``The Erotic Mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It shakes things up,'' he added. ``The disenchantments are
suddenly out on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, an affair doesn't have to be a marital disaster, said
Pete Roussos, a counselor in San Jose, Calif. ``It can be a real
opportunity to reveal what isn't being said,'' and for couples to
communicate what they want, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With honesty, the trust that has been damaged is sometimes
repaired.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not enough for the straying spouse to pledge ``it will
never happen again,'' counselors said. Both spouses must believe
and want it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you return to monogamy out of choice, it's different than
when you stay in monogamy out of fear,'' said Marcia Perlstein, a
Berkeley, Calif., family counselor.
</P>
<P>
   But then there are times, said Alexander, when the pain doesn't
go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes helping people,'' she said, ``means helping people
separate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1926 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-MIGHTY-HN     10-12 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MIGHTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE MIGHTY' CASTS SHARON STONE IN NEW ROLE AS MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There's a scene in ``The Mighty'' when Sharon
Stone is told her crippled son's health is deteriorating. She walks
over to a coffee machine in the hospital, murmurs something about
getting hot chocolate, then breaks down in a rage against the
machine as it slops liquid over a cup, slamming and kicking it
until tears spill from her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   That scene was hard, said Stone, but not as hard as the one
where Elden Henson _ one of the two teenaged stars of the movie _
runs barefoot across the snow to catch up with an ambulance, only
to be told by Stone that there's nothing he can do to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get to the emotional depth of that scene without
being sentimental,'' said Stone. ``Eldon actually helped me. He was
very patient and supportive and loving, standing there in the snow.
... It was so cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing the role of a middle-aged mother in a movie rated PG-13
breaks new ground for Stone, star of ``Basic Instinct,'' ``Quick
and the Dead,'' ``Sphere,'' and ``Casino,'' for which she received
an Academy Award nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mighty,'' which is based on Rodman philbrick's book,
``Freak the Mighty,'' is her best film so far, said Stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm growing each time. I don't take a part unless I
feel I will grow from it,'' she said. ``And I think people see
that. I think people are sure now that I'm an actor who's an artist
and not a celebrity who's a sensationalist.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone provides a distinctive voice to the animated film
``Antz,'' which made $16.8 million in its opening weekend (Oct.
2-4). Her next step was ``The Mighty.''
</P>
<P>
   When Miramax sent her the script, Stone agreed to co-produce the
movie through her Chaos Productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the project was very good, but a film starring two kids
... unless someone attached themselves to it, it probably wouldn't
get made,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone was already talking about the film at Cannes in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Miramax told me I could play a mom, after many people
told me that was a complete impossibility, I jumped at the
chance,'' she said, adding, ``Not having children of my own, I had
no comprehension of the savage, wild, uncontrollable thing that
happens to you when your child is in danger. It made life difficult
for everybody, but it made life great when I got to see the
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone's co-stars on ``The Mighty'' said she didn't made life
difficult at all. Kieran Culkin, 15, who plays Stone's son, said,
``Sharon told me not to try to act like my whole body is
handicapped. She said, `Make this foot handicapped and nothing
else.' And when I did that, it made it a lot easier, because my
foot and whole body moved easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Henson, 20, said, ``Sharon dispelled all my inhibitions and fear
that I was feeling because she was `Sharon Stone.' She grabbed my
hand and said, `You can do this, this is your scene, don't worry
about me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Stone returned the compliment, saying, ``Elden Henson is a
wonderful actor, very developed as an artist. He was very helpful
to me in the hospital scene, which was much more of an
improvisational scene. It's hard for a young actor in an
improvisational scene with the other actors going crazy. I'm very
proud of both of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone is also proud of the final product.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film is much better than I imagined it could be,'' she
said. ``Who wouldn't be happy to see this movie _ to see it as a
family, the closeness it would inspire?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mighty'' has some parallels to John Steinbeck's ``Of Mice
and Men'' _ a friendship formed between brute strength and
smartness _ but ``The Mighty'' goes beyond that, said Stone, into a
world of teenagers caught up in dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what really drew me to it. It doesn't condescend to
teenagers. It inspires teenagers,'' said Stone. ``It lets them know
you can be compassionate. It says the right things, building this
strong sense of the young boys' struggle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
