<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF `BIGFOOD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For $50, Tim Ford will tell you all about the
Bigfoot he saw earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   He'll explain how on Saturday night, when he was roasting
marshmallows at a campsite in Northern California, he heard a loud
rustling in some nearby bushes, and that's when it all started.
</P>
<P>
   Ford shined his flashlight and spotted an ``enormous furry
creature, 9-feet tall, with huge yellow eyes, and with arms that
were hanging way past its knees,'' he told Fish and Game Lt. Don
Jacobs. Even from a distance, there was ``a pungent, sickening
odor.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the night continued, Ford could hear ``screams'' from
the ``man-beast.'' The next morning, footprints were discovered
that were ``20 inches long and 6 inches wide.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 22, of Redding, Calif., was joined by James Harmon, of
Reno, Nevada, and three other unidentified friends. They were on a
hunting trip, camping near Mud Springs, located south of a small
settlement called Wildwood in national forest west of Redding. Ford
told me that he is now charging $50 per session to describe what
happened because it is otherwise ``a complete waste of time.''
</P>
<P>
   You know what's weird about this story? Wait, don't answer that.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks ago, I surveyed this specific area, and many
years ago spent a fair amount of time here when one of my best
friends lived in nearby Platina, population 150 (including dogs).
And once I was assigned by former San Francisco Examiner publisher
Will Hearst to spend six weeks afield, looking for Bigfoot,
scrambling in some of the most remote places in North America,
selecting them only after months of research and interviews with
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Now get this: We found footprints in snow that were 17 inches
long, 6 inches wide. For a brief moment, exactly where we thought
we might see a Bigfoot, the scientist among us spotted the backside
of a large, brown, hairy creature, about a mile distant, high on
the opposite side of a canyon.
</P>
<P>
   In one terrifying moment while staking out a spring, the only
water source in a 5-mile radius, I heard something approaching in
the brush, a one-two, one-two step, a biped, not a bear. And at
night, we heard this strange thumping noise, as if Bigfoot was
thumping a hollow log with a stick, calling for a mate, always in
five rhythmic thumps.
</P>
<P>
   When we found the 17-inch footprints, Hearst got worried and
became extremely nervous about what I might write. When I checked
in at the office, he came up to me and said, ``You didn't actually
find the thing did you?''
</P>
<P>
   Heh, heh. Now for the rest of the story, as some may remember:
</P>
<P>
   The 17-inch footprints were actually boot prints of a 6-foot
man, prints that had melted out in the snow, which we determined by
measuring the stride length between the prints.
</P>
<P>
   That large hairy creature was stalked, then spotted again, and
it turned out to be a large black bear but one with brown fur.
</P>
<P>
   At the stakeout of the spring, the Bigfoot walking in the brush
turned out to be an expedition partner, who after two hours of
waiting, decided on his own to scramble on a game trail to the
spring, trying to flush out anything toward my hiding spot, and in
the process, practically scared the whiskers off me.
</P>
<P>
   And that strange thumping noise? It is the mating call of a blue
grouse in deep forest wilderness, and it really does sound like
someone thumping on a hollow log.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, there is this one area where we found nothing but where
we figured a Bigfoot could live undetected for generations. I've
often thought about this region, and remember how two 80-year-old
Hupa Indians told me that if I wanted to see Bigfoot, this would be
the place.
</P>
<P>
   But it is nowhere near Mud Springs, the spot Ford pinpointed as
the site of his Bigfoot encounter.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long, twisty drive to reach Mud Springs, but it is
accessible by anybody in a car. This region is just above the
transition zone where valley oaks give way to conifers, with a few
small streams and springs sprinkled amid an area that has been
extensively logged. The summer heat and lack of water make it
difficult for many species, and hence, wildlife is not as abundant
as in other habitats. It is the natural beauty in spring and fall,
lack of people, and nearby little-known Chanchelulla Wilderness
that inspires most to visit.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bigfoot episode was first reported, the first thing I
noticed was how ``perfect'' the story was, that is, it had
everything: a sighting, detailed description, footprints in the
dirt, pungent odor, frightening shrieks at night. I can't think of
another account that had all the elements; most have just one or
two.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife expert Paul Wertz of the DFG agree that it seemed ``too
perfect'' and that it ``conjures up the idea of somebody who has
done a lot of reading.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the DFG ``denied any involvement.'' After all,
Wertz said with a laugh, ``Our Bigfoot suit is at the cleaners.''
</P>
<P>
   But he mentioned that even if only one of the thousands of
reported Bigfoot incidents is true, then Bigfoot is real, it's out
there, and like many, he knows of conservative, conventional folks
who swear they have had a Bigfoot experience.
</P>
<P>
   The best research on Bigfoot was conducted in China, where a
team of 30 scientists set out to document more than two dozen
reports of Yeti, as it is known there, that occurred over a
five-year span. After six months, the scientists found their
Bigfoot all right, and he was real, not imaginary. Their Bigfoot
turned out to be a wild man, a truly undeveloped man who had lived
like an animal for most of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let me tell you what happened when I was out researching
this story. I never saw Bigfoot, but one night there were these
bright lights, and I looked up and saw this spaceship land in a
meadow, then these beautiful space aliens walked out and invited me
in.
</P>
<P>
   For $50 I'll tell you what the spaceship looked like, for $100
I'll tell you about the beautiful space aliens, for $500 I'll tell
you about the inside of the spaceship, and for $1,000, whether it
was good or not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
