<HEADLINE>
CAROLINA'S LANE GROUNDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Carolina Panthers' running game started
slowly and went downhill from there, finally grinding to a halt in
the fourth quarter, in which the Panthers ran the ball just five
times for minus-3 yards in yesterday's 27-20 loss.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tough day for Fred Lane, Carolina's workhorse back. But
not because he was getting beaten up by Cowboys defenders. Instead,
Lane, who has accounted for 78 percent of the Panthers' carries and
77 percent of their rushing yards this year, missed the team flight
from Charlotte, N.C. on Saturday and was held out of the game by
coach Dom Capers.
</P>
<P>
   Lane's replacement, Anthony Johnson, managed just 28 yards on 16
attempts, a 1.8 yards-per-carry average, and the Panthers' longest
running play of the day went for a mere 4 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just told me I wasn't going to start,'' Lane said after
spending the afternoon kneeling by himself on the Texas Stadium
sideline, ``but I kind of figured I wasn't going to play at all.
I've been around here awhile, and my mama didn't raise no dummy,
you know what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   He meant that he knew from the moment he arrived at Charlotte's
Douglas International Airport and was told the Panthers' charter
flight had already boarded that he wouldn't see the light of day
against the Cowboys. Still, being the competitor he is, Lane
decided to give it a shot, running out to the tarmac and hoping
Capers would let him on.
</P>
<P>
   But with his team winless, Capers wasn't exactly in the mood to
be forgiving, so the plane took off without Lane with several
players on board chanting, ``Fred-dy! Fred-dy!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it was frustrating,'' Lane said. ``But it just happened.
Everyone has missed a plane. I'm not the first one and I won't be
the last.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
