<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG-12-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV DELAY: TECH START UP IN AIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What if they held a football game and no one knew when to show
up?
</P>
<P>
   That remains the case for Saturday's Texas Tech-Colorado contest
in Boulder, Colo., which has no assigned kickoff time and was not
included on the list of Big 12 telecasts announced yesterday by
league officials.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Allen, Big 12 associate commissioner, said he expects the
game to be played at 12:30 p.m. as a syndicated telecast on
KXTX/Channel 39. But league officials must confer today with
representatives from ABC before announcing a starting time.
</P>
<P>
   Questions arose yesterday when ABC selected the Kansas
State-Oklahoma State game as its 2:30 p.m. telecast, thereby
relegating the Tech-Colorado game into the league's syndicated TV
window. Normal starting time for syndicated telecasts is 11:30
a.m., or 10:30 a.m. Mountain Time in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   But Colorado athletic director Dick Tharp objected, saying his
school had an agreement with Big 12 officials that no game could
start before 11:30 a.m. in the city where it is played.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the contest back one hour, to a 12:30 p.m. start in
Texas, would force the conclusion to overlap with the ABC game.
ABC's contract calls for exclusivity on Big 12 telecasts in the
2:30 p.m. to 5:30 p.m. window, a point league officials must
clarify today before setting a kickoff time between No. 22 Tech
(6-0, 3-0) and No. 19 Colorado (5-1, 2-1).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to ask Colorado to play at 10:30
\RMountain\S,'' Allen said. ``What we're trying to do is get things
ironed out with ABC and make sure we're all on the same page'' to
permit the overlap in Big 12 telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said he is ``so confident'' the Tech-Colorado game will be
a 12:30 p.m. telecast that league officials have not contacted
other schools about a fallback option. If the Tech-Colorado game
goes untelevised, each school would lose $72,500 in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the part that bothers Tech coach Spike Dykes, who
has grown weary of seeing the kickoff time listed as TBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they let us know before Friday what the game time is,
so we can make some travel plans,'' Dykes said. ``TBA is just
wearing me out.'' Extra points Southwestern Bell Cotton Bowl
officials confirmed yesterday that the Jan. 1 game will be a 10
a.m. telecast on the Fox Network. The game, which will match a Big
12 team against a Southeastern Conference opponent, will kick off
at 10:08 a.m. and will be the first of six bowls televised on New
Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Dykes, on breaking into The Associated Press rankings at No. 22:
``I'm glad we're ranked, but you can't go to the bank and borrow a
bunch of money on it. That shouldn't be a concern of this team at
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M jumped from No. 18 to No. 10 in the AP poll on the
strength of its 28-21 upset of Nebraska, marking the Aggies'
highest ranking since the team was No. 8 before a 14-7 loss to
Texas Tech in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Texas quarterback Major Applewhite, who threw for a career-high
293 yards in the Longhorns' 34-3 rout of Oklahoma, improved to 17th
nationally in passing efficiency (146 points). Applewhite is one
spot below a fellow freshman, Georgia's Quincy Carter (146.6), and
one ahead of Cade McNown (145.7), UCLA's Heisman Trophy candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
