<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1959 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     10-12 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEION REFUSES TO LET VICTORY SLIP FROM COWBOYS' GRASP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ ``I didn't find God, God found me,'' Deion
Sanders said softly yesterday at Texas Stadium. Thankfully for the
Cowboys, so did Carolina's Steve Beuerlein when it mattered most,
</P>
<P>
   If it's the power of prayer, as Deion suggests, then maybe we
should all join hands and take a knee.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' interception of Beuerlein's desperation pass late in
the fourth quarter helped the Cowboys seal a 27-20 victory that was
on the cusp of slipping through their fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Until his huge interception late in the game, it had been a
relatively uneventful afternoon for Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   He'd done his usual playing to the crowd. He'd pointed to the
heavens, giving glory to God while being sure that all eyes were on
No. 21. He'd played offensive decoy. He'd strutted. He'd done the
``Do-rag Boogie.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd also been basically a nonfactor in the game, missing a
tackle that allowed Carolina to break a big play and fair-catching
several punts.
</P>
<P>
   Mama Beuerlein didn't raise any stupid children. Son Steve
hasn't stuck around in the NFL all these years by throwing in the
direction of the game's best cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Until he had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is like Michael Jordan,'' Cowboys defensive
coordinator Dave Campo said of Sanders. ``He can make a play at any
time. You attack him enough times, he's going to hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurt you bad.
</P>
<P>
   The play wasn't designed to go to Sanders' man, but a frantic
Beuerlein, facing a third-and-13 situation from the Cowboys' 44
with the clock ticking down to the two-minute warning, was chased
left out of the pocket by the Cowboys' pass rush. He spotted
wideout Mark Carrier, working on Sanders, breaking to the left
sideline near the 30-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was keying the inside receiver,'' Sanders said. ``They'd
been hurting us all day with that inside guy running straight up
the field and I was trying to make a play on him and my man
\RCarrier\S ran an out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a tremendous pass rush on that play. That forced the
quarterback to get out there and throw the ball to me because I
don't think I was the go-to guy on that play, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a cardinal rule: Quarterbacks try not to make a habit of
making Deion the go-to guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a great play but you expect that,'' said Beuerlein,
getting the start because No. 1 quarterback Kerry Collins walked
into head coach Dom Capers' office at mid-week and confessed that
his heart wasn't into the game. ``He's going to make a great play
every game. I knew I had to throw it outside, I just didn't get it
far enough out.''
</P>
<P>
   There may not be a ``far enough out'' when Sanders is defending,
even for a red-hot Beuerlein, who started the fourth quarter having
completed 16 of 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``As many plays as they made on us at the end of the game, they
had to go back to Deion, and it cost them,'' Campo said. ``We were
overloaded \Ron the opposite side\S and there was no way they were
going over there. That's something you can do when you're ahead
that you can't do when it's even-steven all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't go near him until late in the game. Then they made
two throws \Ron Sanders' side\S and on the third one, he picked it.
If he had that same set of conditions 10 times, he might put seven
of them in the end zone. When he touches the ball and he's got a
lot of open field like that, he's very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   He has become perhaps the Cowboys' most dangerous weapon, a
potent threat with his ability to return an interception or a punt,
or contribute offensively.
</P>
<P>
   A bold correspondent might even venture to say that Sanders has
been the Cowboys' clear-cut MVP for the season's first six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me involved in that,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey
pleaded, ``but you'd be a smart guy if you said that.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can measure what he has meant to our team,''
Gailey said. ``The guy has created a sense of excitement and
resolve that we're going to find a way to win, somehow, some way.''
</P>
<P>
   By hook, crook or answered prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a tremendous inspiration,'' Campo said. ``He's
always been one of the catalysts of the team, not so much from a
vocal standpoint but from a confidence standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's feeling real at peace with himself right now. He's
feeling really good about himself and when he's in that mode,
that's his playmaking mode. He's got that feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   And you know Deion. He's never shy about sharing it with the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say enough for what the Lord has done for me,'' Deion
said. ``I figure now some of you guys are saying this Jesus thing
must be pretty good, the way Deion's playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get into God's game, and he'll get into yours. That's
where I'm at.''
</P>
<P>
   Shake your head all you want, nonbelievers, but when the Cowboys
had to have a play yesterday, there stood Deion.
</P>
<P>
   Admit it, he looked pretty divine at the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1405EDT &QL; 
