<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMMITT OF OLD SILENCES CRITICS FOR ONE MORE WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ As he dressed after the Cowboys' 27-20 victory,
Emmitt Smith's mind said to hurry, but his body said no.
</P>
<P>
   His legs, the ones he's used to run for more than 11,000 yards
in his pro career, lifted oh-so-slowly into his baby-blue slacks.
His arms slipped tenderly into his blue-plaid sportcoat.
</P>
<P>
   At the adjoining locker, Cowboys teammate Dexter Coakley made a
teasing remark about Smith moving so slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you went through what I just went through, you'd be moving
slow, too,'' Smith shot back.
</P>
<P>
   He meant the game. I think.
</P>
<P>
   He meant the afternoon, and the 112 yards he rushed for, and the
touchdown he scored and the strained hip that finally forced him to
the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   At least I think that's what he meant.
</P>
<P>
   But for a while here, who knew? Who knew what to think about
Emmitt Smith?
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' media guide this season tried to carve Smith's
niche into immortality. ``In eight seasons,'' it read, ``Emmitt
Smith has become one of the all-time great running backs in NFL
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's resume, to be sure, is golden. As the Cowboys rose to
reborn prominence in the 1990s, Smith supplied the horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   But what the media guide left out were the questions. The
questions about how his production had been dropping off for two
seasons. The questions about the Sunday afternoons, some of them
big Sunday afternoons, when Smith supposedly bruised a rib,
strained a groin, battled the flu or succumbed to a witch's brew of
other ills and checked himself out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   His own greatness was mocking him. It wasn't the same Emmitt
Smith. But on a 6-10 team that underachieved notoriously, who
really knew?
</P>
<P>
   Against the Carolina Panthers yesterday, Smith ran like a ghost
of Emmitts past. At times, despite an early fumble, he burst
through gaps to split would-be defenders. In the open field, he
cocked his shoulder and took on tacklers.
</P>
<P>
   The 112 yards marked his first back-to-back 100-yard rushing
games since December of the 1995 season. That factoid spoke
volumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there's a story to write now,'' Smith said, as the air
around his locker suddenly turned chilly.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a story, however, all season. Smith's 529 yards and
his rejuvenation _ my word, certainly not his _ have been a Cowboys
highlight in this 4-2 season.
</P>
<P>
   Who knew?
</P>
<P>
   Smith knew, he says, staring at the insinuator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to answer those questions because they don't
require an answer,'' he said, when asked simply what made this
season so different than last. ``I'm just playing the game of
football the way I've played it for the past eight seasons.
Whatever happens from there just happens.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're charting Cowboys history, however, you have to have
circled the August day in 1996, when Smith signed a new contract
worth $42 million over eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Since that day, until these past two weeks, Smith had not had
back-to-back 100-yard rushing days. Since that day, Smith had
averaged less than 4 yards per carry.
</P>
<P>
   Since that day, too, Smith, ever the running artist, was leaving
incomplete canvases all over the NFL schedule. He checked out of
the critical San Francisco game last season with a groin injury
after only seven carries. Nursing a bruised shoulder, he had only
two rushing attempts in a December game against the Panthers. In
Cincinnati, fighting the flu, he took a break to go to the
bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   The former head coach, let me point out here, never said a word
about any of this. Barry Switzer wasn't about to tell Emmitt Smith
what to do.
</P>
<P>
   But Chan Gailey took a different approach with the 29-year-old
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the same guy I saw last year, when he was healthy and
when things were going well,'' Gailey said, assessing the 1998
model Emmitt.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey had to have heard, of course, what people were saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't listen to what anybody said,'' the coach replied
yesterday. ``I watched the tape. I saw all I needed to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but the Cowboys did sign Chris Warren. The free-agent
running back came from the Seattle Seahawks for a reported $2
million over three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   For Smith, the handwriting _ in this case, the set of footprints
_ was on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a coincidence Smith, with the former Pro Bowl back Warren
waiting to spell him, suddenly seems to regained his running zip?
</P>
<P>
   Smith bristles at that kind of question. He doesn't want to
compare anything that happened last season or any other season, for
that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's in the past is in the past,'' he said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   He says he sees things from ``a different perspective'' than the
Emmitt-is-done skeptics do.
</P>
<P>
   No, he isn't done, if these first five games are any indication.
With a new coach, a new offense, a mostly new offensive line, and a
symbolic new stand-in waiting in the wings, Emmitt Smith has been
running like a star again.
</P>
<P>
   And he's right. There is a story to write.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1405EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
