<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1962 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-PANTHERS-     10-12 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-PANTHERS-TEX </SLUG>
 
Cowboys barely hold on, skin the 'Cats 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Considering his team's dismal finish in 1997 and
their up-and-down start to 1998, Cowboys coach Chan Gailey is not
about to turn his nose up at any victory.
</P>
<P>
   And, to be sure, he was pleased to see the Cowboys reach their
goal of gaining back-to-back wins in yesterday's 27-20 victory
against the Carolina Panthers before 64,181 fans at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys (4-2), who had followed their first two victories
this season with losses, strung together two victories for the
first time since topping Arizona and Washington last November.
</P>
<P>
   But Gailey hardly sported a victorious smile in the locker room
after what could be termed a fragmented performance from the
Cowboys. Turnovers and breakdowns in the secondary offset
outstanding efforts from the offense and run defense, nearly
turning what should have been a blowout into a nail-biter.
</P>
<P>
   After leading 27-14 in the fourth quarter, the Cowboys didn't
secure their first-ever victory against the winless Panthers until
former Cowboys quarterback Steve Beuerlein's last-chance pass fell
incomplete in the end zone in the waning seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been one to complain about winning,'' Gailey said.
``But in this game, we had to overcome a lot of self-imposed
adversity. Two wins in a row was real good. But it wasn't
dominating by any shape or form. We've got a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys guard Nate Newton was in full agreement, saying the
victory was tempered by the team's inconsistent play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the win, but weren't consistent,'' Newton said. ``We
didn't finish it. We've got to get better as the game goes on. We
didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The inconsistent play was evident not only in the Cowboys' pass
defense, which allowed Beuerlein to hit on his first 12 passes en
route to completing 22 of 32 passes for 286 yards and three
touchdowns, but also in the play of the Cowboys' stars.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith topped 100 yards for the
second consecutive week, rushing 21 times for 112 yards a
touchdown. But it was his second-quarter fumble that helped the
Panthers take a 14-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Beuerlein, who lit an emotional firestorm in the hapless
Panthers (0-5) after replacing starter Kerry Collins in the middle
of the week, capitalized by connecting on the second of his two
touchdown passes to Panthers receiver Raghib Ismail, this one
against Cowboys cornerback Kevin Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys quarterback Jason Garrett, who moved to 3-1 as a starter
in place of injured star Troy Aikman, was 14-of-22 for 287 yards
and two touchdowns. However, it was his fourth-quarter fumble that
allowed the Panthers to get back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   After Garrett's fumble with 6:34 left in the game, Beuerlein
made the game interesting with a 3-yard touchdown pass to William
Floyd. An interception by Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders ended
the next drive, and time ran out on the last.
</P>
<P>
   In between the two fumbles, however, the Cowboys scored 24
consecutive points between the second and fourth quarters. Garrett,
smartly mixing in deep passes to receivers Michael Irvin and Ernie
Mills against the Panthers run-conscious defense, completed nine
passes for 18 yards or longer.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, who caught only one pass last week, finished with six
receptions for 146 yards, while Mills caught five passes for 110,
including an 18-yard touchdown reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``They isolate guys a lot,'' Garrett said of the deep-ball game
plan. ``When we run the ball it makes them commit and open up the
passing game.''
</P>
<P>
   The only area in which the Cowboys were strong from beginning to
end was the run defense, which limited Panthers running back
Anthony Johnson to 28 yards on 16 carries.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' pass defense, helped by a Panthers fumble and an
improving pass rush, played better in the second half. Beuerlein
was 12-of-13 for 160 yards and two touchdowns in the first half and
completed 19 of his first 22 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' play on defense was the continuation of a
season-long trend. They have allowed just three touchdowns after
intermission in six games, including one yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys linebacker Dexter Coakley said it was just a matter of
surviving the early emotion from the Panthers and Beuerlein.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was important to come out fired up in the second
half,'' Coakley said. ``We knew they would rally around Steve. We
just had to follow the game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite not registering a clean knockout as a team, the Cowboys
also took solace in the fact that the victory kept them on track in
their quest to becoming ``a good team.'' And with the Chicago Bears
(1-5) up next Sunday before Aikman returns from his fractured
collarbone against Philadelphia (1-5), the Cowboys have a chance to
add to the string of victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the road to doing becoming a good team,'' Gailey
said. ``But we haven't proved anything yet. It doesn't matter until
you do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
