<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-WETTELAND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WETTELAND PLANNING ON ELBOW SURGERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Rangers right-hander John Wetteland, who has avoided
injuries to his throwing shoulder and elbow during most of his
major-league career, expects to undergo arthroscopic surgery on his
right elbow within the next few weeks, the two-time All-Star said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been bothering me all year,'' the Rangers' closer said.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin could not be reached for
comment on the nature or seriousness of the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's news to me,'' Rangers trainer Danny Wheat said of
Wetteland's plans for surgery. ``I'm supposed to get in touch with
him the first part of this week. Maybe he's speculating that he'll
need surgery. We do know this much: He does have a \Rbone\S spur in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland indicated he plans to undergo surgery after he and his
wife, Michele, return home to New Mexico with their 2-year-old
daughters, twins Addie and Katie. Wetteland also was unclear
regarding the doctor who would perform the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, who went 3-1 with a 2.03 earned-run average,
established a Rangers' single-season record with 42 saves during
1998. His earned-run average ranked as the third-best among
American League relief pitchers, and opponents' .203 batting
average ranked as the fourth-lowest among league relievers.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland's three stints on the disabled list since 1992 did not
involve his throwing arm. Strains of the groin muscle and right
hamstring forced Wetteland to the disabled list during the 1996 and
'94 seasons, respectively. Wetteland also went on the disabled list
during 1993 after fracturing the big toe on his right foot.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, who during the 1999 season will earn $5.75 million,
likely will be ready for spring training after surgery barring any
unforeseen setbacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
