</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STYLE POINTS DIDN'T MATTER IN THIS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Doctors and house cats bury their mistakes. But
few teams in today's NFL have such a luxury, and until yesterday,
the Cowboys certainly weren't considered among league exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a 27-20 victory over Carolina, and with it, the notion
that the Cowboys threw dirt on attempted self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas big plays were randomly mixed with big blunders _ one
seemed to constantly nullify the other. Second-guessing was
rampant, starting with Chan Gailey on play-calling and clock
management. Jerry Jones spent far too much time wandering around
the bench area. Rocket Ismail spent far too much time wandering
behind the Cowboys' secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina used a backup quarterback after the starter complained
last week of heart problems _ Kerry Collins admitted he lacked one.
Carolina used a backup running back because starter Fred Lane
missed the team flight. Injuries cost Carolina its two best
offensive linemen. The Panthers had no running game yesterday and a
defense that was torched for 428 yards of balanced Dallas offense.
Plus, the visitors were yellow flagged repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   All that negative stuff normally adds up to road destruction.
But instead, there was the always gallant Steve Beuerlein, firing
for the end zone as time ran out. Only that incompletion finally
sealed the deal for Dallas, and frankly, delivered justice to Jason
Garrett, Emmitt Smith, Ernie Mills, the offensive line, Greg Ellis,
Leon Lett ... well, there were many who got what they deserved.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty, however, in achieving it, left much to be
deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been one to complain too much about wins,''
deadpanned Gailey, who actually seemed somewhat amused over media
questions in the postgame locker room. It probably had something to
do with this victory being graded on style points. Based on August
expectations, any ol' win would do for Dallas, now ranked among the
NFL's surprises with a 4-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   But defensive coordinator Dave Campo was not so jovial. His
group suffered from big-play skid marks, and frankly, had far too
many problems with Beuerlein and an assortment of Panther offensive
backups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good we won the game,'' snapped Campo, growing weary of
what-went-wrong questions. ``I think Beuerlein is one heck of a
quarterback, too,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Campo did admit, however, that the big-play blues are starting
to concern. And this was after Gailey made a rare admission that
the performance of cornerback Kevin Smith had become worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's more. Besides the defense being burned and two
offensive fumbles leading to 14 Carolina points, special teams also
ran off the road at times. Like being completely fooled on a fake
punt, then being saved by a referee's questionable flag on the
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that mattered in the end was we found a way to
win,'' said Gailey. ``We had to overcome some self-imposed
adversity, and once we had done that, the game appeared to be put
away. Instead, we're fighting our butts off right up until the
gun.''
</P>
<P>
   As the head coach who also calls offensive plays, Gailey is
subject to the double whammy of scrunity. How the overall team
performs come with his territory, as does his decisions on
down-distance-situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' offensive confusion at the end of the second half
was dumped in Gailey's lap, and he said, ``Hit me. I deserved it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the up-and-down nature of play-calling was never more
graphic than at a critical point early in the third quarter. With
Dallas trailing, 14-10, a timely sack was registered by Ellis, the
rookie defensive end who is starting to emerge. When William Floyd
fumbled on the next play, the Cowboys took over at the Panthers'
2-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Bring on Emmitt, who, by the way, continues to run like a guy
trying to outrun last season's dismal performance. Smith got a yard
on first down, but with the ball at the 1, Gailey did the
unthinkable. He had Garrett trying to pass, except Kevin Greene was
there for the sack and a 5-yard loss.
</P>
<P>
   Had Gailey gone nuts?
</P>
<P>
   But on third-and-goal from the 6, here came a perfect call _
meaning, it worked perfectly. Garrett got the shovel pass to Chris
Warren, who barreled up the middle and into the end zone. Again,
what was Gailey thinking?
</P>
<P>
   On the failed pass attempt, he said, ``Last week, we hammered
Emmitt up the middle out of the same formation. I thought they'd be
hanging all over Emmitt. They weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   On the successful shovel pass, he said, ``Last week, out of that
same formation, we put Deion \RSanders\S in motion and got the ball
to him. We did it this time, thinking they'd be all over Deion.
About six of them were.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy come, easy go. And although winning wasn't exactly easy,
it's the only thing that ultimately mattered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
