r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ANALYSIS-     10-12 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ANALYSIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS VICTORY A LESSON IN FILM REVIEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It must have been like watching a sandlot
football game to the average fan, what with Jason Garrett slinging
rainbows all over Texas Stadium on Sunday. But there was a method
to defeating the Carolina Panthers, a method that gave the Cowboys
two 100-yard receivers in the same game for the first time in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Irvin had six receptions for 146 yards and Ernie Mills
had five for 110 and one touchdown in the Cowboys' 27-20 victory
against the Panthers. Most of their receptions came as they beat
the Carolina cornerbacks' one-on-one coverage to run down perfectly
thrown deep passes from Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing how well \RGarrett\S threw the ball today _ not
amazing because I didn't think he could do it, but that anybody
could be that accurate,'' coach Chan Gailey said as he headed for
his locker Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The plan to unleash the Irvin-Mills duo had come during practice
and film-room sessions last week.
</P>
<P>
   Panthers cornerbacks Doug Evans (who was limited by a hand
injury), Eric Davis and Rod Smith are very aggressive in man-to-man
coverage, Cowboys coaches noticed on film. The Cowboys figured they
would take advantage of the Panthers aggressiveness by letting
Irvin, Mills and Billy Davis (one catch, 23 yards) make mid-route
adjustments to get deep on Panthers defenders, who like to sit on
shorter routes.
</P>
<P>
   On most occasions, all Garrett (14-of-22, 287 yards, 2 TDs) had
to do was keep the safety from providing deep help by freezing him
with a look or a pump fake. Then, Irvin said, ``we had to make
plays on the outside.'' They did. The Cowboys converted nine passes
of 18 yards or longer, including a 38-yarder to Mills and a
42-yarder to Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we could run some 12-yard outs, and when Carolina
would bump us we'd convert it to a streak route,'' Cowboys
quarterback coach Buddy Geis said. ``The good thing is that Chan
lets the quarterback and the wide receiver have that kind of
flexibility. A lot of (coaches) won't do that because they don't
want to throw that many deep balls. But we did and executed very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gailey: ``I don't claim to be the smartest guy in the
world. But when it works I'm not going to change a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was sweet for Mills. He'd played for the Panthers last
year, but coaches there didn't think enough of his talents to use
him (he was inactive for six games in 1997), and team management
did not re-sign him in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   He repaid the Panthers by totaling a career-high in yards
Sunday. He made the game's prettiest play, bending backward as if
he were doing the limbo to catch an 18-yard touchdown pass in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The play: 84 Semi Go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fade route and I probably made it more difficult than
it needed to be,'' Mills said. ``I picked the ball up late, made a
run for it and concentrated to make the catch.''  &LR; tagtop:Kevin
Lyons (817)390-7760  &LR; tagbottom:''lyonsnfl &LR; star-telegram.com''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
