<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BURCH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOAST FOR TEXAS FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something crazy happened Saturday night. I fell asleep in Texas
and woke up in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   This had to be Florida, didn't it? Where else would you find
cover-to-cover stories about triumphs by the local college football
teams throughout the Sunday newspaper?
</P>
<P>
   Not your run-of-the-mill victories, either. We're talking about
high-profile wins. The stuff that lifts spirits, turns around
programs and shifts the focus of Monday-morning office chats from
the NFL to the college game.
</P>
<P>
   Check it out: One school knocked off the defending national
champs, ending their 19-game winning streak. Another unleashed its
Heisman Trophy candidate and scored its most lopsided victory
against its archrival in 28 years. A third school continued its
best start since Gerald Ford roamed the Oval Office, improving to
6-0 and forcing its way into the Top 25.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, Florida State and Miami?
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Texas A&AMP;M, Texas and Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Toss in Baylor's comeback victory against Kansas and the four
Texas-based members of the Big 12 swept conference games in the
same weekend for the first time in league history.
</P>
<P>
   Add in TCU, pacesetter in the Western Athletic Conference's
Mountain Division, and you've got four teams from the Lone Star
State receiving Top 25 votes yesterday. Those four are a combined
19-4, with No. 10 A&AMP;M (5-1, 2-0 Big 12) holding its loftiest perch
in The Associated Press poll since 1995 and No. 22 Tech (6-0, 3-0)
already qualified as a postseason participant.
</P>
<P>
   For a state that has been starved for college football success
in recent seasons, Saturday's results provided the biggest one-day
infusion of positive feedback in more than a decade. Especially the
victories by A&AMP;M, Tech and Texas, which all but limited the list of
title contenders in the Big 12 South Division to those three teams.
</P>
<P>
   String enough days like this together and a funny thing might
happen. Texas, the state with the nation's deepest pool of high
school football talent, could rival Florida as the breeding ground
of NCAA football powers.
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen overnight. But coaches realize the potential
significance of Oct. 10, 1998, when A&AMP;M led the parade by knocking
off Nebraska, 28-21, and Texas followed with a 34-3 rout of
Oklahoma before Tech capped the evening with a 24-17 victory
against Oklahoma State. All in front of network or cable television
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great day for college football in Texas,'' said Texas
coach Mack Brown. ``We would all like to bring a national
championship to Texas. But the first step is convincing enough of
these young guys to stay here, regardless of which school they
choose, and play. A day like Saturday helps. As we all get better,
we're all better off.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech coach Spike Dykes concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're connected to those other \RTexas\S teams. So, if we're
not playing those guys, I'm rooting for them,'' Dykes said. ``And
we haven't had a day like this in a long, long time. I think it's
neat to see that what goes around, comes around. We're always
fielding questions about how weak the Big 12 South is in relation
to the North. Maybe this helps in a deal like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to weekend victories by A&AMP;M and Baylor, South teams hold
a 6-4 lead over their North counterparts in Big 12 crossover games
this season. It's not a statistic that would raise an eyebrow in
Florida. But in Texas, it makes for an encouraging start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1407EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
