A1980 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX     10-12 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH FINDS NO RESPITE AT CORNERBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The heel feels fine, Cowboys cornerback Kevin
Smith said. That's not the problem.
</P>
<P>
   So what is?
</P>
<P>
   After Raghib Ismail beat him for a touchdown pass, Smith tried
to put it all in perspective after the Cowboys' 27-20 victory. A
consistent Steve Beuerlein plus increasing pressure will equal the
occasional coverage lapse, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that going into the game, I want to be aggressive, but
I can't be as aggressive as I want to be,'' Smith said. ``I just
have to deal with it. The key is not to give up and just don't give
up a touchdown. \RBeuerlein\S was finding his receivers today.''
</P>
<P>
   Beuerlein, who had his way most of the day against the Dallas
secondary, was 22-of-32 for 286 yards and three touchdowns. A long
gain on a Smith pass-interference call in the fourth quarter was
voided because of offsetting penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Dave Campo said that even though Smith
again took his lumps, this is not the time to panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, his biggest problem is that teams go after him
all the time because of what's going on, and because Deion Sanders
is on the other side,'' Campo said. ``This is all something that
has been created and we have to keep him out of those situations as
much as possible.''
Aikman checkup
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman said he will probably get
another X-ray for his broken left collarbone today.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman has been throwing without much pain. But he said it
``hurts a little bit,'' when he takes the snap from center.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays on his collarbone Oct. 5 did not show much improvement
from the original injury he suffered against the Denver Broncos
Sept. 13. He has said he probably won't return until the club's
Nov. 2 game against the Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   But a favorable examination could lead to Aikman suiting up as
the emergency quarterback against the Chicago Bears next weekend.
Adams grades out well
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Flozell Adams said he felt good about making his first
career start on the Cowboys offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did better than the average rookie,'' said Adams, who got
the start at right guard when Everett McIver went down to a knee
injury last week. ``I picked up everything they tried to throw at
me. I was ready for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line coach Hudson Houck had the best view of Adams'
battles with the interior of the Panthers defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flo did not have any penalties and there were no mental
breakdowns,'' Houck said. ``He wasn't intimidated by the situation
or by the people we were playing against.''
</P>
<P>
   Said veteran right tackle Erik Williams: ``Flo showed great
poise. He's going to be a great player in this league.''
The one that got away
</P>
<P>
   On his best day since taking over for Troy Aikman, Jason
Garrett's most memorable play nearly turned out to be his worst.
</P>
<P>
   On third-and-1 at the Carolina 16-yard line, Garrett sneaked for
would-be first-down yardage. But after he went down, the ball
popped out of the pile and bounced toward the Cowboys' sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Panthers cornerback Rod Smith recovered and ran 35 yards to the
Cowboys' 43-yard line. Three plays later, Steve Beuerlein completed
a 3-yard touchdown pass to William Floyd that cut the Cowboys' lead
to 27-20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Locking the ball down is one of the things I'm supposed to
do,'' Garrett explained. ``I saw a crease to the left and felt like
I had the ball locked down. It hit a helmet or a knee and that
dislodged it.''
Mathis comes up big
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys reserve cornerback Kevin Mathis made the most of his
limited time on the field with a team-record tying two fumble
recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, who plays in nickel situations, sparked the Cowboys to
their first lead of the game when he jumped on a fumble by Panthers
fullback William Floyd on the first drive of the third quarter. The
Cowboys turned it into a 6-yard touchdown pass from Jason Garrett
to Chris Warren.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis' second recovery late in the third quarter led to a
38-yard field goal, giving the Cowboys a 27-14 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Several Cowboys have recovered two fumbles in a game, the last
time was when Broderick Thomas did it against the Eagles in 1996.
On the defensive
</P>
<P>
   It was a strong showing by the Dallas defense. The run defense
held Carolina to just 29 rushing yards, a 1.3-yard-per-carry
average. A pass rush keyed by rookie Greg Ellis sacked Steve
Beuerlein three times. ``We made some mistakes, but once we lit the
light under the defensive line, we started getting to the
quarterback,'' Ellis said.
Big plays
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' offense produced several big gainers and big plays,
including a 32-yard run from Emmitt Smith and Jason Garrett passes
of 42 yards to Ernie Mills and 38 yards to Michael Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   But the day's best catch was 18 yards on a spectacular touchdown
reception by Mills on a fade route in the corner of the end zone.
``Jason made the throw where the defensive back couldn't get it and
only I could,'' Mills said.
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Michael Irvin had 146 yards receiving and Ernie Mills had 110,
giving the Cowboys two 100-yard receivers in the same
regular-season game for the first time since Irvin and Jay Novacek
did it on Sept. 12, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's six receptions moved him into a tie for 10th place in
the NFL all-time receiving list for career catches. He now has 699
receptions, the same as former Redskins wideout Gary Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's victory was the Cowboys' first over the Panthers.
Carolina had won the teams' first two meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Hennings' block of the extra point on the Panthers final
touchdown was the first for the Cowboys since Jim Jeffcoat blocked
one against the New York Giants on Dec. 16, 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
