<HEADER>
A1982 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     10-12 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY! HERE'S A HERO UNDER SECOND BASE!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you were setting out to find a stand-up guy, a role model, a
person you could point to and say to your kids, ``There, that's how
you should handle a difficult situation,'' the world of
professional sports would not be the first place you'd look.
</P>
<P>
   Today's millionaire sports stars seem to spend more time
whining, complaining and offering up alibis than they spend playing
the games that make them rich and famous.
</P>
<P>
   Any time some hot-shot athlete makes a mistake, in sport or in
life, it is always somebody else's fault. The athlete had a lousy
childhood, or he was treated unfairly by management, or his
self-esteem was damaged by unappreciative sports fans. If he drops
a ball, he says the sun got in his eyes. If he gets busted for
drugs or beating up his wife, he says the media blew the incident
out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   The alibi poster child for big-time sports these days is boxer
Mike Tyson, who bit off part of an opponent's ear because the
referee let the opponent get away with head-butting and who
recently snarled curses at licensing officials because the world
gives him no respect.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes' role model could well be the president of the
United States, who apparently believes he had a right to lie under
oath in a sexual harassment lawsuit because the plaintiff's lawyers
were mean to him.
</P>
<P>
   So. It surprised absolutely no one when a player for the New
York Yankees initially tried to duck the blame for a spectacular
foul-up that led to his team's 4-1 loss to the Cleveland Indians in
Game 2 of baseball's American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Quizzed by reporters after the game, second baseman Chuck
Knoblauch refused to accept responsibility for the damage done to
the Yankees when he opted to argue with an umpire rather than chase
down the ball after it hit a Cleveland runner in the back. While
Knoblauch popped his bubble gum and hollered at the ump _ with the
ball lying just a few feet away _ another Cleveland runner was
circling the bases and scoring the go-ahead run in the top of the
12th inning.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch said he didn't know where the ball was _ which was
probably true, since he didn't bother to look for it.
</P>
<P>
   No news here. Just another bratty ballplayer acting like a
world-class jerk.
</P>
<P>
   But wait.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that Knoblauch spent some time later that night
watching TV replays of his breathtaking blunder and finally
realized what most of the world had already known: His mistake was
inexcusable.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, a 30-year-old Houston native who was a baseball star
at Texas A&AMP;M in the late 1980s, met with reporters the next day.
Here's part of what he said, as quoted by The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
   ``I screwed up ... I should have went and gotten the ball,
regardless of what the umpire's call was.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch faced the music. And then some:
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to apologize to my teammates and my manager and all the
Yankees fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Can you believe it? He apologized. To his teammates, to his
manager, to ``all the Yankees fans.''
</P>
<P>
   When did you ever hear a sports star apologize to the fans _ to
the people who ultimately pay his mind-boggling salary?
</P>
<P>
   One other occasion comes to mind. When slugger Mark McGwire
failed to advance to the finals in the home-run derby at the 1998
All-Star Game, he apologized to the fans for disappointing them.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of humility and graciousness was typical of McGwire
throughout the season _ as it was for the Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa,
who competed with McGwire for the title of home-run king. McGwire
and Sosa were hounded by the public and by the media, day in and
day out, week after week, month after month _ and they handled
every moment with dignity and class.
</P>
<P>
   If we were looking for role models in the world of sports, we
found two of them in McGwire and Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   And now we add to the list Chuck Knoblauch, a stout-hearted
Texan who swallowed his pride and accepted responsibility for
letting down his team and its fans.
</P>
<P>
   Do you suppose the president has been following the baseball
playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
