<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1,200-YEAR-OLD TEMPLE OFFERS ORDER, OASIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MATSUMOTO, Japan _ Tucked into an unspoiled forest near the
Japan Alps in the central part of the country, Gofukuji Temple is a
retreat so natural in its beauty that it seems to have sprouted out
of the wilderness that surrounds it.
</P>
<P>
   With its simple wood-beam construction, thatched roof, and
weathered stone steps that ripple down the side of Mount Hachibuse,
the Buddhist temple was built to blend into its habitat, and
throughout its 1,200-year history it has offered worshipers a
bridge to nature and its contemplation.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting Gofukuji is like traveling back in time, past a pair of
bulls that represent beasts carrying scriptures from China that
fell to their knees at this site in 756. Today, it is easy to
forget that there is a bustling, modern downtown of 200,000 people
just 20 minutes' drive away. Perhaps that is why so many harried
city dwellers come here when they need some peace and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese are syncretic in their spirituality, mixing the
indigenous Shinto religion with the imported faiths of Buddhism,
Confucianism, and Christianity. Shinto grew out of the belief that
every natural form, rocks, trees, water, had a deity, or ``kami.''
Even today, in a nation that prides itself on its modernity and
high technology, animism and awe for the simplicity of nature still
guide many in their spiritual beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The coexistence of traditional and modern values in Japan is
obvious in the man who runs Gofukuji, Syuyu Otani, 49. Locals see
nothing contradictory about him, but foreign visitors are usually
surprised to learn that the chain-smoking, sake-drinking,
meat-eating, married jazz aficionado is a monk.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit, Otani was burning wooden tablets inscribed
with petitions as an offering. In another room, women in kimonos
were making a different sort of offering, but one aimed at
achieving the same peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Gofukuji is home to an annual ceremony by tea masters of the
region, and one day last month, visitors paid $22 apiece to serve
or be served tea.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese art of ``chado,'' or ``the way of tea,'' is a
highly stylized ritual that dates back to the eighth century, when
Buddhist monks used tea to stimulate meditation. Earlier still, tea
was introduced from China as a medicine, and tea dumplings were
offered to ancestors at the altar.
</P>
<P>
   By the 14th century, tea had become a refined pastime for the
nobility, who used expensive teacups to show off power and wealth.
The ceremony required tremendous discipline, and became part of
every samurai's training. In the late 1500s, history's most famous
tea master, Sen-no Rikkyu, refined it into a simple aesthetic,
using utensils that resembled nature.
</P>
<P>
   Tea teacher Michiko Arai, 60, says the ancient rite remains a
living art because it provides order and an oasis from worries _
something especially needed during the worst recession since World
War II. ``Japan is in a very tough situation now, politically and
economically, and tea gives people calmness and peace,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Simply stated, the kneeling server whips powdered green tea in
hot water, turns the cup so its design faces the guest, and
presents the tea with a bow.
</P>
<P>
   ``In modern times,'' said Arai, the tea teacher, ``even though
we have a tight budget, we can create simple food and simple
beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Indira A.R. Lakshmanan is the Globe's Asia bureau chief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
