<SLUG> BC-EIFFELTOWER-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARIS, TEXAS, ADDING COWBOY HAT TO ITS VERSION OF FRENCH TOWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS, Texas _ The French would ignite with anger if someone
dared cover their beloved Eiffel Tower with a giant, brightly
colored chapeau; but here in the northeast corner of Texas, it will
be a matter of civic pride when a glossy red cowboy hat is
carefully affixed atop the town's 65-foot Eiffel Tower model.
</P>
<P>
   In this Oklahoma-Arkansas corner of the state, folks are a
little more liberal with their tower. As in their namesake city,
Parisians here are proud of their tower, pleased with the work the
local Boiler Maker's Union did welding it together two years ago.
But they do not hold it in the same reverence as the French do
theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are other sights here. Legendary cattleman John
Chisum is buried here. And at Evergreen Cemetery, there is the
renowned Babcock Monument, a 12-foot statue of Jesus wearing cowboy
boots.
</P>
<P>
   The Paris, Texas, Eiffel Tower is much smaller than the
original, too. Here, kids can climb on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hat will give us a distinction,'' said hat creator Daon
Wall. ``We won't just have a little Eiffel Tower; we'll have one
with a hat on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lamar County Chamber of Commerce uses the Eiffel Tower as
part of its logo. Its tower has a red hat tilted on top. Wall said
he and Gary Vest, director of the chamber, often joked about
putting a hat on the replica, which stands near the town's civic
center, and Vest even contacted outside vendors to see if it could
be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called the people who built Big Tex for the State Fair,''
Vest said. ``They said, yes, they could build one out of
fiberglass. It would cost us $26,000 and that didn't cover the
installation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided against it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 60-year-old Wall knew he could build one, but his concrete
pipe business kept him too busy. But when he recently sold his
company and retired, he suddenly had the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Paris Iron and Metal and asked them if they wanted
to be a part of it,'' he said of the hat project. ``They said they
would provide the metal.''
</P>
<P>
   Wanting a deep, sleek coat of paint for the hat, Wall contacted
folks at Lone Star Collision Center and asked if they could provide
a good automotive paint job. The company said yes.
</P>
<P>
   Shurtleff-Gaharan, a metal fabrication contractor, rolled the
1/8-inch steel crown; Wall took the three-sixteenth-inch steel brim
back to his old company, now CSR-Wall, and rolled it.
</P>
<P>
   The hat stands 4 1/2 feet tall and has a brim that is 10 feet in
diameter. The hat is now on a flatbed trailer where Wall is putting
on the finishing touches, including a 6-inch-wide band that will be
painted white. When the hat is painted, local veterinarian Don
Riddle will add a 16-inch brass feather he made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody I went to was ready to pitch in,'' Wall said.
``Everyone I asked said yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall estimates that he has spent more than a month working on
the project. He began by taking a Stetson hat and ``scaling it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just blew up the scale and started,'' he said. ``I'll have
it to the paint shop soon, and we're planning to put it up Oct.
19.''
</P>
<P>
   Vest said he has been in contact with some people from France,
and at first they were a little upset at the notion of covering the
Texas tower with a cowboy hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've kind of warmed up to the idea, now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Paris, Texas, was formed in 1845, but there is no
documentation to show exactly how it got its name. References to
the area as ``Paris'' go back to as early as 1841.
</P>
<P>
   Historians are certain, however, that this Paris was named for
Paris, France. The cities now have a sister-city relationship.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
