<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2032 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-12 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT DISCLOSURE IS OWED BY CELLUCCI TO THE VOTERS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In politics, a pledge can be more dangerous to the
candidate who takes it than it is for the candidate who refuses.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one knows that better than former President Bush, who
made his famous ``Read my lips, no new taxes'' pledge campaigning
against Michael Dukakis, only to end up agreeing to one of the
largest tax increases in history.
</P>
<P>
   And in this year's race for governor of Massachusetts, nobody
should know that better than Acting Governor Paul Cellucci, who has
had problems with his own tax pledge, and apparently with his own
personal loan pledges.
</P>
<P>
   While Cellucci's no new tax pledge, a continuation of his
predecessor, William F. Weld's, promise, sounds attractive to the
electorate, it is also a costly pledge for taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   With an obvious need of money to pay the state's bills, the
state's borrowing cap, set at $900 million by the Weld-Cellucci
administration, was raised by Cellucci to $1 billion. Even with
that increase, the state still exceeded this $1 billion cap by $233
million.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it would have been better if, rather than have the state
go deeper in debt, Cellucci had advocated a modest tax increase. In
difficult economic times, some economists argue that a minimal tax
increase may be more fiscally responsible than significantly
increasing the state's debt.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cellucci boasts about his $1 billion tax cut, and barely
mentions the state's record debt of $13.9 billion, which he helped
to set.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's problems with debt are not only on the state level,
but on a personal level.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1996 report by the Globe, Cellucci owed $750,000,
with nearly $70,000 of it on his credit cards. Cellucci explained
his debt by saying he had given up his law practice while he still
had education expenses, home improvement costs, and other expenses.
Thus, he said, he had to borrow money and exercise credit. But, he
added, he never missed a loan or credit card payment, and his
assets exceed his liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many people found that level of personal debt troubling;
Cellucci has since refused to elaborate on how he ended up so far
in the red, repeatedly rejecting requests for interviews on the
topic.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Cellucci said at a State House press conference that he
detailed his financial situation in required filings with the State
Ethics Commission, as well as released his state and federal income
tax returns for each of his years in office. During the last four
years, the Globe reported, Cellucci or his real estate business
sold property to reduce some of his personal debt.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a lot of questions remained unanswered about the size of his
debt, despite the fact that Cellucci and his wife declared for the
past four years an average adjusted gross annual income of
$184,175, and a gross annual income of nearly $100,000 a year in
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   As earlier reported, Cellucci still owes more than $100,000 for
a bank loan obtained without any collateral. And, according to the
1996 Globe report, Cellucci was paying nearly $5,000 a month merely
to cover the interest on his accumulated debt _ an amount
approaching his own annual salary from the state, after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's debt issues have not been raised by his opponent,
Attorney General Scott Harshbarger, but there are supporters, as
well as members of the media, who feel Cellucci has a public
obligation to clear up questions, and remove any doubts, about
possible conflicts of interests.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the banks from which he's borrowed money, for example,
also come under the state's banking regulations. Some critics ask
whether the Cellucci administration can truly be an independent
regulator of the same banks that probably could have sent him into
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci can end lingering questions by disclosing the full
terms of his agreements with the banks that hold his loans and
credit card debts.
</P>
<P>
   Some people could argue that a personal debt, regardless of the
amount, should remain a private matter. But the fact that
Cellucci's debts were filed with the State Ethics Commission has,
in effect, placed them in the public arena. One reason for the
filing is to determine whether there are any public issues that
need to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Cellucci has been prompt about paying his loans and
credit card debts. But some critics may ask whether he stuck to his
original payment plan, or whether it was renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Cellucci's debts become a big issue in the remaining
weeks of this campaign remains to be seen. But the fact that
Cellucci had filed some information on his loans with the ethics
commission has made the issue fair game for Harshbarger and his
running-mate, Warren Tolman, if they choose to raise it.
</P>
<P>
   By refusing to be interviewed on the issue, Cellucci may be
creating new suspicions. The best way to assure voters he has
nothing to hide is to fully disclose his loan arrangements and
answer questions from his opponent and the media. If his opponent
had the same debt, Cellucci might well be the first to argue that
the public has a right to know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
