<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2037 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-12 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINGRICH, LOTT PINCH PENNIES ON POOR YOUNG WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; No sex scandal today. Instead: a real crime.
</P>
<P>
   While Congress was preoccupied with the details of an
impeachment inquiry that could preoccupy it well into next year,
its leaders were playing penny-wise games with President Clinton
over the first serious attempt in a generation to tackle one of the
prime causes of poverty and chronic unemployment _ high school
dropouts.
</P>
<P>
   What was at issue was the extent to which Newt Gingrich and
Trent Lott would renege on an earlier commitment to the 500,000
young people who leave high school every year, never to return.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a sweeping change in the country's jerry-built
job-training maze earlier this year _ putting nearly all the scores
of individual federal programs under one roof as direct aid to the
states _ $1 billion was authorized for each of the next four years
to go after the toughest customers of them all. On the way out of
town, however, Gingrich and Lott were playing games with outgoing
White House chief of staff Erskine Bowles over whether the actual
amount would be $150 million or $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's House, which can always find millions for another
Clinton probe, came up with zero. Indeed, for just the documented
amount of military spending pork that goes to Lott's Mississippi
and Gingrich's Georgia district, the full billion would have been
no sweat.
</P>
<P>
   The shame here is that Labor Secretary Alexis Herman has fixed
on an idea that everybody in the manpower field knows works. The
idea, oversimplified, is to work through local initiatives around
the country that saturate targeted communities with employment and
training services. In classic, ``Third Way'' fashion, however, the
idea is NOT to set up a program from here and spread money around
broadly defined metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Herman's idea is to use federal money on local efforts,
targeted like lasers on truly distressed communities where the
young people in trouble are concentrated, and further strengthen
them.
</P>
<P>
   With very little notice, the Labor Department under Herman's
predecessor, Bob Reich, began pilot projects two years ago in Los
Angeles, Houston, and Chicago. It is now completing the start-up
process in three more places _ Boston, New York City's famously
challenging South Bronx, and rural Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, as everywhere, the targeted neighborhoods of Roxbury
and South Boston are meant to be saturated, meaning that services
are available to every single jobless kid (aged 16-24) the managers
can find. And by linking up all the existing human services
operations, as well as business's Private Industry Council, the
probation officers and juvenile justice workers and even the
housing authority, the idea is that every dropout snared in this
net becomes the responsibility of adults who know him or her
personally.
</P>
<P>
   To absolutely no one's surprise, this kind of intensive
involvement with kids works. With whatever new money Gingrich and
Lott end up providing, Herman will be able to travel the country
finding more locally based gems to empower. As also fits Third Way
thinking _ activist but decentralized and intolerant of failure _
each initiative will run on a contract after which it will be
expected to be self-sustaining with local and business support.
</P>
<P>
   Herman was able to get all this going by pouncing on the
flip-side of the debate on Clinton's stalled effort to get special
authority to negotiate trade expansion treaties.
</P>
<P>
   As President Kennedy recognized 36 years ago when he began the
modern era of liberalization, Herman believes one of the
obligations of government is to assist those who are going to be
adversely affected in a global economy, where jobs can move almost
as fast as money.
</P>
<P>
   To make her case this year, Herman had a killer statistic. The
roughly half-million young people who drop out for good each year
just happen to match the 500,000 technology jobs going begging in
the US, and about to be filled under special legislative authority
by imported talent, thanks to our still-underperforming schools.
</P>
<P>
   But there is, of course, much more information that ties
education level to economic success. The national jobless rate may
remain below five percent, but it is above 20 percent among
16-to-24-year-old dropouts, and above 10 percent for young people
with only a high school diploma. In dollars, the equation is
simple: For working dropouts, average earnings are $15,000; for
high school grads only, $22,000; with some college, $25,000; with a
college diploma, $38,000; and with an advanced degree, $61,000.
</P>
<P>
   And, for good measure, this from the Justice Department: two out
of three male state prison inmates are dropouts; and some 30
percent of black males aged 20-29, and eight percent of whites are
either in the clink or on probation or parole.
</P>
<P>
   Case closed. As Herman told me recently, this is either a
permanent drag on our society and economy or a potentially large
tax base. Maybe during the TV time-outs of the impeachment
hearings, Gingrich and Lott can do a little better next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
