<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARSHBARGER'S FAULTY CAMPAIGN ASIDE, HE CAN STILL WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every campaign has its low point. This week, Scott Harshbarger's
gubernatorial campaign reached its nadir.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the debate Monday night, although that was widely
viewed as a defeat for Harshbarger. And it wasn't just the new
Opinion Dynamics Corp. poll (conducted for Mass Insight, a Boston
business group, prior to the debate) showing Harshbarger trailing
Paul Cellucci by eight percentage points. And it wasn't just the
belated endorsements of ranking Democrats, whose support under
normal circumstances would have long since been tendered.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than that. This week, a consensus began to form
among the political cognoscenti that Harshbarger's campaign had no
strategy or purpose beyond the candidate's ambition to move up the
political ladder. No one, except for a few Republican consultants,
said this publicly, of course. But privately the assessments were
scathing.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates for high public office need three ``stories'' to make
their campaigns comprehensible. They need a ``personal'' story that
gives voters a sense of who they are. They need a ``political''
story that shows voters that they can win and accomplish at least
some of what they propose. And they need a ``policy'' story that
gives voters a road map of what actions they would likely take, if
elected. Harshbarger's campaign lacks these three stories.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by the Boston Phoenix what ``one thing he wishes more
people knew about him,'' Harshbarger's response bordered on the
unintelligible. ``I mean, I think that, you know, I think this has
been the great challenge of this _ and, and probably the great
challenge _ and, and an appropriate _ and a recognition of what
running for governor is. I think people know _ the people really
want to know who you are. If there's one thing, I'd like people to
know where I came from.'' He comes from Pennsylvania. He needs a
better personal story than that.
</P>
<P>
   His political story isn't much better. Harshbarger's
fund-raising has lagged behind Cellucci's despite minimal primary
opposition. The belated endorsements this week by Ira Jackson,
Chris Gabrieli, House Speaker Thomas Finneran, and the
Massachusetts congressional delegation only served to underscore
doubts about the depth of Harshbarger's political support. And
Harshbarger's first wave of general election television advertising
seemed almost generic; your double-talking opponent goes here.
Veteran politicians know a good campaign when they see one.
Harshbarger's campaign strikes most professionals as disorganized
and amateurish.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of a policy story is the most surprising missing
element of his campaign. Harshbarger has known for a long time that
he would be the Democratic nominee. He has had more than enough
time to make a substantial case for his candidacy. He has had more
than enough time to hone a serious critique of Cellucci's
stewardship. So far, however, he has not really moved beyond
sloganeering (``Labors agenda is my agenda'') and not very smart
sloganeering at that.
</P>
<P>
   It is a rule of thumb in politics that attorneys general make
terrible gubernatorial candidates. It is the opinion of most
Democrats that Harshbarger has to date been a terrible
gubernatorial candidate. Having watched his campaign squander so
many opportunities and so much time, many Democratic operatives
wonder if his candidacy can be saved.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is yes. Harshbarger is still capable of defeating
Cellucci. Both the Mass Insight poll and the most recent Boston
Globe poll show Cellucci garnering roughly 45 percent of the likely
electorate. That's below where incumbent governors on the road to
re-election usually are at this stage of the campaign. Cellucci's
colleagues in Pennsylvania, Michigan, New York, and Texas are all
running well north of 50 percent in their reelection campaigns.
They're certain to be reelected in November. Cellucci is not.
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains that Massachusetts is the most Democratic state
in the nation, giving Harshbarger a significant homefield
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, Cellucci is vulnerable to intelligent attack. There is
a palpable sense that the combined Weld-Cellucci administration has
run out of gas. And there is a widespread perception among voters
that Cellucci is not nearly as good a politician as his
predecessor. Those are two lines of attack that will fall on
receptive ears. Harshbarger needs only to retool and simplify his
campaign messages to regain the offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, as former state Senate President Kevin Harrington said
this week, if Harshbarger wins in November, he and state Senate
President Tom Birmingham will control the political agenda for the
next four years. If Cellucci wins, he and House Speaker Finneran
will control the agenda for the next four years. Those are two very
different agendas. Democratic interest groups that prefer
Birmingham to Finneran have a real stake in electing Harshbarger.
For these reasons alone, the gubernatorial race remains too close
to call.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
