<HEADLINE>
COLON CANCER'S MISSED OPPORTUNITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Sapna Syngal leans over 59-year-old Andres Hernandez, who is
curled on his side in the darkened procedure room. ``How are you
doing, Mr. Hernandez?'' she asks. ``Fine,'' he mumbles through a
medication-induced haze.
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, only two or three times during the 25-minute
procedure does Hernandez grimace with discomfort, even though
Syngal has pushed a flexible probe tipped with camera, light
source, and tiny instruments deep into his belly.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching the upper end of Hernandez' colon, Syngal reverses
direction. As she slowly withdraws the probe, she examines each of
the 35 inches of its glistening pink surface on a large color TV
monitor. This ``fantastic voyage'' pays off; she finds two small
polyps _ precursors of potential malignancies _ and painlessly
snips them off.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, Syngal sharply reduced the chances that
Hernandez will be one of the 1.3 million Americans destined to
suffer colorectal cancer in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Colonoscopy is undoubtedly the most dreaded common diagnostic
test. Who doesn't squirm at the very idea of it? But no other
procedure can actually prevent a major cancer as well as detect it,
with near-100 percent accuracy, at a stage almost guaranteed to be
curable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody should die of colon cancer, and nobody should be afraid
to ask their doctor about screening,'' says Dr. Peter McNally of
Evans Army Hospital in Colorado Springs, a spokesman for the
American College of Gastroenterology, which is meeting in Boston.
``It's better to be embarrassed and submit to screening tests than
to die of colon cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The claim that every last colon cancer death can be prevented
may be an overstatement. Some cases occur at younger ages, when
annual screening is only recommended for individuals who are are at
high risk because they have a strong family history of the disease,
previous colon polyps, or inflammatory bowel disease. Think of New
York Yankees outfielder Darryl Strawberry, 36, who underwent colon
cancer surgery this month, or Jay Monahan, the NBC legal
commentator and husband of ``Today Show'' host Katie Couric, who
died of colon cancer this year at age 42.
</P>
<P>
   But the general point is valid for the vast majority of people.
In combination with a few other simpler and cheaper screening
tests, colonoscopy has the potential to slash the number of deaths
from colorectal cancer by at least half, according to a recent
panel convened by the American Gastroenterological Association.
</P>
<P>
   That's a big deal, considering that cancer of the colon and
rectum kills 56,500 Americans a year _ more than breast cancer
(27,100) or prostate cancer (39,200). Only lung cancer kills more
(160,100). And both sexes are affected equally, with incidence
rates climbing sharply after age 50.
</P>
<P>
   For its enormous impact, colorectal cancer gets
disproportionately little attention. ``Colon cancer has gotten a
lot less press than breast or prostate cancer, maybe because people
are uncomfortable talking about it,'' Syngal says. ``There are a
lot of misperceptions. Women think it's a man's disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, few people appreciate how much they can do to
prevent colon cancer or nab it when it's curable. No other major
cancer is so amenable to such preemption &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental message is that we need to screen more
people,'' says Dr. Robert Mayer of Dana-Farber Cancer Institute in
Boston, a leading colon cancer treatment specialist.
</P>
<P>
   To appreciate the potential of annual screening, beginning at
age 50, consider this:
</P>
<P>
   _Three of every four large-bowel cancers occur in people with no
known risk factors.
</P>
<P>
   _The average age at diagnosis is 67. But the disease almost
always grows slowly, with pre-malignant polyps typically arising
five to 10 years before cancer is diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   _By age 50, 30 percent of individuals have precancerous growths
called adenomas in their lower intestines, a rate that rises to 50
percent by age 65.
</P>
<P>
   All this presents both a challenge and an opportunity to catch
most colorectal cancers well before they have penetrated the bowel
wall and spread to nearby lymph nodes or organs, such as the liver.
Once this has happened, the chances of being alive five years after
the diagnosis drop sharply _ to about 70 percent if lymph nodes are
affected, less than 10 percent with more distant spread.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms, experts say, don't provide enough warning. As the
American Cancer Society has said for years, blood in the stool,
abdominal pain, or change in bowel habits are warning signs of
colorectal cancer. But most bowel cancers cause no symptoms until
they're beyond _ sometimes well beyond _ the early, curable stage.
</P>
<P>
   This is what happened with Darryl Strawberry, whose colon tumor
was painful and walnut-sized when it was removed. On Friday, his
doctors announced the cancer had spread to one lymph node,
necessitating chemotherapy and lowering his long-term survival odds
to about 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, most patients wait until they have symptoms,''
says Dr. Robert Kurtz, chief of gastroenterology at Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York City. ``The best chance
of finding an early-stage colon cancer is through regular screening
of patients who are asymptomatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Screening for bowel cancer is fairly straightforward, but fairly
few people in the cancer-prone years undergo it _ or are even
offered it by their physicians. The US Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention recently reported that only 26 percent of Americans
over age 50 have been tested for blood in their stool within the
past three years _ the first-line screening test.
</P>
<P>
   Only 29 percent had had a colonoscopy within the past five
years, the CDC found. Rates of both were lower among women and
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get primary care physicians to think about colon
cancer screening, and we have to get patients to ask for it,''
Kurtz says.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what to ask for, if you're over 50 and of ``average
risk,'' meaning there's been no colorectal cancer or precancerous
polyp among first-degree relatives (sibling, parent, or child), no
personal history of polyps, and you do not suffer from inflammatory
bowel disease. (Those with any of these risk factors should get the
same tests, but earlier and more frequently.)
</P>
<P>
   First, get an annual fecal occult blood test, a simple way to
determine if there is any trace of blood in the stool, which might
indicate the presence of a precancerous polyp or an early
malignancy. The test, which costs only $10 to $15, consists of a
set of cards on which to smear a small sample from three successive
bowel movements; a laboratory determines if there's any blood
present.
</P>
<P>
   The test isn't perfect. It fails to detect polyps if they don't
happen to be bleeding at the time the test is done, and it can
falsely indicate the presence of blood. ``If you screen 100 people,
you typically would get about four positives,'' says Ronald
Schoengold of SmithKline Diagnostics, which makes the widely used
Hemoccult tests. ``Of those, two are likely to have either a large
polyp or a cancer, and two would be considered false positives.''
</P>
<P>
   However, done annually, the occult blood test is likely to pick
up a problem at an early stage. Using the test could reduce colon
cancer deaths by 33 percent, the Gastroentological Association
panel estimated. For every 100,000 people screened, that would mean
1,330 fewer deaths.
</P>
<P>
   To pick up polyps missed by the occult blood test, experts
recommend a procedure called flexible sigmoidoscopy every five
years. This is similar to colonoscopy, but it reaches only the
lower third of the large intestine; the theory is that if polyps
are found there, they might also be present further up.
</P>
<P>
   Sigmoidoscopy is a doctor's-office procedure costing $80 to $100
(compared to $300 to $1,000 for colonoscopy), and it doesn't
require heavy sedation or as rigorous a purge of the entire bowel
beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Combining annual occult blood testing and every-five-years
sigmoidoscopy could cut the yearly incidence of colon cancer from
4,988 cases to 1,901 cases for every 100,000 individuals screened,
and prevent 1,609 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   When an occult blood test is positive or a sigmoidoscopy finds
precancerous polyps, that's a signal to do a complete colonoscopy.
A routine sigmoidoscopy exam is what brought Hernandez, a Mission
Hill resident, to the Brigham and Women's Hospital last week for
colonoscopy.
</P>
<P>
   Although relatively expensive, colonoscopy is the only proven
way to prevent colon cancer and catch it early. Studies show it
costs about $25,000 for each year of life saved, compared to
$30,000 for mammograms to detect early breast cancer. Recognizing
the cost-effectiveness of colonoscopy and other colorectal cancer
screening, Medicare began paying for it this year. Harvard Pilgrim
Health Care, New England's largest HMO, pays for it whenever
doctors think it's necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colon cancer screening is more expensive than mammography, but
it's a lot more effective,'' Syngal says.
</P>
<P>
   As for the discomfort, both doctors and patients say it's almost
always less than people anticipate. (The worst part, many say, is
the need to restrict food and to take powerful laxatives the day
before.)
</P>
<P>
   Ask Andres Hernandez. ``It didn't hurt,'' he says. ``It's like a
stomach full of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Richard A. Knox is a member of the Globe staff. His e-mail
address is: knox(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
