<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2062 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-NUREYEV-BOS &LR;      10-12 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NUREYEV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LORD OF THE DANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Born on the Trans-Siberian Express. Could there be any more
dramatic start to a life? And it only became more so. Rudolf
Nureyev, born on that train in 1938, was theatrical onstage and
off, projecting such a huge image in the theater that people
meeting him out of it were often surprised at how slight he was. A
5-foot, 8-inch wisp, he willed himself into looking larger. Before
him, Soviet male dancers performed with their heels barely off the
floor. Nureyev rose to a very high demi-pointe, heels as high as
they could get without his standing on the tips of his toes. He
made himself seem taller _ and also more elegant, competing with
the ballerinas he partnered instead of deferring to them, goading
even Margot Fonteyn to ever-greater heights, until theirs became
the most legendary partnership in the history of dance. Nureyev,
who died in 1993, was not just the most famous dancer since
Nijinsky; like Nijinsky, he loudly asserted the importance of the
male in an art form dominated by the female.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think that by now there would be nothing more to say about
the career of the first of the modern era's dancer-defectors. Not
so. The nervy Nureyev filled his autobiography _ written, with
help, when he was just 24 _ with misleading information that made
for a more interesting story. Most subsequent books have been heavy
on hagiography and luscious photographs. Diane Solway's new
``Nureyev: His Life'' comes as corrective and amplification. A New
York journalist, Solway also wrote the 1994 ``A Dance Against Time:
The Brief Brilliant Life of a Joffrey Dancer,'' about a less famous
dancer, Edward Stierle, who, like Nureyev, died of AIDS. She spent
five years on what is the fullest Nureyev biography to date,
conducting interviews in seven languages, gaining access to
previously classified Soviet documents that explain the dancer's
KGB-provoked 1961 defection, quoting skeptical and even scathing
reviews along with the raves.
</P>
<P>
   Her labor was worth it. This is an engrossing book; even at 550
pages (without notes and index), it doesn't begin to lag until very
near the end. Solway digs beneath the superficialities _ Nureyev's
late start, his flamboyant temperament, his rootless career _ and
explains his compulsion to dance virtually until he dropped dead.
</P>
<P>
   Her account of his early life is moving without being
melodramatic. To his first day of kindergarten, Nureyev wore his
sister's coat and no shoes, because his family was too poor to
afford them. The child grew into a man who owned half a dozen homes
and a trio of islands off Italy's Amalfi coast. By then he could
afford not only shoes, but his own desalination plant.
</P>
<P>
   Solway has the luxury of space to tell us about Nureyev actually
living with a London dance critic who reviewed his performances,
about his great romance with Danish dancer Erik Bruhn, about his
nasty anti-Semitic remarks, and the controversy he caused in the
gay community by never publicly announcing he had AIDS. The one
thing you could always count on with Nureyev was that he'd stir
things up.
</P>
<P>
   However storied his career, it also had great disappointments.
The greatest was being shunned by George Balanchine, whom he
idolized: Balanchine, though, was vehemently against stars, and
Nureyev was the brightest of them all. Balanchine encouraged team
spirit and loyalty; Nureyev was a loner who wandered the world.
While he dabbled in modern dance and new works, and in the few
Balanchine ballets that came his way, it was in the 19th-century
classics _ ``Giselle,'' ``Swan Lake,'' ``Le Corsaire'' _ that he
shone. In his prime, Nureyev routinely received half-hour standing
ovations for making those warhorses thrilling. Solway explains how
he did it: ``In calling attention to the difficulty of a step, he
telegraphed not only his own excitement at carrying it off but the
notion that dancing itself was a risky business.''
</P>
<P>
   His contribution to the art was not only his own dancing, but
sparking that of others, starting with Fonteyn, the Royal Ballet's
prima, and continuing with the Royal's men. Before Nureyev landed
with this company that came closest to giving him a permanent home,
its gentlemen were too gentle. Nureyev gave them a jump-start. As
director of the Paris Opera Ballet, a hidebound and hierarchical
enterprise when he arrived, Nureyev restored the company to the
position of preeminence it still holds. It was Parisian dancing
that first inspired Russian ballet; Nureyev returned the favor.
Just as he'd broken the rules in Russia _ refusing to wear the
traditional puffy breeches he called ``lampshades'' over his
tights, cutting out unintelligible mime _ he scandalized Parisians
by quickly promoting young talent over Paris Opera dancers he felt
were past their prime.
</P>
<P>
   His rent-a-company attitude provoked resentment from troupes who
felt he'd made them into living scenery, pushed to the back so he
could monopolize center stage. He'd regularly leave ballerinas in
the lurch: When displeased, he'd offer his partner a single finger
for support rather than his whole hand. ``Nureyev, Leave Canadian
Ballet Alone'' was the headline on a 1975 article by Canadian
critic John Fraser. Boston Ballet was among the troupes he
``honored'' in the 1980s, and its dancers were often demoralized at
serving as his backdrop. But in his staging of ``Don Quixote'' for
the company, Nureyev roused Boston to give some of its best-ever
performances. In a revival of the ballet after his death, the
dancers looked comatose by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   What is Nureyev's legacy? His efforts at original choreography,
acting in films, and conducting orchestras weren't notably
successful. He wasn't a meticulous dance technician like
Baryshnikov. He was, however, a workaholic who was obsessed with
details down to the last stitch on a costume. He certainly brought
ballet out of the realm of the connoisseur and into the wider
world, appearing on the covers of weekly news magazines and
whipping up his fans in rock-star style. He helped popularize
ballet, but perhaps not permanently. In America, balletomania has
been on the decline since Nureyev's glory years.
</P>
<P>
   A wealthy man obsessed with avoiding taxes, he left an estate
worth millions to two dance foundations Solway criticizes for
failing to make the kind of ``bold artistic statement'' that their
creator was famous for. ``Rather than honor Nureyev's
forward-looking spirit,'' she writes, ``perhaps through major
commissions to new choreographers, the American foundation chose in
1997 to underwrite a Bolshoi Ballet production of the full-length
version of `Le Corsaire' by the Boston Ballet,'' a production that
proved one of the worst 19th-century revivals in the company's
history.
</P>
<P>
   In his last years, weakened by AIDS, Nureyev was as pathetic as
the sad clown Petrouchka. It was painful to watch him hobble
through works he'd once commanded. He refused not only to give up
dancing, but also to give up the most challenging works in the
repertory. When, at age 50, Nureyev was finally invited to dance
with the New York City Ballet _ not by Balanchine but by his
successor, Peter Martins _ he was cast in the relatively placid
``Orpheus'' when the part he'd longed for was the far more
demanding ``Apollo.'' Solway has a perceptive explanation for this,
too. Nureyev, she reminds us, was always more interested in what he
couldn't do than what he could.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
