<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2067 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-COMMUNIST-BOS &LR;      10-12 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-COMMUNIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE READ MENACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Biography is a dubious treasure for fiction writers. Besieged by
the world around them, they are presumed to eschew it in favor of
the imagination _ preferring the province of artistic license to
the more earthly, lead-footed realm we think of as fact. The
fiction writer (says the purists' theory) utilizes reality only in
order to transcend it. Thus we are not supposed to care that Emma
Bovary was modeled after Flaubert's mistress, or that Bellow
extrapolated his tragic poet Humboldt from Delmore Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, especially, are not supposed to care, or even notice:
Calling attention to fact in the midst of fiction is considered
gossip, or at least bad form; and it usually does the novel or
story little literary service to trace its biographical origins. If
the writer has done his or her job correctly, making silk from a
sow's ear, then it won't much matter what the barnyard critter was
to begin with. But when the fiction produced is merely roman a
clef, transparent to the point of its own demise, reality itself
has been the culprit _ invading, often destroying, the harder work
of the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Roth has made great mischief over the years insinuating
his alter ego into his fiction, bestowing Nathan Zuckerman with a
Rothian self-consciousness, turning reviewers into pretzels over
whether or not the stories therein are actually ``true.'' He has
brilliantly inserted details of his own life (the Halcion-induced
breakdown of the protagonist of ``Operation Shylock,'' for
instance) into his novels, making use of what he knows firsthand to
infuse the fiction with depth and awareness _ a kind of
post-Joycean articulation of consciousness. When Roth does this act
of literary camouflage well, nobody does it better; line for line,
there is scarcely a smarter writer in America.
</P>
<P>
   But he has not done it well in ``I Married a Communist,'' which
has a valuable center marred by wooden and neglected character
development _ and by, one must assume, personal invective, since
the villainess at its center so closely resembles the actress
Claire Bloom, Roth's partner of some two decades. Their acrimonious
split a few years ago was followed by Bloom's pathos-ridden 1996
memoir, ``Leaving a Doll's House,'' which detailed Roth's emotional
control over her and his cold insistence that she toss out her
teenage daughter to make room for him and his writerly ways. But
Roth didn't suffer nearly so badly in Bloom's kiss-and-purge
account as he does here, by his own hand. The ghastly look-alikes
in ``I Married a Communist'' _ a failed, hollow actress named Eve
Frame and her pathologically selfish daughter, Sylphid _ so
overwhelm the novel that its larger plot seems like mere
scaffolding by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Which is partly to say that there are actually two stories going
on in this novel; the larger, which engages Roth's full-throttle
intelligence, involves the ruin of a radio actor during the
anti-communist witch hunts of the 1950s. Ira Ringold is a giant of
a man, a Newark kid from a troubled family who grew up under the
care of his older brother to be 6-foot-6, deep-voiced, and
passionately committed to whatever cause got to him first. The
brother, Murray, escaped their past by heading for the light of
knowledge; when he became a high school English teacher, he found
art to believe in and kids to save on the way up. Ira, his wounds
less sublimated and his brawn more imposing, became a ditch-digger
and a rabble-rouser _ what he didn't learn in school, he got at the
knee of the party-line leftists he met in the Army during World War
II. He took that instruction to a factory line in Chicago, then to
the streets, possessing the class roots, the timbre, and the
rhetoric to organize the rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   And what a Bolshevik he was! Roth has infused ``I Married a
Communist'' with the heart and soul of the Old Left; from the
Communist Party's internecine struggles after the war to the
tragicomic passions of adoring the proletariat, the novel possesses
a historical authenticity resonant with authority. Discovered by a
radio producer while fund-raising for the union (with that bulk, he
did a mean Abe Lincoln imitation), Ira eventually makes his way
into radio _ becoming a mouthpiece, as it were, for a soon-targeted
liberal show called ``The Free and the Brave.'' Rube turned radio
star, he is no match for the urbane, thrice-divorced Eve Frame, who
finds in Ira the requisite brute she so longs to tame. Once
ensconced in her New York salon on West 11th Street _ a place of
high life and high manners _ Ira becomes the reluctant witness to
Eve's hysterical inadequacies: her self-hating anti-Semitism, her
unhealthy attachment to her daughter, a wanting of character that
will ultimately be her, and his, undoing.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Ira's rise and fall is relayed some 40 years later
by Murray Ringold to his former student, Roth's Zuckerman; a chance
meeting near Zuckerman's isolated home in Western Massachusetts has
reunited them for a few days. So the narration of the novel is
shared between them: Murray remembering his younger brother's
wrenching story, Zuckerman reflecting on the man who, for a while,
became one of his mentors as the young Zuckerman formed a life.
This joint retelling authenticates the story as well as enhancing
it: A good liberal who believed in Shakespeare instead of ideology,
Murray is an eminently sane and reliable narrator; writer
Zuckerman, who was only a young bit player in Ira's complicated
life, gets to filter the tale through his usual bittersweet
sensibility. Like Swede Levov's angry brother in ``American
Pastoral,'' Murray only wanted to save his sibling from himself.
And as with the plummet from grace that belonged to ``American
Pastoral,'' the real miscreant at the center of this novel turns
out to be the force of history.
</P>
<P>
   That ``I Married a Communist'' forms another piece of a loosely
woven intellectual series (along with ``Sabbath's Theatre'' and
``American Pastoral'') is confirmed by a sentence play buried in
all three books; here, it's about Ira's need to change the world.
The cruel backfire of that need, personal and universal, with all
its attendant yearnings, isn't revealed until the novel's final
pages, which are of such depth and eloquent wisdom they almost make
up for the book's failings. But Roth should have known to leave out
his own merciless insights about betrayal, at least so far as they
result in making Eve and Sylphid caricatured demons whose misdoings
don't work with the rest of the story. They're tacked on like some
larger-than-life shadows of hobgoblins; as with Ira's Stalinist
rages, the indictment of them vacillates between shrill and dull.
``I Married a Communist'' shouldn't have to suffer so much because
of this mother-daughter duo, but it does. If Roth had put half that
misguided passion into his other characters _ particularly Ira, but
also a few inspired walk-ons _ he might have had the book he (or at
least we) desired.
</P>
<P>
   Scavengers of Roth's personal life will find much here to dine
on; literary Rothians, too, will delight in certain highlights _ a
visit to a taxidermist, a wonderful screed by an English Lit mentor
of Zuckerman's, a shimmeringly intelligent evocation of
Shakespeare. I was left feeling forlorn: missing the triumphant
brilliance of Roth, especially in those gorgeous final pages, when
Zuckerman leaves behind the cruel bargains of life, and turns his
sights toward unblemished skies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
