<HEADLINE>
`X FILES' MORE LIKE ZZZ; `W.C. FIELDS' HAS LEGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES:  &UR; ``The X Files''  &LR; _ The big screen didn't enlarge
the scope of one of television's best series. Instead of creating
spook-ier bits of paranoia and alien alienation, this feature was
like a 48-minute episode stretched out. We expected more and got
less.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``W. &LR;  &UR; C. Fields Collection'' &LR;  _ I hate to sound like an old
fogy, but these Fields films are some of the best comedies on
video. ``It's a Gift,'' ``You Can't Cheat an Honest Man,'' and
``Million Dollar Legs'' form a triumverate of classic cinema. The
latter, co-written by Joseph L. Mankiewicz, features Fields as the
president of Klopstokia, and includes visual and verbal gags at
their best. (By the way, this 1932 release has nothing in common
with the dismal 1939 Betty Grable film with the same title.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ULTIMATE GUIDE: The ``Facets Movie Lovers Video Guide'' is an
indispensable reference for videophiles. Priced at $15.95, the
350-page book features a wide variety of lists for a list-happy
readership. Everything from the Vatican's recommendations (does the
pope watch all these movies?) to cult classics are enhanced by
dozens of photos. To order call (800) 248-7323.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN'S HOURS: On Dec. 1, Jim Henson's ``Bear in the Big Blue
House'' will be released in four volumes. Episodes include
``Dancin' the Day Away,'' ``Listen Up,'' ``Home Is Where the Bear
Is,'' ``Friends For Life,'' ``Big Little Visitor,'' ``I Need a
Little Help Today,'' and ``Lost Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
