<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BELOVED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPRAH, WITH FEELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody wanted to see ``Beloved,'' Toni Morrison's Pulitzer
Prize-winning novel, turned into a movie. Not the literary
establishment, not Hollywood, not Morrison herself. She couldn't
see how her dense, elliptical novel about the devastating effects
of slavery could be turned into a stream of film images that would
do justice to her dark, primal hymn to survival. Nobody saw
``Beloved'' as a movie except Oprah Winfrey. Now, 10 years after
Winfrey read the book in a single day, was shattered by it, and
talked Morrison into letting her buy the film rights, ``Beloved''
opens Friday. The deep-running film is part ghost story, part love
story. Winfrey plays its central figure, Sethe, driven by mother
love and haunted love.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't an easy birth for Winfrey, who calls the film her
baby. And it won't be an easy sell. But Winfrey, born in
Mississippi, didn't come out of a Milwaukee-ghetto childhood and a
Nashville adolescence to become the queen of TV talk shows on easy.
She got where she is because of her penchant for getting down in
the emotional trenches and empathizing. Her strength is the
strength of the heart, compelling respect in a time of ever-lower
standards because the dignity, sincerity, and genuineness of her
open emotionalism never are cheap or exploitative. They are the
real thing, and people sense it.
</P>
<P>
   Her emotions are so real, she recalls as she stretches out on a
sofa in a Boston hotel, that she almost disqualified herself from
playing the iron-willed former slave trying to reconstruct her life
in Cincinnati after the Civil War, across the Ohio River from
Kentucky, where she had been a defiant _ and brutalized _ slave.
``That was my biggest challenge,'' Winfrey says. ``To be quite
honest with you, that's what Toni Morrison had said to (director)
Jonthan Demme. Her exact words were `Oprah Winfrey is emotional.
Sethe is not.' Many days, Jonathan would come up to me and say,
`You told me you were going to open yourself up and let Sethe
through. Instead, you're feeling sympathy for her.'''
</P>
<P>
   But feeling, Winfrey knew instinctively, she says, was going to
be her key to the role and her key to moving audiences. ``I wanted
people to feel what I felt when I put down the book after reading
it. I felt a sense of devastation. I felt numbed by the experience.
I felt a raw kind of aching inside myself, and I wanted to explain
what that was. I wanted people to know what slavery was, not
academically, but as felt knowledge. And then to feel the grace and
wonder of this woman who could open herself to love again despite
what she had gone through on that hollow dark path.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I'm trying to say `I want to make a difference'
without saying `I want to make a difference,' 'cause everybody says
they want to make a difference. Everybody who ever accepts an MTV
award says they wrote that song because they wanted to make a
difference. I see people on the Fashion Awards. They wanted to make
a difference. So I realize it sounds trite, but it comes from a
pure place, it really does.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time I was like feeling I had not even the right to
try because I was overweight, this 200-pound woman. Sethe wouldn't
have been overweight. People weren't in that period. Having access
to the, you know, good life, was not as available as you think.
People ate healthier. They grew their own food. There was no junk
food. I learned what it takes just to go to the pump and draw the
water, go to the garden and pick the greens, clean the greens, take
the salt block and chip the salt from the block, churn the butter.
I mean, by the time you go through all that, it is exhausting just
getting one meal done.''
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey says she struggled at first when she acted in ``The
Color Purple'' and ``Native Son,'' her two other big-screen films,
the former bringing her an Academy Award nomination for another
strong woman facing white overlords. ``I always think everybody's
better than I am because they do it for a living,'' she says. ``I
was very insecure on this although I had done the work, the
preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   The preparation included a simulated escape along the
Underground Railway. ``How do you know which way to go in the
middle of the night, barefoot? When you don't know which way north
is? I wanted to experience that. I was taken into the woods,
blindfolded, in Maryland, and they had some people doing what I
call Underground improv. Finally, I hit that psychological chord,
that shock wave in my body. There was a line one of the guys used,
he didn't even know he did this for me, when I said, `I'm a free
woman. If I can just get my papers, I think I can explain.' And he
said, `You don't think nothing, gal. You don't think nothing
because you belong to me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That connected to me like nothing else had. I just started
crying hysterically, but I went, `That's it!' Well, that's what it
is, you know. Your life is not your own. I can tell you this now.
Nobody wants to experience that kind of pain. Sethe knew that any
time she came home from the fields, she could find her children
gone _ sold from her. She knew that any time the master got upset
with someone, thst person could be beaten or sold. Sethe knew that
to the man who owned her she was an animal, that her own children
really weren't hers to love. She knew that to send her children
back to this was a hopeless living death. What does life mean if
you don't belong to yourself?''
</P>
<P>
   As filming proceeded in the summer of 1997, pressure grew.
Winfrey was due back in Chicago to resume her talk show. Phone
lines began heating up. While she stalled by having celebrities
like Jay Leno and Diane Sawyer stand in for her, she finally got a
sense of what the interior life of a slave was like by calling upon
real slaves. Long a collector of slave memorabilia she keeps on her
Indiana farm to keep her in touch with her roots, Winfrey says she
hung on the walls of her film-set trailer actual slave ledgers,
listing slaves as plantation property.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have bills of sale, I have ledgers that contain the names of
slaves along with the mules, the cattle, the furniture, how many
plows, how many wagons, how many sheep, how much silverware, how
many bowls, how many cups. You would have `Little Sarah, $700, 4
years old,' or `Big John, $1,100, 37 years old.' I have one list
with 77 names and another with 42 names. I would sit in my trailer
and I would light candles and have a little display, call it an
altar if you wish, with the ledgers. I would call out the names
before I would do a scene. I would say, `Now I'm doing the milk
scene, and this is for you, Little Sarah.'''
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey's face clouds over when she recalls the most painful
aspect of playing Sethe _ watching makeup artists place prosthetic
lash scars on her bare back every day. ``I cried every time,''
Winfrey says. ``Even when they were just trying to test it, to find
the right set of prosthetics, and, um, then and every other time,
I'd get sick. Nauseous, nauseous. Sick, diarrhea, throwing up,
sick, sick. One day I was so sick, Jonathan came and told me I
could go home. I was determined I would not have them talking about
me getting sick over the tree (gruesome nickname for the network of
scars).''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Winfrey says, she was moved to make the film because
she believes in the healing power of art. ``Art takes your breath
away and gives you new breath. A new way of thinking. It deepens
you. Still, if I had had my book club back in 1988, when I bought
the rights, I might just have said, `Go ahead, read the book!'''
Not that Winfrey won't go on making films. Mostly, she'll produce
them, in large part for TV. She bought rights to another Morrison
novel, ``Paradise,'' jokes that the leading character is Hispanic
and she wouldn't be able to bring it off as an actress. She might,
however, play a character in Zora Neale Hurston's ``Their Eyes Were
Watching God.''
</P>
<P>
   Confronting life, confronting herself, and accepting both,
Winfrey says, are what people react to on her show. ``I got this
great letter from a lady one day,'' Winfrey says. ``She says
`Watching you be yourself makes me want to be myself.' That is the
greatest thing that anybody has said to me because life is about
how to become more yourself. I think what people see in me is my
willingness to be myself. Yet I feel I don't stand alone. I have a
sense that my life is bigger than my own. Stuff still abides with
me, and the spirits of all those names I called in the trailer and
those whose names I don't even know.''
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey takes a deep breath at the prospect of going back to
Chicago to shoot three shows the next day. But, she says, she has
come through a period of turmoil with new energy and resolve. She
had been vacillating about continuing her TV show. But recently she
signed a contract through 2002. She will, she says, take what
comes. ``During the filming, coming to a felt knowledge of what I
had come from and the price that had been paid for me to get here
and be Oprah Winfrey in the 1980s and '90s, all that had cost is
what made me say I can't quit. I didn't do this by myself. I
thought of Margaret Garner, the real-life model for Sethe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought of all the people she knew, all those people who
would never have imagined this life. You know, having enough food
in the house and going to Cincinnati and having the ice wagon come
by to have an ice block to keep the food cold was their idea of
luxury. Then I think of my life and I think, well, I don't know
what tired is compared to what they had done. I mean, I just feel
like it gets better. I never saw all this when I was a girl sitting
on the linoleum in my mother's apartment in Milwaukee and my beacon
was Sidney Poitier,'' says the multimillionaire philanthropist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember I was 10 years old the night he won the Academy
Award. I was in complete awe. Capital A, capital W, capital E.
Because a colored man first of all arrived in a limousine. Then he
won. I thought, wow, I could do that. Was it naive, was it
arrogance? I don't know, but it spoke to the possibility. I see
that God can dream a bigger dream for me than I can hold in my
imagination. And so I'll let the universe do my dreaming for me,
just open myself up to the possibilities, to know what Sethe didn't
know, and that is that tomorrow can be a better day, Miss Scarlett.
Now I just say I'm open, I'm open. Ready to receive whatever the
future has to bring. I'm open.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
