<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2075 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-BEFORE-BOS &LR;      10-12 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BEFORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UNBRIDGEABLE GULF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID MEHEGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
LIKE NEVER BEFORE 
By Ehud Havazelet. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. 268 pp. $23. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this second collection of graceful stories (his first was
``What Is It Then Between Us?''), Ehud Havazelet turns to the most
deeply worn theme in 20th-century American writing: the gulf
between immigrants and their American-born and acculturated
children. That he makes this estrangement so fresh and vivid, that
he handles it mostly without cliches, is a tribute to his sure
command of narrative, character, and convincing emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Havazelet's 10 stories concern the immigrant Birnbaum family,
Max and Ruth, of Queens, N.Y., who are Polish Jews, and their two
children, David and Rachel. Max _ Maxim _ is a teacher in a Hebrew
school, the son of a rabbi who brought his family to America after
World War II. It is not clear how the family lived through the war,
though one gripping story set in the past, ``Lyon,'' reveals that
the father sent his family from Cracow to France while flight was
still possible for Jews. Sixteen-year-old Maxim and his older
brother Rachmil, part of a Jewish underground, collect money in the
south of France in 1943 to support Jews in hiding. A hideaway
apartment is betrayed, and while Maxim escapes, thanks to his
perfect French and false papers, Rachmil does not.
</P>
<P>
   That violent sundering of family is the background of the other
sundering that takes up most of the book, between Max Birnbaum and
his son in America. Max and Ruth are proud of their two children
and have high hopes for them. But both are independent,
high-spirited children of the '60s, freely indulging in pot and
sex, and they reject their parents' religious strictures and
assumptions about what is required for a worthy life.
</P>
<P>
   David, to his parents' enormous pride, graduates from
architecture school, while Rachel becomes a bohemian artisan who
cleans stained-glass windows. She has a succession of good-time
boyfriends who seem to be a lot of fun, though maybe not so good
for her, and definitely not the sort her parents would choose for
her. The one most fully developed, in the story entitled ``Leah,''
is Alex, a pill-popping, dope-dealing, hard-drinking Romanian cab
driver.
</P>
<P>
   Though Rachel is pretty unorthodox, the only son is the bigger
disappointment: David marries a Gentile girl, Maura, lives a bit
recklessly, and winds up losing his marriage and his job. Later he
moves to Oregon (where the author teaches, at Oregon State
University), remarries, becomes a landscaper, and breaks contact
with his parents and past.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-grinding fault between Max and David is the tragic axis
of the book. It would have been easy to make Max an obnoxious,
overbearing table-pounder and David an innocent American boy just
trying to be free. But it's not so simple; in Havazelet's skillful
hands, we see everyone's side of things. Max cannot understand
David's giving up his architecture career and totally rejecting his
Jewishness. Max's bafflement and disappointment has a quiet cast.
From childhood, David is a hot-tempered, combative volcano, filled
with rage toward his parents, his first wife, his own poor luck.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these stories appeared in literary magazines and could
stand alone, but together they form a nuanced portrait of love and
misunderstanding across a chasm no one in life quite bridges.
</P>
<P>
   One story, simply called ``Ruth's Story,'' is told from the
mother's point of view, as she endures a fatal illness. It is one
of the most harrowing and beautiful renderings of a death by
disease, and the end of a long marriage, that I have read. It is
detailed, but graphic only in emotional terms. In ``Leah'' (the
only first-person narrative), Rachel tells of her pious cousin, who
wants only to marry and have a nice family. The tale of Leah's
successive disastrous attempts at marriage would be worthy of Issac
Bashevis Singer; the story's artful subplot is that Rachel, the
supercilious and pitying narrator, is doing no better with her own
free-form and unconventional alliances.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the stories focus on Max and David. In ``The Street
You Live On,'' David's first wife, Maura, is visited at their
apartment on 108th Street in Manhattan by a detective who tells her
that a woman had been murdered in the building next door, in an
apartment whose window is visible from the Birnbaums' window. Maura
is disturbed that she heard nothing, knew nothing, and even more so
by David's casual reaction: ``It's scary,'' he tells her. ``It's
upsetting. ... But we have to look at the statistics. Maybe two
thousand people on this block, right? And one of them gets unlucky.
That's terrible. But New York isn't even one of the most violent
cities. ... This is the city. You're going to run across things.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't sit right with Maura, even so, and the demonstration
of terrible things going on that one does not know about takes a
painful, personal turn.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pillar of Fire,'' David drives off in a rage after a final
parting with Maura, who has found a gentler partner. At a highway
rest stop, two wandering teenage girls hitch a ride with him, and
the three of them end up on a grassy hillside when Drew, the oldest
girl, insists on stopping to look for Halley's Comet. Just as
Rachel's pity for Leah is ironic, so is David's compassion for Drew
and Angie, who at least are able to hope for a sign.
</P>
<P>
   Max's visit to David and his new wife, in the story that gives
the book its title, brings the conflict between them to a
crescendo. In his savage attack on his father, David's sarcastic
summation of his own life suggests that the bitterness he feels is
not all a matter of rage and resistance to his father's
expectations. Max is not the only disappointed one.
</P>
<P>
   In the last-but-one story, ```To Live in Tiflis in the
Springtime,''' David returns to New York for the unveiling of Max's
headstone. He meets Rachel's new boyfriend, Tim, who is some sort
of insurance man (except for Maura, the goyim in this book are an
unappealing lot). Brother and sister talk about their parents, and
it becomes clear that they will be reconciled more to their spirits
than they could ever have been to them as living mother and father.
``I wish I could have told them some things, too,'' David tells
Rachel wistfully. ``I'd apologize, maybe. I don't know. Say I was
sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehud Havazelet's delicate and lyrical voice is beguiling and
consistent. His treatment of his characters is tender but not
cheaply affectionate. A few are familiar fiction-workshop types:
fast-talking wild child Drew could be a character out of Frederick
Barthelme; Alex the Romanian is a caricature of a parent's
nightmare boyfriend. Though he keeps his point of view fairly well
hidden, it is not difficult to see in Havazelet's world that those
who make their own rules and scorn the pieties and verities of an
older time, place, and generation make for themselves a bitter
drink.
</P>
<P>
   In the delightful last story, ``Eight Rabbis on the Roof,''
Max's father and an odd collection of ghosts come to gather the
widower in. While the old rabbi sits at the kitchen table reading
the newspaper, the ghosts raid the refrigerator. Max threatens to
call the police before he begins to understand what is going on.
For both generations, then, the father's spirit wins in the end. In
a book full of hard and bitter moments, this sweet liftoff
concludes a collection full of finely chiseled edges, painful
divisions, and halting, hard-won renewals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
David Mehegan is the book editor of the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
