<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2076 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-KIDJO-BOS &LR;      10-12 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-KIDJO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIP, HOP AND POP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the musical world so fragmented among its many rigid
elements, it's notable that three black women in their 20s and 30s
have made their presence felt with CDs that with a mixture of power
and elegance tear down those barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Lauryn Hill, Angelique Kidjo, and Audra MacDonald will all be on
best-of-the-year lists in their respective genres at the end of
1998 because, ironic-ally, of their skill and courage in taking
those genres to exciting new places. Is there any connection to
their race, age, and gender? Maybe not, but perhaps their playing
the role of traditional outsider has given them the perspective to
see what's wrong with the insiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill'' (Ruffhouse) didn't exactly
come out of nowhere, but the CD by the 23-year-old once and perhaps
future Fugee is the most surprising of the three, with its stunning
mixture of hip-hop, R&AMP;B, reggae, rap, black gospel music,
hard-hitting politics, and an attack on the machismo and misogyny
of many of her rap brothers. It's Aretha meets Angela with nods to
Queen Latifah and Erykah Badu. She literally embodies a marriage of
rap and reggae, since she's about to have a second child with Bob
Marley's son, Rohan.
</P>
<P>
   Hill _ who produced, arranged, and wrote the music _ is still an
unabashed hip-hop artist, but her use of live musicians and her
experimentation with other forms could make people who dismissed
rap as musical graffiti think again while leading members of her
audience out of a self-inflicted ghetto-ization. On ``To Zion,''
for example, Hill combines Carlos Santana's flamenco-ish guitar, a
gospel chorus, a reggae melody, and a march-inflected beat in a
song that is primarily an ode to her first child, but also serves
as a search for a spiritual Eden.
</P>
<P>
   But along with that Badu-like search for spiritual fulfillment
are tough, look-back-in-anger raps at Hill's ``Miseducation,''
which is composed mostly of misogyny and materialism. The songs are
punctuated by a classroom in which children are being led to
examine their attitudes. ``We don't get `in love,' do we?'' the
teacher asks of the black male students in the class. Similarly,
Hill asks of the Ice Cubes of the world, ``Music is supposed to
inspire, so how come we aren't getting no higher?''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of Hill's lyrics aren't terribly sophisticated, and some
are xeno-phobic _ ``Look at where you be in hair weaves like
Europeans/-Fake nails done by Koreans.'' For the most part, though,
this is a very strong, articulate performance. Hill wants a world
without boundaries, where women are free from men interested only
in ``that thing,'' men whom she describes as ``need to take care of
their three and four kids men ... Money-taking, heart-breaking now
you wonder why women hate men/-The sneaky silent men the
domestic-violence men/-The quick to shoot the semen stop acting
like boys and be men.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a ``My Back Pages'' feeling to a lot of Hill's
reminiscences, which may sound like a stretch, but that song by Bob
Dylan was the precursor to the barrier-breaking ``Subterranean
Homesick Blues,'' which has been called the first rap song. In
composing such a rich debut album, Hill is already well on her way
to breaking barriers of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Angelique Kidjo has been a top draw on the world music circuit,
so ``Oremi'' (Island) comes from the opposite direction. As Hill
expands her musical vocabulary from the limitations of hip-hop,
Kidjo incorporates hip-hop into the rolling beauty of her African
melodies.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first of a projected trilogy of Kidjo's in which she
traces the black musical diaspora. ``Oremi'' is concerned with
American soul and funk while future CDs will search South America.
It works both ways _ Kidjo reminds us of the African roots of that
music, but she traces her own roots and development in being
influenced by everyone from James Brown to, who knows, Lauryn Hill.
</P>
<P>
   She gets further than Hill, though, at arriving at a promised
land of mix-and-match beauty. Just as Cassandra Wilson, whose voice
graces ``Never Know,'' brought jazz singing into a new era by
looking to the music of Van Morrison, Joni Mitchell, and, yes, the
Monkees, Kidjo gives voice to a spellbinding version of Jimi
Hendrix's ``Voodoo Child'' to open the CD. The spell isn't broken
until the last song, the unfortunately syrupy ``No Worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way Kidjo brings in Wilson for scat, Kelly Price for
soul, and Branford Marsalis for sax. Together with a hip-hop or
trip-hop beat, Kidjo and friends establish a soundtrack for walking
down the street in Manhattan or staring out onto a South African
vista. (The CD was recorded in both places.)
</P>
<P>
   Like Hill, Kidjo never loses herself in the eclecticism of her
musical choices. Kidjo's assertively joyful voice as well as her
energetic but clean arrangements is full of the confidence of a
woman sure of her place in the world personally, politically, and
artistically. Kidjo brings it all back home to Africa, but you
don't have to speak the language to know that ``Oremi'' puts her
squarely at the head of the world music class.
</P>
<P>
   Her recent appearance at the Somerville Theatre was reportedly
even more transcendent than the CD. The blurb on the CD claims
``From deep within the African spirit emerges a potent global music
for the new world.'' Kidjo makes you believe that's all more than
record-label hype.
</P>
<P>
   Audra McDonald comes to her chosen world, musical theater, from
a completely different direction, a classical music training. And
what training. At 28, McDonald's soaring soprano has won her Tony
awards for ``Carousel,'' ``Master Class,'' and ``Ragtime.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald won those Tonys as supporting actress, but ``Way Back
to Paradise'' (Nonesuch) announces that she's a leading lady _
quite possibly the leading lady in musical theater. Combining the
strength of her Juilliard-trained voice with the elan of a Broadway
star (not to mention her movie-star beauty), McDonald has a
presence that even Zoe Caldwell had to strain to match in ``Master
Class.''
</P>
<P>
   If that isn't enough, add the virtue of extreme generosity to
McDonald's resume. Most Broadway artists would line their first CD
with the ``hits'' that got them there, and McDonald already has an
impressive output on compilations and soundtracks featuring the
music of Richard Rodgers, Leonard Bernstein, George Gershwin, and
the Flaherty-Ahrens songs for Sarah on ``Ragtime.'' Instead,
McDonald has filled her CD with the next generation of
musical-theater songwriters _ Michael John LaChiusa, Ricky Ian
Gordon, Adam Guettel, Jason Robert Brown, and Jenny Giering.
</P>
<P>
   The CD doesn't quite make the case for their looming greatness
as much as it does for McDonald's. But if there aren't any
traditional show stoppers, ``Way Back to Paradise'' grows more
impressive with each listening. These are songs of cool waftings
rather than hot flashes. They also, like the songs of Kidjo and
Hill, speak to personal liberation and political compassion.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald bursts out of the starting gates with the optimism of
Gordon's rich, warm setting of Langston Hughes: ``To fling my arms
wide/-In some place of the sun/-To whirl and to dance .../While
night comes on gently/Dark like me.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald sounds something like fellow opera/Broadway singer Dawn
Upshaw, who joins her on ``Way Back to Paradise,'' only McDonald's
voice has more body. ``Way Back to Paradise'' is from ``Marie
Christine,'' LaChiusa's resetting of ``Medea,'' in which McDonald
is scheduled to star next year. She could be Lauryn Hill's sister
in singing: ``But there is a way back to paradise ... Study all
men/-Learn what they lack/-Sweeten and stroke/-Before you attack.''
</P>
<P>
   LaChiusa's music is the most dramatic of his contemporaries' on
the CD and gives McDonald the best stretching exercises, but she
also brings striking dignity to Gordon's settings of Hughes and
James Agee and a swirl of Sondheim-like passion in ``Parade,''
Brown and Alfred Uhry's upcoming musical based on the Leo Frank
murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   If McDonald has a weakness, it's that she doesn't seem to be
totally relaxed. At the recent season opener at Carnegie Hall on
PBS, Brian Stokes Mitchell, her ``Ragtime'' co-star, and Frederica
von Stade seemed to be having a ball onstage while McDonald was all
work. That translates to her sometimes overpowering a lyric the way
that US Open champion Lindsay Davenport can sometimes overpower a
tennis ball. They're still the champs, but if they add more finesse
no one will touch them.
</P>
<P>
   Not that McDonald is competing. When you listen to McDonald,
Kidjo, and Hill, you realize that the real winner is music for
having three such advocates who can take all kinds of musical
forms, and all kinds of audiences, to places they've never been.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
