<HEADER>
A2080 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      10-12 1549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TO CONSIDER PAYING OFF A SMALL MORTGAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Some time in the not-too-distant future I will need to decide
if I want to invest my severance pay or use it to pay off my
mortgage. The mortgage balance is about $60,000, and the severance
pay is about the same. It would be nice to use this money for other
things, including investments, but what would I be giving up in
additional earnings on the $60,000 and tax deductions by paying the
mortgage? The monthly payment is currently $726, with $314 going to
principal and $412 to interest. The mortgage has a variable rate,
currently 8.25 percent and probably due to decline later this year.
It's a 15-year mortgage with 10 years to go.
</P>
<P>
   R.K., Harrisburg, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Mathematically it's fairly easy to work out. You are paying
about $4,900 annually in interest on this mortgage, and you reap a
$1,372 tax benefit, so the mortgage costs you about $3,528 a year
at this point. (I say about because the cost declines each month as
the mortgage amortizes.) If you were to invest $60,000 in a
fixed-income mutual fund such as one invested in
government-guaranteed mortgage securities, you might expect a yield
of about 6.5 percent, or $3,900. But this, of course, would be
taxable, so the actual yield to you would be $2,808. Thus, at least
on paper, you would be $720 a year ahead of the game by prepaying
the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   But let's look at another option. Suppose you were to refinance
the mortgage, this time obtaining a fixed interest rate, which
we'll estimate at 6.5 percent. In that event, your initial interest
cost would be about $3,900, and the tax benefit would be $1,092,
giving you a first-year mortgage cost of $2,808 -- exactly the same
as the after-tax yield on that mutual fund investment.
</P>
<P>
   You don't mention your overall financial situation, or how you
came to get the severance package. If you are between jobs or
embarking on a new career, it would seem to me that having a
$60,000 nest egg would do a lot to give you a sense of financial
security. Overall, I think I would go with the investment program
and the idea of refinancing the mortgage. But I would also build a
cautious investment portfolio, relying heavily on fixed-income
securities, designed to insure that the financial security remains.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. If I understand the procedure correctly, I simply do not
understand the fairness of the tax procedures that relate to mutual
funds. If you buy a mutual fund position for $5,000 and you gain
$1,000, you pay taxes on that $1,000. If you then lose $1,000 the
next year, you are back to $5,000, but you cannot deduct the $1,000
loss. If you have to pay taxes year by year, why can't you deduct
your losses year by year?
</P>
<P>
   H.S., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The procedure is a little more complicated than you describe
it, but, for many investors, it's no less galling. The easiest way
to view the tax rules that apply to mutual funds is to understand
that the results would be the same as if you were dealing with your
own portfolio of common stocks. The rules require that income such
as dividends and interest payments, net of expenses, be distributed
to the owners of the investments. They also require that the net of
all realized capital gains and capital losses also be distributed.
But, just as with common stocks that you hold for many years, there
is no taxable event if the fund manager simply hangs on to a stock
which has appreciated -- tax liability is triggered only when the
investment is sold. Therefore, your example may not be quite on
point. If you buy $5,000 worth of shares in a mutual fund, and the
value of your position grows to $6,000, you will face tax bills
only for the portions of the gain -- income and realized capital
gains -- which has been distributed to the owners. While it's not
impossible for distributions to equal or exceed the total return,
it's also not particularly common.
</P>
<P>
   What happens when a mutual fund loses money? If the net of all
capital gains and capital losses is negative, the fund not only
need make no distribution, but it can carry that paper loss
forwards into further years, and will not have to make a capital
gains distribution until the loss that has been carried forward is
wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   Thus you can see that mutual fund investors do get some benefit
from realized portfolio losses, but not necessarily at the time
they are realized. The investor who has a paper mutual fund loss on
paper and wants to realize it for tax purposes must sell the
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go back to your example. The investor begins with a $5,000
investment and receives a $1,000 taxable distribution. Suppose the
investor has directed that the distributions be reinvested in the
fund. The effect is that the investor's tax basis increases from
$5,000 to $6,000. Now suppose in the following year the value of
the position falls to $5,000. The investor can then sell, realizing
a capital loss of $1,000 which can be used to reduce his or her tax
liability. Thus while the $1,000 distribution was taxable in the
first year, the investor can recoup the tax by selling before the
end of the second year.
</P>
<P>
   The unpleasant reality of the mutual fund business is that
managers and funds are usually evaluated according to their total
returns, and those bottom lines are much more critical to the
managers than the tax consequences of their actions.
</P>
<P>
   There are a handful of funds whose objective includes managing
the portfolio so as to minimize the tax effect on the owners, the
best known of which are probably the Vanguard ``Tax-Managed''
funds.
</P>
<P>
   There are two other ways to make some pretty good judgments
about whether funds are likely to deliver unwelcome tax bills to
their owners. One is to look for funds with low turnover rates,
which is to say funds which do relatively little trading of their
portfolio positions. A turnover of less than 50 percent is
generally considered fairly low, and many index funds usually trade
only about 5 percent to 10 percent of their portfolios annually,
with the effect of keeping capital gains distributions to low
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing you can look for, in the funds' annual reports or
in the Morningstar Mutual Funds reports, is the potential capital
gains exposure. This figure, measured as a percentage of the assets
of the fund, reflects what percentage of the net asset value would
be distributed as capital gains in the (extremely unlikely) event
that the entire portfolio were liquidated. Of those two measures,
turnover rate is more important, since it reflects the investment
discipline of the managers. A low potential capital gains exposure
figure may simply reflect a fund which has not done particularly
well with its investments, and a high one might simply mean that
the managers have held a large portion of their investments for
many years and are following a long-term strategy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 78,single, and retired in 1985. I don't live lavishly,
but find I am dipping into my principal at the rate of $5,000 to
$7,000 annually. The only money I have is $485,000 invested in
Fidelity Spartan Tax-Free Municipal Income fund, which yields me
about $2,000 a month. I have other income from Social Security and
an annuity.
</P>
<P>
   Until retirement I looked for growth, but since then I have
looked for as little risk as possible. My point of view is to put
money away and forget about it. Can I do anything with my money to
give me more income, less risk, and with liquidity in case I need
to ``dip''?
</P>
<P>
   (I have check writing with Fidelity.) Obviously I don't want any
diminution of my monthly income, and I'm not particularly worried
about growth. I have a will, and the money will eventually go to
relatives, a charity, and friends. Perhaps I shouldn't even worry
about dipping into it.
</P>
<P>
   W.B., Miami
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Your last thought was one of my first: If you simply left the
money where it is and made withdrawals at a rate of $30,000 a year,
the pool would last you more than 28 years, which would take you
well past the century mark.
</P>
<P>
   I have two suggestions. The first is to consider moving the bulk
of your money to a single-state fund such as Fidelity's Spartan
Florida Municipal Income fund. Although it has a lower stated yield
than your current fund -- 4 percent -- the Fidelity Insight
newsletter reports that this yield is the equivalent of a 5.6
percent return for taxpayers in the 28 percent federal tax bracket
and the highest Florida bracket. I suggest you analyze your tax
situation to determine whether you might not profit from such a
move on an after-tax basis.
</P>
<P>
   Second, you might also find that you would profit on an
after-tax basis by moving a bit of your money into a taxable
investment such as Fidelity Intermediate Government Income fund.
This would offer a similar risk level to your current holding, and
it may be that after taxes you would do better by moving some of
the money to such a fund.
</P>
<P>
   But as I said at the outset, nothing horrible is going to happen
if you do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
