<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
! 1/2 ``Holy Man''  A wasted opportunity for sharp social satire.
When Eddie Murphy's blissful guru smiles his way onto a home
shopping network and turns out to be a dynamite pitchman, the idea
of shopping as a religious experience seems ready for skewering.
But the film loses contact with Murphy, veering instead into dull
hand-wringing over the state of TV exec Jeff Goldblum's soul and
his prefab romance with Kelly Preston. (PG)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! &UR; 1/2 ``One Tough Cop''  &LR; This could have been Stephen Baldwin's
breakthrough movie. He looks and sounds right as the tough New York
street cop on whose story the film is based. But gritty
authenticity is undermined by a cliched screenplay that insists on
turning desperate lives into romantic melodrama. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! &UR; ``Unmade Beds''  &LR; Four lonely veterans of the personals ads, as
captured by Nicholas Barker, who wrote scripts of their lives based
on what they told him in interviews, had them play the scripts into
his camera, and invites us to share the voyeurism. The buxom
divorcee, the aging swinger, the overweight woman, and the
diminutive man whose stories are intertwined (but who never meet)
remind us that isolation is the star here. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! &UR; ``Without Limits''  &LR; Robert Towne's gripping film about Oregon
runner Steve Prefontaine, whose all-out style enabled him to break
a handful of records before he died in a car crash at the age of
24. Billy Crudup is electrifying as the fierce competitor. Donald
Sutherland is a satisfying counterweight as the coach whose advice
he mostly spurns, but who invented the Nike running shoe for him
anyway. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
