<HEADER>
A2101 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     10-12 1529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following
 &UR; ScienceTimes &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Oct. 13:
</P>
<P>
   This is the first week of an expanded Science Times, with an
extra seven columns of space devoted to health and fitness.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NOBEL-MEDICINE (Undated) _ Three Americans won the Nobel
Prize in Medicine for their work on how the common air pollutant
nitric oxide acts as a signaling molecule in the cardiovascular
system. Their research led to a method of initiating penis erection
and indirectly to the development of the Viagra anti-impotency
drug. The three were Robert Furchgott, 82, of New York; Ferid
Murad, 62, of Houston, and Louis Ignarro, 57, of Los Angeles. By
Lawrence K. Altman. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PLACEBO (Undated) _ Scientists are uncovering a host of
biological mechanisms that can turn a thought, belief or desire
into an agent of change in cells, tissues and organs. They are
exploring the spooky fact that much of human perception is based
not on information flowing into the brain from the outside world
but what the brain, based on previous experience, expects to happen
next. By Sandra Blakeslee. (1950 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PLACEBO-DOCTORS (Undated) _ Though some people respond more
strongly to placebos than others do, it seems that everyone
responds at some time or other. And doctors seem to play a large
role in the degree of that response. ``The thing that trumps
everything is the enthusiastic physician,'' said Dr. Dan Molerman
of the University of Michigan. (380 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-METEOR-STORM (Undated) _ Periodically for at least 1,000
years, a spectacular rain of meteors _ spawned by a passing comet _
has lighted up the sky, inspiring fear, wonder and admiration. The
Leonid meteor storm, which shot hundreds of thousands of blazing
streaks across the heavens 33 years ago, is nearly due to hit the
earth again, and this time space scientists are concerned about its
effects. By Malcolme Browne. (1650 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-METEOR-VIEW (Undated) _ Unfortunately for residents of the
United States, the Leonid storm on Nov. 17 is expected to begin at
2:43 p.m. EST, and is likely to last for only an hour or so. For
the United States, therefore, the entire show will be during
daylight hours and will be invisible, unless any unusually bright
bolides or exploding fireballs flash through the daytime sky. (440
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANIMALS-COMPUTERS (Undated) _ A new computer study intended
to show how predators choose their prey is just one of an
increasing number of such faux creatures being shaped, colored, and
directed on the computer screen as researchers attempt to ask a
wide array of questions about what makes real animals respond to
other animals the way that they do. This one shows which moths the
birds are most likely to attack. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-GETTY (Undated) _ Conversation with Jeff Getty, the man
who has lived with AIDS for 18 years and received a failed bone
marrow graft from a baboon. By Claudia Dreifus.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: A ``stitch in
your side'' and what to do about it. (325 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NASA-MEMORIES (Undated) _ As the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration marks the 40th anniversary of its founding on
Oct. 1, 1958, aspects of the occasion are more archeological than
astronautical. Or so it sometimes seems on the back roads and in
the weeds along the shore of Cape Canaveral, Fla., where the ruins
evoke memories of all those rockets in the early morning and the
eerie twilight after the cheering stopped. By John Noble Wilford.
(430 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Shorts on science: Leads with plants that
absorb gold from the ground. (650 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANTZ-GENDER (Undated) _ ``Antz'' is a cute movie. It is a
visually dazzling movie. It has some amusing, ant-appropriate lines
in it. But the science is all wrong. Where the movie really misses
out is in its portrayal of males ruling the anthill. By Natalie
Angier. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Health and Fitness &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Calcium is fast emerging as the
nutrient of the decade, a substance with such diverse roles in the
body that virtually no major organ system escapes its influence. As
the most abundant mineral in the body, calcium has long been
recognized as vital to the formation and maintenance of strong
bones and teeth. But bones, rather than serving as the final
destination of calcium, are in a sense, just a starting point. They
continuously release the mineral into the system where new research
suggests it may play a central role in controlling blood pressure
and easing premenstrual syndrome. In addition, new studies indicate
that unused dietary calcium may help to prevent colon cancer. By
Jane E. Brody. (2150 words)
</P>
<P>
   Eds, a trimmed version, at 1500 words, will also be filed.
</P>
<P>
   With grapfic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEALTH-PAIN (Undated) _ For decades, doctors have worried
that they might be disciplined, or even face criminal prosecution,
for aggressive use of morphine and other narcotics to control pain.
Now, some advocates are trying to swing the pendulum in the other
direction, by pressing authorities to punish doctors for not using
pain medicine aggressively enough. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg. (1150
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEALTH-KAVA (Undated) _ The prospect of inner peace with no
strings attached has tempted hundreds of thousands to try kava, an
herbal product derived from the roots of a shrub grown in Hawaii,
Fiji, Vanuatu and other Pacific islands. There have been no
scientific studies of kava in human beings in the United States,
but still, $15 million a year was spent on it in 1996, and twice
that much in 1997, according to the Nutrition Business Journal,
which projects sales of almost $50 million this year. By Denise
Grady. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PREJUDICE-TEST (Undated) _ Ask people if they harbor
negative attitudes toward blacks, women, or the elderly, and the
response is likely to be a chorus of denials. But give those same
people a simple test designed to tap unconscious beliefs, two
psychologists say, and the results often tell a different story.
(575 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEALTH-PRO&AMP;CON (Undated) _ Pro/con: Should women pace during
labor?
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEALTH-VIAGRA (Undated) _ Viagra may have another down side,
this one among the female partners of the men taking it. More and
more older women are suffering from frequent, urgent, burning
urination _ usually found among women half their age and sometimes
called honeymoon cystitis, say three doctors who noticed the
condition among their patients in Covington, Ga. (200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOCS-HANDWRITING (Undated) _ Confirming conventional wisdom,
researchers have found that doctors to indeed have horrible
handwriting. But, they do write numbers clearly. (290 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-NOVICE (Undated) _ The joys and perils of rock
climbing, from the Rockreaction Gym to the 7,500 feet of granite
known as Suicide Rocks. By Gary Taubes. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-REVERSE (Undated) _ Exercising in reverse has now
shifted into high gear because of the popularity of machines like
elliptical trainers, stair climbers and spinning bikes that allow
exercisers to move backward and forward. Despite the increased
popularity of the reverse workout, fitness experts question whether
exercising backward is safe and effective or just another fitness
fad. Many suspect that it is the latter. (660 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEALTH-CHLAMYDIA (Undated) _ It is a finding sure to dismay
parents everywhere: the sexually transmitted disease chlamydia has
become so common among teen-age girls in some parts of the U.S.
that doctors have begun to recommend that sexually active girls be
tested for it twice a year, instead of once a year, as called for
by current medical guidelines. By Denise Grady. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOCS-PEER-REVIEW (Undated) _ How well do doctors follow
directions? Not very well, apparently, when it comes to a standard
practice followed by medical journals. A new study shows that
physicians often neglect to read the instructions sent to them when
they provide peer review for journals. (280 words)
</P>
