<SLUG> BC-MEDICINE-ALTERNATIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END OF COEXISTENCE SEEN FOR DOCTORS, ALTERNATIVE MEDICINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Chiropractors may have been the immediate target of
last week's stinging critiques in The New England Journal of
Medicine, but it's the broader empire of alternative medicine that
the journal and its allies in mainstream medicine really are after.
</P>
<P>
   Such a campaign would not have been surprising even as recently
as the early 1990s, when mainstream and alternative medicines were
openly at war. But this comes in what has seemed to be the era of
detente, one in which even the labels were softened to signal that
``complementary'' practitioners would now practice side by side
with their brethren in the temples of traditional medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's articles, however, make clear that the cease-fire
itself has ceased as the prestigious journal, for the second time
in a month, has attacked alternative medicine for allegedly failing
to back its claims of healing power.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the intense reaction to those articles suggests
that rather than embracing the nascent alliance between mainstream
and alternative approaches, many medical doctors had bottled up
their grievances and were waiting for the right moment to vent
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been giving alternative medicine a free ride,'' says Dr.
Marcia Angell, the New England Journal's executive editor. Doctors
``were leaning over backwards not to alienate their patients. But I
don't think they'll alienate them by leveling with them, by telling
them the truth that there's very little scientific proof that
supports alternative medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors have an obligation to treat their patients as
grown-ups, not as children.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James S. Gordon, a Harvard-trained psychiatrist who runs the
Center for Mind-Body Medicine in Washington, views what the journal
and its supporters are doing through a markedly different lens:
``They seem to see themselves functioning not as scientists in the
truest sense of the word, but as guardians of orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of science is the history of comings and goings of
different kinds of orthodoxy,'' adds Gordon, former chairman of the
advisory council to the Office of Alternative Medicine at the
National Institutes of Health. ``I think this is a kind of protest
by some of the less thoughtful and less critical members of the
orthodoxy.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand today's standoff between alternative and
mainstream medicines, it is critical to understand the history of
the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Distrust was the watchword for most of that history. Many
medical doctors saw alternative healers as peddling an unproven
art, one that unfairly raised patients' hopes and raided their
pocketbooks. Many alternative therapists, meanwhile, saw medical
doctors as promoting toxic and expensive conventional treatments
and as unwilling to consider remedies used for centuries in other
parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Patients were caught in the middle. Signaling frustration over
mainstream medicine's inability to cure their ailments and ease
their pain, many quietly sought treatment from herbalists,
acupuncturists, and other practitioners whose very titles made
clear they were offering very different options. The extent of that
disaffection became apparent in 1993, when The New England Journal
published a study showing that Americans were seeking treatment
more often from unconventional healers than from pediatricians,
internists, and other primary-care doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, there has been a slow building of bridges. You can
see it in the way spiritual healers now practice in such bastions
of traditional medicine as Massachusetts General Hospital. You can
hear it when oncologists at the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute
consult with patients not only about chemotherapy but about ``qi
gong,'' a Chinese system of breathing and exercise. Most of all,
you can count it in the way more and more managed care companies,
responding to patient pressure, are paying for chiropractic and
other alternative therapies.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone has bought into the new alliance, however.
</P>
<P>
   The Federation of State Medical Boards last year urged its
members not just to look at conventional medicine in rooting out
fraud but also to investigate alternative healers. Many private
doctors were complaining, too, although generally in private for
fear of alienating their patients. And last month The New England
Journal, arguably the world's most influential medical publication,
wrote that many alternative remedies reflect ``a reversion to
irrational approaches to medical practice.'' Last week it published
a study suggesting that visiting a chiropractor was only marginally
more likely to relieve lower back pain than was reading a $1
booklet on the ailment's causes and cures.
</P>
<P>
   Such responses, sometimes strident, stem partly from legitimate
concerns by doctors over the lack of evidence that alternative
treatments work. With chiropractors, for instance, the authors of
last week's study found that, among 321 adults with low back pain,
spinal manipulation offered the same relief as a common form of
physical therapy, and both were only marginally successful at
easing symptoms. A second report found that chiropractic care
provided no benefit for children with mild or moderate asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're seeing bona fide scientific methods applied to
evaluating therapies, many of which are basically the placebo
effect, and those methods are demonstrating that it is indeed the
placebo effect,'' says Dr. Tom Delbanco, chief of general medicine
at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center and a coauthor of the 1993
study on the migration from mainstream medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the backlash by medical doctors is explained by
self-interest. Feeling squeezed by managed care, some medical
doctors worry that more of those dollars are going to alternative
therapists and, as Delbanco notes, ``we are beginning to see a
battle for the dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the issue of journalistic competition, in this
case between The New England Journal and its archrival, the Journal
of the American Medical Association. Some close observers say The
New England Journal's recent focus on alternative medicine was
motivated in part by a desire to upstage JAMA, which announced
plans a year ago to make alternative medicine the centerpiece of an
issue due next month.
</P>
<P>
   New England Journal executive editor Angell denies that, saying,
``we didn't solicit these manuscripts (on alternative medicine). We
happened to get these studies; they all came in within a couple of
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. George D. Lundberg, editor of JAMA, declined to comment on
The New England Journal's timing. He applauds his competitor's
focus on alternative medicine as ``helpful in understanding
procedures when they are being evaluated by scientific methods,''
but he wonders ``whether they are helpful in the dialogue between''
of mainstream and complementary medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever motivated them, The New England Journal critiques of
alternative medicine are almost certain to continue, if only
because they have brought into the open simmering issues within the
medical community. Angell, for instance, says the recent articles
generated what may be a record response in letters, and the recent
studies on alternative treatments are ``the tip of the iceberg ...
Finally the scientific community is beginning to mobilize
themselves and conduct rigorous studies on these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Alternative medicine is sure to fight back, as chiropractors did
last week in challenging the methods and results of the back pain
study. Nontraditional healers also are questioning whether
physicians trained in Western medicine are competent to judge
treatments that derive from dramatically different traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John M. Eisenberg, head of the US Agency for Health Care
Policy and Research, is trying to use the studies it funds on
medical quality to carve out a middle ground. ``The alternative
medicine group has to recognize that there are rules of evidence we
use in science that establish what ought to be done for patients,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, the traditional scientific community has to
understand that there are outcomes and processes of care that
patients value. We are starting to be able to measure those in
terms of what the patient sees as important rather than what
laboratory tests show.''
</P>
</TEXT>
