<HEADER>
A2136 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-ELECTION-BOS &LR;      10-12 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEMOCRATS FEAR `FILIBUSTER-PROOF' GOP MAJORITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ever since Republicans took control of the Senate
four years ago, the filibuster has been the favorite weapon
deployed by Democrats to kill GOP legislation. Even the threat of a
filibuster, often made by Senator Edward M. Kennedy, has forced
Republicans to negotiate with Democrats on major issues.
</P>
<P>
   But now, in what some Democrats consider a nightmare scenario,
Republicans are growing increasingly hopeful of winning an
additional five Senate seats in the Nov. 3 elections to reach the
60-vote plateau, providing a potential ``filibuster-proof''
majority that would give the GOP enormous power to control the
agenda. It would also increase chances that the GOP could muster
the two-thirds majority needed to oust President Clinton from
office, should the House impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the focus is on the filibuster, long a
parliamentary survival tool, typically for the party in the
minority.
</P>
<P>
   As employed by Kennedy and other Democrats, the filibuster ``is
our insurance policy,'' Senate minority leader Thomas Daschle said
in an interview. ``If we lose that, we have nothing.'' He said
Democrats are concerned about ``the implications of being
irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are extraordinarily strong words from one of the nation's
top Democrats, especially as Congress is pondering the possible
impeachment of Clinton. Indeed, part of the Democratic strategy to
win some Senate seats is to issue stark warnings about the impact
of electing such a large Republican majority. But Daschle said the
concerns are real and not just campaign spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be the biggest bonanza for the far-right in this
century,'' Daschle said, reeling off a list of bills that
Republicans would be able to pass affecting the environment,
abortion rights, school prayer, and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans now control the Senate by a 55-45 margin. While
Daschle thinks Democrats will do better than expected, he said, ``I
acknowledge we could be below 40.'' In fact, Daschle has said
Democrats could wind up with anywhere from 38 to 46 seats after the
election, meaning he sees the prospect that Republicans could pick
up as many as seven seats for a 62-38 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, playing down the idea they would run roughshod over
Democrats, acknowledge that a filibuster-proof majority would
enable them to pass a handful of key bills, but they said the
possible impact has been exaggerated. Even if Republicans were able
to avoid a filibuster and pass their bills, Clinton could still
veto them, leaving the GOP scrambling for the 67 votes necessary to
override a veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American system of government allows relatively few
dramatic shifts,'' said Senator Phil Gramm, a Texas Republican. ``I
think there would be a shift, but it would be slow and gradual. Is
the world suddenly going to be different if we have 60 seats in the
Senate? No, because we still have Bill Clinton in the White
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gramm hopes to work with Clinton on a bill that would
permit people to put Social Security money into certain long-term
investments. In Gramm's view, the best outcome would be to pick up
enough Republican seats to pass his bill and win Clinton's support
to avoid a veto.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Republicans said a 60-seat majority would enable
them to win prompt passage of what critics call a partial-birth
abortion ban and have enough votes to override a presidential veto.
Republicans would probably pass legislation enabling parents to use
vouchers to send their children to private schools, prompting
another veto showdown that the GOP might win. Republicans also
would have enough votes to win passage of other key bills that have
been killed by Democrats, including a new missile defense plan,
product liability overhaul, and a balanced budget amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hope to pick up open seats in Ohio and Kentucky and
believe they have shot at unseating Democrats such as Barbara Boxer
of California, Harry Reid of Nevada, Carol Moseley-Braun of
Illinois, Ernest ``Fritz'' Hollings of South Carolina, and Patty
Murray of Washington. Democrats, meanwhile, hold out hopes they can
pick up the seats of Alfonse M. D'Amato of New York, Lauch
Faircloth of North Carolina, and the open Indiana seat.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of these Senate races also could have a major impact
on whether Clinton is ousted from office. If Clinton is impeached
by the House, it would take a two-thirds vote by the Senate _ 67
votes if all 100 senators are present _ to convict and oust the
president. That almost certainly means some Democratic votes would
be required to convict Clinton in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, where Republicans have a 228-206 margin, the GOP
hopes to pick up at least a dozen seats. But such a gain would not
have the same legislative impact as in the Senate, mainly because
filibusters are not allowed in the House.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans now hold a majority in the Senate, they do not
always control it. This year, Democrats killed eight bills by
filibuster and numerous others with the threat of a filibuster.
Perhaps no one has been more effective at this strategy than
Kennedy, who has used the threat of a filibuster to kill
legislation he perceived as antiunion, such as compensation time
and company-run unions.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Kennedy ``has as much to do with frustrating the
far right as anybody in Washington,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most significant result of a larger Republican
majority would be that Clinton's veto power would become more
important than ever. With Republicans able to end filibusters at
will, many more GOP-authored bills are likely to reach the
president's desk and be subject to a veto.
</P>
<P>
   Since Clinton took office in 1993, he has vetoed 23 bills,
according to Senate records. Republicans succeeded only twice in
overriding the vetoes, passing a securities overhaul bill in 1995
and erasing a set of Clinton line-item vetoes in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But the addition of even a few seats in the Senate might help
Republicans override Clinton's vetoes on some major issues. For
example, Republicans in October 1997 picked up considerable
Democratic support for overriding Clinton's veto of a bill that
would ban partial-birth abortions. Now Republicans need just three
additional votes to override another veto of the legislation, which
they might get after the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Republican effort to provide vouchers that would
enable poor children to go to private schools in the District of
Columbia, vetoed by Clinton earlier this year, might be successful
with a larger Republican majority.
</P>
<P>
   Still, key Republicans said the impact of a larger GOP presence
in the Senate might be exaggerated. Senator John McCain, the
Arizona Republican, stressed in an interview that the GOP is not a
``monolithic conference'' that will automatically vote together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure you will see a profound impact,'' McCain said.
``You have people who are from different parts of the country,
different agenda in the Republican Party. Even when the Democrats
had 60 or more votes, they were unable to railroad the Senate
because they had Southern Democrats who were very conservative. In
this case, we have more liberal members in our caucus from the
Northeast and in some cases the Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, two of McCain's top pieces of legislation _ tobacco
regulation and campaign finance overhaul _ could be harmed by a
larger Republican takeover. Both measures were backed mostly by
Democrats and killed by Republican filibusters. A larger Republican
majority might make it even more difficult, if not impossible, to
pass the two bills.
</P>
<P>
   While emphasizing that he wants more Republicans elected, McCain
said: ``I don't think it is the nirvana that some Republicans think
it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
