TB infection. Lions were also being darted and tested, after an
earlier sampling found about 90 per cent of them TB-positive.
</P>
<P>
   But Braack emphasised that the dart tests showed only that the
lions have come into contact with the disease, not that they are
dying from it. Like buffaloes, lions must undergo post-mortem
tissue tests for proof that the TB is life-threatening, but there
are 10 times more buffaloes than lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation does not merit killing lions,'' he said in
exasperation, adding that over-reaction was putting unreasonable
