<SLUG> BC-DYLAN-CD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JUDAS' CONCERT CD CAPTURES HISTORIC DYLAN MOMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Judas!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe you.'' Pause. ``You're a liar.''
</P>
<P>
   In all of rock 'n' roll, there is no more famous confrontation
between performer and fan than this: A lone, unknown, and very
angry Englishman calls Bob Dylan ``Judas'' just before the end of a
show at the Manchester Free Trade Hall on May 17, 1966 _ and Dylan
responds.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the confrontation (and the show itself) became
something of a legend. Bootlegged several times over the years, it
was simply called ``the Royal Albert Hall show,'' after the London
venue where it was thought to have been recorded, or ``the Judas
show'' because of the heckler's famous phrase. And it came to be
seen as perhaps the ultimate Dylan artifact: the exact moment his
desire to create electric rock music ran into the brick wall of
angry folk purists, who saw such music as blasphemy.
</P>
<P>
   Well, now it's here _ officially and gloriously. Tuesday will
finally see Columbia Records release ``Live 1966: The `Royal Albert
Hall' Concert _ The Bootleg Series Vol. 4.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all here _ 45 minutes of acoustic solo Dylan and then, on
disc two, the troubled second set, during which he and the Hawks
(who would, with a different drummer, go on to become the Band)
throw down well-nigh perfect electric rock 'n' roll as a large
section of the crowd grows ever angrier and more vocal.
</P>
<P>
   It is every bit as magnificent as the legend that has preceeded
it for the past 32 years. By the time of the 1966 world tour, Dylan
was both the king of the folk movement and a pop star, and he was
turning out amazing material at an amazing pace. In 1964 and 1965
alone he'd released three masterpieces, ``Another Side of Bob
Dylan,'' ``Bringing It All Back Home'' and ``Highway 61
Revisited.'' Perhaps his greatest work, ``Blonde on Blonde'' came
out the same month he played this show.
</P>
<P>
   He was remaking himself quicker than anyone else in popular
music, and with the chart success of ``Like a Rolling Stone'' (from
``Highway 61''), he had outraged many of those who had annointed
him as nearly a mythological figure.
</P>
<P>
   This show, then, stands as the point where one of the 20th
century's greatest artists both embraces and confronts his
audience.
</P>
<P>
   The first set is seven songs, beginning with ``She Belongs to
Me,'' highlighted by a long, stunning ``Desolation Row'' and capped
by ``Mr. Tambourine Man.'' The response is rapturous: Dylan
performs these songs with a quicksilver quality, almost a
recklessness, savoring them, coloring them with vocal phrases and
harmonica licks not found on the recorded versions. At the end of
the first 45 minutes, he's everyone's hero.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the electric set, and those who hate Dylan's electric
sound start booing and yelling almost from the outset. And instead
of just plowing through the material, he actually lets them have
their say, pausing for long moments between songs as people holler
out of the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   It's confrontational, yes, but the music more than backs it up:
With Garth Hudson's carnival organ and Robbie Robertson's twangy
blues/country guitar, the eight songs _ from the obscure ``Tell Me,
Momma'' to classics ``Just Like Tom Thumb's Blues'' and ``Ballad of
a Thin Man'' _ are funky, raucous rock 'n' roll. Dylan is clearly
reveling in denouncing the naysayers' expectations, and in this
loud, raw sound _ he's totally in the moment, totally in control.
It's some of the best live rock music you'll ever hear.
</P>
<P>
   The famous face-off comes near the end, just before ``Like a
Rolling Stone,'' which Dylan and the band dive into with a singular
fury. They're taking the crowd's anger and throwing it back at
them, daring them to find fault with this music, and then the
song's over and they're gone. There is no encore because, really,
what could be said after that? Dylan and the Hawks were changing
the face of popular music, and they knew it, and knew they were up
to the task. This is the power of this show, and why even all these
years later it's every bit as exciting as you may have heard.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Artist: Bob Dylan
</P>
<P>
   CD: ``Live 1966: The `Royal Albert Hall' Concert _ The Bootleg
Series Vol. 4''
</P>
<P>
   Label: Columbia Records
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 5 stars (out of a possible 5)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
