   TECH-REPORT13-COX_ATLANTA _ In just a few years, the Internet
has transformed the wired world into a global village, and
communicating with your neighbors on the Net can be as easy as
talking over the back fence _ no matter how far away that fence is.
(GHIRANDINI, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS-13-COX_ATLANTA _ The Further Adventures of Ace
Warner, Software Detective: 6:23: p.m. Download begins. Takes 10
minutes to get to 5 percent. A big one. Go to Start menu. Select
Programs. Select Accessories. Select Games. Select solitaire. 6:28
p.m. Cards are running lousy. Download has reached 15 percent. 7:15
p.m. Drag solitaire window aside to check download progress.
There's a little panel there that says ``Could not complete
download. Try again later.'' What do you mean, could not complete
download? Did the little guy pumping the handle get tired? Did
somebody refuse to work overtime? I never saw a message like that.
``Connection failed,'' OK, but the connection is fine. ``Download
interrupted,'' maybe. But it doesn't say it was interrupted; it
just says it couldn't do it anymore, as in ``Oh, God, I just can't
go on.'' (WARNER, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT13-COX_ATLANTA _ You don't have to wait for Apple
Computer to update its operating system to improve your Mac's ease
of use. There's been a rival of sorts in development for the Mac,
much of it grass roots. Amateur and professional programmers are
coming up with some wonderful tweaks to the operating system. One
good example is a piece of shareware called FinderPop. Shareware is
software you can download and try out without charge but are
expected to pay for if you end up using it. (HADAD, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
