<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2185 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA-REFUGEES-1013-     10-12 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-REFUGEES-1013-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOSOVO'S ETHNIC ALBANIANS FINDING SCARCE REFUGE IN BOSNIA
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    By SUSANNAH NESMITH 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Sevdije Gashi left Kosovo a few
days after her village was attacked and her home burned down by
Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   Though the timing is never good for refugees trying to escape
such violence, it was particularly bad for this mother of three.
She was about to have another baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was born on the bus to Bosnia,'' Gashi said, shyly showing
off her gurgling three-week-old daughter. ``My mother-in-law had
just been arrested by Serb police. We had to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Gashi's family of six -- including he husband -- lives in an
abandoned Coca-Cola bottling plant in Sarajevo, eating, sleeping
and crying together on the 10-by-10-foot square of floor that has
become their home.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 other refugees live in the same factory, with no
running water, no heat and no idea what their future holds, as
winter looms and NATO officials debate military airstrikes to force
Yugoslavia to end the seven-month conflict in the Serb province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnian government officials estimate 12,000 ethnic Albanian
refugees from Kosovo have ended up in this country. But with about
800,000 of its own refugees to deal with three years after the war
here ended, the government has been reluctant to help the Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the Bosnian government's responsibility to take care of
these people,'' said a frustrated Melissa Ward, the U.N. High
Commission for Refugees official in charge of the makshift camp at
the Coca-Cola plant.
</P>
<P>
   The government wouldn't let UNHCR install heaters or a kitchen
in the camp, and officials have insisted the refugees be moved to
another facility by the end of the month so work to rehabilitate
the factory can begin. A left-over from Bosnia's communist past,
the plant belongs to the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're providing all the funds, but the government isn't
cooperating,'' she said. ``We're only asking for assistance with
the infrastructure, the water, housing facilities, health-care. The
government promised to send a doctor, but he never came.''
</P>
<P>
   While several government officials declined to comment on the
situation, one official in the Bosnian ministry of public affairs
said the government was doing all it could.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bosnian government has problems of its own,'' the official
said, asking that his name not be used. ``The Bosnian government,
the Bosnian people, we have a lot of refugees of our own to take
care of.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot talk about is the situation fair, or unfair,'' he
added. ``These people didn't come here because they wanted to. They
fled terrorism. But there's not much we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bosnia couldn't stop the Kosovo refugees from coming.
Famous for being the only country in the world with no visa
requirements for foreigners, much of Bosnia's border with
Yugoslavia is controlled by Bosnian Serbs -- who don't even require
passports for people coming from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Without passports or money or family connections, the Kosovo
refugees here aren't able to leave Bosnia. And the other countries
of Europe haven't been willing to accept them, even if they did
have passports and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here, like in a trap,'' said Milazim Hasani. ``We
expected we could go somewhere from here. But where can we go?''
</P>
<P>
   Hasani fled Kosovo with his wife and two children -- one three
years old, one 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope NATO will take some steps. The best solution for us is
to go back to Kosovo,'' he said. ``But it seems like the
international community is trying to make a situation like they did
in Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasani blames inaction by the international community for his
problems, like many Bosnians did during the ethnic war here. But
officials worry that it's too late for the international community
to do anything in Kosovo that will help the people in the Coca-Cola
plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to find a solution for these people for the
winter,'' Ward said. ``You can't expect them to repatriate during
the winter. They'll be here until spring at least.''
</P>
<P>
   UNHCR is working to arrange a different facility for the
refugees in the Coke factory.
</P>
<P>
   For now, 1,076 people take showers in a hut with seven stalls
and only one small boiler to heat the water. They wash their dishes
under a spigot of nonpurified water in the middle of a parking lot.
They sleep on mats on the floor of the drafty warehouse with holes
in the roof. Their children play with old Coca-Cola crates, and the
garbage they find in piles around the camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are killing our children here,'' said Ibrahim Shala, a sort
of mayor of the camp. ``Look at our pavilions, with 600 people
sleeping in one of them every night. There are diseases being
spread around. Our children are in mortal danger here.''
</P>
<P>
   When no Bosnian doctor came to the camp, Dr. Lecaj Shukri,
himself a refugee from Kosovo living with family in the area,
volunteered to see patients in a makeshift clinic. After seeing
lots of skin infections, diarrhea, dehydration and
gastro-intestinal problems -- even two cases of hepatitis -- he
wonders aloud ``why we don't have an epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions here are very bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo refugees in the Coca-Cola plant are living in, by
far, the worst conditions in Bosnia. But even here, they are better
off than they would be in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the bombing, they destroyed everything which survived,''
said Nusreta Rama of the Serbian forces that attacked her village.
``They don't want the people back. They burned everything they
didn't steal. All that is left of my house is the basement.''
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't even think about when she will go back to Kosovo,
though she says she wants to return to her home someday. Right now,
life in the camp occupies her thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of being lucky to be out of Kosovo, it's hard to
say,'' Shala said. ``Maybe we are happy because we escaped the
possibility of being shot. But if we stay here longer, if winter
comes and we are here, it will be a catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
