<HEADER>
A2213 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  MORE     10-12 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 MORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-IRISH-BETRAYAL-2ND &LR;   &UR; TAKE-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CORK, Ireland: ... ``The Informer'' &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, O'Callaghan grew disillusioned and dismayed
with the IRA, convinced it indulged in the very acts of
sectarianism and barbarism that it condemned as endemic to the
British state in Northern Ireland it was sworn to destroy.
</P>
<P>
   He decided to get back at the IRA by destroying it from within.
He compromised many IRA missions, none more sensational than a 1983
plan to murder Diana, princess of Wales, and Prince Charles.
O'Callaghan also unwittingly caused the disappearance and presumed
murder of a Quincy man named John McIntyre, who was blamed by
Boston gangsters for compromising a 1984 gun-running mission. In
fact, it was O'Callaghan who gave up the Valhalla, the trawler used
to ferry $1 million of guns to Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about who compromised the Valhalla was intense,
especially after Corcoran's body turned up in March 1985. Without
elaboration, the IRA said Corcoran had been executed for informing.
Some people assumed Corcoran ruined the gun-running mission.
</P>
<P>
   But according to O'Callaghan, Corcoran had been under suspicion
by the IRA for other botched operations. After IRA men abducted him
and accused him of informing, Corcoran quickly confessed, according
to O'Callaghan, who said he later taped Corcoran's admissions.
</P>
<P>
   O'Callaghan said he suggested the IRA hold a press conference
and have Corcoran tell his story to embarrass the police and their
methods of recruiting informers. His motive, he said, was to save
Corcoran. But he said his superior, reputed IRA chief of staff
Kevin McKenna, dismissed the idea, saying, ``Kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Callaghan says he called police, giving them the location of
the Kerry farmhouse where Corcoran was being held. Police refuse to
discuss that allegation. Eventually, it came down to O'Callaghan
and Corcoran. O'Callaghan briefly flirted with the idea of telling
him to run off. But he said that would have amounted to his own
death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the mask off him,'' O'Callaghan said in 1994. ``It was
just the most pathetic sight. To the very end, I was hoping the
Gards (police) would come through the door, just take Corcoran and
his wife away somewhere, give them a new life, a new identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, O'Callaghan said, convinced there was no way out, he
shot Corcoran in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Now, O'Callaghan tells a different story. In his book, he says
he confessed to force the police to conduct an investigation. While
admitting that ``with hindsight such a course of action may seem
foolhardy and difficult to understand,'' O'Callaghan wrote, ``I
knew that my motives were well intentioned. I wanted the truth to
come out.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Callaghan says he has not been told by his handlers why
Corcoran was allowed to die. ``Was I regarded as more valuable than
Corcoran and therefore to be protected even at the cost of his
life?'' he asks. ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither does Eileen Corcoran. But she considers O'Callaghan's
word unreliable. She is not alone. When O'Callaghan testified for
the Sunday Times of London last spring in a libel case brought by
IRA leader Thomas ``Slab'' Murphy, he did little to bolster his
credibility. When Murphy's lawyer asked O'Callaghan to name any
person to whom he had told the truth in the past 10 years,
O'Callaghan replied, ``It's extremely difficult to give you that
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in Belfast, a man who was a senior figure in the
IRA at the time of Corcoran's murder said O'Callaghan fingered
Corcoran as an informer and took it upon himself to kill Corcoran
after Corcoran confessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corcoran was a tout,'' said the man, who spoke on the
condition that he not be named because he would be subject to
arrest for IRA membership. ``The problem is, we didn't know
O'Callaghan was a tout at the time. Now, in hindsight, you can see
why O'Callaghan was so anxious to do him.''
</P>
<P>
   As the IRA man sees it, killing Corcoran helped O'Callaghan
ingratiate himself with his IRA superiors, showing them he remained
a committed revolutionary willing to kill even a friend on orders,
while also eliminating the possibility that Corcoran might blow his
cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``O'Callaghan knew the Gards wouldn't expose him, so it was
perfect,'' said the IRA man who, despite his hatred of O'Callaghan,
steadfastly believes the IRA was entitled to kill Corcoran because
``he knew the rules when he got involved.''
</P>
<P>
   If O'Callaghan's original tale had the ring of truth, his new
claim has the ring of self-preservation. He is open to prosecution
in the Irish Republic. But there is nothing to suggest the Irish
government is anxious to get to the bottom of this.
</P>
<P>
   A few months before he became Ireland's justice minister in June
1997, John O'Donoghue promised to find out what happened to
Corcoran. But since taking office, O'Donoghue has said only that
the matter is under investigation. Police held O'Callaghan for two
days of questioning in Dublin before releasing him without charge
May 1. Damian Hogan, a police spokesman, said only that the
investigation is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians, meanwhile, have failed Eileen Corcoran, whose
plaintive cries for help have fallen on deaf ears. Dick Spring, the
former deputy prime minister, is the only one who has responded,
demanding that the police and government clear the air, ``for the
family's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring's outrage is isolated. Other members of the Dail,
Ireland's Parliament, won't talk about it. This is as much a
cultural as political phenomenon. Since achieving partial
independence in 1922, Ireland has remained one of the most
conservative and authoritarian democracies in Europe. While Irish
politicians seldom hesitate to condemn misconduct by the
British-controlled Royal Ulster Constabulary in Northern Ireland,
they rarely criticize the Garda Siochana. The police and Justice
Department are excluded from Ireland's Freedom of Information Act,
which became law this year.
</P>
<P>
   In Ireland, the police do largely what they want, so there is no
expectation that they should tell Eileen Corcoran why her husband
was killed, nor is there any real public pressure on them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in her living room with her eldest daughter, Catherine,
Eileen Corcoran begins to cry as she explains how important it is
for her and her children to know what happened to her husband, what
his last words were. ``Did he say anything about us?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine is resolute. ``This has devastated our family, and no
one has given us the decency of explaining what happened,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   John Corcoran was not the only member of his family to fall
victim to IRA brutality and police indifference. Eight years after
his murder, his daughter Ursula, 18, hanged herself in the family's
back yard.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   As a 10-year-old, Ursula took her father's death the hardest.
She was hysterical and had to be sedated. As she grew into
adolescence, she had trouble sleeping. The image of his body,
stuffed into a sleeping bag and dumped by the side of a road,
haunted her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It destroyed her soul,'' her mother said, sighing. ``There
have been a lot of souls destroyed by this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
