<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2215 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRISH-BETRAYAL-BOS2TA     10-12 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-BETRAYAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETRAYED _ BUT BY WHOM? IRISH FAMILY SEEKS ANWSWERS IN KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORK, Ireland _ Someone owes Eileen Corcoran an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years ago, her husband was marched into a field and
ordered to kneel. After John Corcoran mumbled a prayer, someone put
the muzzle of a pistol to the back of his head and fired.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 45, with a wife and eight children at home, John
Corcoran died the ignominious death of an informer, the worst of
all possible deaths in Ireland, a nation that for centuries was
betrayed by the words of those who sold out their country for money
or revenge.
</P>
<P>
   If Corcoran was a traitor to the Irish Republican Army, which
killed him, then he died in service to the Republic of Ireland,
which considers the IRA as much a threat to its sovereignty and
national security as Britain does.
</P>
<P>
   But neither the IRA, which claimed his murder in a terse
statement, nor the Irish police, who refuse to confirm or deny that
Corcoran worked for them, will disclose the circumstances of his
death.
</P>
<P>
   That means Eileen Corcoran and her children sit here in a quiet
neighborhood outside the city where Frank O'Connor mastered the
short story, waiting for an explanation, frustrated by the unknown
and official indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Corcoran believes her husband was sacrificed by the Garda
Siochana, Ireland's national police force, to protect its most
prized informer ever: Sean O'Callaghan.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the family's grief, O'Callaghan, a confessed IRA
assassin, has given conflicting accounts about his role in the
murder. In a 1994 jailhouse interview with the Globe, O'Callaghan
said he shot Corcoran because IRA superiors ordered him to, but
insisted he had earlier begged his police handlers to rescue
Corcoran. He said he never learned why police ignored his calls.
</P>
<P>
   Today, two years after his release from prison, O'Callaghan is
the author of a best-selling book on his exploits as the most
senior IRA figure to turn on the organization. Now, O'Callaghan
denies he shot Corcoran, saying he made up the story so Irish
authorities would be forced to disclose what happened in that field
13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   O'Callaghan says he confessed to Corcoran's killing in a
convoluted but ultimately noble attempt to get to the bottom of the
murder that left a widow with eight children to raise.
</P>
<P>
   But that widow, Eileen Corcoran, isn't buying it. ``I don't
believe Sean O'Callaghan,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   As for police, she doesn't know whether to believe them or not,
because they have told her nothing.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the world has applauded the steady progress of the
Irish peace process, what happened to the Corcoran family and what
continues to haunt them is the bitter, enduring legacy of a dirty
war.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tale of idealism, nationalism, the brutality of
guerrilla warfare, and betrayal, of a country, of a cause, and of a
husband and father named John Corcoran, the odd man out in a deadly
game.
</P>
<P>
   John Corcoran grew up in Cork, an area far from Northern Ireland
but where revolutionary fervor still burns. Eileen Corcoran said
her husband was raised listening to romantic rebel tales by his
grandmother, a staunch republican who believed force was necessary
to end British control of the six counties that constitute Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Corcoran worked as a warehouse manager, but his wife knew he did
odd jobs on the side for the IRA. It was a strain on their
marriage. Years ago, the police arrested him. Eileen Corcoran
believes, but has no proof, that her husband made a fatal pact with
the police in which he agreed to pass on information about the IRA
if he was allowed to return to his family.
</P>
<P>
   Corcoran was a guppy in the IRA pond, someone so far removed
from the inner workings of the organization that all he could give
up were other small fish. O'Callaghan, however, was different. He
was a hardened killer and by 1985 had become one of the IRA's most
senior operatives. He had killed people in Northern Ireland, and
had worked with leading IRA figures there.
</P>
<P>
   During a 1994 interview in Maghaberry prison in Northern
Ireland, O'Callaghan described in detail how he shot Corcoran,
stressing that he had done so reluctantly, because his Irish police
handlers had not responded to his calls to rescue Corcoran, and
because he would have been shot by the IRA if he failed to carry
out an order to kill Corcoran.
</P>
<P>
   O'Callaghan was in prison after confessing to two murders in
Northern Ireland: a woman solider killed by a bomb, and an off-duty
Catholic policeman who was shot as he sat in a pub. In 1996, eight
years into a double life sentence, he was pardoned by Queen
Elizabeth, &UR;  &LR; then given a $300,000 advance to write his
autobiography, ``The Informer.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
