<HEADER>
A2231 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WORST-SFCHRON &LR;      10-12 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WORST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A DEEP FIELD, `PFEIFFER' TAKES WORST HONORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite incredible odds, the fulminations of the Rev. Jesse
Jackson and the demonstrated indifference of the American public,
``The Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer'' returned this week for a
second episode.
</P>
<P>
   Truly we live in an age of miracles.
</P>
<P>
   Back when networks were networks and not pipsqueaks like UPN,
this would never have happened.
</P>
<P>
   No sirree. When CBS put ``South of Sunset'' on the air in 1993,
and CBS had profound second thoughts, the cop show was canceled
like (set ital)that.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   One episode and gone, dead, kaput. The coffin was nailed shut
and the thing was buried before anyone debated how bad ``South of
Sunset'' was.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I believe that in the course of reviewing ``Desmond
Pfeiffer,'' I might have called it the worst show of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   We critics like calling things ``worst'' and ``best.'' Some
movie critics, usually the sorts who work on TV, come across ``one
of the year's 10 best films'' as many as 30 or 40 times during the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Some readers have e-mailed me since the ``Desmond Pfeiffer''
debut last Monday to say that my ``worst of the decade'' assessment
was harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Not only harsh, but thoughtless. To which, of course, I always
raise my hand and smile.
</P>
<P>
   In their judgment, ``Desmond Pfeiffer'' was not (set
ital)puh-(end ital)first worst, but in (set ital)puh-(end ital)fact
a poor second worst to some other monstrosity of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jenny McCarthy Show'' is mentioned. That's the MTV series
in which the former Playboy Playmate, in her show's first sketch,
poked her finger down her throat and spewed stage vomit. Then the
show got bad.
</P>
<P>
   That was a cable show. Listen up. If we're going to include
cable, then I'm just not going to participate in this discussion.
Period.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, I reviewed ``The Jenny McCarthy Show'' and the
regrettable Fox series ``Pauly,'' with that annoying Pauly Shore,
at the same time last year and declared that they were two of the
worst shows ever.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind decade. Ever. And that seems worse than ``Desmond
Pfeiffer.''
</P>
<P>
   But we're really unable to put stink bombs extraordinaire on
balance scales and say (set ital)phew,(end ital) this is
scientifically the more malodorous.
</P>
<P>
   Or to subject the shows to a Stink-O-Meter test, where we hook
them to wires and find ``Desmond Pfeiffer'' posting a 9.8 compared
with a convincing 9.83 for ``Pauly.''
</P>
<P>
   No, as always, taste and smell are closely related. I'm not
recanting, exactly, but I'll admit that there have been plenty of
bad shows in the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cop Rock'' was in 1990. Actually, I thought it was an
interesting show. But it will always be remembered otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   An NBC executive's kids liked L.A. radio personalities Mark
Thompson and Brian Phelps, leading to a mishap called ``The
Adventures of Mark and Brian'' in 1991. It lasted 11 weeks. NBC
executives are stubborn critters.
</P>
<P>
   The appropriately named ``Woops!'' was on Fox for several weeks
in 1992. It was a wacky sitcom about nuclear war survivors. One of
my source books calls it ``a post-apocalyptic `Gilligan's
Island.''' Got your scent glands twitching?
</P>
<P>
   ``South of Sunset'' graced the 1993 season for that one
inglorious night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wild Oats,'' ``Hardball'' and ``Models Inc.'' brought up the
rear in 1994. Just for the heck of it, I'm awarding ``Models Inc.''
the Miss Congeniality award for bad TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pinky and the Brain'' didn't do much for me, but ``Brotherly
Love'' is an even worse memory from 1995. Too many brothers. Too
much TV love. Bad taste in mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nick Freno: Licensed Teacher'' came along in 1996 and went on
to become the least watched network series for the next two
seasons. Which made it a licensed loser. But still, remember ``Lush
Life'' on Fox, with Lori (``Tank Girl'') Petty? She tanked. Look at
it this way. Suddenly ``Brotherly Love'' looks like the stuff you
use to wash away the taste of ``Lush Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, 1997. Who was cuter in ``Meego,'' Bronson Pinchot or the
kid? Trick question _ they were both awful. But I hated the insipid
genie series ``You Wish'' (from the creative mind that brought you
``Charles in Charge'') even more.
</P>
<P>
   We're back to ``The Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer,'' with its
Lincoln log anatomical jokes. Is it that much worse than ``The Army
Show'' or ``Mercy Point'' or ``Holding the Baby'' or the yet-to-air
``Wind on Water''?
</P>
<P>
   I'm glad I asked myself that question, because it is. In fact,
I'm now surer than ever, convinced beyond the shadow of a ratings
point, that ``Desmond Pfeiffer'' is indeed the worst show of the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   At least until tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
