<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2241 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-SPACE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     10-12 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-SPACE-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   TAKE-BOS  
 CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla.: ... ``the elderly''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researchers know, moreover, that space flight has a number of
effects on the cardiovascular system, that returning astronauts who
try to stand up can even lose consciousness, and that the heart
actually gets smaller during long flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that aging has some similar effects on the
cardiovascular system,'' said Richard J. Cohen, a Harvard-MIT
Division of Health Sciences and Technology professor who heads the
cardiovascular alterations team for the National Space Biomedical
Research Institute. ``The studies that will be done on Senator
Glenn might tell us whether aging makes some of these effects more
severe. And we may learn some things from space flight about how
aging affects the cardiovascular system.''
</P>
<P>
   All that is the pretext. What matters here at Cape Canaveral,
where the 25th mission of Discovery and the 94th mission of the
17-year-old Space Shuttle program is nearing its countdown, is the
context. And that is unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Glenn was hoisted above a booster rocket, the
nation was involved in a great struggle for prestige and power, and
though the space program was cloaked in romance it was in reality a
proxy for realpolitik.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months earlier, Yuri A. Gagarin, a 27-year-old Russian test
pilot, had orbited the earth once, traveling 25,000 miles in 108
minutes. ``Let the capitalist countries try to catch up,'' Soviet
leader Nikita Khruschev told Gagarin.
</P>
<P>
   Catching up did not prove to be easy. Glenn was in the control
center when an unmanned test orbital mission made a perfect liftoff
from Pad 14. Forty seconds later the Atlas booster, which weighed
135 tons, exploded. ``We looked at each other,'' Glenn said, ``and
thought we'd better have a little chat with the engineers, which we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were the days of NASA's innocence, and perhaps of its
greatest risks. ``Back in those days, we were trying to figure out
whether we could even do space flight,'' Glenn said. ``Doctors were
worried about stuff like whether our eyeballs would change in
flight and we wouldn't be able to see anything, or whether we could
even swallow in space. Those things were up in the air in 1961. We
needed to find out whether space flight was possible.''
</P>
<P>
   One sentence in a popular 1961 paperback, Martin Cadin's ``Man
into Space,'' inadvertently conveyed the risk involved in the first
flights: ``Certainly the astronauts of Project Mercury are being
given the greatest possible chances of survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan B. Shepard and Virgil I. Grissom made successful suborbital
flights in 1961, but though they won headlines, the politicians and
the space professionals knew they had only nicked the surface of
space. It was an orbital flight that mattered, and America didn't
have one yet.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's frustration grew. Ten times Glenn was scheduled to
ride his Atlas booster into orbit, and each time adverse weather or
technical problems caused the flight to be postponed. The 11th
time, on Feb. 20, 1962, the booster pierced the sky, and three
words &UR;  &LR; uttered from Mission Control, pierced the American
consciousness: ``Godspeed, John Glenn.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's pulse rate at liftoff was 110 beats per minute, far less
than Shepard's (126) or Grissom's (162). And for two orbits the
flight went as planned. Then came a cascade of troubles. His
controls went haywire. (The astronaut could die in space.) The heat
shield worked itself loose. (The astronaut could die in the earth's
atmosphere.)
</P>
<P>
   The world held its breath.
</P>
<P>
   But the important thing, according to Glenn, who has relived
those moments for 36 years, is that the world watched it all _ the
launch, the peril, the recovery in the ocean _ in real time, which
seemed like forever but in reality was only 4 hours, 55 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all open, open to the whole world,'' Glenn said. ``That
was a turning point in our national psyche. People stood in those
parades mopping their eyes, they were crying so much.'' In New
York, the cheers came from 4 million people. Later that day
sanitation crews in lower Manhattan swept up a record 3.5 million
tons of ticker tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did something that was new,'' Glenn said. ``I laid the
groundwork for the other flights. Now we're using space for what I
thought we eventually would use it for _ to benefit people back
here. We did basic research back then. We still only have our toe
in the door, but we're doing more and more important research every
time.''
</P>
<P>
   One more time, Glenn is on the verge of space flight. One more
time, Glenn is a national symbol. One more time: Godspeed, John
Glenn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
