<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2250 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-SPACE-BOS-2TAKE     10-12 1816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-SPACE-BOS-2TAKES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HERO OF OUR AGE SETS OFF ON ANOTHER PIONEER FLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Say this about John Glenn, World War II
and Korea veteran, test pilot, Mercury astronaut, legislator,
presidential candidate, Space Shuttle payload specialist, American
hero: He has grit. Staying power. And a willingness to try new
things. A resume for the ages, or at least our age.
</P>
<P>
   And an enduring place in the national imagination.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other figure of our time, John Herschell Glenn
Jr., a product of the center of the country and a devout acolyte of
the center in American politics, has remained at the center of the
action of our national life _ longer than Charles Lindbergh, longer
than Richard Nixon, longer than John Wayne, longer than almost
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   And now, at 77, this man _ who set a transcontinental speed
record in an F8U Crusader fighter in July 1957, who was a cameo
figure in Camelot, who was a stalwart of the Senate for nearly a
quarter-century _ is preparing to strap himself in a spacecraft
again and be hurled, against the force of gravity and maybe against
all odds and all reason, into the heavens for a victory lap around
the world. It is an act of courage, madness, stubbornness,
perseverence _ and publicity.
</P>
<P>
   And it is a moment of nostalgia for the Model T days of our age
of space discovery. There was one man, alone, in Friendship 7 in
1962. Glenn joins a crew of five men and a woman on Discovery on
Oct. 29. There were 20 circuit breakers on Friendship 7. There are
961 on Discovery. There were 48 items stowed on Friendship 7. There
are about 2,600 on Discovery. There were 56 toggle switches on
Friendship 7. There are 856 on Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The crew compartment on Friendship 7 was 36 cubic feet. On
Discovery it is 2,325 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mercury was small,'' Glenn was saying the other day. Unlike
most overachievers, he is a man of understatement. And though he
reflects his time, he is remarkably unreflective. ``All I could do
is get in and be in the contour couch. At best I could loosen the
straps. But I had to sit still. The instrument panel was only 23
inches from the bridge of my nose. Now it's much different.''
</P>
<P>
   Here at Cape Canaveral, where old rocket boosters litter the
landscape like some space-age Stonehenge, Glenn is forever clad in
silver, one of the flyboys of the New Frontier, the wisecracking,
envelope-stretching, death-defying Mercury astronauts who climbed
atop the Redstone and Atlas rockets, squeezed into a space capsule
and, as the world watched on black-and-white televisions in
classrooms and train stations and big urban squares, became the
pioneers of the modern age.
</P>
<P>
   And so last week, when he sat behind the wheel of an armored
vehicle called an M1-13 in the shadow of Pad 39B to practice an
emergency escape technique, or entered a space craft for the first
time in 36 years, he not only looked like a museum piece. He was
one.
</P>
<P>
   But in a way it dos not matter that Glenn looks a lot older in
the blue cotton jumpsuit of the Shuttle crew than he does in the
standard blue business suit of the Senate. (In both roles, he's
been wearing the American flag on his sleeve for decades.) Nor does
it matter that he seemed a bit self-conscious among astronauts who
weren't even toddlers (one wasn't even born) when he piloted
Friendship 7 into space, becoming both the first American to orbit
the earth and an enduring emblem of American courage and resolve in
the Cold War years.
</P>
<P>
   It mattered only that John Glenn, who was here so long ago, was
here again, training amid the growls of a menacing alligator in one
of Cape Canaveral's many swamps, ready to be a symbol for his
country again.
</P>
<P>
   This time he is John Glenn, super senior. This time he is the
symbol not of what a youthful nation with a cult-like worship of
vigor dared to do, but a symbol of what an aging nation that has
come to realize many of its dreams is willing and able to do.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, who has led the life of his times, is having the time of
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's the kind of guy who doesn't change heartbeat or
expression no matter what he's doing, even if he's over Korea and
his plane is being shot at,'' said Democratic Senator Patrick J.
Leahy of Vermont, who like Glenn was elected to the Senate in 1974
and who, even though the launch is scheduled for less than a week
before the midterm congressional elections, will be here at the
Kennedy Space Center to watch Glenn go back into orbit. ``But when
he talks about this _ about this flight _ he looks 25 years younger
and is really, really excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily when the village elders talk about an established
figure hanging around with people younger than his own daughter
there are snickers, looks of disapproval, and the phrase ``midlife
crisis'' hangs ominously in the air. Not everyone approves of what
NASA is permitting Glenn to do. Veteran astronaut Story Musgrave,
for example, has openly criticized Glenn's role and has suggested
that the senator has not been training rigorously enough.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a rhyme, or at least poetic justice, and maybe even
a reason for Glenn's role.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn won his berth on Discovery after convincing NASA officials
that he was uniquely qualified to conduct experiments that might
help scientists better understand the process of aging _ in space
and on earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be able not only to benefit the astronauts on long
flights but also work on the frailties of old age back here on
earth,'' Glenn said in an interview. ``I was feeling for all these
years that my age was a detriment to going back into space, but
suddenly it's an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers are dubious that much can be learned from
Glenn's one-man experiment. But others hope to adapt the methods to
combat the body's disorientation in space to help earthbound
patients, especially older people who fall frequently, with walking
and posture disorders. These scientists hope, moreover, that space
travel might provide hints on how biochemical signals affect bone
formation in astronauts, hints that might help prevent osteoporosis
in the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-GLENN-SPACE-2ND &LR;   &UR; TAKE-BOS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla.: ... ``the elderly'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Researchers know, moreover, that space flight has a number of
effects on the cardiovascular system, that returning astronauts who
try to stand up can even lose consciousness, and that the heart
actually gets smaller during long flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that aging has some similar effects on the
cardiovascular system,'' said Richard J. Cohen, a Harvard-MIT
Division of Health Sciences and Technology professor who heads the
cardiovascular alterations team for the National Space Biomedical
Research Institute. ``The studies that will be done on Senator
Glenn might tell us whether aging makes some of these effects more
severe. And we may learn some things from space flight about how
aging affects the cardiovascular system.''
</P>
<P>
   All that is the pretext. What matters here at Cape Canaveral,
where the 25th mission of Discovery and the 94th mission of the
17-year-old Space Shuttle program is nearing its countdown, is the
context. And that is unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Glenn was hoisted above a booster rocket, the
nation was involved in a great struggle for prestige and power, and
though the space program was cloaked in romance it was in reality a
proxy for realpolitik.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months earlier, Yuri A. Gagarin, a 27-year-old Russian test
pilot, had orbited the earth once, traveling 25,000 miles in 108
minutes. ``Let the capitalist countries try to catch up,'' Soviet
leader Nikita Khruschev told Gagarin.
</P>
<P>
   Catching up did not prove to be easy. Glenn was in the control
center when an unmanned test orbital mission made a perfect liftoff
from Pad 14. Forty seconds later the Atlas booster, which weighed
135 tons, exploded. ``We looked at each other,'' Glenn said, ``and
thought we'd better have a little chat with the engineers, which we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were the days of NASA's innocence, and perhaps of its
greatest risks. ``Back in those days, we were trying to figure out
whether we could even do space flight,'' Glenn said. ``Doctors were
worried about stuff like whether our eyeballs would change in
flight and we wouldn't be able to see anything, or whether we could
even swallow in space. Those things were up in the air in 1961. We
needed to find out whether space flight was possible.''
</P>
<P>
   One sentence in a popular 1961 paperback, Martin Cadin's ``Man
into Space,'' inadvertently conveyed the risk involved in the first
