given the greatest possible chances of survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan B. Shepard and Virgil I. Grissom made successful suborbital
flights in 1961, but though they won headlines, the politicians and
the space professionals knew they had only nicked the surface of
space. It was an orbital flight that mattered, and America didn't
have one yet.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's frustration grew. Ten times Glenn was scheduled to
ride his Atlas booster into orbit, and each time adverse weather or
technical problems caused the flight to be postponed. The 11th
time, on Feb. 20, 1962, the booster pierced the sky, and three
words &UR;  &LR; uttered from Mission Control, pierced the American
consciousness: ``Godspeed, John Glenn.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's pulse rate at liftoff was 110 beats per minute, far less
than Shepard's (126) or Grissom's (162). And for two orbits the
flight went as planned. Then came a cascade of troubles. His
controls went haywire. (The astronaut could die in space.) The heat
shield worked itself loose. (The astronaut could die in the earth's
atmosphere.)
</P>
<P>
   The world held its breath.
</P>
<P>
   But the important thing, according to Glenn, who has relived
those moments for 36 years, is that the world watched it all _ the
launch, the peril, the recovery in the ocean _ in real time, which
seemed like forever but in reality was only 4 hours, 55 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all open, open to the whole world,'' Glenn said. ``That
was a turning point in our national psyche. People stood in those
parades mopping their eyes, they were crying so much.'' In New
York, the cheers came from 4 million people. Later that day
sanitation crews in lower Manhattan swept up a record 3.5 million
tons of ticker tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did something that was new,'' Glenn said. ``I laid the
groundwork for the other flights. Now we're using space for what I
thought we eventually would use it for _ to benefit people back
here. We did basic research back then. We still only have our toe
in the door, but we're doing more and more important research every
time.''
</P>
<P>
   One more time, Glenn is on the verge of space flight. One more
time, Glenn is a national symbol. One more time: Godspeed, John
Glenn.
</P>
</TEXT>
