<HEADER>
A2254 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HALLOWEEN-FEAR-LIFEBE     10-12 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLOWEEN-FEAR-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDLING THE FEAR FACTOR
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By CANDY SCHULMAN 
 c.1998 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a typical 3-year-old, my daughter Amy planned for Halloween
with gusto. She chose her own costume _ a purple leotard and a tutu
_ and wore it every day for weeks before the big event. She could
hardly wait to fill an entire bag with candy!
</P>
<P>
   Little did I know that Amy's Halloween would not be all smiles.
One minute she was shouting, ``Trick or treat!'' and the next she
was petrified of a teen-age witch we saw on our block.
</P>
<P>
   She flew into my arms, sobbing, ``I'm so scared!'' and demanding
to go home to Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed that our fun was ending so abruptly, I took Amy
home. As it turned out, she had a much better time greeting
trick-or-treaters at our door than she had venturing out into
unfamiliar Halloween country.
</P>
<P>
   I shouldn't have been so surprised by my daughter's reaction.
``It's not unusual for a 3-year-old to be overwhelmed on
Halloween,'' notes Ava Siegler, a child psychologist in New York
City and a contributing editor to Child magazine. ``Toddlers and
many preschoolers don't yet have the firm boundaries that help them
differentiate between what's real and what's pretend, making it
difficult for them to see scary things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Young children often don't like to be surprised,'' adds Karen
Marschke, a developmental specialist at the Corlears School in New
York City. ``They can't easily place new experiences into a context
that they understand, and this can leave them feeling confused and
upset.''
</P>
<P>
   How much Halloween excitement is appropriate for young kids? It
depends on your child's age and developmental stage.
</P>
<P>
   Babies are oblivious to what's going on; it's kids between 1 and
5 who are at risk of becoming frightened by what they're exposed to
on Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   But even more essential than following age guidelines is
``taking into account your child's temperament and personality,''
notes Marschke. While an outgoing toddler may thrive on the
excitement, one who's slow to warm up or easily upset would benefit
from a more cautious approach.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Toddlers &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   Keep it low key. Kids under age 3 are really not ready to go
trick-or-treating yet; they will feel much safer at home with you.
Many don't even enjoy the dressing-up part, since they often find
costumes constricting. It's important for you to keep expectations
reasonable and to plan activities that are short and predictable,
like a Halloween puppet show.
</P>
<P>
   If your child wants to dress up, a quick trip to a relative's
house to show off her costume is enough.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preschoolers &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   Stay flexible. Children age 3 and older can better understand
the concept of pretend versus real, and are therefore ready to get
more involved in Halloween activities, including trick-or-treating.
But remember that even preschoolers can have a wide range of
reactions to Halloween _ from delight to terror.
</P>
<P>
   Before the big day, prepare your child for what's to come. Look
at costumes in a store, pointing out that people will be wearing
them. Say, ``This is a day when kids put on funny or scary outfits.
You'll see some ghosts and witches, but remember that underneath
each costume is a little boy like you,'' says Siegler.
</P>
<P>
   When planning activities, remember shorter is better. Limit
trick-or-treating to a few close friends or neighbors, so your
child doesn't get overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how much you prepare, if on the big day your child
still seems frightened, then you need to accept that he's not ready
yet. ``Parents have to determine how much of this holiday is for
them _ because they want to see their child dressed as a pumpkin _
and how much of it kids really enjoy,'' adds Siegler. ``Halloween
is not just about a photo-op. It's a children's holiday, so if they
are not having fun, don't celebrate it.''
</P>
<P>
   If you follow your child's cues and stay flexible, Halloween
will be an adventure to remember. And when he's ready, you'll snap
photos galore.
</P>
<P>
   ( &UR; Candy Schulman lives with her husband and daughter in New York
City.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
