<HEADLINE>
A RUN ON THE WILD SIDE
</HEADLINE>
  With a color slide of participants in 1997 marathon running along
Fourth Avenue in Manhattan 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By ANDREW BLUM 
 copyright 1998 Andrew Blum 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What has 30,000 slightly crazed participants, more
than 2 million spectators and 40 bands along miles of streets all
over New York City?
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Marathon, of course, with this year's 29th
running Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But the race is not just for New Yorkers. About half of the
American participants, from 7,000 to 10,000 men and women, come
from elsewhere in the United States. Another 10,000 are foreign
runners; last year 95 other countries were represented, led by
France, Germany and Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   As this mass of humanity spreads along the route, runners see
parts of New York that many natives never see in their lifetimes,
let alone in one day. And runners are cheered on by spectators
sometimes 10 deep along the sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in Staten Island, the race goes through Brooklyn,
Queens, into Manhattan, briefly into the Bronx and back into
Manhattan, finishing after 26.2 miles at Tavern on the Green in
Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Lately the scene at the 10:40 a.m. start has been a wild one. So
many runners throng the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge that many have to
walk the first mile, with times running as long as 10 minutes. On
the plus side: In clear weather from the bridge's mid-point runners
have a spectacular view of the city, one you'll never get from a
tour bus and perhaps not even from an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Each neighborhood has its history and quirks. Staten Island is
New York's forgotten borough and home of a succession movement.
Brooklyn, founded in 1636, was New York's rival until its
annexation 100 years ago. Queens was named for Catherine Brahanza,
King Charles II's queen. The Bronx is home (for now) of the New
York Yankees (an election will decide the fate of a stadium
proposed for Manhattan's West Side). And to reach that finish line
in Manhattan is, as the song goes, ``to be a part of it, New York,
New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing is the best part of the marathon. The worst, of
course, is hitting The Wall, too often the fate of runners who get
caught up in pre-race excitement. The best advice for average
runners is go out slow, remain steady and save something for the
end.
</P>
<P>
   The wall of fatigue is usually found in the Bronx around the
20-mile mark. The crowds are sparse; the elite runners have already
finished. It's you and the road, and you have to tough it out
mentally to keep going.
</P>
<P>
   Here you might regret having told yourself beforehand, I have to
do three hours or a personal best. Finishing is an accomplishment
in itself.
</P>
<P>
   (I know firsthand. In my first and only marathon, I ran New York
at age 40. My goal was breaking three hours. At the end, I was
happy just to cross the finish line, at three hours 41 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   For your efforts, there's a medal and a long look back at what
you accomplished. And, in passing, a streetwise tour of the five
boroughs. Better than a tourist bus any day.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Andrew Blum is a New York-based free-lance writer. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
