<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2264 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MADIGAN-ESSAY-1400(2T     10-12 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADIGAN-ESSAY-1400(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY AREN'T MORE PARENTS FURIOUS OVER BILL CLINTON'S BAD BEHAVIOR?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since January, my wife and I have never watched the TV news
without a mute button within reach. When President Clinton and his
troubles come up around our 7-year-old son, we speak in code. We
closely monitor the headlines, censoring any mention of the squalor
that has become our national life.
</P>
<P>
   And for several months, our efforts seemed to succeed. Clinton's
grand jury testimony, the furor over his address to the nation, the
release of the Starr Report, all came and went with Patrick still
oblivious. Or so we thought.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on a recent night, came the question:
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that Monica Lewinsky?'' Patrick asked when Hillary Clinton
appeared on the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   My head swiveled toward him. My heart sank.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I said. ``That's the president's wife. And how do you
know about Monica Lewinsky?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding?'' he said. ``The news is crazy about her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, just who is Monica Lewinsky?'' I asked, trying to assess
the damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Bill Clinton is sorry about her, or something like that,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he returned to his childish business. I have had a more
difficult time going back to mine. Instead, my anger builds, my
sense of violation. What else has Patrick heard about? The dress?
The cigar? I'll admit it: I'm afraid to ask.
</P>
<P>
   My son's question was inevitable, I guess. In this media age, no
parent can insulate children from this pornographic tragedy. So
Bill Clinton and his misdeeds collide head-on with the primal urge
to teach my son, to nurture and protect him. But protect from whom?
The stranger on the street corner? The bully on the playground? Sex
and violence on TV? The president of the United States?
</P>
<P>
   As if raising children in this country weren't hard enough.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   I wonder now about other parents out there, the extent to which
the mute button has become part of their parenting ritual, the
extent to which they, too, are outraged. Given Clinton's standing
in the polls, I wonder whether I'm alone. I seem to keep losing
arguments to liberal friends, who are surprised that I would
consider chronic lying, under oath and otherwise, an impeachable
offense.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't talked to my friend Tom in almost a year, so it was
inevitable that our discussion would turn to the president. He is a
highly educated liberal with a keen mind, and once again, as our
argument grew more intense, I found it impossible to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in the Starr Report (Tom had read it from cover to
cover) supports impeachment, he said. Clinton lied about sex, but
who wouldn't? FDR cheated. Kennedy cheated. Eisenhower cheated. All
politicians lie. This is no bedtime parable about George Washington
and the cherry tree, but a true-life tale of a typically randy
politician who lied to cover his flanks, de rigueur behavior in an
increasingly venal political world.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, my views sounded positively Victorian, prudish,
intolerant _ traits I've tended to condemn in others. Polling data
clearly supported Tom's view. I was the one out of step, and for a
few minutes, that bothered me. But only for a few minutes. If I'm
uncool, then so be it.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I try to teach our children to be honest. To admit
their mistakes and learn from them. That actions have consequences.
That laws are important. That our government bodies and the
presidency are institutions to respect, perhaps even aspire to.
That sex is the ultimate expression of love between a man and a
woman who are married.
</P>
<P>
   But at every turn, on every issue, we compete with the words and
deeds of the president, the embodiment of our national mythology.
There once was a time when the president ranked behind only God and
Mom and Dad in the pantheon of American childhood. Now we are
undermined from the same bully pulpit. This just should not be.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps we are not alone in our feelings, after all.
Clinton's behavior, says Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman, himself
a Democrat and Clinton friend, ``is as influential as the negative
messages communicated by the entertainment culture.''
</P>
<P>
   `` ... In choosing this path,'' Lieberman said, ``I fear that
the president has undercut the efforts of millions of American
parents, who are naturally trying to instill in our children the
value of honesty. As most any mother and father knows, kids have a
singular ability to detect double standards. So we can safely
assume that it will be that much more difficult to convince our
sons and daughters of the importance of telling the truth when the
most powerful man in the nation evades it.''
</P>
<P>
   So why do so few seem to care?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a great while,'' former Education Secretary William
Bennett writes in his bestselling new book, ``The Death of
Outrage,'' ``a single national event provides insight to where we
are and who we are and what we esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   O.J. Simpson's acquittal of murder charges in 1995 is one
example. For years, we had been congratulating ourselves on our
progress in race relations. Then came the verdict, and a stunning
demonstration as to the degree that issues of race still divide us.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   The current national trauma is another such window. Clinton's
steady approval ratings are attributable to much more than a robust
economy. More importantly, the polls point to a nation that seems
to have lost its way, to a tired, beleaguered society in which
there are fewer and fewer values upon which we can all agree.
</P>
<P>
   As Lieberman said on the Senate floor last month: ``I am afraid
that the misconduct the president has admitted may be reinforcing
one of the worst messages being delivered by our popular culture,
which is that values are fungible.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it the Jerry Springer Syndrome. The entertainment culture
has grown more and more base. The average American child will
witness 200,000 acts of violence on television by the time he or
she is 18, according to ``Selling Out America's Children,'' a 1994
book by Minneapolis psychologist David Walsh. As the title of
Bennett's book suggests, we are increasingly incapable of being
shocked.
</P>
<P>
   This ambivalence, this weariness, seems to have crept into the
unlikeliest of places. Recently, I called famed pediatrician Dr. T.
Berry Brazelton, expecting to find a man similarly appalled by
Clinton's betrayal of our families.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Brazelton was reticent, and said he is close to Hillary
Clinton, who he said is a wonderful person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to say anything to hurt her, or the things
she's working for,'' Brazelton said.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief discussion about how to talk to children about the
scandal, he went on to say that oral sex ``isn't as frightening to
them (children) as it is to us. Why pass on our anxiety?''
</P>
<P>
   Then, from Brazelton, this: ``We've allowed this to besmirch a
man who's doing a lot for the country, made more of it than it
really deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a few of us out there who would disagree.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   My friend Leslye Rood would be one. Her son, Timmy, is the same
age as my son, Patrick. For most of his life, Leslye and her
husband, Joel, have strived to inculcate in Timmy bedrock values
and a sense of our American past.
</P>
<P>
   So by the time he was 6, Timmy Rood could tell you about George
Washington and the American Revolution, Abraham Lincoln and
abolition of slavery, Franklin D. Roosevelt and World War II. It
was in the past year that he first spoke of a dream of becoming
president himself, his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before Timmy's own question, asked one night after
his parents hurriedly shut off the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   ``But why are people mad at the president?''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, like parents everywhere, Leslye and her husband were
forced to explain infidelity to a boy who was yet to turn 7.
Married people aren't supposed to have girlfriends, Timmy was told
by his parents, and the president had a girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, isn't he a daddy, too?'' Timmy asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, he's a daddy, too,'' his mother told him. ``And that's
another reason why people are upset.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he still married?'' Timmy asked. ``Is he still the girl's
daddy?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he was still married. Yes, he was still a daddy. Yes, it is
wrong to lie. Yes, it is confusing.
</P>
<P>
   But Timmy understood, only too well. As of last week, his dreams
were of playing professional soccer, and owning a company to clean
up the environment, but no longer of being president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is not in Timmy's realm anymore,'' Leslye told
me. ``And it's not because Timmy thinks it's above him. It's
because he thinks it's below him. When Timmy thinks of doing
something noble and significant with his life, he falls back on
these other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a world where the passion for good and the passion for
goals has been kind of suffocated,'' she said. ``It's like the
oxygen has been removed from the atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   But childish disillusionment doesn't seem to count for much when
the economy is booming. Undermining parents doesn't rise to the
level of an impeachable offense. So now we will keep our mute
buttons handy. We will continue to censor the headlines as best we
can. We will wonder where our values have gone. And we will thank
the heavens for Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
