<HEADER>
A2268 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DALLAS-MUSEUM-TEX     10-12 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALLAS-MUSEUM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAMMELL CROW'S ASIAN ART COLLECTION TO MAKE UP NEW MUSEUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When a guy walks into a room of major Asian artworks
and plops down in the first marble Mughal pagoda available, you
assume he has more than a passing familiarity with the material on
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Which would be where Trammell Crow Jr. comes from.
</P>
<P>
   The 46-year-old scion of commercial real estate magnate Trammell
Crow, he grew up with a number of these works _ the snowy white
pagoda for several years was at Millcreek, the Crow family farm
near Mineola, Texas _ and unpretentiously treats them like the old
friends they are.
</P>
<P>
   He pats a granite Indian bull on the head. He points to a pair
of Himalayan gilt-bronze figures and wishes they could be on his
night stand.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Crow clearly is the man in charge of an
ambitious project: a new $5 million museum showcasing the splendid
Asian artworks his parents have acquired during the past three
decades. Admission will be free, and expanded hours are planned to
ensure maximum public convenience.
</P>
<P>
   So here is Crow, asking why a section of gallery wall hasn't
been covered in silk, insisting that a backdrop no one will see is
painted black (just in case) and touting the cutting-edge,
electronic educational aids that will be installed in the new
museum's lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Trammell and Margaret Crow Collection of Asian Art,
it opens to the public Dec. 5 in a graceful, retrofitted pavilion
that rests at the foot of towering Trammell Crow Center. About 300
of young Crow's old friends will be displayed, including a fabulous
collection of Chinese jade objects, Japanese painted screens,
Indian and Southeast Asian sculptures and, yes, Himalayan
gilt-bronzes. Highlights include an outstanding Tang Dynasty horse,
the world's second-largest flawless crystal ball and a Chinese
scholar's desk furnished with several lovely accouterments for
contemplation and writing.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 200 to 250 items will be rotated periodically onto
display.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's emphasis will be on beautiful and unusual objects.
Crow makes it clear that archaic ax heads, though dear to scholars
and not entirely absent from the collection, hold little appeal for
him and weren't what sparked his father's love.
</P>
<P>
   The collection was born of the senior Crow's desire to diversify
his investments: He, of course, is the Dallas-based founder of a
company that has been the world's largest developer of commercial
properties and currently is the world's largest manager of
commercial properties.
</P>
<P>
   So, in 1971, Trammell Crow bought his first piece of carved
Chinese jade. Within three years, his passion for the stuff had
grown to where he bought an entire collection: the aptly named Moss
collection of more than 140 pieces of jade. Today, the Crow
collection of jades, alone, stands at more than 1,200 pieces.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Trammell Crow became not only a lover of jade, but a
Sinophile and lover of Asian art and culture in general, his son
says proudly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The various kids kind of caught a collecting bug from Dad over
the years,'' Crow adds, but then says, ``Actually none of us has so
much collected as we've borrowed from my father.''
</P>
<P>
   Crow and his four siblings first learned of the project almost
two years ago. Their mother and father called them together and,
after everyone milled around for a while, wondering what was up,
said they wanted to use their 3,000 works of Asian art to establish
a museum.
</P>
<P>
   They also appointed Trammell Jr. to make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never knew they were mulling it over,'' he says. ``But it
was probably an easy decision for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, though, carrying out his parents' decision wasn't
that easy.
</P>
<P>
   The project's first expert adviser _ Clarence Shangraw, emeritus
curator for San Francisco's Asian Art Museum _ edited objects for
display from 3,000 to about 550, but wasn't very helpful about
setting up museum administration. Former Dallas Museum of Art
director Rick Brettell came in next, but didn't much further the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jennifer Casler, the Kimbell Art Museum's curator of
Asian art, came on board early, to set up the educational program.
The Dallas Museum of Art, just across the street, lent Crow a
number of exhibition preparatory assistants. And Peggy Booher,
former director of InterCultura _ the now-defunct, Fort Worth-based
exhibitions organization _ came on board as acting director.
</P>
<P>
   So, as Crow and Booher mix joshing with serious talk about what
goes where, the prep staff installs lighting and unpacks objects.
Soon, in a matter of weeks, the rest of North Texas will enjoy what
one remarkable family has enjoyed and is ready to share.
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
