<HEADER>
A2276 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-DOCS-HANDWRITING-     10-12 0292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DOCS-HANDWRITING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UGLY HANDWRITING AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CORNELIA DEAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody knows it, but now researchers in Wales have proved it:
Doctors have rotten handwriting.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, from the Department of Public Health in
Swansea, studied 92 men and women at the health authority
headquarters, an accident and emergency department at one hospital,
and other departments at another hospital.
</P>
<P>
   They grouped the respondents into three classes: doctors, nurses
and other medical professionals, and administrative staff members.
</P>
<P>
   Participants were asked to provide handwriting samples,
including their names, the alphabet and numbers from 0 to 9. They
were told the samples would be used to evaluate software for
scanning handwriting. Instead, it was used to see how many samples
were legible.
</P>
<P>
   Nurses and other professionals had the clearest writing,
followed closely by the administrators. Doctors lagged far behind,
with almost twice as many illegible characters as those from the
other groups.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors were slightly older than the nurses and
administrators, but the age difference did not explain the
discrepancy, the researchers said. The doctors were all equally
illegible, regardless of age or sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study suggests that doctors, even when asked to be as
neat as possible, produce handwriting that is worse than that of
other professions,'' said the report in a recent issue of The
British Medical Journal.
</P>
<P>
   There was one bright spot: all three groups wrote numbers
clearly, which the researchers attributed to the necessity of
writing drug dosages clearly. That finding shows that doctors can
learn to write legibly. Maybe they just need to try harder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
