<HEADER>
A2312 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-NASA-MEMORIES-ART     10-12 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-NASA-MEMORIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANAVERAL'S HAUNTING RUINS OF NASA'S GOLDEN AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Three photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As NASA marks the 40th anniversary of its founding on Oct. 1,
1958, aspects of the occasion are more archeological than
astronautical. So it sometimes seems on the back roads and in the
weeds along the shore of Cape Canaveral, Fla., where the ruins
evoke memories of all those rockets in the early morning and the
eerie twilight after the cheering stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Sand blows over the artifacts of the golden age of American
space flight. Wild hogs root around the edges of derelict launching
pads. Steel beams that once braced Moon-bound ships lie rusting in
a field called the ``bone yard.'' Some scenes, where flowers and
weeds cover concrete fencing and bunkers, bear a haunting
resemblance to forlorn battlegrounds.
</P>
<P>
   This was a major battleground in a war, the Cold War between the
Soviet Union and the United States. Congress gave birth to NASA in
response to Sputnik, the world's first artificial satellite. Three
years later, NASA was challenged to beat Russia to the moon. Thus
began the Apollo Project, the golden age of space flight.
</P>
<P>
   The ruins of Canaveral can be read in two ways. As monuments of
inspired mobilization, they represent a progression of
technological steps leading to the moon, the early artifacts
abandoned like so many stone tools made obsolete by bronze and
iron. Some future archeologist might marvel at how rapidly the
space-age toolmakers progressed.
</P>
<P>
   But the ruins also are a stark reminder that NASA's best days
are behind it. The agency was a victim of its own success: This
prodigy of the Cold War promised us the moon, and delivered.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has had other successes, but its most celebrated mission in
a long time will be a nostalgic moment, not a giant leap for
mankind. The next space shuttle flight, scheduled for launching on
Oct. 29, will be about the past. John Glenn, 77, will be returning
to orbit, where in 1962 he brought respectability and hope to the
fledgling space program as the first American to orbit Earth.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's long-awaited next step into the future is supposed to
occur in November or December, with the first launching of
components for the International Space Station. But the Russians,
adversaries become allies, are having trouble paying for their
share of the project. A space station lacks the urgency and appeal
of the moon goal of old. And workers have painted ``Abandon in
Place'' on the mammoth concrete artifacts of the first space age.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2324 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-PLACEBO-DOCTORS-N     10-12 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PLACEBO-DOCTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTHUSIASM OF DOCTOR CAN GIVE PILL EXTRA KICK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., N.M.)   (af)  
 By SANDRA BLAKESLEE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though some people respond more strongly to placebos than others
do, it seems that everyone responds at some time or other. And
doctors seem to play a large role in the degree of that response.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that trumps everything is the enthusiastic
physician,'' said Dr. Dan Molerman of the University of Michigan.
For example, one study offered the same drug to patients with
identical symptoms, with one difference.
</P>
<P>
   Some were told by their physicians, ``This drug has been shown
to work,'' while others were told, ``I am not sure if this
treatment will work _ let's just try it.''
</P>
<P>
   The first group of patients did much better, Molerman said.
``The physician is an agent for optimism and hope and a great
inducer of beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Physicians can even fool themselves. Years ago, researchers
carried out controlled studies of a drug for angina or heart pain
and found it was no better than a placebo, Molerman said. Once
doctors knew that, its effectiveness fell.
</P>
<P>
   While doctors and patients affect one another's expectations,
both are swept up into a wider context of culture and biology, said
Dr. David Morris, an adjunct professor of medicine at the
University of New Mexico in Albuquerque. The brain circuits through
which placebos act, he said, are activated through the experience
of living in a particular culture.
</P>
<P>
   To explore the importance of cultural context, Molerman, in an
analysis forthcoming in the journal Medical Anthropology Quarterly,
compared 122 double-blind placebo-controlled ulcer studies from all
over the world. Doctors used the same techniques, the same drugs
and the same placebo pills and studied an image of the stomach
lining before and after treatment to see what worked.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs worked 75 percent to 80 percent of the time, Molerman
said, whereas the placebos worked from zero to 100 percent of the
time, depending on the country. The placebo healing rate for ulcers
in Germany was 60 percent, almost double the world average of 36
percent, which is about where the United States fell. But in
Brazil, the mean placebo healing rate was a startling 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have hint of what is going on here,'' Molerman said.
``I can only say that cultural differences affect ulcer treatments,
even though ulcers are the same the world over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
