<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2352 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPRAH-FILM-960(2Takes     10-12 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPRAH-FILM-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWERFUL, PASSIONATE OPRAH BRINGS MORRISON'S CHALLENGING NOVEL TO
SCREEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It's probably a ridiculous thing to say, but in person,
Oprah Winfrey is just like, well, Oprah Winfrey. Meeting actors,
one generally has to get past the fact that they're nothing like
the characters they play _ it IS called acting, after all _ and in
fact, not much like their talk-show personas either. But most
Americans who own televisions have spent some time with Winfrey,
whose combination of iron will and sensitivity has made her the
center of daytime media culture, if not the most powerful woman in
the United States. She's so much like the Oprah we see on her show
that you have to wonder if there's a private Oprah somewhere, who
sits back a remove, judging all the people who charge at her
familiarity and chatter away like old friends.
</P>
<P>
   She's not playful with her power either _ no one else could get
a major studio to finance ``Beloved,'' the story of a former slave
whose life is turned around by a woman who may be the ghost of her
dead infant daughter. ``Beloved,'' director Jonathan Demme's first
drama since ``Philadelphia,'' is probably the biggest-budgeted
black art film in the history of the medium, adapted from a novel
that daunts even the most attentive reader. (Toni Morrison's morose
and dissociative work is not the kind of material that regularly
delights the giant book club that Winfrey has created).
</P>
<P>
   ``Beloved'' is Winfrey's first starring role in a feature film,
and the first theatrical release she has appeared in since her
debut in 1985's ``The Color Purple,'' in which she appeared with
her ``Beloved'' leading man Danny Glover. Winfrey is the first to
admit that she's asking a lot of audiences to suspend disbelief _
to ignore her Oprahness _ and give in to the movie. ``Frankly,''
she says, ``I'm a little worried, not because of that _ I think
that people will accept me _ but because it's a unique movie.''
</P>
<P>
   And casting herself in the lead role of a movie made from a
novel by an African-American Nobel Prize winner is getting the
full-on media spotlight, with Winfey appearing on the covers of
Time and Vogue _ probably the first time that's happened since ...
well, at least since Madonna decided to release her midlife-crisis
electronica album. In an upcoming issue of Vanity Fair, Winfrey is
featured in a story about the three most powerful women in media _
the other two being Diane Sawyer and Barbara Walters.
</P>
<P>
   But there's nothing oppressive or heavy-handed about her in this
conversation. None of that New Age determination to teach the world
to sing in perfect harmony that has recently manifested itself on
her show comes up as she settles onto a sofa at the ruthlessly posh
Mansion on Turtle Creek. Instead, after a few moments of digressive
chat about talk shows _ and how none of the people who are getting
talk shows these days has any realization of how difficult doing
one is _ she allows that she doesn't watch much television at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I want to have a life,'' she says, simply. ``If you
want to have time to see your friends and read after work _ and we
do 200 shows a year _ then you don't have time for television. The
only one I pay any attention to is Rosie (O'Donnell). I like her.
We almost got into business with her, but it wasn't something I was
ready for at the time. I take my time deciding about what I'm going
to do, which is why it took me so long to be in another movie.''
Winfrey's dramatic appearances have been through her TV
productions, which include the miniseries ``The Women of Brewster
Place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to one of those people who got a (talk) show,''
she says, pondering the chatfest glut, ``and you can't even have a
conversation with this person. So why would anybody in their right
mind give this person a talk show? It's surprising to me how little
most of the people who make decisions about TV know about it. I
think it's because they don't go out and talk to people. So they
don't have any sense of what people want to see. It's what I do all
the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like when you see all these polls about the American people
having forgiven President Clinton. That's not what I was hearing
from the people who came to the show. That's why we did a show
about (that topic), and gave folks a chance to say what they
think.''
</P>
<P>
   When it's mentioned that the audience seemed to circle Clinton
like a lynch mob, she responds, ``Really? Is that what you think? I
thought they were just getting something off their chest. Yeah. I
do believe that people are more sophisticated than the media thinks
they are. But they were also mad, and that never came up
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey doesn't harangue, but her mastery of conversational
technique is subtle and acute _ you're never aware of any cunning.
Rather, you note that she regards the conversationalist with her
strictest concentration. She admits that ``Beloved'' is a tough
sell, because ``even I had a hard time getting through it. I kept
getting stuck on those first eight pages. I told Toni it was hard
to get through, that I had to work and she said, `It's called
reading, dear,''' Winfrey says, and laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I knew she didn't think I could do the part. `Oprah's so
emotional, and Sethe (Winfrey's character) is not. I'm just not
sure.' But she saw it and was surprised, and I said, `It's called
acting, dear,''' Winfrey says, savoring the joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extraordinary piece of work. And I thought (the book)
had more of a foreign-movie feel. So at first I was thinking of
maybe Peter Weir, or Jane Campion, because of what I thought they
could bring to it. But after I talked to Jonathan (Demme), I
realized that he had the right ideas for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, didn't she find ``The Piano'' kinda goofy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Um, you mean with that piano on the beach stuff?'' she says,
sheepishly. ``Yeah, I guess I did. But I wanted `Beloved' to be
treated as art, and that meant finding a director who can work as
an artist and has an artist's understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   She agrees that ``Beloved'' is a fuller vision of a world than
``The Color Purple,'' with its peculiar fear of sex. ``Frankly, I
was just happy to be in a movie, and learn from all those amazing
people _ Steven (Spielberg), Whoopi (Goldberg), Quincy (Jones).''
When Spielberg's reticence is mentioned, she nods in agreement.
``Yeah, (the movie's) got its problems. But what bothers is me is
... look at all those movies _ `Boyz 'N the Hood,' `Menace 2
Society' _ that are about kids killing kids, abusing women, that
get treated like art. But people jumped all over `Color Purple'
because they thought it was attacking black men. They missed the
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it got really interesting,'' Winfrey continues, frowning.
``I got to the Oscars''_ Winfrey got a Best Supporting Actress
nomination _ ``and there's the NAACP, out there protesting the
movie, carrying (protest signs) talking about all the harm it did
to the image of black men. Then, when we didn't win any awards and
I'm leaving, they're protesting because the movie got shut out and
that the Academy is racist. I guess they must've had other signs
ready, just in case. How do they work so fast?''
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey undoubtedly gave a lot of thought to the way the
material should be handled, and agrees there was an American
condescension to Morrison's work, not acknowledging its spiritual
connections to Gabriel Garcia Marquez and the like. ``It's true,''
she notes, ``people dismissed Toni's stuff as folklore, when it
really is like the Southern version of magic realism. If you grew
up in the South, you know those kinds of ghost stories and the kind
of spell they can weave.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison's writing is built on that Southern African-American
mysticism. So does Winfrey worry that the adaptation, with its
words like ``haints'' (the Southern term for ghosts) will leave the
mainstream white audience puzzled?
</P>
<P>
   ``That could very well be,'' she says, ``and not just because of
that. I mean, in some of the test screening, people would come out
and say, `This isn't a slave story. It's about a mother and her
daughter.' People have expectations about what to expect in movies
about slaves, and this is so much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a tough sell. That's why I'm trying to keep them very
specific in the marketing. It's important we give a sense of the
movie, and not give it all away. It is definitely a movie that made
me work hard, and will require that the audience works hard, too.''
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7614. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
