<SLUG> BC-BY-DESIGN-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAP PACKS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ The most surprising accessory seen so far on the
spring runways is the reinvented fanny pack. The trend started in
New York with Helmut Lang, who slung a holster-style bag around
models' waists and attached it to the thigh.
</P>
<P>
   A raft of variations have been seen here.
</P>
<P>
   In Dolce &AMP; Gabbana's D&AMP;G show, the models wore zippered pockets
in clear plastic on their belts. At Prada, bags rode in back on a
belt around the waist or hips while a tiny purse was strapped
around one model's arm. Missoni showed bags on belts around the
hips, and Trussardi had double bags on the back of belts. Tiny
purses circled the wrist at Versace.
</P>
<P>
   Bottega Veneta had several versions, including a fold-over bag
on a belt that can be converted to a shoulder bag, a holster that
goes around the shoulder and across the body, and a sizable flat
bag to wear around the hips like an apron.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
