<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-REFUGEES _ SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Sevdije Gashi
left Kosovo a few days after her village was attacked and her home
burned down by Yugoslav forces. Though the timing is never good for
war refugees, it was particularly bad for this mother of three. She
was about to have another baby. ``She was born on the bus to
Bosnia,'' Gashi said, shyly showing off her gurgling three-week old
daughter. ``My mother-in-law had just been arrested by the Serbian
Police. We had to leave.'' Now Gashi's family of six lives in an
abandoned Coca-Cola bottling plant here, eating, sleeping and
crying together on the 10-by-10-foot square of floor that has
become their home. More than 1,000 other refugees live in the same
factory, with no running water, no heat, and no idea what their
future holds as NATO officials debate air strikes to end the
conflict in Kosovo and winter looms in Sarajevo. (Nesmith, Cox News
Service). With photos. If NATO forces attack targets in Kosovo,
CoxNet will produce a page of background and feature stories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ Mayor Roxanne Qualls of
Cincinnati, a Democratic candidate for Congress, stirred
controversy by greeting President Clinton when he came to town to
raise money. Now she's trying to steer her campaign toward
friendlier territory. Like many of her fellow Democrats across the
country, she is pressing the issue of Social Security. The
president, too, has joined the effort with daily jibes at
Republicans. For Social Security recipients, always uneasy to have
the program in the crossfire, it's politics as usual this fall.
(Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GORE13 _ WEST PALM BEACH, FLA. _ Vice President Al Gore, filling
in for a president tied down by the last-minute flailings of a
Congress eager to get on the campaign trail, plans a two-stop visit
in South Florida, flying in to Palm Beach International at 10 a.m.
Tuesday. He will address a Unity brunch in Palm Beach and then make
some Everglades statement at the tarmac before he flies out of PBIA
around 1 p.m. (Staletovitch, West Palm Beach)
</P>
<P>
   CANCERDRUG _ The wave of the future in cancer drugs _
genetically-engineered chemicals that target the buliding blocks of
spreading cells _ is officially here. Amid hype and speculation,
the California company that developed Herceptin, the first of these
drugs for breast cancer, has worked around the clock to begin
shipping it to doctors this week, nearly three months ahead of
schedule and less than two weeks after the drug received FDA
approval. We talk to some of the first Texas women to have tried
Herceptin, which could be a wonder drug for many women who haven't
beaten breast cancer with conventional treatments. (Park, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   UT-NOBEL-PRIZE _ Ferid Murad, a researcher at the University of
Texas Health Science Center in Houston, will share the Nobel Prize
for Medicine with scientists at the State University of New York at
Brooklyn and UCLA. They separately discovered and elucidated the
way nitric oxide (normally considered a contributor to air
pollution) relaxes and widens blood vessels -- a phenom that has
proven useful in the treatment of heart disease and shock but whose
best known exploitation is in the wildly popular anti- impotence
drug Viagra. Not to be confused with the dentist favorite nitrous
oxide, or laughing gas, a different chemical. (Stanley, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN _ Some of them are here and indications are the crowds
could or could not reach expectations for the last words from Nancy
Fowler. A stigmatic expert from Boliviar plans to visit Fowler at
the farm. What do Catholics think about all this? (Scott, Anderson,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
