<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL BRIEFS: WASHINGTON MONUMENT CLOSED; ALL ABOARD THE
BRITANNIA; TOURING THE NORTHEAST; EASIER TRAVEL FOR THE DISABLED;
GIZMO HEAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Pa., Calif., Great Britain)   (For release Sunday, Oct. 18)  
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Washington Monument has been closed to the public until
December to erect scaffolding so that workers can inspect, repoint
and clean its marble skin. At the same time, the red lights that
warn aircraft away from the 555-foot obelisk will be resealed and
its eight observation windows will be reglazed.
</P>
<P>
   It is a big job, since 36,000 stones will have to be dealt with.
The National Park Service hopes to complete the work in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The monument will be reopened when the scaffolding is completed.
Visitors will pass through a 280-foot covered walkway to the
entrance. The walkway will run through a safety zone established by
a fence that will circle the monument.
</P>
<P>
   The monument, which was completed in 1884, was closed from
January to May this year so that its heating, ventilating and
air-conditioning systems and its elevator could be upgraded.
</P>
<P>
   The scaffolding will be wrapped in a fabric designed by the
architect Michael Graves, which will be illustrated in a way to
suggest the stone-and-mortar pattern of the tower but will be
sufficiently transparent to allow people to watch the restoration
work.
</P>
<P>
   _ IRVIN MOLOTSKY
</P>
<P>
   Britannia's Gangplank Lowers for the People
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, world leaders like Nelson Mandela, Tony Blair
and Mahatma Gandhi have been entertained aboard the Britannia, the
luxurious vessel used by Queen Elizabeth and her family around the
world. On Wednesday, the 412-foot yacht, which has recently been
refurbished, will be opened to the public for tours at the port of
Leith, two miles from the center of Edinburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The Britannia, launched on April 16, 1953, was decommissioned
last Dec. 11. Technically a Royal Navy ship, the yacht has sailed
more than a million miles.
</P>
<P>
   Budgetary constraints have much to do with the Britannia's new
role as a tourist attraction. British taxpayers spent $160 million
maintaining the yacht over the last 10 years, and a major refit
would have prolonged her life for only a few more years.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors reach the ship through a visitor center designed by Sir
Terence Conran. Its centerpiece will be the yacht's 41-foot tender
floating in a pool. Britannia's original wheelhouse will also be
displayed.
</P>
<P>
   Once on board, visitors will be guided around Britannia's five
decks by an audio tour. The bridge, the state dining room, drawing
room and the Royal Apartments _ as they were when occupied by the
royal family, with white walls, bronze metalwork and dark mahogany
woodwork _ will be viewed through door-sized glass panels. The
engine room, the captain's cabin and the galleys are also on the
tour.
</P>
<P>
   The Britannia will be open daily except Christmas. A shuttle bus
will run from Princes Street and from Waverley Station in
Edinburgh. Tickets will be about $10, and must be booked in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   Michelin Offers Guide to 3 Northeast States
</P>
<P>
   Michelin has just published its first green guide for New York,
New Jersey and Pennsylvania. The 376-page tourist guide discusses
such sights as the Adirondacks, Niagara Falls, the Hudson River
Valley, New York City, Atlantic City, Philadelphia, Pittsburgh and
Lancaster County, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Maps, photographs and illustrations accompany various sections
of the guide along with historical notations, touring tips and
information about shopping, parks, beaches and other recreational
opportunities. Attractions are rated by stars, ranging from one to
three, to indicate degrees of importance: interesting, worth a
detour and worth the trip. Cape May, N.J., for example, gets a
three-star rating, as do Lancaster County in Pennsylvania and the
American Museum of Natural History in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The guide is available at bookstores and map stores at a
suggested price of $20.
</P>
<P>
   Greyhound Is Adding More Buses With Lifts
</P>
<P>
   Greyhound Lines has announced a plan that it says a year from
now will allow the disabled to catch a lift-equipped bus at any of
its 4,000 stops nationwide, provided the traveler calls 48 hours
ahead. To do this, it will raise to 80, from 26, the number of
lift-equipped buses in its fleet of 2,100.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Greyhound, the country's biggest
long-distance bus company, was made just before the federal
Department of Transportation presented its rule for bus
accessibility under the Americans With Disabilities Act on Sept.
24.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Transportation Rodney Slater announced that a
deadline of 2012 had been set for all big companies that operate on
schedules _ as Greyhound does _ to have their entire fleets
lift-equipped. The department praised Greyhound's step, but said
the new rule went far beyond that. In any case, the rule requires
48-hour call-ahead service until all equipment is lift-equipped.
</P>
<P>
   _ BETSY WADE
</P>
<P>
   In San Jose, a New Home for the Cutting Edge
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever had an urge to design a roller coaster or have a
3-D map of your head made by a rotating laser scanner, the new
permanent home of the Tech Museum of Innovation, which opens in San
Jose, Calif., on Oct. 31, may be the place for you.
</P>
<P>
   In the eight years since it was founded, the Tech has been a
showcase for the kinds of gizmos that make Silicon Valley famous.
The focus on cutting-edge technology will continue at its new
132,000-square-foot building, a vivid mango-colored box topped by a
deep blue dome. Nearly 300 hands-on exhibits will be divided among
four theme galleries _ devoted to exploration, communications,
human health and performance, and innovation in the Silicon Valley.
Some exhibits _ including one allowing visitors to perform
simulated heart surgery using instruments that enter a life-size
mannequin _ have never appeared in a museum.
</P>
<P>
   The building will also house a learning center, laboratories, a
gallery for changing exhibits, a gift shop and cafe, and an IMAX
theater with reclining seats to view the eight-story concave screen
in the dome. The theater will open on Nov. 3 with the film
``Everest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tech Museum, on Plaza de Cesar Chavez, is at the corner of
Market Street and Park Avenue in downtown San Jose. Admission to
either the theater or the galleries is $8, $7 for those older than
65, $6 ages 3 to 12. A combination ticket is $13.50, $12.50 for
seniors and $10 for children. Hours: 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Closed
Monday. Information: (408) 795-6100, or at www.thetech.org.
</P>
<P>
   _ CHRISTOPHER HALL
</P>
