<HEADLINE>
`NOVA' TAKES ON EL NINO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You'll remember El Ni &LR; n &LR; o, the big bad weather machine that
turned much of the California coast into muck and misery last
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Along comes ``Nova'' (Tuesday on PBS) with its scientific look,
with satellites and instrumentation, at what causes El Ni &LR; n &LR; o.
</P>
<P>
   Science's answer: Hey, darned if we know.
</P>
<P>
   It seems science is sharp on the symptoms of El Ni &LR; n &LR; o _ the
trade winds reverse direction and blow west to east, pushing a huge
volume of heated water toward South America _ but not the
underlying cause.
</P>
<P>
   The open question is, what makes the Pacific ripe for a change
in trade winds every three to seven years? And does mankind
influence the frequency?
</P>
<P>
   The impact is plain enough. The 1997-98 version of El Ni &LR; n &LR; o
left about 250,000 people homeless, killed about 300, played
immense havoc on property, made the 49ers lose to the Green Bay
Packers and, for all we know, forced Bill Clinton to fib to Paula
Jones' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains and flooding struck North and South America, as
usual. Drought hit India, southern Africa, Australia and Indonesia.
Winter was uncommonly mild in much of North America. There was a
sparse hurricane season in the Atlantic, where high winds blew
apart developing storms.
</P>
<P>
   Straightforward and comprehensible, ``Nova'' delivers the El
Ni &LR; n &LR; o basics and reminds us that the phenomenon has probably been
around for several million years.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, ancient Peruvians tried human sacrifices to soften
El Ni &LR; n &LR; o's punch. No point in reviving that; it doesn't seem to
have worked.
</P>
<P>
   It's an odd thing about documentaries, though. Sometimes what
you carry away from it isn't the nut of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Here, it's the Ka'imimoana, a ship that crisscrosses the South
Pacific to service an array of buoys that measure changes in the
open water.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the year at sea in the balmy Pacific, benefiting
mankind and probably not exactly balled up with stress.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure, but I think I want that job.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And here's why. I love postseason baseball, but I'm annoyed by
the razor commercials that come with it.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette is advertising its new Mach 3 shaver, which has three
blades. A shaving simulation shows you how the first blade gets
most of the whisker, the second blade leaves a bit of stubble and
the third blade polishes off that pesky follicle.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. But when Gillette introduced its two-bladed Trac II in
1971, the company ran similar commercials. Back then, the simulated
second blade sliced off all the stubble left over from the first
blade.
</P>
<P>
   So, what gives? Was Gillette fudging its commercials then, or
now?
</P>
<P>
   I phoned a Gillette public relations guy in Boston and argued
politely for a bit. He insisted that both commercials were accurate
representations. I'm puzzling over how that's possible.
</P>
<P>
   Um, maybe you can understand now why a sea cruise might be in
order.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
