<HEADLINE>
NO GAIN IN BACKWARD EXERCISE EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By LIZ NEPORENT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a recent Monday night at the New York Sports Club on Wall
Street, a woman was turned around on the stair climber and stepping
backward. Nearby, several exercisers were striding on elliptical
motion trainers, switching the direction of their leg movements
from forward to reverse and back again every couple of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Both activities are common in gyms across the country and
evidence of a growing trend: backward exercising.
</P>
<P>
   Though backward running here and abroad has always attracted a
fun-loving but small following, including participants in an annual
backward mile run in New York's Central Park on April Fool's Day,
exercising in reverse has now shifted into high gear because of the
popularity of machines like elliptical trainers, stair climbers and
Spinning bikes that allow exercisers to move backward and forward.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the increased popularity of the reverse workout, fitness
experts question whether exercising backward is safe and effective
or just another fitness fad. Many suspect that it is the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask someone why they're exercising backwards and they'll
usually tell you they're trying to tone their butt and the backs of
their legs,'' said Ben Gelfand, a physical therapist and author of
``Return to Glory Days'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1997), a primer on
athletic injuries. But computer analysis indicates that the
quadriceps, muscles in the front of the thigh, are doing most of
the work during backward stair climbing, walking and running, while
the buttocks and the hamstrings in back of the thigh muscles are
virtually idle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also not great for the lower back because your posture
and body alignment are thrown out of whack,'' Gelfand said.
</P>
<P>
   He said a better, safer way to tone the buttocks would be to go
to the weight room and do strengthening exercises like lunges and
leg presses, which target that area.
</P>
<P>
   And, while a 1995 Texas Tech University study found that walking
backward at a 16-minute-a-mile pace elicited higher heart rates and
burned more calories than regular jogging at a faster pace, Edmund
Burke, director of the exercise science program of the University
of Colorado in Colorado Springs, warns that it is not a practical
way to get in shape or lose weight. ``Since you don't have eyes in
back of your head it's an awkward way to move,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   As for elliptical motion trainers, which require the legs to
move in an elongated circle, the manufacturers do not push the
backward motion feature. ``Though they probably won't cause any
more injuries than forward movement, there's also no proof that
it's beneficial,'' said Graham Melstrand, a sales representative
for the Reebok CCS Body Trek and Body Peak elliptical motion
trainers. Melstrand explained that the option to stride backward on
the Reebok machines is a byproduct of the belt drive mechanism
design rather than something engineered intentionally.
</P>
<P>
   Retro-cycling, pedaling backward on an exercise bicycle, may
even be dangerous. ``We don't recommend it because of the injury
potential,'' said John Baudhuin, president and chief executive of
Mad Dogg Athletics, the company that trains and certifies aerobic
instructors to teach the popular indoor cycling program, Spinning.
</P>
<P>
   Baudhuin said Spinning bikes have toe clips that act like ski
bindings to keep the feet firmly anchored in the pedals, but they
only work when pedaling forward. Backpedaling increases the risk of
the feet disengaging and the pedal crank hitting the shins. Mad
Dogg was so alarmed by the number of bloodied and bruised ankles
caused in this manner that they released statements warning
instructors to stop the practice. ``We told them that backward
pedaling was unsafe and should not be included as part of the
Spinning curriculum,'' Baudhuin said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2447 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ANTZ-GENDER-NYT &LR;      10-12 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ANTZ-GENDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN `ANTZ,' FEMALES SHOULD BE WEARING THE PANTZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(mk) 
 By NATALIE ANGIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Woody Allen has played many implausible characters in his
career: a human sperm, a failed writer, an aging nebbish who
remains irresistibly attractive to gorgeous Barnard students. Yet
none is as preposterous as the one that he assumes, by voice and
persona, in the new and critically acclaimed animated feature,
``Antz.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen plays Z, a whiny, disgruntled worker ant who digs dirt and
falls in love with Bala, a whiny, disgruntled princess ant played
by Sharon Stone. Z's best friend is Weaver, a hypertrophic soldier
ant, played by that he-man's he-haw man, Sylvester Stallone.
Weaver's boss, and Bala's fiance, is the tyrannical General
Mandible, who has the voice of Gene Hackman and the eternal jaw of
George C. ``Patton'' Scott. General Mandible barks to his soldiers,
``Men, let's move it!'' and ``Gentlemen, now you can see how
dangerous individualism is!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Antz'' is a cute movie. It is a visually dazzling movie. It
has some amusing, ant-appropriate lines in it, like when Z
complains to his therapist about having been neglected by his
parents; but what else can you expect, he sighs, when you are ``the
middle child in a family of 5 million?'' Nevertheless, any viewer
who knows about ants cannot help but feel disgruntled, a case of
rantz in the pantz.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the movie's ad line: ``Every ant has HIS day''
(emphasis added). If there is any group of creatures in the animal
kingdom for which that possessive pronoun is inappropriate and
unjust, it is ants. You might as well say ``Every nun has his day''
or ``Every mythical one-breasted Amazon warrior has his day.''
Edward O. Wilson of Harvard University, a leading authority on
ants, estimates that a million billion ants are alive in the world
today. The sum biomass of ants, he says, weighs four times as much
as birds, amphibians, reptiles and mammals combined.
</P>
<P>
   And that staggering ant biomass is almost exclusively female. If
you could examine each of the earth's million billion ants, you
would almost surely fail to find an example of a Woody Worker or a
Sly Soldier. You would not find a male ant that digs dirt, cuts
leaves, lugs sandwich crumbs back to the nest, or takes on invading
termites, as General Mandible's troops do with unmistakably
androgenic roars.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, nearly every task that is performed in an ant colony is
performed by females. They build the nest, they defend the nest,
they tend the larvae to insure a continuous supply of female labor.
Male ants almost do not exist. In the average colony, they account
for less than one percent of the population, and those that exist
live very brief lives.
</P>
<P>
   So what do these rare specimens do? To get an idea, think back
to Allen's literally seminal role in ``Everything You Wanted to
Know About Sex.'' Male ants subsist solely to inseminate the queen
during her so-called nuptial flight, when she flies out of her nest
in search of sperm. The males are there to greet her, and she mates
with one or more, storing their contributions internally to use as
needed. ``Males are really just bags of sperm,'' said Kenneth Ross,
an entomologist at the University of Georgia in Athens. They are
non-refillable bags, alas, and they do not store well. ``With
almost no exception, males die immediately after mating,'' said
Ross. ``If they haven't mated by the time winter comes, they are
cannibalized by the workers.''
</P>
<P>
   The same principle of female dominance applies to the other
famously social insects, the honeybees. In their case, scientists
have given the males a wonderfully evocative name, drones. Honeybee
drones do not work, and they do not overwinter.
</P>
<P>
   Among ants and bees, the overwhelming majority of the females
are sterile. They do not breed, but instead live to serve the queen
and the tribe, each in her specialized fashion. Colonies of ants
and bees have been called superorganisms because the individuals
act with such a high degree of coordination and interdependence
that they might as well be cells of the body. Behind that
willingness to sacrifice self for the whole is an unusually high
degree of genetic relatedness. For most animals, including humans,
siblings share about 50 percent of their genes. Among ants and
bees, by contrast, the sister workers in a colony are, on average,
75 percent related to each other, the result of a complex system of
genetic inheritance given the appropriately thick name of
haplodiploidy.
</P>
<P>
   That shared legacy encourages each worker to behave as though
the ants to each side of her are practically as valuable as she is.
And that state of group-think in turn helps explain why ants are,
as Wilson has written, ``the dominant little-sized organisms of the
planet.''
</P>
<P>
   The catch for the males is that they do not share and fare
alike. Male ants (and bees) have only half the number of
chromosomes seen in the females. As a result, they are much less
closely related to their female peers than the workers are to each
other. A male cannot depend on the unshakable bonds of close
kinship to save his chitin. His hope rests in the queen's nuptial
flight, when she emerges to gather semen. His hope is that she
chooses him and his. So maybe a male ant does have his day _ but
that day will be his last.
</P>
<P>
   Note to Z: Stop whining, keep digging and dress in drag.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
