   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   NUMBERS _ ATLANTA _ Mitch Reiner can remember 61 phone numbers,
his Social Security number, his parents' birthdays, his locker
combination, his kid brother's age (sort of: ``Twel-el-el-ve. Yeah,
12.''), his best and worst golf scores, the year Columbus arrived
in the New World, and the price and product number of every single
smoothie at Smoothie King. OK, that's because he works there.
Still, that's a lot of numbers to keep track of _ especially for
somebody who just turned 16 a week and a half ago. ``If you think
about it, it's really not much, because it's everything you think
about. All your friends, all the numbers you know,'' says Reiner, a
sophomore at Pope High School in Marietta. Just think of what we
use numbers for every day: phones, pagers, zip codes, bank
accounts, security alarm codes, TV channels, clothing sizes,
airline flights, appointment times, important dates. (Kim, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DORAL13-COX_I was on a mission: To see what it is like to
play from where the pros play on The Blue Monster _ if no longer
Florida's most challenging or beautiful course, then certainly its
most storied. Designed in 1961 by Dick Wilson, the course has been
a pro stop for decades _ the Doral tournament helping to build
Florida's golf reputation in the '60s. But thanks to better
equipment and longer hitters, by the early '90s, The Blue Monster
had lost its teeth. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SWISSREUNION13-COX_Uncle Ray and his wife, Beverly, had
visited Switzerland two years ago. They found the town where my
grandmother was born, but they could find no relatives. They wanted
to visit again. Uncle Dick and Aunt Midge said they'd come. That
made seven of us going. No matter what happened, it would be a
special trip. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLIN-MAKER13-COX_Gerado Passavanti left a job undone, a dream
unrealized when he died of pleurisy in 1930, aged 52, in the Bronx.
If he had died in his native Italy, there would most likely be no
story to tell. But he died in America, where fate and immigrants
and dreams take a common highway. Sometimes they all meet on that
road and travel together for a while before going their separate
ways. (REID, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ Column about raising three sons. (Kabat, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   CLINTONBOOKS _ ATLANTA _ To run any time the week of Oct. 12-16.
Two books about the Clinton scandal _ by William Bennett and Ann
Coulter _ are already on the nonfiction bestseller lists, and, with
the publication this week of two new tomes there soon may be more.
James Carville has written a snitty assessment of Ken Starr, while
David Maraniss has done a thoughtful and revealing reading of
Clinton's Aug. 17 address to the nation. The impeachment debate may
be played out on the bestseller list as well as the judiciary
committee, displacing for a time at least, the staple tell-all
memoirs. (Warmbold, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-EYEMAN13_West Palm Beach, Fla. _ ``If the world (Nelson
Algren) describes is at all like our own, then it's not morning in
America, and it hasn't been for a long, long time . . . the only
things that trickle down to where most folks live are disdain,
violence, and sometimes, on a good day, benign neglect.'' (EYEMAN,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   THE-REGULARS-COX_Amanti and about two dozen other regulars _
though only Don Cheech gets a plaque _ gather every Saturday around
noon to sit and smoke and talk and laugh and argue and smoke some
more and devour a plate of sausage and peppers with a little cup of
espresso mixed with Sambuca. (They bring in their own food.) Owners
Jerry Somma and Abe Debabneh turn on the TV so the guys can watch
the hyperkinetic Emeril Lagasse whip up a dish on the Food Network.
(Fans of the show, they dub themselves The Emeril Club). But when
new customers walk in, Debabneh walks toward them, shakes their
hands and says, ``Come on in! Come on in!'' to break the ice. ``We
always greet them and invite them in. We treat everyone like
they're a regular.'' (Houck, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ZYDECO _ Long renowned and crowned as the ``king of zydeco,''
the late Clifton Chenier might have trouble recognizing much of the
musical legacy that has flourished in his wake. Yes, the sound is
still based on the interplay of sprightly accordion and the
metallic scrape of a rubboard. Yes, the music still fills the
country roadhouses and radio airwaves throughout the Creole
communities of Southwest Louisiana (spilling over the border into
pockets of East Texas), making a visitor feel like he has entered
another dimension: Planet Zydeco. (McLeese, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ZYDECO-COX_ But who is this Beau Jocque character, boasting and
toasting like a rapper, exhorting his fans to ``Check it out, lock
it in, crank it up''? And what about Keith Frank, whose ``What's
His Name'' was inspired by Snoop Dogg and whose transformation of
the theme from an old TV show _ ``Movin' on Up'' from ``The
Jeffersons'' _ has become a signature anthem for both the man and
the music? (McLeese, Austin American Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   FIGHTING-ALS-COX_She cannot move. She cannot breathe unassisted.
But she can think as clearly as she did before Amyotrophic Lateral
Sclerosis _ commonly called Lou Gehrig's disease took over. She can
communicate. And she does worry about the $4,000 a month it takes
to care for her on her $1,800-a-month income. (Wiggins, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HANDY-COX_Hands, like any other body part, need preventive care
if they're going to operate at peak performance. Healthy hands are
part of a healthy lifestyle. Early intervention often can prevent
small problems from becoming big ones, experts say. The key is
paying attention to how the hands are being used. After a long day
of typing, are you playing two hours of tennis or gardening for
three hours? (Martin, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
