<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On a warm Sunday afternoon, my husband, Richard, and I, both
native New Yorkers, were entertaining my cousin Kate and her
boyfriend, Paul, from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the afternoon, after trekking around the city, we
decided to enjoy the view and some refreshments from the top of the
World Trade Center. We were stopped by the lobby elevator
attendant, who said we couldn't go up because Kate was wearing
sneakers, and no sneakers were allowed after 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   He also informed us that there was a ``real cheap'' shoe store
in the mall just outside the lobby. We went searching, but the
cheapest shoes we could find were $50. OK, we thought, we'll try
the observation deck. Admission for four (without drinks) was $48.
We were stymied.
</P>
<P>
   Then Paul had a brilliant idea. We left Kate in the lobby while
the rest of us went up to the bar at Windows on the World. After
being seated at a table with a spectacular view, we slipped my
shoes into Paul's knapsack. My long, flowing pants covered my bare
feet, not that anyone was looking.
</P>
<P>
   Paul took my shoes down to Kate. The Foot Police never noticed
that the same shoes walked by him twice. The tab for the view,
drinks and hors d'oeuvres for four: $62.
</P>
<P>
   _ VICKI COBB
</P>
<P>
   George Banks' daughter, Karen, a high school sophomore, was
preparing for a world history test, and her father offered to help
her study. ``No thanks, Dad,'' she said. ``Your history was a long
time ago. Newer things have happened that you're not aware of.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Hubsmith enjoyed this switch on the usual _ a
handwritten sign at a Duracell battery display in a Home Depot
store: TOYS NOT INCLUDED.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those days. Martin Hason's first appointment was
at 7:30 a.m., and by 9 a.m. he was an hour behind schedule. He
pushed and shoved through the morning, and by early afternoon was
at his desk with three calls to return.
</P>
<P>
   He was on one of them when call-waiting beeped. He picked up. An
unfamiliar caller with a cheery voice introduced himself as a
broker for an investment firm. The caller went on, ``I'd like to
offer you an outstanding issue of municipal ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, I'm busy,'' Hason said, and clicked off.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Hason answered the phone and heard the same voice,
but this time the caller was a little less cheery. ``I don't have
time for you,'' the caller said _ and clicked off.
</P>
<P>
   The scene: A recent matinee of ``Sideman.''
</P>
<P>
   The time: Intermission.
</P>
<P>
   The players: Richard W. Barr, seated beside one matron and in
front of another.
</P>
<P>
   Woman No. 1: (sitting behind Barr and calling out to Woman No.
2, seated beside him) ``Marge, is that you?''
</P>
<P>
   Woman No. 2: ``Helen, where were you? I waited in the lobby
until the last minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Woman No. 1: ``There were heavy rains out my way and I barely
made it here on time.''
</P>
<P>
   Woman No. 2: ``Why did you wait until now to speak to me?''
</P>
<P>
   Woman No. 1: ``I didn't recognize you. You've changed your hair.
It was only when I saw your rings as you were applauding at the end
of the act that I realized it was you.''
</P>
<P>
   My friend Gary Goldsmith came home very late from work and
realized that his wallet was missing. After searching everywhere,
including the grocery store he had just come from, he went to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Early the next morning, his phone rang. A voice asked, ``Mr.
Goldsmith, did you lose something?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You found my wallet?'' Gary responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look outside your door,'' the voice said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Gary could say, ``I'd like to give you a reward,'' the
voice continued: ``Don't worry about a reward. I've helped myself
to one.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside his door, Gary found his wallet, neatly wrapped, with
his credit cards and license intact. But the wallet was $173
lighter.
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD TRACK
</P>
<P>
   Two elderly gentlemen, obviously friends, were on a crosstown
bus, sitting near Hy Farber. They began discussing their health
problems, and one went into great detail about his bout with the
flu.
</P>
<P>
   The other man commented that it was fortunate that the friend
had been attended to by a doctor. ``With those symptoms, a person
could die young,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His friend's answer was succinct: ``It's too late for me to die
young.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Pader saw a pedestal she liked in the window of an
antiques store on Madison Avenue. She ran into the store and asked
the salesman if the pedestal was real marble.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want it, it's real marble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the joys of middle age.
</P>
<P>
   Young enough for a youthful indiscretion, too old for a
one-night stand.
</P>
<P>
   Old enough to have seen Elvis in concert, young enough to not
want to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   Too young for tired blood, but old enough to be just plain
tired.
</P>
<P>
   Middle age. When does it begin? Who knows. But suddenly you're
in it.
</P>
<P>
   Old enough for an estrogen patch, yet young enough for a blind
date.
</P>
<P>
   Too young for Modern Maturity, too old for Cosmo. (But is any
girl ever too old for Cosmo?)
</P>
<P>
   Too old for MTV, young enough for the E! network.
</P>
<P>
   Middle age. The wonder years. As in, I wonder where I put my car
keys?
</P>
<P>
   Too old for ``Bridget Jones,'' too young for Tom Jones. Even if
he is retro cool.
</P>
<P>
   Too young for elastic-waist pants, too old for black leather.
</P>
<P>
   Too young for Viagra, too old for Ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   Too young to think about retirement, too old not to.
</P>
<P>
   Middle age. Those marvelous years between the onset of myopia
and death.
</P>
<P>
   Too old to learn new tricks, yet too young for the same old
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Too old for Generation X, too young to be a total degenerate.
</P>
<P>
   Young enough for road rage, too old for road lust.
</P>
<P>
   Too old for breast implants, but young enough to wonder if they
might change your life.
</P>
<P>
   Middle age. When attention deficit is no longer a disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Old enough to forget what you did during the sexual revolution,
young enough to wish you could remember.
</P>
<P>
   Too young for assisted living, too old for living on the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Old enough for the empty nest, young enough to enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   Young enough for romance, but old enough to steer clear of
hopeless romantics.
</P>
<P>
   Middle age. Has it really been that long?
</P>
<P>
   Too old for thong underwear, too young for Depends.
</P>
<P>
   Too old for the Spice Girls, too young for the Golden Girls.
</P>
<P>
   Too old for Betsy Johnson, young enough for the Gap.
</P>
<P>
   Old enough to know that one size never fits all, but young
enough to hope that maybe it will fit you.
</P>
<P>
   Middle age. When you realize that your body is trying to tell
you something and that the news is not good.
</P>
<P>
   Too old for Power Yoga, too young for Powerball.
</P>
<P>
   Too old for in-line skating, too young for a La-Z-Boy recliner.
</P>
<P>
   Young enough to know the score, old enough to know that it
doesn't really matter who wins.
</P>
<P>
   Middle age. You're not old. You're chronologically challenged.
</P>
<P>
   Young enough to remember when you thought middle age began at
30, old enough to wonder if it really begins at 50.
</P>
<P>
   Too young for foundation garments, too old for body shapers.
</P>
<P>
   Old enough to listen to a ``classic'' rock station, young enough
to be embarrassed about it.
</P>
<P>
   Middle age. What? You worry?
</P>
<P>
   Young enough to dream about a Harley, old enough to drive a
Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   Old enough to remember when a martini looked like a martini,
young enough not to care.
</P>
<P>
   Old enough to think about pre-planning your funeral, young
enough to think that maybe you'll never need one.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star)
</P>
<P>
   The Hubble Space Telescope has seen objects 12 billion
light-years away. Or about halfway between here and the end of the
impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind wearing a Ken Starr mask. If you really want to scare
someone this Halloween, dress up like Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SONGS YOU DON'T REALLY KNOW &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DAVID GRIMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Today's music may sound a lot different than what I listened to
25 years ago, but I take comfort in the fact that the lyrics are
just as indecipherable now as they were then.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, indecipherable lyrics discourage people from
``singing along'' to their favorite song, thus saving the nerves
and ears of the rest of us from irreparable damage. Flailing away
at an air guitar or flapping about the room like a loon in heat is
one thing; attempting to sing, out loud, the chorus of ``Blinded by
the Light'' is another thing entirely.
</P>
<P>
   I mention ``Blinded by the Light'' specifically because few song
lyrics have generated as much confusion in the minds of listeners
as these, written by one of the most incomprehensible composers of
our time, Bruce Springsteen. If you are into computers (and there
is certainly no good reason why you should be), you will find an
entire web page (http://www.kissthisguy.com/) devoted to possible
translations of the chorus, as suggested by hundreds of earnest, if
somewhat underoccupied, fans. Some of the more plausible guesses
include:
</P>
<P>
   _Held up like a loofah by the foreman of the night.
</P>
<P>
   _Shot loose like a goose, another runner in the night.
</P>
<P>
   _Revved up my big Dodge and did a runner with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   _Rabbit in a lot of juice, like a doughnut in the night.
</P>
<P>
   _Racked up like a moose, that's been run over in the night.
</P>
<P>
   _Caught up at the juice bar in the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   _Wake up like a dachshund in the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   And my personal favorite:
</P>
<P>
   _Throw up blah blah blah in the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   (The actual lyrics, for what they're worth, are: ``Blinded by
the light/Revved up like a deuce/Another runner in the night.''
Just further proof that truth is not always stranger than fiction.)
</P>
<P>
   The Web site, by the way, is named after one of the more famous
misheard lyrics from the song ``Purple Haze'' by Jimi Hendrix. The
actual lyrics were ``Scuse me while I kiss the sky'' but many fans
(this one included) thought Hendrix said ``Scuse me while I kiss
this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Older (or younger) readers who find this error to be rather lame
should keep in mind that this all took place in the '60s and
Hendrix concerts were very loud and the concert halls were
invariably filled with a lot of fog, or something, that distorted
the lyrics. So lighten up.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can mishear a lyric, of course, but to qualify as a
classic, a misheard lyric must meet two criteria: 1) You must
believe your misheard version is better than the original, and 2)
You must have convinced at least one other person that your version
is correct.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, I, and millions of other rock fans who suffered
greater or lesser degrees of hearing loss during the '60s, firmly
believed that the Creedence Clearwater Revival song ``Bad Moon
Rising'' contained the lyric ``There's a bathroom on the right,''
when the actual words were, obviously, ``There's a bad moon on the
rise.''
</P>
<P>
   We assumed, I guess, that lead singer John Fogarty was simply
giving us concert-goers some useful information, though, in
hindsight, it did seem like an odd thing to put in a song. In my
defense, I can only say that I didn't take it as far as Creedence
fan Rick Marks did. Marks not only got the ``Bad moon on the rise''
part wrong, he also misheard the line, ``I think we're in for nasty
weather'' to read, ``I think we're in for mashed potatoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Another song that has been misheard is ``Witchy Woman'' by The
Eagles. Benjamin Dover, somehow, misheard the title line as,
``OoohhOoo, windshield woman/See how high she flies/OoohhOoo,
windshield woman/She got the moon in her eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought,'' said Dover, ``that the song was about some
zoned-out freak riding around in his car while having ghostly
hallucinations through his windshield.''
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassing moment of revelation came, predictably enough,
when Dover read the song title on the album jacket. To his credit,
Dover believes that his version of the lyrics is better than the
original and claims to have convinced at least one friend that his
version is the correct one.
</P>
<P>
   TV theme songs are frequently misheard, which is a double
tragedy as some of these tunes are like steel plates, so
permanently embedded are they in our skulls.
</P>
<P>
   Many people have misheard the line in the theme song to ``All in
the Family'' that goes, ``Gee, our old LaSalle ran great.''
Versions that are either better or worse than the original,
depending on your point of view, include, ``Gee, those were the
salad days,'' ``Gee, I love old sour grapes'' and the truly
bizarre, ``G.R.O. LaSalle Redgrave.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Flintstones'' theme song has given me trouble ever since
the show debuted in 1960. I speaking specifically of the line
``Let's ride/With the family down the street/Through the/Blah blah
blah blah blah blah blah.'' I thought, possibly, that the missing
line was ``Making friends with all they meet,'' but that didn't
seem likely as Fred's grumpy nature didn't win him a lot of
friends.
</P>
<P>
   A more plausible possibility might be, ``And see how much old
Fred can eat'' as Fred had quite the appetite, though it was
unclear why anyone would want to ride around with this family just
to watch Fred gorge himself.
</P>
<P>
   But now, after all these years, thanks to The Archive of
Misheard Lyrics, I know that the actual line is ``Courtesy of
Fred's two feet.'' Personally, I think my lyrics are better than
the real ones. And my dog agrees with me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
