   CHINA-WOMEN-WORKERS (Tianjin, China) _ As China's state-owned
industries have contracted and closed, women over 35 have born the
brunt of the pain: they are far more likely to be laid off and far
less likely to find a new job than any other group in China. By
Elisabeth Rosenthal. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   WYO-GAY-BEATING (Laramie, Wyo.) _ A gay University of Wyoming
student dies, five days after he was found pistol-whipped and
lashed to a fence post in an attack denounced nationwide as a hate
crime. Matthew Shepard, 21, died while on life support. Shepard had
been in a coma since bicyclists found him tethered to the post in
near-freezing temperatures outside Laramie, Wyo., on Wednesday. By
James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-INDIAN-GAMBLING (Highland, Calif.) _ The casino run by the
San Miguel Indians is a bitter battleground in what may become the
most expensive fight in California political history, one that pits
the state's gambling tribes against an unlikely coalition of Nevada
casinos, unions, church groups and other businesses that fear
competition from untaxed Indian rivals. It is a potent illustration
of the power of gambling money in politics. By Todd S. Purdum.
(1700 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NOBEL-MEDICINE (Undated) _ Three Americans win the Nobel
Prize in Medicine for their work on how the common air pollutant
nitric oxide acts as a signaling molecule in the cardiovascular
system. Their research led to a method of initiating penis erection
and indirectly to the development of the Viagra anti-impotency
drug. The three are Robert Furchgott, 82, of New York; Ferid Murad,
62, of Houston, and Louis Ignarro, 57, of Los Angeles. By Lawrence
K. Altman. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ Federal budget bargainers buy
themselves more time to work out their spending disputes as some
elements of lawmakers' major concerns began to emerge. By Katharine
Q. Seelye.
