<HEADER>
A2501 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-CLINTON-COX     10-12 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CLINTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton's woes become fodder for two more volumes
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The debate over the impeachment of President Clinton may be
moving beyond Congress and political talk shows to the nonfiction
best-seller lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Death of Outrage,'' a critical view of the Clinton
presidency by former Education Secretary William J. Bennett, and
``High Crimes and Misdemeanors,'' in which lawyer Ann H. Coulter
states the case for impeachment, are among the Top 5 books on The
New York Times Bestseller List.
</P>
<P>
   This week, two Simon &AMP; Schuster volumes join the burgeoning crop
of works about the scandal. Presidential adviser James Carville
attacks independent counsel Kenneth Starr in ``... And the Horse He
Rode in On'' ($14.95), while in ``The Clinton Enigma'' ($17),
Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist David Maraniss details how the
president's Aug. 17 4 1/2-minute televised national address on his
extramarital affairs reveals his entire life.
</P>
<P>
   Carville's snitty little book, which includes a brisket recipe
and a doctored photo of the independent counsel rifling a Simon &AMP;
Schuster trash container, will probably receive more attention. The
outspoken ``ragin' Cajun,'' who directed Clinton's presidential
campaign and later married Republican strategist Mary Matalin, is a
high-profile television guest.
</P>
<P>
   In ``... And the Horse He Rode in On,'' Carville is his usual
outrageous self, though he is serious about putting ``all the nasty
facts about Mr. Starr in one place where everyone can finally see
what a travesty of justice, and mammoth waste of taxpayer ... money
his investigation is.'' If we let Starr ``continue his jihad,''
Carville writes, ``the mean and menacing essence of him will remain
with us forever like Strom Thurmond or a cheap tattoo.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the tone, and if you want the Cliffs Notes, skip to
``Appendix C: Sixty Reasons Why I Don't Trust Ken Starr's
Investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The book most likely will be appreciated only by Starr
detractors, though even they may be weary of Carville's
vituperation. (Even his wife calls him a serpenthead.)
</P>
<P>
   Maraniss' work, however, will probably appeal to a broader
political audience, particularly those who wonder what motivated
the president's self-inflicted political wounds. In little more
than 100 pages, the Washington Post reporter who authored ``First
in His Class,'' the first Clinton biography, paints a sure-handed,
nuanced miniature of hubris.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the president speak on Aug. 17, it struck Maraniss that
the ``uneasy little address, born of necessity, shaped for
survival, delivered with stubborn persistence, argumentative to the
last, brushing off history, clinging to hope, ringing with the urge
to start over and move forward, hated by the elite, grudgingly
accepted by the public, somehow reverberated with all the qualities
of Bill Clinton's melodramatic political life.''
</P>
<P>
   Maraniss uses words, phrases or paragraphs from that night's
rhetoric to review the development of Clinton's political and
religious philosophy, or to reflect on his relationship to wife,
mother, daughter, brother and absent father. He observes that
though the president once revealed his choice of underwear to a
national audience, he is really ``a one-man darkness unit'' who
consistently withholds important information about himself and his
office.
</P>
<P>
   The ``core of the Clinton riddle,'' Maraniss believes, lies in
the president's reference to the liaison with Lewinsky as ``a
critical lapse in judgment.'' It was not an aberration, he writes,
but ``reflected one of the more familiar traits'' of Clinton's
life, ``a recklessness that seemed to contradict his stated beliefs
and imperil his accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   Maraniss finds the president's attack on Starr ``the most
predictable element in his speech. It was the almost inevitable
result of a personality that explained and rationalized
compulsively; that tended ever to the political strategy of
attacking his attackers.''
</P>
<P>
   If politics is war, Maraniss is right to parse Clinton's
rhetoric: his career has increasingly been defined by a debate over
his words, Maraniss writes. Now, the stakes in that debate have
finally ``reached the level of whether his words constituted
perjury or obstruction of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The president remains a bit of an enigma to his biographer, who
has never been able to satisfactorily explain exactly why Clinton
evokes ``a visceral hatred in some people.'' One of the many
ironies of ``the Clinton tragedy,'' he writes, is ``that he was
always his worst enemy, while his enemies, by overreacting, were
often, unwittingly, his strongest allies.''
</P>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   ``... And the Horse He Rode in On''
</P>
<P>
   James Carville
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster ($14.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton Enigma''
</P>
<P>
   David Maraniss
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster ($17)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
