<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glenn's return to space makes lodgings scarce
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still haven't planned your trip to the Kennedy Space Center to
watch John Glenn's historic space shuttle launch? Don't expect a
front-row seat. Or nearby accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, who became the first American to orbit Earth in 1962
aboard Friendship 7, is scheduled to blast off aboard the space
shuttle Discovery at 2 p.m. Oct. 29. At 77, he'll be the oldest
space traveler ever.
</P>
<P>
   More than a quarter of a million people are expected to squeeze
into a one-mile area around the space center in Cape Canaveral,
Fla., to witness the launch, with many more watching from rooftops
and roadsides all over Central Florida. Hotel rooms and parking
spaces should be as scarce as Starbucks outlets on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   The Brevard County Department of Tourism predicts almost all the
hotels within 30 miles of the launch site will be booked, with few
cancellations anticipated. Procrastinators are being steered to
Orlando, about 50 miles west, and even St. Augustine, 118 miles
north.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been sold out for more than a year,'' says Bill
VanEngelenburg, owner of the 126-room Best Western Space Shuttle
Inn, about three miles from the center. ``I haven't seen this kind
of response since the first shuttle launch'' in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   But the Daytona Beach Hilton, 70 miles north, is still taking
reservations for its six-night ``Rocket to the Stars'' package,
which includes lodgings, a view of the launch from the beach and a
champagne toast for $150 a night.
</P>
<P>
   The space center's complimentary parking passes, which are
usually issued to people who ask for them in writing, have been
suspended for this launch to accommodate the large number of
requests from VIPs and the media.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best unofficial places to view the launch are along
the Indian River on U.S. 1 in downtown Titusville and along the
Beeline Expressway, according to the Brevard County Department of
Tourism. But these are expected to fill up very early.
</P>
<P>
   The best bet may be via the space center's $20 launch package,
which includes access to a viewing area in Titusville (about eight
miles from the launch pad), reserved parking and a Glenn space
shuttle T-shirt. More than half the 5,000 packages are still
available, but are expected to sell out by the Oct. 23 ticketing
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Just getting to your viewing destination may be a problem. In
the past, high-profile launches such as the first one after the
Challenger disaster in 1986 have resulted in traffic jams
stretching for miles around the space center.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think that they can get here an hour or two
before the launch,'' says space center spokeswoman Melissa Tomasso.
``But they need to be here a long time before that.''
</P>
<P>
   She recommends that ticket holders arrive at the Titusville
viewing area by the 6 a.m. opening time. To make the wait more
entertaining, the space center will provide concessions and live
music. And a crew from ``Good Morning America'' is scheduled to be
there, conducting interviews with the Glenn faithful.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   For launch viewing packages call 407-449-4444, 8 a.m.-5 p.m.
weekdays. Or order through the Web site:
http://www.KennedySpaceCenter.com
</P>
<P>
   -- Kennedy Space Center general information: 407-452-2121.
</P>
<P>
   -- Brevard County Department of Tourism: 1-800-872-1969.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
