<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE WATCH: A HARVEST OF GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis.)   (The Science Times)  
(nk) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There may be gold on them thar hills. A team of New Zealand
scientists has induced plants to accumulate gold in their tissues
by growing them on ore. If the price is right, the researchers say,
it may be economically feasible to ``mine'' gold by growing
chicory, say, on a pile of mining waste.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of using plants to remove metals from soil is not
unheard of. Certain species known as ``heavy accumulators'' have
been used to clean contaminants from polluted sites. But the
researchers, reporting in the journal Nature, say their studies
appear to be the first evidence of significant accumulation of gold
by plants.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers grew chicory, mustard and other species on gold
ore treated with ammonium thiocyanate, used in mining to make the
metal soluble. After several weeks, the plants were harvested and
tested. Depending on the plant, the ore and the amount of compound
used, gold was found in concentrations up to about 20 parts per
million.
</P>
<P>
   At that rate, with current gold prices of about $300 an ounce, a
field of greens would yield enough gold to more than pay the cost
of treating the soil, the researchers say. If the price rises, they
say, gold farming could become even more feasible.
</P>
<P>
   Color Switch
</P>
<P>
   How does a butterfly change its stripes? Scientists at the
University of Wisconsin have found a biochemical switch that does
the job.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers studied the Eastern swallowtail butterfly, which
usually develops a pattern of yellow and black stripes on the
wings. But some females appear in basic black, mimicking another
kind of swallowtail that is unpalatable to birds.
</P>
<P>
   Butterfly wings are made of tiny scales that are colored
individually, just before the butterfly emerges from its chrysalis.
Colored pigments are deposited first, then black ones.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers isolated an enzyme, DDC, that controls the
pigmentation process. In the Eastern swallowtail, it is active
early in yellow tissues and later in black ones. But in the
all-black variety, it shuts down during the early phase, preventing
the production of yellow pigment. The scales that would have been
yellow are then colored black when the enzyme ``switch'' turns on
again.
</P>
<P>
   A Methane Rain
</P>
<P>
   Intermittent clouds with a chance of methane showers: That is
the forecast for Titan, Saturn's huge moon, astronomers in Arizona
and Hawaii say.
</P>
<P>
   From the Voyager 1 observations of Titan in 1980, the moon is
known to have a thick atmosphere of nitrogen and methane. But all
that gas has also obscured what goes on in the lower reaches of the
atmosphere. Scientists have theorized that the moon might have a
liquid cycle with clouds, rain and seas, of methane rather than
water. But more recent analyses indicate that Titan's climate might
be drier and less dynamic than was previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   The new data, gathered with a telescope and a spectroscope that
use narrow bands of near-infrared wavelengths to ``see'' through
the upper atmosphere, indicate the presence of transient methane
clouds at 5 to 25 kilometers above the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to New Fields
</P>
<P>
   Most people with degrees in science and engineering do not have
science or engineering jobs, according to a study by the National
Science Foundation. Using 1995 data, the foundation reported that
2.6 million people with science and engineering degrees held jobs
in the field, while 4.7 million with the degrees worked outside the
field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
