<HEADLINE>
NOTES ON MUSIC AND ART 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Chamber Music Society of Lincoln Center in
Manhattan will observe its 30th anniversary Wednesday with a gala
at Alice Tully Hall to be broadcast by PBS on ``Live From Lincoln
Center.''
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Sills serves as host of the broadcast, the pianist Andre
Watts will be the master of ceremonies and the soprano Barbara
Bonney will be among the guest artists. Miss Bonney replaces Dawn
Upshaw, who withdrew because of illness.
</P>
<P>
   In a program of work from Bach to Copland, other guest artists
will join the Chamber Music Society and its artistic director, the
clarinetist David Shifrin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paying $40 million of taxpayers' money for an abstract painting
by the Dutch master Piet Mondrian earned a rebuke Monday for Prime
Minister Wim Kok of the Netherlands, his finance minister and the
president of the Dutch central bank.
</P>
<P>
   In a draft report, the Court of Audit, an independent body that
investigates government spending, said the purchase of Mondrian's
``Victory Boogie-Woogie'' with public funds was unauthorized and
inappropriate. Official responses were being prepared.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-by-51-inch diamond-shaped collage of small squares of
bold blues, reds and yellow, in oil and black crayon, belonged to
the publishing magnate S.I. Newhouse Jr. The highly regarded work
goes on display on Oct. 29 at The Hague Municipal Museum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Halloween may be a couple of weeks away, but sprites are taking
over the Frick Collection beginning at noon Wednesday with the
opening of a new exhibition, ``Victorian Fairy Painting,'' running
through Jan. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Said to be the first comprehensive show ever devoted to this
distinctly British genre, popular from the early 19th century
through the beginning of World War I, this display of 34 paintings
and works on paper is derived from a larger touring exhibition
organized by the Royal Academy of Arts in London and the University
of Iowa Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   The artists drew their inspiration from Shakespeare and Sir
Walter Scott, theater, dance, music and even drugs and
spiritualism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dublin has narrowed the field of candidates to design a $6
million sculpture intended to symbolize the city as the Eiffel
Tower and the Statue of Liberty symbolize Paris and New York. The
short list consists of the London-based architectural firms Ian
Ritchie and McGarry Hunt and the young Dublin architect Jonathan
Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   All three designs involve illuminated towers. The new structure
would replace Nelson's Pillar, featuring a statue of the British
naval hero Horatio Nelson, which was blown up by the Irish
Republican Army in 1966 on the 50th anniversary of the Irish
uprising against British rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
