<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Tuesday, Oct. 13, and thereafter. The stories will carry the
``f'' financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For
questions about stories, contact Stewart Slavin at the Daily News,
(818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-SELLOFF (Los Angeles) _ Japanese real estate giants,
caught in the global credit crunch, are unloading marquee Los
Angeles-area holdings at significant discounts, real estate experts
said Monday. By Dave McNary. (Will also move in the ``a'' national
and ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RATES-HOMES (Los Angeles) _ Last week's surprise sudden spike in
interest rates has suddenly frozen what had been a red-hot real
estate market, including the refinancing sub-industry. Why the
sudden spike and what's the immediate future hold for interest
rates? By Ben Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   RATES-VALLEY (Los Angeles) _ The San Fernando Valley's resurgent
housing market cooled in September with sales rising 1.1 percent
from year-ago levels but prices continued their climb, rising 12.4
percent. By Gregory J. Wilcox.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-ONLINE-BOOKING (Los Angeles) _ Walt Disney Co. is
expected to unveil an online-booking system that will let customers
make reservations for hotels, air travel and rental cars at its
Florida theme parks. By Dave McNary.
</P>
<P>
   MALL-AUSTRALIA (Los Angeles) _ The Topanga Plaza and Promenade
Mall in L.A.'s San Fernando Valley could be taking on an Australian
accent under a concept the centers' owners want to bring to the
United States. By Enrique Rivero.
</P>
<P>
   LLOYD-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ Let the hire beware. Daily News
columnist Ken Lloyd, Ph.D., a specialist in organizational
behavior, answers readers' questions on workplace ethics and
relationships.
</P>
</TEXT>
