<HEADER>
A2539 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     10-12 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES SPELLING ALWAYS REFLECT ON PERFORMANCE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Question: I submitted a draft report to my
manager, and when he reviewed it with me, he mentioned several
times that the spelling was atrocious. He made no substantively
negative comments regarding the content, but he circled every
spelling error, and then said I should take more pride in my work.
I said this is just a draft, but he said that does not matter. What
do you think? R.G.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Since your manager spelled out what he is seeking in a
draft report, why not hit ``spell check'' before submitting these
reports to him? This is a situation in which you are both arguably
right, with the emphasis on arguably. However, there is no point in
turning this situation into an issue.
</P>
<P>
   For some people, spelling is a critical reflection of the
quality of any given written material. When a report is laden with
spelling errors, the assumption is that the overall report is
sloppy, and whoever wrote it did not do his or her best.
</P>
<P>
   For other people, spelling is not a major concern, particularly
on a draft. Their focus is on the content, and the assumption is
that spelling errors can be corrected later. Interestingly, one
additional influence in this area is e-mail, where many of the
rules of spelling, punctuation, and capitalization are often
jettisoned into cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   However, this is not the case for your manager. If you want to
work productively with him, remember that his priority list
includes a spelling list.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are a medium sized company, and my boss told me it's time
to have an employee newsletter, and he wants me to be in charge of
it. I hardly have enough time to do my own job, but when I said
this to him, he said he knows I can handle it. Now what do I do?
S.O.
</P>
<P>
   A: This newsletter does not have to be bad news for you. Your
boss has confidence in you and has presented an opportunity to
stand out. Before you refuse to deliver the paper, perhaps you
should do some research as to what this really entails.
</P>
<P>
   Make a few phone calls to other companies, check out the local
bookstore and library, or do an Internet search, so that you can
learn about company newsletters. There is a vast spectrum of
approaches, ranging from glitzy-glossy editions put together by
outside services, all the way to a typed one page monthly
announcement of employee birthdays and a restatement of the
vacation policy.
</P>
<P>
   Since you are obviously busy with other work responsibilities,
try to find a newsletter formula that fits within your time
constraints. In this age of desktop publishing, there are several
user-friendly programs that can help you produce a quality
newsletter. Approached under terms that are acceptable to you, this
project can be an excellent way for you to get some good management
experience and some good press as well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the law firm where I work, the raises have decreased in
frequency and amount, and new employees with lesser skills are
being brought in at a salary close to mine, although I am the lead
secretary. My review is late, and my raise is lower than the rest
of the staff. Going over the office manager's head leads to a
serious repercussions. I feel my options are limited because of my
age and recent health problems. Short of changing jobs, do you have
any suggestions? L.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: You would like the firm to show you the money, but the only
thing the firm is showing is ineptitude. The larger issue is the
firm's apparent lack of interest in employee communication,
satisfaction, and motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Your best hope is to try to turn your office manager into your
advocate. Go back to this person and let him or see the measurable
costs associated with your current pay situation, and the major
benefits associated with a more equitable pay system. You should
approach this person in a sales mode, and try to mirror his or her
speech patterns, body language, and general style.
</P>
<P>
   If you end up with ``no sale,'' it will be important to come to
grips with the realities of this situation: You are not satisfied
in your job, there is no one to help you within the firm, and you
are staying on board primarily because of perceptions about your
marketability due to age and recent health problems. You are being
unfair to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   In today's labor market, you may have more going for you than
you think. Besides, staying in a dissatisfying job is not good for
your health. Although you asked what to do short of changing jobs,
something needs to be changed, and it sounds like the firm may be
very firm indeed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
