<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA MAKES 11TH-HOUR PITCH TO AVERT NATO STRIKES IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (With KOSOVO-NATO) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia mounted a last-ditch campaign Monday to avert
NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia, warning that it may signal an
end to cooperation with the Western alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The intensity of Russia's diplomacy reflected the ascension of
Yevgeny Primakov, the foreign minister turned prime minister who
has often cast Moscow as a wounded great power in an open-ended
struggle with the West.
</P>
<P>
   As foreign minister, Primakov had no higher goal than to
circumscribe NATO's influence and contest American dominance. He
repeatedly described the Balkans as historically an area of Russia
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Monday Russia orchestrated a full-court press.
</P>
<P>
   First Primakov told Italy's acting prime minister, Romano Prodi,
that NATO strikes would be a ``tragic mistake'' that threatened
cooperation between Moscow and NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Then Russia underscored its unhappiness by recalling its
representatives to NATO headquarters. A Russian general even
engaged in a bit of saber-rattling by threatening to ship arms to
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Russia's leverage is somewhat limited.
</P>
<P>
   Russia cooperation with NATO has never amounted to very much.
Its representatives at NATO headquarters are primarily interested
in fighting old wars over NATO expansion, not finding new ways to
work together.
</P>
<P>
   The sole exception has been the deployment of Russian
peacekeeping troops in Bosnia, an arrangement that is widely
regarded as successful but not indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Parliament could vote down the second strategic arms
reduction treaty, and obtaining Russia's approval of the accord is
a high American priority.
</P>
<P>
   But the fate of the treaty is already in doubt in the
Communist-dominated Parliament. And Primakov has publicly said
approving it is in Russia's interest, as its missiles are getting
old anyway.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has never been popular with the Russian public. But with
Russia's economy in a state of near collapse, Western intervention
in the Balkans appeared to be primarily an obsession of Russia's
political establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Primakov has proved to be very skillful at playing a weak
hand. As foreign minister he helped negotiate the Founding Act,
which set the terms of NATO's expansion to the East.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's strategy Monday appeared to be to influence some of
the waffling members of the alliance by threatening a rupture in
NATO-Russia cooperation. The approach also distances Moscow from
NATO in the event the strikes go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Igor Ivanov, Primakov's former deputy and his successor as
foreign minister, Monday described NATO military intervention as
``a very dangerous decision which brings us to the red line, after
which, from our point of view, some very hard consequences may
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov said NATO military action
would lead to an annulment of agreements between Russia and the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Grigory Yavlinsky, leader of the liberal Yabloko faction, was a
rare voice of moderation.
</P>
<P>
   From the hospital where he is being treated for a heart attack,
he said the Yeltsin government had not been tough enough with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and urged Russia and NATO to
find common ground.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia, for one, seemed to appreciate the Kremlin's help.
Monday it announced that Borislav Milosevic, the president's
brother, would be its next ambassador to Moscow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
