<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAZERHOMES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    News of acquisition drops Snow's shares to 52-week low
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Beazer Homes has acquired most of the assets of Snow
Construction of Orlando, but the company's shares closed at a
52-week low Monday after the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The Dunwoody, Ga.-based builder is now the fourth-largest home
builder in that part of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The stock closed at $16.81 1/4 a share, down 31 1/4 cents. Last
week, Beazer and several large U.S. home builders saw their stock
prices take hits as investors were concerned that industry profits
would shrink from the record-setting levels of the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   On April 7, Beazer Homes shares were selling at a 52-week high
of $27.12 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Beazer Homes' Florida deal is in keeping with the company's
strategy of expansion by acquisition. From Snow, Beazer acquired
six subdivisions, 300 lots and a 70-home backlog. Prices in the
subdivisions range from the $100,000s to the $400,000s. Although
that is a bit high for Beazer's traditional market of first-home
and first-move-up buyers, Chief Financial Officer David S. Weiss
noted that Orlando tends to be an upscale market in which the top
tier of first-move-up houses could be in the $400,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   Snow is Beazer Homes' second Orlando-area deal in 12 months. The
company bought Calton Homes last November for $16.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Snow transaction is worth $13 million in backlogs. Weiss
declined to say what percentage of that would show up in profits.
However, he did say the company is comfortable with Wall Street's
$1.28 per-share estimate for the quarter ended in September. Those
fourth-quarter results, and fiscal year 1998, will be released
early next month.
</P>
<P>
   Beazer Homes' mortgage business, now two years old, ``added a
fair amount to our profitability _ between 25 and 50 basis points
to our operating profit margins (in fiscal 1998),'' Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   Beazer Homes has operations in the Southeast, Southwest and
Texas, and employs 1,143 people.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Harte writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
