<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA, union take final stab at settlement
 &HT;    (EDS: Can run with BKN-STERN, a Q and A with Commissioner
Stern.)
 &HT;    By Jeff Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In probably their last chance to save the opening
weeks of the regular season, the NBA and the NBA Players
Association meet in New York today for the first full negotiating
session since team owners walked out of a meeting in August.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides met last Wednesday, when the league answered
questions about a 17-page proposal it made in late September. The
players have complained that the most recent offer is too
restrictive and that it includes language that Hawks center and
union vice president Dikembe Mutombo termed insulting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're saying is we must have some cost certainty in any
agreement, at least percentage certainty,'' commissioner David
Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
