<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-STERN-COX     10-12 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-STERN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q and A with NBA commissioner David Stern
 &HT;    By Jeff Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With hope for the Nov. 3 season opener fading, the NBA
and the NBA Players Association sit down today in New York to
discuss the league's recent offer. In an interview with The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution staff writer Jeffrey Denberg, NBA commissioner
David Stern talks about the stakes and the background of the
league's 104-day lockout of players.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you don't reach agreement soon, can you save the season?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not sure. Frankly, the baseball owners and hockey owners
(both hit by long strikes) were wrong in their assessment and
that's what we preach to our owners, that they should not think
that this will be short. They should be prepared for the long haul.
The rallying cry of the union _ to foster unity _ has been, ``We
made a bad deal the last time and the owners are trying to make it
worse; the owners think we'll fold after one paycheck.'' We've said
exactly the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Players say repeatedly the owners are rich men making huge
profits, but trying to deny them their fair share. How do you
respond to that?
</P>
<P>
   A: They make the point that franchise values have gone up.
That's absolutely true and if owners sell, they will make money. .
. . Players' salaries have gone up from $60 million in '83 to a
billion now and franchise values have kept pace at similar
multiples. It has been a good system for both sides. So, we're
saying to them, we're willing to raise expenses but not at the same
rate as they've been raised in the last three or four years. We
promise in writing it will go up 20 percent over the next four
years. . . . In light of what's going on with the world markets _
Asia is under duress, Brazil and Latin America struggling badly,
the dollar getting pounded and all that impacting the United States
_ a commitment of 20 percent over four years is probably one of the
largest collective bargaining commitments being made in America.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In response to the 17-page offer you presented to the players
two weeks ago, the union charges there are too many restrictions,
too many details after such a long period of inactivity. How do you
respond?
</P>
<P>
   A: Perhaps we should have done this a little earlier but we
couldn't even agree to meet, so the notion of sending a proposal
didn't make a lot of sense. Still, I've been around here long
enough to know, hey, we'd better have something on the table
because as the season begins to dwindle away there are going to be
meetings and we'd better know what we are talking about. . . . The
first deal, I tell you, would have been a good deal for players and
owners alike. The second deal had huge risk for owners because of
the removal of taxes and the addition of other options. But given
the fact there had been work stoppages in three other sports, we
made it and took our changes albeit with the safety valve of being
able to re-open (negotiations). And that brought us to our present
circumstances. Look, people tell us if we had left the previous
agreement intact we would have had three more years of labor peace.
But my argument is that if you are making an automobile for $15,000
and selling it for $14,000, labor peace doesn't get it done.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is this impasse agent-driven? Some see the hand of David Falk
in the players' stance.
</P>
<P>
   A: I think that was fair to say last time. This time it's easy
to bash agents. But I have no proof of that and I have no suspicion
of it. Look, this is driven by historical force. We hear the
players saying that the owners are getting a $3 billion TV
contract, we want a piece of it. They are getting a piece of it.
They're getting 57 percent of it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The percentage of income that baseball and football pay to
players is in the 60s. Why are they able to pay a higher percentage
than the NBA?
</P>
<P>
   A: Baseball is a losing proposition. The majority of teams are
losing money. If you gave me the NFL's network television revenues,
our percentage would go up hugely. If your costs are set and your
incremental revenue is just network television money, you can pay a
higher percentage of each additional dollar to the players. We
would make the deal in a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Although the league average salary is $2.6 million, many
veterans like Tyrone Corbin of the Hawks are limited to minimum
salary by cap circumstances. Hasn't the system failed them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Absolutely. We agree the Ty Corbins of our league shouldn't
have to play for the minimum ($326,000 in '97-98). We say they
should play for $750,000. And beyond that we're also open to making
sure that the money to pay them comes out of some other source so a
team won't be tempted to hire a two-year guy at $300,000 to save
cap room. That's easy enough to do but at the end of the day it has
to come from somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The NBA receives payments from NBC and Turner whether or not
there are games. So, what is the incentive to play games?
</P>
<P>
   A: Our teams won't have any immediate cash flow problems. But as
you know, the TV payments are not a windfall. They ultimately have
to be repaid in terms of product or cash payment. There are a
handful of teams that will do better by not operating than if they
had to operate under (the old agreement), but if they didn't want
to play games they wouldn't be in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Denberg writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
