<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Akinwande may be 'open' to postponing fight with Holyfield
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The manager for heavyweight Henry Akinwande said
Monday the top contender would be open to putting off his mandatory
title shot against Evander Holyfield, thereby clearing a major
hurdle for a unification fight between Holyfield and Lennox Lewis
as early as February.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Courreges said Akinwande, whose bout with Holyfield in June
was voided when he tested positive for hepatitis, might be willing
to accept compensation in lieu of rescheduling the fight
immediately. Akinwande, who has not yet been relicensed, could get
``step-aside'' cash and a contract to fight the winner of
Holyfield-Lewis. ``Henry might be upset, but if the deal is good
for him, I'll put sense in his head,'' Courreges said.
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Don King arrived in London on Monday to try to complete
a deal for Holyfield with the Lewis camp. He was optimistic,
saying, ``I don't know when and I don't know where the fight will
take place, but we are going to work to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest potential deal-breaker is King negotiating his own
guaranteed earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who owns the WBA and IBF titles, likely would make
about $20 million. Lewis, the WBC champion, would get $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
