</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-UVA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Key to Virginia's defensive success is consistency, coaching
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The University of Virginia and outstanding defensive
play have become synonymous.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers went on a four-year tear through 1996 where they
were no worse than third in the nation in pass interceptions and
have been in the top 20 in scoring defense for six of the past
eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   This campaign is no exception. The Cavaliers are second in the
ACC and 10th in the country in total defense, allowing 272.6 yards
per game, while leading the ACC and ranking fourth nationally in
scoring defense at 10.2 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   The common denominator year after year has been defensive
coordinator Rick Lantz, who is in his eight season in
Charlottesville, Va. Lantz will be making a homecoming of sorts
Saturday when the seventh-ranked Cavaliers meet No. 25 Georgia Tech
at Bobby Dodd Stadium. He served as defensive coordinator at Tech
under Bill Curry in 1982 and '83.
</P>
<P>
   ''We play an aggressive defense,'' Lantz said. ''We put people
in position to make plays. What we don't do is have them sitting
and reading and reacting on the line of scrimmage. We've developed
a couple of pressure-type packages.''
</P>
<P>
   Lantz and head coach George Welsh have managed to stockpile an
outstanding array of talent, led by All-America candidate Anthony
Poindexter at safety. In the Cavs' last game, Poindexter dominated
Duke, recording 11 tackles, two interceptions and one fumble
recovery in a 24-0 win.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive line has been a pleasant surprise. Its leader is
Antonio Dingle, who is cool and ice to Dingle's fire and fury.
</P>
<P>
   An outspoken player who has been known to trash-talk during a
game, Dingle wears red contact lenses. Looking across the line and
seeing a 300-pound man with red eyes has unnerved more than one
offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he'd just keep his mouth shut and play, he'd be better
off,'' Lantz said. ''But he's tried to do things the right way this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Dingle is the strength of the defensive front and he's drawing
the attention of the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Dingle tends to draw most attention from the opposition. ''We
have put him in a situation a lot of times where he's getting
double-teamed,'' Lantz said. ''But if they stay down on him too
long, they might find a linebacker running through the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   The defensive boss says Virginia's biggest test to date will
come Saturday against the potent Yellow Jackets.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tech is really talented,'' Lantz said. ''They don't create
theory problems, but they create concentration problems. They run
the same people with a two-back formation, then go to three backs.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a Joe (Hamilton) admirer,'' Lantz said of the Tech
quarterback. ``And their receivers ran by those defenders on the
tape we saw of the (North Carolina game. They're good.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Arey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
