<HEADER>
A2546 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UGA-VANDY-COX     10-12 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-VANDY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Commodores, schedule doesn't get easier
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Vanderbilt lost a 27-24 non-conference game to
Western Michigan Saturday on a last-second field goal, even upbeat
second-year head coach Woody Widenhofer was downcast.
</P>
<P>
   So were his players, some of whom wept openly in the locker
room. The Commodores, who haven't won since a 17-7 triumph over
Northern Illinois on Oct. 11, 1997 _ come to Athens against
13th-ranked Georgia Saturday at 0-5 and carrying the heavy baggage
of a 21-game SEC losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Vandy has played the Bulldogs tough recently at Sanford Stadium,
ruining Georgia's homecoming with a 43-30 win in 1994 and holding
on late before losing 13-2 two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the Commodores are missing seven starters from the
conference's top-ranked defense last year and are using a multitude
of underclassmen at key positions.
</P>
<P>
   Vandy hasn't beaten an SEC team since a 14-10 win over Kentucky
in 1995, and ending its SEC misfortunes this year looks like an
increasingly dim prospect, with Florida, Kentucky and Tennessee
still ahead. A loss to Georgia also would ensure Vandy's 16th
straight losing season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't even talk it or think about it,'' Widenhofer said of
the losing streak. ``We're proud to be in the SEC. It's a tough
conference (in which) to win a game.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, they didn't know how to handle even modest
prosperity, blowing an early 14-0 lead to trail 24-14 before
rallying in the fourth quarter. Placekicker John Markham evened the
contest at 24-24 with a 46-yard field goal with 37 seconds
remaining, but he missed two other makeable attempts in the final
period. Western Michigan, which began the winning drive on its own
20, reeled off a 43-yard pass play to get into field goal range and
judiciously used two timeouts before booting through the winning
points as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   Vandy lost 19-16 in overtime at TCU the week before. Both losses
were precipitated by turnovers and penalties, things that its
previously stellar defense had been able to withstand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good defense the last two years that kept us in a lot
of games,'' Widenhofer said. ``But we've got a new group now that's
getting better every week. It may not show in the results, but
we're playing our best players.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen are playing a larger role than Widenhofer would like.
Of Vandy's 85-man roster, 61 players are no better than redshirt
sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   Redshirt freshman tailback Rodney Williams has been a godsend.
His 156-yard effort against Western Michigan gave him three
straight games rushing for 100 yards or more, something done only
one other time by a Vanderbilt player.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Dave Wallace stepped in as the starting quarterback
after a 42-0 opening loss to Mississippi State and has been making
gradual progress. Redshirt freshman Jamie Winborn has been a
stopper at middle linebacker, inheriting All-America Jamie Duncan's
shoes and leading the team in tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Widenhofer, once the mastermind of the Pittsburgh Steelers' Iron
Curtain defense, admits that maintaining patience for a long-term
payoff is becoming increasingly difficult. But he really has no
choice to approach his task any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players know they're getting better, despite the tough
losses we've had,'' Widenhofer said. ``We don't dwell on defeats.
We have to keep looking ahead, because that's where our team is.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
