<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS MANAGE TO HEAR THIS: NO!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did you ever expect to see the Los Angeles Dodgers begging for a
manager? In your lifetime? In your children's lifetime?
</P>
<P>
   How did things come to this point? Two years ago, the Dodgers
were playing in the post-season. They were the paper champs of
baseball, and the organization was considered a model of
efficiency. Along the Dodgers' 1990's timeline, those were the
glory days.
</P>
<P>
   These are the gory days.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyland rebuffed the Dodgers before they even had a chance
to offer him the manager's job. Felipe Alou just decided to stay in
Montreal, which is interesting since the Expos aren't exactly sure
they're staying in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are surrounded by examples of how drastically things
have changed. Ex-Dodger Dusty Baker is a successful manager in San
Francisco. Davey Lopes and Dave Stewart, despite what happened
Sunday night, are critical to the Padres, who are still on the
verge of entering the World Series. Leyland chose to manage a team
Colorado in the same division.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal put a heavy guilt trip on Alou to get him to stay put.
But riddle me this: In any other year of their 40 in Los Angeles,
would an experienced manager ever have turned the Dodger job down?
</P>
<P>
   Doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. When people around baseball look at the Dodgers,
they no longer see an immaculate franchise. They see this:
</P>
<P>
   An ownership group that made a lot of rookie mistakes in 1998.
Managers are wary of owners who make personnel decisions. If Fox
can trade Mike Piazza, it can trade anyone.
</P>
<P>
   A payroll with a lot of expensive, dead weight. It's hard enough
to win with players you like, want and can afford.
</P>
<P>
   A new management team that is behind in the count. Kevin Malone
is blameless, but future candidates already know they didn't top
his short list.
</P>
<P>
   The image of Tommy Lasorda hanging over the franchise. It
doesn't matter whether Lasorda had anything to do with the canning
of Bill Russell and Fred Claire, or has the ear of Malone or any
Foxie. The presumption around baseball is he did, and does. Image
is everything.
</P>
<P>
   A roster that leans more towards
</P>
<P>
   rebuilding than regrouping. The Dodgers may have to get a lot
worse before it gets better. It's happened elsewhere, and it could
happen here.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Malone doesn't necessarily agree. The new general manager,
who's been as upfront and direct as possible, has a solution in
mind for everything. The decisions by Alou and Leyland do not
change his outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were at the point of their careers where they can pick
and choose where they work,'' he said Sunday. ``It's not about the
organization (in baseball) any more. There are more factors
involved, and managers like Felipe have more choices and options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I analyzed this myself and asked what this really meant. They
were the most high-profile, available guys out there and had
options. I really think Felipe wanted to come, but the Expos made
him feel obligated to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the Dodgers helped make Alou and Leyland the two
highest paid managers. Malone didn't set out to raise this
financial bar. Imagine the marked-up price tag now for Davey
Johnson, who managed the Mets, Reds and Orioles into the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't looking to create a new watermark,'' Malone said.
``It's a reflection on the state of the game. We're starting to see
managers paid like NBA coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   With good reason. Being a major league manager is still about
winning, but it's not the only consideration. If that were so,
Johnson wouldn't have been unemployed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Managers have to have some baby-sitting skills, and be willing
to deal the deck handed them. They need to earn the respect of a
clubhouse filled with players who make 10ten
</P>
<P>
   times as much money, and learn how to deal with diversity and
the potential for turnover.
</P>
<P>
   If they do, they usually get the chance to play in October, at
which time they can show how fundamentally sound they can be (Joe
Torre) or how inept (Bobby Cox). The only thing more regular in
October than Halloween is Cox's annual postseason meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Fans and the media may look at the Dodgers and see a team that
couldn't touch the 1995 or 1996 Dodgers, but Malone sees a team
that can win a division title. To that end, he wants someone who
understands the job and has cachet in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Johnson and Kevin Kennedy, who spent 10 years in the
organization and managed the Rangers and Red Sox, are next in line,
and why Davey Lopes or Mike Scioscia aren't being considered, at
least not yet. Given the choice between Johnson and Lopes, Dodger
fans vote for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Given the choice between Lopes and, say, Larry Bowa or Ray
Knight, they might be willing to spend a year rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   Malone isn't. ``I believe I have to go with someone who has
major league experience,'' he said. ``Lopes, Mike and other coaches
have a lot of qualities. But with the stakes involved now, I don't
think we can develop a manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I felt we were really regrouping, we could with a younger
manager and develop together. But we feel like we're contenders. I
believe we can win a division title. We have adjustments to make;
we have to balance the lineup, and improve our defense, bullpen and
bench. But it doesn't need a drastic overhaul.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully not. It had enough of that in 1998 to last a lifetime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
