<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UPDIKE-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     10-12 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPDIKE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BECH AT BAY': UNEVEN UPDIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the ongoing adventures of Harry ``Rabbit'' Angstrom have
afforded readers a big picture window on four decades of American
middle-class life, the adventures of John Updike's other alter ego,
Henry Bech, have given us a smaller, keyhole glimpse of a more
elitist form of American life _ namely, the life of a minor
novelist, as he has made his bumbling, fumbling way from the
quiescent '50s through the raucous '70s into the noisy,
publicity-mad '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The latest collection of Bech's adventures, ``Bech at Bay,''
finds Bech older but definitely not wiser. Like Rabbit, Bech has
always had a propensity for vague existential dread, unmitigated by
his own modest good fortune, and in this volume, as in ``Rabbit at
Rest,'' that spiritual anomie has evolved into a prickly awareness
of mortality and lost chances. In one of his darker moments, Bech
sees himself as ``a vain, limp leech on the leg of literature as it
waded through swampy times.''
</P>
<P>
   Bech's confidence is not helped by his suspicion that ``his
author'' _ that is, John Updike _ wanted ``to set him aside, to get
him off the desk forever.'' ``Rather frantically hoping still to
amuse, Bech had developed a new set of tricks, somewhat out of
character _ he had married, he had written a best seller.
Nevertheless, and especially as his 60s settled around him, as
heavily as an astronaut's suit, he felt boredom from above dragging
at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bech felt, Updike playfully writes, like ``an experiment whose
chemicals were about to be washed down the drain.''
</P>
<P>
   As this passage suggests, Updike has lost some of his enthusiasm
for his old creation, and his weariness frequently shows. Though
``Bech at Bay'' boasts some delightful set pieces and
intermittently sparkles, like its predecessors ``Bech: A Book''
(1970) and ``Bech Is Back'' (1982), with some wonderfully witty
asides about literary life and death, it's a highly uneven
collection of stories.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these interlinked tales, like ``Bech Presides,'' are
bravura performances, sly, funny and tart as anything Updike has
written about writers, writers' egos and the waning power of the
written word. Others, however, are hokey and contrived, the
frenetic yet oddly perfunctory effusions of an author goading
himself to care.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Bech Noir,'' for instance, Updike turns Bech into a
literary avenger, who, accompanied by a faithful sidekick named
Robin, terrorizes literary critics across the land, murdering those
who have had the temerity to assail his work. This Bechman wears a
cape, carries a ``rod'' with a silencer and says things like ``he's
done me a world of woe.''
</P>
<P>
   Such ill-conceived experiments uncomfortably push the gentle
satire of the Bech books into the more perilous realm of farce.
They not only force poor, long-suffering Bech to try to learn new
tricks but also turn him into a ludicrous puppet, forced to don
bizarre costumes and mouth bad dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   It is when Bech stays in character as his usual self-absorbed,
competitive but strangely melancholy self that these stories work
best, engaging the reader in his quandaries as an aging writer who
feels himself increasingly estranged from the brave new digitalized
world around him and increasingly concerned with the small literary
legacy he will leave behind, even as he finds himself unexpectedly
becoming a father in his eighth decade of life.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Updike notes, Bech had reached ``that advanced stage
of authorship when his writing consisted mostly, it seemed, of
contributions to Festschrifts _ slim volumes of tributes, often
accompanied by old photographs and an uneasy banquet at the Century
Club or Lutece or Michael's Pub, in honor of this or that ancient
companion in literature's heady battles.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Bech's own books are out of print or available only in
college bookstores, and he no longer sees his name, as he once did,
on drugstore racks and in airports. ``If he wasn't assigned in a
college seminar on postwar anti-realism, he wasn't read.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bech becomes president of an arts organization called
``The Forty'' _ an imitation French Academy, hypothetically
consisting of the 40 best artists in America _ he soon finds
himself presiding over its demise. Like Bech himself, the
organization seems to have become obsolete, an elitist dinosaur in
a politically correct, computer-driven world more and more
oblivious to the blandishments of highbrow art.
</P>
<P>
   But then, to Bech's surprise and everyone else's, he is awarded
the Nobel Prize in literature. Never mind that the prize is the
unintended byproduct of game-playing by committee members, never
mind that Bech himself feels unworthy: At 76, preparing to make his
Nobel speech, he has a chance to sum up his own life and the state
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Although much is made in these stories of Bech's identity as a
Jewish novelist (and there are bits and pieces of Saul Bellow,
Norman Mailer and the two Roths, Philip and Henry, in his
characterization), the writer he most resembles is his creator.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are there loose parallels between Bech's early books
and those of Updike (Bech's ``Travel Light,'' like ``Rabbit, Run,''
was a response to Jack Kerouac; his novel ``Think Big,'' like
``Couples,'' was a ``triumphantly sleazy'' best seller), but Bech's
work also seems to evince the same qualities as his creator's:
namely, a fascination with ``the fuzzy texture of daily life, that
gray felt compacted of a thousand fibers, that elusive drabness
containing countless minute scintillae.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, there are huge differences between
Bech and Updike. Bech, despite his Nobel, has a reputation as a
second-string cult author; Updike, as one of America's most
eminent. Bech has a modest oeuvre of seven books, interrupted by a
16-year writing block, Updike a wildly compendious one (running
thus far to some four dozen works), among which this volume must
surely count as one of his more minor, if entertaining,
productions.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BECH AT BAY'
</P>
<P>
   By John Updike
</P>
<P>
   241 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
