   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Tuesday, Oct. 13 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Stewart Slavin at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-TRAGEDY (Los Angeles) _ The hit-and-run death of Salvador
Sanchez over the weekend was the second time his parents lost a
child. A brother, also 4, nearly choked to death several years ago
and remains in a coma, prompting child-welfare officials to place
Salvador and his nine siblings in foster homes. Sunday started out
as a day of great joy for Salvador and his brothers and sisters:
for the first time in years, they were together, away from their
foster homes, to celebrate their father's birthday. The day ended
in tragedy, however, when Salvador was struck by a car while
crossing on an unmarked crosswalk. By Lisa Van Proyen. (Will move
in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-SELLOFF (Los Angeles) _ Japanese real estate giants,
caught in the global credit crunch, are unloading marquee Los
Angeles-area holdings at significant discounts, real estate experts
said Monday. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``a'' national,
``n'' California and ``f'' financial news files.)
