</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFIRM YELTSIN FORCED TO END TRIP TO ASIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin abruptly cut short a three-day
visit to Central Asia Monday after his doctor announced that
Yeltsin was suffering from bronchitis and a slight fever.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kremlin's record of covering up the president's health
problems left many commentators questioning whether Yeltsin's
illness was more serious. It also compounded the sense that the
nation lacked a fully functioning leader during one of its gravest
crises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what it is yet,'' observed the NTV independent
television channel. ``But the situation is very unclear and very
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, when Yeltsin arrived in Tashkent, the capital of
Uzbekistan, he looked weak. He lost his footing at a ceremony, and
at a state dinner he lost his place in his prepared remarks. At
another point in the evening, he had a coughing spell that prompted
him to leave for a few minutes with his doctor.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, in Almaty, Kazakhstan, he painstakingly signed
documents, slowly outlining each letter of his name. Then he left
the ceremony sluggishly, nudged along by the Kazakh president, who
wrapped an arm around Yeltsin's waist.
</P>
<P>
   In returning to Moscow Monday night, Yeltsin, 67, cut short by a
day a trip designed in part to demonstrate his continued capacity
to rule. Instead his first trip abroad in five months reinforced
fears about his health two years after his quintuple bypass
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't need this visit. This was for them,'' said an aide
to Nursultan Nazarbayev, president of Kazakhstan, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity. ``They needed to show that their president
was strong. This is politics.`
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's health has been so unsteady in recent months and his
involvement in the nation's political affairs so episodic that he
has often seemed to operate as a virtual president.
</P>
<P>
   Weakened physically, as well as politically, his management
style has been to appoint a prime minister, allow him enormous
leeway in forming new policies and then monitor the affairs of
state from a country residence outside Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's detachment has often seem so pronounced that the
Russian media has taken to reporting his occasional appearances at
the Kremlin as breaking news. A recent opinion poll indicated that
only 2 percent of those surveyed had confidence in his ability to
govern.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Yeltsin has clung tenaciously to power, insisting that he
will serve out his term, which ends in the year 2000. And while
Yeltsin is no longer immersed in the intricacies of economic
policy, Kremlin veterans say he is still occasionally capable of
cracking the whip.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Fyodorov, the ousted head of the state tax service,
recently speculated that Yeltsin may order yet another government
shakeup if Russia's economy continues to falter over the next
several months. In that sense, Yeltsin is an absentee president,
but not a mere figurehead.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's isolation would be less serious for the nation if his
prime minister had a firmer grip on economic policy. But Yevgeni
Primakov, who has been Yeltsin's prime minister for about a month,
and a consensus choice for many Russians, seems to be at a loss
when it comes to the economy.
</P>
<P>
   A former foreign minister and intelligence chief, Primakov
appears to have stronger views about NATO intervention in the
Balkans than how to close the nation's yawning budget deficit or
revive its insolvent banks.
</P>
<P>
   And the president's physical decline would be less worrisome if
there was a consensus on who should lead the nation after Yeltsin
left office.
</P>
<P>
   But public opinion is split. The leading candidates are Yuri
Luzkhov, the pugnacious Moscow mayor who has sought to reposition
himself as the head of a center-left party; Aleksandr Lebed, the
Siberian governor and former general who has yet to articulate a
clear economic program; and Gennady Zyuganov, the Communist leader,
whose appeal appears limited to the party faithful. Many Russians
distrust all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Russian constitution, if Yeltsin were to leave office
early or die, the prime minister would assume his duties for up to
three months until new elections were organized.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin appears to have never fully regained his strength since
undergoing his heart surgery in November, 1996. Since then, he has
his ups and down. This past week was definite down.
</P>
<P>
   His trip to Central Asia appeared intended to show that Yeltsin
was still capable of leading his nation. Instead, it backfired.
</P>
<P>
   When Yeltsin arrived Sunday evening in Tashkent, he appeared to
lose his footing as he stood listening to a band at the
presidential mansion. He regained his balance only when Islam
Karimov, Uzbekistan's president, shoved an arm underneath Yeltsin
to steady him.
</P>
<P>
   At an official dinner Sunday night, Yeltsin drank two or three
glasses or red wine, according to a diplomat who was present.
Recalling the enfeebled Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev, Yeltsin then
gave a confused rendering of a speech, reading the beginning,
shifting to the end and then plunging, belatedly, into the middle.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996 presidential election campaign, the Kremlin
covered up Yeltsin's heart attack, describing it as a cold.
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin aides insisted that this time it really was nothing more
than a cold and that there were no plans to hospitalize the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Yeltsin caught a cold in Moscow at the end of the
week, before the visit,'' said Dmitry Yakushkin, Yeltsin's new
spokesman. ``When you have a cold, you need to lie in bed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
