<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NBA LABOR DISPUTE, YOU CAN SIDE WITH, AH, IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Somebody asked the other day whether there's ever been
two parties in a public dispute less deserving of sympathy than the
NBA owners and NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   Well, sure. Here's my short list:
</P>
<P>
   Iraq vs. Iran _ Countries that have established why the rest of
the world moved out of the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Starr vs. Bill Clinton _ Ravenous egos more unstoppable than
the combined force of the Constitution, the rule of law, the
English language and common sense.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Tripp vs. Monica Lewinsky _ A real-life version of Mad
Magazine's old ``Spy vs. Spy,'' only without the wit, originality
or cleverness. Just as tasteless, however.
</P>
<P>
   Don King vs. Mike Tyson _ One has electric hair, one has an
electric stare, both deserve the electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   But as far as two parties in a sports-labor dispute completely
devoid of sympathy as well as empathy ...
</P>
<P>
   No. Never has been one like this one.
</P>
<P>
   To put it another way:
</P>
<P>
   Which one is Beavis?
</P>
<P>
   At least in the modern labor disruptions of baseball, football
and hockey, a plausible argument could be offered that the players'
side had been at one time disadvantaged relative to ownership. That
was particularly acute in baseball, where the reserve clause
virtually bound a player to a team for life, creating little
leverage for players and boundless profitability for owners.
</P>
<P>
   But with the huge union advances made in collective bargaining
and the creation of improved free agency in the past 20 years, the
pendulum has swung. In baseball, it has swung so far that the union
runs the sport and the franchises just tag along.
</P>
<P>
   Great advances happened for basketball, too, except that its
landmark labor peace in 1984 was achieved when the sport was at its
nadir. The crisis was tangible enough that both sides worked from
the same pile of devalued rubles.
</P>
<P>
   Now we see the NBA as victim of its own success. The NBA's
two-decade-long merchandising of the game's individual heroes, as
opposed to teams, has produced a star-driven industry whose stars
make the soundest claim among all sports that league success is
more dependent upon individuals than teams, franchises or the game
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, owners have agreed, not only by lavishly marketing
the players but by paying the highest salaries in sports, rivaling
the biggest in show business.
</P>
<P>
   The owners no longer want to pay those salaries. They want
take-backs _ primarily an end to the Bird exception that allows
teams to pay their own free agents unlimited amounts.
</P>
<P>
   The exception is how the Chicago Bulls can have a payroll of
nearly $60 million when the salary cap is less than $30 million.
It's why the league claims up to half its teams are no longer
profitable, a claim the union _ and anyone working with more than a
brain stem _ dismisses as piffle.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is ownership believes the claim sufficiently to
endure a self-imposed shutdown. Owners have two things going for
them _ a huge war chest supplied by TV revenues and the stupidity
of the American sports consumer.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA watched baseball's recovery from the 1994 strike that
cost the World Series and bled into the 1995 season. Disastrous as
it was, the NBA, always mindful of the bigger picture, figured if
it took only four years for the dopes who run baseball to get the
game close to where it was, the basketball slicksters will need
half a season, tops. They're probably right, because of the nearly
infinite capacity of most pro sports consumers to forgive and
forget, as well as their susceptibility to clever apologies and
emotional make-goods (see Clinton).
</P>
<P>
   Owners want something more like the NFL's harder salary cap. Yet
22 of the 30 NFL teams, including the Seahawks, exceed the $52
million cap thanks to a variety of loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   Caps just don't work as advertised. The NBA is asking for an
artificial limit on labor costs, while there is no cap on their
potential revenues. Nor is there a cap on ticket costs. Unless caps
are agreed to on all fronts, their deployment on one element of the
economic equation will create unfairness that almost always leads
to further labor trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite having the economic points on their side, today's
basketball players are not only not disadvantaged like their
sports-labor predecessors a generation earlier, they are
financially on top of the world while operating behind the
protection of a union that works for its elite instead of its rank
and file _ exactly the opposite of all non-sports unions.
</P>
<P>
   No union member at Boeing can be expected to accept the arcane
arguments about market economics when jewelry-bedecked players roll
up to private jets in limos. Nor can the average basketball fan
accept the notion that there is nothing in the enormous wealth
accumulated by players that can't be surrendered in order to have a
season.
</P>
<P>
   The players are atop a false economy, hiding behind a false
front. The owners are creating artificial crisis and applying
artificial brakes.
</P>
<P>
   In this argument, take Iraq, and give the points.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
