<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2618 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADULTERY-INSURANCE-LA     10-12 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADULTERY-INSURANCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY A PARTNER PUTS UP WITH SEX, LIES &AMP; ADULTERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENIFER HANRAHAN 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Cathleen found out after 29 years of marriage
that her husband was having an affair, it broke her heart and
nearly tore apart her family.
</P>
<P>
   But despite her rage at his betrayal, it took her five years to
file for divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that if I got divorced, my lifestyle would change, and
I loved him,'' said the West Hills women, who asked that her last
name not be used. ``I hate to admit that, but I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the same situation, think you would leave your
husband immediately? Maybe so. But if you're like the vast majority
of Americans, your feelings about adultery are complex.
</P>
<P>
   We despise it, condemn it, say we'd never do it or tolerate it,
but when we're faced with it, our actions often contradict our
words, sociologists and ethicists say.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for our ambivalence: mixed messages.
</P>
<P>
   While marriage vows command us to remain faithful until death,
we live in a society in which we're bombarded with images of
promiscuous sex.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, people who identify with the urge to stray
hesitate to cast the first stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``People overwhelmingly consider infidelity wrong, and they
overwhelmingly consider it a common failure,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Our confused feelings about the president are prime example.
During the 1992 election, Clinton acknowledged causing ``pain'' in
his marriage and yet we still elected him. Six years later, he's
confessing again, and we still seem ready to forgive.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the American public's widespread disapproval of
Clinton's liaison with a White House intern, anecdotal evidence
reveals that adulterous acts are going on all around us.
</P>
<P>
   A tabloid caught sports broadcaster Frank Gifford, Kathie Lee's
husband, in a compromising situation with a flight attendant. After
a fairy-tale wedding, Diana and Prince Charles both reportedly had
extramarital affairs. Jim and Tammy Faye Bakker lost not only their
marriage but their televangelism empire after he tearfully admitted
to his affair with Jessica Hahn.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on?
</P>
<P>
   ``The American view of sexuality has always been a strange one,
a mixture of puritanism and promiscuity,'' said John Crossley,
director of the school of religion at University of Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increase in concern about adultery and the strong
abhorrence of it comes from the whole notion that adultery is one
of the most serious violations of family integrity. ... The reason
people are willing to forgive is because of the awareness of the
power of sexual temptation,'' Crossley said.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PAINFUL NONETHELESS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just how many Americans are cheating on their spouses is not
entirely clear. Little data is dedicated specifically to
infidelity, and what's out there is not necessarily accurate.
</P>
<P>
   In one survey by the makers of Durex condoms, half of Americans
who filled out an anonymous questionnaire admitted to infidelity,
defined as carrying on more than one sexual relationship at a time
in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   In another survey, conducted by University of Chicago
researchers, about 22 percent of men and 13 percent of women
admitted to carrying on an extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers vary widely because, even in anonymous surveys,
people lie, said Dr. Robert Simmermon, an Atlanta psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that infidelity may be even higher than this,'' said
Simmermon, a Durex spokesman. ``People are very secretive about
affairs. It taps into our national ambivalence about our sexual
values. What we say and what we do are at odds with one another.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if we know adultery is commonplace, that doesn't make
it hurt any less.
</P>
<P>
   In a March survey by the American Association for Marriage and
Family Therapy, adultery was ranked as second only to spousal abuse
in impact on mental health.
</P>
<P>
   On a scale of 1 to 10 (10 being most stressful), women rated an
unfaithful spouse a 9.1 and men rated an unfaithful wife an 8.8. A
death in the immediate family, divorce or a child abusing drugs
were rated as less stressful than adultery. ``For many couples, it
breaks the real core of trust,'' said Dr. Carole S. Noreen, a
psychotherapist for more than 35 years, who has an office in
Encino.
</P>
<P>
   When Elaine discovered her husband's affair, it caused more
emotional pain than the death of her parents or even her own bout
with cancer, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It damages the core of you, your soul,'' said the Valley
mother, who asked that her last name not be used to protect her
children from further anguish. ``I thought we were living the
American dream. I thought it was so ordinary and normal. Little did
I know my husband was having a very exciting life _ except it
wasn't with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pain, adultery is not a sure marital death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Every couple has their own expectations for their marriage, and
monogamy isn't necessarily included, said Judith Stacey, a
professor of sociology and gender studies at University of Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the case that everyone accepts a single standard of
marriage,'' Stacey said. ``People are very aware that marriage is
for a lot of reasons: having children, security, picking a place in
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathleen said it took years to divorce her husband after his
infidelity was revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of women who haven't had this happen to them don't
understand why you wouldn't just pack and leave,'' she said. ``It's
because your whole life is tied up with this person. Your children
are upset and distraught.''
</P>
<P>
   When nationally syndicated radio-show host Tom Leykis found
tell-tale hotel receipts and phone bills, he tried to find out what
drove his wife to cheat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I surprised myself,'' Leykis said. ``I always assumed that if
my wife had an affair I would end the marriage. I realized when it
happened that that wasn't what I wanted. I wanted to go to therapy
or counseling.''
</P>
<P>
   What finally caused the divorce, he said, was her refusal to
admit to the affair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DISAPPROVAL GROWS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even as opinions about sexual relations _ premarital sex,
homosexuality _ have grown more liberal, according to the
University of Chicago survey, Americans have grown more critical of
adultery than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The survey showed that more than 78 percent of Americans said
infidelity is wrong under any circumstances. When Chicago
researchers first asked the question about adultery in 1973, 69.8
percent said it was always wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't just consider adultery undesirable, but they
absolutely object to it,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Another 20 percent called it ``almost always'' or ``sometimes''
wrong, leaving only 1.6 percent seeing ``nothing'' wrong with it.
</P>
<P>
   But up until the latter part of this century, most women really
had no choice but to stay in a marriage because they had few
financial options. Divorcing also was socially unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   In more recent times, women's increasing economic independence,
the rising divorce rate and the specter of AIDS have contributed to
a dwindling tolerance for adultery, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   While in past decades, many therapy patients opted to ignore
their husbands' affairs, today more women are willing to face it,
said psychotherapist Noreen.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, if they ever were naive about extramarital affairs,
certainly aren't now, experts said. The Clinton scandal thrust
adultery into the limelight, making it impossible to ignore. For
some Americans, this prompted a closer look at their own marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Milo Speriglio, a Sherman Oaks private detective, said his phone
has been ringing off the hook since the tawdry details of the
presidential embarrassment were aired for all to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's brought us a lot of business,'' Speriglio said. ``More
and more people are thinking, `If the president can do it, why not
my husband or boyfriend or wife?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
