<SLUG> BC-RAINY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY DON'T HAVE RAINY-DAY FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
 DAY-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUSS WILES  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Kathleen Lane leaves no stone unturned in her quest to
save money. The Phoenix woman has built up a modest rainy-day fund
over the past three years, even as she worked to pay off nearly
$8,000 in debts. She uses coupons when shopping, picks up pennies
off the ground and slavishly adheres to her monthly budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I'll do with my money even before it arrives,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   More Arizonans would be wise to follow her example. A recent
edition of the Rocky Mountain Poll found that nearly one in four
Phoenix area residents is saving less than 5 percent of his or her
income. About one in eight respondents reported not saving
anything, even as Arizona nears the end of its fifth straight year
of robust job growth.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers see this as a missed opportunity on a grand
scale, especially now that the United States is feeling turbulence
from slumping foreign economies. Although Arizona's jobless rate
has hovered near record lows in recent months, there has been
unsettling news _ announced layoffs at major employers such as
Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix area residents earning less than $25,000 a year would be
most vulnerable to an economic downturn, if one materializes. Ten
percent of the people in this group aren't saving anything, while
34 percent are setting aside less than 5 percent, according to the
Rocky Mountain Poll.
</P>
<P>
   Also, only 25 percent of these lower-income respondents are
saving more than they were last year, compared with 36 percent of
residents in general.
</P>
<P>
   A propensity to save doesn't really take off until family income
passes the $45,000 mark, according to the Behavior Research Center
in Phoenix, which conducted the Rocky Mountain Poll.
</P>
<P>
   The survey's results, coupled with rising bankruptcy numbers,
raise the question of whether some people become financially
reckless during good times _ making impulse buys, ringing up
credit-card purchases and failing to plan ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Arizonans filing for bankruptcy jumped to 24,686
last year from 19,684 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely will fear for a lot of people when the economy
turns,'' said Kim McGrigg, a spokeswoman for Consumer Credit
Counseling Services Southwest, which offers debt-repayment
assistance. ``We're already seeing more people than ever, and
bankruptcies are at record levels.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrigg thinks everyone should build up a rainy-day fund equal
to at least three months' worth of take-home pay. ``Ideally, people
should have a six-month reserve, but that's probably not
realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Lee Wagner, a senior financial adviser at American Express
Financial Advisors in Phoenix, suggests splitting the money into
various types of vehicles:
</P>
<P>
   _A checking account for money that can be accessed quickly and
conveniently, even if the yield is negligible or non-existent.
</P>
<P>
   _A bank savings account or money-market mutual fund paying
higher rates of interest, with possible restrictions on the number
of withdrawals or checks that can be written each month.
</P>
<P>
   _A ``laddered'' mix of certificates of deposit. The idea is to
arrange your finances so that you always have a CD coming due
reasonably soon. As a general rule, the longer the time until a CD
matures, the higher the yield it pays.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in the current environment of low interest rates, no
savings vehicles are paying much. That's why you don't want to
commit too much cash to a rainy-day fund. Once you have compiled an
ample reserve cushion, it's time to turn to stocks, bonds and
mutual funds that hold these investments.
</P>
<P>
   While they are riskier, bonds and, especially, stocks have
tended to produce much higher returns over the years. They're
appropriate if you want to build wealth, rather than merely store
it.
</P>
<P>
   What other tips can help increase your saving rate?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, arrange to have money debited automatically from
your paycheck and placed in a savings vehicle such as a
money-market mutual fund. If your employer doesn't allow this, you
can have the money transferred from a checking account.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payroll (and checking account) deduction plans are valuable
for the majority of people who don't have the discipline or time to
write and mail off a check each month,'' Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   The same principal applies to retirement programs such as 401(k)
plans at work, but these accounts feature additional benefits.
Money is deducted on a pretax basis from your paycheck and
deposited into an investment account of your choice. Typically,
employers offer matching contributions of perhaps 50 cents for each
$1 you invest.
</P>
<P>
   In the same vein, take a new look at individual retirement
accounts, including the new Roth IRAs. It's easy for most Americans
to qualify for one or either of these tax-sheltered accounts,
including many people with pension coverage at work.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, regard saving as a regular and indispensable
activity. ``Don't view this as an optional part of your budget,''
McGrigg said.
</P>
<P>
   If you must cut up your credit cards, do so. If you must conduct
a dollar-by-dollar review of your monthly income and expenses, make
the effort. Lane, who lives on Social Security and disability
payments, funnels at least something from each paycheck into her
savings account. She plans carefully for anticipated expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might take me three months to put away enough money to have
my hair done,'' she said. ``But I live on a budget and stay on
one.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Russ Wiles can be reached at russ.wiles(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
