<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2630 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELD-NEWHAMPSHIRE-BOS     10-12 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELD-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELD FLIRTS WITH GRANITE STATE REPUBLICANS
</HEADLINE>
 HAMPSHIRE-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ In politics, there are those who flirt with
running for president and those who come to the Granite State with
an entourage.
</P>
<P>
   Former Massachusetts governor William F. Weld, a moderate
Republican with a national following, came to the
first-in-the-nation primary state Monday night to flirt. He was the
star attraction at a fund-raiser for Peter Spaulding, one of the
state's five executive councilors up for reelection in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hard, once you get into Salem or Nashua, to be
very coy,'' said Thomas D. Rath, a longtime Republican activist who
is supporting Lamar Alexander for president. ``If you're here,
there is an assumption. It's rebuttable, but people start with the
assumption that you're not up here for the leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Weld strolled alone through the front door of Mike Ruedig's
home, an hour late, all the while denying presidential aspirations
had anything to do with his visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really have any,'' he said, insisting that New
Hampshire has long been a home away from home.
</P>
<P>
   Weld said he expected to play some sort of role in the 2000
race, citing friendships with at least five other politicians who
have been mentioned as candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But when Spaulding told the gathering of Republicans that Weld
had responded to his invitation within a half-hour, Weld could not
resist mischievously jumping in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was positively suspicious!'' he joked. But Weld also
injected a bit of politics into the evening when he told the crowd
that he supported Spaulding because he understands that ``there is
no such thing as government money, only taxpayers' money.''
</P>
<P>
   Some potential candidates already have offices and staff in New
Hampshire, including Alexander, the former governor of Tennessee;
Steve Forbes, the multimillionaire publisher; and Dan Quayle, the
former vice president. Others like to visit from time to time,
dipping a toe into presidential waters. That list includes Ohio
Representative John Kasich, Missouri Senator John Ashcroft, New
York City Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, and now Weld, attorney and
author.
</P>
<P>
   To be a flirtatious potential candidate, a politician must act
as if the mere thought of running for president is preposterous,
without directly ruling out the possibility. The advantage to
flirting is that the political establishment might actually start
begging the flirt to run, creating a buzz of speculation and
interest.
</P>
<P>
   On the ``Today'' show last month to promote his new book,
``Mackerel by Moonlight,'' Weld would not say when he was getting
back into politics. ``Well, I'm happy practicing law,'' Weld said.
``I'll pick a horse in 2000, and we'll _ we'll see after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would run for president himself, Weld said that it
was far too early to speculate and that he was having fun being an
author.
</P>
<P>
   If Weld won't speculate, his friends certainly don't mind doing
so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he would make a great president,'' said Acting
Governor Paul Cellucci, who inherited the corner office from Weld.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Howell, a former Weld aide, said he would be shocked if the
former governor ran for president in 2000. ``But on the other hand,
he's a relatively young guy and politics is in his blood,'' Howell
said. ``I could see him running again for something someday, and
this is Bill Weld, so anything is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Weld threw his support behind California Governor Pete
Wilson, whose campaign fizzled quickly. This summer, Weld showed up
at a lobster bake in Rye, thrown by Alexander, who never stopped
running for the Republican nomination after losing the New
Hampshire primary in '96.
</P>
<P>
   Rath said Weld has not hinted to anyone Rath knows that he is
thinking of running. Nevertheless, Rath said, a trip to New
Hampshire is a good way to guarantee attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ought to preserve every possible option for himself,'' Rath
said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda L. Fowler, a political science professor at Dartmouth
College, said it makes sense for almost anybody to take a look at
running. She pointed to long shots who have emerged in the past,
such as Jimmy Carter. ``It's not an exercise in hubris for people
to be doing this,'' Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   And if Weld doesn't ever formally run for president, the
exposure could lead to other job offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Hampshire might be good for picking a vice president,''
Fowler said. ``That could also be why somebody like a Weld is up
here, positioning himself as a Northeastern moderate Republican to
balance a ticket with someone like George Bush Jr. at the head of
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
