<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2636 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      10-12 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILENCE OF THE LAMBS, IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - It's as if a plate glass window fell from a high-rise
during lunch hour, smashing onto a crowded sidewalk and narrowly
missing hundreds of potential victims, and no one stopped or even
looked up.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday, Oct. 4, edition of ``The Washington Post'' carried a
full-page advertisement that read in big, bold letters:
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you had an adulterous sexual encounter with a current
member of the United States Congress or high-ranking government
official? Can you provide documentary evidence of illicit sexual
relations with a Congressman, Senator of other prominent
officeholder? Larry Flynt and ``Hustler'' magazine will pay you up
to $1 million if we choose to publish your verified story and use
your material.''
</P>
<P>
   It was followed by an 800 number.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a life form lower on the evolutionary scale than Larry
Flynt, aside from the parasitic organisms slithering from the ooze
in hopes of cashing in on his offer?
</P>
<P>
   The politicians in D.C. could have come out swinging. They had a
chance to take all the derisive adjectives the rest of us normally
reserve for them, and use them against Flynt.
</P>
<P>
   Who deserves it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the porno publisher's $85,000 full-page proposition was
met with silence. None of our normally vocal congressman from
Arizona had a thing to say. Nor did most others.
</P>
<P>
   On an average day, news reporters are to Washington politicians
what Leonardo DiCaprio is to teenage girls. But not this time.
There were a few bad jokes, a ``no comment'' or two. That's it.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few days, Flynt said he'd received several hundred
responses, adding, `You gotta understand, a majority of those are
gonna be crank calls without any merit. If I can get only 5 or 10
percent of that, I'll be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy?
</P>
<P>
   The guy lobs slime balls over the heart of the plate and no
bat-wielding politician is willing to take a cut.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if they're afraid of something.
</P>
<P>
   And they are, though it's not what you think. Members of
Congress aren't worried because they cheated on their spouses. Some
may have, but that's not why they refuse to attack Flynt.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about sex; it's about prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians know how Americans feel about people who profit from
tragedy or criminal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   We despise them.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the lawyers Clark, Darden, Shapiro and Cochran, who
made millions off two dead people in the O.J. Simpson case.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the vultures mining gold off their ``friendships'' with
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis or Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the hyenas who hoped to make a buck off pathetic
figures like Tonya Harding or Heidi Fleiss or Susan Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Think about Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   Think about Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The first one illegally tape-recorded her ``friend'' in order
get material for a blockbuster book deal she'd always dreamed
about.
</P>
<P>
   The second seduced a married man, spilled her guts to a grand
jury and now is hoping for a paycheck of much more than $1 million
for book or movie rights.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Congress can afford to condemn Flynt or the low-lifes
who try to cash in on his offer, not as long as their best
witnesses against President Bill Clinton are Tripp and Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians have no choice but to mill around like a flock
of sheep, with Kenneth Starr and Larry Flynt the sheperds. Or the
wolves.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt plans to dole out his millions one at a time. Starr spent
$40 million on a single case.
</P>
<P>
   Each man has the power to ruin politicians. Each can make
millionaires of those whose skills are best described on the pages
of ``Hustler'' or the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   And, both Starr and Flynt reinforce the message that, in
America, the pot of gold we're all looking for isn't located at the
end of a rainbow, but at the bottom of a sewer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
