<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2637 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YELTSIN-ILL-BOS &LR;      10-12 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-ILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN BECOMES ILL ON TRIP, RETURNS TO RUSSIA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In another blow to his dwindling authority, President
Boris N. Yeltsin was forced Monday to cut short his first trip
outside Russia in six months, after Kremlin doctors diagnosed him
with bronchitis, and ordered him back to Moscow for rest.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kremlin hoped that the planned three-day swing through
Central Asia would show that Yeltsin was still capable of running
the country, the abbreviated visit to Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan
appeared to have had the opposite result. The trip was cut back
after a series of mishaps that made the Russian leader look feeble,
ill, and out of touch.
</P>
<P>
   This weakness was displayed a week after a nationwide protest
that united hundreds of thousands of demonstrators under slogans
calling for Yeltsin to resign. Yeltsin has vowed to serve to the
end of his term in 2000, although many observers here doubt that
will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's economy has been in a free fall since August. Yeltsin
has barely commented on the crisis, and has spent most of his time
at his residence outside Moscow in what his aides describe as
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's health scares no longer cause world markets to tumble
and Russians to catch their breath. That would change, however, if
Yeltsin, 67, were to die or become too incapacitated to stay in
office. Russia has no tradition of democratic transfer of power,
and only vague rules for succession.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that may be one reason why the calls for Yeltsin to
resign have been accompanied by little action. An impeachment drive
has been stuck in parliament; Monday, the campaign stalled again
when a commission of lawmakers could not decide whether Yeltsin was
criminally liable for the deaths of some 80,000 Russian citizens
during the war in the breakaway southern province of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin aides insisted Monday that Yeltsin's latest illness was
not serious enough to force the president to go to the hospital or
even change his schedule. A spokesman suggested that Russia's
efforts to halt planned NATO airstrikes against Serbia over its
crackdown in the separatist province of Kosovo would continue. The
Kremlin says Yeltsin has held a number of phone conversations with
leaders of the Western alliance in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo crisis is another cause for concern. Monday,
Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov was quoted by Russian news
agencies as saying a NATO attack against Serb positions would be
``equivalent to a declaration of war against Russia,'' and vowed
Russia would ``support Yugoslavia with all our forces.'' Other
officials have not gone so far, but Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev
Monday promised unspecified ``tough measures'' in response to
possible NATO airstrikes. While Moscow's threats probably will not
prevent the strikes, the new questions surrounding the Kremlin's
commander-in-chief will probably add to the uncertainty about the
Russian response.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's doctor, Sergei Mironov, who accompanied the president
on the trip, was quoted by the news agency Interfax as saying
Yeltsin had a temperature of 99.3 and was being treated with
antibiotics. A Kremlin spokesman, Dmitri Yakushkin, said Yeltsin
fell ill last week but insisted on going ahead with the trip.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Yeltsin's many bouts with illnesses, including the
heart disease that led to quintuple bypass surgery in November
1996, Kremlin aides have played down the severity of his health
problems, and have described the president as a poor patient who is
raring to get back to work.
</P>
<P>
   In his trip, Yeltsin moved stiffly and with apparent difficulty.
At a welcoming ceremony Sunday in Uzbekistan's capital, Tashkent,
he stumbled, and had to be steadied and ushered away by
Uzbekistan's President Islam Karimov. Yeltsin canceled several
other appearances, and coughed uncontrollably at talks between
Russian and Uzbek officials.
</P>
<P>
   In Kazakhstan Monday, Yeltsin did not look much better in talks
with President Nursultan Nazarbayev. At a signing ceremony,
Yeltsin, his tongue poking out of his lips, took several minutes to
put his signature to six documents, then appeared to stumble again
as he got up briefly. Shortly after an odd, rambling speech,
Yeltsin left the room, leaning on Nazarbayev for support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 2016EDT &QL; 
