<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT-RECALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite recall, no illnesses attributed to tainted beef
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Students at Clayton and Rockdale county schools may
have eaten beef patties included in a recall because of possible
salmonella contamination, school officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But no illnesses have been reported that could be attributed to
the bacteria, which can cause diarrhea but usually doesn't result
in serious sickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we didn't know we couldn't help,'' said Wendy McNamee,
Clayton's director of food nutrition. The school system was unaware
of the recall last week when it served charbroiled beef patties
made at Zartic Inc., a Cedartown, Ga. meat processing company.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the U.S. Department of Agriculture and Zartic
expanded a recall of meat products made at the plant. The
nationwide recall, initiated Sept. 25, now includes about 2 million
pounds of beef, poultry and pork products that were distributed to
schools, hospitals and prisons in 34 states.
</P>
<P>
   The meat products were precooked, then quick-frozen for
shipping. While salmonella contamination is not rare, especially in
raw meat and unwashed produce, it is unusual to find it in cooked
foods.
</P>
<P>
   As thorough cooking does kill the bacteria, properly reheating
the frozen Zartic products should eliminate any possible danger,
said Jack Harris, Zartic's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My expectation is that the vast majority of the products we
are recalling are perfectly good, fine products,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said the plant had voluntarily closed three production
lines that were implicated in the contaminated paddies.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company was working with USDA to try to find out
what caused the meat to be contaminated with illness-causing
salmonella bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not yet determined what the source was, but we believe
it is a surface contamination that somehow got on some of the
product after the cooking step.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Rockdale high school students may have eaten tainted
hamburger patties on Monday, said Linda Waters, director of
Rockdale Schools Food Services.
</P>
<P>
   But it is standard procedure in Rockdale cafeteria kitchens to
cook all meat, whether precooked or raw, at 160 degrees or above to
kill contaminants, Waters said. Rockdale has pulled hamburgers from
today's menus.
</P>
<P>
   Other school systems, including Coweta, Fayette, Gwinnett and
Henry counties, also receive meat products from Zartic. Gwinnett
and Henry officials said the Zartic products they have in stock are
not included in the recall. Fayette and Coweta schools have pulled
Zartic products from their menus.
</P>
<P>
   Zartic, meanwhile, is under a ``hold and test'' order, meaning
nothing leaves the plant until a sample is tested from each lot,
said Linda Swacina, spokeswoman for the Food Safety Inspection
Service of the Agriculture Department. The order will stand until
officials determine how the contamination happened, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA has received no reports of illness.
</P>
<P>
   Eating food tainted with salmonella can cause salmonellosis, cq
whose symptoms include diarrhea, fever and abdominal cramps 12 to
72 hours after infection. The symptoms usually last 4 to 7 days,
and resolve without medical treatment unless severa diarrhea causes
dehydration. Young children, older adults and those with impaired
immune systems are more likely to get sicker from salmonella.
</P>
<P>
   Salmonella lives in animal intestines, and is most often
associated with raw or undercooked foods of animal origin such as
poultry, beef, milk or eggs. Thorough cooking kills salmonella, so
people should avoid eating underdone meats, unpasteurized milk and
foods made with raw eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetables may also be contaminated, however, so raw produce
should be washed before eating. Cross-contamination also should be
avoided, by washing hands, cutting boads, counters, knives and
other surfaces after handling uncooked foods.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Diane Lore, Jeff Nesmith, Delbert Ellerton, Leon
Stafford, Jennifer Brett and Patti Puckett contributed to this
article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
