<SLUG> BC-VIRGIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pilgrims gather for final public message at Fowler's farm
 &HT;    By Peter Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Paulina Varbuena is expecting a miracle today at Nancy
Fowler's farm in Conyers, Ga. So are thousands of other people who
are at the farm to hear what Fowler says will be the final message
that she will publicly share from the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   For Varbuena, who arrived in Conyers on Monday from Bogota,
Columbia, the miracle she expects will only add to what she already
has received.
</P>
<P>
   Varbuena, speaking through an interpreter, said she had a vision
of the Blessed Mother Mary during her bus ride on Monday to the
farm. Friends also said that Varbuena had three rosaries that
changed color.
</P>
<P>
   Experts today will be looking to authenticate experiences such
as Varbuena's. Ricardo Castanon, a Bolivian neuropsychophysiologist
who specializes in stigmata and weeping statues, said the
phenomenon is simple: God is talking to the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is saying that he is still alive, but his followers have
forgotten him,'' said Castanon.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 people are expected for the message that
Fowler will deliver today at 1:45 p.m. Police are asking local
motorists to avoid using the main north-south county highway.
</P>
<P>
   But locals like Barbara Frazier, a Baptist who said she plans to
attend, won't have much choice. She said she ignored the event in
the past, but wants to be part of today's gathering ``out of
curiosity and for inspiration.'' Meanwhile, human traffic lines
began forming Monday at stores and restaurants, as a steady flow of
buses, motorhomes and cars made their way to the farm.
</P>
<P>
   The event is attracting media attention worldwide. The Catholic
Church, however, has not given its blessings to the claims by
Fowler, a homemaker and former nurse.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church views all apparitions skeptically, said the
Rev. Peter Dora, vicar general and spokesman for the Archdiocese of
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any kind of study is detailed, and takes many, many years,''
Dora said.
</P>
<P>
   The last apparition site to have been given papal approval was
at Fatima, Portugal. Three shepherd children reported to have seen
an angel of peace in 1916 and, later, the Virgin Mary, on Oct. 13,
1917, when she told the children three secrets. Vatican approval
took 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Tesoriero, an Australian lawyer and television producer, has
been documenting Fowler's claims since 1992. He plans to chronicle
today's events.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who have taken the trouble to examine the story in
detail know that something is happening with Nancy Fowler, and that
it is not something created or the result of any mental imbalance
or fraud by any of her supporters,'' Tesoriero said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Scott writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
