<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEASURESIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firms had different means of measuring Web
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before merging, Media Metrix and Relevant Knowledge
used different methodologies to measure the audience for sites on
the World Wide Web. Just as Nielsen ratings help advertisers
evaluate television programs, these companies created the yardstick
for advertising on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Relevant Knowledge used a randomly selected panel of 10,000
users who downloaded software from a special Web site. The software
let the company track the users' surfing habits as they went from
site to site.
</P>
<P>
   The company pioneered the idea of measuring a site's popularity
by tracking how many separate people visited it rather than the
traditional method of counting how many ``hits'' it received. Under
the older method, one person could visit a site several times and
each ``hit'' by the person would be counted.
</P>
<P>
   Because the company's technology is Web-based, Relevant
Knowledge is able to turn around data for clients faster than Media
Metrix. For example, when the Starr Report was published on the
Internet, Relevant Knowledge was able to release usage figures
several days later.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix uses patented software ``meters'' to measure
Internet and offline usage. The meters capture real-time, actual
behavior of Internet users. Media Metrix asks its panel of 30,000
users to install software that monitors all PC activity, ranging
from surfing the Web to running software to using services such as
America Online, Pointcast and Juno.
</P>
<P>
   Because the disks must be returned to Media Metrix for download
and analysis, the company reports Web usage on a monthly basis
only. The newly-merged company, according to Levy, will be able to
provide new measurement products and services beginning next year.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
