<HEADER>
A2660 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELEVANT-COX     10-12 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELEVANT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web measurement firms to merge
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta-based Relevant Knowledge and Media Metrix, the
two leading Web measurement providers and strong competitors, said
Monday they would merge to form a company that could create an
industry standard for the Web advertising and marketing industry.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will retain the name Media Metrix with the
tagline, ``The Power of Relevant Knowledge.'' Neither Media Metrix
President and Chief Operating Officer Mary Ann Packo nor Relevant
Knowledge founder Jeff Levy would discuss financial terms. Levy
estimated the combined revenue of the new company to be ``in the
low eight figures.'' The companies say the merger of the two
private entities will become final by Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   While company officials called this a true merger of equals, the
top two officers of the new company come from New York-based Media
Metrix. Packo will maintain her title as president of the new
company. Tod Johnson, chairman and chief executive of Media Metrix,
will hold that title in the new company. Levy will be vice chairman
and a board member of the newly created company.
</P>
<P>
   During a one-hour press briefing, company officials said the
newly created firm would not have one headquarters city, but would
split its corporate headquarters near Georgia Tech in Atlanta, New
York City and San Francisco. Packo will remain in New York, while
Levy will continue to be based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Levy said there will be no relocation or downsizing. ``We're
here in downtown Atlanta,'' he said. The newly merged company will
have 90 employees evenly split among Atlanta, New York City and San
Francisco. Levy and partner Tim Cobb, also named vice chairman of
the new company, will focus on new product technology and
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not two big, overstaffed companies merging,'' Levy
said. ``It's two small, understaffed companies.'' He said the new
company plans to expand its staff by at least 35 percent in the
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The merger) is the starting point of more growth,'' Levy
said, ``Not by cost cutting, but by integration and combining the
best of both companies and providing things to our clients neither
of us have been able to provide on our own. This is what the
industry has been looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the merger, Media Metrix and Relevant Knowledge used
different techniques to measure Web usage. Now, according to Packo,
the merged company will be able to leverage the strengths of both
methodologies and create new products that will serve advertisers,
brands and media buyers. Instead of two companies vying for
supremacy, the new Media Metrix could dictate the way Internet
measurement is done.
</P>
<P>
   Packo and Levy said the combined methodologies will enable the
new company to develop products neither would have been able to
produce on its own. ``We are looking at weekly ratings,'' Packo
said. ``We'll have breadth and depth and speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy and Packo both said the merger was a result of advertiser
concerns and demands from an industry conference called the Proctor
&AMP; Gamble FAST summit, held in August to discuss the best ways to
accelerate the growth of the online advertising industry.
Advertisers, agencies and Web sites were clamoring for a reliable
measurement standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FAST Summit crystallized the need for what we're doing,''
Levy said. ``We have numbers they can understand and believe in.
We'll work closely with the FAST group to make sure what we've got
what the industry wants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good thing for the industry,'' said Richy
Glassberg, senior vice president and general manager of Turner
Interactive Sales and a founding member of the Interactive
Advertising Bureau as well as a member of the FAST Summit steering
committee. ``They've stopped the infighting, and now they can get
down to some of the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Glassberg hopes the company expands its panel of business and
university users.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you only measure home usage you miss a lot of the users
on the Web, and that doesn't do anybody any good,'' he said.
``There should be better measuring of Web usage in the workplace
and at universities. Agencies and clients are very concerned that
nobody is measuring this audience. Just because they've gotten
together doesn't mean they've solved any of the problems. They have
a lot to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Winter, president of Cox Interactive Media, also applauded
the merger. ``These two companies have shown the way for audience
measurement on the Web,'' he said. ``It's also a good thing for the
Atlanta Internet industry. It means the premier audience
measurement company will be based here in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What everyone is crying for in the industry is standards, and
while both companies are highly regarded, it will allow further
unified standards and benchmarks for advertisers, publishers and
vendors,'' said Drew Ianni, online advertising analyst with Jupiter
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Ianni said the new company might have joined forces to be better
prepared for the eventual entrance of Nielsen Media Research into
the Web measurement field. ``The key is for them to come out with
one defined standard and they may become the de facto standard if
nobody else becomes a player in the space.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
