<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2679 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     10-12 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THERE was a time, less than 20 years ago, when the NBA was not the
hottest marketing success in the pantheon of American sports, when
the fantasy of every kid on the streets was not to wear his _ or
her _ shorts baggy enough to hide a school bus or to have a
smoothly shaved head and star in a cartoon movie with Bugs Bunny,
just like Mike.
</P>
<P>
   Back in those days, the dark ages, the league was a cult sport
made up of free-spirited players and hard-core, devoted owners who
simply loved the rhythm and individual artistry of this distinctly
American game.
</P>
<P>
   At the very best, it was an underground phenomenon toiling on
the outer fringes of obscurity, playing in half-filled arenas with
championship games shown on tape delay around midnight. At worst,
the NBA was a core of splendid athletes surrounded by a collection
of bad actors and druggies, a bad attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Today, of course, all that has changed. It has crossed
international boundaries, rivaling soccer in worldwide popularity
to the point where every Tom, Dick and Vladimir can recite the
Chicago Bulls' starting lineup. The stars of the game are megawatt
celebrities, journeyman players average nearly $2 million per year
in salary, and shiny new arenas have been erected from coast to
coast to pay homage to the game's marketing success.
</P>
<P>
   But now is the time _ as the current labor showdown begins this
week to wipe out scheduled exhibition games _ for the principals on
both sides of the dispute to be reminded that their fancy houses
and their success are built on a fragile foundation of sand.
</P>
<P>
   We know that NBA players spend much of their time up in the air,
but their brains cannot be so oxygen-depleted that they don't
realize how quickly the fans who support them by buying overpriced
tickets and team jerseys will turn on a labor force that includes
too many whining twentysomethings who are making more than $100
million. We know that NBA commissioner David Stern and the league's
owners believe they will always be able to sell flash over
substance to the American public, but the folks who ultimately foot
the bills for new pleasure palaces and $1,000 courtside seats have
only so many oxen that can be gored.
</P>
<P>
   While raising ticket prices (owners) and demanding
ever-increasing salaries (players), both sides have overlooked one
very salient fact: It ain't baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The supporters of the former national pastime finally had enough
with the shutdown of 1994-95 and cut off the sport at the knees, a
bitter reaction that is only now beginning to soften after a
magical summer of Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   It took decades of abuse to erode baseball's popularity, because
for decades it was America's only real national game. It was a
shared experience that was lovingly passed down like a sack of
ballpark peanuts from generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA success of the '80s and '90s is built on spandex,
3-point shots, fuzzy mascots and exploding scoreboards, the lack of
which will not be mourned in many corners.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming love the public holds for pro basketball is
like that of a one-night stand, no deeper than a wading pool. There
remains a hard-core audience of hoops fanatics whose devotion will
be unswayed by any labor nonsense and who will always come back to
the gym.
</P>
<P>
   The problem will be in keeping the
``we're-here-because-it's-hot'' fans, the ones who would plunk down
$1,000 to sit ringside at a cockfight if the whole experience was
supplemented by loud music, scantily clad dancing girls, a network
TV shill and all of the other little marketing gimmicks of which
the league is so proud. These are the people whom a protracted
labor dispute will send running to the door as if a fire alarm just
sounded, the ones who save their loudest cheers for the dunking
mascot or the fan who shoots to win a car at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The players are following ``union man'' Michael Jordan, who will
never be confused with Samuel Gompers, who was paid $34 million
last season by the Bulls and who is one of the main reasons why the
rank-and-file players are being squeezed on salaries.
</P>
<P>
   The owners are following Stern, the charming lawyer and
marketing Nero who has fiddled at base problems in the game for
years while continuing to foster an atmosphere that would make
Caligula blush.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they stand at the brink, engaged in a staredown. I know of
no one who really cares.
</P>
<P>
   It's a short trip back to the dark ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
