<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS SAY BUDGET DEAL IS NEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ll) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republican leaders said on Monday
night that they were close to an agreement with the White House on
the federal budget, but administration officials were more cautious
and both sides agreed to postpone the Monday midnight deadline to
midnight Wednesday to work out their differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have most items closed tonight,'' Sen. Trent Lott,
R-Miss., the majority leader, said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich said he expected to wrap up negotiations
with the White House late Monday night, but added, ``We've reached
many tentative possible agreements, none of which count until we
finish up the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott and Gingrich both predicted that the House and Senate would
vote by Wednesday to approve the final package reached with the
White House on the $1.7 trillion budget, of which about $500
billion has been in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials cautioned that major issues,
including President Clinton's education initiatives, remained on
the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our two key priorities have not been resolved,'' said Linda
Ricci, a spokeswoman for the Office of Management and Budget. ``It
would be premature to predict any immediate resolution until those
are addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton raised the stakes by pushing Congress publicly to pass
the education initiatives. One would provide $1.1 billion as a
downpayment on 100,000 teachers, the other would leverage billions
of dollars worth of bonds to upgrade scool buildings throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and congressional leaders agreed to provide
money for the teachers, but were debating whether it could be used
only for hiring new teachers, as the administration wanted, or
whether local school districts would have some leeway over the
spending, as Republicans proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Other big issues remain unresolved. These include a major battle
between Democrats and Republicans over how to conduct the census,
which Gingrich has suggested be postponed for six months, and the
conditions under which Republicans would finance the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's extension was the third time that Congress and
the White House pushed back their deadline since the fiscal year
began on Oct. 1. But there is still little sense of what the final
package will look like and what extraneous issues it might contain.
Possibilities include a tiny tax break that the House passed on
Monday. The tax break, in the form of extensions of various
business tax credits, is so small _ $9.2 billion over 10 years _
that its Republican backers say it will cost nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Other items under discussion for the final package ranged from
the global, like money for a Star Wars missile defense system, to
the local, like extending the duck-hunting season in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich is angling for at least a $7.5 billion increase in
emergency military spending. Arguing that it would be
``irresponsible'' not to beef up the Pentagon, Gingrich said he
wanted a dollar-for-dollar match of the Clinton Administration's
request for domestic emergency measures.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., chairman of the Appropriations
Committee, is seeking $1 billion as a downpayment for a Star Wars
missile defense system. Livingston is also seeking language to
block a plan for the national allocation of human organs for
transplant, prefering to keep such allocations under local control.
</P>
<P>
   Lott wants to extend the duck-hunting season in his home state
and five others. Lott, himself a hunter, is concerned that because
ducks tend not to fly as far south as Mississippi during the
migratory season, it was only fair to extend the season an extra 11
days to give Southern duck hunters more of a chance.
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, chairman of the Appropriations
Committee, is insisting that a seven-mile road and utility lines be
constructed through the Izembeck National Wildlife Refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens says that the remote community of King Cove needs a land
link to allow for emergency medical vehicles. Opponents say this
construction would violate pristine wilderness and is a thinly
disguised attempt to promote business development and help link
North America's largest salmon cannery in King Cove with one of
Alaska's premier airstrips at Cold Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Some proposals had the support of both parties, like an $86
million request by several Senators to refinance a loan for the
Tennessee Valley Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he was irked that the Administration was still seeking
several small-sum items in the billion-dollar final package, and
that these demands were made in the top-level meetings instead of
being resolved at the staff level.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're talking about a multi-billion-dollar budget, as
much as a third of the full budget,'' he said, ``for us now to be
arguing over the smallest amount of funds for various and sundry
programs is not a good use of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ricci of the Office of Management and Budget said that
including such items was a normal part of the negotiating process.
</P>
<P>
   And Democrats were not alone in the small-sum game. Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato, R-N.Y., who is locked in a tight re-election campaign, is
seeking $6 million toward a reconstructive surgery program for
women with breast cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
