<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can Cleveland afford not to start Justice, Alomar?
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the situation is so hopeless that St. Jude, the
patron saint of lost causes, laughs in your face, baseball players
turn to the comfort of mumbling bromides and cliches. In the
current case of Cleveland vs. New York, 1998, the Indians are
compiling The Neophyte's Glossary of Cliches &AMP; Bromides.
</P>
<P>
   If the Tribe holds a team meeting before Game 6 of the American
League Championship Series in Yankee Stadium tonight, there will be
25 guys lined up against the wall, their backs against it.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians didn't spend their off day Monday in the vicinity of
the Empire State Building looking for The Miracle on 34th Street.
If they did, they could have read the graffiti on the wall. They
are in trouble. Deep trouble. Deep Six trouble.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a shocking two games to one lead in the
best-of-seven ALCS, the Tribe lost two straight at home in Jacobs
Field _ The Wake at the Jake.
</P>
<P>
   Now they trail three games to two and must win two straight to
advance to the World Series. The ball is in the palm of righty
Charles Nagy tonight, the Tribe's hottest pitcher, against David
Cone.
</P>
<P>
   If they survive, 23-year-old Bartolo ``Pancho'' Colon gets the
baseball Wednesday in Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at the reality, it's going to be difficult,''
Tribe first baseman/designated hitter Jim Thome said. ``But you
know what? We're going to be very confident. And if it works out,
it works out. If it don't, it don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can argue with that . . . except the English.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the misery is the status of catcher Sandy Alomar Jr.
and left fielder/DH David Justice. Neither started Game 5 and while
both say they'll play tonight, the question is, ``How well?''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Hargrove had Justice in the lineup Sunday, but
Justice asked out, saying his forearm was too sore. Justice was hit
on the arm with a pitch Saturday. He did pinch-hit Sunday and
grounded into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar is fighting a bad back. Knowing this, the Yankees are
running full-bore on the basepaths. And Alomar is 1 for 13 (.077)
in the five games he has played.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, knowing Alomar's importance, shortstop Omar
Vizquel said, ``I hope Sandy takes some drugs and plays.'' Alomar's
replacement, Einor Diaz, a late call-up from Triple-A Buffalo,
played only 17 games for the Tribe this season.
</P>
<P>
   And it isn't likely rookie first baseman/DH Richie Sexson will
emerge from the visitor's dugout tonight, despite a sensational run
after a late-season call-up from Buffalo. Since Since Sept. 19,
Sexson is 0 for 24 with 13 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Joey Cora, obtained last this season in a trade
with Seattle for David Bell because Cora is an alleged Yankee
Killer, has been benched in favor of another guy who spent most of
the season at Buffalo, Enrique Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Vizquel, who could be ALCS MVP if the Tribe comes back to win _
otherwise hand the trophy right now to zany Yankee left-hander
David Wells _ is 10 for 20 in the five games, although he has not
driven in a run and scored only one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like our pitching match-ups,'' Vizquel said. Both Nagy and
Colon won games against Boston in the Division Series and they won
the two games the Tribe has won against the Yankees. ``We're using
our two best pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Thome sounded like a guy being handed a blindfold, a cigarette
and asked if he had any last words.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go in there confident,'' he said. ``We ain't
hanging our heads. We're not going to lay down and die.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's check. Nope. Nobody named Daniel on this team. So the
Indians have to walk into the Yankees' lion's den on their own. And
if Tribe pitchers walk 11 and hit two batters, the way they did in
Game 5 Sunday, even Daniel can't help.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
