<SLUG> BC-FBC-OSUFB13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite top ranking, OSU's flaws exposed against Illinois
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ It's not easy to find flaws with No. 1-ranked
Ohio State, but last Saturday vs. Illinois one was readily apparent
in the Buckeyes short-yardage running game.
</P>
<P>
   OSU was stopped twice on third and one by an inferior Illinois
team, which fell, 41-0, to the Buckeyes. The first stalemate came
in the first quarter when they were on the Illini's 2-yard line
poised to score. It took them five plays, including a
fourth-and-short effort, to get the ball into the end zone. And
that score came not on a run but on a 1-yard pass to tight end John
Lumpkin of Trotwood.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the second half, the Buckeyes again were foiled in a
short yardage situation, failing to convert on second-and-1 and
then third-and-1 inside Illinois territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We end up punting the ball,'' OSU coach John Cooper said. ``To
me, that was the most discouraging thing that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper also expressed displeasure that five-play goal line
effort, when his offense failed to gain two or fewer yards on four
straight attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Michael Wiley, who carried the ball three of those four
times, shares the blame for the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a combination of a couple of bad runs by the tailback,
which is me, and a couple of missed blocks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive lineman Rob Murphy, too, admitted there were a couple
of ``breakdowns'' on the line but said, ``We scored, so I don't
understand why everyone's complaining about this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're No. 1,'' he said. ``We wracked up 500 yards of offense.
But I turn on the radio this morning and they're saying we don't
have a rushing game, blah, blah, blah.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there's some nit-picking going on as the top-ranked
Buckeyes (5-0, 2-0 Big Ten) prepare to face another unranked
opponent this week when Minnesota (3-2, 0-2 Big Ten) visits Ohio
Stadium on Saturday. But Cooper and several players agree that the
Buckeyes short-yardage rushing game is a legitimate concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really shocked and kind of upset it took us that long,
third and short, then third and goal (to score),'' wide receive Dee
Miller of Springfield said. ``We should be able to punch it in
anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   Said quarterback Joe Germaine: ``It's definitely something we
need to improve on. In big games, we need to be able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem may be the Buckeyes lack of an experienced,
true fullback. Starter Matt Keller was stopped on first and goal,
although Cooper said he thought the fullback's upper body got into
the end zone for the score. The coach didn't point the finger at
the offensive line, a frequent target of criticism last year,
saying it continues to progress.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Murphy takes it as a personal affront when the running
game is criticized and he vows to make improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuse,'' Murphy said. ``I'm sure there's going to
be a lot of time this week devoted to short yardage and goal line
(plays).''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
