A2705 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BENGALS13-COX     10-12 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After QB shakeup in 1997, O'Donnell settles in
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Jeff Blake gave way to Boomer Esiason, who gave way
to Neil O'Donnell. When it comes to starting quarterbacks, Bengals
management makes no apologies for the upheaval of the last year.
</P>
<P>
   All it knows is that O'Donnell is the No. 1 passer in the AFC
with a 103.2 rating, thanks to his performance in the Bengals'
25-20 victory over Pittsburgh on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell completed 20 of 26 passes for 298 yards and three
touchdowns _ two to Darnay Scott and the 25-yard, game-winner to
Carl Pickens that authored what team president Mike Brown called
``a storybook ending.''
</P>
<P>
   With no timeouts remaining for Cincinnati, O'Donnell launched a
50-yard desperation pass to Pickens on fourth and 12 from the
Bengals' 15-yard line with 48 seconds to go, which Pickens caught.
</P>
<P>
   After two Corey Dillon runs netted a first down at the Steelers'
25, O'Donnell approached the line of scrimmage and yelled ``Clock
Clock'' _ a play in which he has the option to spike the ball to
stop the clock or throw a pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to throw it to Darnay (on the right side),'' head
coach Bruce Coslet said. ``But (cornerback) Carnell Lake jumped in
front of the slant pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carl came off the line, watched Neil look the other way and
geared it down. When Neil looked back at Carl, he took back off. He
laid it up and they made a play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They caught us off-guard,'' Steelers linebacker Levon Kirkland
said.
</P>
<P>
   Coslet said the team has two variations of the spike-the-ball
play. On the first, the quarterback must fling the ball down. On
the second, he has the choice of either downing the ball or
throwing downfield if the defense is lax because it's expecting the
spike. That's exactly what happened on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I yell a certain word and a lot of people think it's something
else,'' O'Donnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Coslet called O'Donnell's effort another step on the learning
curve for the quarterback who joined the team July 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neil's in a real learning process and so are the coaches with
him,'' Coslet said. ``We're learning what he does best and what he
likes to do in certain situations. He's doing a real good job. He's
way farther along than he was two, three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he's learning his receivers. He's figured out that he
cannot overthrow Darnay, and if he throws it up high to Carl,
chances are we're going to come down with a play. He's established
himself now. He knows what's going on good enough to make us
function. He's just got to keep working on little details.''
</P>
<P>
   Coslet said O'Donnell ``came in here with a no-nonsense work
ethic from day one'' and earned his teammates respect _ just as
Esiason did when he replaced Blake after a 3-8 start and engineered
a 4-1 finish that highlighted a 7-9 record in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said O'Donnell and the retired Esiason ``are both very
poised players'' with radically different personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a much quieter, more subdued and introspective
personality,'' Brown said about O'Donnell. ``Boomer is outgoing and
brash. They both are attractive people, just different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boomer walks in and is ready to assume command immediately and
lets everyone sort of know that's how he thinks. That doesn't mean
the way Neil goes about things is less than right. He's just
quieter. When players see him play well, they will react to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
