<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Running game key to Falcons win, Reeves says
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There were a lot of good things from the Atlanta
Falcons' 34-20 victory Sunday night against the New York Giants,
but coach Dan Reeves on Monday praised the success of the running
game.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal Anderson, a fifth-year player from Utah taken as the 24th
running back in the 1994 draft, rushed 29 times for 110 yards to
become the third back in Falcons history to rush for more than 100
yards three games in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Riggs did it twice (once doing it four games in a row),
and William Andrews did it once.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't have a time of possession unless you can run the
ball,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is second in the NFL in average rushing yards per game
(102.4), trailing only Denver's Terrell Davis (144.2). The Falcons
also are second in the NFL in average time of possession at 33:20.
</P>
<P>
   That's a big help to the Falcons' defense. ``When we came here
(before last season) . . . we felt one of the biggest things we
could do to help our defense was be a ball-control team,'' Reeves
said.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't appear the Falcons had any serious injuries Sunday
night. Reeves knocked on wood, literally, when he said that reserve
CB Randy Fuller's strained hamstring was the greatest concern, and
that he was questionable for practice Wednesday. . . . The bursa
sac in QB Chris Chandler's left _ non-throwing _ elbow was swollen
after hitting the turf several times. It was drained after the
game. . . . Reeves also said reserve CB Michael Booker, who hasn't
played since straining a thigh muscle in the Wednesday practice
after the 49ers game, probably will be able to play Sunday against
the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Upon review
</P>
<P>
   When Giants WR David Patten scored on a 39-yard post pattern 33
seconds before halftime, the blame was split between rookie CB
Elijah Williams, who was beaten on the play, and assistant head
coach/defensive coordinator Rich Brooks. The play pulled the Giants
to within 14-13.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was playing in the dime because of Booker's
absence, appeared to give up on Patten as soon as the WR got a
couple steps on him, perhaps thinking dime safety Devin Bush was
going to help deep. But the defensive call was for Bush to
``bracket'' the slot receiver on the left side, not the outside
receiver, Patten.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's (defensive) call is on me,'' Brooks said. ``We should
have bracketed the outside receiver. The disappointing thing is
that he just kind of stopped. (Williams) was supposed to trail him
all the way regardless of what the call was. It was a rookie
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Players of the game were Anderson and Chandler (14-of-27, 266
yards, two TDs, no interceptions, one rushing TD) on offense,
rookie WR Jammi German on special teams (two tackles on kickoff
returns, an assist on a punt return), and DE Lester Archambeau
(five tackles, 1.5 sacks) and CB Ronnie Bradford (12 tackles) on
defense. . . . LB Keith Brooking, the team's first-round draft
choice, forced the first fumble of his career when he stripped New
York TE Howard Cross after a 5-yard pass. He also had a tackle on
special teams, and one at LB. ``My (strained thigh muscle) still
isn't 100 percent, so I can't burst or plant like I want to,''
Brooking said. ``I over-pursued, and when I knew I couldn't make
the tackle I reached back. That felt good.'' . . . Billy Joe
Tolliver will start for the Saints on Sunday, replacing Danny
Wuerffel. Tolliver played with the Falcons on two occasions, from
1991-93 and '96-97.
</P>
<P>
   Slumping
</P>
<P>
   P Dan Stryzinski, who signed a three-year, $1.98 million
contract in the offseason, remains ranked last in the NFL with a
37.7-yard average after averaging 34.3 yards against the Giants.
But New York returned just one of his punts, for 6 yards, and just
eight of Stryzinski's 30 kicks have been returned this season.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said part of the reason Stryzinski's average has slipped
is because he kicked several pooch punts in opponents territory.
``Dan again punted the ball well at times, but we aren't as
consistent as we need to be,'' Reeves said. ``He's just in a slump,
like a hitter, and he's got to work himself out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
