<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons learn about life in the limelight
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons got a rare off day on Monday, a
reward of sorts for their 34-20 road victory on Sunday night
against the New York Giants and the franchise's third 4-1 start in
its 33-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Players normally run, lift and watch film on Monday, but only
about 15 came to the Suwanee, Ga. headquarters, most for injury
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But while players were plodding along, and not thinking much
about Sunday's home game against New Orleans (3-2), coach Dan
Reeves, the media relations staff and ticket office were busy.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves taped an interview with EPSN's Chris Myers for an ``Up
Close'' special. CNN/SI was in Suwanee. Terry Bradshaw of Fox
called to say he's stopping by on Friday, and reporters from ESPN
and USA Today plan to visit today.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket manager Jack Ragsdale said the Falcons sold approximately
3,000 tickets on Monday for upcoming games, including about 2,000
for the Saints game. A crowd of 60,000 _ bigger than any in two
years _ appears possible.
</P>
<P>
   Life certainly is a whole lot better than this time last year,
when the Falcons were 0-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a night and day difference,'' center Robbie Tobeck
said. ``It was miserable (last year). It feels good that we're
getting some attention around here. That's something we haven't had
_ ever. Even a couple years back, when we went to the playoffs
(with a 9-7 record in 1995), everybody thought we were a
pretender.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory against the Giants was the 10th for Atlanta in 13
games, leaving the Falcons tied with the 49ers for first place in
the NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday's game against the Saints, whom the Falcons have
beaten six straight times, offers Atlanta a chance to beat a team
with a winning record for the first time since a 20-17 upset of
Carolina in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Other than back-to-back games on Nov. 8 and 15 against a pair of
4-1 teams, the 49ers and Patriots, future opponents are 18-28.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta put forth a strong performance against New York, scoring
on four of its first five possessions in the second half. Jamal
Anderson became the third back in Falcons history to rush for more
than 100 yards three games in a row, and Chris Chandler threw for
two touchdowns and ran for another. An offensive line that allowed
16 sacks the first three games gave up two for the second game in a
row. Nevertheless, Reeves is cautious. He knows the Falcons'
victories have come against teams with a combined record of 3-19.
After 4-1 starts in 1986 and '95, Atlanta finished the seasons
3-7-1 and 5-6.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have never started a season 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we . . . get big heads or whatever, or get overconfident .
. . we'll be 4-2,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can happen to anybody. If you get some people hurt, all of
a sudden you can be real mediocre real quickly. We've got to be
fortunate to be healthy, and . . . keep things in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Chuck Smith said this team has that perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all feel more confident,'' he said. ``I talked to
(Giants defensive end Michael) Strahan, and he said, `Man, those
guys came at me.' He said he was really surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobeck didn't sound surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of trying to win, or saying, `We think we can win,'''
he said, ``we expect to win, and that goes a long ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
