<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons notes: Coaches find loyalty sometimes backfires
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Loyalty is a wonderful quality to possess as a head
coach and, in fact, might be the attribute players most desire in a
sideline boss. That said, after the events of this weekend, Bill
Parcells and Marty Schottenheimer may want to review their policies
that starters do not lose their jobs because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   It is an unofficial rule, rooted in loyalty. In most cases, it
works. In the case of quarterbacks, however, it often backfires.
There comes a time when loyalty turns to blind trust, and that time
came Sunday for the Jets and Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Vinny Testaverde's 2-0 record as a starter, Parcells
went back to Glenn Foley. Give ``The Tuna'' high marks for loyalty
and a failing grade for not acknowledging that Testaverde is one of
the great streak shooters in recent memory. You ride him while he's
hot and, when he inevitably goes frigid, you make a switch.
</P>
<P>
   The irony now is that Parcells spent 25 minutes Monday morning
discussing with his assistants the possibility of trading for
Carolina's Kerry Collins. Such a move probably would mean cutting
Foley.
</P>
<P>
   Schottenheimer should have learned his lesson in last year's AFC
semifinal defeat to Denver. In his biggest game of the year, he
went with Elvis Grbac, who was returning from injury. Chiefs
veterans who recall how Grbac squandered away precious time in the
final two minutes of that game how their excellent season ended on
a desperation pass for Lake Dawson into double coverage still feel
Rich Gannon would have been the better choice.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Schottenheimer again chose Grbac over Gannon. No
matter who played, it might not have been enough to beat the
Patriots. But the majority of players realize the quarterback
position is different from any other. Most guys admire coaches who
stick to their rules, who remain consistent.
</P>
<P>
   They also know that when it comes to the hot quarterback, rules
are made to be broken.
</P>
<P>
   Hat trick
</P>
<P>
   The trio of former University of Georgia tailbacks starting in
the league _ Terrell Davis (Denver), Garrison Hearst (San
Francisco) and Robert Edwards (New England) _ all reached the end
zone. They combined for 383 rushing yards and two scores on 75
carries and added five catches for 98 yards and two touchdowns.
Davis has 865 rushing yards and is on pace for a 2,307-yard
performance. In Mark McGwire-type fashion, that would smash the
record of 2,105 yards established by Eric Dickerson in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina bluer
</P>
<P>
   Just when it seemed things couldn't get any worse for the
Panthers, starting tailback Fred Lane missed the Saturday charter
to Dallas and coach Dom Capers held him out of the loss to the
Cowboys. Although he should have known better, Lane was victimized
by an ambiguous itinerary handed out to players. Still, no one else
missed a flight that was moved up a few days earlier from 3 p.m. to
2:30 p.m. Lane arrived at the Charlotte airport at 2:25 and, with
teammates chanting ``Freddie! Freddie!'' chased the plane down the
tarmac. Capers instructed the pilot not to halt the takeoff
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tops
</P>
<P>
   Even when he was working against Pittsburgh cornerbacks like Rod
Woodson and Willie Williams, Cincinnati wide receiver Carl Pickens
annually tormented the Steelers secondary. So it shouldn't have
been a shock when he torched suspect cornerback DeWayne Washington
for 13 catches, 204 yards and the game-winning score. A bigger
shock was coordinator Jim Haslett and secondary coach Tim Lewis,
both highly regarded coaches, leaving Washington man-to-man with
Pickens on fourth-and-12 with a minute to play. The result was a
50-yard reception.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive best
</P>
<P>
   When Chris Doleman left Suwanee after the 1995 season, there
were a lot of people in Falcons management convinced he was
finished. But at age 36, the 14-year pro proved again Sunday that
sacking the quarterback is as much science as skill. Doleman netted
four sacks in the 49ers' shutout at New Orleans, three of them
coming against star tackle William Roaf, to move into fifth place
all-time. Since he left, Doleman has 30 1/2 sacks in 37 games. Over
the same period, Chuck Smith, the Falcons leader, has 21 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Truly special
</P>
<P>
   Oakland punter Leo Araguz, who earns $15,294.12 per game, should
get overtime pay for Sunday's effort. In one of the least aesthetic
games in recent history, Araguz punted a league-record 16 times
against San Diego. He and Chargers counterpart Darren Bennett
combined for 27 punts, 1,231 yards and seven kicks inside the
20-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing . . .
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati strong safety Sam Shade, a starter in '97 who is
splitting time this season with free agent acquisition Myron Bell,
relinquished the No. 1 job for Sunday's game but still came up big
against the Steelers. The former Alabama standout, who will attract
attention in the '99 free agent market if the Bengals can't sign
him to a contract extension, had three of his seven tackles in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Weekend worsts
</P>
<P>
   Almost as bad as Pittsburgh's gaffe was the collapse by the San
Diego secondary that allowed Oakland backup Wade Wilson to throw a
68-yard touchdown pass to James Jett in the Raiders' 7-6 victory. .
. . After rushing for 173 yards in his debut as a starter for
Baltimore, tailback Priest Holmes was held to 29 yards on 14
carries by Tennessee. . . . Ryan Leaf continues to struggle in San
Diego and likely will be replaced this week by Craig Whelihan.
</P>
<P>
   Stat stuff
</P>
<P>
   When he was dumped for a 5-yard loss by Seattle linebacker Chad
Brown late in the second quarter, John Elway became the first
quarterback to be sacked 500 times. Proving that mobility isn't
everything, however, Dan Marino had been sacked only 243 times in
16 seasons going into Monday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran Wilson likely gets the start this week in place of
Donald Hollas as Jeff George (groin) remains out of the Oakland
lineup. . . . Cardinals rookie defensive end Andre Wadsworth, who
had four sacks the previous two games, didn't even have a ``hurry''
against Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
