<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS MAKE CONCESSIONS AS NATO ALLIES APPROVE BOMBING CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: An expanded version is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET) 
(See also KOSOVO-RUSSIA) 
(mk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The United States and its allies early
Monday approved an order opening the way for NATO to begin a
bombing campaign in the Serbian province of Kosovo in four days
time. But with the threat looming, the Serbs on Monday made
important concessions and appeared close to an agreement that could
end the threat of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Senior American and NATO officials said Monday that America's
special envoy to the Balkans, Richard Holbrooke, had made
significant progress with Yugoslav president Slobodan Milosevic and
``has much of what we're looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Anxious to avoid a potentially devastating bombing campaign in
the Serbian heartland, the Yugoslav president has agreed to end all
police and military operations in Kosovo, withdraw forces in a
verifiable way, and make a unilateral statement pledging partial
autonomy to the province, American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO diplomats said the chief stumbling blocks to an agreement
were differences over what form of international mission should be
allowed into Kosovo to verify that any accord was respected, and
Milosevic's reluctance to promise cooperation with international
war-crimes investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The principal aim of the ``activation order,'' passed at a
meeting of NATO ambassadors, appeared to be to bring a maximum
amount of diplomatic pressure to bear on Milosevic rather than to
embark on military action.
</P>
<P>
   The order stipulated that 96 hours had to elapse before a first
phase of military action could begin. Earlier drafts had spoken of
48 hours, and Javier Solana, NATO's secretary-general, said the
extension reflected the fact that, ``After analysis of the progress
made, we wanted to give a longer chance to negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO decision was made after Holbrooke unexpectedly
interrupted his marathon negotiations with Milosevic to come to
Brussels and brief NATO officials. Diplomats said Holbrooke had
made substantial progress in his talks, but a few obstacles
remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed more clout behind the negotiating process, and this
NATO decision provides it,'' one NATO diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   After briefing NATO, Holbrooke returned immediately to Belgrade,
Yugoslavia, to continue his talks with Milosevic, whose crackdown
on ethnic-Albanian separatists in the province of Kosovo has driven
the Clinton administration to the conviction that only the credible
threat of force could end the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not NATO does use force, an important precedent
appears to have been set by Monday's decision. In effect, NATO
implied that, without an explicit U.N. Security Council resolution
authorizing force, it has the right, in certain circumstances, to
intervene in the internal affairs of a European state.
</P>
<P>
   Under the NATO order approved Monday, command of more than 400
aircraft and other materiel that might be used against Yugoslavia
was formally transferred from NATO member countries to the
alliance's commander in Europe, Gen. Wesley Clark. Technically,
NATO is now ready to begin a campaign.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
