<HEADLINE>
STOCKS RISE ON TOKYO BANKING NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices rose Monday after Japan's Parliament
approved legislation to revive its moribund banking system, setting
off rallies in Asian and European markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 101.95 points, or 1.29
percent, to 8,001.47. It was the first close above 8,000 for the
Dow since Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Volume in the United States was light, and the bond market was
closed for Columbus Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good rally and a continuation of what went on
Friday,'' said Bill Allyn, head of stock trading at Jefferies &AMP; Co.
``But because the bond market was closed and volume was down,
Tuesday's session might be more telling.''
</P>
<P>
   Broader indexes also registered sharp gains. The Nasdaq
composite index, which has been pounded recently, completed its
biggest two-day advance since October 1987. It climbed 53.59 points
Monday, or 3.59 percent, to 1,546.08, after gaining 73 points on
Friday. Still, the two gains have not completely reversed the
nearly 200-point decline recorded earlier in the week. And for the
year, the index is still down 1.55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 13.32 points, or 1.35
percent, to 997.71. The New York Stock Exchange composite index
increased 6.25, to 492.95. And the Russell 2,000 index of smaller
companies rose 7.22 points, to 325.62.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the Big Board was 691 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Optimism about a solution to Japan's financial and economic
problems had sent stocks in Tokyo up 5.24 percent. Revitalized
banks in Japan could lift the world's second-largest economy out of
recession, helping the rest of Asia in the process and easing the
world financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The news spurred Hong Kong's Hang Seng index higher by 5.68
percent. In London, stocks in the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100 index rose 4.4 percent. German stocks climbed 7.5 percent. And
equity prices on major exchanges in Latin America also registered
big gains.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some traders said they were not convinced about the
Japanese plan, adding that with companies reporting third-quarter
earnings, U.S. stock prices are vulnerable. ``I think the Japanese
plan is a Band-Aid,'' said one block trader who asked not to be
identified. ``What has happened over the last couple of days is
nice, but we are not out of the woods. If we get more bad news, we
will be back in the doldrums again.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts said recent developments had raised their hopes
about the future.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Canelo, a U.S. investment strategist at Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter &AMP; Co., said a global move toward lower interest rates
started by the Federal Reserve Board should help reliquefy the
international economy. Nearly as important, he added, has been the
recent decline in the value of the dollar, a drop that should help
emerging-market countries whose currencies are tied to the dollar.
The reforms in Japan should also help, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our feeling is that the Dow would have a tough time moving
above 8,400,'' he said. ``I am feeling a little bit better about
things than I was a week or so ago. But third-quarter earnings
numbers are going to be very, very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler Corp. helped to bolster optimism about third-quarter
earnings when it surprised industry analysts with a profits report
that exceeded expectations. Shares of the company, which is being
bought by Daimler-Benz AG of Germany, gained 2{, to 44\, after it
said it had earned $1.02 a share in the quarter, up sharply from 65
cents in the period a year earlier. The consensus estimate among
analysts polled by First Call Corp. was 87 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes that earnings at technology companies might have bottomed
out helped to fuel gains among a number of the industry's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp., which is expected to report third-quarter results
after the market closes on Tuesday, rose 1 5/8 Monday, to 85 7/16.
Microsoft gained 2 7/8, to 99}. And Dell Computer jumped 3\, to 56
1/16.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Worries about the stability of the financial system persist,
however.
</P>
<P>
   Prices of many bank and brokerage stocks rose again Monday, but
there were some notable exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, which is expected to release third-quarter
earnings on Tuesday, fell 1}, to 43 7/8. Citigroup lost {, to 34
15/16. And Bankers Trust Co. slumped 4 5/8, or nearly 8 percent, to
54\, after Fitch IBCA, the debt rating agency, lowered its rating
on the company, citing concerns about its earnings prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The financial sector was also the venue for the session's most
spectacular trade, a 2.5-million-share block of Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   The bank, which is completing its $30.7 billion merger with
Norwest Corp. and is expected to report third-quarter earnings next
week, saw its stock price plummet 16} Monday, to 319 15/16. The 2.5
million shares were sold when the stock was trading at 315 a share.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
