<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHANEL TO START CASUAL LINE
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ Karl Lagerfeld, who is not about to let Chanel become a
fashion relic _ a fate that has befallen many French houses _ will
introduce the Chanel Beige label collection for fall and winter
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Lagerfeld said he hopes to bring a fresh, casual spin to the
Chanel line. ``Today, you need sportswear-looking things,'' he
said. ``It's for another way of dressing. I wanted to do a sports
line because I want to use modern materials.''
</P>
<P>
   Chanel has stood alone among major labels without a lower-price
category; this move is sure to attract the attention of retailers
and customers.
</P>
<P>
   Talks with Daryl Kerrigan, who is based in New York, to
collaborate on the line, fell through, Lagerfeld said. But another
collaborator has been engaged, and Lagerfeld said he would announce
the name after the Chanel show scheduled here for Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction comes at a moment when several designer
collections are lowering prices to cope with the economic turmoil
in Asia. This line will help expand Chanel's price range, which is
typically well over $1,000 for an outfit.
</P>
<P>
   The name Beige grew out of the lore of Coco Chanel. ``It's Beige
label because Chanel in the 20's was called the queen of beige,''
Lagerfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it's second,'' he added. ``I hate everything
that's second _ second in line, second rate. It's a sport line.''
</P>
<P>
   MARCEL MARONGIU BOUTIQUE
</P>
<P>
   Up the street from the hip store Colette, and the hipper still
Hotel Costes, Marcel Marongiu has opened his first shop at 203 rue
St.Honore. Marongiu has been a reliably innovative designer on the
French fashion landscape for almost 10 years, even if his name has
not zoomed to its uppermost reaches.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, his clothes are carried in If boutique in
Manhattan. His new store, which opened Monday, gives Marongiu the
opportunity to present his whole vision, including ready-to-wear,
sleek architectural handbags, shoes and CD wallets.
</P>
<P>
   Marongiu's clothes fall within that hard-to-find middle ground
of urban edginess and utter wearability. Early on, he made stretch
sportswear one of his signatures, and the store features ink-black,
body-conscious sleeveless sweaters and asymmetrically cut
accordian-pleated skirts with diagonal zippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, a shop is really important for a designer line,''
Marongiu said. ``Everything becomes clearer to the customer.
Otherwise, you just have a few racks in the corner of a store
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW PHOTOGRAPHER AT KLEIN
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Klein has hired Mario Testino, the photographer best
known for his sexually charged work with the Gucci advertising
campaigns, to shoot the Calvin Klein spring 1999 campaign for his
top collection, as well as for CK and the jeans' line for men and
women.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time the designer, whose campaigns are often a
fashion and cultural bellwether, will work with Testino.
</P>
<P>
   Their new alliance ends, at least temporarily, a long-running
collaboration between Klein and the photographer Steven Meisel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be able to communicate the feeling of sensuality of
the woman in this campaign,'' Klein said. ``I felt this is a moment
when I can say what I want to say with Mario.''
</P>
<P>
   Klein said he has been deeply involved with the new ads,
speaking with Testino almost daily and flying to the set in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, he did not go on shoots with Meisel, who is well
known for making his sets off-limits to designers. ``I've always
found it best if I'm on the shoot,'' Klein said. ``I'm involved
with the photography, the styling. This is the way I worked with
Irving Penn and Dick Avedon.''
</P>
<P>
   Testino's star has been rising in fashion circles in the last
two years, shooting first Gucci and then several spreads for Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   The Calvin Klein campaign, which is being styled with Carine
Roitfeld, a frequent collaborator of Testino's, is something he was
eager to work on, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said to my brother, who is my agent, that I wanted
to work with Calvin because he likes modern, sexy girls,'' Testino
said. ``When I think of Calvin, I always think of Brooke Shields.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
