<HEADLINE>
THEY ARE WOMEN, HEAR THEM ROAR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   As  &UR; John Glenn &LR;  gets ready to be reshot into space, Jane
magazine recalls the early '60s, when a group of women who came to
be known as the Mercury 13 were applying to join the space program.
Testifying in Congress against them was Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The men go off and fight the wars and fly the airplanes,'' he
said at a hearing in 1962, ``and come back and help design and
build and test them. The fact that women are not in this field is a
fact of our social order.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Former FBI agent  &UR; Gary Aldrich &LR;  _ who wrote ``Unlimited
Access,'' a best-selling book about alleged improprieties in the
Clinton White House _ is heading up a nonprofit group attempting to
raise money for public relations help for  &UR; Linda Tripp &LR; , reports
the Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp herself has been hard at work on her image, spending an
hour on Saturday getting a public makeover at a Barbi Brown counter
in her local Nordstrom. Makeup artist  &UR; Sorilya McKinley &LR;  shared
with the Washington Post the secrets of the all-new Tripp: ``We did
white eye shadow with gray with brown liner, and I put her in a
clove lipstick with a chocolate liner and gloss.''
</P>
<P>
   (Unimpressed by the new gloss,  &UR; Anthony Cody &LR;  has created a new
word for the betrayal of a friend's confidence, so as to cause the
unwanted disclosure of sordid personal affairs: entrippment.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Good Housekeeping asked 10 celebrities in their 50s to share
their ``hard-won wisdom'' and whaddya know, they all said they had
found happiness and serenity.
</P>
<P>
   In the encouraging words of  &UR; Diane Keaton &LR; , ``As you get older,
physical deterioration is offset by a larger world view and a
deeper sense of gratitude.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Marta Sgubin &LR; , author of ``Cooking for Madam: Recipes and
Reminiscences From the Home of  &UR; Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis &LR; ''
(Scribner's; $30), says that Jackie O's favorite food was eggplant
fritters, coated in batter and deep fried.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Marie Claire,  &UR; Julie Dannenberg-Regal &LR; , a 38-year-old
magazine executive, describes her almost-daily morning routine:
</P>
<P>
   ``At 7:45, I kiss my husband and the baby goodbye and head to
 &UR; John Barrett &LR;  for my standing 8 a.m. appointment. It's depressing
to contemplate, but I've been getting salon treatments since I was
16. That's over 20 years of having my hair blow-dried three to four
times a week, having weekly manicures and biweekly pedicures and
waxing of various body parts. ... However, I practice great time
management: I get hair and nails done simultaneously. If I'm having
my toes polished, I wear thongs. And of course, it just takes two
seconds to get my eyebrows waxed. So I'm in and out of the salon in
45 minutes, hop into a cab and arrive at work by 9. There are
mornings when I cannot believe how much I have accomplished before
9 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   _ According to  &UR; Meg Ragas &LR;  and  &UR; Karen Kozlowski &LR; 's ``Read My
Lips: A Cultural History of Lipstick'' (Chronicle Books; $14.95),
24.4 percent of lipstick smudges on men are on the cheek; 9.8
percent on the lips; 3.3 percent on the nose; and 2.4 percent on
the forehead.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ed Solomon &LR; , co-writer of the forthcoming movie, &LR;  ``Charlie's
Angels,'' told Entertainment Weekly that it wouldn't be a jiggle
movie. ``Yes, they'll look great in evening gowns,'' he said, ``but
they'll also speak practically every language in the world, and
still know how to escape heavy artillery by scaling up the sides of
chateaus and skiing down luge runs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ At a conference on education in San Francisco on Friday night,
Nobel Prize-winning economist  &UR; Milton Friedman &LR;  got a pie in the
face from  &UR; Al Decker &LR;  of the Headwaters Forest-based Biotic Baking
Brigade.
</P>
<P>
   Decker, who was arrested for misdemeanor battery and released,
blamed Friedman's economic philosophy ``for the destruction of our
environment. ... When it comes to defending the earth from the
corporate criminals of the universe, the pie's the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sotheby's sends word that at a New York auction last week, a
signed print of  &UR; Dorothea Lange &LR; 's ``Migrant Mother'' (mentioned
herein as a stamp) sold for $244,500. Lange's handwritten caption
on the back said: ``This family had just sold the tent from over
their heads and the tires from their car to buy food. The mother is
32 years old. They were living in a open field, cold and rainy
weather, in the hope of getting some work to do picking peas, along
with hundreds of other families.''
</P>
