<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEATING-WYOMING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIM OF GAY BEATING DIES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LARAMIE, Wyo. _ Matthew Shepard died Monday, leaving a personal
legacy of peace and tolerance that his family, friends, and
President Clinton said should inspire others to fight the kind of
blind hatred that apparently incited his brutal murder.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard, 21, a student and gay activist at the University of
Wyoming, died in a Colorado hospital with his family by his side,
five days after he was savagely attacked in an apparent hate crime
that shocked much of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that in the grief of this moment for Matthew Shepard's
family and in the shared outrage across America, Americans will
once again search their hearts and do what they can to reduce their
own fear and anxiety and anger at people who are different,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our shock and grief, one thing must remain clear,'' Clinton
added. ``Hate and prejudice are not American values.''
</P>
<P>
   As the flags in Laramie flew at half-staff and many in this
cowboy college town donned yellow armbands in mourning for Shepard,
Clinton and lawmakers called on Congress to expand the federal
hate-crime law to cover attacks motivated by prejudice against a
victim's sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard's death also caused Wyoming Governor Jim Geringer to say
he will reconsider his lack of support for a state hate-crime law,
but he continued to express doubt about its necessity.
</P>
<P>
   The two suspects in Shepard's slaying _ Aaron J. McKinney, 22,
and Russell A. Henderson, 21 _ could face the death penalty if they
are convicted of first-degree murder. They also face charges of
kidnapping and aggravated robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``If capital punishment is the result, how do you enhance
that?'' Geringer said. ``You can only do it once.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for gay rights said the failure of the federal
government and five states, including Wyoming, to extend hate-crime
protections to homosexuals has provided cover for promoters of
anti-gay bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the two suspects, planning to rob Shepard,
lured him from a Laramie bar to their pickup truck last week by
telling him they were homosexuals. Kidnapping him, the suspects
allegedly pistol-whipped Shepard with a .357 Magnum as they drove
him to a remote bluff on the edge of town.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard, who was 5-foot-2 and weighed less than 110 pounds,
begged for his life, prosecutors said, as the suspects allegedly
lashed him to a wooden fence, continued to beat him, stripped off
his shoes, and then left him for dead in near-freezing
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 18 hours elapsed before a passerby discovered Shepard. He
was unconscious, hypothermic, and his brain was severely damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard never regained consciousness, and he died while he was
on ``full life-support measures'' at Poudre Valley Hospital in Fort
Collins, Colo., according to the hospital president, Rulon Stacey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family was grateful they did not have to make a decision
regarding whether or not to continue life support for their son,''
Stacey said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Shepard ``came into the world premature and left the
world premature.''
</P>
<P>
   Stacey also said Shepard's mother, Judy, asked him to convey a
message to the public: ``Go home, give your kids a hug, and don't
let a day go by without telling them you love them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sandstone buildings at the University of Wyoming, where
Shepard was a political science major, his friends grieved as they
organized an impromptu outdoor memorial service last night. Shepard
died as the school began ``gay awareness week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt came to Laramie because he thought he would be safe,''
said Erik Abbott, 25, a junior and a friend of Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott said bias against homosexuals is not uncommon in Wyoming.
``Why is it that the nice people are the ones who get killed?''
Abbott said. ``I hope his legacy will carry on and stop this kind
of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The school's president, Philip L. Dubois, said the flags on the
Laramie campus would remain at half-staff until Shepard's funeral,
which is sheduled for Friday at St. Mark's Episcopal Church in
Casper, where Shepard grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are heartsick to believe that anyone could have acted
against Matthew with such unimaginable violence, motivated by
irrational personal prejudice and hate,'' Dubois said. ``His
suffering is over. Ours, as a community, endures.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Shepard's parents, who last spoke to him from their
home in Saudi Arabia, where they work for an oil company, said they
would take comfort in his last words to them, according to Stacey.
He said Shepard told them: ``I love you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
