<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2762 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPENDING-CAMPAIGN-BOS     10-12 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPENDING-CAMPAIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW THE BUDGET PROCESS HAS BECOME THE CONGRESSIONAL CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During the almost two weeks that the federal
government has operated without a budget, Congress and President
Clinton have said they want to finish work on a spending plan for
the year and head out to campaign for the mid-term elections.
</P>
<P>
   But now, it has become clear that the election itself is keeping
the lawmakers in Washington. Amid the Monica Lewinsky affair and
the possible impeachment of President Clinton, voters are expected
to head to the polls next month in such low numbers that the budget
process has become an exercise for each party in motivating its
core supporters.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans, that means holding out for provisions on
abortion and contraceptives that conservative voters favor. For
Democrats, it means a last-minute campaign for new programs aimed
at rebuilding schools and hiring teachers. Democrats escalated
their education campaign on Friday, one day after the House voted
to proceed with the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   And for the nation, it means that federal officials have once
again allowed the fiscal year to begin without a formal spending
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate approved a bill Monday to keep &UR;  &LR; the
government running until midnight Wednesday while they finish work
on a budget for the full fiscal year, which began Oct. 1. A
previous extension funded government operations only through Monday
night. Clinton was expected to sign the extension last night.
</P>
<P>
   As budget talks continued Monday, progress was reported on
several fronts. Lawmakers and the White House were close to a deal
to send $18 billion to the International Monetary Fund, the agency
aiding nations hurt in the global economic crisis, in return for
White House promises to demand that the 182-nation IMF change the
way it operates.
</P>
<P>
   The House Monday night approved legislation to extend several
expiring tax credits, which would cost $9.2 billion over 10 years.
But the Senate had its own plan, and the White House complicated
matters with a last-minute tax proposal and a plan to spend $7.9
billion over 10 years on incentives for school construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last thing Congress will do before it adjourns,
and I don't think either the Democrats or Republicans want to give
the other party the last word,'' said Fred Yang, a Democratic
pollster with the firm Garin-Hart-Yang. ``This is going to be a
close election, and so the little things do matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Stakes are particularly high in the budget talks for Democrats,
who want a rallying cry to carry into a fall campaign dominated so
far by news of White House sex. ``Many Republicans have felt that
the Democrats are searching for a theme to unite around, and they
haven't found one,'' said Jeffrey Taylor, a lobbyist for the
Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, many Democratic lawmakers backed a sweeping
bill that aimed to raise tobacco taxes and reduce youth smoking,
but the Republican-led Congress killed the legislation. Democrats
also rallied behind a minimum wage hike and the ``Patient Bill of
Rights,'' which would have given patients new powers when seeking
treatment through health-maintenance organizations. But those
measures died, as well.
</P>
<P>
   A new prospect arose three weeks ago, when House Republicans
approved a five-year, $80 billion tax cut, funded by future budget
surpluses. Democrats have argued that all surpluses should be
reserved until a plan is found to shore up the finances of the
Social Security program, and they argued that the Republican tax
cut would harm the popular retirement program.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans soon killed the tax plan, depriving Democrats
of an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Democrats are trying to energize their base in the
election and find anything to change the subject away from the
impeachment issue,'' said Marty Dannenfelser of the Family Research
Council, a social-conservative group.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative groups, for their part, are pressuring Republicans
to fight during the budget talks for a House-backed provision that
would require many family planning clinics to notify parents when
minors seek abortions or contraceptives. They also want Republicans
to block a proposal that federal-employee health plans cover the
cost of contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   Some lobbyists said GOP lawmakers felt increased pressure to win
on these points because Republicans have walked away from one of
their top promises to conservative groups: a cut in the so-called
``marriage penalty.'' The penalty is a feature of the tax law that
requires many married couples to pay more in income taxes than they
would if they merely lived together as two single people. A measure
to reduce the marriage penalty was part of the House's now-dead $80
billion tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are hoping that they haven't disappointed
conservatives so much that they end up suppressing their vote,''
said Taylor of the Christian Coalition. ``There's no marriage
penalty relief whatsoever, and they made promises that they would
have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why budget talks have dragged on, Democratic pollster
Celinda Lake said: ``The Republicans have wanted to concentrate on
scandal ... because they thought if the election was about Bill
Clinton and morals, they were on winning issues.''
</P>
<P>
   With an eye on the Nov. 3 balloting, lawmakers also took budget
politics to the House floor Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said Republicans had led a ``do-nothing Congress''
that failed on its most basic task: approving a budget.
Representative Rosa DeLauro, Democrat of Connecticut, brought a
chart to the House saying the 105th Congress featured ``the least
number of work days in decades'' and ``the least number of bills
enacted in decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, meanwhile, complained that Clinton has been out
raising money and disengaged from the process. Representative Mark
Souder, Republican of Indiana, said the president's team has spent
its time ``drafting apology statements'' over the Lewinsky affair,
and he read aloud Clinton's schedule Monday for a New York
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-thirds of all days since the first of the year, he wasn't
at the White House,'' said Representative Bob Livingston, chairman
of the House Appropriations Committee. ``He was concentrating on
other things, and the legislative agenda was the furthest thing
from his mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
