u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NUHN-COLUMN-COX     10-12 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NUHN-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baseball's great paradox on brink of usual (dubious) greatness
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ No team has had the success of the Atlanta Braves in
the '90s, nor the failure.
</P>
<P>
   They are baseball's great paradox.
</P>
<P>
   And now they seem about to do it again: Regular-season success.
Post-season failure.
</P>
<P>
   They have won more games than any other team in the decade;
their 106 victories set a franchise record this year; yet they sit
on the edge of extinction again as this is written, down 3-1 to San
Diego in the National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   In a way _ not exactly, but in a way _ they're like the football
Buckeyes. Winningest team in the Big Ten in the '90s, but
Michigan's go-fer and just one Rose Bowl in the trophy case.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has made it to the post-season every year starting in
1991, has been in four World Series, but has won once _ 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The architect of all this, general manager John Schuerholz,
addressed the mixed blessings before Monday's Game 5 of the NLCS,
or the ``perceived lack of success,'' as he called it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain it,'' Schuerholz said. ``I don't know that
anyone can.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, he tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a short series,'' he said, ``sometimes the depth and
breadth of your club isn't shown. Sometimes teams outplay you in
short series. Sometimes you don't play at your very best.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you have Lonnie Smith running the bases.
</P>
<P>
   If Lonnie Smith knew fundamental baseball, Atlanta has two World
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Score tied 0-0, eighth inning, Game 7, '91 Series, Smith on
first, Terry Pendleton at the plate. Hit-and-run. Smith takes off
for second, head-down. Pendleton rips one off the fence in left
center. Smith should score easily. But he stops at second because
he isn't watching the ball and is scammed by Minnesota's middle
infielders, who are looking straight up and calling for it as if
it's a pop fly. Smith reaches third, but no farther.
</P>
<P>
   Still tied 0-0, the game goes to the 10th and the Twins win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball teams can sometimes be at their best for a short
period of time or extended period of time, 10 games, 15 games, then
all of a sudden hit a wall,'' Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   He was talking here about this post-season. The Braves won the
last seven games of the regular season, swept the Cubs in three _ a
10-game winning streak _ then scored three runs in losing the first
three games to the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've gotten to a point, and you haven't gotten over that
hump very often,'' a writer said. ``Do you feel you've done all you
can do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer to that is yes,'' Schuerholz said. ``The answer to
that is yes. The answer is yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, he thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud that we've put ourselves in that position each
year,'' he said, ``which is remarkable when you think about this
crazy economic system in which we work.''
</P>
<P>
   The system is crazy enough that the Braves have $122.5 million
committed to their Big Four starting pitchers through the year
2002.
</P>
<P>
   And they're counting on those four to escape their current
dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle already came through Sunday. If John Smoltz
survived Monday, Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux waited for Games 6
and, possibly 7, back in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   If not, the phrase ``Flop of the '90s'' will be written about
Atlanta as often as ``Team of the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz had a different way of putting it. If they don't
crawl out of this hole, he'd rather the Braves' annual October
plunge be called ``The Unfinished Symphony.''
</P>
<P>
   Subtitle: The $122.5 million sour note.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
