<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-ALTAVISTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alta Vista concentrates on searching vast Internet
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For now, Alta Vista is sticking with its roots
as a powerful Internet search engine.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp., which acquired Alta Vista when it bought
Digital Equipment Corp. in June, announces today new features
designed to make it easier for PC users to get around the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   One new feature, called ``Ask Alta Vista,'' allows users to
phrase simple questions, such as ``Who has the cheapest air fare to
Hawaii?''
</P>
<P>
   That question will return pages of travel agencies and ticket
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq said Alta Vista also recognizes common phrases or word
combinations such as ``New York,'' so searches don't return
possible cites for just one of the words.
</P>
<P>
   What Alta Vista won't be is a flashy World Wide Web portal like
Yahoo, Lycos and Excite, which have added games, stock updates and
chat to their sites.
</P>
<P>
   While searching for information and data is one of the main
reasons people go on the Internet, the growth of the medium to
include tens of millions of Web sites has made that more difficult,
Compaq senior vice president Rod Schrock said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only company still investing heavily in making
navigation more usable,'' Schrock said.
</P>
<P>
   Another addition is Alta Vista's Photo Finder's database of 10
million images, the largest available on the Web. For example, a
search Monday for ``Golden Gate Bridge'' offered more than 13,000
images, while ``Texas Capitol'' offered 4,900.
</P>
<P>
   Family Filter allows PC users to screen out objectionable
material.
</P>
<P>
   Schrock said Alta Vista averages about 12 million distinct users
a month, ranking it No. 10 among top World Wide Web sites. The goal
is to be in the top five within three years, but to reach that
level, Alta Vista will have to have broader appeal, such as news,
sports, entertainment, similar to Yahoo and other sites, Schrock
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alta Vista is at www.altavista.com.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
