<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2766 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UT-NOBEL-PRIZE-COX     10-12 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-NOBEL-PRIZE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    System scientist shares Nobel Prize
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Twenty-two years after his heretical discovery
that the common air pollutant nitric oxide is produced by almost
every cell in the body, Dr. Ferid Murad was awakened Monday at 4
a.m. at his home in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The caller was the secretary of the Karolinska Institute in
Stockholm, Sweden, who told Murad that the Nobel Prize committee
had just finished voting and had decided that Murad would share the
1998 Nobel Prize for physiology or medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a delightful surprise,'' said Murad, 62, the son of an
Albanian immigrant to the United States and a professor and
chairman of the Department of Integrative Biology, Pharmacology and
Physiology at the University of Texas Health Science Center at
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Murad will share the prize, to be presented Dec. 10 in
Stockholm, with Robert Furchgott, 82, a pharmacologist at the State
University of New York at Brooklyn, and Louis Ignarro, 57, a
pharmacologist at the University of California at Los Angeles. They
also will share $978,000.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the discovery, by Murad in 1976, and the other
scientists in 1979 and 1980, that colorless, odorless nitric oxide
is essential for the relaxation of muscles and blood vessels in the
body, was highly controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``People then viewed the gas only as a toxic substance,'' Murad
said. ``So the work was not well received.''
</P>
<P>
   In the intervening years, however, the discovery has stimulated
a wide range of drug investigations for new treatments for
disorders from heart disease to cancer. The gas also plays a key
role in the wildly popular anti-impotence drug Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Nitric oxide is not to be confused with nitrous oxide, or
laughing gas, a popular painkiller used by many dentists.
</P>
<P>
   If news of the award caught Murad in bed, it was a shocker at
the UT medical school, one of 6 health-related schools in the
15-school UT System and the home of Texas' only school of public
health. Murad's was the first Nobel Prize awarded to a tenured
faculty member in the Houston school's history.
</P>
<P>
   The school's public relations department quickly assembled an 11
a.m. news conference but, by mid-afternoon, was still laboring on
their first written news release of the day. They finally got it
out and sat Murad down for a series of telephone interviews with
out-of-town reporters about an hour before he was expected at a
faculty reception.
</P>
<P>
   The Webmaster at the school's graduate department of biomedical
sciences was quicker, getting a ``Congratulations Dr. Ferid Murad''
on the department's Internet home page well before noon.
</P>
<P>
   Murad became the eighth faculty member in the UT System to win a
Nobel Prize, since biologist H.J. Muller won the first one in 1946,
also for physiology or medicine, for work he did in the 1920s at
UT-Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are overjoyed on behalf of Dr. Murad,'' UT System
Chancellor William Cunningham said. ``He joins a distinguished
group of colleagues accross the UT System who have been similarly
recognized. (It) is a clear signal of the important stature
attained by the UT Health Science Center in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   But, although the UT System is expected to benefit in terms of
attracting new financing for research, there are limits to what it
can do. So there were no plans Monday to light the UT tower in
Austin, which is generally lit with orange lights when one of the
school's sports teams wins, said Peggy Kruger, associate director
for public affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Murad, whose parents owned a restaurant in Whiting, Ind., where
he grew up, came to UT Houston from Stanford University in 1997. He
made his discovery in 1976 while on the faculty of the University
of Virginia, but he still does research on the ways in which nitric
oxide is important to health.
</P>
<P>
   He said he originally was studying the muscles of the lungs,
rather than the blood vessels, when he found that the gas, which
was then known only as a byproduct of anything that was burned, was
involved in relaxing the muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked out the biochemical reactions,'' said Murad, ``and
we showed the gas's biological effects.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Furchgott and Ignarro have since then independently shown
that the gas, which is produced by most of the body's cells, acts
as a messenger carrying nerve signals that tell muscles to relax
and blood vessels to relax and widen, which lowers blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The blue, diamond-shaped Viagra pills, for instance, work by
boosting the gas's effects in the blood vessels of the penis,
triggering an erection. But the research also has permitted many
drug companies to develop common treatments for hypertension, heart
disease, shock and hardening of the arteries.
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies have shown that white blood cells also use the
gas to kill infectious invaders, raising hopes for new treatments
for cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The work even touches on the personal life of Alfred Nobel, the
Swedish inventor of dynamite who established the prizes in his
will. Nobel had heart trouble and his doctor prescribed
nitroglycerin, an ingredient of dynamite, as a treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, it would take 100 years until it was clarified that
nitroglycerin acts by releasing nitric oxide gas,'' the Nobel Prize
citation noted.
</P>
<P>
   On average, more than 10 years passes from prize-winning
research to the receipt of the prize. So Murad's, Furchgott's and
Ignarro's prize was not unusual in that sense.
</P>
<P>
   But it was in one way. Analysts have long argued whether the
Nobels awarded for science more often honor work with practical
results or work that makes for fundamental, but not immediately
practical, advances in a particular field.
</P>
<P>
   The nitric oxide findings were both practical and fundamental
and Murad, who has a medical doctor's degree and a doctorate in
pharmacology, has a foot in each area.
</P>
<P>
   Now all he has to do is adjust to his new fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly been an exciting day,'' Murad said.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Stanley writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
