<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HELPS RAISE FUNDS FOR NEW YORK DEMOCRATS
</HEADLINE>
 YORK-CLINTON-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton came to Manhattan again Monday
night, for his third visit in the past month, this time, to raise
money for Representative Charles Schumer, who is running a
dead-heat race for the US Senate against three-term Republican
incumbent, Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his troubles, Clinton is still a popular man in New
York. Polls show his job performance rating at 69 percent, up from
63 percent a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   At a $1,000-a-plate dinner at the New York Hilton, and earlier
at an event at a private residence, Clinton raised $1.1 million for
Schumer, which should help enormously in the three weeks left of
his media-heavy campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may have a special interest in this race, as suggested
by the fact that Hillary Rodham Clinton also came here last month
to speak at a Schumer luncheon, passionately denouncing D'Amato's
voting record on health, education and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, as chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, ran the
first congressional inquiry into the Whitewater scandal, though
dropped it after nothing turned up.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more pertinent, Schumer sits on the House Judiciary
Committee, which will take the first vote on Clinton's impeachment,
if things go that far.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as Labor Day, Schumer was still sitting on the fence
when it came to assessing Kenneth Starr's report, telling anyone
who asked that nobody should ``rush to judgment.'' Since then, he
has joined the vast majority of Democrats to take Clinton's side,
which, given public opinion here, may not be much of a risk.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer was absent from his own fund-raiser Monday night,
explaining via video hook-up that he had to remain in Washington to
vote on the budget and on other bills involving sexual predators
and giving tax incentives to businesses that hire welfare
recipients.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato has been running TV ads that attack Schumer for, as the
ads put it, missing more votes the past 12 months than D'Amato has
missed in the past 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has responded to the ads, saying he had to campaign in
the hard-fought Democratic primary, but adding that he has voted
over 90 percent of the time in his 18 years in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fact that Schumer would miss a chance to stand by the
president, while raking in more than $1 million in additional
campaign funds, suggests D'Amato has struck a sensitive chord.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke for 25 minutes before a crowd of 600 at the Hilton
dinner, defending Schumer's record, attacking the Republican
Congress, and urging Democrats to vote in what he called ``a
profoundly important election.''
</P>
<P>
   He made no mention of his personal troubles or the impeachment
probe, though there may have been an oblique reference when he
reported having told Elliot Spitzer, the Democratic candidate for
New York attorney general, that holding that post in Arkansas ``was
the best job I ever had. I never had to hire people, fire people,
appoint them or disappoint them.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinforcing his message that he was on the job, Clinton told the
crowd that he had talked earlier in the day with Richard Holbrooke,
his emissary to Bosnia, and to Israeli President Benjamin Netanyahu
and PLO chief Yasir Arafat about the peace promises in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee, however, derided this effort,
releasing a statement of sardonic congratulations to Clinton:
``Today you have hit a grand total of 100 fund-raisers for 1998. No
president in American history has spent so much time
fund-raising.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said, in
response, ``I'd suggest there are probably members of the
Republican leadership campaigning for Republican members of the
House Judiciary Committee.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
