<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Two Key Choices
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The Social Democratic Party's parliamentary leader,
Rudolf Scharping, is to be defense minister in the new government
and the party chairman, Oskar Lafontaine, is to be finance
minister, Chancellor-elect Gerhard Schroeder announced.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Accord on Tax Reform
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ The Social Democratic Party and the Green
Party, the new ruling coalition, agreed to push through a tax
reform plan after they take power at the end of October. The plan
would reduce the top tax rate from to 48.5 by the 2002, from 53
percent now, and reduce the overall tax burden for an average
family by about $1,800 a year.
</P>
<P>
   France: March for Better Schools
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ Thousands of high school students in France again took
to the streets in Paris, Bordeaux, Avignon, Saint Brieuc and Lille
to demand smaller classes, more teachers and better overall
learning conditions. Claude Allegre, the education minister,
promised such measures soon.
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Mail on the Move Again
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Three weeks after mail deliveries to most of the
country ground to a halt, the post office is once again moving mail
between cities. The post office agreed late last week to clear up
about $10 million in debts owed to the Railway Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Iran: Campaign Against Rushdie
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ Salman Rushdie's chances of returning to a more normal
life were dealt a blow when an Iranian religious foundation
increased the bounty on the British author. The group, the 15th of
Khordad Foundation, said it was adding $300,000 to the $2.5 million
bounty for anyone who carried out the religious decree to kill
Rushdie, who was accused of blasphemy in his book ``Satanic
Verses.'' Last month, Iran officially dropped the threat, prompting
the British government to say it would restore diplomatic
relations.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   Brazil: Apathy in Brazil
</P>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Final tallies from last week's
presidential election showed President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
winning 53 percent of valid votes cast while his leftist opponent,
Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva, took 31 percent. But the biggest winner
appeared to be apathy. Voting is obligatory, but 36 percent of the
106 million Brazilians eligible stayed home or cast blank or
invalid votes. Only 34 percent of the total voting population
re-elected Cardoso.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Anti-U.S. Protest
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Hundreds of Mexico City residents demonstrated in
front of the U.S. Embassy on Sunday against a proposed radioactive
waste dump in southwestern Texas, near the Mexican border. Burning
American flags, the protesters called the proposed dump, at Sierra
Blanca, Texas, an insult to Mexicans.
</P>
</TEXT>
