<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2787 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUCAS-SFCHRON &LR;      10-12 1513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCAS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Following Their Destiny: Lucas Proteges Leave Empire, Start
Own  Firms   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
A long time ago, a filmmaker named George Lucas made a movie called
``Star Wars.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Star Wars'' begat sequels, and toys and books. And the ``Star
Wars'' empire begat a corporate kingdom for Lucas, a constellation
of companies that he established in rural Marin County, far from
the Hollywood madness.
</P>
<P>
   And as Lucas hired people who shared his vision, his Lucasfilm
Ltd. begat corporate spin-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the spin-offs are the traditional sort _ business units
that split off to form new companies, such as Pixar, a division
that Lucas sold to Steve Jobs, which is now a publicly traded
animation studio. But most of the spin-offs are led by
entrepreneurs, hired and inspired by Lucas, who then go on to
establish their own companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``George and the company want to encourage people to find their
destiny,'' said Gordon Radley, president of Lucasfilm.
</P>
<P>
   Lucasfilm is the umbrella organization for Lucas' various
enterprises including Skywalker Sound, Industrial Light and Magic
(special effects), THX (theater sound systems), LucasArts
Entertainment (computer games) and Lucas Learning (educational
software).
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every division of Lucasfilm has spawned spin-offs.
</P>
<P>
   The people who once led DroidWorks, which has since evolved into
Lucas' post-production facility, Skywalker Sound, ultimately
started Sonic Solutions, a public company in Novato that makes the
technology to produce digital video discs _ an alternative to
videocassettes and CD-ROMs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucasfilm is a great seeding ground for people,'' said Bob
Doris, a co-founder and the chief executive of Sonic Solutions.
``Lucasfilm is primarily a film production company. If you're
interest is, as ours was, developing technology, developing tools,
it's better not to be a part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. Chairman and chief executive Bill Gates sparked
a similar phenomenon in the Seattle area, where many former
Microsoft employees have started companies known as ``Baby Bills.''
Lucas' progeny are strewn up and down the West Coast, but many make
their home in Marin and elsewhere around the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them are self-employed and tap into a network of fellow
Lucas alumni. Noah Falstein, one of the early employees at
Lucasfilm's games division, says his business, the Inspiracy,
sometimes hires other Lucas alumni and is sometimes hired by other
alums.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Gilbert, whom Falstein hired at the game division that
ultimately became LucasArts Entertainment Co., went on to found
Humongous Entertainment, a Seattle software company, with fellow
LucasArts alum Shelley Day.
</P>
<P>
   GT Interactive Software Corp. bought Seattle's Humongous in 1996
for $76 million, and Day and Gilbert still run it _ and have hired
Falstein on certain projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a typical science fiction nerd,'' said Falstein, 41,
whose home office in Greenbrae features posters from his Lucasfilm
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stood in line for six hours when `Return of the Jedi' opened
at one minute after midnight. The chance to work there was an
incredible dream, and really exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Addicted to Yoda
</P>
<P>
   For many star-struck ``Star Wars'' fans, the notion of leaving
Lucasfilm is unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Gresko, who left the LucasArts Entertainment Co. with some
colleagues to form Nihilistic, a Novato computer games company,
said there was a phrase for workers who were particularly rabid
devotees of Lucas. ``We'd say, `He's got his Yoda jammies,' ''
Gresko said.
</P>
<P>
   Working at Lucas companies does have its perks. Skywalker Ranch,
set amid the hills of western Marin, has four top-notch dining
halls for employees and visitors, a health club, jogging trails and
a trophy case stocked with stunning memorabilia, such as Indiana
Jones' famous bullwhip. Walk into Industrial Light and Magic's
central San Rafael offices, and the first thing you see is a
life-size ``Star Wars'' storm trooper standing sentry at the front
desk.
</P>
<P>
   Many star employees stay with Lucas for years, including
legendary effects wizard Dennis Muren and sound designer Ben Burtt,
who worked on the first ``Star Wars'' movie. ``In terms of major
production studios, Lucas probably has a much tighter, close-knit,
stay-with-the-family program than any other studio around,'' said
Michael Moon, who heads a research firm, Gistics, in Larkspur.
</P>
<P>
   New Worlds to Conquer
</P>
<P>
   Yet even Luke Skywalker struck out on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything you do at Lucasfilm is under the shadow of George
Lucas, and sometimes you have the desire to go off and do something
yourself,'' said Falstein, the game-maker.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Williams, who was one of ILM's star computer animators,
said he left when the films no longer seemed fresh and new.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to work on any more Muppet movies,'' Williams
said. ``I saw it deteriorating when it turned into a sequel
factory.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was known as a colorful character at ILM, with a bad
boy biker persona and a reputation for pushing the special effects
envelope on films like ``Terminator 2,'' ``Jurassic Park'' and
``The Mask.''
</P>
<P>
   He is one of the few who talk about ILM with any bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't room for rebels any more,'' Williams said of
ILM's evolution into a 1,000-person company. ``It'll take a rebel
movement to shake them out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Williams left with Clint Goldman and Mark Dippe, forming a
cheekily named production firm, Pull Down Your Pants Pictures, in
San Francisco. The trio collaborated on last year's hit ``Spawn,''
and between movies they work on commercials at Complete
Pandemonium, a San Francisco film and video production company.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Jim Morris, president of Lucas Digital, which includes ILM,
shrugged off Williams as one of many people who left to ``pursue
other stuff we don't really do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Lucas legend now in business for himself is Tomlinson
Holman, the man who led Lucas' theater sound company, THX. The Web
site for Holman's Southern California company, TMH Corp., maintains
that the initials THX stand for ``Tomlinson Holman's Experiment,''
although a THX spokeswoman says they refer to Lucas's first feature
film, the obscure ``THX 1138.''
</P>
<P>
   Other leaders in the effects industry who made their names at
ILM include Scott Ross, one of the co-founders of Digital Domain in
Southern California; Richard Edlund, whose Boss Film Studios went
belly up last year; and Phil Tippett, whose Berkeley company
Tippett Studios employs 125 people and continues to work with ILM
on select projects.
</P>
<P>
   For Tippett, working at ILM was a ``dream come true.'' In his
telling, ``a 35-year-old millionaire gave us carte blanche,'' and
the young wild-eyed effects whizzes created some of the most
popular movies in history.
</P>
<P>
   Another ILM spin-off was formed 10 years ago by Craig Barron,
Mike Pangrazio and Christine Demkowicz, who made matte paintings
that serve as backgrounds in films. Their 12-person company, Matte
World, is tucked in a Novato office park.
</P>
<P>
   Hatching New Firms
</P>
<P>
   Lucas likes to incubate companies, Radley said. Sometimes those
companies stay in the fold, like the Lucas Learning division that
formed last year and is now releasing its first educational
software products.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes those companies don't fit and spin off on their own.
Tom Kobayashi was the general manager of Skywalker Sound when he
hit on a new business idea, setting up fiber optic networks to send
high-quality video and audio great distances.
</P>
<P>
   The technology was used to record Frank Sinatra's ``Duets''
album, even though Sinatra wasn't in the same studio as most of his
musical partners.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas didn't want to be in that business, but he let Kobayashi
form his own company to exploit the technology while he was still
running Skywalker Sound.
</P>
<P>
   About nine months later, Kobayashi left Skywalker and took his
company, EDNet, to San Francisco. EDNet is traded on Nasdaq,
employs 25 people and had sales of $4 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling there was, you should move on,'' Kobayashi said.
``Lucasfilm will always be (Lucas') company. If you want to do it
on your own, that's encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   ILM has retained two of its brightest stars by letting them
follow their inner entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   John Knoll and Scott Squires are two of the three visual effects
supervisors working on ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace,'' Lucas' forthcoming prequel. They're also software
wizards.
</P>
<P>
   Knoll and his brother Thomas Knoll developed the best-selling
Photoshop imaging software, which they licensed to Adobe Systems.
They continue to create products under the Knoll Software label.
</P>
<P>
   Squires, 41, who developed a software called Commotion that
simplifies special effects work so it can be done on inexpensive
computers, started Puffin Designs, a 22-person company in
Sausalito.
</P>
<P>
   Squires offered the software to Lucasfilm, but it didn't really
fit with other company offerings, so _ with Lucas's blessing _ he
formed his own firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
