<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 10/12/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) FORT COLLINS, Colo. -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- WYO-GAY-BASHING,
10-12 -- Scott Collins, lower left, a friend of the gay student who
died Monday after an attack last week, is comforted during a
speak-out for National Coming Out Day at the University of Colorado
at Denver. From Denver to the University of Maryland, people turned
out to honor 21-year-old Matthew Shepard, a freshman at the
University of Wyoming, who was found dangling from the fence.
(Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- BBA-YANKS-INDIANS, 10-12 --
Paul O'Neill pitching batting practice for his sons Aaron, 5, and
Andrew, 9, after the Yankees' workout Monday in the Bronx. Pitching
coach Mel Stottlemyre plays the field. (Ozier Muhammad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- CLINTON-NY, 10-12 --
President Clinton speaking in New York on Monday night. Clinton
came here to raise $1 million for one of the most fiercely
contested Senate races in the nation - Charles Schumer's challenge
to Alfonse D'Amato - and to draw emotional sustenance from a place
where Clinton has been admired, even during his worst of times.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) MIAMI -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- MIAMI-CUBA-NOSTALGIA, 10-12 --
``People said it would not be possible, that Miami is unforgiving,
that Cubans here don't accept anyone who left after the 1960s,''
says Pepe Horta of his Cafe Nostalgia. ``But here I am.'' With
plans to open similar nightclubs in Miami Beach, Madrid and Paris,
Horta may be the first to market internationally nostalgia for a
certain lost moment in history. (Cindy Karp/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- CONGRESS-SPEND, 10-12 --
John Podesta, President Clinton's deputy chief of staff, at the
Speaker's offices Monday after an all-day round of talks to try to
resolve the budget crisis. The deadline on the talks has been
extended to midnight Wednesday. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- CHILDREN'S-AUTHOR-PROFILE,
10-12 -- Peter Sis, 49, says his latest and most personal
children's book, ``Tibet: Through the Red Box,'' uses a story his
father told him. ``It's for the child inside all of us, or
something like that,'' says Sis, who has the dark, soulful looks of
a European actor and the besotted nature of a father of young
children who finds magic in the new world. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) GREENWICH, Conn. -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- TENNECO-SHRINK,
10-12 -- Tenneco's chief, Dana Mead, who is overseeing the
conglomerate's split into two businesses, stands by a portrait of
Michael Walsh, whom he succeeded in 1994. ``I thought investors
would see a mini-conglomerate made up of two superb performers, and
think 2 plus 2 equals 5,'' says Dana Mead, Tenneco's chief
executive. ``They still think 2 plus 2 equals 3.'' (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- SUB-CONGRESS-HAMILTON,
10-12 -- Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., is retiring. The Almanac of
American Politics has called Hamilton one of the most respected
members of the House. The politically moderate son of a Methodist
minister from Evansville, Ind., he has been a major force on
foreign policy issues and led opposition to U.S. aid for the
anti-communist Nicaraguan contra guerrillas in the 1980s. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) ROME -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- YOUNG-PRIESTS, 10-12 -- Roman
Catholic seminary students at the Pontifical North American College
in Rome saying prayers before their lunch Monday. Young American
men entering the priesthood today are far more conservative and
tradition-bound than many of their elders and most American Roman
Catholics, according to bishops, priests and church surveys. (James
Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) PUL-I-CHARKI, Afghanistan -- Oct. 12, 1998 --
AFGHAN-BEARDS, 10-12 -- The Taliban, the ultra-strict Muslims who
govern Afghanistan, run this prison for men whose facial grooming
fails to meet their standards. The Taliban refused on religious
grounds to allow prisoners to be photographed. (Barry Bearak/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MILAN, Italy -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- MILAN-FASHION-2, 10-12
-- The sharp tailoring that Italy is known for is no longer the
prevailing style, but no one has yet come up with a definitive new
direction, although several have tried with varying degrees of
success. From left, layers of chiffon in gray and blue by Giorgio
Armani; a dress veiled in a layer of tulle, at Armani; Pink and
purple beaded top with skirt, by Donatella Versace. (Corina
Lecca/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MILAN, Italy -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- MILAN-FASHION-1, 10-12
-- Fashion, being a reflection of the times, is in its own state of
unease, searching for a new way of dressing post-minimalism. From
left, Gianfranco Ferre's white shirt with belt skirt; Fantasy in
Raffia and pink silk by Ferre; Donatella Versace's pink suit on a
pink-haired Kate Moss. (Corina Lecca/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- SHERYL-CROW, 10-12 -- ``I'm
staying home for the next two months,'' says Sheryl Crow, who is
taking a break from the road. ``I'm going to see how that feels.''
She has also switched from the West Coast to the East, leaving
behind the Los Angeles studio scene that had nurtured her career.
Her music is steeped in country-tinged California rock, from Bonnie
Raitt to Fleetwood Mac, with some Rolling Stones guitar licks for
ballast. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- SCI-HEALTH-KAVA, 10-12 --
Although Kava is emerging now in American stores as a natural
remedy for stress and anxiety, it is said to have been used for
thousands of years in the Pacific to help people relax and
socialize. Unlike alcohol, which can make people boisterous or
belligerent, kava users report that the herb calms them without
dulling the mind or causing hangovers. (Naum Kazhdan/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) HAWARD, Calif. -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- SCI-HEALTH-PAIN, 10-12
-- Beverly Bergman protested medical treatment she said left her
father, shown with her in an old family photograph, to die in pain.
With the help of the Compassion in Dying Federation, Ms. Bergman
filed a complaint, asking that her father's doctor be disciplined
for failing to prescribe narcotics. The effort was unsuccessful,
but the strategy represents a new tack in the long-running campaign
to improve care of the dying. (Darcy Padilla/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) OAKLAND, Calif. -- Oct. 12, 1998 -- SCI-AIDS-GETTY, 10-12
-- Jeff Getty, at home in Oakland, still supports cross-species
transplants even though his baboon bone marrow transplant failed.
``There's this unconscious sense that the procedure has created
something adulterated, a human-animal,'' he says. (Peter
DeSilva/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. -- Oct. 12, 1998 --
SCI-NASA-MEMORIES-3, 10-12 -- A monument to John Glenn's flight
stands near his launch pad at the Cape Canaveral Air Station. As
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration marks the 40th
anniversary of its founding on Oct. 1, 1958, some aspects of the
occasion are more archeological than astronautical. (Keith
Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. -- Oct. 12, 1998 --
SCI-NASA-MEMORIES-2, 10-12 -- Weeds line Pad 34, where three Apollo
1 astronauts were killed in a launch-pad fire in 1967. The ruins at
the Cape Canaveral Air Station evoke memories of all those rockets
in the early morning and the eerie twilight after the cheering
stopped. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. -- Oct. 12, 1998 --
SCI-NASA-MEMORIES-1, 10-12 -- Weeds are reclaiming much of the Cape
Canaveral Air Station, including Pad 14, where John Glenn was
launched into orbit in 1962. As monuments of inspired mobilization,
the ruins of Canaveral represent a progression of technological
steps leading to the Moon, the early artifacts abandoned like so
many stone tools made obsolete by bronze and iron. (Keith
Meyers/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
