<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTIMES-EXEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CHIEF FOR NEW YORK TIMES MAGAZINE GROUP
</HEADLINE>
   (ll) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leonard Forman has been named president and chief executive of
The New York Times Co.'s magazine group, the company announced on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly senior vice president for corporate development,
Forman, 53, succeeds James Fitzgerald, 59, who will serve in an
advisory role as chairman of the magazine group for one year.
Forman will be responsible for the magazine group's publications:
Golf Digest, Golf World and Golf Shop Operations. He will report to
Russell Lewis, president and chief executive of the Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Co. publishes The New York Times, The Boston Globe, 21
regional newspapers and three magazines. It also operates
television and radio stations as well as news, photo, graphic and
electronic publishing services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2813 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RATES-VALLEY-LADN     10-12 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RATES-VALLEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSING MARKET REMAINS HOT, BUT PERCENTAGE GAIN COOLS OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Coinciding with the arrival of autumn, the
steaming housing market in L.A.'s San Fernando Valley and
neighboring Santa Clarita Valley finally showed signs of seasonal
cooling during September, according to a report Monday from the
Southland Regional Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   In the bigger San Fernando Valley market, escrow closed on 1,096
single-family homes last month, an increase of a scant 1.1 percent
from September 1997. That's the smallest percentage gain in volume
since April 1997, when sales declined 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the total number of homes sold in September was
the highest for that month since 1989 and was the 17th consecutive
month of sales increases. The strong market reflects continued
consumer confidence in the economy and the lowest mortgage rates in
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the median price, the point at which half the homes
sold for more and half for less, was $189,900, a 12.4 percent
increase from September a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the Santa Clarita Valley, 264 homes closed escrow last month,
up 16.3percent from a year ago, the group said. The median price
was $210,000, up 5.6percent from September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``That matches the perception we've had that sales are going to
slow down, and the hectic pace of increases we've seen for the last
12 or 14 months clearly is not going to be sustainable,'' said Nima
Nattagh, an analyst at First American Real Estate Solutions, a
market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the rest of the year, sales should remain stable or
increase slightly on an annual basis, industry officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But 1998 will end up being a pretty good year, probably the
best year we've had in the 1990s,'' Nattagh said.
</P>
<P>
   It will certainly be the best year for sellers this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sellers, even those who were hurt during the recession,
realize that the market has turned in their favor,'' said Jim Link,
the association's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   But properties still have to be reasonably priced or they won't
sell, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The only drag on the market is the tight inventory, which did
increase slightly last month.
</P>
<P>
   The number of active listings at the end of September stood at
5,002 single-family homes, up 3.8percent on an annual basis. And
1,910 new listings came on the market last month, up 17.5percent
from September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It's a case of homeowners trying to take advantage of the
firming price trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``As resale prices rise, we're seeing a slight increase in the
number of properties listed for sale, but we're still in a low
inventory position,'' said Bud Mauro, the Realtors Association
president.
</P>
<P>
   But if prices keep climbing, it may induce homeowners to put
their properties on the market as long as they have an equity
position, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sold a lot of properties over the last couple of years,
and we used up a lot of the market of people who had a need to
sell,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   The low inventory is also affecting sales in the Santa Clarita
Valley, said Nancy Starczyk, president of that Realtors group.
</P>
<P>
   She recently took one client to 18 homes, and they were either
already in escrow or in poor condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inventory is so low that it's acting like a brake on sales,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sales fell in the Conejo Valley, but prices continued
to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Last month escrow closed on 288 single-family homes, down from
350 in September 1997, said Jim Keith, president of the Conejo
Valley Association of Realtors. The median price was $319,718, up
from $269,402 a year ago. Condominium sales totaled 123 last month,
up from 101 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Condominium sales were mixed in both the San Fernando and Santa
Clarita valleys last month.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Fernando Valley, 300 condominiums closed escrow last
month, a 2.7 percent increase from September 1997. The median price
was $118,000, a 24.2 percent jump from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred condominiums sold last month in the Santa Clarita
Valley, up 58.7 percent from a year ago. The median price was
$128,500, up 13.8 percent. &UR; ! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
