r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN     10-12 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOBODY WINS IN BERG STANDOFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER _ It is hard to see who benefited from the Kings and
21-year-old defenseman Aki Berg failing to reach contract terms.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is one clear beneficiary, TPS, the team Berg
will play for this year in his native Finland. So if there are any
TPS fans reading this, party down.
</P>
<P>
   Berg loses a year of North American development that would have
helped him if his goal is to play in the NHL; the Kings lose that
year of development, too; and it's hard to imagine Berg's NHL
bargaining power will be enhanced no matter how well he plays in
Finland.
</P>
<P>
   As for Berg's current value to the Kings, it's hard to say. On
the one hand, his skating ability in a 6-foot-3, 203-pound package
makes his potential vast. On the other, he has yet to produce
offensively in the NHL. He had only eight points last season.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, Berg has spent only a little more time on the
power play than Bill Clinton spends at Ken Starr's birthday bashes,
so how much of a chance has he really had to produce? It's clear a
fear of being typecast as a stay-at-home defenseman may have been
as much of a holdup in Berg's mind as the money the Kings were
offering.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see the outcome a year from now when
the Kings and Berg once again try to negotiate a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Another missing signature: The Vancouver Canucks were unable to
come to terms with 18-year-old defenseman Bryan Allen, despite
offering him a three-year deal at $975,000 a season, the highest
allowable salary under the collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The issue that killed the deal was performance bonuses. Some
teams have made it a practice to pay a player all his bonuses even
if he doesn't earn all of them. The Canucks refused to make such an
agreement for Allen. So Allen is headed back to junior hockey for a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Allen's agent is Larry Kelly, the same agent who
represents Berg and a number of other Kings, including Olli
Jokinen.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's crusade: Former NHL forward Sheldon Kennedy has
completed his inline skate across Canada. It was conducted to draw
awareness to childhood sexual abuse and to raise funds for a
facility in British Columbia that would serve as a retreat and
treatment center for abuse victims.
</P>
<P>
   It has been nearly two years since Kennedy, 29, came forward
with the story of the abuse he suffered as a teen at the hands of
his junior coach, Graham James, who is now serving time in a
Canadian prison.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's skate across Canada was not without its difficult
moments. In Edmonton, he admitted to drinking eight beers after
crashing a car, and marijuana was found in the vehicle, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life has been like a dance,'' Kennedy said during a visit
to Los Angeles last week. ``Before, I took two steps ahead and 20
back. Now, I take 15 forward and a couple back. My wife said, `I
don't expect Sheldon to be perfect. I expect him to be honest.'
That incident, I take full responsibility for.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who suffered a broken leg in another auto accident a
year ago, said he still hopes to resume his once-promising NHL
career.
</P>
<P>
   No yen for Japan: Ex-King Bernie Nicholls, now with San Jose,
was not exactly thrilled he and his teammates along with the
Calgary Flames had to travel to Tokyo to play their first two games
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ridiculous, absolutely bleeping ridiculous,'' Nicholls was
quoted as saying. ``A fast start is so important to having a good
year and we're traveling 10 to 11 hours flying across the world to
play two games in a city we'll never see again. You tell me this
makes any sense? Just another example of western teams getting
shafted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say that one day we'll see two New York teams going over
there to play. Yeah, sure. Not in my lifetime. Us and Calgary and
L.A. and Anaheim and Edmonton and Vancouver, we get the tough
travel all season and then they throw this at us on top of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Tokyo games, Sharks coach Darryl Sutter had this
suggestion: ``It wouldn't be a bad idea if we both went to Hawaii,
split the games and laid on the beach and told the league we went
to Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a better idea than Sutter realized. The Sharks went 0-1-1
against the Flames in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway blues: Entering play Monday night against St. Louis,
the New York Rangers were 0-2 and had been outscored 8-1. Among
their most disheartening statistics was only 40 of 126 faceoffs won
in the first two games, a 69.3-percent failure rate.
</P>
<P>
   Some Rangers already were grousing about others' work ethic, a
complaint echoed by coach John Muckler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give them some slack,'' Muckler said. ``I'll put them on
100-percent probation.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be a long year.
</P>
<P>
   Final word: There is so much sadness in this world that we turn
to sports seeking respite, if only for the two-plus hours it takes
to play or watch a silly game. Perhaps this is why it is so painful
and haunting when real life intrudes on the games we follow.
</P>
<P>
   Many fans of the Ice Dogs got to know Stephane Morin the person,
not just the player, during the nearly two full years he played in
Long Beach. Many members of the Kings knew him as well.
</P>
<P>
   He was a star at the IHL level, and much more importantly, he
was unfailingly polite and courteous off the ice, a true gentleman.
</P>
<P>
   For those who knew him, news of his sudden death last week at 29
during a game in Germany drained the excitement from the start of a
new season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLUE LINES &QL; 
Toothless wonders
</P>
<P>
   Given their (how do we say this nicely?) rustic home in
Nashville, Tenn., David Letterman predicted the Predators will be
the first team in the NHL where the players have more teeth than
the fans. &QL; 
Roster research &QL; 
Based on opening-night rosters:
</P>
<P>
   Oldest team: Stars (average player 29.2 years old)
</P>
<P>
   Youngest team: Canadiens (25.5)
</P>
<P>
   Tallest team: Kings, Flyers, Lightning (6-2)
</P>
<P>
   Shortest team: Five teams' average player is 6-0
</P>
<P>
   Heavyweights: Kings (208.6 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   Lightweights: Stars (194.2)
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Canada: The Sharks lead the NHL with 22 players from the
Northland
</P>
<P>
   Stars and Stripes: The Coyotes and Islanders lead with seven
Americans apiece
</P>
<P>
   Foreign accent: The Penguins and Senators lead with 11 Europeans
each
</P>
<P>
   Ugly Americans: The Blackhawks have just one European player &QL; 
Bottom five, from bad to worse (records through Sunday) &QL; 
1. Rangers (0-2): Announcers said they looked a bit tired Friday
night _ in the second period of their season opener.
</P>
<P>
   2. Islanders (0-1): Instead of worrying about their decrepit
arena, this sorry team's owners should worry about their decrepit
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   3. Lightning (0-1-1): Their new owner is a close friend of
televangelist Jerry Falwell, and this team is going to need some
divine intervention.
</P>
<P>
   4. Panthers (2-0): Undefeated, yes, with scintillating victories
against the Predators and Lightning. We'll wait and see. Their next
game is Friday against Dominik Hasek's Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   5. Predators (0-1): Who will score their first goal, sometime in
November? Will it be Tom Fitzgerald or Sergei Krivokrasov? The
drama is unbearable. &QL; 
Crunching the numbers &QL; 
4.82: The average number of goals in a game during the first three
days of the season, with new, offense-friendly rules in place. In
17 games, 16 teams scored two goals or less. Last year, teams
combined for 5.28 goals a game. In 1981-82, the year Wayne Gretzky
scored 92 goals, teams combined for eight goals a game.
</P>
<P>
   18-0: The first period shots-on-goal margin, in New Jersey's
favor, in the Devils' opener against Chicago. But it provided only
a 1-0 lead. The Blackhawks came back and won 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   $35 million: The amount of money the Canucks say they lost last
season. Things will be better this year: They don't have to pay the
$8 million salary of holdout star Pavel Bure.
</P>
<P>
   20: The number of NHL seasons played by Wayne Gretzky, Mark
Messier and Ray Bourque, who became the 24th through 26th players
to accomplish the feat. Will we see many more reach this mark?
``They don't have to play as long to make the same amount of money
I made in 20 years,'' said Kings coach Larry Robinson, a member of
the 20-year club. ``They can make it in one year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
