<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2836 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ALCS-HNS &LR;      10-12 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By JOSEPH DUARTE 
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ Silly as it might have sounded at one point this season,
if the Yankees were going to reach the World Series, the road led
straight through Cleveland.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of course, that was only by virtue of the Indians' now-hourly
rental of the title ``defending American League champions.''
</P>
<P>
   But reality has finally begun to soak in for the
underdog-from-the-start Indians. If they are to continue playing in
October, they'll have to go through New York.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive year, Cleveland finds itself in a
must-win situation after losing two of three games at home in the
playoffs. The Indians stand on the edge of elimination heading into
tonight's Game 6 of the AL Championship Series at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go in there with confidence. We're not hanging our
heads. We're not going to lay down and die,'' Cleveland first
baseman Jim Thome said. ``It's not going to be easy, but we've been
in situations like this before.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland has made a habit of pinning itself in a corner during
the postseason. A year ago, the Indians dropped two of three games
at home to the Florida Marlins during the World Series but came
within two outs of breaking a title drought of nearly a
half-century before losing Game 7 in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But following Sunday's 5-3 loss to the Yankees at Jacobs Field,
Thome shook his head when asked if this year's predicament was like
last year's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to New York,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there's no place like the House That Ruth Built. And
there may not be a team like the 1998 Yankees, whose 120 victories,
including the postseason, are the most ever by one team in a single
year.
</P>
<P>
   And as if they needed the odds stacked higher against them, the
Indians enter tonight's possible elimination matchup having to
hurdle Yankees 20-game winner David Cone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to win,'' said Cleveland outfielder Kenny Lofton.
``No other assessment has to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   After last year's near miss, the Indians have waited for another
chance at the World Series, which the franchise hasn't won in 50
years. The Yankees won their most recent title just two years ago
but nonetheless have longed for payback, since the Indians' 1997
playoff run started with a five-game victory over New York in the
Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   The road back to the ALCS has been filled with potholes for the
Indians. Cleveland sleepwalked to its fourth consecutive AL Central
championship with an uninspiring 89 victories and was 39-38 after
the All-Star break. But the Indians surprised the Boston Red Sox,
who had the AL's second-best record, in the Division Series and
took a 2-1 ALCS lead over the powerful Yankees before losing Games
4 and 5 this past weekend at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   Said Yankees owner George Steinbrenner: ``Now, we get 'em in our
home to beat the out of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The boisterous Boss has reason to be confident, considering his
team was 62-19 in the Bronx during the regular season. New York
lost two or more games in a row at Yankee Stadium only four times,
the last a season-high three-game home skid from Sept. 11-13
against the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   To prolong their season at least another day _ if necessary,
Game 7 would be Wednesday _ the Indians will hinge their hopes on
31-year-old righthander Charles Nagy, no stranger to playoff
pressure. Nagy has made 11 starts in the postseason and pitched 7
shutout innings against Baltimore in Game 6 of the ALCS last year
to send the Indians to the World Series. Nagy entered in relief
during Game 7 of the Series last year and wound up losing.
</P>
<P>
   Against New York this season, he has allowed one run in three of
his last four starts, including two appearances at Yankee Stadium.
He received a no-decision in Game 2 of the ALCS last week after
allowing one run in 6 innings. The Indians eventually won 4-1 in 12
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Having won one of two games at Yankee Stadium already in the
series, the Indians realize their task is not impossible. But in
the best baseball tradition, they're taking things one game at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't think about beating them twice,'' said reliever Paul
Shuey. ``We've got to think about beating them in the first inning
of Game 6. Then we think about beating them in the second inning,
because if we go there and try to beat them twice, it's probably
not going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
