<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 When to Get More RAM for Your PC   By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 Q:  My 166 MHz Pentium PC has 32 megabytes of RAM. With memory 
 prices falling so low, I'm considering doubling the amount to   64
megs. My question is, will that give me a noticeable boost   in
performance? And if I decide to upgrade, what kind of memory 
 should I get? 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; The benefit of increasing RAM depends on how you use your
computer. If you have a lot of complex programs open at the same
time, you should find they work faster. Also, the more memory you
have, the better your PC can handle multimedia graphics and
fast-paced games. If you just do word processing and browse the
Web, 32 megs is sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of memory you need depends on what kind of memory
modules your computer uses. Up until about a year ago, most
Pentium-class systems _ probably including yours _ came with DRAM
SIMMs, which are finger-length chips. Most of today's PCs use SDRAM
DIMMs, which are bigger and faster. If I explain what all the
acronyms mean, it'll take up the rest of the column. Just don't
confuse DIMM and SIMM with dim sum, which is Chinese food. Anyway,
check your computer manual or call the manufacturer to find out
what kind of modules you need. Also bear in mind that if you're
dealing with SIMMs, you may have to add them in pairs.
</P>
<P>
   The only other consideration is speed. Memory speed is
calculated in nanoseconds _ 60 ns, for example. Make sure that any
modules you add are at least as fast as the PC's existing memory.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; As an America Online member, I use the Favorites &LR;   &LR; feature
daily. I would love to be able to change the order of &LR;   &LR; some of my
entries. Is there any way to do this? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Sure. You can simply drag the entries into different
positions within a folder or from one folder to another. This works
for both AOL 3.0 and the new 4.0 version of the software. Also, you
can create new folders to further help organize your entries. In
version 3.0, do this by clicking the Add Folder button in the
Favorite Places window. In 4.0, click the New button and choose New
Folder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; Do fax modems require a separate phone number to send &LR;   &LR; and
receive faxes? I already have a dedicated line for my &LR;   &LR; computer. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; You can use the same line for phoning and faxing. The only
thing is, you won't be able to talk on the phone and use the fax
simultaneously. So if you're waiting for an important fax, you'll
have to stay off the phone _ and also off the Internet, if that's
your data line.
</P>
<P>
   Most fax-software programs let you set things up so that the
computer answers the phone and determines whether a call is an
incoming fax. Many new PCs also can be used as answering machines.
That way, you can leave the computer on all the time and let it
field your calls and incoming faxes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;   &UR; Q:  &LR; I would like to be able to listen to audio on the Web. &LR; 
 &LR; I've downloaded the RealPlayer from the RealNetworks Web site, &LR; 
 &LR; but after installing it, the sound comes out as rapid garbage. &LR; 
 &LR; Their suggestions for troubleshooting didn't help, and their &LR; 
 &LR; automated help is a waste of time. I'm not hooked on &LR;   &LR; RealPlayer.
I'll use anything that works. Can you point me to a &LR;   &LR; resource? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Sounds like rapid garbage, eh? Are you sure you're not
listening to the Beastie Boys? (Just kidding, guys.) Without
knowing more about your computer system, it's hard to tell where
the problem is. At the risk of sounding like a Microsoft salesman,
I'd suggest that you try installing Microsoft's Windows Media
Player. It's a competitive program to the RealPlayer and does all
the same things. Maybe it will be more compatible with your Windows
PC. You can find the Windows Media Player under Free Downloads at
 &LR; www.microsoft.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; A Better Idea: &LR;  Last week, I recommended removeable hard disks
as a way for a nonprofit organization to archive old photographs
and documents. A number of readers wrote in with a better
suggestion _ a CD-ROM recorder. CD-R, as it's called, lets you
store up to 660 megabytes of data on a blank compact disc. Because
it records optically, the stored information is safer than it would
be on a magnetic disk. And the data can be read by any PC with a
CD-ROM drive. CD recorders can be had for about $200.
</P>
<P>
   TIP OF THE WEEK &QC; 
If you often use Windows Explorer to manage your files and folders,
here's a quick way to open it: Right-click the Windows Start
button, and choose Explore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions to computers(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
