<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Huge Loss Expected For BofA   By Sam Zuckerman  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
When BankAmerica Corp. posts its third-quarter results tomorrow, it
will disclose a substantial loss, possibly $100 million or more,
from its stake in a Wall Street firm,people close to the bank said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The loss stems from the bank's interest in a stock-and-options
portfolio managed by D.E. Shaw &AMP; Co., a New York investment firm
that uses computer-driven mathematical formulas to profit on tiny
variations in securities prices.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's big loss, combined with red ink elsewhere in corporate
and investment banking operations, is embarrassing to executives of
the old BankAmerica, analysts noted.
</P>
<P>
   The new BankAmerica was created two weeks ago when NationsBank
Corp. of Charlotte, N.C., bought San Francisco's BankAmerica and
took its name.
</P>
<P>
   The loss could undermine former BankAmerica chief executive
David Coulter, who is president of the combined bank and has risk
management as one of his main responsibilities. Corporate banking
chief Michael Murray also is on the spot, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This clearly weakens their position in the new company,'' said
Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co. analyst Lawrence Cohn.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's investment techniques are similar to those that nearly
toppled the giant hedge fund Long-Term Capital Management last
month, but Shaw remains solvent because it didn't borrow as heavily
to fund its money-losing investments.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement last month, BankAmerica said it recorded a $12
million loss in interest income from its securities holdings during
July and August. Analysts said the result appeared to be triggered
by losses at Shaw, which offset gains elsewhere in BankAmerica's
securities holdings.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica's loss in its Shaw investment comes as global
financial turmoil takes a toll on the bank's trading, venture
capital and international lending businesses. Analysts expect the
bank to take a series of charges covering losses by the old
BankAmerica, sharply depressing profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to stuff all kinds of things'' into the
third-quarter earnings report, said Campbell Chaney, an analyst for
the brokerage firm Sandler O'Neill &AMP; Partners. ``They'll probably
make it a dump-truck quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica spokesman John Keane declined comment. Shaw
spokesman Nick Giankouros said the firm was ``not in any form of
financial distress.''
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank didn't have broad international operations and
didn't sink much money into exotic investment vehicles such as
Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw was founded 10 years ago by Columbia University computer
scientist David Shaw. It rapidly became one of the most highly
regarded quantitative investment houses on Wall Street, using
esoteric computer analysis to buy and sell stocks, convertible
bonds and stock options in global markets.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, BankAmerica entered into an alliance with Shaw
and agreed to fund an investment portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica's stake took the form of a loan of about $1 billion
to Shaw. In return, it collected a below-market interest rate but
garnered 50 percent of the profits or losses of the portfolio, said
people familiar with the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, Shaw manages a private hedge fund for BofA,'' Cohn
said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's portfolio, like that of Long-Term Capital, is designed to
make money whether securities prices go up or down. The system
broke down, however, when the recent extraordinary turbulence in
worldwide markets caused the value of Shaw's assets to plunge
faster than the firm could unload them.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica has several accounting options for its Shaw losses.
It could include the loss on its income statement, set aside a
special reserve or take a charge against capital, analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
