<SLUG> BC-PHONEADS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Startup Gives Callers Free Long-Distance for Listening to
Phone  Ads   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
At the intersection of consumers' distaste for advertising and
their zest for freebies stands BroadPoint Communications, a
Maryland startup that is offering free long-distance service to
people willing to listen to recorded ads.
<TEXT>
<P>
   BroadPoint's FreeWay service gives callers two free minutes of
domestic long-distance service for every 10- to 15-second ad they
listen to. The service should be available in the Bay Area starting
in January.
</P>
<P>
   To use the service, members first must fill out a questionnaire
at  &LR; www.broadpoint.com &LR; . The information they give, such as income,
ethnicity, education level and children's ages, is used to
determine which ads to play for the caller.
</P>
<P>
   To use FreeWay, members dial a toll-free line from any telephone
and then plug in an identification number and the phone number they
wish to reach. They may then listen to as many ads as they choose,
racking up two minutes of long-distance service per ad. They can
stop listening to ads at any time, and their call will be
connected. Most people listen to seven or eight ads.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``It's an interesting concept that we think will be very
successful,'' said Jim Pagano, executive vice president of the
Flower Club, a FreeWay advertiser. ``Free long-distance time is a
very powerful currency,'' similar to frequent-flier miles.
</P>
<P>
   Results for the advertisers appear to be quite mixed, however.
</P>
<P>
   A hefty 27 percent of FreeWay users who heard promotions for
Eagle Eye Sportswear called the company's 800 number after hearing
its ad, which promised a free turtleneck to respondents.
</P>
<P>
   But less than one-10th of 1 percent of those who listened to ads
for Vermont Teddy Bear's BearGram, a service in which people send
teddy bears instead of flowers for special occasions, called to
place an order.
</P>
<P>
   With other forms of direct marketing, such as mailers, a 2
percent response rate is considered successful. In four months,
FreeWay ads generated just six orders for Vermont Teddy Bear.
</P>
<P>
   But Irene Steiner, Vermont Teddy Bear's marketing manager, said
she expects orders to increase when BroadPoint begins using a new
technology that allows callers to ring directly to the advertiser
and then get linked back to their call.
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep saying that they're adding people (to the program),
so the response should go up,'' said Steiner. ``But we're also part
of a trial period and we're not paying for it, so to us it's all
bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   FreeWay started with an 800-person pilot project in April in
Pittsburgh. The test group has been expanded to 10,000, and
BroadPoint is planning a national rollout in a few months. The
company has several patents pending on its technology.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Neufeld, an advertising analyst with Jupiter
Communications, said there clearly is demand for a service like
FreeWay. But to generate enough advertiser revenue to pay for the
long-distance capacity that BroadPoint gives away, FreeWay probably
will need to attract between 500,000 and 1 million regular users,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   BroadPoint chief executive Perry Kamel, a former McKinsey
consultant and MCI executive, said the company's success in
attracting new members has exceeded his expectations. Because of
strong word-of-mouth advertising, the company spends only about $1
to acquire each new user, compared with between $50 and $150 spent
by long-distance companies to steal one customer from a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing out of people's mouths when they're making a
call with FreeWay is, `Hey guess what, I'm calling you for free,'
'' he said. ``We call it virus marketing _ it just spreads.''
</P>
<P>
   The voluntary nature of the service _ unlike radio or TV, people
aren't forced to listen to ads _ ``engenders a lot of good will and
creates a very responsive audience,'' Kamel said. As a result, only
about 5 percent of users drop out in the first month, compared with
about 20 percent for long-distance promotional programs offered by
conventional long-distance companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Household incomes of FreeWay users are relatively high,
averaging $60,000 per household, because better-off households tend
to make more calls, Kamel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
