<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Microsoft's New Business Suite Melds With Web   By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The next version of Microsoft's popular Office software suite will
offer a few interesting improvements for consumers. But it's what
it will do in the corporate setting that's truly amazing.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Due out in the first half of next year, Office 2000 will take
the big step of making HTML _ the format for creating pages on the
World Wide Web _ interchangeable with the file formats it uses for
its own programs.
</P>
<P>
   The move could have a profound impact on business computing
because Office controls more than 80 percent of its market _ nearly
as much as Windows itself. The suite includes the most popular word
processor (Word), spreadsheet (Excel), database (Access) and
presentation software (PowerPoint) in the world.
</P>
<P>
   With Office 2000, users will be able to save documents directly
onto a company intranet (an internal, Web-based network) as easily
as if they were storing them on a hard drive. And people with
access to the intranet will easily be able to edit the documents,
make corrections and add comments.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Microsoft says almost no type formatting will be lost
in the transition to and from HTML.
</P>
<P>
   ``To enable easy viewing and sharing of information, Office 2000
will elevate HTML to be a companion file format with the native
Office binary file formats,'' Microsoft said. ``This is a big
change for Microsoft, which has spent more than 10 years
fine-tuning and optimizing the native Office file formats.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that Microsoft is letting anyone _ even the
Internet _ loosen its grip on the corporate desktop. In fact, the
new Office 2000 could strengthen the software giant's monopoly by
making Microsoft products crucial to Web-based computing.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a company probably would need Microsoft's Web
server to get the full benefit of Office 2000's intranet
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The new suite also promises to increase market share for
Internet Explorer, Microsoft's Web browser. Office 2000 will
include a new version of the browser specially designed to display
documents that have been created in Office documents and saved in
HTML.
</P>
<P>
   HTML notwithstanding, Office 2000 offers some improvements that
should appeal to the average consumer or small-business owner. The
following new features are included in the first beta of the
software, which now is making the rounds of testers:
</P>
<P>
   _ Open and Save As commands launch a window with a bar along the
left side that gives you access to frequently used folders,
including My Documents, as well as to Web servers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The clipboard now can hold multiple items _ up to 12 _
including text and graphics. When you go to paste something into a
document, a small panel displays icons of all items on the
clipboard.
</P>
<P>
   _ The main drop-down menus (File, Edit, etc.) are short lists.
But if you open one and wait a couple of seconds, a longer list
appears. When you choose an option from a long menu list, it's
automatically added to the short list _ where it stays if you
continue to use it over time. If you don't, it's dropped from the
short list.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Help feature is easier to use. When you ask for help, your
document remains on the left side of the screen while the Help
feature appears to the right. Some help topics can be expanded into
Web-type pages with illustrations and links to subtopics.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Word, you can look up synonyms simply by selecting a word
and clicking the right mouse button.
</P>
<P>
   _ PowerPoint's default window has three panes that let you view
your presentation, outline and notes at the same time. And when you
add too much text to a slide, the font size automatically is
reduced to make it fit.
</P>
<P>
   As for shortcomings, the new version of Outlook is still too
complicated. Personal-information managers seem to be one of the
few things beyond Microsoft's grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Pricing for Office 2000 has not been set. The current version
goes for about $500, though people who already own it can upgrade
for about $300.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
