<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Diamond Multimedia Systems Is Caught in Legal Quagmire   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In the old days, the computer industry was wild and unregulated.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nowadays, tech territory is crisscrossed with legal barbed wire.
The mess facing Diamond Multimedia Systems is a case in point.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Diamond will ask a federal judge in Los Angeles for
permission to start selling a pager-size portable device that plays
music through headphones.
</P>
<P>
   Why, you might ask, would a federal judge care whether Diamond
wants to sell a $200 digital gizmo that is like a cheaper,
tape-based Walkman?
</P>
<P>
   The simple answer is that last week, the Recording Industry
Association of America, which represents major music publishers,
filed suit against Diamond. The association charged in the suit
that Diamond's device, called the Rio, would ``facilitate and
encourage'' music piracy by making it easy to download bootleg
music using MP3 technology.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote about MP3 last month. It lets people take music from a
CD, record or tape; compress the sound into a digital file; and
then ship the file over the Internet so others can download it,
uncompress it and listen to the music.
</P>
<P>
   Music pirates have used MP3 to put thousands of copyrighted
songs up on Web sites where people can download these bootleg
files. But so far, to hear bootleg MP3 files, you must hook
speakers up to a computer.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the Rio comes into play. Diamond created Rio to
make MP3 music portable by storing digital files on memory chips in
the device. The Rio can play an hour's worth of recorded music on
batteries that last half a day.
</P>
<P>
   In its lawsuit, the RIAA is trying to halt distribution of the
Rio _ before Diamond can create a market for its two-ounce playback
device &UR; . &LR;  There have been other MP3 portable devices. But they cost
more and did less than Rio, making the new device the first real
threat.
</P>
<P>
   The RIAA has charged Diamond with violating the Audio Home
Recording Act, which was passed in 1992 to discourage music piracy
on Digital Audio Tape. Among other things, the AHRA forced DAT tape
makers to pay a royalty on each tape they sold, to compensate music
publishers for the piracy that would take place on DAT.
</P>
<P>
   RIAA is trying to apply the logic to Diamond in the world of MP3
music stored on computer chips. It will ask the federal courts to
rule that the Rio device is covered under the same laws as DAT
tapes.
</P>
<P>
   That may be tough, says Bob Kohn, an expert on music law. Kohn
is hardly a neutral source. He is, after all, chairman of GoodNoise
Corp., a Palo Alto startup that sells music in the MP3 format.
</P>
<P>
   But he is also the author of a textbook on music copyrights and
has said the 1992 act on DAT tapes specifically exempts all
computer-based devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The RIAA lawsuit ought to be laughed out of court,'' Kohn
said.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Diamond will go into court Friday to argue that
there's plenty of legitimate music _ much of it from smaller or
lesser known bands _ available for sale in the MP3 format. It
argues that this is the legitimate market it is going after.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``The RIAA is really trying to limit access to
distribution,'' said Ken Wirt, Diamond's vice president of
marketing. ``If you're a little guy and you want to get your music
in a record store, you have to go through them. They don't like the
idea of music distribution over the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   RIAA attorneys did not return calls, but they'd see things
different. The 1992 act also required DAT tape makers to implement
a copy protection scheme to limit piracy. So far, piracy protection
isn't part of the MP3 technology, and this lawsuit seems like the
music industry's way of forcing the issue.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Polling experiment: &LR;  Today, most political polls are done on
the phone. But Harris Black Internation, the company that runs the
Harris Poll, will use the Internet this year to try to pick the
winners in 18 Senate and gubernatorial races _ including
California's _ on election day.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Black President David Clemm said his pollsters have spent
the last year assembling a database of 1 million Internet users who
represent the country's racial, economic, occupational and
geographic groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what they look like, we know what they think and we
know how they compare to the larger population,'' Clemm said.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, Harris Black has surveyed this Internet sample on
political matters like the Lewinsky scandal. They have compared
these Net results against surveys done by phone to make sure the
Net group wasn't different than the phone sample.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Clemm said he's confident the Net sample can call 36 races
in 18 states. ``The proof will be in the pudding,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   You can view the Harris Black poll results on Excite
 &LR; (www.excite.com) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
