<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 2 Rating Services For Web Merge   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The two leading Web audience ``ratings'' services, Media Metrix of
New York and Atlanta's Relevant Knowledge, announced their merger
yesterday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ratings services use computer software or hardware to track
the activity of Web visitors, producing data about computer usage
much as A.C. Nielsen does for television. Their clients include
advertisers, who use the data to decide which sites to buy ad space
on; and Web sites, which use it to get a better handle on who their
visitors are.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings service data are popping up more and more in the news as
well, as journalists used their numbers to gauge interest in
Internet sites and events such as the posting of the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   The merged company, which maintains the Media Metrix name, will
track Web-viewing habits of 40,000 consumers by adding Relevant
Knowledge's 10,000 panel members to Media Metrix's existing 30,000.
The all-stock deal leaves the next biggest service, NetRatings of
Milpitas, trailing a distant second with a panel size of 3,500.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, ``there are some months when (Media Metrix's report)
is ... off by a fairly large magnitude,'' said Peter Brine,
director of online marketing for Santa Monica's EToys, a Media
Metrix subscriber.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing the sample size by 10,000 will allow Media Metrix to
measure many smaller Web sites that can't currently be tracked in a
statistically significant fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix will ``jump, all of a sudden, to being able to
report on more than 15,000 sites,'' compared with Media Metrix's
previous 8,000 sites and Relevant Knowledge's 1,500 to 2,000, said
Jeff Levy, vice chairman of Media Metrix and the former chief
executive of Relevant Knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   NetRatings collects statistically significant data from about
450 sites, said Tim Meadows, vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The merger also will allow Media Metrix to adopt the best
technologies of its predecessor companies. For example, the new
Media Metrix will adopt Relevant Knowledge's Web-based tracking
technology, which delivers information instantly. Media Metrix's
system, in which panelists mailed in floppy disks that recorded
their computer usage once each month, will be discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Media Metrix will be able to expand its measurement of
advertising activity in other Internet-related services such as
e-mail, America Online and Pointcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both companies had significant strengths, and their plan is to
bring those strengths together so we would have a more encompassing
total measure of the competitive Web marketplace,'' said Andy
Fessel, director of the database and research group at Microsoft
IMG, the company's interactive media division.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Several Web executives said yesterday's deal relegates
NetRatings to niche status. But Fessel pointed out that the Web
ratings race is just beginning, and there is plenty of room for
innovation and change.
</P>
<P>
   Also, NetRatings has a head start in measuring the effectiveness
of specific banner ads, something Media Metrix has not started
doing, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Packo, president of Media Metrix, said it will take
about five months to completely integrate the two companies'
systems, although the basic monthly report, which tracks traffic on
the biggest Web sites, will include information from the combined
panel in December.
</P>
<P>
   Packo and Levy said they decided to join forces after sitting
together on a recent conference panel debating the merits of their
respective systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided we could do much more together than by devoting our
energies to creating competing products,'' said Levy.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month ago, the two companies' systems gurus decided
it would be possible to mesh their data sets, spurring serious
talks, Packo said.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix expects to be profitable next year and generate
revenue in the low eight-digits, the executives said.
</P>
</TEXT>
