<SLUG> BC-LUCASSIDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Oscar's Lure Draws High-Tech Workers to Lucas   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
How does a private company that can't offer stock options lure
high-tech employees?
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Lucas' film production empire dangles a golden statuette.
</P>
<P>
   Lucasfilm Ltd. employees ``have a tremendous upside which will
generate cash later on: getting an Oscar,'' said Michael Moon, who
runs Gistics, a high-tech research firm in Larkspur.
</P>
<P>
   Lucasfilm has won 17 Academy Awards, while its divisions
Industrial Light and Magic and Skywalker Sound have a combined 24
Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas employees are ``in that hallowed group of artists who can
reasonably expect to get an Oscar,'' Moon said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the cachet of putting Lucasfilm on a resume, Moon
said workers are lured by the workplace, with offices throughout
Marin County, away from the Hollywood rat race.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of the individual who most consistently pushes the
envelope in artistic and technological endeavors, George remains
paramount, peerless,'' Moon said.
</P>
<P>
   Upon taking the job, he said, people know they ``will learn more
about the craft hanging out here than anywhere else except maybe
Disney.'' But, he added, ``Disney's a pretty corporate environment,
a pretty harsh environment for creative people _ it's L.A., and
it's got a bunch of suits running around.''
</P>
<P>
   While some Lucas employees are well paid, the company has a
reputation of not paying top dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most people don't leave because they want to make money,''
said Gordon Radley, president of Lucasfilm. ``The work is the issue
... They want to be in charge of their own shop, work in their own
environment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
