<SLUG> BC-ASSOCIATION-AD-COLUMN-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: NATIONAL ADVERTISERS ARE UPBEAT ON THE ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Fla. _ A luxury hotel on the Gulf of Mexico has little
in common with a home on the range. But the 89th annual conference
of the Association of National Advertisers, held at the
Ritz-Carlton, shared with that little house on the prairie the
absence of discouraging words.
</P>
<P>
   The recent events that have rocked the world's financial
markets, which have newspapers publishing and newscasters uttering
phrases like ``unnerving panic,'' ``how low can it go?'' and
``rapid selling,'' were barely mentioned at the general sessions of
the conference, which ended on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, it was only in response to a question after an
upbeat speech that Robert A. Eckert, president and chief executive
of the Kraft Foods unit of Philip Morris Co., confirmed a report
this week in the trade publication Advertising Age that his company
had ``scaled back some brand advertising'' spending for the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And when the worldwide financial difficulties were discussed, as
in a speech by Harry S. Dent Jr., a financial consultant and
author, the outlook was uniformly rosy; Dent, for example, burbled
about the Dow Jones industrial average reaching 35,000 by 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with increasingly common forecasts of a slowdown in
economic growth, if not outright recession, the topic was on the
minds of attendees at the conference. In interviews, they described
themselves as cautiously optimistic that the damage would be
contained.
</P>
<P>
   Next year ``will be a softer year relative to other years,''
said Ave Butensky, president of the Television Bureau of
Advertising, ``with a very modest increase in ad rates of 2 to 3
percent for television stations. But we see a pretty good 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not supposed to advertise when business is coming in
over the transom,'' he added. ``You're supposed to advertise when
business is hard to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph W. Ostrow, president of Cabletelevision Advertising
Bureau, said that if a recession led to cutbacks in spending on
advertising, ``I could even argue the point that cable would get a
bigger share of a diminished tie'' because of the growth in cable
network ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The astute marketer looks at a recession as a time to build
share,'' he said, ``when the competition may be pulling in their
horns.''
</P>
<P>
   Marnie Delaney, senior vice president and director for
advertising and marketing communications at Bank of America, a unit
of BankAmerica Corp., agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone recognizes the value of brands these days,'' Ms.
Delaney said. ``I'm not sure we can afford not to invest in our
brand very aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   David G. Ropes, director for corporate advertising and
integrated marketing at Ford Motor Co., said the automaker
``remains committed to brand-building advertising regardless of the
economic climate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has become a strong believer in branding, so
there's absolutely no intention to cut spending,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several parts of the conference were devoted to interactive
advertising and marketing, which prompted this thought: If the
economy falls into recession, will spending on pitches on the
Internet be reduced, a variation on the last-hired, first-fired
school of recession employment attrition?
</P>
<P>
   ``Most new enterprises need to be protected,'' said John H.
Costello, the 1998-99 chairman of the Advertiser Association, who
is also senior executive vice president and general marketing
manager at Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I worry about,'' he added, ``is if we as an industry will
continue to experiment with and test (new media) when we have tough
times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're entering our Darwinian period in marketing, where
results will be king,'' Costello said. ``Boom times or recession,
those media that demonstrate return on investment will capture a
greater portion of marketing dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Denis F. Beausejour, vice president for advertising at Procter &AMP;
Gamble Co., is at the forefront of interactive marketing as the
catalyst for FAST Forward, an Internet industry coalition dedicated
to accelerating the development of digital advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say what will actually happen'' with the economy,
Beausejour said. ``I don't think any of us has a clear sense of
where bottom is.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``We normally don't cut experimentation and
research and development when times are tough. We're more likely in
times of trouble to look at extremely different ways to solve
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``if consumers cut discretionary spending,'' Beausejour
said, staying home rather than going out, ``I would bet time on
line might go up.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of the current economic problems, some
things never change. Among them are the annual election of officers
and bestowing of awards at advertising industry conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Costello, who had been the 1997-98 vice chairman of the
association, was elected chairman on Friday morning. He succeeded
James J. Garrity, senior vice president for advertising and brand
management at the First Union National Bank, a unit of First Union
Corp., who had been the 1997-98 chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph V. Tripodi, executive vice president for global marketing
at Mastercard International, was elected vice chairman for 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   On the awards front, Matthew J. Dee, advertising production
director at Wendy's International Inc., was presented the Robert V.
Goldstein Award for his work as volunteer campaign director for the
4-H public service ads from the Advertising Council. The award is
named for a former board member of the association and the council.
</P>
<P>
   The conference also featured the presentation of the third
annual Casie Awards for effective interactive advertising and
marketing. Casie is the Coalition for Advertising Supported
Information and Entertainment, founded by the Advertiser
Association and the American Association of Advertising Agencies.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G won for best interactive product ad for a campaign for Scope
mouthwash designed with Blue Marble ACG, a unit of MacManus Group,
which had a ``click rate'' among computer users of 30 percent. John
Hancock Variable Life Insurance Co., part of Hancock Mutual Life
Insurance, won for best interactive service ad for work produced by
the Modem Media.Poppe Tyson unit of True North Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The award for the best packaged goods Web site went to Avon
Products Inc. for a site developed by Think New Ideas, part of the
Communicade unit of Omnicom Group. And the award for the best
corporate Web site went to Dell Computer Corp. for a site by the
Grey Interactive unit of Grey Advertising, which now generates an
average of $6 million a day in computer sales.
</P>
<P>
   And the trade publication Brandweek presented its Marketer of
the Year Awards for 1998 at a dinner at the conference. The top
honor, Grand Marketer, chosen from among winners in 16 categories,
went to Steve Wilhite, senior marketing executive for the
Volkswagen of America unit of Volkswagen AG, for the introduction
of the new Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a farewell honor for Wilhite; Advertising
Age reported that he would be leaving Volkswagen after nine years,
effective on Jan. 1, and would move to his hometown of San Diego
from the Detroit area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
