<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: YANKEES KEEP ONE EYE ON PADRES AND BROWN
</HEADLINE>
   (ll) 
 By MURRAY CHASS  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday night's Game 5 of the National League Championship Series
was critical for three teams: the Atlanta Braves, the San Diego
Padres and the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who are confident they will win their American
League Championship Series against Cleveland, had a good reason for
caring about the outcome of Monday night's game. His name is Kevin
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   If the Braves won, Game 6 would be Wednesday in Atlanta and
Brown would pitch for the Padres. If the Padres won Game 5, the
series would be over and Brown could open the World Series at
Yankee Stadium on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Not only would he able to pitch the first game, but if the
Padres so chose, he could also start Games 4 and 7. That's why
Monday night's game was critical to the Yankees. Not that they will
talk about the World Series and their preferences before they wrap
up the league series, but the Yankees don't want to face the
prospect of seeing Brown in three games, let alone two.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do the Indians, for that matter. The Indians are included
here, as an afterthought perhaps, because they would be offended if
they thought they were being ignored, as though they had already
lost the series.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Indians could beat the Yankees on Tuesday night and
then Wednesday night; that's why they play the games instead of
rewarding pennants on the basis of what is supposed to happen. But
the Indians had their best chance when the series was in Cleveland
and squandered it.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the Yankees to contend with Brown, an 18-game winner
with a 2.38 earned run average who has been even more dominant in
the postseason. In three starts, he has defeated the Houston Astros
twice and the Braves once, allowing one run and eight hits in 23
2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're talking about a short series, Kevin Brown can make
a big difference,'' said Dave Dombrowski, general manager of the
Florida Marlins, for whom Brown pitched with mixed success in the
postseason last year.
</P>
<P>
   The intense right-hander allowed San Francisco one run in seven
innings, but was not the winning pitcher in a 2-1 victory that
sparked a sweep of the division series. Then he beat the Braves
twice in the league series, including Game 6, which sent the
Marlins to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, however, was not as overpowering in those two victories
as he was in his three-hit shutout of the Braves last Thursday. He
was not effective in the World Series, losing twice to the Indians,
who battered him for 10 runs in 11 innings.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Brown the Yankees would like to see if they meet in
the World Series, but he doesn't come with that kind of guarantee.
On the contrary, he is improving with age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brown really has stepped it up,'' said Doug Melvin, the Texas
general manager, who was joining the Rangers in 1994 as Brown was
leaving as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter, a teammate for two years in Florida, said Brown, 33,
has expanded his pitching repertory in recent seasons. From being a
sinker-slider pitcher, he has added a four-seam fastball that
``stays on the same plane and explodes up.'' This year, Leiter
said, Brown began throwing a split-fingered fastball at the urging
of Dave Stewart, the Padres' highly capable pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   This is what awaits the Yankees, or the Indians (wink, wink).
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bochy, the Padres' manager, hasn't addressed his plans for
Brown in the World Series. He figured the team should get there
first before he sets a pitching rotation. But there's no question
how much stronger the Padres would be with Brown starting Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a pitcher started Games 1, 4 and 7 was in 1991
when Jack Morris did it and won the first and seventh games for the
Minnesota Twins. The last pitcher to start Games 1, 4 and 7 and win
all three was not Mickey Lolich of Detroit in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Lolich is the name that comes to mind when the question is
raised. He started and won three times, all right, but he pitched
Games 2, 5 and 7, starting the seventh game with only two days'
rest. No, the last pitcher to work and win Games 1, 4 and 7 was Bob
Gibson for St. Louis in 1967. In almost single-handedly beating
Boston with three complete games, Gibson allowed only three runs
and 14 hits in 27 innings.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of pitching Brown has been doing this
postseason, and that's exactly what the Yankees (Indians) don't
want to see, whether he pitches two games or three.
</P>
<P>
   In the division series against the Astros, Bochy started Brown
with three days' rest but had him scheduled for five days' rest for
his second start in the League Championship Series against the
Braves. The Yankees wouldn't mind if Bochy told him to take off the
rest of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
