</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-KNOBLAUCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOBLAUCH'S MISCUE: FORGOTTEN, NOT GONE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last time Chuck Knoblauch was on the field at
Yankee Stadium, he made an awful mistake. He forgot to chase after
a loose ball. It was the sort of reaction that could get a
10-year-old second baseman benched, even if his father was the
coach. It is the sort of lapse that should never happen in a
major-league game, but it did.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch knows that now. After initially being defensive about
a terrible choice that enabled the go-ahead run to score and helped
vault the Cleveland Indians to a 4-1 victory in 12 innings over the
Yankees in Game 2 of the American League Championship Series,
Knoblauch relented and blamed himself the next day. And the day
after and the day after that.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch has apologized for bickering with an umpire during a
sequence that was fraught with team mistakes and has admitted that
he ``screwed up.'' Is that enough for the Yankee fans who berated
Knoblauch when he batted after the bogus play last Wednesday? Is
Knoblauch safe from more taunting? Or will Tuesday night's
reactions in Game 6 be positive for 24 adored Yankees and negative
for the player who was dubbed ``Blauch Head'' by headline writers?
</P>
<P>
   That scenario should not materialize. The Yankees lead the
series, 3-2, and need to play nine sound innings to advance to the
World Series. That has been their goal since February and that is
what should matter to their fans Tuesday night. Not criticizing
Knoblauch. He doesn't deserve a standing ovation or any kind of
ovation, but Knoblauch should not be booed for a regrettable play
that has caused him to stop watching television and to seek advice
from Fran Pirozzolo, a team counselor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really doesn't matter,'' Knoblauch said when asked about
the possibility of being bathed in boos. ``They pay their money,
they can do whatever they want. Like I said, I'm concentrating on
the game only and not anything that takes place outside of the
lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some fans might argue that spending $60 allows them
to use their vocal cords any way they choose. Even Knoblauch
mentioned that that is their prerogative. But New York fans are
constantly lauded for being so savvy. They stand and clap
rhythmically with two strikes on opposing hitters. They devise
creative K corners to count the strikeouts for pitchers. Jack
Russell terriers for David Cone, after he was bitten on the hand by
his mother's dog. Beer mugs for David Wells, no explanation
necessary. The fans in the bleachers even chant each starter's name
to elicit waves during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no better place for a big game than Yankee Stadium,''
Cone said. ``It is center stage. There's no place like it in all of
sports. You feed off the crowd here.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely. So how would it look if these shrewd fans booed the
first Yankee to bat Tuesday night? How would it look if a team that
has 120 victories hears boos for the player who scored two
important runs and started a crucial double play in Game 5? It
would look and sound silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to boo him, then they might as well boo every
one of us because we're all a team,'' Wells said. ``We're all in
this together. So we win together and we lose together.''
</P>
<P>
   After Knoblauch's brain cramp, he was rightfully compared to
Bill Buckner, and there was a theory that this unforgettable play
would plague him for the rest of his career if the Yankees lost the
series to the Indians. But even that notion seems stale. Knoblauch
has played well in the three games since his mistake. If the Yanks
drop the next two, is it suddenly Knoblauch's fault because of
something that happened last week? That is foolish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they focus on us being up, 3-2,'' Joe Girardi said.
``Chuck is not the reason we lost that game anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wells does not think Knoblauch has been rescued yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this doesn't work out, he's going to be criticized about
that for the rest of his Yankee career,'' Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch was terse about the play and about fans Monday. It has
been a topsy-turvy season and he has numerous reasons for hoping
the Yankees march into the World Series. If Knoblauch's miscue has
not been forgiven by Tuesday night, it should be if the Yankees win
the series. Actually, only the fans can make that happen by letting
go. Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to play the game,'' Knoblauch said. ``I'm not
worried about how any fans react. I'm worried about winning the
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
