<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-ISLES-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      10-12 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE TURNS ABSURD FOR THE NEW YORK ISLANDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Islanders, a proud team that won the Stanley Cup
four times from 1980 to 1983, find themselves in a sports opera
bouffe, a landlord-tenant dispute gone wacky.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the team abandoned Nassau Coliseum in Uniondale,
N.Y., declaring it unsafe for fans, beer men or goalies, but
returned by court order after National Hockey League inspectors had
declared that conditions at the arena posed no danger.
</P>
<P>
   Life has turned absurd at the Uniondale arena, where 24 banners
representing long-ago glories hang from exposed rafters. The team
is fighting legal issues with Nassau County and SMG, its landlord,
a credibility gap with fans who say the safety argument is a ploy
for a new arena and dubious news media coverage.
</P>
<P>
   While 15 arenas have opened in the NHL since 1993, the
26-year-old Coliseum remains a shabby presence on Hempstead
Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make sure this franchise can be healthy for the
long term,'' Gary Bettman, the NHL commissioner, said Monday. He
stepped into talks with the county on financing a new arena when
the team's owners withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult for a team to be stable in an antiquated
building with a difficult lease,'' he added. ``We can't guarantee
success, but we guarantee we'll work at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Few franchises in major sports long for stability more the
Islanders. In late 1996, John Spano appeared from Dallas, promising
$165 million and a free-spending, hands-on style. But he never had
the money and pleaded guilty to federal bank and wire fraud
charges, and handed the franchise back to John Pickett.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners _ Howard Milstein, a billionaire real-estate
magnate, and Steven Gluckstern, an insurance executive _ are angry
but resolute, believing they were stonewalled on safety by SMG,
certain that the Coliseum was unsafe when lawyers advised the team
to leave, and positive the building attained habitability only
after they filed the federal lawsuit against SMG.
</P>
<P>
   And is it safe now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know,'' said David Seldin, president of New
York Sports Ventures, which owns the team. ``Our owners are not
willing to make short-term decisions to be popular when an
unpopular decision may be better for the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, on Saturday night, during the season opener against the
Pittsburgh Penguins, fans were not too willing to believe the
owners. They wanted the team to sign Ziggy Palffy, its star player,
and stifle its rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   When Pittsburgh jumped in front by 4-0 in the first period, Bill
Cox and his buddies in Section 311 began a derisive chant, ``We
want Spano!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck,'' said his friend Tim Brown, ``we want Roy Boe!''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the strangeness of life in Uniondale, where fans chant
the name of a disgraced owner, and the founding owner, who sold the
team to Pickett, whom fans disliked for his parsimony, who sold it
to Spano. ``Welcome to the twilight zone,'' said Cox, who lives in
Valley Stream.
</P>
<P>
   Said Matt Pilla, of Ozone Park: ``There's nothing wrong with the
arena. It's the lease.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's mandate to play in the Coliseum forestalled the
Islanders' playing home games at Madison Square Garden or
Continental Arena in East Rutherford, N.J.; at arenas in Hartford,
New Haven or Philadelphia, or at an ice rink near you.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the court order, Gluckstern and Milstein withdrew from
talks about building an arena after Thomas Gulotta, the Nassau
county executive, called the team a ``pig at the trough'' and left
Bettman to negotiate the team's future.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Torrey can hardly fathom his former team's predicament. ``I
spent 20 years there when it was as good as it could get,'' said
Torrey, the general manager from the team's inception through 1993,
when he moved to the Florida Panthers. ``I hate to see this
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Westfall, an original Islander, shook his head dolefully.
``What's important is to get a competitive team, have the building
bulge and fall apart from the noise, then ask for a new arena,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   New woes arose Saturday night, when Fox Sports New York refused
to televise the opener for lack of advertising. During the game,
Seldin complained that the scoreboard had no video replays but
sprouted a steady drip of water and that the ticket windows were so
understaffed, some fans missed the game's first half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   The team's lawsuit against SMG alleges that the landlord
breached the lease by ignoring safety hazards. If the team wins, it
could forge a new lease with the county, or move within the region,
to Suffolk County, or to Queens, where the team would like to
relocate to the retractable-dome stadium being planned by the Mets
beside Shea Stadium. An executive involved in the discussions said
the Islanders approached the Mets about moving to the new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they set themselves on fire,'' said Wes Westley, the
SMG president. ``I've never seen anything like this in sports where
right before the season starts, a team evicts itself.'' Westley
denied the team's core allegation: that the hoists supporting the
scoreboard and sound system were unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, SMG has replaced the hoists and removed the sound
system; the team said that would not have happened without the
lawsuit and stunning move from the arena.
</P>
<P>
   If the team loses the case, bankruptcy or relocation could loom,
but leaving the market would mean losing $13 million a year from
Fox Sports New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best solution is a new arena,'' Seldin said. ``If we win,
the objective is to have the team on Long Island, but Long Island
is bigger than one town.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettman and the county are discussing the framework for
financing a new arena in Uniondale, adjacent to the Coliseum, and
are not discussing any other site, or commercial development on the
70-acre location.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the owners will participate on the terms we
negotiate,'' said Bill Daly, the NHL's senior vice president for
legal affairs. ``That'll be their decision. It could be that a deal
we negotiate may be good for another owner.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Westley said he had not considered whether SMG would buy the
team to protect its investment under the lease, in which it shares
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   League and county officials are to meet for a second time on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to work from the owners' and the county's standpoint,
or it won't get built,'' Bettman said. ``That's a situation I don't
want to contemplate.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams, landlords and municipalities often clash, especially in
an era when franchises threaten to skip to cities that promise
arenas or stadiums with increased revenues. But although the
Islanders have one of the NHL's worst leases _ they get no money
from parking and concessions _ they did not have the leverage of
another city in the wings.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Devils alleged that the New Jersey Sports
and Exposition Authority had breached its Continental Arena lease,
but they had a sweetheart deal _ a new Nashville arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say you're terminating your lease days before the season
with nowhere else to play is as strange as it gets,'' said Marc
Ganis, president of Sportscorp Ltd., a consulting firm. ``Safety
seemed to be the hook to get out of their lease.''
</P>
<P>
   The clash of egos and issues pitting the Islanders against the
county and SMG has been gaudy. At different times, Gulotta has
accused SMG and the Islanders of holding a gun to the county's
head. ``I was not overly pleased with the way SMG functioned in the
past,'' Gulotta said, ``but their level of performance did not
justify the Islanders' action.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hardball negotiating,'' said Gulotta, who is happy to
negotiate with Bettman rather than the owners he mistrusts. ``Team
owners will come and go, but the league will remain in place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders threw off their gloves by creating a Web site
_``www.coliseum-coverup.com'' _ to explain the alleged breaches and
the reasons that ``constructive eviction'' occurred at the arena.
Visitors to the Web site can access letters, reports and the
federal lawsuit, under headings like ``Political Smoke and Coliseum
Mirrors.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Seldin: ``There's been a lot of skepticism. It's an
accurate description of what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettman described it as ``an intriguing function of the new
media.''
</P>
<P>
   The team and SMG also dueled in competing full-page
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Real Idea Is Not to Hurt the One You Love,'' was the
headline on an Oct. 2 Islanders' advertisement in Newsday. A few
pages away was an ad from SMG, vowing that the arena ``remains the
safe, secure place that holds many great memories for us all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders' situation is an odd wrinkle in the league's
portfolio of franchise problems. ``From early on, the sense was
clear that the building situation on Long Island was going to be an
issue,'' Bettman said.
</P>
<P>
   Gluckstern and Milstein had two major advantages: they were rich
_ their wealth was well known _ and neither was John Spano. ``We
thought they were white knights,'' said Steve Ellers, head of the
Save the Islanders Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The owners are not only the richest in Islanders history, but
also the most aggressive. ``It's probably a shock to SMG and the
county to be up against such tough businessmen,'' said Pickett,
adding that he never asked to renegotiate his lease and paid $15
million to improve the Coliseum. ``Maybe I shouldn't have been so
passive and butted heads.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start of the relationship between the Islanders' new
owners and SMG, there was strife. Before they completed the deal
with Pickett in February, SMG demanded a document requiring them to
declare what they felt was wrong with the arena. The owners
refused, Bettman intervened and the demand was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   SMG's demand surprised the owners, but Seldin said: ``We didn't
think there were safety issues. There were 12,000 seats in
disarray. But was it a moment of `uh-oh'? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't trying to absolve ourselves of responsibility,''
said Westley said. ``We said, `If there's something wrong, tell us
now and flush it out.'''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship deteriorated from there, culminating with the
team leaving the arena. What now? The team lost by 3-0 to Boston
Monday, and travels to Tampa Bay and St. Louis before returning to
its beleaguered home next Wednesday. But hockey seems like the
least important activity at the coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   A sign at the arena Saturday night _ ``Wrestling Monday''_
heralded what may continue to be the most riveting sport in Nassau
County.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
