<HEADER>
A3003 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CHARITYGAME-HNS &LR;      10-12 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CHARITYGAME-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA may be involved in a lockout, but Houston-area fans can
still see some of the game's biggest stars playing a little
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Jim and Linda McIngvale, owners of Westside Tennis Club, site of
the Rockets' practice facility, announced Monday they will sponsor
the Gallery Furniture Charity Basketball Game, to be held at 7:30
p.m. Oct. 23 at Hofheinz Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   The game, which will benefit the M.D. Anderson Cancer Center,
came about through the efforts of the McIngvales and former Rockets
guard Kenny Smith, who wanted to put on a showcase for NBA players
who have been locked out of training camps and have been working
out locally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows that we have a lot of professional basketball
players playing here at Westside through the week,'' Jim McIngvale
said. ``They were looking to play some real games, so my wife,
Linda, myself, Kenny Smith and (San Antonio's) Avery Johnson and
some of the other players came up with the idea for a charity
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Committing to play in the game are San Antonio's Tim Duncan,
David Robinson and Johnson; Vancouver's Shareef Abdur-Rahim;
Minnesota's Kevin Garnett and Stephon Marbury; Seattle's Vin Baker
and Gary Payton; Boston's Kenny Anderson; Denver's Nick Van Exel;
Portland's Rasheed Wallace and Damon Stoudamire; New Jersey's Sam
Cassell; Atlanta's Steve Smith and Chucky Brown; Sacramento's Otis
Thorpe; Cleveland's Derek Anderson; Indiana's Mark Jackson;
Detroit's Jerry Stackhouse; Toronto's Kevin Willis; the Rockets'
Mario Elie; and the Lakers' Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   More players are expected to commit in the next few days,
including some ``surprise announcements,'' according to Smith, who
said more big names may volunteer to play. In fact, Smith is
working his Carolina connections in an effort to land the biggest
name of all _ former Tar Heel Michael Jordan _ for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``(There has been) no direct contact with Michael, but we've put
out some different kites to everyone (connected with Jordan),''
Smith said. ``We're trying to get everyone in the NBA involved. I'm
getting calls constantly from guys interested in playing and
enthusiastic about the whole situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been myself, Avery Johnson, Sam Cassell and a lot of guys
networking together. It's easy to catch people at this time of year
because they expected to be playing at this time of year, so
they're in their home cities working out.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith will coach one team while former Rocket and current
University of Houston basketball coach Clyde Drexler will run the
ship for the other team, splitting the players via a draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his (Drexler's) coaching debut,'' Smith said.
``Hopefully, I can spoil it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tickets, which will range from $20 to $100, go on sale Friday.
The game will be the first to be played at the revamped Hofheinz
Pavilion, which will feature a new scoreboard and a new sound
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing to this entire event is that 100 percent of the
money from ticket sales will be given to the M.D. Anderson Cancer
Center,'' Jim McIngvale said. ``If we sell out this event, as we
hope we will, that will be about $300,000 for the M.D. Anderson
Cancer Center.''
</P>
<P>
   Westside Tennis Club also has been busy providing NBA players
with an outlet to keep their skills sharp until the lockout is
resolved. Several players are participating in the Westside lockout
league, which is played Monday and Wednesday evenings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was basically the guards' idea,'' Horry said. ``Avery, Sam
and them. The guards, they run the show, so they said, `Let's do a
little league, get some refs in here and try to make it a game-like
situation.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
