<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3007 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDRENS-AUTHOR-PROF     10-12 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDRENS-AUTHOR-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM FATHERS TO CHILDREN, A TWICE-TOLD TALE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ll) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The best place to start is with the fish that were
staring up from the clear mountain lake and had the faces of people
from the traveler's childhood. It was 1954, and the traveler, a
very tired Czech filmmaker lost for 14 months in Tibet, had put his
feet in the water to cool off.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, there was Novak, a neighbor from the street of his
childhood, swimming in on the right. There was Bitnar floating on
the left. When Novak and Bitnar started to nibble at the
filmmaker's toes, he quickly pulled his feet from the water _ and
later, back home in Prague, Czechoslovakia, told the story to his
wide-eyed 5-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Move forward 44 years, to a small SoHo studio on Elizabeth
Street, where Peter Sis, the now grown-up but in some ways still
wide-eyed son, was telling the story on his own last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father,'' he said, ``has got obviously a very vivid
imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   So, obviously, does the son: He is a filmmaker, writer and
illustrator (and goose-egg painter) who has turned his father's
lost journey into his latest and most personal children's book,
``Tibet: Through the Red Box.'' Actually, the soon-to-be-published
book is too full of things adult _ the communist takeover of
Czechoslovakia, a grown-up son's questions about whether the Tibet
of his father's stories ever existed _ to be really for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for the child inside all of us, or something like that,''
said Sis, 49, who has the dark, soulful looks of a European actor
and the besotted nature of a father of young children who finds
magic in the New World.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dear Madeleine,'' he wrote to his 6-year-old daughter in
the dedication of one of his earlier children's books, ``The Three
Golden Keys,'' about his childhood in Prague. ``You might never
speak Czech. You may prefer other parts of this beautiful planet _
blue seas, green islands, bustling metropolises. You are free.''
</P>
<P>
   The first stirrings of ``Tibet'' began across a different pair
of generations in 1994, when Sis' father sent him a letter from
Prague. ``He said, `We have to talk about what I will leave you,'''
Sis said. ``It really spooked me.'' One of those things was a red
lacquer box, forever locked, containing his father's diary from
Tibet. Sis' mother filled in the rest by phone: his father had
prostate cancer. Sis flew to Prague, made arrangements for
treatment, opened the red box, and read all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very strange feeling,'' he said, ``because I was
reading the diary of somebody who was still alive, but 45 years
younger.''
</P>
<P>
   He discovered no horrible secrets _ his father had kept the
diary locked because of a generic fear of communist government
officials _ but far more detail in the stories he had heard so many
times during his childhood. In the fall of 1953, his father,
Vladimir Sis, had been drafted into an army film unit to record the
building of a mountain highway in what was described as a remote
western province of China. But when a wall of the mountain broke
off, destroying the road, the elder Sis was separated from the
project, and lost in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   Many strange things happened.
</P>
<P>
   In a forest of giant rhododendrons, a boy covered with jingle
bells delivered a letter to Vladimir Sis from his family in Prague.
Sis, astonished, gave the boy a pair of scissors, and the boy tried
them out on the leaves, then stayed by the fire that night.
Vladimir Sis hoped the boy would help him find his way, but the
next morning he was gone. Then he noticed an unusual cut on a leaf,
and then another, that led him out of the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Is it true? ``It's his story,'' Sis said. ``But who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1954, Vladimir Sis had made his way to Lhasa,
Tibet, where he met the Dalai Lama, then 19, who gave him a shawl
as a gift. In 1959, long after Sis left, the Dalai Lama fled the
Chinese army and began what is now almost 40 years in exile. That
is not in Sis' book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to turn the book into good and bad,'' Sis said.
</P>
<P>
   Sis grew up in a large gray house in Prague, and since his
mother was an artist she allowed him to paint pictures on chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Sis went to the Royal College of Art in London, made animated
films, moved to Los Angeles, met the children's author Maurice
Sendak, then drove across country to begin a career as an
illustrator in Manhattan. ``I remember driving around it, and I
couldn't find the entrance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sis has since done thousands of illustrations for newspapers and
magazines, including The New York Times. He has written 14
children's books and illustrated 27 others. He is married, has two
children, and on Easter 1995 he presented a painted goose egg to
President Clinton at the White House. His artist friends said he
was selling out, but Sis wanted a story for his children, which he
got when his daughter somehow got hold of the egg during the formal
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madeleine dropped the egg, of course, so I threw myself at the
feet of the president _ it was the ultimate nightmare of the
immigrant _ and caught the egg,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His father is still alive. ``He's OK _ it's a strange feeling,''
said Sis. ``Well, actually, it's a good feeling. I did the book in
a hurry because I thought it would be too late.'' This summer, Sis
presented the Dalai Lama with an early copy of his book, and gave
him a second present wrapped in the same shawl that the Dalai Lama
had given his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He remembered everything about it,'' Sis said. ``There was
something said about a full circle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-98 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
