<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-COLUMN13-COX     10-12 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who's wearing conservative stripes?
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One candidate is a Republican businessman who talks
about cutting the size of state government. The other candidate is
a Democratic lawyer under attack as too liberal for the state.
</P>
<P>
   One candidate has made cracking down on school discipline the
keynote of his education program. He's for after-school programs to
keep students off the streets and a 10 p.m. school night curfew.
</P>
<P>
   He argues that the state needs to concentrate on accountability
rather than launching off into another big reform movement. As for
higher education, any new money would probably be targeted at
vocational education.
</P>
<P>
   The other candidate wants to hire 7,500 new teachers and spend
$375 million for new classrooms to meet the goal of reducing
elementary school class sizes by 20 percent. Salaries for new
teachers would be increased 15 percent, and they would be required
to have a higher college grade-point average.
</P>
<P>
   Students would be monitored in annual standardized tests.
Teachers who do well on the statewide teacher tests and their
students' tests would receive $472 million in bonuses over four
years.
</P>
<P>
   If you've been following the governor's race, it's obvious that
the candidates and their education platforms haven't been placed in
parallel order in the preceding paragraphs. It is actually Roy
Barnes, the Democrat, who is preaching discipline and retrenchment,
while Guy Millner, the Republican, is the advocate of more teachers
with higher pay.
</P>
<P>
   An outsider would easily be confused, however. By the measure of
any conservative theory from Edmund Burke to Newt Gingrich, there
is something infernally skewed in the way ideological lines have
been drawn in this race.
</P>
<P>
   On what voters say is their most important issue this year, the
labels have been mismatched. Whichever plan is better for the
state, Barnes' position is clearly to the right of Millner's.
</P>
<P>
   This confusing situation is a result of the way education has
developed as an issue in the South over the past 30 years. Millner
is following in the footsteps of Republican governors such as
Tennessee's Lamar Alexander, who campaigned in Georgia for him
recently. They leaned more conservative on some issues, but pushed
as aggressively for big school packages as Democrats Terry Sanford
in North Carolina and William Winter in Mississippi once did.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, on the other hand, has less temptation to push big
programs of his own when he is also running as the custodian of
Zell Miller's legacy. In what amounts to a significant departure in
the South, certainly in Democratic politics, he's running on the
proposition that the era of reform has run its course and a period
of consolidation should begin.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the very different education proposals being made in
the governor's race didn't come up much Sunday in the GPTV debate
of school superintendent candidates, sponsored by the Atlanta Press
Club. Perhaps that's another sign of how the issue has become
disconnected from its philosophical moorings.
</P>
<P>
   The Barnes and Millner education programs offer voters a clear
choice. It's just that the choices don't jibe with all the other
liberal-conservative rhetoric of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the tax issue. There, you have a candidate who'd favor
middle-class homeowners by increasing the homestead exemption
against a candidate taking the more populist approach of
eliminating the car tax.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
