<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL ENVOY TO WORLD'S FAIR 
FINALLY GOT A SEAT  
 A REALISTIC TRIBUTE
</HEADLINE>
   (ll) 
 By JAMES BARRON with ALAN FEUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is a Democratic donor _ he gave more than $480,000 to the
Democratic National Committee from 1991 to 1996 _ and in 1994 he
and his wife stayed overnight at the White House. Now the donor,
William Rollnick, and his wife, photographer Nancy Ellison, are
being sent to the next World's Fair.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton named Rollnick to head the U.S. effort for
Expo 2000, which is scheduled to be held in Hanover, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``My killer title,'' Rollnick said, ``is special envoy and
personal representative of the president of the United States. It
has a certain lilt to it.'' How does he say it in German? ``My
German is terrible,'' he said. ``I can hire people who speak
German.''
</P>
<P>
   The president named Ms. Ellison the deputy commissioner general.
</P>
<P>
   Rollnick, a former chief executive of Genstar Rental Electric,
said he took the job when the president called and began the
conversation by saying, ``Billy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only my mother and the president of the United States call me
Billy,'' Rollnick said, ``and my mother is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Clinton asked him to take the job. ``I said, `Of
course,''' Rollnick said. ``How can you say no? I said, `What's our
budget?' He said, `Depends on how much you raise.'''
</P>
<P>
   The goal is $45 million for a nonprofit foundation connected
with the fair. Rollnick will oversee the design and operation of
the U.S. pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Rollnick said the invitation to stay at the White House came
after he and his wife accepted an invitation to a benefit in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I thought was, it was a joke,'' he said. And
no, Clinton did not put him in the Lincoln Bedroom. ``I slept in a
bedroom upstairs across from where his mother used to play poker
with her buddies. I don't know if the room had a name, but I
thought it was a wonderful experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally Got a Seat
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You never know how people will react to secondhand
furniture. Rufino Lopez discovered this when he bought the dining
chairs that had been at Daniel, the restaurant in Manhattan that
Daniel Boulud closed in August.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez moved them to Irvington and put them in the back room at
his new restaurant there, Solera II.
</P>
<P>
   A woman walked in the other day. She did not want to eat
anything. ``No,'' she said, ``I just want to sit in one of these
chairs. I could never get a reservation at that place in New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   A Realistic Tribute
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was no unveiling of the new Nelson Shanks
portrait of mezzo-soprano Denyce Graves. It was not veiled to begin
with.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there much time for artistic contemplation: Shanks, a
realist painter who did the last commissioned portrait from life of
Diana, princess of Wales, finished his ``demonstration portrait''
of Ms. Graves in less than three hours. He worked in front of 300
art students and painters, two video cameras and a microphone at
the Art Student's League on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Graves, starring as Dalila in ``Samson et Dalila'' at the
Metropolitan Opera, seemed to enjoy sitting for Shanks. She said
that while she was accustomed to working live in front of crowds,
it was a strange pleasure to play to just one person, Shanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it felt like a dance,'' she said. ``Sometimes I
could actually feel where he was on my face _ my mouth or my
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanks, who plans to paint a new, 7-foot image of Ms. Graves for
the National Gallery in Washington in the spring, sounded please by
her review.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Denyce was happily surprised to see so many
recognizable parts of herself on the canvas so quickly,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
