<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-NKOSI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST NKOSI, 58, SOUTH AFRICAN MUSIC PRODUCER
</HEADLINE>
   (ll) 
 By JON PARELES  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   West Nkosi, a saxophonist, songwriter and producer who helped
bring South African music to the outside world, died on Thursday in
Johannesburg, South Africa, from injuries he had received in a car
crash in August, said an executive of Gallo Records, where Nkosi
had made hits since the 1960s. He was 58.
</P>
<P>
   For more than three decades, Nkosi was a prime mover of South
African music, combining traditional elements with pop. By signing
and acting as producer for the a cappella choir Ladysmith Black
Mambazo, he set the direction for iscathamiya, Ladysmith's
``stalking style,'' with its quiet and loud passages.
</P>
<P>
   As a producer and the saxophonist for the band Makgona Tsohle,
he shaped the style called sax jive and then the music that grew
out of it, called mbaqanga (named after a homemade stew) or
mgqashiyo, ``the indestructible beat.'' It was the beat that Paul
Simon used for many of the songs on the 1986 album ``Graceland,''
which also featured Ladysmith Black Mambazo's vocals.
</P>
<P>
   To create mbaqanga, Nkosi said in a 1990 interview, ``we took a
little bit from each individual tribe, put them together and made
one solid rhythm that could cater to all the South African
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Nkosi's recordings can be heard on a series of
collections called ``The Indestructible Beat of Soweto''
(Shanachie).
</P>
<P>
   Nkosi was born in Nelspruit, South Africa, and went to
Johannesburg when he was 16. His first instrument was a penny
whistle, the lead instrument in a South African pop style called
kwela, and he was in a band led by Spokes Mashiyane, a well-known
kwela musician. As kwela gave way to sax jive, Nkosi took up the
alto saxophone.
</P>
<P>
   The Makgona Tsohle band was formed in 1962 and became the Gallo
Records studio band through the 1960s and 1970s, playing
instrumentals and backing vocal groups, like a South African
equivalent of the Stax Records studio band Booker T. and the
M.G.'s. Nkosi wrote more than 100 songs and was heard on hundreds
of recordings.
</P>
<P>
   While working with Makgona Tsohle, Nkosi became a producer with
Mavuthela, the black-music division of Gallo Records. He signed
Ladysmith Black Mambazo after hearing them on the radio in Durban,
on South Africa's east coast, and produced 22 albums for the group,
which merges Zulu traditional styles with gospel.
</P>
<P>
   Every album released by Ladysmith Black Mambazo has been a gold
album (selling 25,000 copies) in South Africa, and some have sold
more than 200,000 copies there. ``Nobody wanted to record that kind
of music, without guitars,'' Nkosi said in an interview for ``The
Rough Guide to World Music'' (1994). ``But I took it up and it
worked out good.''
</P>
<P>
   Nkosi had hits of his own, notably the sax-jive tune ``2
Mabone'' (``Two Headlights'') in the 1970s, which spawned a dance
craze and answer records like ``4 Mabone'' and ``6 Mabone.'' His
best-known mbaqanga production was Mahlathini and the Mahotella
Queens, a deep bass ``groaner'' and a female harmony group, who
adapted traditional Zulu wedding songs to a pop format.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by Makgona Tsohle, the group became hugely popular in
South Africa in the 1960s and '70s, and was discovered
internationally in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Nkosi continued to produce music for Gallo Records through the
'90s, recording, among others, the Zulu traditional singer
Phuzekemisi and Zulu-style pop with Joe Mifela. ``He had hits all
the time,'' said Ivor Haarburger, the executive director of Gallo
Records.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Thami, and three daughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
