<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME ON: UCLA VS. MIAMI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They have no flight, no hotel, no kickoff time and
no television contract.
</P>
<P>
   But they've got a game.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA and Miami have rescheduled their canceled game for Dec. 5
in the Orange Bowl, assuming the schools agree on a start time. The
Bruins want to play at 12:30 p.m. (PST) so they can travel Friday.
Playing at 9 a.m. would necessitate traveling Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the very beginning, I was inclined to play,'' UCLA
athletic director Peter Dalis said. ``If it happened to us and we
had an earthquake and needed a team to (reschedule), I'd hope they
would do it. That was the most prevalent part of my thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, UCLA announced tailback Jermaine Lewis has been
reinstated following a one-game suspension for fighting. He'll play
Saturday against No.11 Oregon but won't start.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's Lewis-less victory at Arizona and subsequent climb to
No.2 in the rankings did not affect the decision to play Miami,
Dalis said. He had hoped to finalize the matter last week but
didn't speak to Miami athletic director Paul Dee until Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Dalis and I) wanted to play,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said.
``Arizona had nothing to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS, which owned the rights to the Sept. 26 game, is scheduled
to show the Army-Navy football game and the Miami-Kentucky
basketball game Dec. 5. But Dee assured Dalis the football game
will be televised, perhaps by ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA basketball team also plays that day, against Oklahoma
State in the Wooden Classic at 4:15 p.m. The football game should
finish before tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following the cancellation, Toledo and Dalis voiced
several concerns about rescheduling: Fans weren't keen on playing a
game after USC; it would eliminate a critical recruiting weekend;
and it would extend the season by two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players were not real interested in extending the
season,'' Dalis said. ``I can't blame them. They've got lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But team sentiment shifted after the 52-28 victory in Tucson. No
one knows if playing Miami will help or hurt UCLA's national
championship drive _ if the Hurricanes are 5-5, the game could
damage UCLA's strength-of-schedule rating _ but the Bruins don't
want to find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be sitting back in December being mad at
ourselves because the game slipped away and we're in the Rose
Bowl,'' offensive tackle Kris Farris said. ``I never thought the
Rose Bowl would be second-best. But to be that close (to the Fiesta
Bowl) and not obtain our goal is terrifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lewis practiced Monday for the first time since his
Oct. 6 suspension. He and Elonza Malone III have filed battery
complaints against each other following an off-campus fight in the
early hours of Oct. 4. Campus police have not concluded their
investigation, but Toledo is satisfied with the length of
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to a lot of people and police and came to the
conclusion that he has suffered enough,'' Toledo said. ``A one-game
suspension for what happened, in my opinion, is enough. He didn't
throw the first punch.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he does not know Malone and called the incident a
misunderstanding. He said he was hit twice before fighting back _
``It was self defense'' _ and a plethora of witnesses will confirm
his version of events to the police.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the weekend at home in Lancaster, watching the Bruins
on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I let my teammates down,'' he said. ``I was
depressed. I had a hard time sleeping (last week). During practice,
I sat on a car (in an adjacent parking structure) and watched. It
was rough. It was the longest week of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
