<DOCNO> NYT19981012.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3030 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-NEGATIVE-CAMPAIGN-     10-12 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NEGATIVE-CAMPAIGN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES RISK LITTLE WITH HARSH ADS
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-NY) 
 (nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a Sunday morning service recently, the Rev. Floyd
Flake went to the pulpit of his church in Queens and urged the
candidates for the U.S. Senate, Alfonse D'Amato and Charles
Schumer, to cease their ``dirty campaign.'' They were doing
themselves a disservice and would ultimately turn voters away from
an important political contest, Flake told the congregation, which
included D'Amato that morning.
</P>
<P>
   Flake got the answer to his plea two days later. D'Amato, the
Republican incumbent, released three new advertisements attacking
Schumer (``Chuck Schumer consistently votes against us,'' the
announcer says in one), while Schumer, a Democratic congressman
from Brooklyn, slashed into D'Amato's environmental record,
asserting that ``people are wise to his act.''
</P>
<P>
   Civic leaders like Flake, and some voters, might frown on such
politicking _ thrashing the opponent, rather than advancing one's
own record and accomplishments _ but the candidates and their
advisers in this pivotal Senate race have concluded that they have
no other choice.
</P>
<P>
   The unrelenting attacks _ on voting records, on ethics, on
political ideology, even on the place that Schumer calls home _ are
the inevitable result of a competition that features a relatively
unpopular incumbent fighting for re-election in a Democratic state,
and a relatively little-known challenger trying to knock out one of
the most resourceful figures in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Flake's concerns notwithstanding, the candidates and their
strategists have decided that the risks of ``going negative'' are
far outweighed by the effectiveness of such politicking. The
finger-pointing between Schumer and D'Amato about who started it,
and who has been more negative, might present intriguing questions
for historians one day, but it is unlikely to influence many voters
in November.
</P>
<P>
   The latest New York Times/CBS News Poll underscores their
judgment. By any objective measure, the campaign between Schumer
and D'Amato is about as negative as they come _ it is, arguably,
the most negative Senate race in the nation this fall _ yet 54
percent of voters said it was no more negative than D'Amato's last
contest, in 1992, against Robert Abrams. In fact, 14 percent said
it was more positive.
</P>
<P>
   More voters blame D'Amato for the tone of the race, by 34
percent to 26 percent, and slightly more are inclined to think
D'Amato's attacks are unfair, instead of the ones offered by
Schumer, the Times/CBS News Poll found. But there is no evidence of
voters punishing the candidates for what they see as tactical
transgressions. Three weeks of punch-for-punch campaigning have
produced a statistical dead heat for the candidates, the Times/CBS
News poll found.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll of 1,066 registered voters in New York state,
taken from Oct. 1 to Oct. 6, has a margin of sampling error of plus
or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the campaign has devolved to this level so fast is
certainly not a surprise to anyone familiar with the dynamics of
the race or its two tenacious contestants. ``Neither of these guys
had a choice; it was inscribed the day before the primary,'' said
Norman Adler, a political analyst from New York who is not
affiliated with either candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But though both have embraced the same tactic, they have done it
for different reasons, and that is revealing of the shortcomings
and political positions Schumer and D'Amato find themselves in this
year.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's motivates can be determined from a cursory reading of
any public opinion poll: The three-term senator invariably scores
less than 50 percent against his opponent. In the Times/CBS News
Poll, 41 percent of registered voters said they would support him.
That is not good for an incumbent who has been in office for 18
years, since by this point, there is little that D'Amato can tell
undecided voters to win them over.
</P>
<P>
   That means that D'Amato must provide them with reasons not to
support Schumer, which he has been doing since the night Schumer
won the Democratic primary (and as the senator has done in all of
his statewide races in New York).
</P>
<P>
   To this end, D'Amato has combed through 23 years of Schumer's
legislative record, picking out votes _ some on major pieces of
legislation, and others on procedural or inconsequential matters _
to portray the congressman as liberal or hostile to upstate New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, he has seized on the fact that Schumer, who has
for most of his career had a strong attendance record in Congress,
missed more than 100 votes this year as he attended to his campaign
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's attacks on D'Amato have been no less brutal. Schumer's
challenge has been built on one overarching theme: that D'Amato is
a chronic liar. (``Too many lies for too long'' is the last line of
most commercials, a slogan so harsh that it appears to have taken
even D'Amato's breath away).
</P>
<P>
   It is a broad pre-emptive attack intended to inoculate Schumer
against any criticism D'Amato might come up with between now and
Nov. 3, by stirring what polls suggest are strong doubts about
D'Amato's trustworthiness.
</P>
<P>
   As an all-encompassing theme, Schumer's approach pushes the
horizon of negative campaigning, and could, if Schumer wins, be
remembered as a political benchmark one day. Early indications are
that it is successful. The Times/CBS News Poll shows that Schumer
continues to have a generally favorable rating among voters,
suggesting that D'Amato's attacks have yet to stick.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's confrontational strategy has two other unstated
purposes. First, it was designed to catch the attention of
Democratic contributors across the country who were deciding where
to send their checks in this year's 34 Senate contests, by
signaling that Schumer would run the campaign against D'Amato that
some Democrats believe Abrams failed to do six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And the unusually sharp cast of the attack _ even some Democrats
describe it as a little over the top _ is intended to be splashy
enough to win Schumer a few newspaper articles and some television
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer and D'Amato are executing the kinds of campaigns that
have been part of American politics for the better part of 200
years, but which really came into focus with the 1988 Presidential
contest. That year, Vice President George Bush and the Republican
Party devastated Michael Dukakis with a searing run of
advertisements that questioned Dukakis' fortitude, ideology and
even his patriotism. It is often cited by analysts as evidence of
the potency of such tactics.
</P>
<P>
   There are some notorious examples of negative campaigning this
year as well. In the Nebraska Republican primary for governor, Rep.
Jon Christensen accused Mike Johanns, the mayor of Lincoln, of
condoning child pornography after a cable television channel in his
city showed some nudity. Other Republicans assailed Christensen,
and he went on to lose the primary.
</P>
<P>
   But viewed by the three best measures of a campaign's negativity
_ the sharpness of the attacks, their sheer volume, and the mix
between positive and negative _ the New York race stands out this
year. D'Amato's menu of television is almost entirely negative.
Schumer has leavened his mix with a handful of positive
advertisements and is expected to produce more upbeat ads as
Election Day approaches.
</P>
<P>
   That has formed the backdrop for a second subject of dispute
between Schumer and D'Amato: which candidate is responsible for the
attacks, and who is the most negative. That may sound like an
academic question to viewers bombarded with one attack ad after
another, but it is particularly relevant this year because D'Amato
has _ once again _ tried to portray himself as a victim of unfair
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer notes, correctly, that D'Amato was the first to run
attack ads, starting the day after the primary with one that
asserted: ``Liberal Chuck Schumer. Wrong on taxes. Wrong on
welfare. Wrong on crime. Wrong for us.'' (D'Amato actually began
attacking Schumer in a Dec. 30, 1997, letter to supporters, in
which he said, ``I've listened to this guy for 17 years and I still
can't figure out what they taught him at Harvard. It wasn't common
sense!'') Schumer knew D'Amato's history well enough to be ready
with his own attack ad the moment the senator ran his.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the two are quarreling about what is fair in political
discourse. D'Amato contends that Schumer crossed the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaigns aren't always gentlemanly-like,'' D'Amato said
Monday at a news conference in Manhattan in which he assailed
Schumer's attendance record. ``However, I do believe it is one
thing to point to a person's record and it is another thing to use
pejoratives that have been used in this campaign that go beyond.''
He said he was referring specifically to Schumer's having described
him as a liar and a bully.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer responded by mocking D'Amato. ``When he finally gets
someone to answer him back, he starts whining,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, even the representative's supporters acknowledge that
calling someone is a liar is extraordinary by the standards of
American politics. Still, the senator's bid for sympathy based on
Schumer's perceived excesses arguably runs up against his own
history.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato played a very prominent role in writing the book on
attack politics in the United States over the past 25 years. He
helped produce a seminal snippet of campaign advertising 18 years
ago. ``And now, at age 76 and in failing health, he wants six more
years,'' the announcer said as the screen showed a crumpled Javits
poster fluttering to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of the attack was Sen. Jacob Javits, a fellow
Republican. D'Amato defeated him in the GOP primary by 70,000
votes, and went on to win the general election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
