<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-12 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3037 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-SPOTTSWOOD-NYT     10-12 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SPOTTSWOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTTSWOOD ROBINSON III, 82, CIVIL RIGHTS LAWYER
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Va., Md.)   (ll) 
 By ERIC PACE  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spottswood W. Robinson III, a Virginia civil-rights lawyer who
argued one of the five cases that led to the Supreme Court's 1954
desegregation ruling in Brown vs. Board of Education, died on
Sunday at his home in Richmond, Va. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   The cause appeared to have been a heart attack, said Robinson's
only surviving son, Spottswood W. Robinson IV.
</P>
<P>
   After the Brown case, Robinson went on to become dean of the
Howard University Law School and chief judge of the District of
Columbia U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's decision in Brown vs. Board of Education
declared that segregation in public schools violated the
Constitution. When the court handed down its decisions, the
justices also ruled on four other cases, among them a Virginia case
Robinson had argued challenging conditions at an all-black high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Jack Greenberg of Columbia Law School, an authority on
civil rights law, said on Monday that Robinson, who was black, was
``one of just a very small handful of practicing lawyers who
handled civil rights cases in the late '40s and early '50s in
Virginia.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, a former director of the NAACP Legal Defense and
Educational Fund, added: ``He was a curious combination of a
property lawyer, who knew the ins and outs of property law, and a
constitutional lawyer, who knew the great policies of the
Constitution as they were expressed in 14th Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Howard's law school, Robinson became legal
representative of the Legal Defense and Educational Fund in
Virginia in 1948. Three years later, he began working on the case
of a black student in Prince Edward County, in south-central
Virginia, who said that the Robert R. Moton High School there,
which had only black students, was inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was eventually combined with the Brown case, out of
Kansas, and the other cases, from South Carolina and Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   While the Virginia case was being heard in Richmond, Robinson
recalled in a 1963 interview, when he wanted lunch he had to rush
to a hotel for blacks 12 blocks from the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   A black lawyer then sometimes had ``a hard time finding any
place to eat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When it was time for the Brown cases to be heard by the Supreme
Court, recalled Greenberg, who argued the Delaware case before the
justices, Robinson ``got the assignment of, among other things,
arguing the constitutional history of the 14th Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   In his court appearances, Greenberg said, Robinson ``was
uniquely effective, in that he was just one of a couple of people
doing what he was doing in Virginia'' at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg added: ``He was also an exceptionally capable lawyer.
He was good with judges and juries. He knew the law. He knew some
of the esoteric, technical, sort of obscure parts of legal
history.'' Robinson's view was that the 14th Amendment had
envisioned the establishment of complete equality for all people,
regardless of race. Equality was denied to blacks, he held, as long
as their children could not go to white schools.
</P>
<P>
   In Robinson's appearances before the Supreme Court, Greenberg
said, ``He was very calm and just absolutely brimming with facts
and information and legal doctrine.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson became a professor and then dean at Howard's law school
from 1960 to 1963, and was named a judge of the U.S. District Court
in the District of Columbia from 1964 to 1966.
</P>
<P>
   He was elevated to the District of Columbia U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals in 1966, where he became chief judge from 1981. He
retired from the chief judge position when he turned 70 on 1986,
and from the court in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer's son, Robinson, who was tall, spare and mild-mannered,
attended Virginia Union University in Richmond and received his law
degree in 1939 from Howard, magna cum laude. He began his law
career as a teacher at Howard, mainly in property law. He took a
leave of absence in 1947 and did not return until he became the
school's dean. In the intervening years he practiced law in
Richmond, for the NAACP and other clients.
</P>
<P>
   Among his other civil rights cases over the years were lawsuits
involving interstate bus travel, public parks and restrictive
covenants.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Robinson practiced law in Richmond on his own, as
a law-firm partner and as a general counsel in the banking
industry. He was a member of the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights
from 1961 to 1963.
</P>
<P>
   The honors he received included an honorary doctorate of laws in
1986 from New York Law School, for his efforts ``to achieve true
equality under the law for all Americans'' and addressing ``the
conscience of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his son, a Richmond resident, Robinson is
survived by his wife of 62 years, the former Marian Wilkerson; a
daughter, Nina Govan of Greenbelt, Md.; one grandson, and a sister,
Isadore Burke, of Freeport in the Bahamas.
</P>
</TEXT>
